<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-SERVICE-STRUCTURE23-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill wouldwould revamp Texas funeral agency
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The troubled exas Funeral Service Commission
would remain an independent agency, but would be restructured to
give public members a 2-to-1 majority as regulators of the state's
1,280 funeral homes, under a bill approved Thursday by a House
committee.
</P>
<P>
   As a backup measure, the public health committee also approved a
bill that would abolish the funeral agency and transfer its
responsibilities to the Texas Department of Health. Lawmakers said
they would push that bill only if they can't get the votes to
revamp the funeral commission.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral agency, run by a commission of five public
representatives and four industry members, has become the target of
lawmakers because of its poor performance over the years. The
agency has a backlog of complaints awaiting investigation, takes
half a year to resolve a complaint instead of the three-month time
limit set by agency, and is beset with continual staff turnover
that leaves key jobs vacant for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the confidence of the public in this
industry,'' said Rep. Dale Tillery, (D-Dallas), who helped write
the bill to revamp the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral service commission has attracted national attention
during the past year because of a controversial investigation it
launched against the largest funeral home company in the world,
Houston-based Service Corporation International. Agency
investigators said SCI used some unsupervised apprentices to embalm
bodies in unlicensed locations in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   The agency denies wrongdoing, but a funeral agency panel
proposed a fine of nearly $450,000 against the company last summer.
The company has appealed the fine and complained to Gov. George W.
Bush's office that the agency used ``storm trooper'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral commission Chairman Dick McNeil, vice president of the
largest independently owned funeral home company in Fort Worth,
said the funeral agency had been well on its way to correcting
problems until the staff became entangled in the bitter fight with
SCI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stuff we did was dealing with SCI in the last
year,'' McNeil said. ``Everything got stalled.''
</P>
<P>
   He favors retaining the commission in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got one of the most consumer-oriented
commissions we've ever had,'' McNeil said. ``I really hate to see
this board take a beating like this when they're good quality
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The new bill to restructure the funeral agency would set the
commission at six members, with four public members, including the
chairman and vice chairman, and two from the industry. The bill
would also bar the funeral agency from revealing the dollar amount
of any proposed fine against a funeral home until the case is
closed. The proposed fine against SCI, the largest ever proposed by
the agency, would have been kept secret if such a rule had been in
place last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Funeral Directors Association, which favors
restructuring the funeral agency rather than abolishing it,
supports the proposal to keep proposed fines secret.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any information like that could be used in an injurious
fashion by a competitor,'' said Hank Schmidt, president of the
Texas Funeral Directors Association. ``We want to make sure that
before it's released, that it is final and it's not just
speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
