<HEADER>
A0025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      04-23 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHTROPE FOR REPUBLICANS ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Ky., Md., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Democrats lined up on the floor of the House
last week to sign a petition that would force Republican leaders to
allow a vote on campaign finance legislation, Rep. Christopher
Shays, R-Conn., one of the bill's two authors, was among them, or
rather beside them, thanking them for their support, even shaking
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   But Shays did not grab a pen and put his name on the document. A
week later, his signature is still not there. Neither is that of a
single other House Republican, even though 30 of them are
officially co-sponsors of the bill and the petition would succeed
instantly with their support.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons reflect the tangle of strategic considerations that
lawmakers encounter whenever they venture onto politically
difficult terrain and the particular dilemma that confronts Shays
and other House Republicans who support campaign finance overhaul
but face the ardent opposition of Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, they are letting their actions be dictated in
large part by political etiquette and party loyalty. But they are
also haunted by a sense of urgency about the legislation, which
would effectively ban the unlimited and unregulated donations to
political parties that are known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a tightrope,'' Shays said in an interview.
``I just have to be very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker J. Dennis Hastert and other Republican leaders have
asked party members not to sign the petition and to leave in the
leaders' hands the timing of a vote on the bill, whose co-author is
Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has said that the bill would come to the floor sometime
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's supporters said they believe it must pass the
House before August, and maybe even before Memorial Day, if similar
legislation is to have any hope of success in the Senate, where it
faces the tall hurdle of a threatened filibuster by Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky. And thus far, although a crowded House calendar
for the next few months is taking shape, no debate has been
scheduled on the Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   To force such a debate, the petition needs the signatures of 218
members of the House, or a simple majority. At last count, it had
only 189. No Republican had signed it, and Democrats who support it
said that they had hit the limit on the members of their own party
willing to lend their names to the document.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 12 Republicans, including Shays, signed a similar
petition that prodded Speaker Newt Gingrich to bring the
Shays-Meehan bill to the floor, where it passed by a vote of
252-179 in August. Sixty-one Republicans voted for it; 53 of them
are still in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich had never pledged to allow a vote on the bill, and
Hastert has. Given the newness of Hastert's leadership and his
nonconfrontational style, Shays and his Republican allies are loath
to buck him without good cause.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Republicans realize that their hold on a
majority in the House is tenuous, and that party in-fighting could
jeopardize it in the elections of 2000. Signing the petition would
be the epitome of dissent, because it would take the majority's
control over the legislative calendar and hand it to the opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary measure,'' said Rep. Constance Morella,
R-Md., who signed the petition last time around. ``You're defying
the protocol of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., who signed the petition last year,
said she was willing to wait at least a little longer to see if
Hastert would accommodate her concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we owe it to him,'' Ms. Roukema said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roukema, Ms. Morella and Shays are heeding not just
diplomatic considerations but tactical ones. Some House Republicans
inclined to vote for the Shays-Meehan bill could withdraw their
support if they felt that the bill's backers unnecessarily defied
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Even though such a defection would probably not doom the bill's
passage, it would narrow the voting margin. And some of the bill's
advocates believe the size of that margin could determine whether a
similar measure musters the requisite support in the Senate, where
it takes 60 votes to break a filibuster. Last year, there were only
52 votes to bring campaign finance legislation to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and his allies said that that they wanted Hastert to allow
a vote by the beginning of August. But a senior Republican aide
said that Hastert had signaled an intention to bring campaign
finance to the floor sometime around September.
</P>
<P>
   Shays acknowledged that if he and his Republican allies let that
happen without protest, they could lose credibility with
constituents. Shays has already received a drubbing from liberal
advocacy groups and editorial writers for not signing the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it at all,'' he said of the position he was in.
But in the end, he added, what he wants is a law, and the best path
to that is not wholly clear. ``This issue is very important to me
and a lot of other people, and if I'm precipitous, I could end up
killing the bill,'' Shays said.
</P>
</TEXT>
