<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0027 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BROWN-COLUMN-LADN     04-23 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET GEORGIA BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Monday, two days before his start against the
Atlanta Braves, Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown has a glint in his eye,
a black Sharpie marker in his right hand and a flock of fans at his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Brown pinches the cheek of a cherub in a tiny Dodgers jersey. He
flips the bill on the cap that another child is wearing so the
person next in line is left staring at the St. Louis Cardinals
logo. He gently needles a woman wearing an autographed Atlanta
Braves T-shirt before signing a baseball card.
</P>
<P>
   Then a man steps forward and hands Brown a recent ``Sports
Illustrated'' issue for him to sign. He might as well have been
handing President Clinton a copy of the Kenneth Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is on the cover of the magazine. He is not smiling.
``Kevin Brown Has Nasty Stuff, (And he's one Ornery S.O.B.),'' the
caption reads. The portrait of Brown inside wasn't much more
flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's 6-foot-4 frame straightens. He smirks. Oh no, you say to
yourself, this could get ugly. You half expect him to put down the
pen and take a bat to the magazine. Brown, after all, has a
reputation to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have anything else I could sign?'' Brown asks the man.
``I don't know if I want to sign this.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, laughing, he does.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment it dawns on you that maybe Brown has gotten a bit
of a bum rap, that perhaps he's not unlike a lot of people in the
work force whose personalities are night and day depending on
whether they're on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ornery S.O.B.) is an accurate reflection of me on the day I
pitch,'' Brown concedes a little while later.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the other 325 days of the year? Brown's life is
KEVtv, but only about once a week. Except for every fifth day, the
lights and cameras and tape recorders largely leave Brown alone.
And invariably, the image the public gets of him is incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   He's a hick or a hothead, arrogant or just plain rude. People
seem so sure of what they see, especially in Brown's hometown of
McIntyre, Ga., where, as one lifelong resident put it, ``You just
can't go anywhere without finding someone who knows Kevin and his
family.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, like so many specks on the map spread out in your lap,
is much more than it seems from your car window. Take your eyes off
the two-lane road between Dublin and Milledgeville for just a
moment and you risk missing the town of 552 altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Whoosh. There it was, behind the towering pines, beside the
antebellum homes, beyond the kaolin chalk that is Wilkinson
County's lifeblood.
</P>
<P>
   You see a lot more when you park your car near the only
stoplight in the county, where Highways 441 and 57 meet, and eat
the home cooking at Maebob's Diner across the street and talk to
people hawking sacks of Vidalia onions in the name of the Lord. Ten
pounds for $10, with all the proceeds going to the local Baptist
church.
</P>
<P>
   The pride and populace rise up to meet you, and as sure as gravy
accompanies Maebob's biscuits, the hug that follows the hello is
coming from Carolyn Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, a retired schoolteacher known simply as Miss Sis, is one
of the friendly faces behind one of the meanest mugs in baseball.
She taught science to Brown's sister and brother at Wilkinson
County High before retiring the same year Kevin, the youngest child
of Carolyn and Gerald Brown, entered the ninth grade there.
</P>
<P>
   She also played softball on a team with Brown's mother and
sister, in recreational-league games that Brown's paternal
grandfather umpired. The player who can shrink teammates, reporters
and pitching coaches with a withering look was then just a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd set Kevin down in the dirt with just a diaper on and give
him a softball,'' Petty says.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a little older, that tyke started climbing onto
Petty's lap to listen to Braves' games with her on a transistor
radio. He grew some more, into a sweet young man who rang Petty's
doorbell one Christmas Eve. Shyly, he thrust a box of chocolates
into her hands when she opened the door and said, ``Miss Sis, I
just want you to have this,'' before running off into the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Petty remembers the philanthropist who outfitted
a local Little League team and the prodigal son who showed up one
night last year at the Bible-study class she teaches and signed
autographs for everybody in the room.
</P>
<P>
   For free.
</P>
<P>
   The person who is kind, cuddly, cordial; that is the Kevin Brown
that Petty knows.
</P>
<P>
   The player who wears a scowl like a 5 o'clock shadow on days
that he pitches, who lashes out at teammates and toilets, who keeps
a permanent home in Macon and makes himself scarce around McIntyre?
</P>
<P>
   That Kevin Brown she doesn't recognize at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does have some little something that people here would not
admire,'' Petty says, choosing her words carefully. ``He's always
wanted the best, even when he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so much a perfectionist, just like his sister. I don't
know where it comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   You suspect that maybe he's that way because there's so much in
Brown's life he can't control, he's bound and determined to control
what he can. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His mother had a brain tumor. His father has a pacemaker. His
sister isn't well and neither is his mother-in-law. Can you blame
this son of a small town for wanting to win the lottery?
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Powerball pitcher, hit baseball's all-time jackpot
this past December when he won $105 million, to be paid over seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   All that money and six trips to L.A. for his family thrown in
for free? Brown's gluttony was hard to swallow. It left a bad taste
in a lot of mouths.
</P>
<P>
   It's not until you're given bits of his past to chew on that it
occurs to you maybe Brown couldn't see the forest for his family
tree, that it wasn't greed that fueled him so much as a basic need
to keep his kin close.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was in grade school when his mother underwent brain
surgery to remove a tumor that turned out to be benign. Carolyn
Brown suffered short-term paralysis after the surgery, but she's
fine now. Brown doesn't remember much from those days, except that
he virtually took up temporary residence at the hospital in Macon
where his mom was being treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty bad time,'' Brown says. ``I spent a lot of
time at the hospital. It was an eye-opener.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister Joy, who is 13 years older, juggled her own grown-up
responsibilities and looked after her kid brother. Now it's his
turn to return the favor. Health problems hastened her retirement
from the Engelhard Corporation, the kaolin-mining company that once
employed her dad. She lives in McIntyre, in the house where she and
her brothers were reared.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Brown has more pressing concerns than how to spend the
$1.25 million paychecks he receives on the 1st and 15th of every
month. He worries about his sister's well-being and his father's
heart and his mother-in-law's ongoing battle with lupus, an
autoimmune disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wish you could snap your fingers and do what it takes to
make everyone healthy,'' Brown says with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Money can't buy you peace of mind, but it will get you
plantation-size pieces of land in Macon, a city of 106,612 some 25
miles west of McIntyre, in Bibb County. Brown is building a
palatial home there, next to the two homes he and wife Candace
erected for their parents.
</P>
<P>
   There are people in McIntyre who will tell you Brown not only
has moved out of Wilkinson County, he has moved on. They feel he
has hollowed out his roots until he's just a shell of the person
they once knew.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind his pitches; some people in Wilkinson County chart
Brown's charitable offerings to see how far he is from his home
base. He has earmarked $1 million for inner-city baseball in L.A.,
bought 50 loge seats to every Dodgers Sunday home game for
charitable distribution and doled out a bundle more to his son's
private Christian school in Macon. But because he hasn't given any
money lately to his high school alma mater, there are people who
say he has fallen behind in the count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're proud of him,'' says Jimmy Green, echoing the
sentiments of many residents. ``But he kind of left us behind.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more complicated than that, of course. If Brown learned
anything growing up it's that you can never be too close to family
or a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the big reasons I finally convinced my parents
to move to Macon,'' Brown says. ``That was me being selfish. I
wanted both sets of parents to be closer. I wanted my kids (sons
Ridge, 8, and Grayson, 4) to have a chance to see a lot of their
grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   If that makes him the poster boy for self-centered '90s
athletes, well, go ahead and stick a tack in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have McIntyre in my blood,'' he insists. ``I'm still
pretty much the same person. I still have the morals and an
appreciation of the outdoors from my days of growing up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown grows animated as he talks about his plans to build
baseball fields for the kids of McIntyre as a way of planting
dreams for future harvests. He says the fields have long been one
of his pet projects. You're inclined to believe him when you hear
the tinge of sadness in his voice, and he hastens to add, ``If
everybody down there doesn't hate me.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't always see eye-to-eye, Brown and his hometown,
maybe it's because they are so much alike.
</P>
<P>
   There is, after all, a depth to both that doesn't take much
digging to uncover. The key thing to remember is not to use an ax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
