<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT REDS, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ There is a popular saying these days: Act like
you've been there before. Still, it would have been understandable
if Al Leiter were a little more excited that he seemed here on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter (1-2) had just tossed six and one-third strong innings of
five-hit ball for his first triumph of the season in the New York
Mets' 4-1 victory over the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Leiter forced a smile and said things like ``I'm
happy I won'' and ``Results-wise, tonight was the best game I've
thrown,'' he did not seem all that happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to finish the seventh inning,'' Leiter said.
``I'll feel better tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are hoping that Bobby Bonilla feels the same. For the
first time since last Thursday, the Mets fielded their starting
outfield of Bonilla, Brian McRae and Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   But the reunion lasted only an inning. After Bonilla, who has
been bothered by a partially torn ligament in his right knee, drove
in the Mets' first run with a first-inning groundout, he told
Manager Bobby Valentine to keep an eye on him.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla said of Valentine: ``And he said, `No, no, no. That's
all I needed. I'm just going to take you out because I need you for
the weekend.'''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets will need Leiter to be more like he was last
season if they are going to challenge for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need Al,'' Valentine said. ``And the way he pitched
tonight was like a guy possessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had said on Wednesday: ``The difference between a good
year and a great year, or a good year and a bad year, are moments
in every single game that could be called crunch time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was talking about when it is absolutely necessary to
record an out. Leiter, who went a career-best 17-6 last season, had
not been able to nail down that key out in his last start, a 6-4
loss to the Montreal Expos. He had not been able to do so in any of
his three starts this year before Thursday night, coming in with an
0-2 record and a 5.95 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch time came for Leiter on Thursday evening in the bottom of
the fourth. For the second consecutive game, the Mets had jumped
out to an early lead against the Reds, only to see their offense
disappear. On Wednesday, with Masato Yoshii pitching, the Mets had
squandered a 4-0 lead and lost by 7-4. On Thursday night, after
Bonilla's run batted in, the Mets had added two runs in the second
on Todd Pratt's second homer in as many nights and Edgardo
Alfonzo's run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bonilla departed before the bottom of the second began, the
Mets' attack against a shaky Brett Tomko went on sabbatical. And
when Brian Johnson led off the Cincinnati third with a homer to
straightaway center, the Mets' lead was 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, the Reds were threatening to wipe out the rest
of Leiter's lead. With runners on first and third, up came Johnson
again, this time with two outs. Leiter quickly got ahead of the
Cincinnati catcher at 1-2. Johnson took two balls and then fouled
the next two pitches off. But Leiter did not give in. On the eighth
pitch of the at-bat, Johnson swung and missed for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds did not threaten again until the seventh. And by that
time the Mets had a 4-1 lead on a run-scoring single by John Olerud
in the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter departed after 117 pitches and after the Reds had put
consecutive runners on base for the first time on Johnson's single
and a walk to Pokey Reese. But Turk Wendell induced Dmitiri Young
into a pop-out to third and Mike Cameron flew out to center.
</P>
<P>
   That put Leiter in line for his first victory of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
