<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-KONRAD23     04-23 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-KONRAD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins' Konrad has no fear of 44
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Imagine owning a magic shirt.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to wear it. Just the knowledge that this
one-of-a-kind, hand-me-down item is hanging in your closet sends
everyone around you into a frenzy. It makes strangers want to get
close to you, to take your picture, to ask for your autograph, to
buy replicas of the shirt and wear them around town.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes some of them call talk radio and rip you for
failing to live up to their expectations. Makes them sit down at
their computers and post all kinds of nasty messages, most notably
that you don't deserve to own the shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that you spend four years getting used to this, fighting
it, accepting it, embracing it.
</P>
<P>
   Then you move to a new city, show up for work wearing the shirt
and ... nothing.
</P>
<P>
   No hype. No controversy. Just another shirt.
</P>
<P>
   This is what will happen today to Rob Konrad, a fullback from
Syracuse University, when he and the rest of the Miami Dolphins'
1999 draft picks trot onto a practice field in Davie for the first
workout of a three-day mini-camp.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad will the one wearing No. 44, the same number he wore in
college.
</P>
<P>
   Only it won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   A t Syracuse, 44 isn't just another number. It has become part
of the university phone prefix (443), the zip code (13244), the
nightlife (a hangout called ``44's'') and, most of all, the
tradition this upstate New York town has of cranking out running
backs.
</P>
<P>
   Three former No. 44s _ Jim Brown, Floyd Little and Ernie Davis _
went to the Hall of Fame wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for anyone who hasn't been here to really understand
what it means to wear No. 44,'' said Syracuse running backs coach
David Walker. ``Rob came in here with incredible expectations. He
was almost set up to fail. You're talking about a 17-year-old kid
who before he even stepped on campus, they're handing him the
Heisman Trophy. He handled all that. Handled it great.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the strength of this 6-foot-3, 255-pound player.
</P>
<P>
   His head.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' Class of 1999 will be known for its toughness. For
size. For power. For, in the case of third-round pick Grey
Ruegamer, the story about how he once castrated a lamb. With his
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad's toughness is different. More cerebral. That's not to
say he can't be physically intimidating. When Dolphins coach Jimmy
Johnson asked running backs coach Joel Collier about Konrad,
Collier recalled his time spent in the New England area _ and what
he had heard about Konrad's hometown of North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I moved to Massachusetts, I was told you don't mess with
guys in North Andover, because they'll just as soon hit you as they
would smile at you,'' Collier said. ``Meeting Rob confirmed that.
To me, he's a great kid but he looks like he could be nasty if he
gets up on the wrong side of the bed.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to be mentally tough to do what he did at Syracuse. Off
the field, he was an honor roll student. On the field, playing in
an offense famous for its complexity, he learned the plays for both
tailback and fullback _ and handled all that came with wearing the
hallowed number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I realized what the number meant to people until
I got here,'' Konrad said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been wearing No. 44 for years. He first chose it, not
because of dreams of ending up at Syracuse, but because he wanted
to be like NFL fullbacks Tom Rathman and Tommy Vardell. It was his
number at St. John's Prep, a place where they still tell stories
about No. 44.
</P>
<P>
   About how he went out for track his junior year and, seven days
after picking up the javelin for the first time, had the
third-longest throw in the nation. About how he had 103 at-bats and
never struck out. About how he arrived at St. John's wanting to be
a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day in practice, he threw a pass 62 yards in the air;
almost knocked the kid over in the end zone,'' said St. John's
football coach Jim O'Leary, chuckling at the memory. ``That's the
kind of athlete he is.''
</P>
<P>
   By his junior year of high school, he was being pursued by Notre
Dame, Southern Cal and virtually every other big-time program. But
most schools wanted him to play linebacker. He wanted to play
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse coach Paul Pasqualoni didn't just offer him a chance to
carry the ball. He walked Konrad through the school's exhibit
honoring former No. 44s _ and asked him if he wanted to become the
first fullback to wear the number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Pasqualoni sat him down, told him he had to understand
what came with it,'' O'Leary said. ``Not just the football, but
that he had to be a good citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Konrad didn't bother waiting until his senior year to make a
decision. He committed to Syracuse as a junior. And while he spent
another year growing, so did expectations.
</P>
<P>
   When he showed up for his first practice, the summer before his
freshman year of college, and drew more attention than Marvin
Harrison, a senior who would end up with the Indianapolis Colts, he
began to understand what No. 44 meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had as many people asking me for autographs as were asking
for his,'' he said. ``At that point, I realized I was an instant
celebrity just by having the number.''
</P>
<P>
   And he soon realized that being a celebrity wasn't easy. By most
standards, he had an impressive career, rushing for 1,516 yards,
catching passes for 473 yards and scoring 23 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But by No. 44 standards, it often wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   There were the injuries: a broken hand as a sophomore, a torn
hamstring as a junior, a sprained knee as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Some said he was like a skilled boxer with a glass jaw. Some
said he wasn't featured enough, often forgetting that wasn't his
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism hit home.
</P>
<P>
   This week when his mother, Betty, was asked to talk about her
only son and the youngest of two children, she called her husband
to the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say something I shouldn't when I talk to the media,''
she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Konrad took the phone and, when asked about the Rob's
personality, used the question as a chance to rebut draft analyst
Joel Buchsbaum's assertion that one of Rob's flaws is arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I never get a chance to talk to Mr. Buchsbaum,'' he
said. ``Rob has pride. Don't get me wrong. But he's not full of
himself. Mr. Buchsbaum obviously never met Rob or talked to any of
his coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Walker, his position coach for four years, scoffs at
such talk, saying that ``a lot of people would have let everything
that comes with being No. 44 go to their head, but Rob didn't ...
the Dolphins won't be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend of the draft, the consensus was that Konrad would
end up either returning home to the Boston area to play for the
Patriots or heading to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He told friends and family he was waiting until his name was
called to pick what kind of car he would buy with his signing
bonus. Durango for the north. Corvette for the south?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I get a Corvette,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Now Konrad, an avid outdoorsman, is talking excitedly about
coming to Florida, getting a boat and, of course, wearing a
Dolphins' jersey. With a 44 on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With No. 39 I might run into some problems,'' he joked,
referring to the number worn by Larry Csonka.
</P>
<P>
   Although he insists he loved being No. 44 at Syracuse, Konrad
also seems to be looking forward to being in a place where his
number isn't magical, where he's just wearing another shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be someone else. I'm not trying to be Jim
Brown. I'm just trying to be Rob Konrad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
