<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWTIZ-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSURE TOUGH TO FIND ANYWHERE IN THIS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The snow fell all Thursday, smudging the ink
of a thousand scrawled messages, bending the roses and the
carnations beneath its weight. Slush covered teddy bears.
Footprints tracked every which way. By midmorning, the park
bordering Columbine High School felt shrouded, more obscured than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   As does this story with each new day.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way these things are supposed to go, of course:
Normally after 48 hours we have gained a solid purchase on the
facts, some handhold, but in Littleton the normal techniques seem
not to apply. We have an accurate body count _ 11 males, four
females _ an inventory of firepower, a chronology, videotape enough
to circle the Earth, but no real answer to the question scratched
on a greeting card now covered in slush.
</P>
<P>
   The handwriting is a teenage girl's swirl. The signature
``Jami'' is accompanied by a heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss all of you,'' she has written. ``I don't understand
why this had to happen to us. Why?''
</P>
<P>
   The question of the day, and every day hereafter. Thinking it
through is like chasing ghosts. Two, in particular: The teenagers
who stand accused here but lay dead, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   We have heard from former friends, classmates, acquaintances,
teachers. For all they have said, we seem no closer to answering
``Who?,'' let alone ``Why?'' &QL; 
Last Saturday, Dylan Klebold went to Columbine's prom. The
17-year-old was a Boy Scout. He worked at Blackjack Pizza, favored
the Boston Red Sox, drove an old four-door Bimmer. Then there's his
house: all cedar and glass, on 5 acres. It would fit fine in north
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Just as every other fact in Klebold's biography _ the swastikas,
the goose-stepping in the halls, the roll of the dead _ seems to
fit some other story altogether.
</P>
<P>
   This also holds for Harris, 18 and equally a cipher.
</P>
<P>
   His dad, Wayne, was an Air Force pilot. Eric loved computers and
bowling. He had a thing for fireworks. How much of a thing no one
knew until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in retrospect, that knowledge doesn't help much. It gives a
little shape to the ghosts, is all. And the ghosts seem woefully
pale compared to the sentences dripping down the poster board:
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss those who are gone now. One question. Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Our response takes the form of thumbnail sketches, psychological
portraits, sleuthing in print. It seems logical: It has been done
this way for years. This is a new America, though, one with the
volume perpetually cranked high, where measurements of caliber have
replaced tests of IQ. With Columbine, the old logic fails,
especially when it tries to explain the irrational in rational
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth, with this story: There are no simple truths.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold gave off warning signs galore, say some;
precious few, say others. They were ``freaks,'' I have heard, and
``normal high school kids.'' There was an arrest for breaking into
a van; there was also an early release from the diversion program. &QL; 
Thursday, a Denver TV station got hold of the probation officer's
reports: ``Eric is a very bright young man, likely to succeed in
life,'' was the word on Harris.
</P>
<P>
   As for Klebold: ``Dylan is a bright young man who has a great
deal of potential. If he is able to tap his potential and become
self-motivated, he should do well in life.''
</P>
<P>
   More shape for the ghosts. They flutter above Littleton as snow
veils everything. A day's worth of shoes turns the white to gray.
One Columbine freshman, Joe Dreaden, now readying for two friends'
funerals, cannot stand it.
</P>
<P>
   He walks to the red Acura of his late classmate, 17-year-old
Rachel Scott, and begins to brush the snow from bouquet after
bouquet. He straightens the wet cards, moves a small wooden cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make it so the bright colors show through,'' Joe
explains. ``That's the only way maybe we can understand what
happened to our friends.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
