<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-CHILDRENDEAD-MISSI     04-23 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-CHILDRENDEAD-MISSINGMOM23 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dead children identified, missing mother sought
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer and Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After identifying two children found dead in a
creek Monday, investigators Thursday were looking for the
children's mother, Tina Marie Cornelius, a soft-spoken 22-year-old
who recently dropped the auto mechanics class she seemed intent on
completing and mysteriously disappeared from the job she held for
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they want to speak with Cornelius, who until
recently lived in a North Austin apartment, about the deaths of her
children, Dominick Cornelius, 2, and Amanda Miller, 3. Police said
Dominick was killed by a blow to the head that fractured his skull;
Amanda was suffocated, police said. The children have different
fathers who live out of state, and investigators have been unable
to reach either man.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not call Cornelius a suspect but said they are
concerned for her safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the mother of these children, and we're concerned that
we have not been able to locate her,'' said Capt. Linda Bunte of
the Williamson County sheriff's office. ``She may be endangered. We
don't know. We're trying to locate her and determine what has
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius' relatives last saw her more than a week ago, Bunte
said.
</P>
<P>
   She missed a court appearance Monday, where she was supposed to
pay a $375 fine for passing a school bus.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. Thursday, investigators issued a bulletin to area
airports and bus stations asking them to be on the lookout for
Cornelius, said Sgt. Ron Gober of the Austin Airport Police.
Cornelius was last seen wearing baggy blue jeans, a pink T-shirt
and her hair in a pony tail, according to the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   An employee of Expose(accent), a South Austin adult
entertainment club, said Cornelius had worked at the club for about
three weeks, including Tuesday, the day after her children were
found dead. ``She was totally calm,'' the woman said. A manager of
the club said that police had been to club asking questions but
that Cornelius had never worked there.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's investigators would not comment whether Cornelius
worked at the club.
</P>
<P>
   Tip from a day care
</P>
<P>
   Both children were wearing Mickey Mouse diapers under their
clothing when a Round Rock couple found them lying lifeless in
Brushy Creek just south of Hutto, a small farming town about 20
miles northeast of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The diapers were a key to solving the mystery that had dogged
investigators for three days. Employees of a Austin day-care center
recognized the sketches of the children released Tuesday, and the
description of their diapers. The workers had not seen the children
since April 14.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and co-workers said Cornelius is a hard-working single
mother who worked a full day, then spent four hours in her
mechanics class. Her co-workers at a Super Wal-Mart said she showed
up on time, worked hard and hoped one day to become an auto
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Thompson, the only other woman to work in what she called
``the pit'' of the oil-changing facility, said Cornelius seldom
spoke, but when she did, the topic was usually her children or her
desire to become a mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very gentle and soft-spoken person,'' Thompson said.
``She is sweet, really just a sweet person.''
</P>
<P>
   Another co-worker said that when his baby was born a month ago,
Cornelius promised to make them a quilt.
</P>
<P>
   `Darling' children
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors at the apartment complex remembered Tina Marie
Cornelius as a caring mother, whose adorable children often peeked
out onto the world from between the blinds of their first-floor
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just darling, absolutely darling,'' said neighbor
Holly Roth. ``I wished they would come out more because I would
have loved for my own 2-year-old to be able to play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith's children did play with Amanda in the grassy
courtyard that separated their apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty quiet and easy-going,'' he said of Cornelius.
``I can't believe she'd be involved with this. . . . This is
something that hits real close. Having them as neighbors and having
something like this happen is just appalling. First, it's
disbelief. Then, it's how? Why?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar reaction at Wal-Mart, where employees said
she sometimes brought her kids by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what happened to those kids,'' said one
employee who did not want his name used. ``I can still see them
here laughing and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   If she had to stay home with one of her kids when they were
sick, she would always call in and say so, a manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Then just before Easter, she told her colleagues she had to
leave early because she had a court appointment.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last they heard of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked a lot of people if they had heard anything from her,''
Thompson said. ``It just didn't seem right. Everyone was like,
`Nope, we haven't seen her.' And then this happened. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping for the best, or the best that can come out of
a tragedy like this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After ending work at Wal-Mart at 5 p.m., Cornelius would go to
the Capitol City Trade and Technical School, at 205 E. Riverside
Drive in Austin, where her mechanics class lasted from 6 until 10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very interested in auto mechanics and was a good
student,'' instructor Kenneth Echols said. ``She enjoyed the class
as far as I could tell.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cornelius started at the school in January, she was dating
a 24-year-old man she identified as her fiance, a school official
said. Other acquaintances said the couple later had broken up.
</P>
<P>
   In early March, she suddenly stopped attending classes without
saying why. And mail the school sent her was returned by the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could never find her,'' the school official said. ``As far
as I could tell, she was a single mother who was determined to make
it, provide a life for herself and her children. Otherwise, she
wouldn't have worked all day and come to school at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember those darling kids. They were precious little
angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
