r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     04-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEBERT VOWS HE'LL START TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ If Guy Hebert's play proves to be as sharp as his wit,
goaltending should be the least of the Mighty Ducks' problems
tonight in Game 2 of their Western Conference playoff series
against the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after being kicked in the head by the skate
of Brendan Shanahan, Hebert went through a full workout on the ice
in front of the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in here, I wasn't sure who I was,'' Hebert
joked. ``The guys told me I was (Buffalo's) Dominic Hasek, so I
feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his head, Hebert laughed and said, ``It feels
as good as it ever has.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert was knocked out midway through the second period of
Wednesday's series opener, which forced backup Tom Askey to finish
up the 5-3 loss to the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt horrible (for Tommy),'' Hebert said. ``It's an old
goaltender's creed that you never come out of the game unless
you're dead, so I guess I thought I was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On a serious note, Hebert said he never lost consciousness and
would be ready to play tonight despite waking up Thursday with a
slight headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come too far to get back in the playoffs,'' he said. ``I
think it would take wild horses to keep me out of the starting
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan went head-over-heels into Hebert after being upended by
defenseman Ruslan Salei. The Anaheim goalie was on the ice for
several anxious minutes as the Ducks' medical staff attended to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me pretty hard . . . I felt the vibrations all the way
down my body,'' he said. ``I haven't seen it and really don't want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting back to his feet, Hebert felt there was no way he
could, or should, stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been effective for 10-15 minutes,'' said
Hebert, who later resisted the urge to return. ``Tom was settling
in and I knew the guys would play hard in front of him. I didn't
want to unsettle things.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim is hoping Hebert's return in goal will help settle them
down after the young Ducks were rattled by Detroit's early
pressure. They fell behind 3-1 less than a minute into the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody was a little nervous,'' Hebert said. ``But
the first five minutes got some things out of our system. A lot of
young guys came up today and said, `I'll be a lot better tomorrow.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne scored a goal at 13:03 of the third period to pull
Anaheim within 4-3, but the NHL's leading goal scorer was held
without a shot in the first 40 minutes and was not his usual
dominating self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teemu knows he can play better and he will,'' Ducks coach
Craig Hartsburg said of his standout winger, who struggled down the
stretch with only two goals in the last eight regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, rather than dwell on the negative, tried to put a
positive spin on things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Game 2 is going to be totally different,'' he said.
``That was our first playoff game in two years. I know we will only
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard, however, to imagine Paul Kariya performing at a
higher level. Anaheim's captain had seven shots, scored on a wicked
slap shot, assisted on the Ducks' other two goals and more than
held his own against the physical Detroit defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul was great,'' Hartsburg said. ``His game rose to another
level. Everybody else has to raise their game, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
