<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI BUILDS SCHOOL VOUCHERS AND TAX CUTS INTO CITY BUDGET
PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani proposed a $35.3 billion
spending plan for New York City on Thursday, emphasizing tax cuts,
school vouchers and other initiatives favored by the national
Republican Party at a time when he has all but declared himself a
candidate for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But as Giuliani proclaimed that the city had a record surplus of
$2.1 billion, Peter Vallone, the speaker of the City Council,
questioned why the mayor had proposed cutting more than $110
million for libraries, cultural groups, youth services and other
programs. He also complained that Giuliani's tax cuts were
insufficient and his voucher plan inappropriate, setting the stage
for a battle over how to spend an unusually large pot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is a great economy, but a budget that does not go
far enough,'' Vallone said on Thursday. ``These are not good cuts.
These are not good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for $157 million in new tax cuts, Giuliani's budget plan
was almost identical to the one he proposed in January, which
called for accelerating a class of 1,500 police recruits and
building new schools with the city's anticipated share of the
settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   But while Giuliani proposed putting $6.15 billion toward school
construction in his preliminary budget, he vowed on Thursday to
withhold the money until the Board of Education presented him with
a detailed plan for spending it.
</P>
<P>
   ``By law, they were supposed to present us with a plan by March
1,'' Giuliani said. ``We really need to hold them to a very strict
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the education proposal that drew the most scrutiny on
Thursday was Giuliani's plan for an experimental voucher program,
which would use millions of tax dollars to send poor children from
a single school district to private and parochial schools. The
mayor had originally proposed administering the program through the
Board of Education, but Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew protested and
even threatened to quit.
</P>
<P>
   So in his budget presentation on Thursday, Giuliani proposed
running the program out of City Hall instead, using $12 million
from the general budget as ``incentive money'' for whichever school
district volunteers. But Crew said later in the day that he was
still adamantly opposed to the voucher proposal, and he also
expressed frustration with the mayor's plan to withhold the capital
funds.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done in recent speeches to Republican audiences around
the nation, the mayor spoke passionately about the need for
vouchers, saying the competition they created would force failing
schools to improve. ``This is where America is going to be five
years from now,'' Giuliani said. ``We've got to open up our
thinking and get out of almost the inquisitional mindset that we're
in, the box that we're in, and understand this and embrace it.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
