<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT PENGUINS, 3-1, IN PLAYOFF OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils accomplished just
about everything they could imagine in the regular season. One of
their disappointments, however, was the inability of either Petr
Sykora or Bobby Holik to become the first New Jersey players in six
years to reach the 30-goal plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora finished with 29 goals. Holik ended up with 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get my 30th in the playoffs,'' Sykora said Monday after
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, true to his word, Sykora did better than one
goal in the opening game of the playoff series against the
Pittsburgh Penguins. The 22-year-old wing from the Czech Republic
scored twice to lead the Devils to a 3-1 triumph before a crowd of
16,209 at Continental Arena, about 3,000 short of a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   The second game of the four-of-seven-game series will be played
here Saturday afternoon before the series moves to Pittsburgh for
two games, starting with a game Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora's goals were his first career playoff points. Last season
he played only two games against Ottawa as the Devils chose to go
with veterans rather than youth and the Senators eliminated the
Devils in that opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Sykora played and scored, and when Jay Pandolfo
added an empty-net goal, it sealed the victory for the Devils with
30.2 seconds left. Sharing the credit for the effort were the
players who collectively worked to limit Jaromir Jagr's
effectiveness and enrich Martin Brodeur's goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur made 24 saves, including a glove save on Kip Miller with
3 minutes 27 seconds left and another on Jagr with 2:07 left, that
earned a standing ovation. ``Marty's the reason we won the game,''
Sheldon Souray said. ``That's the kind of goalie he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's only blemish was the goal by Jan Hrdina that opened
the scoring. His saves were more timely than those of Pittsburgh's
Tom Barrasso, who faced 21 shots and stopped all but the two from
Sykora that got the Devils off on the right foot and got Sykora to
the 30-goal plateau one game late.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have been the conference's best team in the regular
season the past three seasons, but they were eliminated in the
first round last season and in the second round by the Rangers two
seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   While coach Robbie Ftorek of the Devils used all four of his
line combinations, coach Kevin Constantine of the Penguins went
primarily with three lines.
</P>
<P>
   Rotating four lines has been one of the Devils' strengths all
season and it was one of the reasons they set a record for most
victories on the road with 28, breaking Montreal's mark of 27 set
in the 1976-77 season and again a season later.
</P>
<P>
   Using four lines was also the Devils' strength in winning the
Stanley Cup under the direction of Jacques Lemaire in 1995, when
they eliminated the Penguins in five games in the Eastern
Conference semifinals en route to their first title.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr's first speedy trip through the Devils' defense set up the
first goal. He moved from left to right when he got near Brodeur
and took a shot that rebounded out in the slot, where Hrdina jumped
on it to open the scoring 7:20 into the game, beating a fallen
Brodeur over the glove.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora tied it for the Devils just 15 seconds later. Standing in
the right circle, he one-timed Patrik Elias' pass from the other
side past Barrasso for the first playoff point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora's second goal of the night came with 5:05 left in the
second, when he poked in a loose puck from the low slot over
Barrasso's stick. The goal came during confusion in Pittsburgh's
zone after Sheldon Souray entered with the puck down the right
flank.
</P>
<P>
   In the first playoff game here in which two referees were used,
a penalty to a player playing with a broken stick was called. It
occurred at 5:19 of the first period when Elias was penalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
