<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE ZIMMERMAN SHINES IN RELIEF FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates asks that pitching
coach Dick Bosman serve as the ``guardian angel'' for right-hander
Jeff Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, all the available evidence suggests that Zimmerman serves
as the Rangers' guardian angel.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman rode to the Rangers' rescue again with 1 2/3 innings
of scoreless relief during last night's 6-4 victory against the
Minnesota Twins at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked Dick Bosman to be his guardian angel,'' Oates said.
``You get tempted to let him pitch every night. I really didn't
want to take him out tonight, but he threw 20-plus pitches
\RWednesday\S night in New York and 20-plus pitches again tonight.
I've asked Boz to make sure I don't hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers continue to place Zimmerman in meaningful situations
because of the results the former TCU pitcher produces. That
includes 10 scoreless innings since being promoted April 13 from
Triple-A Oklahoma, and opponents are hitting only .065 (2-for-31)
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Another meaningful situation presented itself against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Oates summoned Zimmerman from the bullpen to protect a one-run,
sixth-inning lead for right-hander Aaron Sele (3-1) with runners
aboard first and second. Zimmerman wisely pitched around veteran
catcher Terry Steinbach and issued a four-pitch walk to load the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to give him anything to hit there,'' said
Zimmerman, who threw Steinbach sliders on the first three pitches
of the at-bat before issuing the walk on a 3-0 fastball off the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, though, stepped forward and met the intended
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Cristian Guzman stepped to the plate with an
opportunity to deliver two runs with a base hit, but the Rangers'
26-year-old rookie abused the Twins' 21-year-old rookie during the
evening's most significant at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman placed Guzman at a distinct disadvantage after the
shortstop took a 1-1 slider for a second strike and then induced a
weak ground ball with another slider on the ensuing pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile fielded the ball cleanly and _ despite
apparently losing track of the number of outs in the inning _
retired first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz at the plate with an
accurate throw to catcher Gregg Zaun.
</P>
<P>
   Threat over.
</P>
<P>
   Another meaningful situation, and yet none of them appears to
faze Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get so focused on the catcher that I don't even see the
hitter up there,'' he said. ``I think I've really prepared myself
for this moment. I've dedicated myself to baseball. I've done
everything I could do to be here, and that gives me peace of
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers failed to make the evening easy by continuing to
struggle at the plate, this time against Twins left-hander Eric
Milton. The Rangers, who scored only twice during their two-game
series with the Yankees and entered last night's contest hitting
.205 for the past five games, managed only two runs against Milton
through the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro, who entered the game 0-for-14
this season against left-handers, put an end to that streak with a
mammoth, 412-foot home run to center field off Milton during the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Lee Stevens also continued his more-than-adequate
job against left-handers by hitting his team-best fifth home run
against Milton during the third inning that gave the Rangers a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sele made that stand until running into trouble during the sixth
inning, but Zimmerman gave the Rangers an opportunity to break the
game open with their four-run eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive two-run, eighth-inning doubles by center Roberto
Kelly and left fielder Rusty Greer snapped the Rangers' 0-for-25
drought with runners in scoring position and gave the Rangers an
insurmountable 6-1 lead.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
