<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABUSER-LIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE SOUGHT IN LISTING ALL THOSE ACCUSED OF CHILD ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, a stranger approached Michael Divon in a grocery
store. How, she asked, did his 6-year-old son get that ugly bruise
on his face? Divon explained that Jonathan had fallen against a
sandbox in the school playground.
</P>
<P>
   Divon thought it a little odd when the woman followed him home
in her car.
</P>
<P>
   A few nights later a state child abuse investigator knocked at
his door. The woman from the store, it turned out, had reported
Divon's license plate number, along with her suspicion that Divon
was a child abuser.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation soon was debunked; Jonathan Divon's schoolyard
accident was witnessed by two teachers. But Michael and Donna
Divon, of Hastings, N.Y., have not been able to put the incident
behind them. Try as they might, they cannot get their names off a
state registry of people accused of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the scarlet letter they kind of erase, but they
don't get it all off,'' Mrs. Divon said. ``I have this scarlet
letter on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1973, the registry, which is open to child abuse
investigators but not the public, contains about a million names,
of alleged abusers and their victims. For more than two decades,
names had been taken off the list whenever investigators determined
the allegations were unfounded _ that is, that there wasn't enough
evidence to substantiate the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1995, Elisa Izquierdo, 6, was killed in by her mother
though she had repeatedly come to the attention of child welfare
workers in New York City. In response to a public outcry, state
legislators changed the registry rules to prevent unfounded cases
from being expunged until 10 years after the 18th birthday of the
youngest child in the alleged abuser's family.
</P>
<P>
   The Divons are among those supporting a proposed amendment to
state law that would allow the wrongfully accused to get their
names removed from the list sooner. Under the proposal, sponsored
by State Sen.r Nick Spano, a Republican, and State Assemblyman
Richard Brodsky, a Democrat, both of Westchester County, people
seeking to have their names removed would have to provide ``clear
and convincing evidence'' of their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Two previous attempts to change the law failed over
disagreements about how much proof would be required. Spano and
Brodsky said they were optimistic about getting the law changed
this year, but the amendment's chances are unclear. Gov. George
Pataki has been noncommittal on supporting such an amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky said the abuse registry should balance investigators'
needs for complete records against the privacy concerns of the
wrongfully accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the law isn't doing that when you have people who were
the victims of a terrible tragedy and then they have to come back
and face a lifetime of inquiries,'' he said. ``I suspect the number
of people who ought not be on this list is in the hundreds or the
thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrance McGrath, a spokesman for the State Office of Children
and Family Services, said his agency has not yet analyzed the
proposed change.
</P>
<P>
   ``But remember,'' he said, ``this is not a list available to
everyone. It's simply an investigative tool for future
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Divon, a florist, and her husband, a psychiatric nurse,
worry that their continued existence in the registry will somehow
come back to haunt them. ``What happens later on?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Months after the schoolyard mishap, Jonathan Divon fell again at
summer camp and scratched his face. His parents demanded a written
report about the accident, which they carried with them for weeks,
just in case another stranger approached in another grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have it in my wallet,'' Divon said. ``You never
know.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
