A0051 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-POLO-LADN-(SLANG)     04-23 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-POLO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S DURLEY TRIES PLAIN HARD WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGLES _ Many athletes cringe at the thought of their coach
yelling at them, even though the coach's main objective is probably
to motivate or make them better.
</P>
<P>
   Not Jennifer Durley.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me, `Please don't stop. Keep criticizing me. I know
it's in my best interest,' '' USC water polo coach Jovan Vavic said
of his sophomore two-meter player. ``That tells you about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Durley has developed into the third-leading scorer on the No.
1-ranked team in the nation. The Trojans begin play today in the
Southern California regional tournament at UC San Diego, with a
berth in next month's national tournament going to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Her 28 goals this season helped her earn All-Mountain Pacific
Sports Federation and All-MPSF Tournament First-Team honors. But
Durley's success wasn't a sure thing when Vavic recruited her out
of Thousand Oaks High. She played just two seasons in high school
and received a scholarship because Vavic liked her potential.
</P>
<P>
   The coach knew Durley was right for the program. She had the
height (6-feet-2), and she had the background.
</P>
<P>
   Durley's father, Brick, who is 6-5, is a former assistant
football coach at Tulsa, New Mexico and Hawaii. There was
discipline in the Durley house, so Vavic knew Jennifer could handle
his demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad taught me you can tell a coach, when he stops talking
to you, that's when you worry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Brick would ever stop talking to his oldest daughter.
As with many athletically inclined parents, Brick coached Jennifer
through softball, basketball and soccer, telling her whatever she
did, ``Do it at full speed, try to be the best fundamentally and go
all out. Coaches will appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was her father who led Durley into aquatics. A friend of
Brick's was involved in a junior-lifeguard program, and Jennifer
thought it would be fun because the family often made trips to Zuma
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Brick knew a junior lifeguard had to be able to swim long
distances. So one day he and 9-year-old Jennifer swam the 150 yards
from the beach to a buoy and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when she got the confidence she could do it like the
big boys,'' Brick said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only could Durley swim, she could swim fast and for
distance. She regularly won lifeguard contests that included
swimming 1,000 yards or paddling on a board 800 yards in the open
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   At USC, Durley has impressed her teammates with her desire to
improve and her ability to handle a coach's criticism. She often
comes to practice early to ride a stationary bicycle for an hour,
or will stay afterward to work on her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think highly of her,'' said roommate and teammate Kim
Camacho. ``I'd like to be like her. She gives everything 100
percent. That's the way I should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The work, coupled with Vavic's demanding style, has toughened
Durley to the point that she laughs at other players who
occasionally try to advise her in practice or after a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won't let anyone do that,'' said senior goalie Bernice
Orwig, who often tries to order Durley around but gets nowhere.
``People tell her what to do, and she says, `No, I'm a senior
member of this team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her development has caused pride all around, from coach, father
and herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants it more,'' Vavic said. ``There's nothing worse
than a talented player who's not utilizing their talent.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WOMEN'S WATER POLO &QL; 
__ What: Southern California Western Regional &QL; 
__ Where: UC San Diego &QL; 
__ Who: Seven teams, incuding top-seeded USC and second-seeded
UCLA &QL; 
__ When: Today through Sunday &QL; 
__ At stake: Four berths in the NCAA National Tournament &QL; 
__ Analysis: They really make it easy for the top teams to advance
to the May 7-9 nationals. All USC or UCLA have to do is win their
first two matches and they're in. USC opens today at 2 p.m. against
third-seeded San Diego State, then plays UCLA Saturday at 2 p.m.
UCLA plays twice Saturday, starting with San Diego State at 9 a.m.
If the teams have defeated San Diego State when they meet, then the
loser will have to win just one of two matches Sunday to secure a
berth.
</P>
<P>
   __ USC: The Trojans (24-2) have the advantage, having beaten
three-time national champion UCLA four times but never by more than
two goals. Goalies Bernice Orwig (USC) and Erin Golaboski (UCLA)
are among the nation's best. Freshman Aniko Pelle leads the Trojans
with 42 goals, followed by Nina Wengst with 32 goals and Thousand
Oaks graduate Jennifer Durley with 28 goals. &QL; 
__ UCLA: The Bruins (18-8) are without three players who are
redshirting the season to compete on the U.S. national team. The
Bruins' coach, Guy Baker, is coaching the national team, so Adam
Krikorian is the interim head coach. Freshman Elaine Zivich scored
a team-high 48 goals.
</P>
