<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TURNPIKE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 MEN IN N.J. TURNPIKE SHOOTING FILE SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A year ago, a seemingly random traffic stop placed
them at the center of a public outcry over racial profiling,
triggering numerous investigations into its practice, and if the
pronouncements of public officials hold true, its end.
</P>
<P>
   But when Leroy Jarmaine Grant, one of three young black and
Hispanic men shot by state troopers on the New Jersey Turnpike a
year ago, spoke about his experience Thursday, he did so not as a
symbol of a civil rights crusade but as a young man in pain. ``I
just want to tell you all it has been a hard-fought year for all
four of us,'' Grant said, after lawyers for him and his companions
announced that they were filing a civil suit against the state, the
New Jersey State Police, the troopers and their supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future's just been snatched, for no reason,'' he said, so
overcome by emotion that he could barely speak. ``To this day, I
still don't know why we got shot. It's been mentally, physically
hard for us. The bullets are still lodged in our bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, 1998, Grant, who is black, and three friends,
Daniel Reyes, Rayshawn Brown and Keshon Moore, were driving in a
van to a basketball tryout at North Carolina Central University.
Two troopers, James Kenna and John Hogan, pulled them over,
although they say they were not speeding, and fired 11 shots into
the van after it began to roll backward. Grant and Brown, who is
black, and Reyes, who is Hispanic, were wounded. Moore, who is
black, was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout since has seen the dismissal of the superintendent
of the state troopers, the convening of two grand juries and the
start of investigations by federal and state authorities into the
practice of racial profiling _ making stops and searches based on
the race or ethnicity of motorists _ which civil rights lawyers and
even many troopers have long maintained is practiced on the New
Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, a grand jury indicted the troopers, both of
whom are white, on charges of falsely reporting the race of black
motorists as white to disguise racial profiling. And on Tuesday,
Gov. Christie Whitman conceded that an investigation showed that
racial profiling was indeed being practiced on the turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   For Grant, that admission did not come soon enough. ``Christie
Whitman, the governor, as a parent, I want to know why couldn't she
acknowledge us, as a parent, not as a political leader, but as a
parent,'' he said. ``Why didn't she come forward and give an
apology about what happened, and that racial profiling did exist
all these years and was ignored?''
</P>
<P>
   One of Grant's lawyers, Johnnie Cochran Jr., was more blunt. He
called racial profiling a ``cancer'' and said, ``If we don't get
public officials who are responsive to these problems, they should
be voted out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's colleague, Peter Neufeld, said that there had been
``overwhelming evidence'' of racial profiling for a decade and that
he believed state officials were aware of it. ``All of this could
have been changed long ago, and if it had been changed long ago the
bottom line is, that these four men wouldn't be standing here today
with their lives cut short by this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who was the only one of the four men to speak at a news
conference Thursday at his lawyers' offices in lower Manhattan,
described months of therapy and operations. ``The injuries will
prevent us from playing the game we love the most, and that's
basketball,'' he said. ``That's all we want to do _ just have a
future, provide for our family and friends. We're good kids.
There's no criminal record for any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed in Superior Court of New Jersey but
also includes some claims under federal law, seeks unspecified
damages, saying that the young men all had the potential for
athletic scholarships and promising basketball careers. It also
seeks injunctive relief to end racial profiling and any practices
that encourage it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the suit's claims are that racial profiling was a
well-known practice among troopers and that it was encouraged by
supervisors and ignored by state officials for years. The suit
asserts that troopers Hogan and Kenna denied the young men medical
care after they were shot, strip-searching them instead.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also asserts that the stop itself was illegal and
discriminatory because it was made solely on the grounds of race.
Linda Kenney, the lawyer for Keshon Moore, noted that the
indictment charging the two troopers with falsely recording the
race of motorists indicates that they filed one such false report
just 50 minutes before the four young men were stopped and shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
