<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SLIDE AT FIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Mo Vaughn returned with a bang, but the Angels
finished their three-game series against the Toronto Blue Jays with
a thud.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the previous 14 games with a sprained left ankle,
Vaughn hit the first pitch he saw Thursday an estimated 451 feet to
center field for a two-run homer in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to inspire the Angels, who built a five-run lead. But
the Blue Jays, the hottest team in baseball, rallied for an 8-7 win
before 28,212 at SkyDome to complete a three-game sweep and extend
their winning streak to eight games.
</P>
<P>
   After his homer, Vaughn flied to center, grounded to second and
struck out. The game ended when Matt Walbeck struck out with Vaughn
on deck.
</P>
<P>
   For the Angels, the loss was their fifth in a row and was
something even Vaughn couldn't stop. But if there was a positive
for the Angels, it's that Vaughn's ankle was fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tweak the ankle so it's another day of progress,''
Vaughn said. ``It's a gradual process. I know my game and what I
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also said he felt comfortable at the plate despite not
hitting in a live game since April 6. The home run hit a window of
the restaurant ``Windows'' about 50 feet above the center-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is I had a decent approach,'' Vaughn said.
``You try to swing at strikes. I'm an aggressive hitter. I believe
in three strikes _ you use all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad and Garret Anderson each followed Vaughn's lead
with two-run homers, Erstad's coming in the second inning and
Anderson's in the fifth. But the Blue Jays rallied against Angels
starter Tim Belcher with long balls of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green and Darrin Fletcher each hit two-run homers in the
fifth inning, and Pat Kelly hit two homers, the second tying the
game at 7 in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one's clearly on me,'' said Belcher, who gave up six runs
and 10 hits in 42/3 innings but didn't get the loss. ``If your
starter can't hold a 7-2 lead, there's trouble. You can't expect
the bullpen to do miracles for you. You can't expect the offense to
keep pounding out runs. Seven runs in four innings is clearly
enough. . . . I got killed. I got my (rear) beat. What else can you
say?''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays scored the winning run with a bloop single and
three walks. Tony Fernandez, who reached base five times (three
singles, two walks), walked on a 3-2 pitch from Troy Percival with
two out in the eighth inning to drive in Kelly with what turned out
to be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in trying to throw fastballs as hard as I can,''
Percival said. ``He fouled off some good pitches. It was a good
at-bat by him. With the last pitch I got too fancy, I should have
thrown the ball down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival hadn't pitched in a game since April 17 and has had
only one save opportunity all season, which came on opening night.
But he wouldn't use his lack of activity as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be ready in that situation,'' he said. ``I don't
need any excuses made for me. I didn't do the job. I should have
done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fun situation for me. Bases loaded in a tie ballgame.
You have to relish that. You win or you lose. Today we lost. I had
a chance to get us back in the dugout and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough loss for the Angels, especially considering the
importance manager Terry Collins placed on it before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night right now is big, very big. We need to break it
(losing streak) and get it going,'' Collins said. ``Tonight's the
biggest game we've played thus far this season.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Vaughn said there's no reason to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team's going to be fine,'' he said. ``We just need to
make sure we stay together and have a strong attitude. It'll turn
for us. When it does, it'll be like wildfire. When you're in a
slump for four or five games, the first one is always the toughest
to get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
