<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-OJAI-LADN-(SLANG)     04-23 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OJAI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSETS RUIN BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Another year, another early exit for UCLA's
Jean-Noel Grinda in the Pacific-10 singles championship at the 99th
annual Ojai Valley tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an injured elbow and inexperience derailed Grinda in
the first round. On Thursday, it was a sloppy net game and the
tenacity of unseeded Michel Stopa of Arizona that knocked the
second-seeded Grinda, ranked fourth in the country, out in the
opening round, 7-6, 4-6, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year he doesn't have an excuse,'' said UCLA coach Billy
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Grinda quickly left Libbey Park after the loss and wasn't around
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It was a surprisingly bad day for the No. 1 Bruins, whose four
players were eliminated on the first day. In fact, only Calabasas
graduate Jason Cook made it to the second round after beating
Oregon's Thomas Schneiter 7-6, 7-5 to open play Thursday. But Cook
later fell to Arizona State's Gustavo Marcaccio 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a little break now before the NCAA tournament (in
May,) and we've been going pretty hard the last month so we can use
it,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It was a better day for the USC men's team with Patrick
Gottesleben advancing to today's quarterfinals with wins over
Washington's Christopher Kull, 6-4, 7-5, and Stanford's K.J.
Hippensteel, 6-3, 6-3. Teammate Andrew Park made it to the second
round but lost 6-4, 6-3 to Stanford's Ryan Wolters.
</P>
<P>
   In women's play, USC's Kara Warkentin and Jacqui Boyd and UCLA's
Annic Cooper, the defending champion, all advanced to today's
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Grinda rallied in the third set to force the tiebreaker, staving
off four match points to break Stopa and tie the set 5-5. Grinda
held serve to go up 6-5, but Stopa dominated on serve to tie it
6-6. He overpowered Grinda 6-2 in the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you miss four match points, it gets to you and it's
pretty easy to get frustrated and let up,'' Stopa said. ``But I
told myself that I'd been out there for three hours already,
another 10 minutes wasn't going to hurt me in a match this big. I
got some lucky shots and I hit some good shots in the tiebreaker
and things worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who watched nervously as Grinda fought off elimination
to pull even in the third set, was impressed with the way Stopa
rebounded to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Grinda broke serve), I thought he was in good shape, but
(Stopa) kept his head and did a good job,'' Martin said. ``I
thought (Jean-Noel) hit some bad forehands in the tiebreaker, I
thought he shot himself in the foot a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopa went up 4-0 in the tiebreaker, then easily closed out the
win.
</P>
<P>
   With the NCAA tournament starting in May, Grinda had hoped to
use Ojai as a final tuneup. Now he has to put the loss behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tournament like this, with 32 top players, I'm not sure
anything is an upset,'' Martin said. ``But hopefully this shows
(Jean-Noel) that he has to be ready to play everytime he steps on
the court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
