<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MAY GO TO FOUR-MAN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Manager Johnny Oates says the Rangers might use a
four-man rotation beginning May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The concept emerged after the injury to starter John Burkett,
whom the Rangers placed on the 15-day disabled list with stiffness
in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled left-handed reliever Mike Venafro from
Triple-A Oklahoma to replace Burkett on the roster. Right-hander
Rick Helling is scheduled to assume Burkett's turn in the rotation
Sunday with three days rest, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers prefer that Esteban Loaiza remain in his role as a
long reliever, where he has flourished of late, Oates said. The
Rangers also prefer another left-handed reliever for the bullpen
with the number of quality left-handed hitters the Rangers will see
against the Minnesota Twins, New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians
during the next week, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need another starter until \RMay 1\S, if then,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starting pitchers entered last night's game averaging
only 87.5 pitches per appearance, which increases the likelihood of
the four-man rotation becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it'll work, but I'm willing to try anything,''
Oates said. ``Maybe it'll never get past'' May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Oates spoke to Helling about the possibility Wednesday, and the
pitcher responded favorably. Mike Morgan and Aaron Sele also
reacted positively to the idea, Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that hasn't been tried before,'' Oates
said. ``I'm not inventing the egg. We could be back in a five-man
rotation \RMay 1\S. Loaiza could be starting.''
RODRIGUEZ EXAMINED
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers sent catcher Ivan Rodriguez for X-rays after a
first-inning collision at the plate with Twins right-fielder Matt
Lawton forced him to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Steubs, the Twins' physician, examined Rodriguez, who
complained of dizziness after Lawton's forearm hit him in the left
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton, who was trying to score from second base on an infield
single, left the game after the second inning with a bruised right
shoulder.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Burkett is scheduled to be examined Monday by Dr. James Andrews
in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Simms (torn left Achilles' tendon) suffered another setback
in his attempt to rejoin the Rangers by Tuesday. Simms did not play
in Oklahoma's 7-2 victory yesterday against Tacoma. The Rangers
expect Simms to start tonight at first base for his first
appearance in the field since beginning his medical rehabilitation
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of injuries forced the Rangers to promote outfielders
Corey Wright and Ernise Baez from their extended spring program to
Class-A Savannah. The Sand Gnats placed three players _ shortstop
David Meliah (fracture in right wrist), outfielder Antwon Rollins
(fracture bone outside right wrist) and pitcher Carlos Figueroa
(strained left shoulder) _ on the disabled list.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
