</P>
<P>
   Seselj and Draskovic were once close friends who jointly founded
a (now defunct) political party; each was best man at the other's
wedding. Now they are at loggerheads.
</P>
<P>
   Seselj wants Yugoslavia to make parliamentary and military pacts
with Russia and Belarus, while Draskovic says Serbia must still
seek amity with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign peacekeepers, says Draskovic, should be allowed
into Kosovo, but none from NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   He also claims credit for countermanding an order from Serbia's
information minister, who belongs to Seselj's Radicals, expelling
all foreign correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, the Radicals have won more influence
than Draskovic's lot over the press and the security services.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Milosevic plays the two parties off against
each other. For the moment, unity is all. But Milosevic is probably
keeping his options open.
</P>
<P>
   If he felt he had to negotiate with NATO, he might use
