<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLY-AZR &LR;      04-23 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEER VALLEY MOURNS FRIEND SLAIN IN COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BRENT WHITING  
 Bill MULLER and  
 CONNIE CONE SEXTON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was a gentle, quiet girl with long hair and a wry sense of
humor. A people-pleaser who wanted to be remembered for her
writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember some students over your lifetime; she was one of
them,'' said Judy Dolan, a mathematics teacher at Desert Sky Middle
School. ``Kelly was a gentle soul, just a lovely person.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Fleming, 16, who was killed in the Littleton, Colo.,
school massacre, was mourned Thursday by former classmates and
teachers in the northwest Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, her eyes moist, described Kelly as a naturally quiet and
reserved student who sat at the front of the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``She liked to show her work,'' Dolan said. ``She was careful
and meticulous. She wanted to please you.''
</P>
<P>
   In her memory, trees will be planted next Friday on Arbor Day at
three campuses in the Deer Valley Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was gunned down at Columbine High School, where she was a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   The Flemings' middle-class neighborhood in Littleton is one of
winding streets lined with split-level homes. Manicured lawns were
covered with snow Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The family left Arizona in 1997 when Donald Fleming's job
transfered him to Colorado. Kelly didn't take it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a teenager,'' the father said Thursday night. ``Not very
good. She had some really good friends down there. Who wants to get
up and leave at that age?''
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been 18 months since Kelly and her family left,
her death resounded through both Desert Sky and Bellair Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly liked to write stories based on her life experiences, said
Joy Carrell, 15, a Deer Valley High School sophomore who had been
close with Kelly since sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was learning to play the guitar. She said Kelly was eager
to get a driver's license and a part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me in a letter that she wanted to be remembered for
her writing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her short stories offered a glimpse of a sensitive soul full of
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   In one short story, she wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt there was nowhere to turn, no place to run to. Right
then and there, it felt like I forgot where I was, I forgot who I
was. I didn't feel whole anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the story she finds happiness at the end: ``I felt happy
and safe. From that moment on, I knew that I wasn't going to feel
sad or alone anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrell's heart was in her throat as she scanned TV news
accounts of the shooting, hoping for happy news about her friend.
</P>
<P>
   Her worst fears began to be realized when she telephoned Kelly's
parents that evening and learned that her friend was among the
missing students.
</P>
<P>
   Carrell said that despite the bad news, she tried to keep up
hope that Kelly somehow still was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I realize that she is really gone and I won't get phone
calls from her and I can't write her and she can't write me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's father, tense with waiting for word on his daughter's
whereabouts, didn't need formal notification.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew by 4 o'clock in the afternoon, not by notification,''
he said. ``Kelly was always in the library at that time of the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said he also got a phone call from a friend of Kelly who
said she had seen Kelly on her way to the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``So obviously, when the last of the students were out and there
was still no Kelly, it didn't take much to figure it out,'' he
said. ``The official notification came late last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming was still in a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I feel, I really don't,'' he said. ``We're
hanging in there. Acceptance-wise, I don't know if we have. Maybe
we have. I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Kelly was close to her sister, liked music and
poetry, and had gone to the prom Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kelly was happy in Colorado, Carrell said her friend
dreamed of returning to Arizona. During a phone call April 16,
their last conversation, Kelly talked of making a summer visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was kind of shy, but she was very nice,'' Carrell said.
</P>
<P>
   People who took the opportunity to get to know Kelly soon found
a sweet, loving and caring personality, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't mean or hateful in any way,'' Carrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, who has 11 brothers and sisters, said the outpouring of
support has been unbelievable. He said United Airlines has given
the family free round-trip airfare. At last count, Best Western had
donated 15 or 16 free rooms. Pizza Hut is giving them free pizza
when they call, and the funeral costs _ casket and transportation _
no charge.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said he doesn't second-guess moving his family to
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scoured the whole city looking for the right community. In
fact, our Realtor was a retired principal and he even recommended
this community. It's still a great community. It's still a great
school. We didn't make a mistake moving here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
