<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-TOP-FUEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP FUEL DRAG CHAMPION STRUGGLING IN THE CLUTCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ The five-disc clutch is turning the National Hot
Rod Association's Top Fuel points chase absolutely topsy-turvy.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers Mike Dunn, Doug Herbert and Larry Dixon _ whose tuners
have mastered the vagaries of drag racing's hottest innovation _
have bolted to the top of the standings after four of 22 Winston
Drag Racing Series national events.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, two-time and reigning Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi
began the season with three first-round losses. And then it got
worse for Team Winston. Scelzi and owner/tuner Alan Johnson failed
to qualify for the 16-car ladder at the O'Reilly Nationals at
Houston Raceway Park on April 10, the first DNQ in their heretofore
storybook, 48-race Top Fuel careers.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread to these performances traces to the ``clutch
can'' area of the drivetrain. The nitromethane-burning,
500-cubic-inch engines seated in the back of a Top Fuel dragster
typically produce 6,000 horsepower. The trick is to transfer all
that power through the drivetrain to the rear tires. That is the
job of the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   What started as an experiment by some Top Fuel and Funny Car
teams in 1998 _ the addition of an extra, 3-pound composite clutch
disc to the four in use _ has developed into a must-have
performance part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we needed the five-disc clutch this season, because
the four-disc was at its limit,'' said Dunn, who has forged a
32-point lead over Herbert heading into first-round qualifications
for the Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes these things run is fuel system and clutch,'' said
Dunn, driver of the Team Mopar Dragster owned by Darrell Gwynn and
tuned by Ken Veney. ``The more fuel you burn, the more power you
make and the faster you run. The five-disc clutch has been a little
more forgiving, and it's making all the cars more consistent. Our
car, if we can get it 80 or 100 feet down the track, we feel it's
going to run good numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was wallowing in a winless streak stretching to 1996 when
he defeated Dixon in the final of the season opener at Pomona,
Calif., on Feb. 8. Dunn also won Round 3 at Gainesville, Fla.
Despite a first-round loss against Texan Eddie Hill at Baytown on
April 11, Dunn is scheduled to roll into the staging lanes at the
all-concrete Motorplex with the combination to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert and Dick LaHaie, the 1987 NHRA Top Fuel champion and
tuner of the Snap-On Tools Dragster, used their five-disc system at
Baytown to end a series winless streak that dated to June 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the five-disc has helped consistency with our
car, but not the speed so much,'' said Herbert, who also cashed in
the $100,000 Winston No Bull Challenge bonus with his victory over
Tony Schumacher. ``The five-disc is definitely making it easy to
apply all this extra power.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher and crew chief Dan Olson applied enough power to the
Exide Batteries car to record the first quarter-mile pass in excess
of 330 mph at Phoenix on Feb. 28. Schumacher's first-round pass at
300.23 mph is the fastest speed in NHRA history.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dixon attacked the elapsed-time half of the
performance equation at Baytown, where he became the first driver
to crack the 4.5-second barrier. Dixon ran 4.486 seconds in the
Miller Lite Dragster owned by former Funny Car champion Don ``The
Snake'' Prudhomme and tuned by Dale Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys that are running well and setting the speed and
elapsed-time records, 80 percent of it can be attributed to the
five-disc,'' said Cory McClenathan, driver of the MBNA Dragster
tuned by Mike Green and the winner of six races in 1998. ``There is
so much more parity in the class this year. I highly doubt that
anybody is going to win six races, whether it's me or Scelzi or
anybody. If a guy wins four races, he's going to be pretty proud.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
