<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-Y2K-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COUNTRY LIVING' BECOMING THE BIBLE FOR Y2K HOME PREPAREDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Y2K bug may or may not bite, but worries about
massive computer problems when 1999 turns 2000 are already spinning
a web of profits for Sasquatch Books of Seattle, due to the sudden
popularity of one reprint paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Emery's ``The Encyclopedia of Country Living'' (Sasquatch,
864 pages, $27.95) is apparently becoming the Bible for those
concerned about having to rely on their wits and skills should
there be a computer nightmare. Her massive tome is a folksy, but
authoritative do-it-yourself guide to just about everything, from
buying land to slaughtering a pig to cooking on a wood stove to
delivering a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Sasquatch purchased reprint rights and had enjoyed steady sales
ever since its first edition in 1994, with 8,000 copies sold in
1995 and 8,700 sold in 1996. But suddenly last summer, sales
started to take off, from 2,500 copies sold last August, then 7,000
last October and finally 10,600 copies last month.
</P>
<P>
   The spike in sales at first mystified folks at Sasquatch, until
sales director Linda Stark started to question some of those
ordering the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious that worries about Y2K were definitely
propelling the sales,'' Stark said this week.
</P>
<P>
   So staggering has been the growth in sales that ``The
Encyclopedia of Country Living'' has just become the first single
edition of a title to earn Sasquatch more than $1 million. And the
profits from this one book, Stark added, have played a significant
role in Sasquatch's recent expansions into Northern California and
Alaska, as well as the doubling of its annual number of titles to
25.
</P>
<P>
   Emery's guide to self-sufficiency is a homespun success itself,
first self-published with 875 mimeographed copies in 1974 and
distributed to friends by subscription only. The author lived on a
three-acre farm in Lewiston, Idaho, during the years of initial
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Emery, 60, has continually expanded her landmark book ever
since, while also driving herself around the country to spread its
gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Encyclopedia of Country Living'' is now in its ninth
edition, with 350,000 copies sold.
</P>
<P>
   Writers honored
</P>
<P>
   Michael Byers of Seattle, who won a Whiting Writers Award last
year, has won the Sue Kaufman Prize for First Fiction presented by
the American Academy of Arts and Letters. Byers' marvelous
short-story collection, ``The Coast of Good Intentions,'' was
chosen over all other first books of fiction and poetry for the
prize, which carries a $2,500 award.
</P>
<P>
   Byers, now working on his first novel, expects to attend the May
19 awards ceremony in New York. ``How often is this kind of thing
going to happen?'' the Seattle native said.
</P>
<P>
   Also being honored at the same ceremony will be Jon Krakauer,
the former Seattle resident who now lives in Colorado. Krakauer,
author of ``Into Thin Air'' (now 2 million copies in print), will
be one of eight writers receiving Academy Awards in Literature for
exceptional accomplishment (which includes $7,500).
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer said Wednesday that he was surprised by the honor:
``The academy is the type of high-brow organization that doesn't
seem as though it would be disposed to my work, so that makes this
award even more meaningful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer added that he is ``waiting to be struck by
inspiration for my next book,'' while also serving as guest editor
of a series of reissued adventure classics being published by the
Modern Library.
</P>
<P>
   Poet Heather McHugh of Seattle was recently among nine poets
named to the board of chancellors of the Academy of American Poets.
Last fall, the much-honored professor at the University of
Washington received the O.B Hardison Poetry Prize (honoring a poet
who excels at teaching) from the Folger Shakespeare Library in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Wells' ``Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' is the
favorite book sold last year by independent booksellers. The
popular Seattle writer will receive the 1999 ABBY Award of the
American Booksellers Association at next weekend's BookExpo America
in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
