<SLUG> BC-WATSON-STAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING FAMILY SHINES ON HOLLYWOOD WALK OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They may be among the least-known actors ever to
get a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame but the 11 members of the
Watson family who collectively appeared in more than 1,000 films
since 1912 scored a first Thursday _ they were honored with a
plaque on Hollywood Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The Watsons appeared in small roles in a number of Hollywood
classics _ from ``Keystone Kops'' movies to ``Boys Town,'' ``Mr.
Smith Goes to Washington'' and ``Heidi.''
</P>
<P>
   They are considered the first family of Hollywood, said Johnny
Grant, honorary mayor of Hollywood and chairman of the Walk of Fame
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1912 to the present, the Watson family has left an
indelible mark on the moviegoing public,'' he told a crowd of more
than 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the event wearing name tags stuck to their
foreheads were Harry, Garry, Billy, Coy Jr. and Delmar Watson and
their sister Louise Watson Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nine children, Vivian and Gloria, have died. Bobs
Watson is ailing and listened to the proceedings from his Laguna
Beach home via a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Delmar, acting as the family spokesman, choked up while thanking
the crowd. ``From all the Watson family,'' he said, ``God bless.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as inveterate pranksters, the Watsons refrained from
shenanigans during the ceremony in front of 6674 Hollywood Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hit anybody with a pie at the drop of a hat,'' said
Billy Watson, mentioning the late Sheriff Eugene Biscailuz and the
late Police Chief William Parker as two noteworthy victims.
</P>
<P>
   The nine Watson children grew up in Los Angeles' Edendale
neighborhood across the street from the Mack Sennett Studio. Their
father, Coy Sr., started out in Hollywood breaking horses for Buck
Jones, then began appearing in films. He also designed some of the
first movie special effects, such as Douglas Fairbanks' midair
rope-climbing scene in 1924's ``The Thief of Bagdad.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, Grant told the crowd that Coy Sr. would go
to work dressed as a cowboy and gallop over a hill, take a lunch
break and then dress up as an Indian ``and chase himself over the
same hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the family lived near the studio, casting directors
would come over and ask to use one or more of the children in
films. Most of the Watson children got their start in movies before
they were even a year old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going Hollywood before Hollywood was even going,''
said Delmar, who played Peter the Goat Boy opposite Shirley Temple
in ``Heidi'' and who hands Jimmy Stewart a new briefcase in ``Mr.
Smith Goes to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Coy Sr. wasn't thrilled about his three daughters getting too
involved in the business ``because he had been a casting
director,'' Delmar said.
</P>
<P>
   All the boys later became news photographers. Bobs, who last
year had a role in a movie called ``Deadly Delusions,'' due to be
released this year, is the one who really loved the movie business,
said Delmar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is a fantastic place but it has a tendency to chew
people up and spit them out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The star for the Watsons was special for fans as well as family.
Kim Bowness and her father, Bill, came from Tempe, Ariz., to see
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinated by child actors, Kim founded Watson Watchers
International about 10 years ago after meeting Delmar. Now it has
about 60 members and her family visits the Watson family regularly,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another fan, Rick Matzner of Los Angeles, nominated the family
to Grant's Walk of Fame committee, which approved the star.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bowness: ``We've been praying it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
