u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-23 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW'S NEUHEISEL TAKES CONTROL WITH AUTHORITY, EASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ We are walking out the tunnel, the famous one at Husky
Stadium, and we are walking fast toward sunlight. Rick Neuheisel
has a little post-practice business to take care of with two of his
football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a reminder,'' the new Husky coach said Thursday,
keeping the pace brisk.
</P>
<P>
   A ``reminder'' is another way of saying Neuheisel was about to
make offensive tackle Joe Collier and nose tackle Toalei
Mulitauaopele run penalty sprints while the rest of the team
showered and discussed what's for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe here missed a class today,'' Neuheisel announces.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you like your parents to read about that in the
paper?''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Collier doesn't look too thrilled, even though he is
attempting a brave smile to quash any hint of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is little room for errors, blown assignments or
missed classes in Neuheisel's football program.
</P>
<P>
   If the perception of laid-back sloppiness has accompanied the
38-year-old coach to Montlake from Colorado, it does not seem
entirely fair, just as knocks against his coaching acumen seem
hollow in the face of Neuheisel's .702 winning percentage (33-14)
as a college head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The former UCLA quarterback and boy-wonder Buffaloes head coach
has eased away from the cowboy hats and guitar-strumming image.
Accountability is a major issue for Neuheisel, which explains why
Husky players have been dropping to the ground for ``reminder''
push-ups and various other minor punishments.
</P>
<P>
   Spring practice ends Saturday, meaning Neuheisel has had time to
evaluate his players _ whom he refused to watch on film before
spring camp in order to give each player a fresh look.
</P>
<P>
   Upperclassmen like receiver Joe Jarzynka and inside linebacker
Marques Hairston said Thursday they thought Neuheisel's approach
was more than fair and Neuheisel said his first priority was to win
the confidence of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though kids are pretty resilient, it's pretty traumatic
to lose the coaches you know, the coaches who recruited you,''
Neuheisel said. ``There is always going to be a little bit of a
`Show Me' attitude ... but it is important to open really strong
lines of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to how things ran in the past, the door to
Neuheisel's office is always open. He encourages his players to
stop by, to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Some players have actually gone up to the office just because
under Jim Lambright they never saw the inside of the head coach's
office _ unless there was a serious problem. The atmosphere, the
relationships, the comfort level is entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   As for he and his family, Neuheisel is settling in. Well, sort
of.
</P>
<P>
   While he was lavished with a $1 million-a-year contract,
Neuheisel, his wife and three sons have yet to come up with a house
to buy. Seattle real estate being so hard to come by, no matter
what price, Neuheisel has not found what he is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could buy a house that was just to come home to after
work, OK. But I need a place where I can do what my job requires;
entertain players, so they can come over now and then, a place to
have the opportunity to bring new recruits _ when it's legal,'' he
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   As billed by Barbara Hedges, the UW athletic director who went
after Neuheisel hard with a (her words) ``blockbuster deal,''
Neuheisel is extremely bright, extremely confident, extremely easy
to deal with and apparently not below making a joke of his own
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his take on what people thought of him after his inital
recruiting gaffe just weeks into his new job, Neuheisel came right
to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were thinking, `He better be good,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when out in public, Neuheisel said reaction to him has been
good. What do people say when they see him?
</P>
<P>
   ```Go Dawgs,''' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you read things in the newspaper and you go, `God,
people must think I'm just the worst thing in the whole world.' But
the truth of the matter is, people are very supportive,'' he said.
``The main thing is how much they love the program and are excited
to see what can become of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also learning about Seattle, a place where overnight he
became one of the most visible, most scrutinized, most recognizable
citizens. His first lesson was a powerful one.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Seattle) is infatuated with the university. I guess I knew
that, seeing as how there are 68,000 season-ticket holders,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a complete love affair with this place. People
don't just like it because it's a country club of sorts and a
gathering spot on Saturday afternoons. They really have a deep
commitment to it. I've not been around a program like it, so that's
why I'm so excited.''
</P>
<P>
   While it might cause people to question whether Neuheisel is too
glib or too slick, it no doubt helps Neuheisel immeasurably that he
is such a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   And while there is much for him to prove, this is not a man who
flinches under such pressure. Now drop and give him 10. Later,
he'll have you over for a barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
