<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-REAX-LADN     04-23 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-REAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA'S INFLUENCE ON SCHOOL KILLERS OPEN TO DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Talking with teen-agers about the Colorado high
school massacre, President Clinton posed the question Thursday that
everyone is asking: Who's to blame?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ask ourselves some pretty hard questions here,''
Clinton told a group of two dozen students at T.C. Williams High
School in Alexandria, Va. ``What is the role of the larger culture
here?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you are exposed to much higher levels of violence
through television, through video games ... you can actually find
out how to make bombs on the Internet. Does that make a difference?
Does it make these things more likely to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Across the entertainment industry, many responded defensively,
suggesting that officials should look within the homes of the two
outcasts who massacred their classmates this week in Littleton,
Colo., before placing the blame on TV, movies and other forms of
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really easy to blame everybody else _ especially movies,
TV, the Internet and video games _ but you can blame guns, too,''
said John Carpenter, director of many horror films, such as
``Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wanted to be safe, we should disarm the public, ban
violence on TV and the movies, put metal detectors and guards in
schools and become a police state. But we'd lose all our freedoms.
None of this stuff intends to get people to commit crimes. Its
intent is to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about people with serious psychological
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the industry acknowledged a connection between
portrayals of violence and a small percentage of people who act it
out. But it was also mentioned that Europe and Asia import the same
films, TV shows and music while their levels of violence were far
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Author-songwriter Steve Allen, who has become increasingly
concerned about the issue, said films and TV should be more closely
examined because of the impact they are having on society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The percentage of emotionally unstable people in our society
is at an all-time high today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, an adviser to the Parent Television Council, a national
organization that studies offensive imagery in the media, said
violence has been far too prevalent in America from its earliest
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has something to do with the way in which this country was
constructed region by region. One reason why we are violent in this
country today is because we were violent from the very beginning,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   KABC-AM (790) talk show host Larry Elder said he was sure
graphic violence in the media influences some percentage of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is arguing movies have zero effect, but the question
is, what can we do?'' Elder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a role for more government regulation? No. The top
reason for something like this is (the killers) have poor moral
foundations _ and it can come from all sorts of factors. We have to
explain how it is that much of Europe and Asia can see the same
films yet their rate of violence is far lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simplistic to point the finger at Hollywood, we've
always had negative cultural influences. Where do we decide the
good stuff and the bad stuff? How do you know what piece of work is
going to trigger what in whom?''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Thompson, director of the Center for the Study of
Popular Television at Syracuse University, said there was nothing
new about today's death culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at the great books,'' he said. ``That culture of
death is part of pop culture and it has been for a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem with what Clinton said is, you're making the
argument that because of a tiny percentage of people who might take
movies as inspiration to do crazy things _ and they could also take
a Pepsi commercial the wrong way _ you're going to harness the most
powerful communications industry of all time so these people won't
be set off? You can't run a modern civilization that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with this culture of death is this culture of anger. We
have totally lost any kind of respect with people in power _ from
our bosses right up to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
