<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS EXPECT BRIGHT FIRST QUARTER AT DOLE AFTER FARM DISASTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dole Food Co., the international fruits,
vegetables and flower retailer, is expected to release an improved
earnings report today for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A First Call survey of five analysts pegs Dole's quarterly
earnings at 52 cents per share, up from 37 cents in the year-ago
period.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a big improvement from the way the Westlake
Village-based company ended the year.
</P>
<P>
   Dole lost $7.8 million or 13 cents a share in the 1998 fourth
quarter as inclement weather pounded the balance sheet. The company
earned $23.3 million, or 38 cents, in the prior year's last
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   During the last three months of 1998, the company recorded a
one-time charge of $120 million. Of that, $100 million was
attributed to Hurricane Mitch, which ravaged 30,000 acres of Dole's
Central American operations.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during December, unseasonably cold weather in California
caused about $20 million damage to the company's 6,500 acres of
citrus orchards.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts surveyed by First Call rate the company's stock a
hold.
</P>
<P>
   They estimate that Dole will earn $2.24 a share for all of 1999,
up from $1.86 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dole treasurer Beth Potillo said the earnings report will be
released before the market opens today. For the first quarter, the
company will not record any big charges like those that ate up 1998
fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has been hovering in the $30-to-$35 range
since October. Its 52-week high was $52.5625, set in July.
</P>
<P>
   Dole closed Thursday at $33.375, down 43.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
