<HEADER>
A0129 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALEM-IPO-LADN     04-23 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALEM-IPO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS BROADCASTER EMBARKS ON ROAD TOWARD IPO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Salem Communications Corp., the nation's largest
radio broadcaster of religious and family programming, has filed to
go public.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of KKLA-FM (99.5) in Glendale and 44 other radio
stations across the country hopes to tap the equity market to pay
down debt and expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the next step for us in terms of being flexible in our
financing,'' Dirk Gastaldo, chief financial officer of Salem, said
Thursday. ``We'd like to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Salem filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission this
week to go public. BT Alex Brown is the lead underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   If the IPO is funded, the company would trade under the symbol
``SLC.'' The number of shares being offered and the IPO price and
date have not yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Salem intends to use the money it raises to repay $55million in
corporate debt, pay back its credit facility, make more
acquisitions and other general corporate purposes.
</P>
<P>
   According to its SEC filings, the broadcasting company had sales
of $78million last year, up from $68million in 1997 and $59million
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But while sales have grown, the company had suffered net losses
in recent years, mainly due to huge interest payments. Salem had a
net loss of $1.6million in 1998, which included a $16million
interest payment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's loss was smaller than the one in 1997, when the
company was in the red by $2.4million due to a $13million interest
expense. In 1996, Salem recorded a net income of $12.75million, but
it included a gain from the sale of two radio stations for
$16million. Without the gain, Salem would have lost money.
</P>
<P>
   However, Salem's cash flow grew at a compound annual rate of
21.2percent from 1994 to 1998, according to IPO Monitor, a
Calabasas IPO tracking service.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
