<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICSHAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS BEAT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cosmetically speaking, Rick Pitino knew of no make-up
artist alive who was capable of pulling off a miracle makeover of
his injury-riddled Celtics, who were playing their second game in
as many nights, minus three starters, and against a well-rested
Atlanta Hawks squad that had played only one game in the previous
five nights.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much explained why, as he stood in the bowels of
Georgia Tech's Alexander Memorial Coliseum before Thursday night's
106-94 loss to the Hawks, Pitino took a realistic look at the
matchups and intoned, ``This one has `ugliness' written all over it
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That it did.
</P>
<P>
   The ugliness, however, was deferred until the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Celtics had all their blotches, blemishes,
scars, and cosmetic flaws exposed. After rebounding from a 23-20
first-quarter deficit to streak to a 41-30 lead in the second, the
Celtics wound up squandering their advantage and barely held on to
a 49-47 lead at intermission after the Hawks put on a 17-8 surge at
the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a shot,'' Pitino surmised afterward. ``They took us a
little lightly, and they came out really hard and made it very
difficult for us to score. We turned it over too much and didn't
get shots.''
</P>
<P>
   After hitting 21 of 47 shots and committing just six turnovers
in the first half, the Celtics wound up collapsing in the third
when they missed their first six field goal attempts of the second
half and committed six turnovers in the first 6:15. To make matters
worse, Boston went almost eight minutes between Tony Battie's
rim-bending reverse alley-oop dunk with 1:07 left in the first half
and Vitaly Potapenko's driving lane hook off a nice spin move at
5:23 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime I just kind of reminded them why we're here,''
said Atlanta coach Lenny Wilkens, whose Hawks remained in
contention for the Central Division title by winning their fourth
in a row. ``I thought we came out all about business in the third
quarter _ and that's what we have to do. You can't allow yourself
to get complacent, or get a team to get you complacent. I don't
think we took them for granted, but I thought we just let up after
the first few minutes of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith, who led the Hawks with 26 points on 9-for-17
shooting, broke the game open when he stole a lazy Battie inbounds
pass and converted it into an easy layup underneath. It gave
Atlanta its first double-digit lead of the game, 61-51, with 5:41
remaining. Chris Crawford chipped in 16 points on 5-for-9 shooting,
which helped make up for the limited output of Dikembe Mutombo (8
points, 8 rebounds) in 28 foul-plagued minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going out and playing hard,'' said Celtics rookie Paul
Pierce, who led the team with 23 points on 8-for-17 shooting. ``We
aren't playing as smart as we should, but the effort is there, the
intensity is there and we're getting the pace that we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Potapenko, who was acquired in a trade with Cleveland in
Boston's last visit to Atlanta during the trading deadline March
11, got the Celtics off the schneid with his nice lane move.
Potapenko, who had 14 points on 6-for-15 shooting, added a lane
jumper that pulled Boston within 63-57 with 4:06 remaining, but
that would be as close as the Celtics would get.
</P>
<P>
   All this, after Boston outscored the Hawks in the fourth, 32-29,
tying a season high for Atlanta opponents in that period. Although
the Hawks twice led by as much as 19 (84-65 and 91-72) in the
fourth, the Celtics came back to pull within 101-94 when Dana
Barros (14 points) drilled a 16-foot jumper with one minute to go.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the temporary blush it gave Team Green, it did little to
alter the unappealing cosmetic nature of Boston's 27th loss of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no complaints,'' Pitino said afterward. ``This group
was playing really hard. We're really shorthanded, and we played
very, very hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
