<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINSHURRICANES-     04-23 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINSHURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BEAT HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The rule of thumb in the playoffs is that the
best players cancel each other out, and a series comes down to how
the role players produce.
</P>
<P>
   So it was fitting that right wing Rob DiMaio, a lunchpail player
of the first rank, and rough-and-tumble forward Ken Belanger came
to the rescue in the third period, giving the Bruins a 2-0 victory
over the Carolina Hurricanes Thursday night in Game 1 of their
best-of-seven, first-round Eastern Conference series.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio is the quintessential blood-and-guts forward, assigned to
check the opposing team's best. Belanger is a
do-what-you-can-with-the-little-bit-of-ice-time-you-receive winger
who alternates with Ken Baumgartner in the enforcer's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason we won tonight was Rob DiMaio,'' said goalie Byron
Dafoe, who stopped 19 shots and earned his second career postseason
shutout. ``He played unbelievable and that's a prime example of how
role players can dictate a series. Rob, Tim Taylor, and P.J.
Axelsson are probably the three guys who can really help swing this
series one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio gave Boston all the offense it would need at the 1:50
mark of the third on an unassisted strike. DiMaio was in the right
place at the right time when center Jeff O'Neill coughed up the
puck in the right circle of the Hurricanes' zone and then fell
down. DiMaio teed up a slapper from the top of the circle and it
blew past goalie Arturs Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to get into a defensive posture to protect the puck
and down he went,'' said Hartford coach Paul Maurice. ``It wasn't
the prettiest of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   For DiMaio, pretty didn't matter. It was merely the result of
doing what was expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to pick up their game,'' he said. ``We have to
do our job against their top lines. Nothing has changed in that
respect but if we get an opportunity to score, we're going to take
it and make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina forward Kevin Dineen had a chance to pull his team
even, but he hit the post at 2:43. ``I got lucky,'' said Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger cashed in at 7:37. He took a pass from Jason Allison
and fired in a wraparound at the right post. The score was reviewed
because Dmitri Khristich was in the crease, but the video clearly
showed Keith Primeau holding him in there.
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, the Bruins and 'Canes split their
series (2-2-1). Thursday night, the hitting was ferocious, the
checking suffocating, and the goaltending excellent, though Dafoe
had to come up with some much bigger stops than Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina, which was hurt by losing forward Ron Francis to an
ankle sprain early in the game, came out very strong at the start
and kept the Bruins from generating a shot until nine minutes in.
They wound up with seven for the period, the two best by defenseman
Darren Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no surprise to us whatsoever,'' said coach Pat Burns of
the Hurricanes' early pressure. ``They're an aggressive,
forechecking team. We circled the wagons early and then got
stronger as the game went on. A lot of teams try to run us out out
of the building and it hasn't worked all year long. This isn't the
first team that's tried that. They've all tried it with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Primeau had a monster game, hitting every black-and-gold shirt
in sight. Carolina did an excellent job of preventing Boston from
establishing any kind of a forecheck early on.
</P>
<P>
   The situation heated up in the middle period with each team
being called for three penalties after a penalty-free first.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side's power play could break through.
</P>
<P>
   Among Boston's best scoring chances on Irbe were a couple of
bids midway through the period by Shawn Bates. Anson Carter set up
another decent opportunity when he fed Steve Heinze at 14:59. With
the Bruins killing a penalty to defenseman Don Sweeney, Dafoe came
up big on a shot by former Bruins defenseman Glen Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe staved off a big flurry by Carolina in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half-minute of the third, Dafoe again was called on
when Gary Roberts, who had a terrific game, blasted a shot from
point-blank range. But the goalie turned it back, setting up
DiMaio's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd come flying and we had to weather that storm
early,'' said Dafoe. ``I don't think we can get away with that in
every game of this series.''
</P>
<P>
   For a night, they did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
