<HEADER>
A0132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUPONT-BOS &LR;      04-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUPONT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GOING GETS TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Touch really isn't Ken Belanger's game. The
terms ``hands'' and ``Belanger'' go together, most of the time,
like a right-left combination, the Bruins' strapping forward
slotted firmly into the role of enforcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I love about playoff hockey,'' said Belanger, who
swapped sweet science for a luscious goal Thursday night in the
Bruins' 2-0 win over the Hurricanes in Game 1 of the playoff
series. ``It's just good, hard contact hockey. You don't have to
worry about the fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The knuckles, hooks, and right crosses stripped out of the game
_ all of it swapped for some fierce, often ferocious hitting on
both sides _ Belanger suddenly became an important role player of a
different kind in Game 1. Coach Pat Burns rolled him over the
boards for 14 shifts, about double or triple his typical workload,
and he responded every time by slamming every red-and-white shirt
that came his way.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger finished with a team-high eight hits, but in the end,
as usual, it was his goal that drew the most attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen guys do that on TV,'' said Belanger, who circled out
from behind the right post with a Jason Allison feed and stuffed it
inside the right post with 7:37 gone in the third period. ``That
wraparound part . . . I've seen guys do that, so I figured, what
the heck, I'd try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Touch. Hands. Maybe it wasn't a Denis Savard spin-o-rama or a
Paul Kariya deke-and-shoot, but it had some style, some grace to
it. It also held up to the scrutiny of the replay judge, who had to
make sure that Dmitri Khristich was pushed into the crease and
didn't commit the ultimate postseason boo-boo, the dreaded foot
encroachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked with Kenny before the series,'' said Burns. ``We
told him we'd need some size players.''
</P>
<P>
   Size players. Guys with brawn and the brains not to take stupid
penalties. Guys with the kind of gumption to keep delivering
checks, answer body blow for body blow, jump off the bench full of
spit and hiss and take a bite out of the Zamboni if that's what it
takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to get in that kind of game,'' said Belanger.
``The best part is the big hits _ getting the big hits. I love it.
That's hockey. It's what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were faced with a torrent in the opening 6-8 minutes.
The Canes, led by Keith Primeau, stormed out with a pounding
forecheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first few minutes,'' said Boston goalie Byron Dafoe,
``it felt like there were 25,000 people in here. The fans fed off
it, and their players fed off the fans. We stood around in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were retaliating, and returning with their share of
slams, but the Canes dominated in the early going. Burns soon saw
that he wouldn't be able to survive without getting something out
of Belanger. He needed that size player, and he needed him before
his club was looking at a 3-0 deficit and a series gone wrong from
the first ring of the bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny showed right off the start that he wanted to get
involved in the game,'' said Rob DiMaio, who scored Boston's first
goal, collecting a Jeff O'Neill giveaway and slapping it home from
the right faceoff circle. ``Pat sees that in a guy. He's smart. He
saw the intensity, and Kenny responded to that. I was really
impressed with the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger kept pounding. His most impressive work came when he
slammed his 225 pounds into Keith Primeau's 220, the two colliding
on the icy track as if sent down the rail by Uncle Fester from the
Addams Family days.
</P>
<P>
   No series can go on like that forever. Both sides were racing
for the ice packs when it was over. Belanger had a pile of cubes
mounted on his neck as he read the scoresheet, taking some of the
sting out of his night's work. He didn't have to tend to his hands,
but that goal scoring thing can be such a pain in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years I've been waiting for this,'' said Belanger,
thinking back to his brief trials with the Leafs and Islanders,
clubs that didn't make it to the postseason. ``Funny, I was
watching TV (Wednesday) night, and the announcers kept saying,
`(Tommy) Salo, (Marty) McInnis, (Travis) Green . . . these guys
haven't been in the playoffs much.'''
</P>
<P>
   All of them were on the Island with Belanger, but all are
working elsewhere now, different chances in different cities. And
for some, different results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 0223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
