<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS HEAD OUT ON ROAD  
 TRIP CAN EXORCISE DEMONS OF 1-5 START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - The five losses in the first six games, four of them
excruciatingly painful for the Diamondbacks, remain emblazoned in
the minds of the players. Most members of the club quietly think
about where they could be right now if not for the four losses in
the last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   While the Diamondbacks try to push the nightmare finishes to the
far recesses of their brain, they set out on the longest trip of
the season, a 13-game stretch that will see the Diamondbacks set
down in four cities.
</P>
<P>
   This, for all practical purposes, will be a major test for a
club that finished its first homestand in impressive fashion,
sweeping a three-game series from Philadelphia to win eight of the
10 games played at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't just 1-5 on that trip, it was more the way we were
losing games in the last at-bats,'' reliever Brian Anderson said.
``We have to wash those away. Hopefully, we got them all out of our
system. Good teams win no matter where they play. If we can only
win at home, then we're not a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no better way for the Diamondbacks to show the rest of
the National League, and themselves, that they are a good club than
by having a successful road trip as they play in San Diego,
Houston, Milwaukee and Cincinnati over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting they must win 10 of the 13 or any such
thing. But even a simple winning record on this trip, say 7-6,
would represent a tremendous move forward for a club that strongly
believes it can win a division title this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in here knows that if we get to where we want
to be, we have to be able to win on the road,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``I'm not sure anyone ever looks forward to playing
on the road, but we know we must be successful on the road. These
are some tough cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, playing anywhere on the road is difficult. The San
Diego Padres, who will host the Diamondbacks over the next three
days, managed a 44-37 record away from Qualcomm Stadium while
winning 98 games and the NL West title last season.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 clubs that finished with losing records last season,
only the Kansas City Royals had a winning road record. Of the 14
clubs that had winning records, six had losing records away from
their home stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we go that deep intellectually,'' said third
baseman Matt Williams, who is off to a torrid start. ``At least I
know I don't. We have enough veteran guys on this club who know
what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with winning tight games on the road was clearly
evidenced during those first six games in Los Angeles and Atlanta.
The home club always has the final at-bat, and giving up a lead in
the last inning means taking the slow walk off the field knowing
your club has no more at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, this trip might be viewed as one where the
Diamondbacks can exorcise the evil spirits that overtook their
bullpen in so many last-inning situations while losing four of
those first six games in the opponents' final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should all be behind us,'' said Randy Johnson, who is
scheduled to start three games on this trip. ``As soon as we took
three out of four from LA, we knew we could compete with the club
everyone is picking to win the division. No matter what, I still
think it will take until the All-Star break for us to make
believers out of the fickle people who don't believe in us. Right
now, they just think we had a hot streak during this homestand.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one player is truly being consumed by the disastrous first
trip, and his name is Gregg Olson, the club's closer who was on the
mound to watch three ninth-inning leads evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club didn't do anything bad on that first trip,'' Olson
said. ``These are my demons I have to confront, not the rest of the
club.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 0224EDT &QL; 
