<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-EDGERSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FORWARD EDGERSON MULLING SITTING OUT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eugene Edgerson, Arizona's last link to its 1997 NCAA
championship basketball team, realizes that playing pro basketball
is a longshot for him.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches understand that Edgerson, a backup power forward,
wants to stay on track to complete his degree in elementary
education next spring. That requires a semester of student
teaching, which Edgerson said would make it difficult _ if not
impossible _ for him to play his senior season for the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Edgerson told a Tucson newspaper that he has
decided to sit out next season, which would leave the Wildcats with
no seniors on their roster and only two experienced inside players.
But on Thursday, Edgerson said through a UA spokesman that he had
not made a final decision. Edgerson met with Coach Lute Olson on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long way to go before anything is decided,'' UA
associate coach Jim Rosborough said. ``Everybody wants what's best
for Gene. We recognize that graduating in four years is a very
worthy goal, and we support him. But there are ways to work out the
conflict, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosborough said that the UA coaching staff and the UA College of
Education were trying to work out a schedule that would allow
Edgerson to complete his degree on time while playing his senior
season _ ``if that's what Gene wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgerson told the`` Arizona Daily Star'' on Wednesday that he
would sit out next season, possibly returning in 2000-2001 after
completing degree requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Mike Bibby. I'm not Jason Terry, where basketball is
guaranteed for me,'' he said. ``What's guaranteed for me is I'm
going to be somebody, whether it's as a teacher or as a basketball
player, and I think my chances are better as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I spend eight hours a day in class and be 100 percent for
practices? That's not possible, man. The only way I could do it is
if I took (expletive) kinds of classes, and I'm not a (expletive)
kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does sit out, Arizona's only experienced inside players
would be 6-foot-7 power forward Michael Wright, the Pac-10 Freshman
of the Year, and 7-foot-1 center Loren Woods, a transfer from Wake
Forest who becomes eligible next season.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has been recruiting another big body, 6-foot-10 Robertas
Javtokas, a Lithuanian who attends Akron (Ohio) St. Vincent's High
School. Javtokas has agreed to make a campus visit to Tucson next
month, although he has not yet attained a qualifying test score
that would allow him to be eligible to play NCAA Division 1
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, North Carolina-Charlotte and Louisville also are
recruiting Javtokas, who must pass a Ohio proficiency exam before
May 10 in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, UA also has come into contention for Luke Recker, a
6-6 swingman who is transferring out of Coach Bob Knight's Indiana
program after leading the Hoosiers in scoring last season. Recker
will visit UA next month. He would be ineligible next season
because of the transfer. Recker also is considering North Carolina,
Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats have had an in-home visit with Jason Kapono, a 6-8
All-America forward at Lakewood (Calif.) High. He also is
considering Kentucky and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has two scholarships available. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
