<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0140 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR     04-23 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES, FUHR STOP COYOTES  
 ST. LOUIS STOPS 4 POWER PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They said all the right things. Believed them, too. No
more excuses. They've got something to prove. Second round or bust!
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed like a distant memory, at least for a night, after
the Coyotes lost their collective edge Thursday night, suffering a
3-1 setback in Game 1 of their Western Conference quarterfinal
series against the St. Louis BLues.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a costly lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if they can't get their awful power play untracked.
The Coyotes went 0-for-6 and wasted four first-period chances,
including a pivotal two-man advantage that was the story of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made terrible decisions with the puck,'' Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said. ``I'm not going to stand here and point out who or
when, but it's something we've been working on, we have the plays
that we run, and we were completely brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to keep working on it. There's only so many
things you can do. You can watch video, which we've done. You can
practice it, which we've done. You can discuss it, which we've
done. But it still boils down to the execution on the ice and
people making split-second decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes seemingly had everything going for them, except
having to play without injured star center Jeremy Roenick. They had
motivation to prove they could undo past sins both here and in
Winnipeg and actually win a first-round playoff series. They had
home-ice advantage. They had the Whiteout, a supercharged, ominous
sight that nearly tore off the roof at sold-out America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, it was Bluesville in the land of white.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes couldn't solve Grant Fuhr. They couldn't stop Al
MacInnis. And they couldn't score on the power play to save their
souls.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for a late goal by Robert Reichel, there would
be almost nothing positive for the Coyotes to take into Game 2 here
Saturday at noon in what looms as a must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't lose the series tonight,'' right wing Shane Doan
said. ``We lost one game. We just have to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues got a goal and two assists from MacInnis and scores
from Jamie Rivers and an empty-netter from left wing Scott Pellerin
after Reichel's goal. They also received a 26-save performance from
the ageless but acrobatic Fuhr, who now is a staggering 16-1
lifetime in the playoffs against the Winnipeg Jets/Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a strong game tonight,'' Coyotes right wing Rick
Tocchet said. ``He made at least four big saves that were Grant
Fuhr-type saves. He was out of the net, came flying in, and made
the save. They expect that from Grant Fuhr and he did the job for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The only shot he couldn't stop was a too-little, too-late goal
by the newest Coyote. Dallas Drake dug out the puck along the
boards, fed it down low to Tocchet, and he centered a pass out to
the slot that Reichel quickly jammed past Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   The goal briefly gave the Coyotes some life and brought the
crowd back into the game. But there was only 1:52 remaining in
regulation, and not enough punch to force overtime. Especially
after a Fuhr outlet pass to MacInnis paved the way for Pellerin's
empty-net goal with 42 seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Any momentum the Coyotes thought they had from the hyped-up
crowd vanished just 22 seconds after faceoff when Juha Ylonen was
whistled for a hooking minor. But just as the penalty expired,
MacInnis, who had dashed from blue line to blue line untouched,
unleashed one of his rocket slap shots. It sailed inside the post
just past Nikolai Khabibulin's glove hand and hit the back of the
net.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing. How problematic were the four punchless
Phoenix power players in the first period?
</P>
<P>
   It only got worse after that. The Coyotes had an apparent
game-tying goal by Ylonen wiped away with 6:52 left in the second.
Referees Paul DeVorski and Paul Stewart said the puck never crossed
the line, although replays made it look afully close.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Doan got whistled for tripping and the
Blues made it 2-0 on the ensuing power play, just their third of
the game up to that point. With 2:36 left in the period, Rivers
deflected Terry Yake's shot with his stick while camping outside
the crease to Khabibulin's right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
