<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-A     04-23 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING SIGNAL COMES VERY EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It didn't take long for Jim Schoenfeld to blend in
with the locals.
</P>
<P>
   It could've been just 22 seconds, the time it took for a Coyote
to land in the penalty box. Or maybe it was the moment he learned
that Tverdovsky is Russian for turnover. Or when a blue-line
special whizzed by his goalie, turning a night of anticipation into
a futile, brutal game of catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   No, it didn't take long before the color drained from the
Coyotes coach. And just like that, Schoenfeld's face joined the
Whiteout.
</P>
<P>
   Stop if you've read this before, but it didn't take long for the
Coyotes to put down their shovels and jump in a hole, a team facing
an 0-1 deficit. A team facing a must-win situation on Saturday, the
same old postseason nausea, the same old ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Deja Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a sleepless night (on Thursday),'' Coyotes
warrior Rick Tocchet said. ``We'd like to have that one back.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason for panic, not when home-ice advantage means
very little in hockey, and even the most raucous building in the
NHL can be silenced with a quick goal and a hot goalie. But the
frustration is understandable, especially for a hockey team
desperately in need of a good start. And the concern is real. Very,
very real.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of dissection, there are some inevitable
conclusions. Oleg Turnover-dovsky was terrible. The power play set
a new standard for impotence, enough to encourage the Blues to
ignore the risks and take a few aggressive chances in the near
future. And that first goal . . .
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much Nikolai Khabibulin freezing in awe. It was a
pair of defenders shying away from Al MacInnis as he approached the
blue line, afraid of his sizzling slap shot, treating the puck as
if it were a live grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, whatever happened to paying the price?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the real concern is the offense and whether the
Coyotes can score enough goals to win a game, much less a series.
All night long, they seemed to be a man short on the ice. Even on
the power play. And this condition might not disappear.
</P>
<P>
   A shame, too, because Grant Fuhr looked shaky. Ready to be
conquered. But too often, centering passes found an empty crease,
rebounds were flailed at with stone hands, opportunities came and
went without a red light in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 5-on-3,'' Schoenfeld said. ``And we went out there
like we were brain-dead.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the most flagrant offense. That belonged to the
power play resulting in a 2-on-nothing break for the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play just demoralized us,'' Tocchet said.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, even with Jeremy Roenick, this team barely had enough
offense to cling to the fringes of the elite. Without him, they're
struggling. More than anyone wants to admit.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was a total loss. The Coyotes want to overpower the
Blues, force a softer opponent to wilt. A good strategy, but at the
same time, they must stay out of the penalty box, especially with
an additional referee on the ice. This is the dilemma of balance
facing the Coyotes, and for the most part, they handled it
wonderfully on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But they're going to have to mount some offense, and it won't be
easy. Not without pinching defenders, taking chances, risking the
odd-man rush that has been so damaging in the past.
</P>
<P>
   It is also clear that this series will be miserable for Keith
Tkachuk. On Thursday, he was slashed, chopped, diced and sliced. He
is the ultimate power forward confronting the ultimate power
defenseman in Chris Pronger. But Pronger got a lot of help from
MacInnis, and no matter how determined Tkachuk may be to erase the
stigma of first-round loser, something else is clear:
</P>
<P>
   He's going to need some help. From somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what type of team we have on Saturday,'' Tocchet
said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, while the crowd was still alive, a
band in the third deck broke into song, and the lyrics were
striking:
</P>
<P>
   This is our last chance &QL; 
This is our last dance &QL; 
Under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is. And yes, they are. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
