<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD LEARNS ABOUT THE WHITEOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Actor  &UR; Tom Arnold is used to attracting attention, but
when he arrived at America West Arena Thursday night, he had no
idea what was in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize everyone was going to wear white,'' said
Arnold, who was dressed in black. ``They didn't tell us in LA. I
walked in and went, `Oh my God. I feel like such a jerk.' But it's
a great place to play and a great place to watch a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is a longtime Blues and longtime NHL fan. He said he has
never seen passion from a crowd like the passion Coyotes fans
showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've ever been to and I've been to a lot,''
he said. ``The crowd is great. They're almost organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could never get fans to do this in LA. One, they'd leave
after the first period. Two, they'd never all dress the same
because they're too conceited.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Saved teeth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter how big a save &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin or  &UR; Grant Fuhr make
in the first-round playoff series between the Coyotes and the
Blues, it won't match the save  &UR; Dr. Reed Day made, according to the
Coyotes' injured &UR; Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   When it was learned that Roenick's jaw was dislocated and broken
in three places after the jarring hit thrown by  &UR; Derian Hatcher of
Dallas last week, it was also feared that the Coyotes center would
loose eight teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they're all going to be all right,'' Roenick said before
Thursday's playoff opener. ``I feel fortunate and lucky. Actually,
I feel fortunate and lucky to have a great doctor like Dr. Day. If
anybody out there needs oral surgery, I'd recommend him highly.
There's nobody better.'' &QL; 
Niki all the way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goaltending coach &UR; Benoit Allaire ended speculation that the
Coyotes might split duties between  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin and  &UR; Mikhail
Shtalenkov Saturday and Sunday, when the Coyotes and Blues play
back-to-back games inside of 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it will be Niki,'' Allaire said on Thursday. ``He's got to
be in there for us. He's our guy.'' &QL; 
Staying together &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes center &UR; Robert Reichel, obtained from the New York
Islanders at the trading deadline, credits  &UR; Keith Tkachuk with
willingly moving to center on the No. 1 line to keep the second
line intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a positive thing when you can keep your lines
together, and our line has been working hard and playing well,''
Reichel said of wingers  &UR; Greg Adams and  &UR; Rick Tocchet. ``Hopefully,
we'll stay together.'' &QL; 
Daigneault questionable &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; J.J. Daigneault's injured hip flexor kept him out of
the series opener Thursday night. Assistant General Manager  &UR; Taylor
Burke said Daigneault is questionable for Saturday's Game No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to skate for 20 to 25 minutes hard (today), and
we'll see how it is,'' Daigneault said. ``If I skate hard for 15
minutes or so, it gets sore. I don't know if it's part of the hip
bruise I had or not. But I want to play on Saturday if I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman &UR; Brad Tiley was recalled from Springfield on Wednesday
and took Daigneault's place in the lineup, partly because veteran
defenseman &UR; Jamie Huscroft is nursing a minor injury.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen  &UR; Deron Quint and &UR; Gerald Diduck each took part in the
team's morning skate Thursday. It was the second straight skate for
Quint, who has been out since April 1 because of a concussion.
Diduck still is listed as being two weeks away from playing. &QL; 
Cup arriveth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether &UR; Tkachuk, Tocchet or  &UR; Dallas Drake will get to skate
around the rink holding it above their heads is one thing, but
Phoenix is assured of receiving the Stanley Cup nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's Holy Grail will visit the Valley on Tuesday and
Wednesday to promote the Coyotes' quest for sport's most historic
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Three special Stanley Cup events will be held Wednesday: at
Supai Middle School in Scottsdale from 10 to 11 a.m., at Phoenix
Children's Hospital from 12:30-2 p.m. and at the Scottsdale Boys
and Girls Club, 4-5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Cup will be on display for Coyotes fans from 4-8 p.m.
Tuesday at Alice Cooper's Town during Game 4 of the Coyotes-Blues
playoff series at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup will be accompanied by its caretaker,  &UR; Paul Oke,
who will be on hand to discuss facts and trivia regarding the
trophy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
