<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BLUES-SIDE-AZR &LR;      04-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUND AND THE FUHR-Y 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was a lock. A given. A Fuhr-thing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the cold, hard truth, Coyotes fans: Grant Fuhr has this
franchise's number. And it's 16.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old goalie's playoff record against Winnipeg/Phoenix
improved to 16-1 following St. Louis' 3-1 victory over the Coyotes
Thursday night at America West Arena. The man his teammates call
``Father Time'' and ``Grandpa'' demonstrated what 18 years of NHL
experience can do for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Time was definitely ticking tonight for us,''
defenseman Jamie Rivers said. ``He was awesome. He had his game
face on, and he'll wear it for the rest of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fuhr, ``I know I only have a few years left, so anytime you
get into the playoffs, you want to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr had several key stops, including a barrage in the second
period when the Coyotes outshot the Blues, 9-7. He even stopped one
with his neck with 13:34 remaining in the first period and had the
welt to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I did that,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He was instrumental in stopping the Coyotes' 5-on-3 advantage in
the first period, and it seemed to take some life out of the hosts.
Throughout the game, he came up big: high shots, low shots,
rebounds. He stopped nearly all of them and finished the night with
26 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Only one got by him: Robert Reichel's tap with 1:52 remaining in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   For years, critics have tried to write off Fuhr, but he
continues to silence them in his own quiet way.
</P>
<P>
   Before undergoing arthroscopic knee surgery earlier this season,
he was 7-7-5 with a 2.70 goals-against average and an .876 save
percentage. The Blues went so far as to audition replacements after
the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Since his return, he has appeared in St. Louis' last 18 games
and posted a 9-4-3 record, a 2.10 goals-against average and a .912
save percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a remarkable recovery from his surgery,'' St. Louis
Coach Joel Quenneville said. ``He's the type of guy that relishes
the situation he's in now, and he gives us some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr's quiet demeanor might have kept others from knowing just
how much his injured knee bothered him and how much it affected his
play.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Fuhr played like a man who has been a member of five
Stanley Cup championship teams and is a six-time NHL All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good right now,'' Fuhr said. ``The body's healthy. I
had a week off to rest. I'm just out there having a good time.
Things are bouncing off in the right spots, so I just need to enjoy
it while I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to the rest of the league's dismay, he may not be ready to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   He said in January that next season would be his last. But in
March, after feeling strong because of his successful third knee
surgery, he suggested he would like to play in 1,000 career games.
But that would likely mean he would have to play for another three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr, who joined St. Louis in 1995, has a two-year, $6 million
deal. Who knows how long he'll go?
</P>
<P>
   Based on the opinions of those on the ice Thursday night, Fuhr
has a lot of hockey left in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a strong game tonight,'' the Coyotes' Rick Tocchet
said. ``He made four saves that are Grant Fuhr-type saves. He was
out of the net, then would come flying in and make the save. They
expect that from Fuhr, and he did the job for them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
