<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYTOES-SIDE-AZR &LR;      04-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYTOES-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PUNCH TO POWER PLAY HURTS COYOTES  
 WASTED OPPORTUNITIES IRK TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``It will be there when we need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pick a member of the Coyotes' power play _ any player _ and each
uttered those words at one point during a season in which the power
play converted only 12 percent of its opportunities _ 41 of 342, to
be exact.
</P>
<P>
   Never was it needed more than in Thursday night's 3-1
playoff-opening loss to the St. Louis Blues in the best-of-seven
first-round Western Conference series at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And never was it more missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play, like it has all year, really killed us
tonight,'' Keith Tkachuk said. ``It was absolutely miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Added defenseman Jyrki Lumme: ``We got better traffic in front
of the net tonight 5-on-5 than we did on the power play. Guess
we're going to have to check the video and see what we did wrong
and what we did well, and do those things and correct the
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Special teams figured to be the Achilles' heel of the Coyotes
coming into the series. The Blues' power play ranked third in the
NHL during the regular season and its penalty-killing unit was
second, while the Coyotes ranked 26th out of 27 teams and its
penalty-killing unit ranked fifth.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis showed the Coyotes the value of its power play last
week in Phoenix, when it cashed in four goals with a man edge,
including three straight in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Blues gave the Coyotes six power-play
opportunities, including a 5-on-3 for 1:29 in the first on which
Phoenix failed to put a shot on goal.
</P>
<P>
   And, when the 5-on-3 became a 5-on-4, they nearly compounded the
misery by allowing St. Louis to fly down the ice on a two-man
breakaway. Fortunately, goalie Nikolai Khabibulin stonewalled Craig
Conroy and Scott Pellerin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 5-on-3 was disheartening,'' said Phoenix's Rick Tocchet.
``We were making plays that veteran players shouldn't make. We had
five veterans out there and we're making dumb cross-ice passes. If
we don't get it straightened out quick, we're going to be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Schoenfeld was even more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play, especially that 5-on-3, cost us the game,'' he
said. ``We have our plays that we run with a two-man edge and we've
been working on them, but we were completely brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the difference in the hockey game. They got one on
theirs and we got none on ours. We need better execution. That
2-on-0 on our own power play was totally of out line.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix gave the Blues just three power-play opportunities and
they responded with two goals. Granted, as Schoenfeld alluded, Al
MacInnis' first goal of the game technically was not a power-play
goal. It only looked, tasted and smelled like one.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis' hard slap shot from the blue line flew past a stunned
and screened Khabibulin at 2:22, exactly two-minutes after Juha
Ylonen was penalized for hooking 22 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy comes out and scores on a big shot like that early in
the game it takes some of the wind out of you,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues cashed in a second power-play goal with 2:36 remaining
in the second period when defenseman Jamie Rivers beat Khabibulin,
screened again, on his stickside on a slap shot from the slot after
Shane Doan was called for hooking in front of the Coyotes' net.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at their two goals, there was no diagram or
anything,'' Tocchet said. ``They just blasted them and had a guy at
the net. We had a lot of chances, they just didn't go in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
