<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 03:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSSIL-HUMANS-SFCHRON     04-23 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-HUMANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOMINID FOSSILS MAY REVEAL LINK BETWEEN MAN, APE  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists sifting the rubble of a desert hillside in Ethiopia
have discovered a trove of fossil bones 21/2 million years old that
may reveal the first direct link between the apelike creatures of
ancient Africa and the earliest members of our true human lineage.
</P>
<P>
   This newfound hominid species, still far more ape than human,
could include the very first beings on Earth to use stone tools to
butcher their meat and crack the juicy bones. That entirely new
technology in diet marked a major turning point on the long
evolutionary path toward modern Homo sapiens, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, a team of 40 researchers from 13 countries has
been collecting and analyzing countless fossil fragments from an
arid site near Ethiopia's Awash River. At the African site, the
scientists pieced together some of the most remarkable evidence of
the ancient past that has yet to come from Ethiopia's fossil-rich
Afar Triangle, where the skeleton of the early hominid ``Lucy,''
about 3.2 million years old, was discovered 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the latest expedition were Tim D. White, an
anthropologist at the University of California at Berkeley, and
Berhani Asfaw, a leading Ethiopian anthropologist who has
frequently worked with White at Berkeley. Together with J. Desmond
Clark of UC Berkeley, who at 83 is a famed pioneer in the study of
human evolution, and their colleagues, they are publishing two
detailed reports on the new finds Friday in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Their extraordinary discoveries include fragmented fossils of
eight creatures known as hominids, including bits and pieces of one
with a thigh bone long enough to foreshadow the legs of later
humans and thereby adopt a more humanlike gait. Less than 300 yards
away they found a skull with a small brain case not much larger
than an ape's and a very primitive face with unusually large back
teeth, characteristics never seen before in any fossil hominids,
the scientists say. The creature It  &LR; stood only about 4 feet 9
inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that cranium's size and shape, the scientists have
determined that it represents a new hominid species and have named
it Australopithecus garhi. The first word, meaning ``southern
ape-man'' indicates the genus line that includes ``Lucy'' whose kin
first emerged nearly a million years earlier, while ``garhi'' is
Ethiopian for ``surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid their perplexing collection of ancient material, the
scientists are still uncertain whether all the humanlike fossils
were members of the same new Australopithecus species, or which
ones actually did the revolutionary act of butchering their meat.
</P>
<P>
   One antelope leg bone, for example, clearly shows the marks of
deliberate cutting and a cracked area that could only have been
made by pounding it with a rock, according to White, And a fragment
of the animal's skull showed where a sharp tool had obviously cut
away the tongue _ presumably a delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the evidence for deliberate tool use on the animal
bones is clear, White and Clark said in interviews this week that
the past three years of tedious searching and excavating at the
site near the village of Bouri have yielded none of the actual
stone tools.
</P>
<P>
   The site is largely composed of the sedimentary remains of
earthquakes and volcanic eruptions that have disrupted all of
Africa's great Rift Valley for more than 5 million years, and there
are no cobbles anywhere near the newfound hominid remains.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier expeditions at a site near the village of Gona, 35
miles to the north, have found abundant rocks showing clearly that
creatures there knew how to chip away sharp flakes into knives and
use rounded stones for pounding meat and bashing bones, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The new site near Bouri was not always a harsh desert, and when
the fossils found there were alive 21/2 million years ago, the land
was a pleasant grassy meadow where antelope and primitive horses
grazed, saber-toothed cats hunted prey, and a lush lake provided
water and campsites with a view.
</P>
<P>
   White and his colleagues, in the respected tradition of
anthropology, are being ultra-cautious. While while they have
placed their new Australopithecus species on a direct evolutionary
line midway between Lucy, called A. afarensis, and Homo habilis,
the earliest known members of the truly human race, they concede
that their own A. garhi species might _ just might _ have been an
offshoot of the line rather than directly on it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that caution, however, White showed far more excitement
in discussing the implications of the discovery:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major breakthrough because it tells us about a new
species previously unknown to science,'' White said, `'and it tells
us about the early, early _ 21/2 million years early _ acquisition
of meat and marrow eating among our human ancestors, revolutionary
technological and dietary steps in the human career. This is the
first time we have anatomical evidence and behavioral evidence
right together''
</P>
<P>
   To White and Clark the revolution in diet was a key step toward
nourishing the hominid brain that was then still small. It was, as
White put it, ``the next major revolution in human evolution''
because it allowed the hominid brain to evolve into a larger and
larger organ, eventually toward human brain size.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of humanlike human-like  &LR; creatures remains
shrouded in mystery, however. Anthropologists believe that the
hominid line must have separated from the lineage of the great apes
_ chimpanzees, gorillas and bonobos _ sometime between 5 five  &LR; and
6 six  &LR; million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even the various hominid lineages known as Australopithecenes
must have evolved from earlier species that began to walk on two
legs and separated from the four-legged early apes. And today that
earliest change is attributed to a bipedal hominid that lived some
4.4 million years ago and whose fossils were discovered in the
Awash region by Berkeley's White and his Ethiopian colleagues in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   White named that species Ardipithecus ramidus, meaning ``ground
ape,'' while ``ramidus'' is the Ethiopian word for ``root.'' Today
Ardipithecus is the earliest known hominid, while we humans are _
until now, of course _ the last in the hominid line of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The latest discovery of what may well be the long-sought link
between the australopithecenes and Homo is certain to meet with
skepticism by rival anthropologists.
</P>
<P>
   But in Berkeley Thursday F. Clark Howell, one of the world's
foremost specialists in the evolution of early humans, called the
new report ``a real coup and a fine piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``White and his colleagues are highly conservative, and they
have much more than merely fragmentary material to back them up,''
Howell said. ``They have cranial remains and arms and legs _ an
entire assemblage. And while we can't definitely link the arms and
legs with the cranial parts, they do show evidence that places them
more definitively toward the Homo lineage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
