<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANNIVERSARY-SFCH     04-23 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AS BOMBS FLY, NATO MULLS ITS FUTURE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's 50th anniversary summit opens Friday in
Washington with a three-hour council of war dealing with Kosovo _
rather than a gala with flyby jets _ as the alliance grapples with
a conflict that will determine, unexpectedly, the course of
European-American relations into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo _ now in its fifth week, with no sign that
NATO will scale back its bombings _ has crystallized fundamental
questions about the future of what many call the most successful
alliance in the history of the world: Where should it fight? For
what end? Who should join and who should lead?
</P>
<P>
   Should NATO evolve from a security pact between Europe and the
United States against the Soviet threat to a sort of global
policeman that intervenes in ethnic conflicts and battles
terrorism, rogue states and the spread of chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons, as the Clinton administration would like?
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, how will NATO avoid the humiliation of a
belligerent Balkan dictator defeating the entire Western military
alliance and its high-tech war machine right in its own back yard?
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is spoiling the party,'' said Simon Serfaty, director
of European Studies at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies. ``Clearly, it is not even a quagmire we face. It's a dead
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Will NATO commit ground forces to Kosovo, to battle an
entrenched Yugoslav army, village by village, most of them now
emptied of the people NATO sought to protect? Or will it seek
Russia's aid in brokering a truce with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, whom some NATO leaders say should be indicted as a war
criminal rather than negotiated with.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the alliance's 19 members, along with 23 of the
25 ``partner'' nations _ Russia and Belarus will skip the event to
protest the bombings in Yugoslavia _ will face those questions in
the largest summit ever held in the United States. The three-day
summit will shut down much of the city. The federal government will
close, along with schools. Downtown law firms have already packed
up and moved to temporary quarters in Virginia. The heart of the
city is now what NATO calls ``Prohibited Area 56.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington now has its own no-fly zone. Pilots are forbidden to
fly lower than 18,000 feet within a 10-nautical-mile radius of
Reagan National Airport. Access to a 100-block area running from
the Capitol to the White House to the U.S. Naval Observatory will
be heavily restricted. Bus routes are being canceled and visitors
told to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Washington on April 4, 1949 on the rubble of World
War II, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization bound the United
States and Europe in mutual protection. Like many postwar
international institutions created under U.S. auspices, NATO
succeeded and endured. For the next 50 years, the alliance secured
peace and prosperity in Europe after two devastating world wars
and, without firing a shot, held off the threat of another world
war.
</P>
<P>
   Today, NATO finds itself enmeshed in its first live war,
confronted by basic questions about its purpose and its credibility
in the wake of the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly and inconveniently we've got a test case ... and so
far we're not doing well,'' said Jeffrey Gedmin, a foreign policy
analyst at the conservative American Enterprise Institute. ``If
Kosovo ends up being a fiasco and the general conventional wisdom
is that we lost, it's going to do more than mar the summit this
weekend. It's going to damage NATO's credibility, and it's going to
damage the relationship between the United States and Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But if NATO wins _ and much depends on the definition of victory
_ the alliance could emerge stronger.
</P>
<P>
   It is no small irony that NATO plans to reveal at this summit a
new ``strategic concept'' defining its core mission, and to welcome
three new members admitted only last month _ Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary, which now finds itself a frontline state in
NATO's first war.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's original mission was crystal clear: ``to keep the
Americans in, the Russians out, and the Germans down,'' as NATO's
first secretary-general, Lord Ismay, memorably put it.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union, the Clinton
administration has pushed for NATO to address broad new areas from
terrorism to nuclear proliferation. More worrisome to the European
allies, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has also outlined a
vision of a kind of ``global NATO'' that would call on the alliance
to police not just Europe, but the Persian Gulf and even Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has clearly answered the question about whether NATO
would engage in so-called out-of-area operations beyond its own
borders. Whether it succeeds may well determine if it ever tries
again.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' internationalist wing, a bipartisan bloc that includes
Republican Senators John McCain and Richard Lugar and Democrats
Joseph Biden and Joseph Lieberman, fully supports NATO and believes
that if anything, the Clinton administration should have committed
itself fully to the possible use of ground forces at the outset of
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake today is order and stability in Europe as a
whole, and that is why American interests are involved,'' Lugar
said in a speech this week, where he introduced a resolution ``to
use all necessary force'' to accomplish NATO aims in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo has also made it painfully clear that NATO's military
power rests almost solely with the Pentagon. While contributing
planes, European nations have proven unable _ in military parlance
_ to ``project power'' beyond their borders.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 90 percent of NATO's ``power-projection''
capability lies with the United States, according to the European
Institute, a Washington think tank. The United States is fielding
roughly 80 percent of the Kosovo military operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the Europeans don't spend the money,'' said
Serfaty of the Center for Strategic and International Studies.
``They do spend actually quite a bit of money on defense, but
instead of spending it as one, they spend it as 15, so they don't
spend it well. They have maybe 7,000 combat aircraft. That's a lot
of planes. But those planes cannot lead missions. They have 2.5
million troops under arms, but very few of those people are able or
willing to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans contend they want a more equal role in the
alliance, a ``European pillar'' within NATO or even a separate
``European security and defense identity.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Kosovo makes clear, said Gedmin of the American
Enterprise Institute, ``the reality is that the Europeans are
neither politically nor institutionally nor infrastructurally ready
_ whether we like it or not, this is just the reality _ they're not
positioned in any foreseeable future to deal with any military
conflict of consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for Europe and the United States to part
ways, some NATO critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should realize that it was a mistake to try to enlarge
NATO's membership and mission because it's not an appropriate
vehicle for dealing with security issues in the 21st century,''
said Lawrence Korb of the nonpartisan Council on Foreign Relations
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Serfaty counters that, despite complaints about U.S. leadership,
European leaders ``know quite well that they cannot do without
it,'' and have acknowledged ``the centrality of American power and
the indispensability of American leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the U.S. also needs Europe as a political and
economic ally, he contends. ``Their institutions are comparable to
ours, their values are comparable to ours, it's a complete
relationship,'' Serfaty said. ``There's a security relationship
related to Russia, related to the Balkans, and therefore the case
for the U.S. in and with Europe is based not only on issues of
principles _ in this case to get the Kosovars back to their home
and stop ethnic cleansing _ but it is also based on interest, and
it is the convergence of principles and values on the one hand and
self-interest on the other that motivate this action, unlike say,
action in Rwanda.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is indeed the test case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
