<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 04:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-GETS-PERSONAL-FI     04-23 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-GETS-PERSONAL-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING A STAKE THROUGH `THE VERY HEART OF MILOSEVIC'S REGIME'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy, 825-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ We stood on the well-groomed lawns beneath the plain
trees of Novi Beograd Wednesday afternoon and looked at what
British Defense Minister George Robertson called ``the very heart
of Milosevic's bloodstained regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra-large blackbirds and magpies fluttered around the great
smoldering ruin of the Usce Business Center, a curtain of pale blue
smoke drifting from the upper stories where two of three cruise
missiles had smashed into the building before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   But striding the lawn, the waistcoated Yugoslav minister without
portfolio, Goran Matic, begged to differ. The 23-story pile with
its 100-ft. television transmitter, he told us, was nothing less
than ``the symbol of Yugoslavia's existence.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputed that the ``Black Building,'' as it was
disrespectfully called by the people of Belgrade, had been _ as
NATO might put it _ very seriously degraded.
</P>
<P>
   Tons of concrete and glass had been blasted from the upper
floors into the park lot while up all four outer walls crept the
dark stain of a huge internal fire.
</P>
<P>
   Three television channels had been blasted off the air _ hence
Matic's reference to Yugoslavia's ``existence'' _ while two
solitary flags, one red for socialism, the other the tricolor of
Serbia, hung limply from the offices of President Slobodan
Milosevic's Socialist Party of Serbia. Hence Robertson's reference
to the ``bloodstained regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that the president's SPS headquarters were struck
_ along with smaller offices of the Yugoslav Left Wing party of
Mrs. Mira Markovic (better known as Mrs. Milosevic) _ there's one
conclusion that anyone in Yugoslavia could make: NATO's war is
getting personal.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO had chosen to DHL a message to the Serbian leader, it
couldn't have done it more effectively. But the target also allowed
the Serbs to claim that NATO was trying to drive Yugoslavia's
television services off the air.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's sports channel SOS _ with no political content _
vanished in a millisecond, along with transmission facilities for
the punk-rock Pink Channel of Zeljko Mitrovic (a Markovic protege)
and the Kosava Television and the nominally independent but
pro-Milosevic BK channel.
</P>
<P>
   Had not Pink TV been playing a diet of Hollywood movies these
past weeks, Matic asked rhetorically? Had not BK been showing
American and West European serials?
</P>
<P>
   `How could we name these attacks as anything but `Monty Python's
Flying Circus'? You only have to see this image of our television
stations to understand that for NATO our media is more dangerous
than our military. I don't need to spend as much time as Jamie Shea
to explain this.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Matic watches NATO's cockney spokesman _ extracts
from Shea's briefings often appear on Serb television if they suit
Yugoslavia's purposes _ says a lot about the Balkans information
war.
</P>
<P>
   So does the diet of western movies shown on Serb television.
``JFK'' and ``Nixon'' led off the first week of war, ``The Wizard
of Oz'' the second.
</P>
<P>
   But RTS, Radio Television Serbia _ whose pro-Milosevic news
broadcasts now run to two hours (without, of course, any mention of
``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo) _ has not been touched.
</P>
<P>
   Its directors invited the foreign press to visit the station
only two nights earlier, warning pointedly that NATO was due to
attack the channel's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Yugoslavs, the attack on the ``black building'' has
less to do with television broadcasts or the regime's ``nerve
center'' _ as Robertson also exotically described it _ than the
steady broadening of NATO targets across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   From the strictly military targets attacked in the first week,
NATO's assaults have increased each week to embrace more and more
civilian buildings and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   From barracks and anti-aircraft defenses, NATO has moved on to
destroy road and rail bridges, oil refineries, car and plastics
factories, chemical facilities, a cotton yarn factory, television
relay transmitters, electrical power grids and cigarette factories.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, precisely the same pattern followed in the
bombardment of Iraq in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   So what next? If NATO continues the same pattern, electricity
and water supplies will soon be targeted, along with telephone
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Novi Beograd received contaminated water after its oil heating
plant was hit two weeks ago. Parts of Belgrade lost water for 24
hours this week.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has insisted that it targets only military infrastructure.
But as the targets are more promiscuously chosen, so greater and
greater civilian casualties are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, a NATO jet destroyed a passenger train. Two days'
later, an attack supposedly intended to destroy Serb paramlitary
forces in southern Kosovo slaughtered 74 Albanian refugees.
Wednesday the Serbs claimed a NATO jet had killed 10 Serb civilians
in Djakovaica, again in southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can call the road out there a military supply line if
they want,'' my Belgrade hotel receptionist said acidly Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, a long queue had formed for cigarettes now
that the tobacco factories at Nis and Vranje have been attacked.
Soldiers smoke cigarettes. Another military target. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 825-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
