<HEADER>
A0312 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIGRAINE-ALTERNATIVE-     04-23 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGRAINE-ALTERNATIVE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUROLOGISTS LOOK AT 'ALTERNATIVE' MIGRAINE REMEDIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By KATE JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most neurologists are skeptical about alternative therapies for
migraines, but a careful review of the literature and clinical
evidence might convince them otherwise, a headache specialist
reported at a recent conference on headaches in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is not widely known, there is evidence supporting
the use of magnesium and riboflavin (vitamin B2) for migraine,''
said Dr. Alexander Mauskop, associate professor of clinical
neurology at the State University of New York/Downstate Medical
Center in Brooklyn and director of the New York Headache Center in
New York. ``These therapies are worth trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnesium deficiency has long been suspected to play a part in
migraine, with studies showing that between 30 percent to 50
percent of sufferers are deficient in this element, according to
Mauskop, who spoke at the 11th Annual Symposium on the Treatment of
Headaches and Facial Pain sponsored by the New York Headache
Foundation and the Eastern Pain Association.
</P>
<P>
   Magnesium deficiency can cause blood-vessel spasm, leading to
migraine, he explained. The element also helps block pain messages
from being sent and received along the nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Migraine sufferers may be deficient in magnesium because they
don't eat enough dark green, leafy vegetables, or they may also be
depleted because of stress, according to the New York specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say that stress contributes to their migraines,
this is one possible mechanism for that, because stress depletes
magnesium, which then leads to more headaches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauskop said that daily supplements of 400 milligrams of of
magnesium, given orally or by injection, can lead to a decrease in
the frequency of migraine headaches after three to four weeks, and,
in some cases, can actually relieve a migraine in progress.
Injecting the element is often more effective because it is not
easily absorbed into the body, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanism by which riboflavin, or vitamin B2 supplements,
relieve migraine is not well understood, but a daily megadose of
400 milligrams may bring some relief after two to four months,
according to Mauskop.
</P>
<P>
   A herbal supplement of 100 milligrams of feverfew has also been
proven effective in two small, double-blind studies, he added.
Injections of botulism toxin, which are primarily used to treat
wrinkles, have also been shown to reduce headache because they
cause muscle paralysis, Mauskop added.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recognizes that alternative therapies are sometimes
criticized for diverting attention from conventional treatments.
``Some people argue that it will divert people's effort toward
something that may not be effective, and costs time and money,'' he
said. ``I don't really think that's the case, because most people
would rather spend a little time and money rather than taking drugs
that can have serious side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients should know that magnesium taken on an empty stomach
can sometimes cause diarrhea, and patients with kidney problems
should not take large amounts of magnesium, Mauskop warned.
</P>
<P>
   Another headache specialist agreed that alternative therapies
have a role in treating migraines. ``I'm a firm believer that many
of the alternative therapies for migraine have a place, and are
time-honored because they work,'' said Dr. Roger Cady, director of
the Headache Care Center in Springfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Cady said that alternative therapies, particularly dietary
supplements and lifestyle changes, are a part of migraine
management in which patients can take an active role _ and should
not be turned to as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, that is what often happens, which means that
alternative therapies are often tried only on a very recalcitrant
population,'' he said. Cady said that he has had success in
treating migraines both with magnesium and riboflavin supplements,
and urged physicians to look at alternative therapies as
complementary to other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two approaches are not incompatible,'' Cady said. ``You
can achieve a lot of success with daily supplements, but if a
patient then gets a bad headache, most of them would welcome a
prescription medicine to get them out of it,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
