A0316 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHANGING-DOCTORS-NYTS     04-23 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-DOCTORS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENT: PATIENTS ARE CHANGING, BUT ARE DOCTORS?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 BY DR. ERIC G. ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm too long in the tooth to have been impressed by the concept
of the doctor's mystique. I remember once being asked by a mother
whether, in general, Tylenol or aspirin was safer for children. I
discussed the pros and cons and ended with my opinion that Tylenol
was better. Next time the mother was in my office with a feverish
child, she said she was there because the illness hadn't responded
to aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were talking about this last month,'' I said,
``and agreed Tylenol was safer?'' She sniffed and said, ``You said
that but I asked my cleaning lady and she said aspirin was
better.''
</P>
<P>
   We may be losing our hold on the public, this beneficent hold
that has allowed some doctors to work near-miracles over the last
few centuries. It's good that we're off the pedestal and can deal
with patients with the trappings removed.
</P>
<P>
   But the American public seems to be going too far _ not just in
its rejection of things medical but in its renunciation of common
sense, too.
</P>
<P>
   So we hear a number _ I believe I read somewhere 60 percent _ of
Americans believe that something weird happened at Roswell, N.M.,
and that UFOs really landed there; and we're told by the Associated
Press that nearly three of four Americans believe a conspiracy was
definitely or probably behind the assassination of President
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, junk science is espoused by the legal profession and
medical use of marijuana is embraced by five more states following
the wacky lead two years ago by my state, California. On
reflection, maybe it's not doctors who are losing their clout; it's
the public losing its marbles.
</P>
<P>
   And as I walk down the aisle at our supermarket I pass bottles
on the shelf that apparently allow weight loss without any effort.
The labels read Ultra Burn, Fat Burners, Pounds Off, Metabolift,
Thinz, PhenSafe, ZeroFat and Chroma Slim.
</P>
<P>
   It would be bad enough if this array of bottles was in a
pharmacy, but it's in a supermarket and, beyond, with shelves
groaning, is the herbal medicine department at hand for all age
groups from ``baby boomers obsessed with hormones and hair loss''
to ``malady-rich matrons.''
</P>
<P>
   All those weight-loss bottles confirm the clarion call of
today's America: ``Something For Nothing! Results Without Effort!
Perfection Makes Perfect!'' And they make it more understandable
why our patients don't listen to us as much as they used to _ the
alternatives are so much more attractive. Indeed, we're losing our
way with many patients because we don't meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is our fault. We don't listen enough. We address what
we think is important without necessarily considering what the
patient is concerned with. We set bad examples, ourselves, by being
overweight and not exercising, sometimes even smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly we're at fault for not recognizing many of our
patients have changed -- and we haven't.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Eric Anderson is a charter diplomate of the American Board
of Family Practice. A former president of the New Hampshire Academy
of Family Physicians, he now practices part-time for a large
medical group in San Diego and writes regularly on medical
matters.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0318 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHANGING-DOCTORS-NYTS     04-23 0591
