<HEADLINE>
TARRED AND FEATHERED, WITH HUMOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Thank goodness for humor. Sometimes when life on the
job is at its most tense, when a situation is at its bleakest, a
witty word and a good laugh come along to save the day. Readers
offered so many cases in point that a second serving of their
stories became obligatory.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years ago, early in the public relations career of
Sanford Teller of New York City, he worked as a junior account
executive in the Manhattan office of a large out-of-town
advertising and marketing company.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to impress, he usually arrived before 8 a.m. and remained
until well after 6 in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``One morning, after breakfast with a client, I got to the
office at 9:30,'' he writes. ``As I passed the desk, the
receptionist wished me a good morning and informed that I had to
sign `the book.'''
</P>
<P>
   Teller was told that the office supervisor had decreed that
beginning immediately, all account executives had to sign in each
morning, giving their time of arrival. There was also a heading
called ``reason for being late,'' and the receptionist said company
business was the only acceptable excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was appalled that my creativity and professionalism were
being judged by the clock,'' Teller writes. ``And if the company
was so interested in the time I arrived, why didn't it care about
my time of departure?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that an angry response would not go down well. Which is
why, after some deliberation, I wrote that I was late because `My
parakeet developed a hernia, and I had trouble finding a pet shop
that sold a tiny truss.'''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 30 minutes later, Teller was summoned to the office of
the boss, who told him to close the door and take a seat. Teller
could see the book, with its offending entry, open on the desk.
</P>
<P>
   The boss asked him to explain, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   The boss listened carefully, thought for a moment, then broke
into a smile. ``I think you're right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, the book was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Teller adds two postscripts:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``I've used humor in business whenever appropriate ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``I must admit that I've never owned a parakeet.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a job seeker's nightmare,'' writes Peg Mancuso of
Hicksville, N.Y. Two university vice presidents and two directors
were taking turns questioning her about how she would handle the
role of alumni relations director for the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university had lost track of many of the alumni and needed
to regain contact,'' Mrs. Mancuso says. ``I had some ideas and
answered all the questions with the confidence that I could do the
job for my alma mater.''
</P>
<P>
   But then one of the vice presidents asked, ``So, do you think
you could find all of the lost alumni?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mancuso hesitated. The tension built.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that if I answered `yes,' I would be showing
overconfidence and a lack of knowledge about the challenges of the
job,'' she recalled. ``But to answer `no' would be to admit to the
possibility of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mancuso repeated the question and, with a smile, gave her
reply: ``No, I don't think that I'll find all the alumni, at least
not those in the Witness Protection Program.''
</P>
<P>
   She got the job. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When George A. Cohon, now senior chairman of both McDonald's
Russia and McDonald's Restaurants of Canada, was negotiating in the
early 1980s to introduce the fast-food chain to the Soviet Union,
he often met with Vsevolod Shimansky, an official of the Russian
Federation's Trade Ministry. Shimansky often wanted to continue
their talks over dinner, especially at restaurants with live
balalaika music.
</P>
<P>
   One night during this period, on a trip to Australia, Cohon
found himself in a restaurant where the owner went from table to
table, playing a guitar in what seemed to be a very accomplished
fashion. ``But when he stopped strumming, the guitar kept playing;
he had a tape deck inside the guitar,'' Cohon writes with David
Macfarlane in ``To Russia With Fries'' (McClelland &AMP; Stewart). ``As
soon as I saw it, I thought: Shimansky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a tape deck. I got a balalaika. I carefully inserted the
tape deck into the body of the balalaika.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Cohon came to Russia, he wasted no time telling
Shimansky that he had been studying the balalaika, a guitar-like
instrument. Shimansky wasted no time telling Cohon that he wanted
to hear him play.
</P>
<P>
   Cohon stalled until the last night of his visit, when they went
to Valdai, not only one of Shimansky's favorite restaurants but
also a place that featured balalaika music.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, over coffee, Cohon said, ``Well, it is now time for me
to play the balalaika.''
</P>
<P>
   The instrument had been planted in a corner. With his back to
the table, Cohon switched on the tape, turned around and began
strumming a classic balalaika tune, ``Moscow Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Shimansky was astonished. ``He stood there in amazement, moved
almost to tears,'' Cohon writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How beautiful!'' Shimansky exclaimed. How he wished he could
play such a song.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can,'' Cohon said, still strumming.
</P>
<P>
   Shimansky said: ``No, I have not the gift of music. Not like
you.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Cohon replied, ``No, really, you can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohon passed the instrument to Shimansky. ``And, of course, when
I handed it to him, it continued playing,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Shimansky almost fell over his chair. And then his laughter
boomed through the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gift,'' Cohon said. ``For you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohon writes, ``Shimansky turned out to be a good ally for us to
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
