<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO PERSONAL AT THE INTERVIEW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am just beginning a job search, and I've already
been asked twice in interviews whether I am married, have children
or plan to have children. While my answers to the first two
questions are yes and no, I have dodged the third, for fear that
any child-bearing plans might cost me a new job. Is it true that
employers aren't supposed to ask? How should I handle it when they
do?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A job hunt is tough enough without having to dance around
uncomfortable _ and, yes, illegal _ interview questions.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, it is illegal even to ask about a candidate's
marital status, said Mark A. Jacoby, an employment lawyer at Weil,
Gotshal &AMP; Manges in Manhattan. And regardless of where you live,
interview questions about pregnancy or plans for becoming pregnant
are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, he explained, ``The issue would be tied to a
possible disability as a result of pregnancy _ in effect,
discriminating against someone who plans to get pregnant and
therefore be disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, however, boldly asserting your legal
rights may not be the best way to get what you want. ``You can say,
`Those are illegal questions,' and refuse to answer,'' said Caryl
Rae Krannich, co-author of ``Interview for Success'' (Impact
Publications, 1998). ``That may make you feel good at the moment,
but it is sure to kill your chances of getting the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the interviewer is just trying to make small talk
and isn't thinking about the legal consequences of his questions,
Jacoby said. If you make a big deal out of a question, you're
likely only to increase the interviewer's interest in it.
</P>
<P>
   One approach is to finesse the issue by playing it ``honest but
smart,'' Ms. Krannich said. If you deny any plans to have children,
but then show up pregnant shortly thereafter, she said, you could
hurt your relationship with your new employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' Ms. Krannich cautioned, ``you want to put
the best face on the situation.'' Offering too much information _
how many children you're hoping for, or just when you plan to have
them _ falls into the ``honest and stupid'' category, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your responses brief and to the point, she advised. ``A lot
of people talk too much when asked about things that make them
uncomfortable,'' she said. ``Just answer the question and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   A long, rambling response will alert an observant interviewer to
your discomfort and can make the interviewer wonder, ``If she
responds this way to this question, what will she be like to work
with?''
</P>
<P>
   If you object on principle to the questions, you can make the
subtle point that they are inappropriate, Ms. Krannich said. ``Say
something like: ``Gee, that's interesting. I've not been asked that
question before in a job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in some cases an interviewer's motives may not be
so innocent. If you sense that your questioner knows that his line
of inquiry is inappropriate but is pursuing it anyhow, you may want
to seriously reconsider whether you want to work for that company.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
