<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LESABRE-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUICK LESABRE: A QUEEN OF THE BALLROOM LEARNS A RED-HOT TANGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 40-something neighbor cut to the chase: ``What are you doing
with that old-folks car in your driveway?''
</P>
<P>
   I stammered and muttered something about how this new Buick, the
2000-model LeSabre, had a totally different feel. But I could tell
he wasn't buying it. His mind was made up, like those of many Baby
Boomers. He was thinking that Buicks have mushy rides, imprecise
handling and styling that shouts, ``Hey, Mom, Grandpa is here!''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him? Buick has long catered to the senior set that
loves big American cars. With a preponderance of models that were
conservative on the outside, unexciting on the inside, Buick long
ago lost the high-style appeal it had in the '50s and '60s with
snazzy Skylarks, sporty Wildcats and elegant Electra 225s.
</P>
<P>
   As younger Americans discovered cool, crisp-handling European
sedans, Buick was left selling cars to the Sun City crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest full-size Buick has been completely rethought.
Following on the successful redesign of the plush, V8-powered Park
Avenue, Buick engineers have recast the LeSabre, their big-selling,
V6-powered front-drive sedan, from the suspension up.
</P>
<P>
   The LeSabre's biggest surprise is the way it rides and handles.
It rivals and in some ways improves on the smooth competence of the
Toyota Avalon and Chrysler Concorde, two competing cars I drove for
comparison purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In this Buick, taking a high speed turn doesn't feel as if you
are trying to steer a bag of water, as it does with another LeSabre
rival, the Mercury Grand Marquis. The Buick's body has been
considerably stiffened, the handling is as crisp as any large car I
know selling for less than $30,000 and the acceleration and road
feel are pleasant surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, I tested a car with the optional Gran Touring
package, which includes 16-inch aluminum wheels and a tighter
suspension. But even that is a sharp improvement over a 1999 model
similarly equipped. At $185, it is small price to pay for excellent
handling.
</P>
<P>
   A week before, I had driven a $50,000 BMW wagon through the
twisties, and when I got in the Buick I reminded myself that I was
now judging a car costing $20,000 less. But while the LeSabre is
hardly at the level of a rear-drive German sports sedan or wagon, I
was surprised by how well it held the road, took the turns,
accelerated onto freeways and isolated its occupants.
</P>
<P>
   The LeSabre's biggest disappointment is its looks. While the
car's fresh and flowing curves improve on the frumpy lines of the
'99 model, it is still conservative and undistinctive. It borrows
heavily from both the Park Avenue and the midsize Century and
Regal; while that gives Buick a ``family look,'' it is still pretty
dull.
</P>
<P>
   Buick and some other General Motors divisions face a dilemma;
because they sell lots of cars to a fiercely loyal older crowd,
they tend to be cautious about making changes that might alienate
their best customers. After all, my neighbor may turn up his nose
at the LeSabre, but it has been the nation's best-selling
full-sized car for seven years. Even a gutsy product planner
tinkers very carefully with such a sales machine.
</P>
<P>
   For a little extra room, the LeSabre's wheelbase was stretched
almost 1.5 inches and the front and rear wheels were moved out a
hair to improve ride and stability. The engine and transaxle have
hardly changed. GM's 3.8-liter V6 has its roots in the early 60s,
but it is one of the company's most widely used engines. In the
LeSabre, it cranks out 205 horsepower and gets up to 30 highway
miles to the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the old dashboard was junked in favor of bigger gauges
and a swooping, horizontal design that is a nice change from the
conventional layout _with stereo, climate controls and ashtray
stacked in a center chimney _ of the Avalon and Concorde. Another
nice touch: The window and lock switches are well lighted at night.
</P>
<P>
   I disliked the center console, though. In a clumsy effort to
entice younger buyers, Buick is offering the LeSabre for the first
time with a bucket seat-and-console configuration as an alternative
to the three-person bench. The seats are comfortable, but the
console looks like a he-man design ripped from a Suburban. It is
way too large for this car and its folding cup holder mechanism is
so big it blocks access to the center of the dash.
</P>
<P>
   The LeSabre and the Avalon have four air bags, two in the dash
and one side-impact bag in each of the front seats. For a better
fit, Buick's shoulder belts are attached to the seat instead of to
the door pillars, and the front seats have headrests that
automatically sense when a front occupant is pushed backwards in a
crash and adjust to cradle the back of the head. In the rear, three
passengers get shoulder and lap belts, though they do not have
adjustable headrests.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde has neither adjustable rear headrests nor side air
bags, but it is anything but dull on the outside. I loved its
design from the moment it was introduced as a 1998 model.
Unfortunately, driving the car dampened my excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's design moves occupants forward, and the hood's sharp
slope lets the driver see little between the windshield and the
front end of the car. In fact, you have the perception of steering
the car from just behind the front bumper. Some people love this;
some don't. In any case, it takes an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   For all the luxury touches of the Concorde in LXi trim, it does
not give as smooth or quiet a ride as the Buick or Toyota. While
Chrysler says it tried to reduce noise and harshness, the Concorde
remains unduly harsh and its 3.2-liter V6 is downright noisy.
</P>
<P>
   Stiffness is important in a large car _ it contributes to the
Concorde's fine cornering ability _ but Chrysler has not hit the
sensitive balance that delivers both precise handling and a supple,
comfortable ride.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Avalon was probably the ride and handling leader
in this segment, and it remains an impressive American-built family
sedan even with a four-year-old design. While it has the smallest
engine _ a 3-liter V6 _ its horsepower rivals that of its bigger
competitiors and it holds its own in interior roominess.
</P>
<P>
   And no one can boast a better reputation for quality than
Toyota. Still, the top-line Avalon is $29,128, the priciest car of
this bunch.
</P>
<P>
   With a LeSabre Custom starting at just $23,505, this new,
much-improved Buick seems a compelling value. It also shows that
Detroit can offer a big family car that delivers not just ample
room and a pleasing ride, but also impressive handling.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A big Buick that doesn't drive like one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
