<HEADER>
A0334 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-column-ADV25-CO     04-23 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-column-ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: ENTERING AN ERA OF CHEAP DIGITAL EATS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- You can sense that a seismic shift is uprooting the
computing world when fully loaded machines are being sold on the
World Wide Web for $599. Each of these units is more powerful than
the $80 million behemoth that ran the North American Air Defense
Command a few decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those $599 computers ship with Windows 98. But Seattle-based
Microworkz Computer could perhaps knock another $50 or so off its
price if its customers chose to load Linux, which is in the public
domain.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the spring Comdex trade show in Chicago snapped up
tens of thousands of free CDs that were imprinted with a new
release of the Linux operating system. This version can be dressed
up to have the look and feel of Microsoft Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, an IBM subsidiary is shipping Star Office, a full
suite of applications, including a neat integrated Internet
browser. Star Office holds its own against Microsoft Office, which
sells for hundreds of dollars. A single-copy Linux version of Star
Office is available for free for non-commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Microsoft just reported record fiscal third-quarter
earnings, and its short-term prospects look bright. After all, even
a bare-bones $299 computer, the Webzter Jr., another Microworkz
Computer offering, requires a suite of applications to do serious
work. And, for most folks, Microsoft remains still best suited to
fill their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, a $599 package based on Linux and Star Office would
appeal mainly to the kind of savvy insiders that frequent Comdex.
But how long before Microworkz Computer or another bargain-priced
supplier starts to sell machines with Linux-based Windows-like
systems? (Dell Computer, which is to Microworkz Computer as
Microsoft is to Linux, has began to ship powerful units installed
with Linux, which has 15 million users.)
</P>
<P>
   Some computer gurus who came to Comdex see computer usage
reaching saturation levels in the workplace early in the new
millennium. But, they say, hard-core home non-users will remain
unplugged forever.
</P>
<P>
   This anti-rodent minority will never know what it's like to roll
a computer mouse through the Internet, even if computers come to be
available for free. (A few marketeers have begun to give them away,
seeking to recapture their costs through pricey Internet sign-ups.)
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need a computer to compute. Bright programmers at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology have written a
conversational interface for online weather information. For
example, a user can call up and ask, ``What's the forecast for
today in Dayton?'' or ``Will it rain tomorrow in London?'' (During
the MIT test period, you can try it by a toll-free call to
1-888-573-8255.) (CQ)
</P>
<P>
   Many of MIT's networking computers run on Linux. That makes
Linus Torvalds, Linux's 29-year-old creator, quite happy at a time
that Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates is giving the university $20
million to build a new computer lab, to be named after Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds came to Comdex to taunt Goliath by predicting his
fledgling operating system will crush Microsoft. Some people who
heard Torvalds speak thought he was joking. But Gates, who was at
Comdex while the taunt was hurled, did not. Even on a digital
battlefield, paranoids can have real enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass2(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
