<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The $5 miracle that made a difference
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I am here to tell of a miracle _ or at least
it was a miracle to me _ and, what's more, a miracle with a
message. Miracles do not come along every day. Certainly, I've only
had one in my life.
</P>
<P>
   If you have chosen not to believe in miracles, I have no desire
to shatter your lack of faith. Call it a coincidence, call it a
scientific anomaly. Call it pure, dumb luck. I know what it was.
</P>
<P>
   A miracle. Though lightening did not flash in the sky and no one
but me noticed it. I tend to believe that most all miracles are
tiny ones, so small that they are not seen by anyone but the one
who receives the blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Such is my story.
</P>
<P>
   It happened when I was a boy, maybe 8 years old. It was a
Saturday morning and my parents were fighting.
</P>
<P>
   My parents did not fight often, at least not where the children
could hear them. But this Saturday was different, both my mother
and my father were raising their voices. The situation was made all
the more unpleasant because I so rarely had heard them fight.
</P>
<P>
   If parents knew the feeling of fear and helplessness that enters
young hearts when Mom and Dad argue in front of children, they
would do it far less often.
</P>
<P>
   On this day the disagreement was such that any restraint they
might have ordinarily felt had melted away.
</P>
<P>
   And what was the argument about? Simple. Money, or, more
accurately, the lack of it. I have a theory that money is the root
of almost all arguments among married couples and it certainly was
that day. I heard it over and over and over. No money. No money. No
money.
</P>
<P>
   Though the day was cold and I did not really want to go outside,
the fighting finally drove me from the house. I grabbed the
football and began playing ``solo football.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who grew up with many friends or siblings may not
recognize the game. Solo football is played by one person, who is
both the passer and the receiver. The trick is to throw the ball up
high enough so that you can
</P>
<P>
   catch it as a receiver. If you think this isn't much fun you are
right, but it is still better than listening to your parents fight.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the yard I threw and I caught, threw and caught. One
particular pass I threw high, but far too deep. I missed it by 10
yards.
</P>
<P>
   I trotted over to pick up the ball and, when I did, I found a
crisp, new $5 bill underneath. I reacted as if I'd found a chest of
gold. I ran into the house waving that $5 bill. ``I have money!'' I
said. ``I have money! Now you can stop fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   And, by golly, they did.
</P>
<P>
   My father took that $5 bill and examined it as if it were an
artifact from Pluto. It seemed to me that he rubbed his eyes to
make sure they were seeing properly.
</P>
<P>
   Then he handed the $5 bill back to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to all the neighbors,'' he said. ``Ask every one of them if
they have lost $5. If they say that they have, give the money to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   (I'm sure some of you remember a time when you could do that and
count on all your neighbors to tell you the truth. I'd like to
think that is still possible in a town like Marshall.)
</P>
<P>
   I went to every neighbor within two blocks of our house and
asked if they had lost that $5 bill, but I already knew the answer
would be ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   I believed then, and believe now, that as that ball went
skyward, God _ who, I'll admit doesn't often use money to provide
miracles _ slapped that $5 bill on the ball so it would land on the
bottom for me to find.
</P>
<P>
   When I got back home with the $5 still in my hand, I gave it to
my father who promptly announced we were going out to see a movie.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, I didn't have much concept of what a movie would cost,
but it surprised me you could get a family of five into a theater
for $5, but maybe so.
</P>
<P>
   Then my father told us we were also going out to eat. What? You
could really go to the movies and eat out for $5?
</P>
<P>
   But I was a kid and I didn't question it. That $5 bill, simple
as it was, turned the mood of the day. We ate at a nearby
cafeteria, then went to the Gateway Theater, most probably to watch
a war film or a Western.
</P>
<P>
   After the movie my mother mentioned ice cream and we went to the
original Ashburn's ice cream store on Fort Worth's East Side. My
mom had a banana split and the rest of us had double-dip cones.
</P>
<P>
   I remember watching as the server rang up the total on one of
those cash registers where numbers pop up instead of an electronic
display.
</P>
<P>
   The total was $5.27.
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   That was more than I had found. How had my father paid for the
movie, the dinner and ice cream?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that things are almost never as bad as they seem.
I've no doubt my parents were having money problems, my father was
a cop and money was always tight.
</P>
<P>
   But the night we shared as a family was worth whatever money it
cost and my parents understood that. We made it through whatever
difficulty hounded my parents that day and dozens more
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story is this: When things get so bad that you
believe they can't get worse, you need to find a reason to believe
in miracles again.
</P>
<P>
   You need to eat ice cream and hug your children _ not
necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
