<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do you own a gun? If so, like Dixie says, `We have to talk'
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was one of those spring nights when the
neighbors come out after the long hibernation of winter, greeting
each other for the first time in months, when folks find any excuse
to be in their front yard for the sheer joy of being there.
</P>
<P>
   This neighbor I'd never met couldn't resist talking to my little
girl in the stroller. ``How old are you, sweetheart?'' he said, and
I answered, ``Three,'' when Queen Veronica didn't deign a reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a new little boy,'' my neighbor said, offering the
cigar of his irrepressible smile. ``He's five days old.''
</P>
<P>
   A shadow falls over my neighbor's face. ``I hope I can bring him
up in a better world than the one I'm living in.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need to say it: Columbine High School. The image
pushed itself into my mind: The children running out of the school
with their hands over their heads. A girl sobbing, ``This isn't
supposed to happen at school. School is the place where you're
supposed to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we tell our children?'' the TV anchorperson
breathlessly intones, previewing one of those ever-helpful
how-to-parent segments. ``How do we assure them they're safe?''
</P>
<P>
   We could tell them the murdered students are statistically
insignificant, as columnist Vincent Schiraldi opined last year. ``I
have been on television news following every one of the recent
school killings, answering basically the same question: `How do you
explain the trend of shootings by kids in rural schools?'''
Schiraldi wrote. ``My answer is always the same: I cannot explain
it, because no such trend exists.'' Many more people, he explained,
are killed by lightning every year.
</P>
<P>
   No need to mourn, then, as another statistically insignificant
town buries its statistically insignificant children. There is no
trend here.
</P>
<P>
   What do we tell our children?
</P>
<P>
   We could tell them that no right is more sacred than free
enterprise, the right of Hollywood and Madison Avenue and the music
industry to fill kids' heads with violent fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   We could tell them that no right is more important than the
right to bear arms. The Second Amendment is the alpha and omega of
rights, the one right that should come without restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Pay no attention to Dixie Kirkland, who has given away 1,900 gun
locks as part of a gun-safety program, one of the first of its kind
in the country, at Grandview Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``These teens are children, still kids, not yet adults,''
Kirkland said. ``We as adults have to be responsible for children's
actions, and we have failed.'' We have failed, she said, by the
very fact that these children have gotten their hands on these
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland knows how parents can close their eyes to the danger.
She goes to festivals, schools, anywhere they'll take her,
spreading the gospel of gun safety. At a recent safety fair in
Washington Twp., ``People walked by me and shrugged _ `Oh, that,
it's just gun safety,''' she said. ``I put up with that for about
10 seconds.'' Then she starting calling out to passers-by: ``Do you
have a gun?'' If the answer is yes, she beckons with her strong,
grandmotherly arms, the kind you never say no to: ``We have to
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   What gives her such passion? Friends lost their son, a shooting
victim. ``If I can save just one life . . .'' she said, her face
turning red, ``it would be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   What do we tell our children?
</P>
<P>
   We can listen to Dixie Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   Or we can tell them that every right takes precedence over their
right to grow up safe, to go to school without fear.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
