<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let me tick off the ways the clock runs my day
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the burdens of being semi-retired
is being asked: ``What do you do with all your time?'' It's hard to
explain where time goes when you aren't punching in 8 to 5. I'm
tempted to give people the answer they expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep until about 9:30, get up, put on my robe, eat
breakfast, read the newspaper, and watch television. Then I shower,
go to my club for a leisurely lunch, play a round of golf, enjoy a
couple of beers with my cronies, and get home in time for the
cocktail hour. After dinner I light my pipe, read a book until the
11 o'clock news.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not quite true. The Moose Club doesn't serve lunch, and I
haven't played golf since 1964. My wife and my doctors have nagged
my pipe away, and when I read or watch television, I nod off within
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I spend most of my time waiting for somebody to come fix
something. My golden years are complicated by having married a
child bride who continues in the work force. I'm the one who has to
be home when repairmen come to fix the air conditioning, the
dishwasher, the microwave, the freezer, the stove, the garbage
disposal and our other modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   My typical day: When the alarm goes off at 6:15, I dash to the
kitchen and start breakfast before she gets out of the shower.
Otherwise there won't be butter in the grits, and I'll get
Eggbeaters cooked in Pam rather than real eggs fried in bacon
grease.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do today?'' she inquires before I have a
chance to finish the sports section.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I haven't decided,'' I reply. ``I'll probably go back to
bed for a nap and then call George Patton to see if he wants to go
to lunch. Then we may go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to be here when Gene Walker comes to measure for
carpet,'' she said. ``And you need to call Chuck Watkins about the
irrigation system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything else?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to go to the hardware store for light bulbs and you
can go by the laundry and pick up the dry cleaning I dropped off
last week.''
</P>
<P>
   After spraying the roses for blackspot, opening the house for
Gene Walker and calling Chuck Watkins about the irrigation system,
I drove to town, picked up the light bulbs and the dry cleaning.
One of our new neighbors was parked in the driveway when I got
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have about a dozen cows and a great big bull?'' he
wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you ask?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in my yard eating my flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually they're my semi-farmer son's cows,'' I explain. Two
hours later the cows are back in their pasture and my neighbor is
no longer threatening to call the police.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted and brier-scratched from chasing cows through the
woods, I check the refrigerator to see if my wife was thoughtful
enough to fix a sandwich for my lunch. Before I can eat, the phone
rings. A fabulous offer to switch to a new telephone company! I
decline. I hang up and check the answering service.
</P>
<P>
   I receive a spousal suggestion that since I have to go town to
get light bulbs I can stop by the grocery and pick up a carton of
Eggbeaters, a quart of skim milk and a jar of low-fat mayonnaise.
And since Alex and Judy Moye are coming for dinner Friday night,
can I find somebody to dispose of limbs almost blocking the
driveway where the tree fell last month?
</P>
<P>
   I've already been to the hardware store and anybody who thinks I
can produce somebody to dispose of a fallen tree in less than three
weeks is out of touch with reality. I called my wife at her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we need to get the tree out of the driveway?'' I ask.
``Alex is a former airline pilot. Anybody who can fly a jet from
Atlanta to San Franciso can guide an automobile around a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look in the Yellow Pages and call a tree service,'' she
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   I get an answering service. ``We're sorry, we're not available
at this time. Please leave your name and number and we'll call you
back as soon as possible.'' Same thing with two other calls. I go
to the shop and dig out my chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   The blade is dull. I go back to the hardware store to get a
file. The saw needs gas. After paying for the file, the Eggbeaters,
the skim milk and the fat-free mayonnaise, I am out of money. I go
to the bank and cash a check. Since I haven't had time to eat my
sandwich, I stop at the Quickie for a Diet Coke and cheese
crackers. It is suppertime when I finish with the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you do with your day?'' she asks when we sit down for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, nothing much. Just fooled around the house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need to find yourself something to do with your
time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Contitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
