<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ghosts of past can haunt even most routine events
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA SPRINGS, Ark. _ Contact with the planet is limited to a
few square inches of rubber humming on asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-present wind roars in your ears and buffets your body.
You concentrate on the road _ brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   Miles pile upon miles. I think of my father, how in his grave he
has decided to talk.
</P>
<P>
   We never talked until years after the rifle salute made me jump
and the bugler playing taps made my mother cry.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what happened to the flag that the uniformed men folded
so smartly and handed to my mother so respectfully. Maybe my
brother has it.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   We come up behind a slow moving truck. The road hum and wind
roar drops in volume and pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The lead rider studies his passing opportunities on this narrow
mountain road. Each rider, in turn, will do the same. We know the
drill.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   As I wait my turn, I wonder why we have been drawn together in
an activity that precludes talk.
</P>
<P>
   Some motorcycle riders rig up small transmitters and microphones
so they can talk as they travel. No one in our group likes that
idea. We have a few hand signals. That's talk enough.
</P>
<P>
   We pass the truck, regroup and get back into our rhythm. Here's
a left-hand sweeper. Next is a right-hand switchback. We pick our
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   My companions listen to the same road sounds, see the same
sights, smell the same pine trees and feel the same wind gusts. I
wonder if they also talk to their fathers while they maneuver their
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   The men of our fathers' generation were seldom disposed to talk.
They saw a lot and did a lot. But they kept it to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Our fathers were men who survived the Great Depression and World
War II. They knew the hardships of keeping a family together during
the years of America's deepest deprivations.
</P>
<P>
   Their hard-earned experience taught them the importance of work.
Any task undertaken must be completed with utmost diligence.
</P>
<P>
   My father, and the fathers of my companions, knew the sacrifices
of fighting a brutal world war that lasted for years with no hope
for relief except in victory, death or incapacitation.
</P>
<P>
   The men of our fathers' generation returned home from World War
II and went to work. They rejected sympathy. They refused to
complain. They improved themselves with the GI Bill. They got jobs.
They did not talk about their privations or their feelings. They
raised their families. Us.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   My father never asked me how I felt about anything or told me
how he felt. For him, feelings were irrelevant _ a waste of breath.
</P>
<P>
   When you survive the Great Depression and World War II, you
learn that feelings don't put beans in a pot or turn back an enemy
attack. Everyone felt desperate. Actions count, not words. You have
to be strong to survive, and sometimes lucky as well. But you make
your own luck.
</P>
<P>
   We stop for gas, exchange a few comments, tighten our helmet
straps, blip the throttles and take off again enveloped in our
noise and thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if my companions chase the same ghosts. I wonder if
they also have conversations with their fathers that never
happened.
</P>
<P>
   One time I thought my father was getting ready to tell me
something that had been on his mind, something important. He
started to say something but stopped. Then he just punched me
lightly on the shoulder. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Brake, lean, accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His columns appear on Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail:
RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
