<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Playing doves and hawks
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Jefferson Clinton, as he's called when he's in trouble,
gave his fullest _ and best _ explanation of the war in Yugoslavia
to newspaper editors in San Francisco. We were there, he said, to
prevent a slaughter in a part of the world that, additionally,
tends to self-destruct periodically. It will be difficult now for
opponents to claim they just can't get it.
</P>
<P>
   The political landscape is like the surface of the moon,
fragmented, barren, hard to read. Both sides claim moral high
ground. Stop the slaughter. Stop the bombing. Send in ground troops
and bring the boys back home all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   After a period of bemusement, the public has found Yugoslavia on
the map. The Serbs, playing on the Vietnam analogy, have made a
poor case for themselves as victims. Americans seem to understand
the difference between war and premeditated slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be emerging is a need for any administration to
define what slaughters we are likely to oppose in the future. Many
African Americans, for instance, wonder if we'd do the same if the
victims were of color. Barring our involvement in all world
atrocities, what seems to be emerging is the need for a clear
demonstration of the national interest. That's cold-blooded, but
fairer than any alternative offered.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
