<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weighing the pros and cons of woodworking magazines
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anyone who has visited this space for very long knows
of the soft spot that lurks in my heart for Fine Woodworking
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the magazine, and its publisher, The Taunton Press, I
wouldn't be writing this. The magazine, and Taunton Press's books,
published the first widely available information on how proper
woodworking is done, and as far as I'm concerned, launched the
woodworking revolution that continues apace today.
</P>
<P>
   I've had some differences _ on occasion fairly loud ones _ with
the magazine, and for a time it fell somewhat behind its burgeoning
competition, but by and large it remains the best woodworking
publication on the market for my money.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Woodworking pioneered woodworking how-to videos, but was
rather late to jump into the Internet. However, it now has a
remarkably good Web site which, even more remarkably, offers a lot
of free information.
</P>
<P>
   Most magazines don't give away much of their content on the
Internet; after all, they're in business to get subscriptions which
help them to charge more for their advertising. But Fine
Woodworking's site is generous.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the free stuff are videos. I looked at a slick
video clip of Mario Rodriguez demonstrating how to properly tune a
hand plane, beginning with flattening the sole. To view these
online videos, you need a little program called RealPlayer. There's
a free version of it, and Fine Woodworking's site will lead you to
a place where you can download it if you don't have it.
</P>
<P>
   The free version isn't anything great. It presents the video in
fits and starts, although the audio flows pretty well. However, it
was adequate for this purpose. The clip is not one of those
30-second teases you so often see in situations like this. It lasts
for several minutes and provides a good demonstration on flattening
the sole, truing the blade and all the other elements of plane
tuning.
</P>
<P>
   There are also featured videos of Richard Raffan turning a bowl
and another expert carving linenfold panels. These are, the site
says, tied into articles in the current issue. This raises some
confusion; the current issue, according to the site, is the April
issue, which does not have those articles. Presumably they'll be
forthcoming in the May-June issue.
</P>
<P>
   The quick-loading site also includes useful excerpts from past
tool reviews, technique and material advice, and a lot of other
good stuff. It will take you a while to absorb it all. There is a
veritable gold mine of links to other woodcentric sites. The
address, predictably, is www.finewoodworking.com.
</P>
<P>
   American Woodworker, FWW's chief competition, was sold earlier
this year by Rodale Prerss to Reader's Digest. American Woodworker
has a good site, too, although it is considerably less ambitious
than Fine Woodworking's.
</P>
<P>
   Its chief attraction is reprints of many, if not all, of its
major tool reviews, a rather obvious kind of article that FWW
refused to do until American Woodworker gobbled up serious amounts
of its territory.
</P>
<P>
   The American Woodworker address is www.americanwoodworker.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
