</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, April 24
and Sunday, April 25, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books, fashion, and
home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-LIGHT _ Terri Evans of Atlanta will join nine other
national finalists this weekend in a recipe contest/cook-off at
Turner Field. The contest is part of a first-ever festival staged
by Cooking Light magazine, which has become the nation's number one
food and fitness magazine. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COOKLIGHT-RECIPES _ This inside story has short intro and list
of highlights and two recipes from the Cooking Light Extravaganza
at Turner Field. Photos: Local woman who's entering contest, and
closeup of a pie slice. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ Exploring the Fine Woodworking magazine's Web
site. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY FOR
SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0423 CHILD ALIENATION _ The American teen-ager:
yearning to stand out, and desperate to fit in. Struggling to be a
rebel, yet terrified of losing status with the cool group. It is an
age of alienation. A sense of being on the outside looking in is
``typical in adolescence, from 12 to 18,'' say experts who deal
with teens. Such alienation breeds feelings of rejection. What
makes a troubled kid cross the line into real anger, and real
violence? (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOOK EXCERPT _ The ability of children to manage anger and
handle conflict is a topic of conversation in the wake of the
school shootings in Colorado. During the next five weeks, the
CoxNet SCIHEALTH page will feature excerps of a book that addresses
the conflict issue, ``Tired of Yelling.'' Part 1 wil deal with
reflexive defensiveness _ a conditioned, rapid, automatic response
of resistance children develop that limits communication and shuts
down learning (Waugh, Longstreet Press) Art includes 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH BRIEFS _ (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLLEN _ Every morning by 5:10, Atlanta's pollen patrol peers
through a microscope at hundreds of pink circular blobs. Then, they
sort and count: One pine, two pine, three pine; one oak, two oak;
one ash; one sweet gum. How those numbers add up will make or break
the day for hundreds of thousands of metro Atlanta allergy
sufferers. The blobs are pollen. LaWanda Day, Marie McFalls and Pam
Griggs are the pollen counters for the Atlanta Asthma &AMP; Allergy
Clinic that posts the information daily on its pollen hotline.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION and
PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT _ The debate over health care costs almost always focuses
on hospital costs, doctors fees and the supposed evils of managed
care. But health care costs burn holes in the pockets of millions
of Americans who incur a hidden expense caring for a loved one at
home. As our population ages, more and more families find
themselves in this caretaking situation _ often at great, even
crippling expense. Mary Bennett is one of those people. With more
than $2 million in health care bills for her son, Bennett is one of
those people who say they could use the $1,000 tax credit proposed
by President Clinton for families who care for loved ones at home.
But is this something government should be doing? And where do we
draw the line? As more and more families incur added burden of
caring for a loved one at home, this is a debate that will continue
for some time. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 25
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-CARE _ Members of emergency relief teams sponsored by
Atlanta-based CARE, risk their lives for people in need. Their work
is often uplifting. It's also often depressing and difficult.
Occasionally volunteers begin questioning their faith and values.
We write many stories about people finding God. This story will
focus on people who have lost their faith after being confronted by
the horrors of genocide, war, famine and disease. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUTS
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-PSYCHIATRY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ People don't expect to see a
yarmulke on their psychiatrist's head, but Dr. David Rube says
they're often reassured at the sight of his. It tells them they are
welcome to talk about God here, even if they don't share his
Orthodox Jewish faith. That's not true in every psychiatrist's
office, Rube (pronounced ``Ruby'') says. Many of his colleagues
prefer to keep spirituality as far from their practices as palm
reading or spoon bending. ``The history of psychiatry has been
extremely secular,'' he says, ``taking the view that religion is
something to be interpreted and is a neurotic defense mechanism.''
As a result, Rube says psychiatrists often shut out their patients'
spiritual sides at a time when they're most likely to surface.
That's one reason he developed the course for residents at that
Wright State University School of Medicine that was awarded
nationally last week for incorporating spirituality into medicine.
(Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FORSATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE NELSON _ SHREVEPORT, La. _ We visit Willie Nelson on his
tour bus in Shreveport, La. for a profile advancing his appearance
at Music Midtown. Despite his IRS woes, which drove him to the
brink a few years ago, this most intransigent of American voices
has never one out of style. Of late, he's been making some of the
best records of his career. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
45. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TVSWEEPS _ When May sweeps start Thursday (4/29) look for big
historical blockbusters, including ``Cleopatra,'' ``Joan of Arc''
and ``Noah's Ark'' - new TV versions, not old movies. Also, ``Home
Improvement'' and ``Melrose Place'' take their leaves - not quite
causing the stir of the ``Seinfeld'' finale. (Kloer/, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
