<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ A quiet conversation with my father while
riding the roads on a motorcycle. (Rowland Nethaway is senior
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ When things get so bad that
you believe they can't get worse, you need to find a reason to
believe in miracles again. You need to eat ice cream and hug your
children _ not necessarily in that order. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ My golden years are
complicated by having married a child bride who continues in the
work force. I'm the one who has to be home when repairmen come ...
(Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ What do we do in the midst of the Littleton,
Colo., tragedy? We can listen to Dixie Kirkland, who passionately
tries to save lives with her gun-safety program. Or we can tell our
children that every right takes precedence over their right to grow
up safe, to go to school without fear. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The ever-sharp Sam Nunn is making the point in
interviews that NATO should first have unleashed an aggressive
information campaign before an air campaign. Our failure to make it
clear to Serbian civilians just what horrors Slobodan Milosevic was
committing has made the NATO attack seem arbitrary and abusive to
most Serbians. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Keeping the Croats, the Serbs, Kosovars and
whomever else apart by adhering to a homogeneous formula might
appear inviting until you recognize the precedent it is setting.
While the world at one time must have been ethnically divided by
natural means, it is not now, and cannot be. (Howard Kleinberg is a
columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ CHICAGO -- You can sense that a seismic shift is
uprooting the computing world when fully loaded machines are being
sold on the World Wide Web for $599. Each of these units is more
powerful than the $80 million behemoth that ran the North American
Air Defense Command a few decades ago. (Andy Glass is a columnist
for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTTAKES-ROSENFELD _ What seems to be emerging from Kosovo is
a need for any administration to define what slaughters we are
likely to oppose in the future. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ It's the lesson we should be teaching and
stressing to our children in our homes and our schools, demanding
it no less than we do racial tolerance: Be kind to one another.
Accept people as they are. Be a friend to the friendless. Cliques
are for jerks. Nerd is an n-word. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
