<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-COUNTRY-FUNDS-     04-23 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COUNTRY-FUNDS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE-COUNTRY FUNDS SEEKING NEW HORIZONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the closed-end country fund becoming a thing of the past?
Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Several closed-end stock funds have changed their charters to
broaden the geographic areas in which they can invest. And since
mid-1997, a half-dozen country funds have decided to either convert
to open-end status or liquidate altogether, among them the Scudder
Spain and Portugal, New South Africa and Emerging Mexico funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a declining relative importance and a real argument,
particularly among the pan-European funds, that they're obsolete,''
said Michael T. Porter, a managing partner at Salomon Smith Barney,
who specializes in closed-end funds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike open-end mutual funds, closed-end funds issue a fixed
number of shares that trade like those of ordinary companies. As
such, they may trade at a premium or a discount to the value of the
assets they hold.
</P>
<P>
   As of February, $6.6 billion was invested in 46 single-country
closed-end equity funds, which were once a preferred way to invest
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For European offerings, one problem for country funds was the
launch of the European Monetary Community in January. Analysts
expect that with one currency, European markets will move more in
tandem, dampening demand for funds that limit themselves to one
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In response, a number of country funds are looking farther
afield from the geographic areas in their names. Both the Future
Germany fund, rechristened the Central European Equity fund, and
the Emerging Germany fund, now the Dresdner RCM Europe fund, have
asked their shareholders for approval to change their charters to
allow them to invest more of their assets outside Germany. The
Dresdner fund will also convert to an open-end structure next
month.
</P>
<P>
   France Growth, meanwhile, has formed a committee to consider
changing its charter, although the fund remains 100 percent
invested in France.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for some funds seems to be a lack of
distinguishing characteristics. There is little difference, for
example, in the portfolios of two closed-end funds managed by
Deutsche Bank _ the Germany Fund and the Central European Equity
fund _ Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the euro is by no means the only force
behind the changes. Shareholder activists, irate that closed-end
funds of all kinds are trading at discounts, have been pressing to
liquidate such funds or convert them to open-ended structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single-country funds are under the most attack by the
dissidents,'' said Thomas J. Herzfeld, a closed-end fund specialist
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian market meltdowns of 1997 and 1998 did not help the
region's closed-end funds. As investors fled, managers sought the
greater flexibility offered by a regional approach.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, for example, the Templeton Vietnam Opportunity fund
changed its name and expanded its charter to focus more on
Southeast Asia. (Schroder Asian Growth changed its name to Schroder
All-Asia and converted to an open-end fund last month and Fidelity
Advisor Asia plans a conversion in June.)
</P>
<P>
   Also sapping demand for country funds has been the growing
popularity of World Equity Benchmark Shares or Webs. These unit
investment trusts closely track the Morgan Stanley Capital
International index for particular countries, and are now available
for 17 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts say they are not yet ready to write the
funds, even if some of them are now facing tough times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everything else in the market, this, too, is cyclical,''
said Douglas Beck, a senior international equity fund analyst at
Merrill Lynch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
