A0355 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV25-N     04-23 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leveraged Buyouts For the Middling Wealthy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leveraged-buyout funds for individuals are here. Or at least
buyout funds for pretty rich individuals.
</P>
<P>
   With a minimum investment of just $250,000 _ a pittance for its
type _ a fund introduced by Independence Holdings Partners LLC, a
New York investment firm, has given investors a chance to partake
of leveraged buyouts. Though that fund has already closed, another
is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The first fund, Independence Private Equity Select, closed in
March after a subscription period that netted more than $50
million. A fund of funds, Independence Private Equity is invested
in three leveraged buyout funds, all of which are managed by
leading investment firms: Apollo Advisors; Clayton, Dubilier &AMP;
Rice, and Hicks, Muse Tate, &AMP; Furst.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a need for a relatively budget-priced leveraged buyout
fund? Absolutely, said Mark Klein, managing member of Independence
Holdings. ``Wealthy individuals don't have access to private equity
markets,'' he said, noting that institutions were the primary
beneficiaries of earlier buyouts. That means individuals have
missed out on returns of more than 40 percent a year from past
funds managed by three other firms, according to Klein's research.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pay Independence Holdings a 1 percent annual advisory
fee, as well as a so-called incentive allocation of 5 percent of
all profits after their initial investment is returned to them over
the funds' life. That is in addition to the fees paid to the
underlying funds. Klein expects the fund to return all capital and
proceeds to investors in less than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Holdings, which Klein describes as an ``alternative
investment company for high-net-worth individuals,'' expects to
offer its second leveraged-buyout fund later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The funds, which are treated as private equity placements, have
stringent requirements for assets and income. Investors may contact
their private bankers or financial advisers to see if they
qualify. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Bill to Increase Bond Transparency &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors frustrated by the dearth of bond price data may soon
be getting some help from Washington. The House of Representatives
is expected to consider a bill this week that would require
corporate bond traders to disclose the same kind of price, volume
and other data as stock traders do.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the Bond Price Competition Improvement Act of 1999,
instructs the Securities and Exchange Commission to insure that
transaction information is made public. The SEC would decide how to
disseminate the data.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., who is chairman of the
commerce committee, the bill also asks the SEC to study price
competition in municipal bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bliley cited the wide price differences that
investors face when buying. ``In the equity markets there is a
mechanism for distributing price information to the public to make
sure that does not occur,'' he said. ``No such system exists in the
corporate debt markets, and that needs to be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill is endorsed by the Bond Marketing Association and the
National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Is Seeking A Higher On-Line Profile &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the world's biggest mutual fund company,
will try to increase the visibility of its Internet brokerage
business with a new advertising campaign. The ads, starting Monday,
are aimed at attracting on-line investors who don't already own
Fidelity funds.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will emphasize the speed and reliability of
Fidelity.com with the theme ``every second counts,'' said Stephen
Cone, president of Fidelity's personal investing and brokerage
group. He added that Fidelity would spend 20 percent to 30 percent
of its roughly $200 million 1999 advertising budget on building its
brokerage business.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has rejected the idea of selling some stock in the
brokerage business to the public as a way to raise its profile,
Cone said. ``We don't need the capital,'' he said, adding that
Edward C. Johnson, Fidelity's chief executive, ``feels very
strongly about remaining private.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the story out more,'' Cone said. ``Not many
people know that we are the second-largest on-line broker'' in
terms of the number of accounts, behind Charles Schwab. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News)
</P>
</TEXT>
