r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN25-CO     04-23 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The case against cliques
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We'll always have psychotics among us, often never knowing it
until they explode with mass violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some psychotics are born that way. Some are made that way.
</P>
<P>
   Some learn it in school.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine put it best:
</P>
<P>
   The recent school massacre, the worst ever, was another revenge
of the nerds.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't said lightly. Truth should never be taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   It's this simple:
</P>
<P>
   Friends don't kill friends.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every case of school shootings, the killers were kids
who couldn't fit in.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't be like everyone else, then they'll be different.
They'll wear black leather jackets, or black trenchcoats.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't be an all-American kid, they'll be a Nazi.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't be a part of the school, they'll blow it apart.
</P>
<P>
   You remember what it was like in school. If you didn't run with
the crowd, the crowd ran over you. And there was always the odd guy
out.
</P>
<P>
   How did we deal with him? We avoided him, as if whatever he
lacked would somehow rub off on us.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't surprising that a few of the shunned ones, constantly
picked on in the pecking order, end up gunning down their
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising is that there aren't more.
</P>
<P>
   Schools worry about gangs. They should worry about cliques.
</P>
<P>
   There's no crueler society than school cliques.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the adult world were the same, if individuals were
singled out to be shunned or ridiculed by adult groups, in the work
place, in religious gatherings, in social and civic clubs, as they
so often are in school.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an outrage, something akin to racial prejudice. Yet
it's an attitude common among our children, more so in their teen
years.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that all changes once we've graduated into real life.
It's class dismissed for the class system of jocks and nerds.
</P>
<P>
   Decency, civility, good manners and common courtesy become a
second nature that comes with maturity. Snobs are a joke. Only the
worst of people think they're better than someone else.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson in life that we eventually learn for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's the lesson we should be teaching and stressing to our
children in our homes and our schools, demanding it no less than we
do racial tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Be kind to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Accept people as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Be a friend to the friendless.
</P>
<P>
   Cliques are for jerks.
</P>
<P>
   Nerd is an n-word.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
