<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 23, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING-GUNS (Littleton, Colo.) _ Other than the
victims' families and friends, nobody has been more devastated by
the Columbine High School massacre than Doug Dean, the state
legislature's House majority leader, say his friends and fervent
opponents. Dean sponsored two anti-gun-control bills that failed
after triggering one of the most heated debates in Colorado's
history. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING-INTERNET _ While the murders were still under
way in Columbine High School, the Internet was becoming a magnet
for entrepreneurs, wackos and a gullible media anxious to find a
teenage massacre-World Wide Web connection. Almost as soon as news
of Tuesday's horror was being broadcast, the domain name
``Trenchcoat Mafia'' was being registered on the World Wide Web. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT-BUTCHERS (San Francisco) _ The primeval equivalent of
your neighborhood meat market has been found near the village of
Bouri in the Afar desert of Ethiopia, scientists have reported. The
discovery of prehistoric antelope bones covered with scratches
caused by knife-like rocks means that a primitive version of the
butcher shop has been part of humans' ancestry for 2.5 million
years, at least a half million years longer than previously
thought. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-TRANSPLANTS (San Francisco) _ Survival rates for patients
who received heart transplants from people infected with hepatitis
C are not much different than for similar patients who got
uninfected hearts _ lending support to the trend of using such
organs in the face of a nationwide shortage, according to two new
studies. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   ROJAS-DALLAS (San Francisco) _ This city's school chief Bill
Rojas has accepted an offer to run Dallas' school system and will
leave here by August, sending a jolt through a district already
shaken by allegations of fiscal recklessness and questionable
testing practices. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP-SEA-PROBE (San Francisco) _ Secretary of Commerce William
M. Daley, in announcing the launch of a five-year, $12 million
underwater research project here, says, ``What this means is divers
can go to depths we can only dream about.'' By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-CHURCH (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Rev. James Kenyon of the
Christ and St. Barnabas Episcopal Church in Troy, N.Y., has in the
last decade brought some 200 southeast Asian refugees to this
region and has approached their resettlement with a missionary
zeal. By MICHAEL LOPEZ. (For release Sunday release.)
</P>
<P>
   COCKFIGHT-RAID (San Antonio) _ The fruits of a police raid on an
illegal cockfight are now in the custody of a Texas veterinarian.
Dr. David Darter of Crystal City says timid owners are slowly
claiming their gamecocks. Although illegal in the state, cockfights
remain popular. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DURANGO (Undated) _ With a movie named ``Durango,'' you knew
there had to be a cattle drive. You just figured it would have been
in 1880s America, not 1939 Ireland. But even with the brogues and
lush dells, ``Durango,'' based on the autobiographical novel by
Irish writer John B. Keane, still has a Western feel. And it is
worthy as the 201st installment of the Hallmark Hall of Fame
series. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   MASEKELA (Houston) _ South African trumpeter Hugh Masekela has
moved around a lot over the years. Since he has returned to his
homeland, he has become something of a national institution. By
RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GETREAL (Undated) _ With the American high school
sex comedy of late being in more desperate shape than a girl
without a prom date, it's odd that ``Get Real,'' the coolest, most
sophisticated entrant in this dubious sweepstakes would come from
England and would feature being young, gay and conflicted as its
subject. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD-MUSEUM (San Francisco) _ The new Cantor Center for
Visual Arts at Stanford University has an impressive exhibition,
``Pacific Arcadia: Images of California, 1600-1915,'' which
continues through June 27. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   BBC-MUSIC (Undated) _ It's more than a bit humbling to sit down
with the first batch of ``Great Performers of the Twentieth
Century,'' the exceptional new historical series of compact discs
published on the new BBC Legends label and distributed stateside by
Koch International. By ALLAN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BLUES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Great One has quit hockey for
good. John Elway is still contemplating whether or not to join
Wayne Gretzky and Michael Jordan in retirement. Cal Ripken isn't a
man of steel after all. Depressing times call for desperate
measures, like watching a movie. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING-LESSONS (San Francisco) _ You'd pray that after
Littleton, the growing national revulsion against firearms would
achieve a critical mass, making radical political measures
possible. You'd hope that people in power would stand up on their
hind legs and shout, ``Melt the damn things down! Never make them
again!'' It won't happen. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
