<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT ABOUT PEER ABUSE AT SCHOOL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been hearing all the appropriate questions about that
horrifying murder spree at a Colorado high school:
</P>
<P>
   How did a pair of psychopathic teen-agers get their hands on
such a deadly arsenal of guns and explosives?
</P>
<P>
   How did the killers' parents, friends and teachers fail to see
that these young men were walking time bombs who posed a lethal
threat to themselves and to everyone around them?
</P>
<P>
   Why did officials at Columbine High School in Littleton fail to
provide sufficient security to prevent such a rampage?
</P>
<P>
   Why can't society do something to stop the epidemic of ambush
violence that has plagued American schools in recent years?
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and on. In the end, though, every question is
just another way of asking the one question that no one seems able
to answer:
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   When Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris began their mindless, random
assault at Columbine High School the other day, Colorado joined a
growing list of states where schools have suffered such terror:
Mississippi, Kentucky, Arkansas, Pennsylvania, Oregon ...
</P>
<P>
   And the question is always the same: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Too many guns? Too much violence in the media? Too little
discipline at school? Not enough parental involvement at home?
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure, all those factors play a role in such tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another factor, a common thread that seems to run
through these events, and it raises yet another question: How in
the world did these young people become so alienated, so full of
rage, that they would even contemplate such a cataclysmic act of
violence, much less carry it out?
</P>
<P>
   Friends and acquaintances of the two students who shot and
bombed their way through the school have been saying that Klebold,
Harris and their cohorts in the so-called Trenchcoat Mafia were
angry about their treatment by other students, especially athletes.
</P>
<P>
   News reports suggest that there were racist and Nazi overtones
to the Littleton murders. But it is clear that the killers' primary
source of fury was that they were ``picked on'' by kids who
disliked the small band of trenchcoat-wearing misfits.
</P>
<P>
   TV talk-show host Larry King interviewed a girl who had been
friendly with one of the killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would he kill people just because they were athletes?''
asked King, an ardent sports fan and unabashed admirer of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really mean to him,'' the girl replied.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids don't resort to mass murder as retaliation for being
picked on at school, of course, and it goes without saying that no
amount of verbal humiliation can justify violence. No one is
looking to mitigate the horror of what Klebold and Harris did; no
one is looking to minimize their culpability.
</P>
<P>
   If the perpetrators hadn't preempted the judicial process by
taking their own lives, the people of Colorado no doubt would have
and should have demanded the maximum penalty available under the
law.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no mercy for these coldblooded assassins. There can
be no excuses for what they did.
</P>
<P>
   But in trying to understand why such things occur, we must not
overlook the torment they endured at the hands of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who aren't ``cool'' and aren't part of the ``in'' crowd are
all too often treated with disdain by those who are. The ``nerds''
and outsiders who don't wear the right clothes, join the right
clubs or frequent the right hangouts are all too often subjected to
a level of public and private humiliation that can destroy a young
person's already shaky confidence and sense of self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   When the victims of derision complain, they are usually told
that they will just have to live with it; that it's part of growing
up; that life isn't fair.
</P>
<P>
   And those who inflict the humiliation?
</P>
<P>
   Are they ever reprimanded, or even called aside and told that
they have an obligation to show a reasonable amount of respect
toward fellow students _ including those who might seem
``different''?
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a fair question to ask. As long as we're asking
questions.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
