<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DURANGO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS OFFERS A GOOD RIDE IN `DURANGO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a movie named ``Durango,'' you knew there had to be a
cattle drive. It's a law or something. You just figured it would
have been in 1880s Colorado, not 1939 Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the brogues and lush dells, ``Durango,'' based on
the autobiographical novel by Irish writer John B. Keane, still has
a Western feel. You half expect John Wayne in his ``Quiet Man''
garb to amble in with a ``Wagon ... Ho-oh.''
</P>
<P>
   Sight unseen, you know ``Durango'' (Sunday at 9 p.m. Eastern,
CBS) is going to be good. Forget the alphabet networks, the HBOs,
all the other cable outlets. If you want a quality movie on
television, go with anything stamped ``Hallmark.'' And ``Durango''
is worthy as the 201st installment of the Hallmark Hall of Fame
series.
</P>
<P>
   Set in County Kerry just prior to the outset of World War II, it
is the story of Mark Doran (Matt Keeslar, ``The Last Days of
Disco''), who tires of the monopolistic cattle-buying practices in
his hometown and decides to drive his and his neighbors' cattle
over 40 miles of terrain to get a better price in another town. Of
course, the rough Irish countryside and the cattle barons seek to
thwart the young Doran, leading to fires, stampedes, fisticuffs,
you know, everything short of Apaches waiting to attack from the
cliffs. In the end, everyone rides off, not into the sunset, but a
saloon.
</P>
<P>
   Predictable? A bit, but so were some of those great old
Westerns. Kick back for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bergin (``Sleeping with the Enemy,'' ``Patriot Games''),
Brenda Fricker, George Hearn, Nancy St. Alban, Dermot Martin and
Paul Ronan co-star.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patty Duke Show'' began about four months before the
Beatles landed in New York City, and ended as acid rock was
arriving on the scene. It was a fun little sitcom about cousins,
identical cousins, two of a kind, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patty Duke Show'' ran from September 1963 to August 1966
at 8 p.m. Wednesdays on ABC. Duke, the teen-ager who won the
Academy Award for her spellbinding performance as Helen Keller in
``The Miracle Worker,'' comes back Tuesday night at 9 Eastern (CBS)
in ``The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Lane the wild one grew up to be the drama teacher at good
old Brooklyn Heights High School. Cathy, the proper cousin, returns
from her native Scotland after the death of her husband. The two
re-unite to fight a morally corrupt developer _ their high school
foe _ from closing the school so a new mall can open.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the old cast, even Patty Lane's parents (William
Schallert and Jean Byron) return, although old nemesis Sue Ellen is
played in the telemovie by Cindy Williams (``Laverne &AMP; Shirley'').
</P>
<P>
   The value here is purely nostalgic. This is a so-so movie. Then
again, it was a so-so series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After an initial report, CBS was very late in cutting back from
regular programming Tuesday to update the high school shooting
situation in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, WRGB, Channel 6 in Albany, N.Y., was forced to stick
with Sally Jesse Raphael while other networks were going to
extended live reports.
</P>
<P>
   It probably didn't matter much, since the best coverage of the
tragedy was on CNN and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Sally's topic: ``I was locked up for punishing my
teen.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
