<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BLUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS FANS, MAKE WAY FOR THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Great One has quit hockey for good. But
mostly, for bad.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association is plodding listlessly
through a season that has as much meaning as an episode of ``Just
Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   John Elway is still contemplating whether or not to join Wayne
Gretzky and Michael Jordan in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken isn't a man of steel after all.
</P>
<P>
   The true Olympic movement has turned out to be a hand reaching
under a table for money.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenyans have taken over the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Depressing times call for desperate measures. The only sensible,
mature response is to get away from it all. Escape. Take a break
from reality.
</P>
<P>
   Go into a dark room and shut out the real world. See a movie.
Now showing at a theater _ or coming to a video store _ near you:
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' _ Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence play Ray and Claude,
two men who are wrongfully convicted of murder in Mississippi in
the 1940s. Ray and Claude manage to keep their sense of humor and a
healthy outlook on life despite seeing O.J. Simpson walking the
streets a free man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is Beautiful'' _ Roberto Benigni stars in this Academy
Award-winning film about an overprotective father who convinces his
young son that their incarceration at a concentration camp is part
of an elaborate game. Despite the grim setting, the film has a
feel-good ending when Benigni's character fails to live to see a
day when synchronized swimming, snowboarding and softball are
Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' _ Steven Spielberg directs this wringing
drama about Ryan Leaf, whose childishness and churlishness get him
demoted from field general.
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' _ The year is 1957, and the Russians have just
launched Sputnik, and America appears to be losing the space race,
and the only thing that can prevent global destruction is the
Chicago Cubs winning the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' _ Bill Murray gives a deftly subtle portrayal of a
man tormented by how much the New York Knicks have begun to
resemble stone monuments carved into a mountain in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' _ Clint Eastwood directs, produces and stars in
this story about a reporter sent to interview a death-row inmate.
The reporter works frantically to reverse the conviction until he
discovers that the inmate used to be a sports agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' _ Jennifer Love Hewitt
stretches her acting muscles by playing Mark McGwire, who can't get
any peace and quiet after he hits 70 home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Geniuses'' _ Kathleen Turner and Christopher Lloyd play
two evil doctors who are convinced that baby talk holds some of the
secrets of the universe. Their plan goes awry when one of the
babies escapes from the lab and grows up to become Shaquille
O'Neal, and he starts doing movies and making rap records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Waterboy'' _ Adam Sandler stars in a coming-of-age story
of a waterboy who blossoms into the best player on the New Jersey
Nets. After one season at the Meadowlands, the title character
decides he was less of a loser in his old life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions'' _ Sarah Michelle Gellar portrays Augusta
National and Ryan Phillippe portrays Greg Norman in this trashy
update of ``Dangerous Liaisons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The King and I'' _ Darrell Hammond stars in this Shakespearean
adaptation of a story about a boxing promoter who always knows the
outcome of a fight in advance. Miranda Richardson does a convincing
turn as a boxing judge without a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You'' _ Philadelphia fans give a warm
welcome to Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb when the Eagles take
him with the No. 2 pick of the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hideous Kinky'' _ Kate Winslet stars in one of those English
countryside mood pieces that takes a dramatic twist when a
gum-chomping football coach _ played by Mike Ditka _ tries to trade
all his earthly possessions for a set of dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go'' _ Doug Liman directs this surprising gem of a picture
about an assortment of Los Angeles troublemakers who go out into
the night in search of ways to feel alive. A strange series of
coincidences draws the characters to a Clippers game, compelling
them to buy Nikes and monitor the Hale-Bopp comet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' _ Ian Bannen and David Kelly star as two
old men who learn the sobering lesson that winning the lottery can
mean ending up with Derrick Coleman on your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' _ Billy Crystal stars in the Harold
Ramis-directed film about a shrink who tries to talk NFL draft
analyst Mel Kiper Jr. into getting a life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight Millimeter'' _ Nicholas Cage stars in this documentary
about the height of major-league baseball's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Favorite Martian'' _ At long last, the truth about Dennis
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' _ Darryl Strawberry. A female undercover
cop. A heaping helping of white powder. Can there possibly be a
happy ending?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
