<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REIVEW-GET-REAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RARE TEEN MOVIE THAT GETS REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the American high school sex comedy of late being in more
desperate shape than a girl without a prom date, it's odd that the
coolest, most sophisticated entrant in this dubious sweepstakes _
``Get Real'' _ would come from Britain and would feature being
young, gay and conflicted as its subject.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Shore's film of Patrick Wilde's play, ``What's Wrong with
Angry?'' is the first of these movies to circumvent pop-culture
savvy and goes straight for John Hughes
adolescent-angst-as-adult-torment.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of coming to terms with his homosexuality, Steven
Carter (Ben Silverstone) falls in love with John Dixon (Brad
Gorton), the highly closeted prep school track star. John falls
back, but gives Steven a heap of parameters to follow. (It'd be
simpler for Steven to maintain a Gremlin farm than the secrecy of
this relationship. He can't tell his best girlfriend, the great
Charlotte Brittain).
</P>
<P>
   When the film's poised tone and occasional staginess threaten to
intrude on the moving, sincere, recognizably true drama, the fact
that the source material comes from a recent work, not some
400-year-old play, keeps it real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
