A0474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-LESSO     04-23 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-LESSONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSON FROM COLUMBINE HIGH: OUTLAW GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You would pray that after Littleton, the growing
national revulsion against firearms would make radical political
measures possible.
</P>
<P>
   You would hope the people in power would stand up on their hind
legs and shout, ``Melt the damn things down! Never make them
again!''
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: Littleton was business as usual in America; these
campus bloodbaths are a thing with us, like assassinations in the
1960s. That's the awful truth, and it should stick in every
citizen's craw like a jagged turkey bone.
</P>
<P>
   Before Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold ran amok at Columbine High
School, other crazed boys armed to the teeth behaved with similar
brutality toward students and teachers in Springfield, Ore.;
Fayetteville, Tenn.; Edinboro, Pa.; Jonesboro, Ark.; West Paducah,
Ky.; and Pearl, Miss. You could organize a tour of the nation's
blood-soaked schoolyards, like tours of Civil War battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the laugh Slobodan Milosevic had when he saw the
children fleeing the Colorado high school on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Redemption lies in one direction and one only, but we don't have
the will to go there. This is as contemptible as it is tragic.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie Becker, director of the Legal Community Against Violence
in San Francisco, took the nation's pulse after Littleton and found
it lamentably weak in political resolve to ban firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that this happened in Colorado,'' Becker said,
``at a time when its new governor, Bill Owens, has been very
friendly to the gun lobby and has promised to expand legislation
that would expand the state's concealed-weapon permit law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colorado leaves the question of who should have a concealed
weapon to the sole discretion of police chiefs and sheriffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker said the gun lobby is pushing hard in favor of concealed-
weapon permits in every state without a right-to-carry law.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby is also fine-tuning its vigilance on the issue of
``pre-emption.''
</P>
<P>
   This is legal jargon for the federal law _ specifically, the
purported right to bear arms _ that pre-empts state gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the gun nuts claim, at least. Denver has tough
controls, Becker said. Not so Littleton, a suburb of 35,000 to the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owens also has been encouraging a bill that would pre-empt
places like Denver from regulating guns beyond what the rest of the
state decides to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Becker if there is any chance to enact a national
handgun ban.
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about banning guns altogether. I don't see that,''
Becker said, with the impatience of someone who understands a
problem too well.
</P>
<P>
   What about piecemeal measures? Say you were a fence-sitter
before Littleton and you're a gun-control proponent today. What can
you do?
</P>
<P>
   Call your lawmakers, Becker said. Make it clear to your
representative that he or she should back measures that would make
the widespread illegal trafficking in guns harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get closer to a sane gun policy,'' Becker said, ``with
every shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker also wants to see schools pony up as much as $20,000 each
to buy safety assessment programs. There are plenty of experts out
there who can analyze a school situation, both the physical plant
and the site's collective mentality, and identify the points of
vulnerability. Metal detectors? Maybe. Mental health counselors?
Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   But many schools are hard-pressed for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the philanthropic and business communities should offer
the resources,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   There was urgency in her voice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
