<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern festivals
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Blairsville, Ga., _ The annual Wildflower Walk at Vogel State
Park in the heart of the Chattahoochee National Forest is Saturday.
The hike is led by an experienced naturalist. 706-745-2628.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Ga., _ The 30th Anniversary Riverfest Weekend Friday
through Sunday along the Riverwalk Downtown features Salisbury
Fair, Pig Jig BBQ Cookoff and Folklife Village. 706-324-7417.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga., _ The Thomasville Rose Festival Friday
through Sunday encompasses the 78th Annual Thomasville Rose Show
Friday and Saturday at the Thomasville Exchange Club Fairgrounds
(featuring a garden show, lectures and ``Tea and Rose,'' a tea and
fashion show; 1-800-704-2350); a parade and street dance in
historic downtown on Friday night; the Rose Patch Country Fair
Friday and Saturday next to the Victorian Rose Garden; and the 58th
Annual Flower Show Sunday. 912-227-7020.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Huntsville, Ala. _ Panoply 1999, Huntsville's Festival of the
Arts, is Friday through Sunday at Big Spring International Park
downtown. The event includes a Songwriter's Showcase, a
choreography competition, dance groups, bands and sidewalk
entertainers. Children will enjoy discovery activities such as Art
Car, theatrical makeup and Lego City. 1-800-648-5381.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Townsend, Tenn. _ The Spring Festival is Sunday through May 1
at the Visitors Center, where musicians will jam and there will be
old-fashioned children's games, antique engine and tractor show,
storytelling and nature talks. The festivities conclude with the
Smokies Bar-B-Que Cookoff and Old Timers Day on May 1.
1-800-525-6834.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saluda, S.C. _ The 8th Annual Saluda County National Timber
Festival and Wildlife Expo Saturday includes a parade featuring
some of the newest logging trucks and equipment in the industry,
entertainment, amateur competitions (crosscut saw, bow saw,
pulpwood stick relay and log rolling), logger load competition,
arts and crafts and food. 864-445-4100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Panama City Beach, Fla. _ The Car Craft Magazine Spring
Nationals Thursday through Sunday include citywide activities,
including a manufacturer's midway, vendor booths, poker run,
navigational rally, show and shine competition, scavenger hunt and
street cruise. All makes and models of cars are invited to
participate; to pre-register or get information, call the hotline
at 323-782-2831.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Live Oak, Fla. _ The Children's Wish Foundation and the
National Wildlife Federation are sponsoring an Earth Awareness
Festival Friday through Sunday at the Suwannee Music Park. Acts
include Badfinger, Les Dubek, Mindwalk, Nicko McBrain from Iron
Maiden, and Me and Jeremy, along with children's acts and an
enivronmental awareness village. 904-464-1683 or www.surfguru
</P>
<P>
   .com/music/Earth-awareness
</P>
<P>
   -fest.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The 30th anniversary New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage
Festival is Friday through Sunday and April 29-May 2 at the Fair
Grounds Race Course. In addition to music on 12 stages, the fair
includes food and contemporary and folk crafts. Among the hundreds
of acts: Willie Nelson, Dave Brubeck, Irma Thomas, Santana, Kirk
Franklin and Nu Nation, Fats Domino, Ray Charles, Dr. John,
Branford Marsalis, Widespread Panic, Pete Fountain, Hugh Masekela,
the Neville Brothers, the Isley Brothers, Hootie and the Blowfish.
1-800-380-3378; tickets: 1-800-854-4714.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louisville, Ky. _ The monthlong Kentucky Derby Festival
culminates May 8 with the fabled Run for the Roses. Preceding the
world's most famous horse race are par-
</P>
<P>
   ades, sports competitions, concerts, food tastings, fireworks
and more. 502-584-6383 or www.kdf.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 90th Annual Ashley Hall Tour of Homes
Saturday features homes and gardens on Legare and Broad streets and
South Battery. 803-720-2853.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
