<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOVESONGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite top actors, trilogy is a lightweight
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showtime's promising-looking ``Love Songs'' doesn't stay
promising for long: It arranges its cliches early and often and
never looks back.
</P>
<P>
   It should've been a contender, as one of these characters would
just love to say. A trilogy of interlocking tales scripted by
Pulitzer Prize-winning writer Charles Fuller (``A Soldier's
Story'') and starring a rotating cast that includes Andre Braugher,
Louis Gossett Jr., Lynn Whitfield and Robert Townsend (Braugher,
Gossett and Townsend also take directing turns), ``Love Songs''
looks like the kind of quality black-themed drama TV almost never
makes.
</P>
<P>
   The three stories unfold on and off ``the Avenue,'' a commercial
strip that runs through a working class African-American
neighborhood. It's a leafy, urban Anywhere, a kind of
postcard-imperfect place where everyone walks, talks and squawks.
</P>
<P>
   That point is driven home _ then underscored, then underlined,
then italicized _ in the opening tale. Otis (Townsend), a club
boxer hoping for a break into the big time, jogs down the street
during his morning run. Everyone calls out to him, ``Hey, champ!''
A grocer tosses him an apple. A kid playfully spars with him, after
which Otis admonishes, ``Get to school, youngblood.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this story of a boxer looking for a break in a dirty
business so he can raise a family and live happily ever after is
more like an after-school special for adults. Wisdom is mouthed as
if read straight from workplace Post-It notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel like you're sailing alone, you're usually in the
same boat as everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got each other and the baby and that's all that
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not all that matters when you have two hours of TV to
fill. The two other stories don't offer much more than the first:
One follows an obnoxious truck-stand grocer (Braugher) trying to
woo a beautiful regular (Whitfield), whose brutal assault helps
bring the two together; the other centers on the domestic violence
that challenges the woman's brother-in-law (Gossett).
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are all here for some worthy melodrama, and Whitfield
brings glory to every scene she's in. But anything that begins to
resonate, like the women's assaults, is so quickly turned trivial
that the melodrama devolves into soap opera. ``Love Songs''
promised more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Songs''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
