<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA REVISITED AT STANFORD MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A season doesn't go by without an exhibition
dealing with some aspect of California art in regional museums. The
Oakland Museum, which bills itself as ``The Museum of California,''
usually takes the prize for such shows.
</P>
<P>
   It has both a focused agenda and an unsurpassed collection of
California art on its side. Last year's ``Art of the Gold Rush,''
organized on the 150th anniversary of the event that launched the
Golden State, was the exemplary Oakland Museum event.
</P>
<P>
   But Oakland is not alone in mounting California shows. The new
Cantor Center for Visual Arts at Stanford University (the former
Stanford University Art Museum) has followed its inaugural
exhibitions with an impressive entry in Californiana. ``Pacific
Arcadia: Images of California, 1600-1915,'' which continues through
June 27, is not only the most ambitious exhibition ever to
originate at Stanford, it is also one of the most critical
exhibitions to address the California experience through art ever
to appear in regional museums.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Stanford's new American art curator, Claire Perry,
the show and catalog (Oxford University Press, $25 paper) are
generally fine but univocal examples of the new analytic art
history. Applied to a subject _ historical California art _ that
has largely escaped such scrutiny, probably because it has been
seen as too marginal to merit such investigation, the exhibition
and catalog demonstrate that no subject is too minor to be run
through the deconstructionist's mill.
</P>
<P>
   The full force of Perry's thesis is more evident in the catalog
than in the exhibition, but even from the show's succinct text
panels you can easily tell that images usually used for
celebratory, boosterish or nostalgic purposes are being looked at
freshly for the political, economic, cultural and racial biases
they carry, whether consciously or not.
</P>
<P>
   In Perry's view, no image is innocent or free of the values of
the dominant class that makes, commissions, buys or uses it.
</P>
<P>
   Every image, even the most innocuous, serves as propaganda for
the elite in power at the time of its making. Perry and her
colleagues in the new art history believe that it is the task of
the art historian to unlock the unexamined bias behind images to
expose their hidden ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Such a process is largely healthy _ Americans particularly have
enjoyed a false sense of their own historical innocence _ but its
application to individual images sometimes borders on the
ludicrous. In Perry's relentless reading of the first 315 years of
California history, there is hardly a painting, print or photograph
created that doesn't bear propaganda's stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Artists frequently have ideas of their own that contradict
prevailing master narratives. What is interesting, especially in
art from the 19th century to the present, is how artists undercut
the official line with their own subversive takes on events and
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Perry suggests that artists are either dupes or willing
collaborators with the power elite. Granted, none of the artists in
the Stanford show were rebels. Most of them knew who paid their
bills and they gave their patrons what they wanted. But perhaps
some of them were legitimately thrilled with the spectacular
California landscape and endeavored to capture a sense of it for
audiences while at the same time they served the Southern Pacific
Railroad, which benefited from both permanent settlers and
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Perry's scrutiny is largely welcome. From the start, in
her view, California was a promoter's scam, a series of sites _
gold field, bonanza ranch, tourist destination, urban center _
exploited for the profit of mine owners, growers, railroad tycoons
and developers who dominated the Golden State's politics and
economy, then as now.
</P>
<P>
   Her work is most valuable when it addresses how imagery changes
over time _ for instance, that of California's original Spanish
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Perry contrasts early images of Monterey made by Spanish, French
and English observers. The 1791 watercolor by the Spaniard Jose
Cardero shows a well-organized and smoothly functioning frontier
settlement dominated by the strong walls of the Monterey Presidio.
Another 1791 drawing, commemorating the 1786 visit of the Comte de
La Perouse to Monterey, tells another story entirely. The rude
village is populated exclusively by monks and cowed Indians, shown
as only partly civilized, i.e., Europeanized.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Monterey is depicted as a frontier outpost
almost asking to be taken over. Two English watercolors show it
even more ripe for the plucking, a tiny village unlikely to resist
superior force.
</P>
<P>
   The bias that the Spanish were decadent, lazy and fanatical and
that the mixed-breed Mexicans who descended from them were
incapable of achieving a state of civilization only accelerated
after the discovery of gold brought thousands of Anglo-Saxons over
the Rockies to seek their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Between then and now there was a period when California's
Spanish heritage was valorized. Starting in the 1870s and
continuing through the 1930s, California tourism was inextricably
caught up with the myth of Old California. Missions, ranchos,
tempestuous vaqueros and sultry (but chaste) senoritas became the
key to the tourist dollar, and interest in Spanish California, by
then safely dead, sparked the production of images of the colorful
past.
</P>
<P>
   The section of the show devoted to the rediscovered Spanish
heritage is one of the most interesting. Paintings such as Charles
Christian Nahl's ``The Fandango'' (1873), which luridly depicts a
fiesta on the old hacienda, is a veritable encyclopedia of
stereotypes. Such pictures parallel the orientalizing tendencies of
European art of the period, with Spanish and Californios
substituted for Arabs. Paintings and photographs of missions in
ruin, including a handsome selection by Carleton Watkins, function
as romantic readymades for late 19th-century Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens with maps dating back to the 17th century that
represent California as an island, suggesting that from the start
California was a mythic land apart. It moves swiftly through five
sections featuring images of the Gold Rush, California as the
``Cornucopia of the World,'' a reappreciation of the wilderness as
spiritual antidote to the modern city, the rediscovery of the
Spanish heritage, and San Francisco, Pacific metropolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
