<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JADED-WAR-REPORTING-N     04-23 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JADED-WAR-REPORTING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTING LIVE, FROM A WAR ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 FOR RELEASE: APRIL 25 or thereafter  
 By PETER GODWIN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It has become a televisual cliche. The 45-second parade of
refugees' vignettes, followed by the reporters' brow-creased
displays of concern. Then the question from the anchor, in response
to which reporters soften their voices to tell us how the personal
dimension of the tragedy pierced their professional husks.
 &HT;    Except it really isn't so. The backstage truth is that no matter
how tenderhearted reporters may be at the outset, any capacity for
empathy is all but drowned by the sheer flow of suffering during
wartime.
 &HT;    Most war reporters must cultivate a controlled schizophrenia to
survive. We develop a sangfroid, a mordant humor and a studied
machismo, much the same way that cops and ER doctors do.
 &HT;    As we interview dozens of victims, usually through interpreters,
the barbarities start to merge, to become prosaic even, especially
as deadlines loom. Garnish this with the logistics of filing the
story and the fierce competition with other channels, and soon the
individual plights we witness flash by like passing traffic.
 &HT;    I learned this in my years as a foreign correspondent in Africa.
It was my job to try to get you involved in the conflicts there, to
engage you in the way that you have now become so engaged in
Kosovo. Mostly, I failed.
 &HT;    The wars I covered were obscure. They were in places that did
not affect ``vital interests.'' The conflicts were devoid of the
high-tech footage taken by missile-mounted cameras; to outsiders
the people involved looked and sounded confusingly alike. Their
courage _ the kind of courage presented by a life with nothing left
to lose but itself _ was often mistaken for the myth of Third World
fatalism. Worst of all, in the atrocity ratings war, both the
casualties and the perpetrators were black.
 &HT;    And so I found you weren't particularly interested in an old
chief in Matabeleland, standing against a blood-orange sun and
defying a squad of murderous soldiers. ``I must speak the truth and
shame the devil,'' he pronounced.
 &HT;    Nor were you interested in Bongali Dube, a thin young man who
led me up a small hill to a pile of bones. ``This is my father,''
he said, as if introducing me to a living man. He had been warned
by soldiers not to bury the body, and it had been eaten by dogs.
 &HT;    Nor were you even interested in the Ugandan town of Mbale,
nestled beneath the towering green cone of Mount Elgon, where the
old Edwardian clock tower had been used as a backdrop for a firing
squad; corpses were still sprawled against it. When the clock
struck noon they shivered with each chime.
 &HT;    The hospital there was empty, except for those too ill to flee.
A rivulet of blood still flowing from under a door led us to a
white-coated mound of executed doctors. But the restless
searchlight of international attention had flicked elsewhere.
 &HT;    How can anyone decide what, in this parade of Hogarthian horrors
all clamoring for attention, to zoom in on? Whose suffering do we
broadcast as representative? The family whose father was dispatched
in a particularly gory way? The one that speaks English? Of course,
the most telegenic win the audition.
 &HT;    The ``victims'' instinctively understand this. They are not
interested in hand-holding or in our bogus words of small comfort;
they have no use for our threadbare empathy. They know that come
nightfall we will be back in the Hotel Splendide, while they still
sleep in the open. They understand that we are simply there to
amplify their suffering to a far wider audience. I remember a man
in Matabeleland.
 &HT;    ``We hope you put our problems on the World Service,'' he said
in halting English. ``Otherwise our future will run out. Surely,
surely.'' He gave a solemn bow and shook my hand.
 &HT;    But this faith is often misplaced. What light we can shed on
refugees' plight usually falls too late. The slow and deliberate
shuffle toward the ethnic endgame in Kosovo, so obvious to all of
us who had been there, elbowed its way to the top of the evening
lineup only when it was already too late to prevent.
 &HT;    And the attention span of war correspondents is only as long as
that of our viewers. When your finger hits the remote, we must
leave and seek out a more entertaining tragedy.
 &HT;    The terrible reality is that the more visible the suffering, the
more we get on the air. We grow with the story. So we end up as
practitioners of the ``something must be done'' school of
journalism, automatic advocates of intervention _ as much out of
professional self-interest as genuine humanitarian concern.
 &HT;    Most of us are attracted to this job by the glamour of it. But
in the end, protracted exposure to violence and tragedy can be
highly corrosive. Even those who no longer deeply feel other
people's suffering become prisoners of their own harrowing
anecdotes. Like Scheherazade in ``The Arabian Nights,'' we live for
only as long as our stories engage you.
 &HT;    So is Kosovo a ``good'' war for the media? The viewing
experience can feel like a session with a Sony Play Station
followed by a Bombing Tactics 101 seminar. And there are only so
many times you can watch an F-16 take off from Aviano before you
reach for the remote.
 &HT;    But in their favor, the Albanians make empathy-positive
refugees, and there is the added frisson of Russian saber rattling
just out of theater.
 &HT;    Although it's hard to imagine that their situation could be any
worse, in one sense the Kosovars are a lucky people. An accident of
geography has ordained that their fate, unlike that of so many,
many others who suffer in media silence, is relevant to our vital
interests.
 &HT;    And so for the moment at least, their cries are heard across the
world.
 &HT;     c.1999 Peter Godwin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Peter Godwin, the author of ``Mukiwa: A White Boy in Africa,''
has covered Africa for The London Sunday Times and for BBC-TV.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
