 ART ADV.: A photo with BBO-PAPPAS and a graphic with MARKET-BOOMERS
are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO-ISSUES (Medford, Mass.) _ As leaders gather in Washington,
NATO faces two issues _ the radical role it has assumed in the
Balkans and the stability of a group of nations as suspicious of
one another as Greece and Turkey. By John Yemma. 1320 words. (i and
a coding)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-APACHE (Washington) _ Now that the Apache helicopters are
landing in Albania, NATO and Serbian forces might finally soon be
fighting each other. By Fred Kaplan. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-POLAND (Warsaw) _ The Balkans conflict has produced little
discernable regret in Poland about the timing of its entry into
NATO last month. By David Filipov. 970 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GORE (Washington) _ Kosovo situation is hurting Al Gore's
image as he runs for president. He was the point person on foreign
policy, especially with Russia's Primakov. By Ann Scales. 1200
words. (w and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCHOOL SHOOTINGS (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-VICTIMS (Littleton, Colo.) _ Before the bullets and
bombs, before the tears, they were volleyball players and actors,
church group members and fishermen, honor students and average
students. By Mitch Zuckoff and Ellen. O'Brien. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CULTURE (Newton, Mass.) _ All schools can be a maze of
hidden geography -- cliques and subcultures known only to the
students who walk the halls. But the pressures to fit in are
particularly strong at suburban high schools. By Beth Daley. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-WEAPONS (Washington) _ Guns are easy for teenagers to
come by, even in states where it is illegal to own or possess one,
criminologists and gun-control advocates say. By Louise D. Palmer.
625 words.
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Littleton, Colo.) _ School uniforms will not
fix what has gone wrong in America, but already we are seizing on
such facile solutions. By Eileen McNamara. (k)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-KINGS (Boston) _ They shot enemies at point-blank range,
sliced gang tattoos off the arms of members who crossed them, and
recruited children to peddle crack. &UR;  &LR; But the New York City Latin
Kings say that's history. Now, they're a political organization. By
Cindy Rodriguez. 912 words.
</P>
