<HEADER>
A0516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-23 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING ATTITUDES RAISE HOPES OF INVESTORS IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese stock market is a lot like the Red Sox:
Periodically it teases you into thinking it's going to do something
great, only to crush your hopes in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, the Nikkei, the main Japanese
market index, has risen 15 percent; small-cap stocks in Japan are
up 45 percent. The question for investors: Is this another in a
series of false starts or is it the beginning of a bona fide rally?
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with a variety of Japan specialists have turned up
something like a consensus: There are genuine reasons to be
optimistic about Japan but don't order your World Series tickets
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Warren, a money manager at Putnam Investments in Boston,
has been following Japanese companies for 20 years. ``For the first
time in my history Japanese executives are waking up to the fact
that they have to make a profit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is one of a number of investors who are excited by what
seems to be a revolution under way in Japan's private sector.
Companies that once believed the only thing that mattered was
building market share have dropped that notion in favor of a much
more American way of viewing the world.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to Japan, Maureen Allyn, chief economist at
Scudder Kemper Investments, noticed that about half of the
companies she met with had investor relations executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started to see that in Europe in the early '90s,
I pooh-poohed it,'' she says. ``In fact, it actually turned out to
be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   It was significant, says Allyn, because it signaled a new
mindset. It meant that companies were concerned about shareholders
and finding ways to boost shareholder value. Other signs of change
are also visible.
</P>
<P>
   A number of big companies, including Sony and Toshiba, have
announced major US-style restructuring plans, including job cuts.
Merger activity tripled in Japan last year and this year promises
to be bigger. Investors love all of this reshuffling because the
end result should be stronger, more profitable companies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States went down this path in the 1980s and the stock
market boomed; Europe is doing it in the '90s and the markets have
responded favorably. Is Japan going to be next?
</P>
<P>
   Not right away, say money managers. First the Japanese need to
fix their economy. That won't be easy. The Japanese economy has
been in trouble since 1991. Growth since then has averaged 1
percent a year; the United States has done roughly three times
better over the same stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Japanese economy shrank nearly 3 percent and just
this week the International Monetary Fund predicted a 1.4 percent
contraction for 1999. ``There is little reason to think any
recovery is under way in Japan, much less a sustainable one,'' says
Francisco Larios, an economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in
Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Japan's problems is a familiar one: the banking
system is a mess; national and local governments are deeply in
debt; and deregulation is only in its infancy. The government has
cut taxes, cut interest rates, and boosted spending, but so far the
results are tough to spot. Larios said he thinks the Japanese
economy could shrink again next year, a third straight year of
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the positive steps taken by the corporate sector
could make things worse in the short run, say economists.
Cost-conscious companies may slash capital spending and fire more
workers, pushing the jobless rate above the current record of 4.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, however, most money managers are more optimistic.
They expect the new way of thinking on the corporate side to lead
to a similar mental restructuring on the government side. When that
happens, the investment opportunities could be big, says Warren of
Putnam. ``There's a huge potential in Japan,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Just when this potential might be realized is difficult to say.
The best advice for investors might be the same advice given each
year to Red Sox fans: Be patient. Eventually you will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston Partners Asset Management has lost a key mutual fund
management contract that helped put the firm on the map four years
ago and accounts for 23 percent of assets under management today.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Partners, formed by Desmond Heathwood and other former
Boston Co. managers who bolted from the firm in 1995, will be
replaced as advisers of the $3.6 billion Smith Barney Premium Total
Return Fund on Monday. Boston Partners manages a total of $15.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fund trustees voted April 15 to replace Boston Partners with the
in-house Salomon Brothers Asset Management on an interim basis and
to ask shareholders to approve the firm as a permanent new
subadviser at a meeting June 30. Salomon Smith Barney is part of
Citigroup Inc.
</P>
<P>
   An internal memo at SSB Citi Asset Management cited the ``recent
challenges presented to our (financial consultants) and their
clients by the underperformance'' of the fund as a reason for the
change.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which invests in large, value-oriented stocks, earned
just 6.2 percent in 1998 and has roughly broken even so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Partners spokeswoman said the firm ``very much valued
and appreciated our relationship with Salomon Smith Barney'' and
understood ``the business reasons for bringing their fund
in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
