<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-BOOMERS-ART-BO     04-23 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BOOMERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS POWERING MARKET RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They revolutionized music in the 1960s, protested to end the
Vietnam War in the 1970s, and made two-income families fashionable
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with retirement pressing in on them, the nation's 76
million baby boomers are changing the stock market as well,
powering it to previously unthinkable heights as they pour money
into investments for their approaching golden years.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average has doubled since November
1995, flying beyond the 10,000 milestone last month and shattering
records almost daily since. The Dow rose Thursday for a third
straight day, gaining 145.76 points and achieving yet another
all-time high, 10,727.18. The Nasdaq Composite Index, a leading
indicator of the high-technology industry, stumbled Monday but
rebounded smartly, posting its strongest three-day rally in a
decade to finish up Thursday at 2561.61.
</P>
<P>
   Experts hard-pressed to explain the market's remarkable feats
point to conventional economic theory, which holds that stocks are
propelled by a unique combination of low interest rates and
inflation, rising productivity, and a US economy enjoying an
unprecedented peacetime expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But these explanations go only so far. A growing number of
market watchers link the irrepressible stock market to the
country's most significant demographic phenomenon: A baby boom
generation of Americans born after World War II who are now between
the ages of 35 and 53.
</P>
<P>
   Just as a wave of immigrants in the 19th century changed
American cities, the generation that once protested the
establishment is having a huge impact on Wall Street as they enter
their peak investing years. Boomers are behind the torrent of money
that has flooded into stock mutual funds and fueled an explosion in
pension-fund assets, which have more than doubled since 1992, to
$5.9 trillion, due not only to higher stock values but to a wave of
contributions to 401(k) plans by boomers and their employers.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not over yet: They will account for $9 trillion of the
$10 trillion growth of all invested assets over the next five
years, according to the discount brokerage firm, Charles Schwab
Corp. Boomers currently hold about one-third of all invested
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a self-fulfilling momentum cycle,'' said Zhiwu Chen, a
finance professor at Ohio State University, whose research shows
that baby boomers are a ``major factor'' fueling the bull market
which began in the early 1980s, as the first members of the
baby-boom generation, born in 1946, were facing 40.
</P>
<P>
   A stock market moved as often by psychology as by economic
events appears at times to be soaring simply because the `Me
Generation' wants _ even needs _ it to. ``The stock market has
bailed a lot of boomers out of a lifetime of not saving money,''
said Walker Smith, managing partner of Yankelovich Partners Inc., a
market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Steven and Stacie Elliott, both age 44, are typical. They are
socking away $1,200 a month _ twice that in a good month _ into
their already considerable portfolio invested mainly in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Having met later in life, they began to worry about retiring
soon after marrying two years ago. Stacie Elliott works part-time
as a tutor. Her husband, an engineer at Xiox Corp., a high-tech
company in Manchester, N.H., earns close to $100,000 a year. Since
they have no children, she can spend part of her day in their home
watching stock reports on the CNBC channel so that she can get more
involved in investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 20, you think (money) is always going to be coming
in,'' she said. ``But when you're older, you start to realize you
don't have as much time, so you get more serious about saving.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Elliotts, boomers typically own homes and have paid off
a portion of their mortgages at the same time earning power is
peaking and _ for older baby boomers _ their children are
graduating from college.
</P>
<P>
   More than three-fourths of all boomers surveyed in 1996 by the
Investment Company Institute, a Washington trade group, own mutual
funds invested in stocks. The typical boomer earns a household
income of $60,000 and has $45,000 in investments.
</P>
<P>
   While their parents actually have bigger investment portfolios,
boomers are at a phase of life which requires that they withdraw
funds, or put them into more conservative investments like bonds.
Their children's wealth, in contrast, is expected to grow
tremendously in future years, investment experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of accumulating their assets, they've only really
just begun,'' said Sandra West, director of the Investment Company
Institute's market and policy research.
</P>
<P>
   A boomer-driven stock market is dismissed by mainstream
economists, who contend that low interest rates are the fuel for
the market. Historically, when interest rates are low, bonds pay
poorly and drive investors into stocks, which promise _ but do not
guarantee _ better returns. ``Stocks sell against bonds all the
time,'' and currently ``bonds aren't rewarding people,'' said
William Shiebler, vice chairman of the Boston mutual-fund company,
Putnam Investments. The boomer theory ``doesn't hold water.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear that boomers play a huge role in the surge of
stock investing. In the past three years, stock funds attracted an
average $200 billion each year _ up from average yearly inflows of
$44 billion in the early 1990s. Contributions to 401(k) and similar
retirement plans rose continually during the first half of the
decade, from $76 billion in 1990 to $117 billion in 1995, federal
data show. At the same time, there was a substantial rise in the
percentage of boomers' portfolios in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographics is a factor behind the favorable markets,''
said Ken Leibler, president Liberty Financial Cos., which manages
around $62 billion in investments.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, large stock market gains, year after year, have
padded portfolios for all investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's research, buttressed by econometric models, attempts
to explain the unusually high level of the overall market _ as well
as a spiraling prices of blue-chip stocks. ``Companies have been
increasing earnings by a few percentage points'' a year, Chen said,
``but the demand has been getting stronger and stronger,'' causing
stocks to be ``priced more than they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhiwu (pronounced Ji-wu) Chen is not a member of America's baby
boom generation. But he could fit the demographic profile. Born in
the countryside in Hunan province of China, he came to Yale
University in 1986 for graduate school, eventually settling in
Ohio. Now age 37, Chen has two young daughters and a wife who he
said insists they save for their girls' education and for their own
retirement. Chen is also at the height of his career: He has
accepted a post at Yale and promotion to full professor of finance,
starting in July. He is also an investment consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's baby boom study, originally published in the Journal of
Business in 1993 and recently updated, used the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index to track the stock market through the end of 1998. He
found the index moved in tandem with an increase in the average age
of the US population over 20 years old. Aging boomers accounted for
more than one-third of the market's recent rise _ a strong
correlation in academic research. He reached a similar conclusion
about housing prices, which rose when boomers entered home-buying
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they get older,'' Chen explained, ``the demand for housing
will decrease and the demand for financial assets will increase.
After retirement, the demand for housing will decline dramatically
and at the same time they'll also move assets from the stock market
to relatively safer assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lo, a professor of finance at the Sloan School of
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, agreed
that boomers ``have an effect'' on the market's level.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he said, the market's high returns recently have
made investors ``more willing to go into the stock market.''
Investors today, Lo said, are not as ``risk-averse'' as earlier
investors who have seen market drops.
</P>
<P>
   But the boomers' market magic may not last forever. Just as they
are expected to create a fiscal crisis in the Social Security fund
when they retire in droves, the bubble may burst as they begin to
withdraw their assets as they leave the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Chen doesn't predict market levels. But, he said, after 2005 or
2010, there will be ``less and less new money coming in and more
money going out of the stock market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
