<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST NOT TO PUT EDUCATION FUND ALL IN ONE BASKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 25, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 49-year-old woman with an 11-year-old son who will be
going to college in seven years. I have a total of $146,000 in a
401(k) plan invested in nine different Fidelity stock funds, and a
Roth IRA of $35,000 divided evenly among Fidelity Puritan, Fidelity
Magellan, Fidelity Value and Fidelity Growth and Income funds. I
contribute $9,500 a year to the 401(k) and $2,000 a year to the
IRA. I have $25,000 in non-retirement savings, all of it invested
in Magellan, and $76,000 in a UTMA account for my son's education,
with this money divided evenly between Fidelity Blue Chip Growth
and Fidelity Growth and Income. Are my investments appropriately
allocated to allow me to send my son to a four-year private college
and to retire in 16 years with an annual income stream of $40,000?
Should I adjust my allocations in my 401(k)? I have too many funds
to keep track of. My company offers only Fidelity funds.
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the education account. You're in good shape
there. According to the Princeton Review publication Paying For
College Without Going Broke, the projection of costs for a
four-year private college education beginning in 2006 will be
$128,475 (starting at $29,808 in the first year and escalating to
$34,506 in the final year). If your son's UTMA account grows at an
average annual rate of 8 percent, it would amount to $130,250 in
seven years, which is to say that you have slightly overfunded it.
</P>
<P>
   There are worse problems to have. An example of a worse problem
would be a severe stock market downturn that would threaten the
projected growth. For that reason, I suggest you make some major
changes in that portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I would retain about one third in Fidelity Growth and Income,
divide another third among Fidelity Puritan and Fidelity Asset
Manager, and put the final third in Fidelity GNMA. Moreover, every
two years or so, I would move a little more out of the stock fund
and a little more into the balanced and fixed-income funds. Even if
this strategy threatens the projected 8 percent growth rate, your
son should be in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course you have probably heard by now that the money would
have been better saved in your own name, a strategy that would have
increased your son's ability to win financial aid, but at this
point what has been done is done and you can't reverse the moves,
so the point is moot in your case.)
</P>
<P>
   As for your own retirement savings, on the surface it seems
you'll be in good shape. If you presume 8 percent average annual
portfolio growth and ongoing contributions over 16 years, the pool
would grow to $981,569; using a more optimistic 10 percent growth
presumption, the figure would be $1,263,999. Both accumulations
would clearly support a $40,000 income stream.
</P>
<P>
   But the trouble is that if inflation runs at a 3.5 percent
average over the next 16 years, youll need $69,359 to provide the
same buying power that $40,000 does today. At the lower projected
growth rate, you could come fairly close, presuming a 6.5 percent
income stream from a fixed-income portfolio, which would bring you
$63,801 a year. But that would leave you nothing in growth
instruments that might protect you against the ravages of likely
future inflation. At the higher growth projection, you could figure
that $1.06 million could be put in a fixed-income account to
provide the needed income stream, leaving $203,999 to provide you
with future growth.
</P>
<P>
   True, the growth account seems a little thin, but you also
should figure that as those 16 years of accumulation elapse, you
will probably win raises, and as your income increases, you can
increase your savings rate simply by maintaining your savings at
the same percentage of income it now represents. Also note that
none of these calculations include the $25,000 that you have saved
in the taxable account; simply left alone, that would grow to
something in the range of $85,648 to $114,874, representing the 8
and 10 percent growth assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   One reason I include the fairly modest 8 percent growth
assumptions is that I'm not particularly optimistic about the
short-term prospects for the stock market, but an equally important
reason is that I'd like to see you both diversify your retirement
portfolio and reduce its risk level. The 401(k) holdings are
dominated by positions of $46,000 in Fidelity's Magellan, $29,000
in Growth and Income, $31,000 in Equity-Income, and $18,000 in
Spartan US Equity Index funds. Combining those holdings with token
positions in Contrafund and Growth, you come up with more than 89
percent of the 401(k) invested in large cap domestic stocks. The
final three holdings _ $12,000 in Asset Manager and $2,000 each in
OTC and Overseas funds, aren't enough to represent meaningful
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to simplify the portfolio, I'd leave 60 percent in
the large-cap funds, dividing it evenly between Growth and Income
and Spartan US Equity Index, and I'd divide the remainder evenly
among OTC, Asset Manager, Overseas, and (if allowed within your
401(k)), Fidelity Select Health Care. I would suggest similar
allocations within the IRA account. If you aren't able to buy
Health Care within the 401(k), you could build the desired position
within the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd use my ongoing contributions to steadily decrease
the risk level, putting about half of the contributions into Asset
Manager or Fidelity Puritan funds, and dividing the remainder among
the other funds so as to maintain the proportions set forth.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My daughter is 41 years old and recently divorced, with two
teenaged children. She is starting a new job at a large company
where she intends to stay until she retires. She plans to invest at
least 6 percent of her earnings in a retirement account, and I have
helped her select these four Fidelity funds and allocations:
Fidelity Puritan, 15 percent; Fidelity US Equity, 35 percent; Janus
Twenty, 25 percent; and Janus Worldwide, 25 percent. Your
suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Bedford, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. I think your selections are solid, but titled a little too
heavily to large-cap domestic stocks. I presume Fidelity US Equity,
which is not one of Fidelity's retail funds, is a large-cap fund
available through the retirement plan, possibly tracking the
Standard and Poor's 500 Index. If so, her only holdings that are
not in domestic large caps are the roughly 40 percent of Puritan
that's on the fixed-income side and the two thirds of Janus
Worldwide that's invested outside the United States. I suggest you
confine large-cap domestic holdings to a maximum of 60 percent, and
establish small-cap, mid-cap, and health care positions to
represent the remainder of the portfolio. But the selections you
have made will likely serve her well over the course of 20-odd
years.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 48, single, and plan to leave a company where I have
worked for 11 1/2 years. In my 401(k) I have $91,143 in my
company's stock, $38,654 in Fidelity Puritan, $72,265 in Fidelity
Magellan, $38,609 in Fidelity Growth Company, $5,400 in
Intermediate Growth, and $29,610 in Government Retirement accounts.
I plan to leave the account with the company, but I am thinking of
investing more aggressively by pulling all the money from
everything but Magellan and putting it in the company stock. What
do you think?
</P>
<P>
   P.L., Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a little tough to explain, since you don't want me to
identify the company, but I think it would be a mistake. You're
dealing here with a company with an ultra-high price-to-earnings
ratio and no dividend. It's a good company, but you already have
more than 33 percent of your money in it. That's enough. I can't
tell from your letter what the two last-mentioned funds are _ the
Intermediate Growth and Government Retirement accounts _ but if
Government Retirement is a fixed-income account, I would move that
money to Puritan and figure that you have assumed enough risk. Good
as your company's stock has been, it's simply too risky to put most
of your retirement money in a single, high-priced stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
