<HEADLINE>
`EXISTENZ' PLAYS GAMES WITH HORROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: eXistenZ is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
eXistenZ 
Written and directed by: David Cronenberg 
Starring: Jennifer Jason Leigh, Jude Law, Ian Holm, Don McKellar,
Callum Keith Rennie, Sarah Polley, Robert A. Silverman, Christopher
Eccleston, Willem Dafoe 
Running time: 97 minutes 
Rated: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought ``The Matrix'' had a complicated story line,
check out David Cronenberg's ``eXistenZ.'' It hasn't the techno
flash of ``The Matrix,'' but, unlike that film, which is pretty
moronic beneath its dazzling F/X, ``eXistenZ'' at least achieves a
little philosophical heft as it teases us with a world that fuses
the technological and the biological. By grisly coincidence, its
consequence-free trigger-pulling also resonates ominously with the
blood-spilling in Littleton, Colo., this week, even though its
starting point is an imminent future-world where high-tech games
can be downloaded into the human nervous system via a spinal jack
known as bioport.
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg's films are obsessed with the vulnerability and
impermanence of the human body. No filmmaker of stature has more
frequently reminded us of the corruptibility of the flesh,
``eXistenZ'' included. But it's more playful than genuinely
horrifying. Plenty of blood and biomass is splattered across the
screen as a focus group is drawn into an advanced game system that
looks like a great lumpy breast and is plugged into its players'
bioports via a 12-foot connector resembling a giant umbilical cord.
The game pods are alive, sort of. Grown in breeding pools from
fertilized amphibian eggs filled with synthetic DNA, they're the
most arresting props in any Cronenberg movie since the terrifying
stainless-steel gynecological instruments in ``Dead Ringers.''
</P>
<P>
   Events (or is it just the game? or both?) are set in motion when
a gunman rises up out of a focus group and shoots the diva of all
game designers, Allegra Geller (Jennifer Jason Leigh). In the
tumult, she's hustled out of the church (nice touch!) where the
marketing exercise is unfolding. Her rescuer is a company nerd
(Jude Law) working for the big-bucks corporation that has funded
the game's expensive r&AMP;d. He's also a techno virgin. In a droll
reversal of the usual chase movie sexual aggressiveness, she puts
the moves on him and achieves penetration when she makes him agree
to being fitted with a bioport so he can keep up with her
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh's confident bounce, born of believing that she's operating
with complete impunity and not killing real people as she blasts
her way through the landscape, is the frightening thing about
``eXistenZ,'' even without its obvious parallels to the roots of
the Littlewood and other recent slaughters. When the fleeing pair's
hectic itinerary is the real thing and when it's only the game is
left to the audience to figure out. It is not a heavy workout, even
at its goriest, as Cronenberg seems to be revisiting his early
``Videodrome'' and filtering it through that Michael Douglas
roller-coaster ride of a couple of seasons ago, ``The Game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's diverting enough, but not jolting enough, unless, of
course, you press the parallels between escapism into virtual
reality and the social disconnectedness that has been a factor in
America's school and other massacres of the last few years.
Otherwise, this film about game-playing plays too much like a game
and not about anything that seems to matter on any other level. In
trading genuine horror for lightweight existentialism, it forfeits
the visceral impact of Cronenberg's best films _ ``Scanners,''
``The Fly,'' ``Dead Ringers.'' ``eXistenZ,'' in other words, needs
a few more cHeaP thRillZ, although its metal-detector-proof guns
made of bone and gristle and shooting human teeth are a step in the
right scary direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
