<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHSCHOOL-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBAN SCHOOL STRESS HEIGHTENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Newton North High School's second floor is known
as Main Street, the primary drag in a teenage city of 2,100. The
artsy students lean against red lockers between classes, the
``freaks'' huddle in front of the green. Seniors have their space
in front of the purple and hearing impaired students camp out in
front of the yellow lockers.
</P>
<P>
   For many suburban students, this is the whole, small world. In
city schools, say sociologists, students are more prone to scatter
when the last bell rings, to their neighborhood and other sets of
friends. But in suburban schools, like Newton, or the Columbine
High School where two students went on a rampage this week, the
social pressures are even more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Students in communities like Newton say that almost everyone
they grew up with goes to the same high school. Weekend parties are
planned in the cafeteria, romances sparked in math class. And
whether you like to play chess, french horn or pranks, the school
serves as the brick-faced backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to both suburban and city high schools and it's
harder in those small towns where everyone knows each other,'' said
Judi Storey, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rejection at school can mean total rejection, say
students, because there are few other places students can find a
sense of self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some kids, if they don't get accepted at school, there is
nothing else,'' said Maria Morreale, 17, a junior at Newton North.
``Some kids have other things going on after school, but for many,
school is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In any school, of course, the forces of peer pressure can be
brutal. With a hierarchy defined by social cliques, students say it
takes little to suffer social banishment. It takes a look, a
whispered comment or a vacant seat beside a student in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid stuff,'' Storey said. ``But a lot of kids take it
really, really seriously. I know some that still talk about it even
after they graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, though, it is a simple matter of geography. In
Boston, for example, there are more than 15 high schools and
students crisscross neighborhoods to attend them. So when school
ends, students go home to neighborhoods to be with friends, and
school may not even come up in conversation. Many urban school
students work and find another group of friends there, they say.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban communities, however, many students and parents said
there are few other opportunities to discover new friends. Students
may not seek out afterschool jobs either because their parents can
financially provide for them or they are pushed to take advantage
of the many afterschool programs suburban schools offer. The school
becomes the center of students' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to a city school, you can belong to a different
community at home. But for many of these kids in suburban schools,
they are here and this is it,'' said Virginia Hunter, who has eight
children, including one at Randolph High School.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure in suburban schools can also come from more
surprising places. Students at suburban schools interviewed
Thursday said they feel extra pressure to be accepted in their
school, academically and socially, because they know their parents
moved to their community for its stellar schools. To fail, they
said privately, is not simply failing school. It is failing their
parents, their community and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is the predominant factor in these students' lives and
the parents emphasize that if not overemphasize it,'' said Gary
Siperstein, head of the Center for Social Development and Education
at University of Massachusetts in Boston. ``The message is to
participate in afterschool activities, join clubs. You are expected
to fit into the school as well as get good grades.''
</P>
<P>
   Siperstein and a colleague just completed a study analyzing the
different social stresses facing 581 Massachusetts suburban and
urban middle school students. In suburban schools, students worried
being left out of a group they wanted to be a part of. But in city
schools, that worry was rarely mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   After they leave, students who attended close-knit suburban
schools say they sometimes look back in bewilderment. Fitting in,
they said, seemed so important at the time. Little things, like
being invited to eat lunch with popular kids, or being chosen for a
gym-class volleyball game, were major events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be pure hell,'' said Storey, who said she had trouble
fitting in during her high school years. ``Once you get out, it's
like, `I'm so glad that was over.' You realize the world doesn't
run'' like a high school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
