<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-MUSIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC LEGENDS PUT TO SHAME AMERICA'S CLASSICAL RADIO SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's more than a bit humbling to sit down with the first batch
of ``Great Performers of the Twentieth Century,`` the exceptional
new historical series of compact discs published on the new BBC
Legends label and distributed stateside by Koch International.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, where listeners are hungry for any kind of
serious music on the radio, what can one make of a national network
like the British Broadcasting Corp. that not only has consistently
aired concerts by the finest musicians of the age, but also
produced most of those concerts for the sole purpose of
broadcasting them?
</P>
<P>
   Commercial radio networks in the United States gave up on
classical music a generation ago. Americans can still hear several
of our leading opera companies, while most of the important
American orchestras have lost their syndication contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Listen here and weep. The initial 10 offerings in the BBC
Legends release are a godsend for the serious music lover. They
were recorded from 1951-79 (mostly in public performance without
retakes), and all but two are in stereo. A few of the performances
have appeared on unauthorized labels, but the master tapes, which
have been digitally restored, have delivered better sonic results,
and where possible, BBC Legends has included interviews with the
featured musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Interest focuses first on performances by artists who never made
commercial recordings of the works they attempted here. At least
three fall into the ``don't miss'' category.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1959, conductor Jascha Horenstein assembled 756
musicians in the Royal Albert Hall, and for an audience that
numbered 6,000, led a reading of Mahler's Symphony No. 8 in E-flat
Major (BBCL-4001, two CDs) that, to one listener who heard the tape
soon after, left an indelible impression. A much undervalued
Mahlerian, Horenstein tells interviewer Alan Blyth that conductor
Wilhelm Furtwangler taught him to rehearse a score in broad spans.
</P>
<P>
   And that philosophy here generated a performance that soars on
the wings of inspiration for 80 minutes. Mahler's most grandiose
work had not been performed in England for 11 years, and the sense
of occasion is often overwhelming. There are no cheap theatrics in
Horenstein's reading, simply a gradual unfolding of the music, and
it leaves you profoundly stirred.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the BBC engineers caught much of the detail without
sonic overloading.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's Berlioz's ``La Damnation de Faust'' (BBCL-4006,
two CDs), conducted by one of the composer's finest 20th century
advocates, Pierre Monteux, in 1962, when this most beloved of
musicians was basking in a glorious Indian summer as chief
conductor of the London Symphony. The soloists for this
Goethe-inspired hybrid included soprano Regine Crespin at her
stylistic and vocal zenith, tenor Andre Turp and baritone Michel
Roux. The energy and elan with which Monteux, then 87, imbues the
score are never less than astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   The recorded legacy of Clifford Curzon, that most patrician and
perfectionist of British pianists, is much too small. So, BBC
Legends' exhumation of Brahms' Piano Quintet in F Minor with the
Amadeus String Quartet (BBCL-4009, two CDs) adds a fiery (1974)
performance to the discography. A bonus disc features these
musicians in a 1971 Schubert ``Trout'' Quintet, a somewhat more
extroverted reading than their earlier commercial collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The curiosity of the collection is Bach: Mass in B Minor
(BBCL-4008, two CDs). This 1951 studio recording offers the Boyd
Neel Orchestra conducted by the famed Romanian violinist-composer,
George Enescu; soprano Suzanne Danco, contralto Kathleen Ferrier
and tenor Peter Pears dominate the soloists. This will sound
dreadfully old-fashioned to the hip period performance crowd, yet
Enescu was a foremost Bachian, and his reading wants nothing in
spirituality, shapeliness and thrust.
</P>
<P>
   To all tastes will be Schubert: Sonatas D. 575, D. 625 and D.664
and ``Moment musical'' in C Major (BBCL-4010), the contents of a
March 1979 Royal Festival Hall recital with Soviet pianist
Sviatoslav Richter. On that day, this extraordinary artist chose
two of the composer's less frequently heard sonatas, including the
B Major (D. 575), with its incomplete first movement, and wound up
with an inimitable traversal of the wondrous ``little'' A Major (D.
664). The audience holds its breath for such magical playing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the album that captures a historical moment most
dramatically is Shostakovich: Symphony No. 8; Mozart: Symphony No.
33 (BBCL-4002, two CDs). This 1960 concert introduced one of
Shostakovich's most powerful symphonic utterances to the United
Kingdom 17 years after its premiere in the Soviet Union; the
conductor on both occasions was the formidable Yevgeny Mravinsky,
here with the Leningrad Philharmonic, the orchestra he steered to
greatness, in one of its then-rare visits to the West. A bonus disc
includes the Mozart, nice but a bit soupy.
</P>
<P>
   The next series of BBC Legends releases, due by the end of this
month, will feature composer Benjamin Britten in his guises as
conductor and pianist, performing with colleagues like alto Janet
Baker, baritone Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau and cellist Mstislav
Rostropovich _ not a shabby crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
