<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PAPPAS-ART-BOS &LR;      04-23 1779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PAPPAS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER/PHYSICIAN ARTHUR PAPPAS IS UNDER A MICROSCOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Most Red Sox fans think they know the story of Dr.
Arthur Pappas. He's the limited partner who doubles as the team
doctor, a relationship that seems inherently conflicted. He's the
guy who had to pay Marty Barrett $1.7 million in a malpractice
suit, who Butch Henry says pushed him to pitch when he was hurt,
and who several current players say has complicated their comebacks
as this season gets started.
</P>
<P>
   But Pappas's defenders tell a decidedly different story _ of a
concerned citizen who devotes as much time to caring for crippled
children as for prima donna sports stars; of a physician who's
respected enough that Sox players send their wives and kids to him,
while players from other teams say he salvaged their careers. They
see him, in short, as a saint in a white coat.
</P>
<P>
   The true story is a bit of both.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas's role does present potential conflicts, but no more than
those of any doctor who collects a paycheck from a team and might
be tempted to put its financial interests ahead of a player's
health. His medical judgment has been questioned by a lineup of
players, but there's a longer line who swear by his diagnoses and
treatments. And while some in the medical world say it's time,
after 22 years, for the 66-year-old Pappas to step aside, others
insist his experience and acumen are needed more than ever if this
injury-plagued Sox team so short on stars hopes to stay healthy
enough to remain a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Butch Henry's recent claims about Dr. Pappas on sports
radio,'' says Bob Tewksbury, a New Hampshire native who pitched for
six big league clubs during his 11-year career. ``I never called a
sports talk show in my life, but I called WEEI about how we never
hear the other side of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe in Dr. Pappas so strongly I had to let people
know there's another side . . . I wouldn't have pitched my last 10
years in the big leagues without the care Dr. Pappas provided me on
a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Altchek also is fed up with the finger-pointing, some
of it from his sports medicine colleagues. ``Arthur Pappas is
highly regarded as a pioneer in the field of orthopedic sports
medicine,'' says Altchek, the New York Mets physician who performed
pioneering shoulder surgery on Boston pitcher Bret Saberhagen.
``Dr. Pappas was there trying to figure out players' problems
before we had MRIs and lots of other sophisticated diagnostic
tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're an owner, in a way it ensures no conflict,'' adds
Altchek. ``These are your players and you want the best for them.
If anything it makes that more important to you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To understand the intensity of Pappas's friends, it's critical
to understand the intensity of his foes.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett was the first to challenge the doctor publicly, in a
1992 lawsuit claiming that Pappas misdiagnosed his knee injury a
decade ago and caused his career as the Sox second baseman to
fizzle. The jury sided with Barrett, which Pappas says was the
first and last time he's been convicted of malpractice, or even
charged with it.
</P>
<P>
   But concerns about Pappas's role with the team predated the
Barrett case and have persisted into this still-young season.
Henry, a lefty the team let go last year, recently told a Seattle
newspaper that Pappas had advised him he could pitch despite a
ligament tear that required immediate surgery. Questions also have
been raised about the handling of injuries to pitcher Brian Rose,
infielder Lou Merloni, and designated hitter Reggie Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the medical community share those doubts. It is critical
for players ``that the team doctor have an arm's length
relationship with owners so when you talk to players they don't
think you're just an extension of management. But Art is an
owner,'' says one respected sports medicine specialist, who asked
that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   While the grousers have gotten the attention, however, they're
not the only ones with strong opinions on Pappas. He helped Roger
Clemens return to form after shoulder surgery in 1984, prolonged
the careers of Dennis Eckersley, Bruce Hurst, Jim Lonborg, and
Sonny Seibert, and aided Dennis ``Oil Can'' Boyd in overcoming his
combustible combination of emotional, physical, and fiscal stress.
Even Tim Naehring, who never made it back after a raft of injuries,
has said he's eternally grateful for Pappas's help, as is Larry
McCoy, an umpire from Arkansas who thought so much of him that he
sent his daughter here for back surgery several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mike Flanagan, the former ace of the Baltimore
Orioles, who says simply that Pappas ``saved my career.'' The year
was 1980 and Flanagan was coming off a Cy Young Award year, but he
spent most of the next season with a pain that his doctors could
neither understand nor relieve. During a trip to Boston the last
week of the season he consulted with Pappas _ home team doctors
always treat the visiting team _ and Pappas determined the pain was
emanating from the back of his shoulder rather than front, as other
doctors had said. He also suggested a program of physical therapy
that could avoid surgery, and offered to supervise the care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached for help and he responded, I never felt
uncomfortable seeing him based on our baseball rivalry or going to
the enemy camp,'' Flanagan recalls. ``After that I'd drag young
pitchers to him. He diagnosed their problems early and probably
saved them from the agony I had to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Jobe, whose 35 years as doctor for the Los Angeles
Dodgers make him the dean of professional baseball physicians, also
is a Pappas admirer: ``I've never found him to be anything but
ethical and first class.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising source of kind words about Pappas, however,
is Barrett, who's retired now, living in Las Vegas, and coaching
his children's teams at the same time he's doing charity work. ``I
respect Dr. Pappas,'' Barrett said in a telephone interview. ``I
think the Red Sox and Dr. Pappas treated my situation as business
and I treated it as business right back. But personally, I like Dr.
Pappas and would say `hi' to him if I saw him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of things for my family and children and helped
them . . . I think he's a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the supposed conflict in Pappas's roles as owner and
doctor?
</P>
<P>
   Some Sox watchers say his ownership gives him more clout in
standing up to management and protecting his players as patients.
``Every doctor on every team is hired by the team,'' explains
Saberhagen, who has experienced a lot of them. ``If he wants to
stay the team doc, he pretty much does what the team wants him
to.''
</P>
<P>
   George Annas, a medical ethicist at the Boston University School
of Public Health, agrees that all the furor over Pappas's dual
roles is ``almost a made-up thing . . . If everyone knows that he's
a part owner and that they can get a second opinion I don't see the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, meanwhile, says he ``would advise any athlete that gets
hurt with a team to always get a second opinion'' regardless of
whether the team doctor is an owner or an employee. ``For the most
part, all team doctors try to be objective. Where they get in
trouble is the grey areas where they might lean toward doing
something that's favorable to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pappas generally leaves it to others to defend him. Touting his
own accomplishments simply isn't his style, although a sense of
what he's done and how he feels about the controversy surrounding
him did trickle out over the course of two interviews last week,
one in his tattered office at the rump end of the Fenway clubhouse
and the other in his section of seats in Row A just to the right of
the Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Auburn, where his Greek father and Albanian mother
ran a small grocery. He learned his love of sports in high school,
where he was a four-sport athlete, and developed his fascination
with sports injuries at Harvard, where he was an offensive guard on
the football team and tore up his shoulder. He also injured his
knee, and still walks with a slight limp.
</P>
<P>
   After medical school at the University of Rochester he completed
a residency at Children's and Massachusetts General hospitals,
focusing on orthopedic injuries in children and on the nascent
field of sports medicine. He'd been close to the Red Sox and after
team owner Tom Yawkey died in 1976, Pappas was invited by
then-trainer Buddy LeRoux to join a group that was purchasing
limited-partner shares in the team; his 4 percent cost him about $1
million. At the same time he became the Sox full-time physician.
</P>
<P>
   Being an owner mainly involves watching your money multiply,
with Pappas's initial investment probably worth more than 20 times
what he paid for it. But being the Red Sox medical director is a
year-round job, even though he isn't paid. He starts work in the
offseason, working with the team's trainer, physical therapist, and
strength coach to come up with conditioning plans for more than 200
major and minor league players. The advising and monitoring
continue through spring training and now that the season has
started, he oversees a staff at Fenway of five doctors, three
trainers, and nine first-aid people, along with others throughout
the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are just part of what Pappas does as a doctor,
however, and not necessarily the most important part.
</P>
<P>
   He's at least as proud of his work chairing the Department of
Orthopedics at the University of Massachusetts Medical Center in
Worcester, and of the text he's written and more than 100 papers
he's authored on injuries to the elbow, shoulder, and other upper
extremities. And his bushy eyebrows really rise when he talks about
his efforts on behalf of disadvantaged children, including years of
participating in clinics for the handicapped in Haverhill, Lowell
and Worcester, helping found the Bay State Games and serving as
chairman of the board of the Massachusetts Hospital School in
Canton.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas also remains a die-hard Sox fan, rooting for the team
even as he analyzes the motions and mechanics of every player who
comes to bat or fields a ball. As for the controversy that has
surrounded him, Pappas seems philosophical: ``It's frustrating, but
I guess it's part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gordon Edes of the Globe staff contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
