<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FRYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRYE IS OUT AT SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ What Jeff Frye feared all along has come to pass. Jose
Offerman is now the Red Sox second baseman, and Frye believes he is
the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything out of respect for Jimy Williams,
but he told me they have to try to start doing something with the
offense, and Offy will be playing second base,'' Frye said Thursday
morning. ``This is a situation I anticipated happening, and my
theory is that there's not much I can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here for the money. I'm here to play ball. To keep my
mouth shut and sit on the bench, making $2 million, that isn't
going to make me happy. I've gotta be playing ball. That's the kind
of player I am. I'm not a utility player. If I'm not good enough to
be the starting second baseman on a particular team, maybe I
shouldn't be on that team.''
</P>
<P>
   What looked like a one-shot deal Wednesday, when Offerman made
his first start of the season at second base, took on a more
permanent appearance in Thursday's 1-0 loss to the Detroit Tigers
and lefthander Justin Thompson, when Offerman played second, Lou
Merloni played first, and Frye sat on the bench for the second
straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams chose to have Merloni make his first professional start
at first base rather than move Offerman to first, where he has
played, and insert Frye at second.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jefferson's recovery from his back problems, and the Sox'
ongoing offensive woes, were the catalysts to Offerman becoming the
second baseman. The only way Williams can get Jefferson and
Offerman in the lineup at the same time against righthanded
pitchers, as well as Mike Stanley, one of the few power threats on
the club, is to move Offerman to second, DH Jefferson, and have
Stanley play first base. That leaves no place for Frye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie's here now,'' Williams said. ``He's a major league
hitter. We need his bat in the lineup. We've got to have all three
of them in the lineup against righthanded pitchers. The only way we
can do it is put (Offerman) at second.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Red Sox placing a big emphasis on pitching and defense,
Frye, a better gloveman than Offerman, seemed to have the edge at
second base. Many scouts rate Offerman as a below-average second
baseman; only Joey Cora, who had 20 errors last season, made more
errors than Offerman, who had 19. Thursday, Williams defended
Offerman's play afield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose's a bona fide second baseman,'' Williams said. ``He
played well for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a good defensive player out, add two good offensive
players and a defensive player out there. Basically, that's what
we're doing for the time being, to jump-start us and move on from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who missed all of last season after surgery to repair the
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, was batting .265 in 10
games, with two RBIs. All nine of his hits have been singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't do anything to get himself out of the lineup,'' said
Williams, who insisted even after the Sox signed Offerman last
November to a four-year, $26 million contract that Frye was his
second baseman. ``He's going to get his playing time. As time goes
by these things take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a lot to our team _ his skill, makeup, heart,
determination. All put together, you've got to have a guy like that
on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman had been the DH for 10 games and first baseman three
times until playing second base Wednesday, the position he played
for the Kansas City Royals last season. It has been clear from the
time Dan Duquette signed Offerman that the Red Sox general manager
envisioned Offerman as the second baseman, and at the outset of the
season, the player expressed unhappiness about being limited to a
DH role.
</P>
<P>
   Frye was asked if he thought Duquette was behind the decision
for him to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way of knowing,'' Frye said. ``But we all know what
Jimy Williams thinks about my game. I know how he feels about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for Jimy Williams, and I love
playing in Boston and for the fans in Boston. But maybe there's
something in the cards that has to play itself out. I've been the
so-called scapegoat many times in my career, situations where we're
not going well and the only guy they take out is me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Duquette has openly lobbied for Offerman to play second
base, Williams has held his ground on playing decisions, as he
demonstrated at the end of the '97 season, when he gave lefthander
Steve Avery a final start that triggered a $3.8 million contract
option.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the Red Sox were looking to trade him, Frye
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've proved I'm healthy,'' he said, ``and we have four
players for three spots. The middle infield, it's hard to
interchange guys. It's hard to let Offy DH one day and me play
second base, and then have him at second base the next day. Maybe
the feeling is, stick with him at second base, let him and Nomar
(Garciaparra) get comfortable, and interchange other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It would not be a shock if Frye eventually elects to ask for a
trade if he finds himself anchored on the bench, although the $5.1
million due him in the last two years of his contract makes it
tougher for the Sox to move him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him on this team,'' Williams said. ``He's a winning
player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
