<HEADER>
A0534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-APACHE-BOS &LR;      04-23 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-APACHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANK BUSTERS HEAD TO HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that Apache helicopters are landing in Albania,
NATO and Serbian forces might soon be fighting each other at close
range.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes have been bombing Yugoslavia for a month now, but
only from altitudes of 15,000 feet _ beyond the range of Serbian
antiaircraft weapons and too high for the NATO planes to damage
much military gear on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   One NATO plane has been shot down. In turn, the NATO planes have
destroyed a mere handful of Serbian air-defense sites and only 10
or 20 percent of their 400 or so armored vehicles in and around
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Apaches, also known as AH-64As, start to fly, this
situation will likely change _ for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache's main mission is to kill tanks. Each helicopter
carries up to 16 Hellfire heat-seeking missiles, capable of
destroying the turret or tread of any tank in the world. Each also
holds a few dozen 2.75-inch rockets and 1,200 rounds of 30mm
cannon, which can disable thinner-skinned vehicles, kill people, or
make them run in panic.
</P>
<P>
   Attack helicopers, including Apaches, fired 2,876 Hellfires in
the 1991 Gulf War and are credited with destroying 500 Iraqi tanks
and several hundred armored personnel carriers and self-propelled
artillery cannons. An Apache also fired the first shot in that war,
sneaking across the Iraqi border to take out an air-defense radar.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches fly low _ well under the clouds, as little as 500
feet off the ground or even lower. This makes it easier for their
missiles to hit tanks _ but it also makes it easier for enemy
missiles to hit Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have hundreds of antiaircraft weapons, including
shoulder-fired surface-to-air missiles, all across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some helicopters are going to get shot down,'' an
administration official acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Army field manuals on Apache operations spell out ways to
minimize this vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 Apaches in Albania are joined together in a unit called
``Task Force Hawk,'' which includes 27 Multiple-Launch Rocket
Systems (MLRS).
</P>
<P>
   Each MLRS can fire 12 rockets having a range of 20 miles, or two
Army Tactical Missile Systems (ATACMs) with a range of 120 miles.
Each ATACM releases 950 grenade-size bomblets over an area several
hundred feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   Apaches, MLRS, and various surveillance systems work in a
coordinated fashion. Once a target is located, Apaches fly in,
hugging the terrain. When they reach the area, MLRS fires its
munitions, pelting the area to suppress enemy air-defense crews.
The Apaches pop up from behind a hill or from under the treeline,
fire their missiles and shells, and pop back down.
</P>
<P>
   That's the theory, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are not going to make it easy for us,'' Barry Posen,
professor of national-security studies at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, said Thursday. ``If the Serbs are any good
at air defense, they can probably figure out where they need to
deploy to keep the Apaches vulnerable while staying out of MLRS'
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``if you start hosing the area'' with MLRS, he added, ``they
could start hugging refugees again,'' so the Apaches cannot attack
Serbian tanks without also killing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be hard to find Serbian tanks. The sensor in a
Hellfire missile detects tanks by the heat they give off. ``If the
tanks are on the road, that's no problem,'' said Robert Pape,
professor of national-security studies at Dartmouth College. ``But
if they're under a tree, in the shade, or hiding in the mountains,
the heat-signature is not easy to pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there seems little doubt the Apaches will ratchet up
NATO's air war, in terms of both damaging Serbian forces and
putting US troops in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO decides at some point to send in ground forces, the
Apaches could be the wedge for them, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Apaches are not only MLRS transporters but also a
small number of M1 Abrams tanks and M2 Bradley infantry fighting
vehicles, as well as a ``ready brigade'' of 800 troops from the 82d
Airborne Division.
</P>
<P>
   These troops and armor are there to defend the Apaches'
staging-areas from possible attack. But once they are set up, John
Pike, military analyst at the Federation of American Scientists,
said, ``It doesn't require a lot of buffing'' to bring in a lot
more for offensive operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 Gulf War, Apaches did not see much action until the
ground invasion began, and they moved with _ or slightly ahead of _
the US troops, clearing away paths of resistance.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials, however, continue to oppose a ground war in
Yugoslavia. Robin Cook, the British foreign minister, told
reporters here Thursday, ``Let me just repeat, for the avoidance of
doubt: no ground troops that have to fight their way in; yes,
ground troops to guarantee a cease-fire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
