<HEADER>
A0542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-POLAND-BOS &LR;      04-23 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-POLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NATO MEMBER HAS FEW REGRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ Joining NATO was supposed to be a joyous occasion for
Poland, a confirmation of victory in an centuries-old struggle to
stake out an identity as a stable, independent, Western-oriented
state.
</P>
<P>
   Few Poles knew that their country would join the Western
alliance just as it plunged itself into a major military conflict
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Kosovo crisis has cast a shadow over celebrations of
NATO's 50th anniversary in Washington, it has also dampened the
fanfare here over last month's accession to the alliance. Still,
Poles regard their new NATO membership as a measure of how far
their country has progressed from the sullen, Communist birthplace
of the Warsaw Pact _ the Soviet-dominated alliance that faced off
against the West during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Balkans conflict has produced little discernable regret
in Poland about the timing of its entry into NATO last month.
Instead, the Kosovo crisis, and NATO's military response, seems to
have confirmed for Poles why they wanted to join the alliance in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that Poland will be safer with NATO,'' said
Teresa Szczurowska, a researcher at the Center for Public Opinion
Studies in Warsaw. ``The support people had towards NATO has not
changed because of Kosovo. To tell the truth, it may have
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the center in February showed 63 percent of Poles
supported joining NATO. That edged up to 70 percent in a poll
completed March 31 _ after a week of bombing showed that the
campaign against Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic was going to be
long and difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Poland approves of NATO's airstrikes, but
support is strong _ between 50 and 60 percent in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   The way Poles see it, twice in this century the West failed to
back Poland against a powerful foe: in 1939, when Britain and
France allowed Hitler to annex parts of Poland, setting the stage
for World War II; and again in 1945, when Britain and the US
accepted the division of Europe into two camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering our historical background, this is a very positive
change for Poland,'' said Col. Wieslaw Kurzyca, deputy head of the
Polish military's liaison office with NATO. ``That happiness is
offset by the war. It was bad luck. Our new situation is very
fortunate, but we cannot enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland was a battleground in most of the great European wars,
and it was partioned, annexed, and erased from maps for long
periods by the Austro-Hungarian, Prussian and Russian empires.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Poland's defiance of foreign crackdowns and
military invasions is etched into one of Warsaw's central
monuments, the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, which celebrates the
Polish Army' resistance against Nazi Germany; the ill-fated 1943
Warsaw Getto uprising; and Poland's struggles for independence from
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   It was here, just a few blocks from the building where the
Soviet Union and its Eastern European satellites signed the Warsaw
Pact agreement in 1955, that the NATO flag was raised last month
next to the Polish flag.
</P>
<P>
   Just days later, NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, with the full
backing of Poland's government. The few Poles who dissented
expressed concern over the precedent NATO's action sets for
international law.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did NATO, that is the United States, illegitimately
appoint itself policeman of the world?'' asked an editorial in the
leftist Trybuna daily.
</P>
<P>
   But many Poles, mindful of their own history, support the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1939, Europeans did not want to die to save Gdansk from
Hitler, and so we got World War II,'' said Pawel Wronski, defense
and security analyst at Gazeta Wyborcza, Poland's most influential
daily. ``Sometimes you need to use force to stop a greater evil.''
</P>
<P>
   But could Poland to contribute to that force if NATO decided to
send in ground troops? Like the Czech Republic and Hungary, which
also gained membership to NATO in March, Poland has met the
alliance's minimal criteria by cutting the size of its Soviet-style
army, putting its military under civilian control, and agreeing to
purchase NATO military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But the Polish army will not be fully integrated into NATO until
2003. In many ways, it is still the same under-equipped, draft army
it was before, lacking officers who speak English, training with
NATO forces, and even NATO flags, Wronski said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Poland has one elite unit, the ``Red Berets,'' who have
trained with American troops and is considered combat-ready. But
Kurzyca of the Defense Ministry said Poland, which has had
peacekeeping troops in the former Yugoslavia since 1992, was ready
to send a similar force to Kosovo to help implement an eventual
peace agreement to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Poles are eager to do something to show their loyalty. Although
no government official will say so, NATO membership for Poland, the
Czech Republic and Hungary is first and foremost a guarantee
against threats from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's angry response was not lost on people in Warsaw. For
Poles, Russia's nuclear saber-rattling over the NATO bombing, which
included a vague proposal to put nuclear weapons back in the former
Soviet republic of Belarus, Poland's neighbor to the east,
underscored the importance of NATO's security umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``During communism, we were always afraid of American weapons,''
said Wronski. ``After communism, we are always afraid of Russia.
How long do we have to be afraid? Now, we are really not afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
