<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-23 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A TIME TO FLINCH FROM THE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ School uniforms will not fix what has gone
wrong in America, but already we are seizing on such facile
solutions in the aftermath of the massacre this week at Columbine
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of addressing the need for stricter gun controls and
better outreach services to alienated adolescents, we are talking
about dress codes, video games, and rock 'n' roll lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Like every act of violence, the slaying of 12 students and a
teacher by two disaffected teenagers is a reflection of the culture
in which it occurred. Our children play out apocalyptic fantasies
on their computer screens. They listen to the suicidal seductions
of self-styled ``death rockers.'' They line up for tickets to
movies marketing horror and mayhem expressly to them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of our children, however, do not spend their weekends at
dad's workbench fashioning pipe bombs out of propane tanks from the
backyard grill. Most do not stroll into school on a sunny spring
morning, toting sawed-off shotguns and semiautomatic rifles under
their long black coats.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did the two presumed killers Eric Harris, 18, and
Dylan Klebold, 17?
</P>
<P>
   We can blame Marilyn Manson, and what adult would not be
tempted? But we have been here before. In Bethel, Alaska. In Pearl,
Miss. In West Paducah, Ky. In Jonesboro, Ark. In Edinboro, Pa. In
Springfield, Ore. Haven't we learned yet that the obvious answers
are the simplistic ones?
</P>
<P>
   It may be more comforting to blame an epidemic of teen suicide
on Kurt Cobain than to confront the psychic pain so many of our
children are apparently suffering.
</P>
<P>
   If we are going to look to the culture to explain the gunfire
that rained terror and death in the halls of one of Colorado's best
public high schools, let's talk, too, about the proliferation of
guns and the epidemic of adult indifference to children in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of our unwillingness to tackle those
considerably tougher issues that the sponsor of legislation to
expand the right to carry concealed weapons in Colorado withdrew
the bills until the next legislative session out of ``respect'' for
the Columbine victims and their families. If the sponsor, House
Majority Leader Doug Dean, wants to honor the victims of Tuesday's
shooting rampage he should rewrite his legislation to ban concealed
weapons entirely, just as seven other states do.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for movie star and gun lobbyist Charlton Heston
to make the fatuous claim that the Columbine tragedy could have
been avoided if only the school had employed an armed guard. Dean,
a Republican from Colorado Springs, knows that an armed guard was
employed there. But an armed guard was little defense against two
people bent on murder and suicide and equipped with a 9mm
semiautomatic carbine, two sawed-off shotguns and one semiautomatic
pistol.
</P>
<P>
   We do not yet know where the killers got the weapons that
wreaked such destruction, but the fact that two such disaffected
young people had access to so much firepower should give us more
than pause. It ought to mobilize us with the same sense of urgency
that propelled Great Britain to ban handguns in the wake of the
fatal shootings of a kindergarden teacher and 16 of her students in
a schoolhouse in Dunblane, Scotland in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Alone, a ban on guns would not have prevented the carnage at
Columbine High School anymore than a ban on Marilyn Manson's CDs.
The makings for the more than 30 crude pipe bombs that Harris and
Klebold planted throughout their school and its parking lots are
available at most hardware srores.
</P>
<P>
   What was less available to these children was the active concern
of alert adults. Columbine school official will tell you that the
boys, members of an informal clique known as the Trench Coat Mafia,
dressed in black dusters and dark sunglasses, but gave no hint of
the carnage to come. They will tell you that Columbine High School
is a safe suburban school where the tensions between cliques of
preppies, of jocks, of freaks and ``goths'' is no more alarming
then it has ever been at any American high school. But the facts
are clearly otherwise. Six months ago, the Jefferson County
Sheriff's Department warned school officials that fights among
suburban students were increasing. Administrators dismissed those
alarms then, and again this week as an exaggeration, despite the
fact that in the last academic year 506 students in Colorado were
expelled for bringing weapons to school. That's an 18 percent
increase from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In the specific case of Harris and Klebold, the warning sounds
were loud and clear, had only some adult been listening and willing
to intervene. The pair produced a video for a television production
course that classmates say displayed violent gunplay in the school.
One Columbine High School parent says he reported to the Jefferson
County Sheriff last year that Harris, who maintained a well-known
and hate filled website, had threatened his son. In addition, both
boys were arrested a year ago for a property crime. They would
celebrate a strike scored during a school bowling class with a Nazi
salute, a fascination with Adolf Hitler that extended to wearing
Nazi paraphernalia and scrawling swastikas on their books,
</P>
<P>
   Harris wrote essays for his English classes preoccupied with
death and other dark themes.
</P>
<P>
   This set off no alarm bells?
</P>
<P>
   These kids even advertised their despair. In a yearbook ad last
year the Trench Coat Mafia celebrated their ``Insanity.'' ``Stay
Alive, Stay Different,'' they wrote. ``Stay Crazy.''.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Denver School District banned black trench coats
in class and the mayor called on Marilyn Manson to cancel his
concert here next week. That oughta solve things.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
