<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-VICTIMS-BOS &LR;      04-23 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-VICTIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT IN THE FIRE, A VARIETY OF LIVES AND DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Before the bullets and bombs, before the
tears, they were volleyball players and actors, church group
members and fishermen, honor students and average students, beloved
friends and treasured children.
</P>
<P>
   Before they were victims, they laughed, got sad, wrote poetry,
worked after school, watched movies, did homework, picked colleges,
had crushes. They went to the mall, pleased and perplexed their
parents, babysat, and dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 students massacred Tuesday at Columbine High School fit
no neat categories or cliques, no convenient pattern from which
conclusions about their killers' motives can be drawn. One was
black, four were girls; some were jocks, some were not; some were
leaders, some were followers; some were seniors, some juniors, some
sophomores, at least one a freshman. The 22 other injured students,
more than a dozen still hospitalized Thursday, were similarly
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the real possibility that when the gunmen
were not simply spraying bullets and tossing explosives, they were
targeting anyone plainly unlike themselves. They killed students
with easy smiles and high hopes, healthy relationships and bright
futures, comfortable in the world, in their community and in their
school.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the dead was one teacher, William ``Dave'' Sanders,
who taught business and coached girls' basketball and softball. He
fit that same description, friends and students said Thursday,
describing a man who cherished his wife, his daughter, three
stepdaughters, several grandchildren, and many hundreds of other
people's children he taught and coached for nearly a
quarter-century. He died clutching a family photo, telling the
students who worked for hours in vain to stop his bleeding, ``Tell
my girls I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a spring snowstorm blanketed this grieving city,
providing a temporary cover for the spontaneous memorials that have
sprung up all around the school grounds to declare everlasting love
for the 13 victims, and, in some cases, forgiveness for their
presumed killers, Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's snow also threatened to delay the expected May
blooming of the delicate columbine flowers, sprightly blue and
white perennials for which the school is named. For the moment, no
one here is ready for such a concomitant of spring. Rather, they
want to stop the world long enough to look back and remember.
</P>
<P>
   Through tears and a quavering voice, Carol Samson, an advanced
placement English teacher, wanted to share a line from
Shakespeare's ``Othello,'' a play that had so moved slain senior
Lauren Townsend. It comes from Act 5, Scene 2, when Desdemona's
maid says to Othello: ``Thou hast killed the sweetest innocent that
e'er did lift up eye.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be no better description for Townsend, her teacher
said. ``She's just an excellent woman, tall and thin, beautiful,
with a fragile voice. But we've lost her. I'll never forget her.
Now she's engraved on my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Samson said Townsend had stood in her classroom just days ago,
holding a baby chick she was raising as part of a science project
before giving it to a farm. ``I just keep seeing her with that
chick, how loving she was, how good she was,'' Samson said.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend, 18, was captain of the girls' volleyball team, coached
by her mother, and worked in an animal shelter. She also carried a
perfect 4.0 grade point average and was a candidate for
valedictorian at a May 23 graduation, after which she planned to
attend Colorado State University.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine High School class play, performed just days before
the student body was thrust into a real-life drama, called for
Rachel Scott, 17, to play an outcast, a student searching for
herself in a world of peer pressure and popularity contests.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Scott, a teenager who read the Bible as
enthusiastically as she did stage scripts, rose beyond
expectations, stealing the scenes in ``Smoke in the Room.'' She was
pretty, confident, and had a reputation for warmth, distancing
herself from petty rifts in high school hallways. She wanted to
join a missionary group in Africa, said her friend Rob Salyer, who
worked with her at a local Subway sandwich shop.
</P>
<P>
   During the massacre, Rachel Scott's younger brother Craig, 16,
played dead in the library and helped lead others to safety. After
they were safe, Craig Scott led the group in prayer for their
siblings trapped inside. All emerged safely except for Rachel. Her
car later became a shrine in the school parking lot, covered with
flowers, candles, and heartbreaking notes from friends.
</P>
<P>
   If any one death revealed the twisted minds of the killers, it
was the execution-style slaying of Isaiah Shoels, 18, a senior and
the only black victim. Witnesses said he was singled out because of
his race and his status as a popular athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Shoels had suffered health problems as a child and had heart
surgery twice, pulling through despite fears he would die on the
operating table. He dreamed of becoming a music executive. A
wrestler and football player, Shoels made up for his small stature
with hard work, lifting weights so much that he could bench-press
twice his weight.
</P>
<P>
   Shoels' father, Michael Shoels, said Thursday that Isaiah and
his brother and sister, all three of whom attended Columbine, had
been repeatedly harassed by the presumed killers and their friends,
the self-styled ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   Before killing themselves, Klebold and Harris also robbed this
community of the first boy Michelle Oetter ever loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met at church,'' Oetter said Thursday, recalling her
initial crush on 16-year-old John Tomlin, a sophomore two years her
junior whose broad shoulders and blue eyes first drew her to him.
Tomlin was a young man who loved his Chevrolet pickup, his
after-school jobs tending plants at a nursery, and, like many of
the teenagers here, Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``John had a personal relationship with Jesus Christ,'' Oetter
said. ``And I do, too. And I know he's in heaven right now. I know
I will see him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin was in the library, Oetter said, probably reading his
favorite automotive magazine, sitting alone, when he was shot and
killed. The tuxedo he was supposed to wear to Oetter's prom this
weekend at a nearby high school hangs in the hallway of his
family's home. His parents spent Thursday making plans for their
son's funeral in Wisconsin, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Mauser, 15, a sophomore, also was in the school library
when he was ambushed. No one who knew the blond-haired boy with
glasses was surprised that he was studying during lunch hour,
sitting alone because his small group of friends had differing
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him since first grade,'' said Kristen Schoenoff,
also a sophomore. She was among the students who ran to safety from
the cafeteria Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just the sweetest kid. He probably would not even have
known about the Trenchcoat Mafia,'' she added. ``I can't imagine
what he must have been thinking,'' Schoenoff added. ``But I can't
cry right now. I can't cry anymore. I just feel dried up. I prayed
and prayed last night. I don't know what else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauser was also remembered Thursday as a boy who knew how to
make his elderly neighbor Ken Greenlaw feel good about his fate.
Greenlaw suffered a debilitating heart attack five years ago, so
Mauser would come to his house and rake leaves, said Greenlaw's
crying wife, Donna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he couldn't work, Ken spent a lot of time making
birdhouses,'' Donna Greenlaw said. ``Dan would come by and say,
`Hey Ken, that's a great job you're doing there.' Dan was a very
deep child, a very sweet boy. We've watched him grow up. We wanted
to watch him become a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassie Bernall, 17, was a junior whose friends knew what she
would have wanted them to do: They went to church. She was a member
of the West Bowles Community Church youth group, which also counted
Rachel Scott among its members. Friends said Bernall loved God
above all, and two years ago became a born-again Christian. She
also was passionate about writing poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Corey DePooter, 17, was going through life having fun. He was
easygoing, a fisherman, devoting as many hours as he could spare to
the pleasure of sitting with his friends and waiting for a bite.
</P>
<P>
   On land, DePooter liked to get around on in-line skates or in
golf spikes, translating his enjoyment of golf into a job doing
maintenance at a golf course. DePooter was thinking about joining
the Marines. He had been on the wrestling team, but quit to focus
on his schoolwork, friends said. DePooter's 15-year-old sister,
Jenna, escaped from the school unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of 16-year-old Kelly Fleming, who moved to Colorado just
18 months ago, say she was in the library when gunfire erupted, and
they imagine her writing poetry, as she often did, dedicating pages
each day to a journal of life experiences. She wrote short stories
as a hobby, hoping to one day have a writing career. Looking
forward to getting her driver's license this summer, Fleming stood
out for her maturity and curiosity, philosophic in ways beyond her
years, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Kechter was 16, a strapping junior whose hobby was
weightlifting. He hoped to start for the football team as a
lineman. At the same time, he maintained an A average. Witnesses
said he was shot in the library while trying to reach friends
hiding in the adjacent video room.
</P>
<P>
   The three other dead students were identified as Steven Curnow,
14, a freshman who dreamed of being a Navy top gun and piloting an
F-16; Daniel Rohrbough, 15, who helped in his father's electronics
business and was shot while holding a door open for fleeing
students; and Kyle Velasquez, whose age was not immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of lean years, the Columbine girls' basketball
team last season rewarded its long-suffering coach, Sanders, with a
winning record, 12-9. But it wasn't the wins that motivated
Sanders, 47, the only teacher killed, said his friend and fellow
coach, Rick Bath.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarterfinals of last season's girls' softball
tournament, the team's best player, All-American catcher Amber
Burgess, was at bat in the last inning with two outs and a runner
on first base. Their team was losing 4-3. But Burgess couldn't
muster the hit; she grounded out, ending the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first reaction was to run to Amber, to take care of her,''
Bath recalled. ``Winning was nice, but what mattered to him was the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Sanders died a hero, running into the cafeteria
to warn students when he saw the heavily armed gunmen headed that
way. As a result, witnesses said, the cafeteria was nearly empty
when the killers arrived. But Sanders, fatally wounded, could only
stumble into a science classroom where students were hiding. He
died how he lived, surrounded by students.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara of the Globe staff contributed to this report;
wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
