<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-WEAPONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY CITES EASY ACCESS TO WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Guns are easy for teenagers to come by, even in
states where it is illegal to own or possess one, criminologists
and gun-control advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 60 percent of students in grades six through 12 said
they ``could get a handgun if they wanted one,'' according to a
survey of 2,508 students across the United States commissioned by
the Chicago-based Joyce Foundation several years ago. One-third
said they could find a handgun in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet known how the two young gunmen in Littleton,
Colo., got their hands on the handgun, rifle, sawed-off shotguns,
and more than 30 explosive devices they apparently used during
their bloody rampage through their high school.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear, academics say, that the number of school
shootings and other mass slayings has climbed dramatically in the
past two decades as a result of greater and easier access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame guns for creating monsters, but you can use
them to explain the large body counts and these tragic
circumstances,'' said Jack Levin, a criminologist at Northeastern
University in Boston. ``It's the proliferation of firearms among
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Two in 25 high school students, or 7.9 percent, reported having
carried a gun in the past 30 days, according to the national
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have lots of access to guns because there are lots of
guns out there,'' said Stephen Teret, director of the Center for
Gun Policy and Research at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 220 million guns in circulation, and an
additional 12 million guns are manufactured and sold each year,
according to the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Juveniles get guns by buying them illegally on the street, at
gun shows, and through newspaper ads, or by stealing them, paying
someone to buy them, or taking them from their home or the home of
a friend or family member, according to gun crime specialists.
</P>
<P>
   But, as in almost every major school shooting case over the past
two years, juveniles most often use firearms taken from their home
or the home of a family member. Criminologists expect the Colorado
shooting too fit the same pattern.
</P>
<P>
   In a study for the Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency
Prevention, researchers found that 53 percent of the 758 high
school students they interviewed said they could ``borrow'' a gun
from someone they know.
</P>
<P>
   There are guns in one-third to half of all American households,
according to government statistics. And a study conducted last year
for a handgun-control activist group arrived at similar figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 42 percent who reported a gun at home, many said that
the guns were loaded and unlocked,'' said Bob Walker, director of
Handgun Control, a group started by James Brady, the White House
press secretary who was wounded during the assassination attempt
against President Ronald Reagan. ``The key is for parents to make
sure their children cannot access the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   After several school shootings had occurred last year, the
Senate voted down a measure that would hold parents responsible for
keeping their guns locked away from their children. A similar bill
is pending this year in both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, there is no minimum age required by law to
possess a firearm, although a juvenile must be at least 18, or 15
with parental consent, to receive the firearm identification card
that makes possession legal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
