<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSERVATIONS ON AN AIR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been a number of astonishing developments in the four
weeks since NATO's air bombardment of what used to be Yugoslavia
brought war back to Europe. Here are some surprises,
contradictions, and unintended consequences:
</P>
<P>
   --It is incredible that thousands of combat sorties flown by
NATO aircrews against a relatively sophisticated air-defense system
came without the loss of a single flier. That only one plane has
been shot down is remarkable, given what the pilots face, the foul
weather, the difficult terrain, and the odds of maintaining a
perfect record of aircraft maintainance.
</P>
<P>
   --The United States slipped into a war for which none of us were
prepared. Americans don't seem to talk much about this war; it's
confusing, the geography is remote, the history complex, the
languages strange, the names difficult to spell. It's a TV and
newspaper war, but not a coffee-shop or kitchen-table war.
</P>
<P>
   --The refugees tipped the balance of public opinion, here and in
Europe. The plight of these strange mountain people, most of them
peasants evicted by a merciless military machine, became apparent
as they were driven out.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO's political coalition, stitching together 19 nations
ranging from the US to Iceland, has held together, with no
defections, or political collapse, in the face of the sternest
challenge the alliance has faced in its 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   --President Clinton's congressional opponents, so vociferous in
the year-long impeachment imbroglio have been virtually silenced by
the administration's conduct of a war that no one really
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   --The criticism of US policy by the dozen candidates seeking to
prevent the accession of Vice President Gore is strangely muted.
The war has diminished the candidacies of all but Senator John
McCain, whose clear grasp of the hard end of the stick has elevated
his standing. None of the others seemed willing to pay the price a
superpower must.
</P>
<P>
   --The obduracy of Slobodan Milosevic has surprised all who had
been assured the Serb chief understands only force and would back
down, as he has backed down before, when confronted with resolute
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   --The second-guessing of the NATO strategy seems to have
coalesced around the decision, announced at the outset of the air
war, that no ground combat forces would be employed. What seems
obvious now is that the threat, at least, of imminent invasion on
the ground was essential to convincing Milosevic of NATO's serious
intent. But it may have been a prudent political strategy, both for
assuring a public unprepared for casualties, and for keeping the
NATO governments in harness, to rule out ground combat at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   --The news Thursday that the European Union is prepared to
enforce an oil embargo against Serbia and Montenegro economy puts
more pressure on Milosevic. His house has been blown up; he's lost
half his jet fighters, 10 to 20 percent of his armor, probably
one-quarter of his antimissile defences, by Pentagon estimate. In
return, he shot down one US plane (whose pilot was rescued) and
captured three US soldiers on the border.
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslavia's communications, infrastructure, oil refining
capacity, and rail and bridge network are getting hammered. This
gets worse by the day. The Serbs' economic infrastructure crumbles
before their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   --What has to be conceded is that the NATO planners made a
colossal blunder in unerestimating Milosevic's willingness to
employ the scorched-earth tactics of Hitler and Stalin. By a
Reuters estimate, some 960,000 Kosovars have fled or been driven
from Kosovo in the last year, 590,000 of them since the bombing
began April 24.
</P>
<P>
   --A refugee crisis of a scale not seen in Europe since the Nazi
era complicates NATO's strategy. The European Union is much closer
to the disruption than we are. Our economy soars, as the Euro
plunges. One big reason for NATO's resolve: Europe cannot afford to
lose to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   --There is a slow but perceptible groundswell of reluctant
support for the use of ground troops. If that's what it will take,
then that's what it will take, seems to be the grim consensus.
Europe cannot have a million refugees sloshing around its southern
flanks, and remain unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   --The professionalism of the American military, never mind the
other NATO contributors, is praiseworthy on a number of counts.
Performing a dangerous job, under adverse conditions, in a cause
that is difficult to explain, in a region of the world where ethnic
hatred is the favorite crop, with allies of 18 different
nationalities and a dozen different languages, is an unusually
difficult assignment.
</P>
<P>
   --The West cannot afford to lose this war to a nationalist with
a taste for blood-curdling policies. The beast must be caged. The
390 million people of Europe, never mind the 300-odd million of the
US and Canada, cannot leave a rabid dog running wild at the edge of
Europe. Can one bloodthirsty dictator with fewer than 10 million
people under his heel get away with what this guy just did? Not for
much longer. This is not Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fire that badly needs putting out. NATO is in the
process. One month in, the Serbs have taken a shellacking. But
that's only a foretaste of what's to come, till their leader is
killed, toppled, or comes to realize his miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
