<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEILING FAN NEEDS ITS OWN SPECIAL BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 25, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to put a ceiling fan in a recessed ceiling
light, but the electrician said it is difficult to put a fan on a
can light. Is there a practical way to do so?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE MURRAY, Mendon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Frankly, no. There would have to be a fastener set up around
the can light to hold the fan, and since a ceiling fan must have a
special reinforced box identified for such use for legal
installation, you must do it another way.
</P>
<P>
   That other way is to remove the can light, and install the fan
in that special box. And buy a ceiling fan with its own built-in
lights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to put cedar floor boards on my small balcony,
which is concrete, but I don't know quite how, and have gotten
various suggestions. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA STRINGER, Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cedar can be used on your balcony floor, but it should be
raised above the concrete, and the boards spaced, to allow water to
drain through it and across the concrete to drain over the edge of
the balcony. If that is done, the cedar can last for many years. To
do this, install 2 x 4 sleepers on the balcony, from back to front,
on their wide side, 16 to 24 inches apart, using construction
adhesive. Then, nail or screw the cedar floor boards on the
sleepers. The cedar will weather to gray in two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am tiling a hallway with 12-inch-square granite tiles. I
plan to take up the old tiles and hardwood top floor; there is a
wood floor under the hardwood. One man said he would put down
plywood, then the tiles with thin-set mortar. Another said he would
use cement board instead of plywood. A contractor said he didn't
think the granite tiles will stick to plywood with thin-set. Now I
am totally confused. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   SANDY ROSEN, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. How about taking up the old tiles, sanding the hardwood (or
have them sanded) and varnishing it with three coats of high-gloss,
oil-based polyurethane varnish? You will get a good-looking floor
that will resist wear and tear pretty well for a lot less money.
But even with a well-varnished floor, I would put a runner or a
carpet of some kind on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want the tiles, here is the best thing you can do. In
fact, you may not need to take up the hardwood, unless the added
tiles and underlayment would bring the floor up too high,
interfering with door openings. Use cement board, either on the
hardwood or on the subfloor; I think the cement board will give a
much better surface for the granite tiles.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you must be alert to: the cement board must be very
even; if there are any ridges or rises or any other uneven
surfaces, you run the risk of the tiles moving, despite the
thin-set, and breaking. A way to get around that is to use smaller
tiles.
</P>
<P>
   While I think the tiles will stick to plywood with thin-set,
they will stick much better with thin-set on cement board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just cannot keep my stainless steel sink clean. And, I
think some kind of acid made a distinct stain on it. How can I
remove it, and how can I keep the sink clean looking?
</P>
<P>
   P.O., Stow, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Stainless steel is a great sink; I have one and have the same
problem of its never looking clean. It always looks a little
greasy. For polishing and cleaning, try Cameo Aluminum and
Stainless Steel Cleaner (in supermarkets).
</P>
<P>
   The acid might have etched the steel _ does the stain feel
rougher than the rest of the sink? _ If so, it is etched, and the
etching would have to be abraded off. So, Never Dull Magic Wadding
(in a blue and red can in hardware stores) might work.
</P>
<P>
   This might also work: Spray Easy Off oven cleaner, leave
overnight and wash. Once or twice a week, wash with baking soda. Do
not use steel wool on stainless; bits will get into steel and cause
rust spots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am building an addition, and my builder says I don't need a
vapor barrier with insulation. Is that so? I have never heard of
that.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN QUARTARONE, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No, it is not so. Every wall, ceiling and floor needs a vapor
barrier with the insulation. That is why insulation makers put
kraft paper (a vapor barrier) on one side of fiberglass insulation.
A vapor barrier should always face the heated part of the house.
</P>
<P>
   While insulation does insulate by reducing the loss of heat
through it to the outdoors, that's only half the job. A vapor
barrier is an air stop, which stops the passage of air to the
outdoors, therefore the passage of heat.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is suggested not to put a vapor barrier on the
attic floor; contractors were afraid a vapor barrier there would
seal the house up, allowing the buildup of pollution (mostly water
vapor) in the house. That could happen in a complete new house, but
it is impossible to seal up an existing house enough to cause
pollution buildup. As for the addition, this is only part of the
house, and while it may be very tight, the rest of the house is as
loose as a goose, preventing buildup of pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
