<HEADLINE>
STUDY BACKS USE OF HEARTS FROM DONORS WITH HEPATITIS C 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Survival rates for patients who received heart
transplants from people infected with hepatitis C are not much
different than for similar patients who got uninfected hearts,
according to two studies.
</P>
<P>
   The findings lend support to the trend of using such organs in
the face of a nationwide shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become more pressing as the number of organs known
to be infected with hepatitis C grows. In Alabama, for instance, an
estimated 10 percent of donated hearts test positive for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The research, presented this week at the International Society
for Heart and Lung Transplantation in San Francisco, looked at
survival rates averaging about two years after the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   One study also found the vast majority of the 40 patients who
got the infected hearts later showed evidence of the hepatitis C
virus in their bodies. Seven came down with hepatitis and one later
died of the disease, said Cedric Sheffield, a transplant surgeon at
the Cleveland Clinic and co-author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The results raise concerns among some doctors, who worry that
infecting more people with hepatitis C _ even if their lives are
saved in the process _ provides more chances for it to spread.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 percent of the U.S. population is believed to carry the
virus, which was discovered in 1989 and is transmitted by blood and
sometimes by sexual activity. The infection rate is much higher
among some groups, like IV-drug users.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers can be symptom-free for years, but many develop serious
liver damage. The only available treatments work in a small
percentage of patients, are very expensive and have serious side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1991, surgeons at the Cleveland Clinic began
offering some of the sickest patients _ expected to live only days
or weeks _ the chance to get a hepatitis C-infected heart in order
to replace their failing hearts faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``These patients are doing very poorly,'' said Nicholas G.
Smedira, transplant surgeon at the Cleveland Clinic and co-author
of the study. ``You have a great heart that matches their blood
type, you use it. You accept the immediate gain _ living _ for the
potential complication later on.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Cleveland Clinic, for instance, about 30 percent of the
people waiting for hearts die before they can get one, Smedira
said.
</P>
<P>
   While donation rates have risen slightly in the past few years,
air bags and seat belt laws have kept fewer people from dying in
car accidents, one of the chief sources of donated organs, said
James Kirklin, a transplant surgeon at the University of Alabama at
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin co-authored a study to be presented Saturday that looked
at data collected from more than 40 transplant centers. It found
that just 64 out of 3,084 hearts transplanted from 1993 to 1997
were from hepatitis C infected donors.
</P>
<P>
   The survival rate of those patients mirrored that of patients
who were equally as sick at the time of the surgery, Kirklin said.
</P>
<P>
   The average follow-up was about two years, although some were
followed as long as 4 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term studies are needed to show how hepatitis progresses
in recipients. It is not known whether the anti-rejection drugs
patients must take will make them more susceptible in years to come
to the effects of the virus, Kirklin said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the new data on survival will encourage more
surgeons to use hearts infected with hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is increasing belief that depending on how sick
your patient is, the profound shortage of organ donors suggests
that in patients whom you believe their probability of survival is
very low, that it's probably totally justified to use hepatitis C
positive donor,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
