<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENCH-CULTURE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSIDE LOOK AT OUTSIDERS' CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the murders this week of 12 students and a teacher at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., by two classmates who
later turned their guns on themselves, pop culture again finds
itself on the hot seat of harsh scrutiny. That the apparent gunmen,
Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, were fans of goth music and
violent video games has led to the usual frenzied search among song
lyrics, Web sites, and popular movies and games for answers as to
the origins of this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is nothing new. In the 1950s, such films as
``Blackboard Jungle'' and ``Rebel Without a Cause'' were blamed for
encouraging teen delinquency. A decade later, some believed the
Beatles' so-called ``White Album'' _ in particular the songs,
``Helter Skelter,'' ``Piggies,'' and ``Revolution'' _ motivated
Charles Manson and his ragged ``family'' to commit the
Tate-LaBianca murders in Los Angeles in 1969. More recently,
hard-core and gangsta rap have been targeted as a frequent cause of
violence among youth.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Littleton tragedy, the media has latched onto such
names as Marilyn Manson, Rob Zombie, Doom, KMFDM, and ``The
Basketball Diaries,'' presenting them as portholes into the minds
of these teenage murderers. It has revealed a pop-culture lexicon
familiar to youth but opaque to most. The following offers a brief
background on the most often-heard terms in the wake of this latest
school shooting:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROWTH OF GOTH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goth was one of the numerous subcultures that formed in England
in the wake of the punk-rock movement of the mid to late 1970s. As
is the case with many British music-and-fashion waves, it spread to
the United States a bit later and took hold here in the early
1980s. Despite having the earmarks of being a quick fad, goth
turned out to have long legs, remaining a force today. Longtime
English goth icon Nick Cave told the Globe last year: Goths ``are
the most enduring and brave of the (subcultures). There's something
sweet about that. When the big bomb goes off, all that's going to
survive are goths and cockroaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Favored goth bands of the day included Siouxie and the Banshees
_ singer Siouxie Sioux was held up as queen of the goths _ the
Cure, Joy Division, Bauhaus, and Depeche Mode. Goth musical culture
spills over into the more aggressive industrial rock genre, where
Marilyn Manson, KMFDM, and Ministry roam.
</P>
<P>
   The music goths listened to tended to employ minor chords and
take a downbeat worldview, expressing futility, frustration, and
despair. Bauhaus wrote ``Burning From the Inside,'' Joy Division
wrote ``Love Will Tear Us Apart.'' Fittingly, performers and
audiences dressed in black, with some folks sporting garish
eyeliner and powdered faces. The idea was to sport an unhealthy
looking pallor. Hair: dyed jet black. As with many of the post-punk
subcultures, one of the prime ideas was, and remains, to define
yourself as an outsider or outcast, yet bond with others who felt
similarly. If goths were angry, they tended to turn their anger
inward, maintaining an outward demeanor of passivity, taking solace
in shared gloom.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, ``goths are beautiful,'' Bauhaus singer Peter
Murphy told the Globe last year, citing ``a vast depth of
subcultural, aesthetic, and poetic ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Littleton shooting, one goth posted a message on a Web
site called www.gothmafia.com. It read: ``The `gothic influence'
does not kill. White supremacy, violence, and stupidity are not
part of the `gothic culture.' I am angry and saddened by what those
idiots . . . did. I am outraged at the scapegoating of the goth and
industrial scenes . . . The universal truth that individuals can be
complete losers on their own without a clique to blame has
obviously not occurred to some people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, the Cambridge club Man Ray has been the
nexus of goth culture, Thursday through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   --JIM SULLIVAN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOOM AND QUAKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both these games were created by Texas-based id Software,
pioneers of first-person, shoot-'em-ups for the PC generation. In
1991, the company, founded by a handful of 20-something gamers and
tech-heads, created Wolfenstein 3-D for computers. The game was
instantly hailed for its three-dimensional, point-of-view design:
The player was the gun whose barrel maneuvered through each level.
It was also the first game with a major body count, with corpses
still strewn about long after they'd been shot. That game featured
a captured Allied soldier trying to escape from a prison filled
with gun-toting Nazis. Each level was adorned with swastikas and
renderings of Adolph Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, id had unveiled the futuristic Doom, which was
bolstered by technological advances and realistic graphics,
including eviscerated prisoners and rooms filled with bloody
skulls. Doom was a major leap in gaming, while maintaining the main
premise _ shoot anything that moves. That included other soldiers
and fireball-throwing imps. It also eliminated a traditional
scoreboard, tallying the percentage of kills at the end of each
level.
</P>
<P>
   But the game, which won several major awards from the leading
computer magazines, was also notably more violent. Everything was
dispatched in a splash of simulated blood and gore. A year later,
Doom II: Hell on Earth was released, and proved as popular as its
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   When Quake hit stores in 1996, it was unlike anything before.
Players could jump and swim through various environments. The
jaw-dropping design was so detailed that fired rockets left a trail
of light and smoke while traveling through a darkened hallway. It
also upped the ante with an extensive multiplayer mode that allowed
gamers, through the use of a modem, to compete against other
players worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In Quake, there were far more things to kill, among them armored
knights, chainsaw-wielding ogres, piranhas known as rotfish, and
razor-clawed fiends. Everything about the game was bigger, faster _
and a lot bloodier. There was a variety of ways to kill: from brass
knuckles to nail guns, from pump-action shotguns to grenade
launchers. Again, the level of violence and gore increased
significantly. Heads could be blown off, and various baddies could
be splattered in a number of ways depending on firepower. For
instance, a shotgun used at close range inflicted far more damage
and spewed more viscera than one used from a greater distance. It
was followed in 1997 by Quake II. Now Quake III is under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--RENEE GRAHAM
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sound of metal
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here was the scene outside last November before the rock group
Marilyn Manson played its concert in Lowell, Mass. Hundreds of kids
were milling about, many dressed in black, multiply pierced, highly
made up _ generally sporting the provocative goth look. And here
was the word from the police on-site: ``Well-behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is usually the case. A concert may have violent themes _
and you can go back to Alice Cooper of the early 1970s for this _
but it's all part of rock theater, at its best serving a cathartic
need for its intended audience, the young and rebellious, those in
need of a quasi-verboten thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Manson _ both a band and the adopted name of Brian
Warner, the band's leader _ came up from Florida in the mid-1990s
and was nurtured by Trent Reznor of Nine Inch Nails, America's most
popular industrial rock band. The industrial genre, begun in the
late 1970s in England with bands such as Throbbing Gristle and in
Germany with Einsturzende Neubauten, came to prominence in the
United States via Chicago's Ministry in the late-1980s and, shortly
after, Nine Inch Nails. Featured sounds: piston-pounding rhythms,
barking vocals, anti-authoritarian worldview, heaping doses of
angst and anger, distorted synthesizers or guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Marilyn Manson band of today has gone in an
androgynous glam-rock direction, its 1996 breakthrough album,
``Antichrist Superstar,'' was full of rants such as ``let's kill
everyone and let God sort 'em out'' (``Irresponsible Hate Anthem'')
and ``I hate it all and I have no choice but to/I'll make everyone
pay and you'll see'' (``Man That You Fear'').
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
