<HEADER>
A0565 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRENCH-CULTURE-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     04-23 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENCH-CULTURE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... You Fear'').  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manson told the Globe that's ``how I define the more nihilistic,
hopeless elements of my personality. It's when you've finally given
up on the world and only want to see its destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the nihilistic premise behind much of what is called
death metal, a subset of heavy metal. You can trace its roots back
to Black Sabbath and up through Slayer, Metallica. A slew of bands
such as Deicide, Rob Zombie, KMFDM, Morbid Angel, and Napalm Death
employ helter-skelter tempos, thunderous drums and guitar, spewing
violent tales of death and destruction, satanism and damnation.
Optimistic, it's not; an outlet it is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--JIM SULLIVAN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Political rock
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With their German backgrounds and violent-rich lyrics, KMFDM and
Rammstein are often crowded into the neo-Nazi category by critics.
Both groups beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``KMFDM are an art form not a political party,'' founder Sascha
Konietzko said in a statement loaded onto the KMFDM Web site
(www.KMFDM.com) on April 21. ``From the beginning our music has
been a statement against war, oppression, fascism, and violence
against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Although bound together by Littleton, the two groups come from
opposite ends of the musical spectrum. Rammstein was started in
Germany in 1995. The group is known for its rhythmic metal sound.
KMFDM, an industrial band known for fast beats and electronic
sounds, began in Paris in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   While KMFDM has influenced bands as mainstream as U2, it never
reached pop superstardom. The song ``Blitzkrieg'' includes the
lyrics: ``Leatherclad warriors/Fighting tolerant fools/Mutilation
of values/Where ignorance rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Rammstein turned an unlikely German metal song called ``You
Hate'' into an MTV and radio staple last summer, thanks to an
action-packed video that stole liberally from the films ``The Usual
Suspects'' and ``Reservoir Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, American fans had picked up more than
200,000 copies of Rammstein's album, ``Longing.'' Buyers heard
brutal songs like ``Jealousy,'' which begins: ``Am I pretty/Then
cut me in the face/Am I stronger/Break my neck in disgrace/Am I
smarter/Kill me and eat my brain.'' And even the less aggressive
tunes had an edge since they're sung in Rammstein's guttural,
consonant-rich native language.
</P>
<P>
   But the band, whose stage shows are famous for their eye-popping
pyrotechnics, states on its Web site: ``We only show violence
during our gigs and we make it the subject of our lyrics. But we
definitely refuse to practice violence . . .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--VANESSA JONES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hate sites
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hate proliferates in cyberspace, where fringe groups of any
persuasion can spread their messages quickly and inexpensively.
Even the most rudimentary search can lead to propaganda pages
posted by neo-Nazis, white supremacists, Holocaust deniers, and
bigots of every stripe. Experts say there are some 250
sophisticated hate sites on-line, plus more than a thousand
additional sites run by militia and terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, recipes for explosive devices are all over the
Net, notably in excerpts from ``The Anarchist Cookbook'' or a page
called the Racial Holy War Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether the gunmen in Littleton, Colo., pulled
bomb recipes off the Internet. But it is clear that one of the
killers, Eric Harris, posted violent material on his America Online
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldman, founder of the activist group, Hatewatch.org of
Cambridge, Mass., said he had received material from Harris's Web
site before the tragedy, but he dismissed it as the ramblings of an
alienated teenager. ``You have to distinguish between individuals
who are lured into hate groups because they are alienated and angry
and individuals who are ideologically committed to national
socialism or white supremacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is said to have frequented a site called the Floating
Pancreas, an anarchistic site emblazoned with grinning skulls. It
features a page called Nazi DiscOrama, which asks, ``Care to cut
the rug with Hitler?'' and features a collage of Hitler's face,
arranged Andy Warhol-style.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Abraham Cooper, associate dean of the Simon Wiesenthal
Center in Los Angeles, said, ``The subculture of hate on-line gives
deep resonance to and magnifies feelings of alienation and anger.''
</P>
<P>
   But while hate is just a mouse click away in cyberspace, the
Internet can also be a powerful teaching tool. Scores of civil
rights groups have created their own sites as an antidote to hate
sites. ``People and parents have to understand that what frightens
them about the Net also _ and I hate the term _ empowers them,''
said Goldman. ``It's a powerful tool to sit down with your child
and talk about hate groups in a contextualized situation. Kids need
to know what the moral parameters are, and you don't do that by
putting in V-chips and blocking software. You need to arm your kids
with information, and that requires sitting down, taking that extra
step, and looking at this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--PATTI HARTIGAN &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Movie violence
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural Born Killers'' and ``The Basketball Diaries'' don't
have much in common. One's a major Hollywood film about a couple on
a violent rampage. The other's a small independent movie about poet
and singer Jim Carroll's drug-addled teenage years.
</P>
<P>
   But the two films have found common ground in the courts.
Lawsuits say the makers of both movies drove kids to violence. And
after the Littleton tragedy, ``Heathers'' and ``The Matrix'' may
soon be added to the list.
</P>
<P>
   The stylish ``Matrix'' shows Keanu Reeves and company blowing
away the enemy in hip black shades and chic leather jackets. That's
just how the teens, clad in trench coats, looked to at least one
terrified witness as the pair bombed and shot their way through
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Since the so-called ``Trench Coat Mafia'' members used bombs to
hurt their victims, people are pointing to the 1989 cult classic
``Heathers'' as a latter-day inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Violence and film are not exactly distant cousins. ``Clockwork
Orange,'' ``The Deer Hunter,'' and ``Money Train'' have had scenes
that reportedly spawned copycat crimes. ``The Deer Hunter'' was
responsible for Russian roulette deaths; ``Money Train'' inspired
people to ignite token booth clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the parents of three students killed in a high school
shooting spree in Kentucky announced they were suing Time Warner,
New Line Cinema, and Island Pictures among others. They say the boy
responsible for the carnage, Michael Carneal, was inspired by a
scene in the 1995 film ``The Basketball Diaries.'' In a dream
sequence in that movie, a trench-coat-clad Leonardo DiCaprio goes
on a shooting spree in a school.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of freedom of speech and First Amendment rights won't
shield filmmakers from the legal onslaught. Last month, the Supreme
Court decided to allow the ``Natural Born Killers,'' case, in which
a couple shot a woman after watching the film, to move forward. The
lawsuit says the film intended to make viewers commit a crime after
watching the movie.
</P>
<P>
   --VANESSA E. JONES &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
