<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ISSUES-BOS &LR;      04-23 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AT 50: EX-LEADERS SEE LIMITS TO NEW ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, Mass. _ In a sunny office on the campus of Tufts
University this week, two white-haired former generals were
reminiscing about the war that never happened _ and the one that
did.
</P>
<P>
   Each had been supreme commander of NATO in Europe, an elite club
of US Army generals that began with Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1950.
Under their authority was an arsenal of tanks, planes, and infantry
built for one purpose: to defend the democracies west of the Iron
Curtain even if it meant a nuclear battle that would have laid
waste to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   NATO never fought that war. Its great adversary, the Soviet
Union, broke up in 1991. And now in the Balkans, the old soldiers
agreed, NATO is in a fight unlike any they could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Allied Force ``has taken me into a new era,'' said
Andrew Goodpaster, who headed NATO from 1969 to 1975 and is now a
fellow at the Eisenhower World Affairs Institute in Washington.
``The experience we are having in Kosovo requires us to do some
very serious thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are very lucky that NATO is hanging together,''
said John R. Galvin, who served as NATO commander from 1987 to 1992
and is now dean of Tufts' Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.
Galvin had invited Goodpaster to Tufts on Tuesday to address
graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   As leaders of the 19-member alliance mark its half-century
anniversary, those two issues _ the radical new role NATO has
assumed in the Balkans and the present and future stability of a
group of nations as dissimilar as Iceland and Hungary, as
suspicious of one another as Greece and Turkey _ will surely
dominate discussion.
</P>
<P>
   And that could be a big problem, said Ashton B. Carter, who was
assistant secretary of defense for international security during
President Clinton's first term and is now a professor at Harvard's
John F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the world around us contains its Kosovos, we
shouldn't be fooled into thinking that is the most important
security priority'' for NATO, said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter lists Kosovo as a ``C priority.'' His A-list includes
threats like the one the Soviet Union once posed. Though there is
not a Soviet-style foe lurking in the world right now, he said,
NATO should always be focused on that kind of problem. Among its
concerns, he said, should be preventing Russia from collapsing and
becoming desperate and militaristic; managing the relationship with
China as it grows into a global power; guarding against the spread
of nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons; and countering
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's B-level priority, he said, should be maintaining its
ability to fight two major wars in different parts of the world.
Only after taking care of those concerns, he added, should the
Balkans be on the alliance's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But the Balkan crisis is too big right now to be set to the
side, he acknowledged, worrying that ``the preoccupation with
Bosnia and Kosovo will slow the process of strategic adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's Washington summit was originally designed to make
that very adjustment. Then came Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Allied Force, the first official engagement that NATO
has fought in its 50 years, is precedent-setting on many counts,
analysists say. It is, for instance, a military venture that does
not strictly defend the territory of NATO members, as outlined in
the alliance's charter. In addition, unlike the 1995 NATO bombing
campaign in Bosnia, Allied Force does not have explicit United
Nations approval. And while it is motivated by humanitarian
concerns, it is a direct, uninvited intervention in the affairs of
a sovereign nation _ Yugoslavia _ a step the US and its allies have
been loathe to take until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has phenomenally broad implications,'' said Senator
Joseph R. Biden, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee. ``But if NATO does not stand for putting an
end to violence and `ethnic cleansing' in Kosovo, then what in the
hell do we stand for?''
</P>
<P>
   Most strategic analysts in the United States and Europe agree
that the US and its allies were right to try to stop the
persecution of Kosovo Albanians by the forces of Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic. Where they differ is on whether NATO should
have been the vehicle, and bombing the means.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration has expressed no doubts. In
Yugoslavia, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in a recent
speech, ``NATO is responding to a real post-Cold War threat to its
interests and values.''
</P>
<P>
   Interests and values, however, are not the same as security,
which is what NATO was narrowly formed to defend when allied
nations signed the North Atlantic Treaty in Washington on April 4,
1949 _ a few short months after the Berlin airlift and as eastern
European nations were falling under communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NATO was stretching its charter even before the Soviet
Union collapsed and the Cold War ended. In the Gulf War, for
instance, Galvin led the alliance's efforts, and he now calls the
conflict an out-of-area NATO action disguised as a multinational
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you did not mention that `NATO forces' were
involved _ it had to be `the forces of NATO nations' _ it was OK,''
said Galvin. ``But it was basically a NATO operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even France, which was not then a member of NATO's military
command, joined the effort, allowing US B-52s to operate from
French bases. The reason NATO acted was not that the territory of a
member nation was in jeopardy, but because the West's oil supplies
were threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Like all NATO operations, Desert Storm was carried largely by
the US, which enjoys overwhelming military superiority in the
alliance and the world. But if NATO is to survive, says Britain's
defense secretary, George Robertson, its European members will have
to pick up more of the burden from the US. This will require
modernization of European armies and navies and the acquisition of
the sort of airlift capability that the US alone now has. Airlift
is what will allow NATO forces to move into areas beyond its
traditional European neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But where to draw the line? Biden, for instance, opposes using
NATO to intervene in ethnic wars in Africa or Asia, for fear of
getting stretched too thin. Like many members of the foreign-policy
establishment, he would give that job to various ``coalitions of
the willing'' depending on the nature of a crisis and the part of
the world in which it occurs.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO expands, it will be under ever more strain in deciding
where and when to act militarily. Even before it grew from 16 to 19
members, its decision-making was hampered by a need for the North
Atlantic Council, the alliance's governing body, to make unanimous
decisions. Unanimity will become ever more difficult to achieve,
said Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving such questions will be essential and will be part of
the Washington summit's business this weekend. But, Goodpaster
said, in all the brainstorming it is important to remember that
NATO was successful in its original mission. There was no war with
the USSR _ not that the world didn't come close during the Cuban
missile crisis and other moments over the past half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so tense back then that the danger was that somebody in
our army or theirs would think he had to do something,'' said
Goodpaster, recalling the bristling forces facing off in Europe
during the Cold War. ``That would have set everything loose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
