<HEADLINE>
LOGROLLING: A SIGN OF THE TIMES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend writes: ``You might be interested to learn that The New
York Times Sunday book review killed a review of Natalie Angier's
book, `Woman: An Intimate Geography,' written by Helena Cronin,
because the editors considered it `too negative.' Cronin, a
well-known evolutionary biologist, found the author's grip of the
facts shaky and her position unsupported. Angier, as you may know,
is a star reporter at the Times. `Woman' was reviewed in the daily
New York Times by Marilyn Yalom, author of `A History of the
Breast,' a book Angier herself reviewed glowingly in a 1997 Times
Sunday book review.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that we didn't run Cronin's review,'' Sunday book
editor Chip McGrath told me, ``although `too negative' would be her
words, not mine. I didn't like the tone of the review _ I thought
it was too snarky, which is partly the difference between British
reviewing (Cronin teaches at the London School of Economics) and
American reviewing. And I thought the review failed to address the
whole range of the book. This happens.'' McGrath knows full well
that he will be accused of rolling over for a colleague, which he
denies. ``There's no tradition here of writing positive reviews of
books by Times authors.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronin, whose study ``The Ant and the Peacock'' was selected as
one of the nine best books of 1992 by the Times editors, doesn't
want to discuss the dust-up. But she's happy to talk about Angier's
book, published by Houghton Mifflin. ``It's totally idiotic,'' she
says. ``She uses phrases like `the vagina as a model for the
universe itself.' Then she has these menstrual epiphanies you find
in modern feminist literature _ you know, how we must all dance in
a circle around a Tampax. She was so wrong-headed in the areas
where I knew the science that, even if there were areas where she
might have been correct, I could no longer trust her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the daily review, here is Stanford professor Yalom
swooning over ``Woman'': ``. . . dazzling . . . Its upbeat message
_ that women are far stronger, more sexual, aggressive and adaptive
than usually given credit for _ is supported by rigorous scientific
underpinnings.'' In 1997, Angier called Yalom's breast work ``a
fascinating cultural, political and artistic history of our most
symbolically freighted body part . . . Yalom shows how the breast
dialectic has been in full swing for centuries now,'' etc. etc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
At Random
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A certain mystery attends the future of Edmund Morris's ``Dutch:
A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' to be published this fall by Random
House. Fourteen years in the making, the book was yanked from
Random's fall list last year, so that the perfectionist Morris
could put finishing touches on the work.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, author of a widely hailed, two-volume biography of
Theodore Roosevelt, is a terrific writer. But some unsettling
question marks are hanging over the Reagan book. A year and a half
ago, Random House editor Robert Loomis told C-Span that Morris has
``a new idea about how to write this book _ which I don't want to
talk about right now _ which is controversial, but it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he spent a great deal of time with Reagan and
members of his family, the Kenya-born Morris has complained that he
had difficulty fathoming the former president's personality. So, to
tell ``Dutch,'' he assumes the guise of a fictional narrator, one
of the 70-odd people Reagan saved as a young lifeguard. Morris's
fans say the unusual device works well. But even they question
whether the unorthodox narrative will translate into the
mass-market success Random is hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a subject Random House wants to discuss. The fate of
the all-important first serial rights _ the right to print an
excerpt from the forthcoming book _ is likewise not entirely clear.
A previously reported commitment from Newsweek turns out to have
been a verbal agreement between the magazine's late editor, Maynard
Parker, and a deceased Random House executive. No contract has been
signed. A Newsweek spokesman says the magazine still plans to
publish a portion of the Morris book. That will have to appear
after a ``60 Minutes'' feature on Morris and Reagan, which has yet
to be scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
