<HEADLINE>
`RELAX. . .' IT'S ABOUT FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RELAX. . .IT`S JUST SEX 
Written and directed by: P.J. Castellaneta 
Starring: Mitchell Anderson, Jennifer Tilly, T.C. Carson, Lori
Petty, Cynda Williams, Eddie Garcia 
Running time; 106 minutes 
Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Relax. . .It's Just Sex'' is a big, bouncing puppy of a movie,
an energetic crowd-pleaser so long as the crowd includes the more
liberal-minded among us. Set in present-day Los Angeles, it's an
often-funny, sexually frank look at the pursuit of love and
happiness among a racially and sexually inclusive group of friends.
Though the film gets a little light-headed at times atop its
soapbox, there are some whipsmart observations about modern
romance, sexual identity and, most of all, friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Vincey (Mitchell Anderson) is a playwright who just can't write
a happy ending for his own love life. He's had a series of
boyfriends and bedmates, but no one he's ever been able to call Mr.
Right. He laments to his galpal, Tara (Jennifer Tilly, whose usual
over-the-top style actually works here) that he's ready to fall in
love with a great guy, ``move in together, get a dog, pick out
china patterns, get Lakers' season tickets, and live happily ever
after.'` But Tara has her doubts. She describes Vincey as a
``Christmas Eve-type person. You can never enjoy the presents once
they're open; as soon as you realize there's a living, breathing
person behind the image, you lose interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of all this, Tara's trying to conceive a child
with her boyfriend Gus (Timothy Paul Perez), who's beginning to see
domestic life as an unwieldy ball-and-chain. Then there's Gus's
brother Javi (Eddie Garcia), recently diagnosed as HIV-positive,
who begins a relationship with Buzz (T.C. Carson), an artist with
outspoken views on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Those are only half of the main characters. There's Sarina
(Cynda Williams) and Megan (Serena Scott Thomas), a lesbian couple,
whose nine-year relationship implodes when Megan takes up with a
man, who also happens to be Sarina's second cousin, Jered (Billy
Wirth). Sarina, meanwhile, seeks solace in the arms of her friend,
Robin (Lori Petty), who's had a crush on her for years. Then
there's Dwight (Gibbs Toldsdorf) and Diego (Chris Cleveland), a
too-beautiful, too-happy couple both admired and envied by their
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because writer-director P.J. Castellaneta had so many
witty things to say _ there's an great zinger comparing delayed
sexual gratification to Andrew Lloyd Webber shows _ he had to
create enough characters for all those snappy lines. Still, since
most of the characters are so deftly drawn, it's hard to imagine
who Castellaneta might have cut. Even the smaller roles are
memorable, such as Susan Tyrell as Megan's hilariously irate
mother, who simply can't abide her lesbian daughter dating a man.
(``What are we going to say to our friends in PFLAG?'' she seethes,
referring to the support organization, Parents and Friends of
Lesbians and Gays.)
</P>
<P>
   Castellaneta also kitchen-sinks his script, and the film is
longer than it needs to be. There's an awful lot to keep track of
here, including a violent gay bashing which takes a shocking,
unexpected turn. That entire scene is so horrific, it seems out of
place with the film's overall lighter tone. It's as though
Castellaneta wanted something heavy to anchor his frothy film, but
it almost sinks it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's awfully hard to quibble with a film with so many
laugh-out-loud moments, and one which isn't afraid to celebrate
friendships between diverse people. All that, and Castellaneta
winningly presents characters rarely seen on screen _ lipstick
lesbians without ice picks, gay men who love sports, black lesbians
and gays beyond tokenism, and what certainly must be a film first _
born-again Chrsitan gym queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
