<HEADLINE>
SPADE LOST WITHOUT FARLEY IN `LOST &AMP; FOUND' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LOST &AMP; FOUND 
Directed by: Jeff Pollack 
Screenplay by: J.B. Cook, Marc Meeks, David Spade 
Starring: David Spade, Sophie Marceau, Patrick Bruel, Artie Lange,
Mitchell Whitfield, Martin Sheen 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (crude and sex-related humor, brief nudity and
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe David Spade can carry a movie without the late Chris
Farley, but you can't prove it by ``Lost &AMP; Found.'' It's a lame
romantic comedy that makes the mistake of inviting comparisons to
``There's Something About Mary.'' Like that film, it puts a dog
through a lot of mayhem and lumbers through a retirement community
full of unfunny senior-citizen sight gags. Rich, but only in dog
droppings, it has the crudeness of last summer's gross-out hit, but
not nearly the laughs or the offsetting sweetness of Cameron Diaz.
In her first Hollywood comedy, French actress Sophie Marceau is
stuck with a lot of unbecoming pouting as a Frenchwoman in LA,
Lila, who not only can't find a job as a cellist, but can't find
her little terrier either.
</P>
<P>
   The reason she can't find the dog is that Spade's restaurateur,
Dylan, has it hidden in his apartment. He dognapped it, and
intended to return it, pretending he had found it. The idea was to
score points with his pretty neighbor. But while in his apartment,
the dog swallows an expensive anniversary ring Dylan's partner has
given him to hold. So Dylan, a glib but increasingly nervous
schemer, must keep the dog until it passes the ring. That's about
it as far as story, except that Lila's full-of-himself ex-fiance
shows up from Paris to provide romantic competition and shoot down
the sincere but inept wooer Dylan. You will be thinking that there
isn't enough here for a single episode of Spade's TV series, ``Just
Shoot Me,'' much less for a full-length movie. You will be right.
</P>
<P>
   Spade's needling wiseguy persona is softened in a few scenes
when he encourages Marceau's jangly but professionally unassertive
cellist. He's funnier in the smart-mouth stuff on which his
reputation rests, infrequent as the laughs are here. The others
labor valiantly, but the vapid material defeats them. Mitchell
Whitfield is the most sympathetic character as the partner who
stays in the restaurant actually doing all the work, and roly-poly
Artie Lange is the performer with whom one sympathizes the most.
Obviously cast to fill the Farley void, he's sweet where Farley was
wild, even in the gross-out scenes to which he is mostly relegated
as they flit from a strip poker game with senior citizens to a room
filled with all the dog excrement you could hope for. ``Lost &AMP;
Found'' is more lost than found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
