<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-KINKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSLET'S WINSOME WAYS REIGN IN `KINKY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HIDEOUS KINKY 
Directed by: Gillies MacKinnon 
Screenplay by: Billy MacKinnon (novel: Esther Freud) 
Starring: Kate Winslet, Bella Riza, Carrie Mullan, Said Taghmaoui 
Running time: 99 minutes 
Rated: R (some sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hideous Kinky'' is neither hideous nor kinky. It's a modest
but unexpectedly affecting autobiography of a daughter recalling
her English hippie mother's spiritual quest in Morocco and Algeria
in 1972 with her and her sister in tow. The film could easily have
degenerated into a caricature of hippies or a cruel shattering of a
naive young woman's illusions. The reason it gets to us is that it
was made with affection and, more important, respect for the
sincerity of the young mother's motives and the gentleness and
generosity she found in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The film, in short, is a stereotype-free and winningly generous
evocation of a sympathetic screenful of characters. It's a
villain-free film, too. The closest it comes to one is the girls'
absent poet father, who dumped their mother in London, where he has
remained with a new woman and new children. He takes an
out-of-sight, out-of-mind approach, to judge by the infrequency and
meagerness of the checks he mails to Marrakech. While the film
empathizes with Kate Winslet's young mother, Julia, tired of gray,
dreary England and searching for something better, it's open-eyed,
as she is not, about what's happening to them.
</P>
<P>
   It pulls no punches about the fact that the door to
soul-expanding adventures has been pretty much slammed shut by
their poverty. The only skill they possess is making cloth dolls.
But the dolls don't fetch much in the bustling street market, and
it's corrosive waiting around for the irregular checks to arrive.
Things finally take an upturn when Julia is attracted to a hunky
street acrobat, Said Taghmaoui's Bilal. He's sweet and sexy and
he's more than willing to serve as the surrogate father the girls
need. But Bella Riza's elder 8-year-old daughter, Bea, sees a few
drawbacks that her more naive mother does not.
</P>
<P>
   When they journey back to Bilal's village, Bea sees, as her
mother does not, that Bilal already has a wife there. She has
already picked up on the fact that he's a shady character known to
the police. When he takes off and Julia decides to embrace the life
of a Sufi mystic in Algeria, Bea voices a desire to be left behind
in the care of a European couple to attend school and obtain the
structure and normality she craves. The younger sister, Carrie
Mullan's 6-year-old Lucy, doesn't care what happens as long as
she's with her mom. But the spiritual life proves more problematic
than Julia anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   So is the reunion with Bea. The characterizations are on the
superficial side, but Winslet is appealing as a woman whose heart
is in the right place even if she hasn't thought things through.
Taghmaoui brings both softness and dazzle to the role of the warm
but wayward acrobat who's shocked to learn that a European can be
poor. Riza and Mullan are perfect as the girls whose word games
give the film its title. Certainly, it serves up Morocco in a heady
swirl of images that show the appeal of the place for Westerners in
the '60s and '70s. It doesn't even make fun of its resident hippies
as the soundtrack gracefully finds room amid its Sufi trance music
and North African drumming for Jefferson Airplane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
