<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PUSHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPOINTING `PUSHING TIN' IS PLANE SPEAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
PUSHING TIN 
Directed by: Mike Newell 
Screenplay by: Glen and Les Charles 
Starring: John Cusack, Billy Bob Thornton, Cate Blanchett, Angelina
Jolie, Jake Weber, Vicki Lewis, Kurt Fuller, Matt Ross 
Playing at: Copley Place; suburbs 
Running time: 123 minutes 
Rated: R (language and a scene of sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Newell's ``Pushing Tin'' charts some slightly new territory
in the movies-about-alpha-males sweepstakes. And it's got some
flavorful acting. But it doesn't take us all the way into the
high-pressure world of metropolitan New York air-traffic
controllers as strongly or as affectingly as Newell's ``Donnie
Brasco'' took us into the trenches with low-level Mafia soldiers.
Closer in spirit to one of Newell's earlier hits, it could be
thought of as two weddings and what everyone hopes won't be
hundreds of funerals as the mostly male controllers reach for the
caffeine and sort out the moving blips made by the incoming planes
on the control center's busy radar screens.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not without its share of midair near misses,
``Pushing Tin'' (the controllers' way of referring to their
stressful central traffic management of La Guardia, Kennedy, and
Newark airports) wisely avoids the kind of melodramatic strokes
that made all those '70s disaster movies so memorably bad. It
spends most of its time focusing on the domestic embroilments of
two rival controllers, both good at their jobs, but differing
widely in style: John Cusack's hyper Nick Falzone and Billy Bob
Thornton's challenging newcomer, a half-Irish, half-Choctaw Indian
named Russell, whose laid-back cool threatens Nick. In no time,
they're all but pawing the ground and lowering their heads to lock
horns. Or at least Nick is.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what galls Nick is Russell's utter absence of even the
smallest hint of trying too hard. In focusing on their rivalry, or
at least the rivalry that Nick instigates, the film sacrifices what
could have been a more interestingly textured cross section of a
microcosm we don't often see and, especially if one is a frequent
flyer, probably don't want to. But the film pretty much comes down
to a Nick-Russell square-off that crosses the competitive line to
include each going after the other's wife. Cusack brings his usual
naive motormouthing to his pursuit of Russell's lonely and
intoxicated young spouse, played with lots of turquoise-and-silver
jewelry and even more sultriness by Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's Russell retaliates by putting a few moves on Nick's
wife, played in a realistic style poles apart from her young Queen
Elizabeth by the increasingly impressive and as of now amazingly
versatile Australian actress Cate Blanchett. On this occasion she
will absolutely convince you she's from Queens. She and Thornton,
as a loner whose self-containment and slow, deliberate tempo
advertise that he's not a native New Yorker, deliver the most
impressive acting chops here. But Cusack and Jolie are easy to
take. The film's shortfall hasn't to do with the acting, but with
the script's inability to successfully dramatize the fact-based
magazine article on which the film is based. It's amusing to think
of a roomful of understandably nervous people whose idea of a great
day on the job consists of boredom. But ``Pushing Tin'' runs out of
fuel, dramatically speaking, and can't bring them in for the
landing they need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
