<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSINA WINS ACT OF THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Aerosmith won a Grammy and performed on the Oscars
this year, but were humbled at the Kahlua Boston Music Awards
Thursday. They won a video award and singer Steven Tyler got his
obligatory nod for best male rock vocalist, but that was it.
Instead, the big winner was country singer Jo Dee Messina, who
waltzed off with three trophies, including the top prize for act of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of upsets, you've just witnessed one of the
biggest in the history of these awards. A country singer had never
even been nominated for act of the year, yet Jo Dee Messina _ the
little engine that could from rural Holliston _ blew past
Aerosmith, as well as Paula Cole, the Mighty Mighty Bosstones, and
Rob Zombie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked,'' admitted Candace Avery, director of the awards,
which took place at the sold-out Orpheum Theatre and featured
performances by Messina (a beautiful piano ballad, ``Even God Gets
the Blues,'' dedicated to the bereaved families in Littleton,
Colo.), Jonatha Brooke, Melissa Ferrick, Godsmack, Joey McIntyre,
Jude, Susan Tedeschi, Big Wreck, Martin Sexton, and Buffalo Tom
(playing as a trio because singer Bill Janovitz was off with his
wife, who was having a baby).
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, some people may question Messina's many wins _ after
all, these awards have always had a rock/pop slant in past years
(the winners are chosen by half industry vote, half public vote,
with ballots from Strawberries and the Boston Herald) _ but
Messina, for her part, was a gracious winner. And let's not forget
she has become the first country female to ever have three,
multiple-week, No. 1 country hits in a row. That's prime national
news, but to think she's become so big in country-deprived Boston
is a real shock. She's never headlined her own show here, though
she's on the George Strait stadium bill coming to Foxboro Stadium
next month and has twice been an opening act at the Tweeter Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past year has been phenomenal for me,'' Messina told the
crowd, which gave her a warm ovation. ``The year before was rough,
but radio . . . and mostly the fans have pulled me out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   New blood _ and Messina is still young enough to qualify _ was
rewarded handsomely. The rising star award went to the Push Stars,
a bright, Triple-A radio act that has a new album coming on Capitol
Records May 18. Fast-climbing hard-rockers Godsmack won debut album
of the year (for ``Godsmack''). Swiss transplants My Favorite
Relative won outstanding new rock band. Alt-poppers the Gravel Pit
won best club band. Susan Tedeschi was a well-deserved choice for
outstanding blues act. And lovably raucous Big D &AMP; the Kids Table
won top ska act and promptly gang-tackled each other on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   In general, these were the most professional local awards in
some time (MC Julie Barr kept things moving), right down to the
staging (a pop-art depiction of Y2K with tangled wires dangling
from a computer) and the overall sense of crowd harmony. And, yes,
a former New Kid won again _ Joey McIntyre for single of the year
(``Stay the Same''). He, too, was warmly received, compared to
years ago when the New Kids drew boos in a more divisive, more
strained era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
