<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DREAM-BOS &LR;      04-23 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DREAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING CREDIT TO THE INDEBTED AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FINANCING THE AMERICAN DREAM 
A Cultural History of Consumer Credit 
By Lendol Calder 
Princeton University Press, 377 pp., illustrated, $29.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lendol Calder has taken on quite a challenge: to find nice
things to say about consumer credit. From the New Testament (Owe no
man anything) to Shakespeare (Neither a borrower nor a lender be),
debt has acquired a rotten reputation. Borrowing money has been
blamed for causing economic misery, for forcing people to live
beyond their means and for destroying the long-held American
virtues of thrift and frugality.
</P>
<P>
   Calder has a simple answer for the critics of credit: You don't
know what you're talking about. In ``Financing the American
Dream,'' a surprisingly lively book about a potentially dreary
subject, Calder argues that debt is as American as apple pie and
that consumer borrowing has been an important engine of economic
growth. And he doesn't stop there. Rather than encouraging
profligate behavior, writes Calder, the installment borrowing we
use to buy cars and houses forces us ``to commit to regimens of
disciplined financial management.'' If we don't, the bank can take
away our cars and houses.
</P>
<P>
   Calder is at his best in exploding what he calls the myth of
lost economic virtue. You've heard the myth articulated by your
parents. ``You kids are in debt up to your ears. Back in our day if
we wanted something we saved up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so. The author cites reliable sources that put average debt
per household in America at $300 in 1858 and $880 by 1890. ``It is
often forgotten, but from Plymouth Rock to the present, American
dreams have usually required a lien on the future,'' says Calder.
More interesting still, the book points out that in every era,
people have bemoaned the rise in borrowing. In 1923, the New York
Times wrote that ``in other simpler days debt was a thing dreaded
as the worst of ogres.'' In 1956 journalist William Whyte said that
``thrift is now un-American.'' Apparently the age of economic
virtue is always 20 years before you showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer credit took a great leap forward with the rise of
installment borrowing. The sellers of farm equipment pioneered the
technique in the 19th century. Eventually the practice was taken up
by retailers of furniture, pianos, and sewing machines.
Installment's appeal was obvious. By letting consumers pay for
merchandise over time, borrowing made goods affordable that
otherwise would have been too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was an alternative. People could have saved up to buy
things. That's what Henry Ford thought they should do. The auto
magnate liked credit about as much as he liked Jews and blacks. In
the 1920s, when rival General Motors adopted installment borrowing,
Ford had a different idea. He created something like a Christmas
club. Potential buyers set up a schedule of payments and deposited
money each week with Ford dealers. When they had saved enough to
buy a car, the automobile was theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was a colossal failure. Consumers wanted their cars
first and payments later, not the other way around. Borrowing made
sense to Americans, even if it forced them to work ever harder to
keep up with the payments.
</P>
<P>
   In every era there has been a disconnect between the rhetoric
and reality of credit. Everyone from preachers to novelists has
denounced credit as the tool of the devil. In this century, credit
expansion has also been blamed on women, big spenders who allegedly
don't know how to control their impulses to buy. Yet in every era,
credit expands and the economy manages to grow. In the one period
when the economy shrank, the Great Depression, people borrowed less
rather than go deeper into debt. To Calder, that experience proved
that consumers were smarter than their critics appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financing the American Dream'' is not a page-turner. In spots,
Calder tells you more about the history of credit than you'd
probably care to know. But for a professor _ he teaches history at
Augustana College in Illinois _ Calder writes forcefully and
clearly. Occasionally he can be downright lyrical, with lines like,
``A river of red ink runs through American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Calder's story leaves off with the Depression. He doesn't tackle
credit cards or any of the modern techniques for lending money to
poor people. Still it isn't hard to imagine what he would say about
them. Credit will never be popular, Calder believes, but it will
always be an essential part of the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   You can also bet a borrowed dollar that some time in the future,
our free-spending kids, who don't know the true value of money,
will one day scold their children for spending money like drunken
sailors and relying too heavily on debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0590 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-KURDS-$ADV25-COX     04-23 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-KURDS-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAQI KURDS SEE YUGOSLAVIAN MIRROR, FROM REFUGEES TO 'SAFE
HAVEN'
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, the Kani Shaitan Refugee
Camp is about 15 miles west of the city of Suleimaniyah, a large
Kurdish city in northeastern Iraq.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., April 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANI SHAITAN REFUGEE CAMP, Iraqi Kurdistan _ They don't have
electricity or television in this camp between grassy mountains, so
they can't follow events in Kosovo. But, the Kurdish refugees
huddled around these tents and mud outhouses know all about death
and displacement -- at the hands of Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, Kurds are forced from their homes in Iraq and
trucked to this semi-autonomous area in northernmost Iraq. About
the size of Austria, it is protected now by U.S. air cover and has
been run for the last seven years by a provisional Kurdish
government.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations estimates that, since 1991, more than 150,000
Kurds have been forced to the Kurdish zone from homes in other
parts of Iraq. In this tent village of 103 families and the
hallways of the grimy, fetid and crumbling hotel where many others
end up for years, refugees tell of being jailed until they agree to
leave the country, then having an hour to pack and leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish leaders see an almost eerie similarity between their
peoples' plight and events in Kosovo. They say their current
``safe-haven'' in northern Iraq could provide a model for a
solution in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parallels are quite striking,'' said Shafiq Qazzaz(CQ), a
Kurdish cabinet minister in Iraqi Kurdistan. ``I have a satellite
television. I sit there and watch. It is mesmerizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish leaders favor the NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia's Serb
military forces -- just as fervently as Iraqi leaders have sided
with the Yugoslavian Serbs -- and say the world should not be cowed
by the scenes of refugees in flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end result is what's important,'' said Sami Abdel Rahman,
a top leader of the Kurdish Democratic Party in an interview this
month with Cox Newspapers. He expects the refugees to be returned
to Kosovo in a safe-haven arrangement similar to Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was NATO -- the U.S. and Britain -- that saved us,'' Rahman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Kosovars, Kurds throughout the region have sought their
independence for decades. In southeastern Turkey, a civil war has
killed 35,000 Turks and Kurds since 1984 with little intervention
from the West.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, drawn by Hussein's invasion of Kuwait, the West has
intervened. But, before it did, the Kurds already faced brutality
and persecution that continues, though to a lesser extent, today.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1970s, Hussein has destroyed more than 4,000
Kurdish villages. In the late 1980s, Iraq's campaign of ``Anfal,''
or ``Plunder,'' killed tens of thousands of Kurds. When Kurds and
Iranian troops briefly took over the Iraqi town of Halabja, Iraq
used nerve gas to kill more than 5,000 civilians in one horrible
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After the Persian Gulf War in 1991, Kurds answered the call of
then-U.S. President George Bush to rise against Hussein. But his
army, thought to be reeling from its defeat in Kuwait, mustered an
overwhelming counter-attack that the U.S. did little to impede.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown thousands of Kurds died and an estimated 1 million fled
to the neighboring mountains near Turkey and Iran. The pathetic
scenes of refugees streaming for cover in the rugged, frigid
landscape, prompted the United States and Britain to use their air
power and establish the so-called ``safe-haven'' now in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi representatives deny they mistreat the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish Najdid Abdel Majid, member of a council of Kurds in
Baghdad who support Hussein's regime, calls the notion of chemical
attacks, though widely confirmed, ``propaganda.'' He notes that
more than a million Kurds live in Iraqi controlled-areas and they
own hotels, stores and factories. He says only criminals are forced
from their lands.
</P>
<P>
   But those in strategic and oil-rich Kirkuk, just outside the
autonomous area, still face what Amnesty International calls Iraq's
``Arabization'' of the important city.
</P>
<P>
   Their first stop is often this refugee camp Kani Shaitan, or
``Devil's Spring, ``a refugee camp near the Kurdish city of
Suleimaniyah in northeastern Iraq. Many of the several hundred
people there have been there more than a year and say they were
forced to leave Kirkuk after refusing to change their official
identity from Kurdish to Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, one mother was trying to get her family of six
set up in the small tent that was now their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army came to our house. My husband was away, so they held
me in jail (two days) until my husband came back,'' recounts Saydan
Ali, 27. Then, they were given an hour to pack, and dropped off at
the border of the autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The children always ask why we left the house and always ask
about the bathroom. In Kirkuk, we had a good bathroom, here we
can't even wash,'' said Ali, gesturing to an open latrine. ``I tell
them this is our fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish minister Qazzaz said it is the kind of treatment the
world will no longer ignore, whether it occurs in Iraq or Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that kind of treatment toward people, then the
international community has an obligation to intervene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
