<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YUGOSLAVIA'S NEIGHBORS: AT A GLANCE
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-BALKANS-$ADV25.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., April 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACEDONIA
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2 million
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic makeup: Slavic majority of Macedonians; 23 percent ethnic
Albanian minority, though unofficial figure is estimated as high as
45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Background: A former republic of Yugoslavia making strides
towards democracy. Accepted U.N. and NATO forces to prevent Balkans
conflict from spilling onto its soil.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Ethnic tensions high. Fears refugee crisis will
destabilize government. Opposes NATO forces launching ground attack
from its territory, but flexible on this point if Macedonia gains
NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA
</P>
<P>
   Population: 3.3 million
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic makeup: Albanian majority of 95 percent
</P>
<P>
   Background: Turbulent political past; has virtually turned
country over to NATO and humanitarian aid agencies to cope with
more than 360,000 refugees who have fled Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Main staging area for possible NATO ground action;
fighting along border between Serb forces and KLA. Europe's poorest
country, will depend heavily on international aid.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO
</P>
<P>
   Population: 638,000
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic makeup: Slavic majority of Montenegrins, 70 percent; 7
percent ethnic Albanian minority.
</P>
<P>
   Background: The smaller partner with Serbia that forms
Yugoslavia, a new president elected several months ago has
distanced the republic from Belgrade and sought close relations
with United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Uncertain. Yugoslav army is testing the police troops
loyal to the local government; NATO is bombing strategic targets in
Montenegro even as the government is trying to remain neutral. The
influx of more than 66,000 refugees from Kosovo has strained
resources.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA
</P>
<P>
   Population: 4.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic makeup: Croat majority, 78%; Serb minority of 12%
</P>
<P>
   Background: Formerly part of Yugoslavia, Croatia fought a bloody
war of independence in 1991 with the Serb-dominated Yugoslav army
and later became involved in the Bosnian war that ended in 1995.
Still dealing with a massive rebuilding problem as a result of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Fears the economic gains, particularly in tourism,
since the war's end will be lost as a result of war over Kosovo.
Concerns conflict could spill across its borders.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA
</P>
<P>
   Population: 3.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic makeup: Estimated at roughly 40 percent Muslim, 40
percent Bosnian Serb and 20 percent Croat (Uncertain because of the
massive dislocations caused by Bosnian war).
</P>
<P>
   Background: The breakup of Yugoslavia in 1991 prompted a bitter
and bloody three-way war between Muslims, Serbs and Croats.
U.S.-sponsored peace talks in Dayton, Ohio, led to an agreement in
1995 that called for a Muslim-Croat federation and a Serb entity
with a rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: A force of 32,000 NATO-led troops keeps the fragile
peace; fears that the Kosovo war will fuel Serb animosity against
the Western presence and re-ignite the conflict in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
