<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BALKANS-$ADV25     04-23 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BALKANS-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEXT DOOR TO WAR: INSTABILITY SHAKES YUGOSLAVIA'S NEIGHBORS
 &HT;    With BALKANS-BOX-$ADV25.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., April 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ To understand the prevailing attitude among
Serbia's neighbors toward the NATO air war against Yugoslavia,
think of a trip to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   The drilling is underway and maybe it will fix the region's
unsettling problem in Belgrade. But the quicker the drilling ends,
the better.
</P>
<P>
   Any second-guessing over the wisdom of NATO's war against
Yugoslavia faded weeks ago in the frontline states that have been
politically and economically shaken by the ongoing bombing campaign
and refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, NATO needs to finish its operation quickly and
decisively in order to minimize the damage already done to the
Balkans, according to government officials and political analysts
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO leaders meet in Washington to mark the 50th anniversary
of the alliance, the small countries along Yugoslavia's southern
and eastern flank -- Macedonia, Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Croatia and the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro -- are grappling
with the consequences of a war now in its fifth week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day the war continues is dangerous,'' said Srdan
Darmanovic(CQ), a former Yugoslav parliament member from Montenegro
who heads a think tank in Podgorica. ``All of our historic
divisions are so sharp and so tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, the junior partner with Serbia in the Yugoslav
republic, is braced for a coup or civil war amid confrontations
between its pro-Western government of Montenegro and federal army
troops controlled by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, already the target of sporadic Serb shelling, fears the
conflict could grow as the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, operates
freely in its territory. The poorest country in Europe, it has been
overwhelmed with the influx of more than 350,000 ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic tensions in Macedonia are near a flashpoint as the
country has been overwhelmed in recent weeks by more than 140,000
refugees from Kosovo. The country's president, Kir Gligorov urged
Macedonia's supreme defense council to declare a state of emergency
to handle what he called ``one of the most dangerous'' situations
since independence from Yugoslavia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, the NATO-led force of 32,000 troops that has
maintained a delicate peace since 1995 have had their mission made
more difficult by the war next door. They are on high alert as
tensions grow between them and the Bosnian Serb population.
</P>
<P>
   To the north in Croatia, which is heavily dependent upon
tourism, summer bookings are down and nervousness has grown over
reports that Yugoslav troops crossed the border onto part of its
territory demilitarized under the accords that ended the Bosnian
war.
</P>
<P>
   The widely held view of moderate politicians and analysts is
that the regime in Belgrade must be transformed. The Balkans
without Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
would be more stable and offer better prospects for the advance of
democracy, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. Macedonia has asked for immediate NATO
membership in part because of the possible repercussions of a
half-finished NATO campaign that leaves Milosevic's war-waging
machine intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here fear reprisals from Belgrade because the Serbs
have long memories and even longer knives,'' said Athanas Kirovski,
a political analyst in Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of communism a decade ago, and the bloody
civil war in Bosnia, parts of the region in recent years were
beginning to inch their way toward democratic reforms and market
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   With the onset of the air war, they see the gains slipping away
and are unnerved by the feeling that their fate is once again out
of their hands, controlled by the actions Belgrade on one side, and
Washington and Brussels on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst political loss of this crisis, this feeling
that the optimism is gone. When I look to the future, it is
depressing. Here, everything is possible and nothing is possible,''
said Zarko Jordanoski, editor of Dnevnik, Macedonia's leading
independent newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration is compounded by the knowledge that even if
Milosevic were to surrender tomorrow, the logistical effort to
rebuild Yugoslavia and resettle the hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians who have fled Kosovo will take years and cost billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the small and weak republics have suffered
significant economic losses.
</P>
<P>
   Factories in Macedonia have begun to lay off thousands of
workers because the Yugoslav market, 20 percent of its foreign
trade, is closed and access to other European markets is
restricted.
</P>
<P>
   ``However you look at the map, the shortest route to Europe is
through Serbia,'' said Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski of
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has acknowledged the regional economic damage cause
by the NATO campaign against Yugoslavia. Earlier this month,
President Clinton raised the prospects of a Marshall Plan-style
rebuilding program for the Balkans once the war is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should try to do for Southeastern Europe what we helped do
for Western Europe after World War II and for Central Europe after
the Cold War,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The war also promises a political by-product for the budding
democracies: closer ties to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria and Romania, non-NATO countries on Yugoslavia's eastern
border, have given the alliance approval to use their airspace to
expand the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis appears certain to strengthen military ties between
the West and the former Yugoslav republics, too. As in the
aftermath of the war in Bosnia, the prospects seem strong that the
United States and Europe will have to commit tens of thousands of
troops and spend heavily in the region to restore Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Yugoslavia is not in war but in cooperation with
the international community,'' President Milo Djukanovic of
Montenegro told Cox Newspapers in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, Djukanovic had been working toward democratic
reforms and better relations with America and Europe. Now, he
simply struggling to remain in power.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's growing presence in the region is also aggravating
historic ethnic divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, where the bulk of Kosovo refugees have fled, has
virtually given itself over to NATO control as the alliance builds
up its forces there to deal with the refugee crisis and launch a
possible military operation using ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly close association between NATO and Albania has
stoked historic fears among its Slavic neighbors that the West
would help to build a ``greater Albania'' linking Albanian and the
considerable ethnic Albanian populations in Macedonia and Kosovo.
The inter-ethnic dispute over Kosovo stretches back to the 14th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, Macedonia and Bosnia -- with sizable ethnic Serbian
minorities and pro-Serbian nationalists -- are struggling to keep
the lid on political unrest in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states that have the strength of tolerance will survive,''
said Hisen Ranadani, an ethnic Albanian political leader in
Macedonia and former member of the federal parliament. ``Otherwise,
the Balkans will always be bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
