<SLUG> BC-ANCIENT-BUTCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUTCHER SHOP' 2.5 MILLION YEARS OLD IS FOUND IN ETHIOPIA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The primeval equivalent of your neighborhood
meat market has been found near the village of Bouri in the Afar
desert of Ethiopia. There, scientists found prehistoric antelope
bones covered with scratches caused by knife-like rocks, clearly
wielded by human- like butchers millions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery means that a primitive version of the butcher shop
has been part of humans' ancestry for 2.5 million years, at least a
half million years longer than previously thought, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   They dated the antelope bones by analyzing their ratios of
radioactive elements, which vary over time and so provide a kind of
clock.
</P>
<P>
   By tracing butchery back so far, ``we're right at the beginning
of that great leap (in hominid development) that followed (the
start of) meat eating,'' said one of the researchers, J. Desmond
Clark of the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Meat-eating transformed our ancestors and enabled them to
outlast other hominid types millions of years ago, Clark said
Thursday, while he polished off his lunchtime meal _ a hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   Meat's protein fueled hominids' body growth, strength and brain
power, Clark said. Those traits gave them powerful advantages over
other hominid species that subsisted largely on vegetarian diets,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   The antelope bones contain many V-shaped, irregular gouges,
which are characteristic of stone tools used by hominids, Clark
said. The nicks would have been smoother and U-shaped if they had
been made by wild animals, such as coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   This ``evidence of large mammal butchery shows that the earliest
stone technologies were aimed at getting meat and marrow from large
animals,'' said UC-Berkeley spokesman Robert Sanders. ``This
signals a dietary revolution that may have eventually paved the way
toward (hominids') invasion of new habitats and continents.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development at the Afar desert site, the scientists
found another branch amid the numerous prehistoric twigs of the
hominid family tree.
</P>
<P>
   The new branch _ a sort of lost family cousin _ has been named
Australopithecus garhi, or A. garhi for short. ``Garhi'' means
``surprise'' in the language of the Afar Desert's native
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise is the appropriate word because A. garhi's skullcap has
completely unforeseen and unanticipated bony and dental features,
Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   With its unusually big teeth and other features, ``this cranium
was a big surprise to all of us,'' acknowledged one of the
discoverers, Egyptian anthropologist Berhane Asfaw.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on both discoveries, made between 1996 and December
1998, were published in Friday's issue of the journal Science.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
