<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING BERRIES CAN BE AS EASY AS EATING THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 25) 
(jt) 
 By LEE REICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plucking a perfectly ripe raspberry or blackberry from a plant
and popping it in your mouth is an ambrosial experience. And these
berries, collectively known as bramble fruits, are easy to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much the only thing you have to do for the plants,
besides harvesting, is prune them diligently once or twice a year.
When plants are pruned properly, their stems and leaves bathe
freely in air and sunlight, so they dry quickly following dew or
rain to minimize disease problems.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning also keeps these spreading plants from taking over the
rest of the garden. And rather than being buried in a tangle of
thorny canes, the fruits on pruned plants are splayed out for easy
picking.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning a bramble patch is not at all difficult _ nothing like
the combination of art and science needed to prune an apple or a
pear tree. Just follow a few simple steps.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing something about how brambles grow and fruit helps you
understand how to prune them. Although all brambles have perennial
root systems, individual canes live only two years.
</P>
<P>
   Canes of summer-bearing varieties do nothing but grow leaves
their first year, bear fruit in midsummer of their second year,
then die. Canes of everbearing varieties begin fruiting near the
top in late summer and early fall of their first year. These same
canes bear additional fruit farther down in midsummer of their
second year, then die.
</P>
<P>
   Because new canes grow from ground level each year, a planting
of either summer-bearing or everbearing brambles can always have an
assortment of one- and two-year-old canes, and so bear fruit every
year (twice a year for everbearing varieties).
</P>
<P>
   Because the canes are biennial, the first step in pruning is to
cut down all canes that have completed their second growing season.
Old, cracking bark makes them easy to identify. Cut these canes all
the way to ground level as growth is starting this spring.
Alternatively, you could have cut them down right after they
finished fruiting last summer.
</P>
<P>
   With full sun and fertile soil, brambles are productive plants,
each spring sending up many _ too many _ new canes. This leads to
the second step in pruning: getting rid of excess young canes. Cut
them to ground level as growth is beginning.
</P>
<P>
   First go after wayward young canes. If you grow your brambles in
a continuous row, lop down any canes that make the row wider than
12 inches. If your planting consists of ``hills,'' or tight
clusters of plants three to six feet apart, lop down any canes
escaping a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have removed these wayward canes, the next step is to
further reduce the number of young canes. Prune plants growing in a
continuous row so that no canes are closer than six inches apart.
If plants are in hills, reduce the number of canes in each hill to
6 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   As you choose young canes to lop to the ground, always save
those that are thickest and healthiest. Keep an eye out for and
remove canes with gray splotches of disease or swellings due to
borers.
</P>
<P>
   From this point on, various sorts of brambles begin to differ in
their pruning needs, and can be divided into two distinct groups.
</P>
<P>
   The first, which includes upright blackberries and black and
purple raspberries, bears fruit on branches on the year-old canes.
Prod these brambles to make fruiting branches by pinching out the
tip of any new cane as it reaches three feet in height. Canes do
not reach this height simultaneously, so go over the planting a few
times through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The final pruning needed for this group of brambles is to
shorten those fruit-bearing branches. Do this now, cutting all such
branches back to a length of 4 to 18 inches, allowing more growth
on huskier branches, because they can bear more fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The second pruning group consists of red and yellow raspberries,
which bear fruit directly on the canes, not on branches. So once
the old canes and excess young canes have been cut to the ground,
the only further pruning needed is to shorten the canes that remain
while plants are dormant.
</P>
<P>
   This is done for convenience and to prevent the canes from
flopping around in the wind, so the amount you shorten them depends
on how you support them. The longer the canes, the more fruit you
will harvest. For instance, one common method of training is to tie
the canes _ shortened to about six feet _ to wires strung between
two posts, one wire at two feet above the ground and the other wire
at five feet. With this same trellis, you could also leave the
canes nearly full length if you bent them along and wove them
around the upper wire.
</P>
<P>
   Prune everbearing types of red and yellow raspberries the same
way as the summer-bearers, with one slight difference. The year-old
canes that started fruiting at their ends last year will finish
fruiting lower down this year. Therefore, shorten those canes to
just below where they stopped fruiting last year. Old fruit stalks
still hanging on the canes will show you where to cut.
</P>
<P>
   A simpler way to prune everbearing red and yellow raspberries is
just to cut the whole planting to the ground each autumn. This
sacrifices your midsummer crop, but will give a somewhat larger
fall crop. It also reduces problems from pests that overwinter in
canes and eliminates damage from cold or browsing deer in winter.
And it's easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
