<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROJAS-DALLAS-HNS &LR;      04-23 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROJAS-DALLAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS-BOUND SCHOOLS CHIEF LEAVES LIST OF PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ School officials in Dallas have voted to hire
the head of the San Francisco school system, a move that rankled
education officials here at a time when the school district faces
major budget challenges and desegregation issues.
</P>
<P>
   During his seven years as superintendent, Waldemar (Bill) Rojas
has enjoyed a mostly tranquil relationship with the board, a
significant accomplishment for the head of an urban school system.
But there have recently been cracks in the administration of the
San Francisco Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   The system has been assailed for spending money it doesn't have;
buying buildings for vague purposes from funds not readily
reimbursable; and touting academic gains while removing thousands
of low-performing children from the testing base.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the end of a federal desegregation order that governed
the district for 16 years and assigned students based on a rigid
racial formula, San Francisco Unified must now craft an enrollment
plan that maintains diversity without considering race. It is one
of the most complex issues facing any district in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, 54, told board members he would discuss his decision to
leave his $185,000-per-year job and go to Dallas at a school board
meeting Tuesday night. He could earn up to $275,000 per year in the
new job.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas school trustees voted 9-0 Thursday to give the job to
Rojas. The announcement took some officials here by surprise and
some criticized his timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the superintendent to walk away from us in a time of
crisis, a crisis that is his making, is a total betrayal and is
cowardly and pathetic,'' said San Francisco school board member Dan
Kelly. ``He has spit in the face of the board and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing for another job without notifying board members was
a ``flagrant violation'' of the superintendent's contract, said
board member Jill Wynns.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas' contract, which began April 16, 1992, and extended
through June 2001, requires the superintendent to notify the board
in writing of any job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions have voided his contract,'' Wynns said. ``I think
it will be suggested that he leave immediately and an acting
superintendent step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynns, who has often been the lone board member to openly
challenge Rojas, said there were two ways to look at the timing of
the job switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take the positive spin and say he's been here for
seven years, which is a long tenure for an urban superintendent,''
Wynns said. ``You can also say that things were starting to fall
apart for him. You had questions about his budget, about real
estate deals, about his special education programs, about the test
scores.''
</P>
<P>
   The past few weeks have been a time of trouble for San Francisco
Unified.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from a lawsuit, the system agreed in an
out-of-court settlement to abandon its desegregation formula that
tried to balance the ethnic makeup of each school.
</P>
<P>
   In March, two California lawmakers called for an outside audit
of the district's finances. Then it was revealed the district
borrowed $7.8 million from the general fund to buy a building
without having a guaranteed reimbursement from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Then district testing and reporting policies were questioned. An
analysis of 10 years of district test scores, conducted by the San
Francisco Examiner, indicated that while student enrollment
remained flat, test results from fewer students were being reported
each year, raising questions about whether the gains were real or
manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is the only urban district in the United States to
post six years of consecutive gains in test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This news (of Rojas leaving) couldn't have come at a worse
time,'' said San Francisco teachers union President Kent Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with assignment policy for next year, budget
cutbacks, possible layoffs _ issues that take leadership. I didn't
anticipate that when things started getting tough in the district,
the superintendent would leave so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, born in Puerto Rico and reared in the South Bronx, has a
personality that mixes eloquence with braggadocio, power with
compassion. He has managed to maintain more supporters on the board
than detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas will be lucky to get him,'' said board member Mary
Hernandez. ``For many years, because Bill has such a good national
reputation, there has been interest from other school districts.
He's a great superintendent. I think he's the best there is.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Board of Education President Juanita Owens, also a
Rojas supporter, said, ``He's a change agent. He's creative, a risk
taker. He was brought here to bring about reforms and I think he's
done that. Dallas' gain is San Francisco's loss.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, Rojas would be taking on a significantly greater
challenge in terms of district size and budget.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 158,000 students and 9,300 teachers, the Dallas
system is the nation's 10th largest district. San Francisco 64,000
students and 4,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas district's budget for the 1997-98 year was nearly $967
million, compared with $550 million in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving here in 1992, following two decades in the New
York City public school system, Rojas has pushed for significant
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas and the board also approved tougher graduation
requirements and added a seventh period to the school day for
middle school kids.
</P>
<P>
   Popular for some reforms, Rojas has been denounced for others.
He stirred controversy with his policy of ``reconstitution,'' in
which employees at chronically failing schools are replaced by a
new team.
</P>
<P>
   He was also criticized for his brazen challenge of state
policies on testing children who speak little, if any, English.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, San Francisco Unified _ joined by the school districts
in Oakland and Berkeley _ successfully sued the state Department of
Education to excuse children who speak little English from testing.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Rojas has cast unprecedented attention on the
achievement gaps between racial and ethnic groups, vowing to raise
the test scores of blacks and Hispanics to the national average by
this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
