<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW OUT THE WINDOWS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am about to get my first PC, and it will have
Windows. I've read so much about Linux and how good it is. Would it
be possible to use it without removing Windows? Also, would you
recommend that a newcomer use Linux?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Gates' Nightmare
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NIGHTMARE: I'd recommend you using it, but not installing
it. That's what your good buddy at work is for. You know who I'm
talking about: the four-eyed geek in Information Systems who gives
``socially dysfunctional'' a whole new spin. Sure, you never spoke
to him before in your life, but you never really needed to, did
you?
</P>
<P>
   Linux makes strange bedfellows. And it gives Big Bill heartburn.
It's an incredibly stable, free operating system you can use
instead of Windows or DOS. Unfortunately, a new user like you is
going to need help from Geek-boy installing it. You really have to
know a lot about your hardware and what you want to do with it, and
newbies rarely know either.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that if you struggle through the installation
and get everything to work correctly, you'll know one heck of a lot
about your computer, unlike the people who just wave a mouse at the
screen and expect things to magically work the right way every
time.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to dump Windows to use Linux, which is probably
the only thing keeping Bill's intestinal walls intact. You'll need
to divide your hard drive into a Windows partition and a Linux
partition, though, using either a utility that comes with Linux or
a separate package like Partition Magic. In the wrong hands, these
utilities can hammer everything on your drive, so let Geek-boy do
this step. At least you have somebody to blame when things go
horribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't a lot of commercial programs designed to run under
Linux yet, so don't expect to be playing Half-Life any time soon.
You can find shareware out the wazoo, though, most of it free for
the downloading. There's even something called StarOffice, a free
suite of applications that will leave Microsoft Office owners
wondering what they paid all that money for.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing footsteps, Bill?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Would you please explain memory? If you have 64
MB of memory and use 32 MB researching something, but never shut
the computer completely off, the next time you use it, will you
only have the remaining 32MB available?
</P>
<P>
   _ Memory Lapse
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MEM: I'm sorry, I've forgotten the question. They said the
ginkgo would help, but ... Well, maybe it was ginkgo. They might
have said ginseng. No, that wasn't it. Uhhhh. ... Gecko? Glocko?
Gorgonzola? Somebody help me out here.
</P>
<P>
   Ohhhh, that's right. I remember now. Think of RAM as a shelf.
You pull some stuff off a disk or create some new data and stick it
on the shelf so it's handy when you need to refer to it.
</P>
<P>
   A decent program cleans off the shelf when it finishes its work
so others can use it. Less-than-decent programs leave remnants that
take up valuable shelf space other programs are expecting to use,
bringing the whole thing crashing to ... I forgot where I was going
with this.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted something-or-other Dr. Emilio Bombay offers, uhhhh, you
know, all that stuff about, uhhhh ... was it computers? No, that's
not right. He can be reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via
snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257. At least I think he can. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
