A0669 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUNECARTERCASH-TEX     04-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNECARTERCASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER DECADES IN SUPPORTING ROLES, JUNE CARTER CASH RETURNS TO
RECORDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   June Carter Cash is two months shy of 70, bewildered and a
little saddened at finding herself in the matriarchal role. She
has, after all, spent a lifetime as the daughter of country music's
sainted mother, Maybelle Carter, and 31 years as the wife of the
legendary Johnny Cash.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's her turn to, as Madonna might say, express herself. And
what a statement: June Carter Cash just released an
autobiographical album that is as much a personal statement as
Johnny Cash's ``American Recordings'' five years ago. ``Press On,''
which gets its title from a line in the A.P. Carter song ``Diamonds
in the Rough,'' is an honest, powerful acoustic journey through one
woman's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I've wanted to do one like this, authentic and
real, the style of music my family played,'' Cash says during a
phone interview last week. Despite her lifetime in the music
business, ``Press On'' is only her second solo album, following
``Appalachian Pride'' in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had contracts with RCA, Liberty and Columbia, but I quit
recording years ago to keep up with John,'' she says. ``It's been a
pretty good job itself, you know, to have seven children, and be a
wife to John, and he doesn't have much of a love for business, so
I've done a lot of business stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It took three years to pick the 13 cuts for ``Press On,'' eight
June Carter Cash originals, three A.P. Carter songs and two others.
An entire recording studio was installed in the Cash family cabin
late last year, with her son John Carter Cash and J.J. Blair as
producers. June's former sons-in-law, Marty Stuart and Rodney
Crowell, as well as Norman Blake and Dave Rowe, were contributing
musicians. June's daughter Rosie Carter and Johnny Cash contributed
vocals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, these are the first takes on everything I did,''
Cash says. ``I kept saying, `John Carter, I know I can sing better
than this.' '' But the tapes were taken to California for mixing,
and in three days, the album was complete. It is being issued on
the independent label Risk/Small Hairy Dog.
</P>
<P>
   While traditional Carter Family cuts are poignant, especially
June singing alone on ``Will the Circle Be Unbroken,'' other more
eclectic songs such as the self-penned ``I Used to Be Somebody''
define June's own life more clearly. They are anything but
innocent. They reflect, Cash says, her own take on her family's
history of limelight and pain. The few times she is alone and
quiet, she says, she is still overwhelmed by such memories _ as
well as that she is the only Carter family member still active and
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I feel strange coming to grips with,'' she
says. ``I used to think Bill Monroe had a few more days on me. But
I can't tell you anybody that's been in the business longer than
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although born in Virginia, June began her career in Texas,
singing on border radio with her mother and two sisters at age 9.
By 1944, teen-age June was on the road continually with her mother
and sisters, and by 1950, the Carter Sisters act was a Grand Ole
Opry regular. She remembers coming to Fort Worth to play major
dates at Panther Hall through the touring years. (Cash once studied
acting with famed director Elia Kazan in New York. She has had
occasional roles in television and movies, the latest being Robert
Duvall's mother in 1997's ``The Apostle.'')
</P>
<P>
   But her career has always been a sideline to her supporting role
beside Johnny Cash. ``That never really bothered me. I made a
choice,'' she says. ``I just felt very lucky to have John in my
life. If a woman is lucky enough to really fall in love, then she
makes a choice. I've never regretted mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a trying one for June. Her sister Helen died, and
their other sister Anita has been hospitalized in her battle with
arthritis. Then there was the diagnosis of Johnny's Shy-Drager
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is much better now. We took off a year and nine months
(mostly in Jamaica),'' she says. ``We told them a year, but we
liked it so well, we took off more.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter Cash says many outside observers just don't see the
rhythm of their lives at this point, focusing instead on health
reports and touring and recording hiatuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Is he bored?' and I always say, `He's having the
time of his life,''' she says. ``You see, we're OK; even if we died
and went to heaven, we're all right. I've always walked with
thousands of angels. They've put me on their wings and they've
carried me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country and western music for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 548-5565. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
