r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     04-23 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD I BACK DOLE? TELL ME WHAT SHE THINKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Women split over female president,'' said a front-page
headline in Monday's paper. ``Possible Dole bid triggering
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   With apologies for contradicting my own newspaper: Not in my
circle of friends, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   So Elizabeth Dole, her recently vacated chair at the helm of the
Red Cross still warm, is contemplating a run for the White House.
Various political pundits and academicians think this will twist
Republican women into a tizzy about whether they're ready to vote
for one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sometime between now and the Republican National
Convention in 2000, Dole will give America some idea where she
actually stands on issues instead of just leaving the media with a
giddy glow because a ``credible'' woman might be going after
politics' brass ring next year. Then Republican women _ and men _
can decide about her qualifications as a viable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Bob Dole's other half has chalked up an
impressive career of public service. The Harvard Law School
graduate has worked directly with three administrations in
Washington: served as a federal trade commissioner and headed two
Cabinet Departments _ Transportation and Labor _ under Nixon;
organized a Task Force on Legal Equity for Women during the Reagan
days; and served as President Bush's labor secretary. She went on
to head a internationally respected relief agency, the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   As I said, impressive. And she was the show-stopper at the '96
Republican National Convention with her mingle-with-the-people,
I'm-just-a-simple-girl-from-the-South-who-loves-her-husband
introduction of Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The gal can walk and chew gum at the same time, all right, but
does that make her presidential material? Not until and unless she
gives America specifics about what's on her agenda.
</P>
<P>
   I had the same misgivings about retired Gen. Colin Powell when
it was rumored that he might be interested in a presidential run in
'96. You'd be hard pressed to find many folk who can match his
impeccable record of achievements and values. Stand-up patriot, war
hero, loves his wife and kids, rose above adversity to achieve
success, the whole ``from tiny acorns, mighty oaks grow'' story.
</P>
<P>
   But no one other than perhaps his immediate family and close,
close friends ever found out where he stood on specific issues
facing the country. Turned out it didn't matter, because Powell had
more sense than to put his family through a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The problem I have with people jumping up at this early stage of
the campaign to wave flags and shout hosannahs for Liddy _ or
George W. Bush, or any of the Republican candidates who are testing
the political waters without really committing themselves to
specifics _ is that ambiguity and verbal gymnastics are all we're
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem I have with the question, ``Will women vote for
a woman?'' is that it is based on an oversimplified premise. The
idea of identity politics, that women will vote for Dole or any
female candidate out of some kind of ``atta girl'' motivation, is
insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, I've heard the same cliches everyone else has about
men in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have been running this country for more than 200 years,
and look where it's gotten us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America's had enough male, pale and Yale presidents to last a
lifetime _ give someone else a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Kate O'Beirne, Washington editor for the National Review, hit
the nail squarely with bright red polish in a recent column for The
Women's Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Activist Republican women ... will support politicians who
think like them over ones who look like them,'' O'Beirne wrote in
the Independent Women's Forum publication.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. Republican women want intelligent, decisive, strong,
articulate, competent leaders who share their ideologies. If they
happen to be wearing skirts, or went to a state university, or have
Hispanic surnames, great. And if they don't, that's fine, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
