<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0672 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     04-23 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL TRAGEDY EXPOSES THE EMPTINESS OF OUR SOULS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Adolf Hitler's birthday. And the evil unfolded at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. What does it all mean?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not simple. But religionists agree that America
needs a wake-up call in taking care of its children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evil in the world,'' said the Rev. John Tietjen, a
former bishop in the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
``Forces are out there ready to turn our children into demons. And
we saw that happen this week.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a bright side, said Tietjen, now senior minister of
Trinity Lutheran Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces also are out there in America eager to help kids learn
how to be human beings,'' he said. ``They don't have to be angels _
just human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conservative religionists gave a familiar explanation of
why two teen-age boys, apparently fascinated by the dark and evil
forces of Hitler's Nazism, began shooting down their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``God was violently expelled from school by a Supreme Court
decision in 1962,'' said the Rev. Flip Benham of Dallas, director
of Operation Rescue, the anti-abortion group. ``When God is
removed, violence always fills the void.''
</P>
<P>
   Benham referred to the high court's decision to outlaw
government-organized prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   One of Benham's associates, Eileen Schopf of Buffalo, N.Y., who
led an Operation Save America program at high schools in northern
New York this week, expanded on that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have crawled away from the moral upbringing America has
always had, and are refusing to say evil is evil and sin is sin,''
she said. ``We've ignored God's laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Raymond Barber, an independent Baptist leader for 48
years, said he is disturbed and angry about the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what do we expect to happen in America when we try to
diminish the power and presence of Almighty God?'' the Fort Worth
minister said. ``Every time you turn on the TV, you see somebody
sticking a gun in somebody's face, about to blow them away. We've
left God back in the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Tietjen doesn't agree that the problem can be solved by merely
giving God a higher profile in America's classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any assumption that God is not there in school.
We have a magnificent bunch of people in the public schools,'' said
Tietjen. ``The problem is with individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   He concurs, though, that schoolchildren need spiritual guidance
and more love and attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot abandon our children to the odd and the morbid and
the evil that is very prevalent in the world,'' Tietjen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Scott Colglazier said those who think the Colorado
massacre can be explained simply do not appreciate the complexity
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about good schools and bad schools, good parents
and bad parents, good neighborhoods and bad neighborhoods,'' he
said. ``It is a problem of the American soul.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes beyond just having prayers in public schools, he said.
It is a deep, systemic problem that must be addressed on the soul
level.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, he believes, must have a new resolve to care for many
adolescents at risk in America's schools who are plagued by
feelings of emptiness and hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Members of all faiths must work together in helping to alleviate
such despair in the very young, said Colglazier, senior minister of
University Christian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every faith is rooted in divine love, and thus hope,'' said
Colglazier. ``And when we know we are loved and feel ourselves
loved in this universe, it opens the door for caring for ourselves
and for our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Colglazier and his congregation will join with many others
Sunday in remembering the Littleton catastrophe. A candle will be
placed on the Communion altar for every person killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to mourn this, because God is mourning today,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, Americans must immediately take action to give
better care and loving attention to their children.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
