<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0673 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANDY-INTERNET-TEX     04-23 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANDY-INTERNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANDY'S STOCK PRICE, QUARTERLY INCOME SOAR AS IT TIES FORTUNES TO
INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Leonard Roberts has long believed that Tandy
Corp. would be part of the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy's stock price, a laggard for much of the decade, has
surged 75 percent since Jan. 1, ranking it No. 5 among the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index companies.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Tandy in the same neighborhood as the index's No. 4,
America Online, a bellwether for today's digital times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth is dependent on how big the Internet becomes,''
said Roberts, Tandy's chief executive. ``It's going to be a major
new anchor for this company.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two days, Tandy's stock has gained more than $10 a
share, catapulted first by a deal to sell Internet access at Radio
Shack stores and then by a report of strong earnings that surpassed
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy's stock closed at $72.3125 Thursday, up $2.8125. It ended
1998 at just over $41 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy said that net income, before dividends, totaled $55.9
million for the first three months of 1999, a 50.6 percent increase
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales declined 29 percent because the company no longer
operates the Computer City chain. But same-store sales for the
quarter, considered the key measure of a retailer's health,
increased 13 percent at Radio Shack.
</P>
<P>
   Strong demand for wireless phones and satellite TV drove the
sales gains, the company said, while higher productivity pushed up
operating profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy's stellar results come on top of an 11 percent sales gain
for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all these great visions and strategies, but if
you don't get results along the way, you'll never get there,''
Roberts told analysts in a conference call. ``This has been one of
the best-performing quarters in Radio Shack history.''
</P>
<P>
   It also happens to be Roberts' first quarter as CEO. And he has
been ushering in a series of strategies that are remaking the
company and capturing the attention of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   He is positioning Radio Shack as ``the home connectivity
store,'' the place where America can turn to hook up to high-speed
Internet lines and learn how to apply the latest consumer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he announced a strategic agreement with NorthPoint
Communications, a firm that provides digital access lines. The deal
will let Radio Shack sell the service in up to 28 markets, some
beginning this year, and will allow Tandy to use the technology at
its outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that NorthPoint will pay the costs of installing
the infrastructure at Tandy, which will save the company money
while also helping its workers become more efficient. Separately,
the Tandy board also approved a $20 million investment in
NorthPoint's initial public offering, slated for later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is trying to build loyalty and boost morale in an
industry often known for high turnover and poor service. After
telling employees that Radio Shack wants to become the best place
to work in America, he has relaxed the dress code, given stock
awards to store managers and increased benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts appear to be paying off: He said turnover among
store managers is 15 percent, down from about 40 percent several
years ago. And he said productivity gains are reflected in the
growth of same-store sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team of store managers tell me that morale has never been
higher,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy is demonstrating how it can earn a steady stream of
recurring revenues, a key trait that makes Internet companies so
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   When Tandy sells service contracts for wireless phones and
satellite TV, it earns a percentage of the monthly fee, which it
calls ``residual revenue.'' That money is almost pure profit, and
it is having an growing impact on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tandy's residual revenue totaled $32 million. This
year, Roberts projects that it will hit $60 million, and by 2000,
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet offers a separate windfall that may be as
lucrative. By selling connections to high-speed Internet lines,
Roberts said Tandy could bring in up to $100 million in a separate
residual stream early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are developing a low capital-intensive, high
earnings-growth model,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the market is responding to the company's
results and its prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers they're putting out are clearly topping the
expectations of the street,'' said David Leibowitz, a managing
director at Burnham Securities in New York. ``And Tandy appears to
be in perfect position to be a direct participant as the home
becomes more digital.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit is being directed toward Roberts. He joined
Tandy as president of Radio Shack in 1993, when the parent company
was struggling with several underperforming units.
</P>
<P>
   During the mid-'90s, Tandy took write-offs totaling more than
$500 million as it closed or sold Incredible Universe, Computer
City and other operations.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was promoted to Tandy's chief executive this year, after
John Roach retired from the post. Roach remains chairman of Tandy.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts unveiled the slogan, ``Tandy is Radio Shack,'' to help
clear up confusion about the company's identity. And while Roach
had tried to grow the organization by creating new retail concepts,
Roberts has focused on leveraging Radio Shack's 7,000 outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have an absolute understanding of our strategy,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Telzrow, an analyst at Hoak Breedlove Wesneski in Dallas,
cited a few other factors for the stock's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company has gotten a lot stronger over the past three
months,'' said Telzrow, who has followed Tandy for many years.
``And there's no question that there is a lot of confidence in
management.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
