<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-SEA-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LAUNCHES A 5-YEAR, $12 MILLION DEEP SEA PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Secretary of Commerce William M. Daley, in
announcing the launch of a five-year, $12 million underwater
research project, said it will allow scientists to travel ``to the
depths of our marine sanctuaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is divers can go to depths we can only dream
about,'' Daley added in describing the Sustainable Seas Expedition,
a major ocean exploration by his department's National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) and the National Geographic
Society.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition will include exploration of areas off the San
Francisco and Marin County coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's visit here Thursday was part of an Earth Day tour of the
San Francisco Bay area, where he met with business and port
officials at the Port of Oakland to discuss dredging and stopped by
Fisherman's Wharf to talk about revitalizing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Scuba divers normally cannot go below 100 or 150 feet, but once
inside a tiny submarine called ``DeepWorker 2000 _ which resembles
a mini Volkswagen bug with crab arms _ they will be able to plunge
as deep as 2,000 feet with a high level of maneuverability. The
expedition will use more than one sub to explore 12 sanctuaries
administered by NOAA. Four of them are in California.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Guardino, a chemistry and physics teacher at Carmel High
School, is one of about 60 scientists and teachers being trained to
pilot the new mini-subs. He and other teachers said they see the
opportunity to travel deep below the surface of the sea as a
learning experience for his students. ``These kids have already
learned how to cite and identify more than 160 species of marine
organisms in the (Monterey) Bay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of organizations are financing the project, including
the Richard and Rhoda Goldman Fund, a San Francisco philanthropic
and environmental group that provided $5 million; National
Geographic Society ($1 million) and $5 million from NASA, NOAA and
other federal agencies, said Dale Petroskey, a senior vice
president with National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind the project has been Sylvia Earle, a
marine biologist from Oakland, Calif., who is now
explorer-in-residence at National Geographic Society.
</P>
<P>
   Earle, who said the mini-sub was tested last weekend in
Monterey, Calif., will help lead a team to explore California's
four marine sanctuaries _ the Gulf of the Farallones, Cordell Bank
near Point Reyes, Monterey Bay and the Channel Islands. The team
will then head up to the coast off Washington's Olympic Peninsula.
The project will shift to the East Coast and down to the Florida
Keys by August.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers planning to pilot DeepWorker, built by Nuytco
Research Ltd. of North Vancouver, B.C., said they were excited
about what they might find.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Brown, executive director of the Farallones Marine
Sanctuary Association, said, ``If people don't know what's down
there, they won't understand it and they won't protect it. With
knowing, comes caring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
