<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORBANEK-COLUMN25-COX     04-23 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORBANEK-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen-age killers raised in a U.S. culture in decay
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By George Orbanek
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the cell phone call came on the long-planned vacation-day
off, I thought to myself, ``This better not be about someone
complaining about an editorial or griping that the TV logs are
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Would that it had been.
</P>
<P>
   Instead I was told that two heavily armed gunmen, wearing ski
masks and black trench coats had entered a Littleton high school
and were indiscriminately shooting up the place. I was told that
police SWAT teams were assembling outside the high school amid
fears of widespread hostage-taking and dozens of casualities.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to leave the mentally therapeutic currents of the
Roaring Fork River and get back to The Daily Sentinel's newsroom.
When I arrived late in the afternoon, it was all over but the
incalculable shock and grieving. The news wires and television
broadcasts were reporting that up to 25 people may have been
killed, including the two trench-coat-clad assailants, who had not
yet been identified but were presumed to be Columbine High School
students.
</P>
<P>
   Good Lord.
</P>
<P>
   Time once was not all that long ago _ let's say, in the late
'60s _ that a relatively harmless fistfight over a girlfriend or
knocking over a headstone in a cemetery was about the most serious
trouble a 17-year-old kid would ever find himself in. For those
with a hard-core anarchist streak, a really dark fantasy may have
tended toward dreams about taking over the dean's office and
lighting up a joint after spending just a semester or two at dear,
old State.
</P>
<P>
   How quaint. These days, spraying bullets in a recreational
murder spree has replaced spray-painting the school colors around
town as the trouble-making du jour of high school kids.
</P>
<P>
   As the old '60s Buffalo Springfield lyric said, ``Something's
happening here. What it is ain't exactly clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, something is clear. The popular culture of the late '90s
is several shades darker than the popular culture of the late '60s.
There are, of course, many reasons behind the degradation of the
nation's popular culture and attendant societal decay. There's
enough blame to go around for all us to share. But you can place
the influence of Hollywood and the mass media at the top of the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, the suicidal killers
responsible for Tuesday's horrific shooting spree, are products of
the culture they grew up in.
</P>
<P>
   On his late-night television show a few weeks ago, the
ever-so-midwestern-mainstream David Letterman attempted to talk up
Marilyn Manson _ the cross-dressing, violence-spouting,
satanic-worshipping shock rocker said to be Harris' and Klebold's
favorite musician _ as if Manson were merely an outrageously garbed
version of Kathy Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   Call me an old-fashioned relic of a 1950s childhood, but I don't
understand what the likes of a Marilyn Manson is doing on network
television, even on a late-night show which airs after most kids
have presumably gone to bed.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s, Hollywood gave us director Sam Peckinpah's
``The Wild Bunch,'' a film celebrated by critics for its ``balletic
violence.'' Since then, most of us have become anesthetized to the
film violence once lauded as groundbreaking movie making. At the
same time, it's become increasingly difficult to avoid the
conclusion that some people aren't anesthetized to film violence,
but are inspired by it.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 film ``Basketball Diaries,'' Leonardo DiCaprio is
featured in a dream sequence in which he guns down a teacher and
school classmates. As his shooting fantasy fashion statement,
DiCaprio sports a long, black trench coat similar to the trench
coats worn by Harris and Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Cause and effect? Nah, say apologists for the purveyors of our
contemporary cultural crudescence. It just must be a strange
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Shock rock. Millenial doom-mongering. Dark computer games. A
fascination with Hitler and Nazism. Pervasive movie violence. Mix
in the virtual cesspool found on much of the Internet. To suggest
that none of this contributes to the corruption of the human soul
evilly manifested in the likes of Harris and Klebold is to suggest
the music of Johann Sebastian Bach and movies like ``Chariots of
Fire'' are incapable of elevating the human spirit. In fin de
siecle America, there seems to be far too much of the former and
not enough of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural influences aside, Harris and Klebold are, at bottom,
responsible for the boundless suffering and carnage they inflicted
last Tuesday. And you can spread some of the responsibility toward
the killers' parents. (Hello-o-o-o-o-o, Mom and Dad. How do kids in
this day and age go about building three or four dozen pipe bombs
without parents having any clue?)
</P>
<P>
   Those of us in the business of putting out newspapers are
generally disposed toward the broadest expression of opinion and
artistic creativity. After what happened at Columbine High School
last Tuesday, it's time to wonder whether we as a society can
continue to afford it.
</P>
<P>
   George Orbanek is the publisher of The Daily Sentinel in Grand
Junction, Colo. E-mail: gorbanek(at)gjds.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
