   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT (Washington) _ President Clinton and other NATO
leaders reject Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's latest
proposal for an end to the bombing of his country. NATO,
considering an invasion of Kosovo with ground forces, also issues a
document laying out the way it sees the war ending. By STEWART M.
POWELL and ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-ANNIVERSARY (Washington) _ At an unexpectedly harrowing
moment in its history, NATO marks the 50th anniversary of what has
been the world's most successful military alliance. In the same
auditorium where the alliance was founded, leaders acknowledge that
the fight in the Balkans with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
challenges its reputation and future. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-MOOD (Washington) _ With dark gray clouds over the nation's
capital, the mood is somber on the 50th anniversary of the founding
of NATO. As alliance bombs continue to fall on Yugoslavia, NATO's
originally slated celebration of the West's victory over communism
is marked by solemn speeches and low-key ceremony. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-STREETS (Washington) _ Largely empty streets, except for
limousines and motorcade, and high security greet the largest
diplomatic gathering in Washington's history. Scattered protesters
angry about nuclear weapons and NATO's involvement in the Balkans
also converge on the nation's capital. By BENNETT ROTH and JENNIFER
DAY.
</P>
