<HEADER>
A0722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NITEOUT-TITO-PUENTE-A     04-23 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-TITO-PUENTE-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING `LA VIDA LOCA' WITH MAMBO KING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 25) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bronx belonged to Tito Puente last Tuesday night.
As dusk fell, stars were heading uptown on the Major Deegan
Highway, and local Bronx heavyweights like the rapper Fat Joe were
suiting up in their flashy best. All were coming out to pay homage
to Puente, the godfather of Latin music, who was celebrating his
76th birthday in grand style at Jimmy's Bronx Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Puente had to make a stop. Clad in a light cream
double-breasted suit and collarless gun-metal shirt, he stepped
onto the infield of Yankee Stadium to throw out the opening pitch.
Introduced as ``The King of Latin Swing,'' Puente swiveled his hips
in a deft mambo step, went into his windup and then delivered an
anemic, one-hopping pitch over home plate. The stadium erupted in
cheers, as if he had just burned a hole in catcher Jorge Posada's
mitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous,'' Puente explained moments later,
exiting through the stadium's underground passageways. As a child
on the streets of Spanish Harlem he had always dreamed of being a
professional ballplayer. Instead, he became the most famous of the
Latin band leaders, and a seemingly ageless pop icon. His fans
range from grandmothers who grew up dancing to his mambo rhythms,
to teen-agers who know Puente from crossover pop records like ``Oye
Como Va'' and TV appearances on ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo, Tito! Como 'ta?'' called two Hispanic police officers
outside Yankee Stadium, who then offered birthday greetings to
Puente and did exaggerated we-are-not-worthy bows. With his wife on
one arm and his daughter on the other, he took his place in the
back of a white stretch limousine replete with long-stem Champagne
glasses. But when the limo pulled up outside Jimmy's, all seemed
quiet _ just the bouncers and a parked television news van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're too early,'' said Puente's daughter, Audrey, a
television weather anchor in Jackson, Miss. ``Should we go back and
watch the rest of the baseball game?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Puente said. ``Jimmy told me get here by 8.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it was almost as if he had walked into a surprise
birthday party. Television lights flashed on as Puente talked to
reporters, hugged old friends and was kissed by complete strangers.
``Happy birthday to me,'' Puente said softly, raising a glass of
wine. As barrel-chested bouncers cleared a path through the crowd,
women in bright lipstick and shimmering gowns blew kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy's Bronx Cafe, the cavernous club in a former auto
dealership on West Fordham Road, is best known as a hangout where
Latino athletes, rappers and salsa stars carouse alongside
silk-shirted tough guys. But for most of the non-Latin celebrities
in attendance, the glitz of the South Bronx night spot was a
revelation: a breezy, high-ceilinged, palm-tree-adorned throwback
to nightclubs like the Copacabana.
</P>
<P>
   Like a scene from a Ricky Martin video, salsa-steppers in
pinstriped suits whirled athletic women in tight white skirts slit
up to the hip. Chris Noth, the star of the television series, ``Sex
in the City,'' who had never been to Jimmy's before, congratulated
Puente, barely taking his eyes off the long-legged dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby ribbed Puente about his bouncing first pitch at
Yankee Stadium: ``You thought you were playing cricket, Pops?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to throw it over his head,'' Puente said, moving
on to glad-hand friends like the actor Armand Assante and the
former light-heavyweight boxing champ Jose Torres. Jimmy Rodriquez,
the restaurant's proprietor, served Moet and platters of jumbo
shrimp, but Puente had no time for a nosh. He was still lost in the
scrum when Cosby and city luminaries took the stage to toast and
roast him. Felipe Luciano, a Fox TV newsman read his poem ``Why I
Love the King.'' Rep. Jose Serrano spoke, and a proclamation from
Gov. George Pataki was read, declaring Oct. 20, 1999, as Tito
Puente Day in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 p.m., the tributes had stretched on too long for Puente's
wife, Margaret. ``Latin crowds don't want to hear speeches,'' she
said. ``They want to dance.'' As if on cue, the all-star band,
featuring the vocalist Tito Nieves and the flautist Dave Valentin,
fired up. The soul star Isaac Hayes jammed for a few numbers, as
did another of Puente's friends, the 91-year-old jazz great Lionel
Hampton. Wheeled onto the stage, he played vibraphone during ``How
High the Moon?''
</P>
<P>
   When Puente climbed on stage himself it was as packed as the
dance floor. He tried to thank all the vocalists he had ever worked
with, then gave up. ``I have 117 albums out; who can remember them
all?'' he asked, and then attacked his brightly painted timbales.
Wagging his tongue, rolling his eyes with cartoonish glee, he
circled one drumstick overhead like a lariat. A woman in a silver
lame dress gyrated her hips onstage beside him. Puente's frenetic
pace seemed to exhaust even the head-nodding rappers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito Puente at 76 still looks sexy,'' said Sandra Guzman,
editor in chief of Latina magazine. ``He is el hombre. He is el
macho.''
</P>
<P>
   By midnight, Puente paused at the exit for a farewell photo with
a woman in a feather wig and purple Lycra miniskirt, then his wife
put him in his black trench coat and they headed home. The king had
an early flight in the morning. Monday (April 26) he was to be in
Fort Lauderdale, for another club, another gig.
</P>
</TEXT>
