<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS CONDITIONED TO DEAL WITH PROBLEMS VIOLENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A Scottsdale friend was talking with his 10-year-old
daughter at dinner Wednesday night about the Colorado high school
shootings, trying to convey his alarm and despair.
</P>
<P>
   She gave him a quizzical look and a reply that spoke for
contemporary America, or at least the image of our society widely
held by young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why's it so tragic? It happens all the time,'' she shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into a similar reaction last year after watching ``Saving
Private'' ``Ryan'' with my teenage stepdaughter. Some of the battle
scenes were the most frightful I'd seen on film, and I asked how
she felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't all that impressed,'' she said. ``I've seen a lot of
stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   To blame the high-school slaughter on an indifference to
violence would oversimplify an event with many roots. But I think
it's one cause, one that has infected American kids from coast to
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by so much violence _ in real life and in pop culture
_ kids develop emotional immunity. On television alone, a typical
child will see as many as 8,000 murders and 100,000 acts of
violence before reaching high school. Is it any wonder their brains
become numb to it?
</P>
<P>
   Few psychologists think that exposure to fictional violence, no
matter how frequent or intense, turns teens into killers. But many
believe that violent images desensitize them, and in many cases,
make them less empathic. They also worry that kids who see violence
portrayed as justified self-defense are then able to rationalize
their own outbursts more readily.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in pop culture these days is less the exception than
the rule. Movies glorifying mayhem, blood-drenched video games and
noxious music lyrics are solidly mainstream. Death is talked about
dispassionately. News media, local TV news broadcasts in
particular, reinforce the view that anti-social behavior is
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rohde, an adolescent psychologist in Phoenix, said kids who
feel disconnected from their peers are especially prone to see
violence as an appropriate response to any serious offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two boys in Colorado apparently felt alienated,'' Rohde
said. ``Kids like that often feel powerless. So they want to get
power. When you put power and alienation together, you get
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys, Eric Harris, liked to play a homicidal computer
game called Doom, as do a lot of well-adjusted kids. For him,
however, the line between fantasy and reality didn't seem very
clear. Students who survived Tuesday's rampage said the killers
laughed as they went on their murderous binge, as if it were just a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Gratuitous use of violent imagery isn't confined to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Limited Inc., a national clothing chain, recently adopted an
employee campaign called WAR (Win at Retail) that features a
motivational film with battle scenes drawn from war movies. The
company told the ``Wall'' ``Street Journal'' that lagging sales
made it necessary to do something dramatic to shake up managers.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, CEO Leslie Wexner affirms, ``It is a war, and in
wars people really do live and people do die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be willing to shed fear and doubt,'' another
executive declares. ``Make the critical and key decisions
effectively and efficiently, then move in for the kill.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's film indulges in a kind of desperate, catastrophic
thinking that's common to troubled teenagers. Problems take on
life-or-death significance and can be resolved by only the most
extreme response. The two outcasts in Colorado evidently thought
killing their classmates was the only way they could get
satisfaction for the years they had been treated as losers.
</P>
<P>
   Much in our society has legitimized violence as an acceptable
way of dealing with conflict. If you have a grudge, grab a gun and
get even. We see it on the streets, where police are fatally shot
and road rage is on the rise, as well as on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   What happened at Columbine High School was a nightmarish
aberration, but the contributing social forces are thriving. That's
a good subject for more dinnertime conversations between kids and
parents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
