<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-23 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former White House deputy chief of staff Harold Ickes is not the
only high-powered political operative working hard behind the
scenes in New York to help Hillary Clinton get elected to the US
Senate next year. Thomas Doherty is also doing what he can for the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty is a close personal friend of Governor George Pataki. He
also serves as Pataki's chief dispenser of patronage and favors. If
you're wondering why the patronage czar of the Republican governor
of New York is trying to derail the Senate candidacy of the
Republican mayor of New York City, at a time when the GOP's control
of Congress is tenuous at best, well, let's see _ where would you
like to begin?
</P>
<P>
   The best place to start is the summer of 1994. Rudy Giuliani had
just been elected mayor. Senator Al D'Amato had just handpicked
George Pataki to be the New York GOP's gubernatorial candidate.
Previously, Pataki had served in obscurity as the state senator
from Peekskill, N.Y., a small Hudson River community one hour north
by northwest of Manhattan. Giuliani had never heard of Peekskill
and couldn't imagine that anyone from such a backwater could ever
be elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   In this opinion, many others concurred. Based on these good
opinions, Giuliani endorsed Governor Mario Cuomo's candidacy for a
fourth term, crossing party lines to do so. Unfortunately for
Giuliani, Cuomo had by then become such a crashing bore that even
the state senator from Peekskill looked like Teddy Roosevelt. And
so it came to pass that Pataki was elected governor, despite
Giuliani's best efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's treachery was neither forgotten nor forgiven. Four
years later, Pataki put pen to paper to describe exactly how much
he hated Giuliani for what he had done. The passages, though never
published between hard covers, were made readily available to
members of Albany's news-starved press corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no mere endorsement,'' wrote Pataki. ``Giuliani wasn't
just for Cuomo. It was an all-out trashing of our effort.'' Pataki
went on to characterize Giuliani's endorsement as ``a knife in the
back,'' that left him ``speechless,'' ``stunned'' and feeling ``as
if the wind had been knocked out of me, after a sucker punch.'' His
wife, wrote Pataki, was ``even more outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when nasty New York GOP political disputes were
mediated by Wall Street barons. The fat cats would gather, slap the
politicians around for misbehaving, and then lay down what was
known as Rockefeller's Law: no comity, no cash.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's loathing of Giuliani, however, makes Pataki's
hatred of the man seem almost benign. In the 1980s, Giuliani had
led the prosecutions of many Masters of the Universe. The memory of
leading investment bankers being hauled out of their offices in
handcuffs seared the consciousness of every last trader. There, but
for the grace of God, went them. So, rather than intervene, Wall
Street has stood by and let Giuliani suffer.
</P>
<P>
   National Republican leaders have every reason to broker a peace
deal, since it is manifestly in the party's interest to pick up the
Moynihan seat to protect against possible losses in other parts of
the country. But so far, only Texas Governor George W. Bush (who is
my cousin) has made it public that he fully supports Giuliani.
Everyone else has steered clear, for fear of alienating the
governor of the nation's second-largest state.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator Al D'Amato, whose patronage made possible
Giuliani's service as the US Attorney for the Southern District of
Manhattan, has also been mentioned as a possible peace maker, but
he too loathes Giuliani with white-heat intensity. D'Amato harbors
MacArthur-like political ambitions and sees Giuliani as a threat to
his return. Having been displaced by his former protege Pataki as
the leading GOP political figure in New York, D'Amato has no
interest in helping Giuliani ascend to the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Republicans, another group that might think it
wise to repair the breach, look to Albany for guidance. It is here
that Tom Doherty, dispenser of patronage and favors, serves as a
kind of political directory assistance. The message Republicans
hear from Doherty is succinct: Help Giuliani and you're out of
business with the governor. Last Monday, Doherty took the unusual
step of reiterating this message in the pages of the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   It is an axiom of modern American politics that protracted
primary battles make victory in the general election much harder to
achieve. Forces loyal to Governor Pataki are actively trying to
recruit a primary challenger to Rudy Giuliani. They may or may not
succeed, but the damage they do in the interim will have its
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of all these Republicans conspiring to clear
Hillary Clinton's path to the Senate is a wonder to behold. But as
the TV detective Kojak once said, ``Hey, baby, it's New York.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
