</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-FASHIONS-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY FASHIONS: TODAY'S CLOTHES NOT ALL SUGAR AND SPICE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Country fashion has changed so much that it may no
longer be a recognizable style.
</P>
<P>
   When Emma Lee Turney organized the first Round Top Antiques Fair
31 years ago, traveling to a small Texas town to buy fine antiques
was an odd idea to city slickers. But not any odder than the notion
of dressing up to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, high-heels-and-pantyhose women from the city tended
to dress down for the country, emulating the natives or recapturing
their own roots. They were, as they told themselves, ``country when
country wasn't cool,'' with a nod to the country-western song, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   But in Texas, Turney's Round Top shows, as well as a general
back-to-the-country movement, changed all that. In the newly
acceptable country dress, denim and diamonds were not out of the
question. Prairie skirts ruled the rural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen country fashion change from Levi Strauss to Ralph
Lauren and watched denim go from country hick to country chic,''
Turney said.
</P>
<P>
   Turney, along with Beverly Harris, is author of ``Denim and
Diamonds`` (C. Going Press, $35), a book that last year chronicled
the first 30 years of the Round Top show. Now the show has grown to
include two more Turney sites, and many more dealers set up
temporary shop in Round Top, as well as nearby Carmine, Warrenton
and Shelby. As the show evolved, so did country dress.
</P>
<P>
   Now fashion is changing again, but the Round Top show remains a
good place to get a handle on country dress _ if there is such a
thing today _ as shoppers and browsers arrive in vehicles from
Model T Fords to Mercedeses.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular vehicles are the roomy and utilitarian sport
utility vehicles, and this trend to utilitarianism and comfort
carries into fashion. As Lauren graduated from his country clothes
into Southwest-inspired fashions, and now active-sports-inspired
clothing, so have customers.
</P>
<P>
   Urban sprawl has blurred the boundaries between city and
country, so that now clothing also tends to cross boundaries. Today
city folks dress down for work, and that ethic is spilling over to
country dress.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the glitz is gone. As in city dressing today, jeans and
blue denim are increasingly in the minority, although blue is still
the most popular nonurban neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Khaki _ and, this time of year, white _ clothing far exceeds
indigo blues and denims in what is known as the ``city casual''
look. In fact, most fashions at the recent semiannual Round Top
Antiques Fair looked as if they were purchased from Old Navy, the
Gap or Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   City casual calls for pants, shorts or capris, with a few
miniskirts and long skirts. Unlike in rodeo season, footwear in
warm weather is either athletic shoes, sandals or mules. As fire
ants continue to proliferate, closed shoes are becoming more of a
country necessity.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe/Southwestern look remains a key trend in the
country. Colors tend to black, browns and beiges, sunrise and
sunset golds and peaches, and many shades of green, from celadon to
olive.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular fabrics are linen, cotton, rayon or blends of
these fibers, but washable linen is the innovation most responsible
for this look, especially that with the Flax label.
</P>
<P>
   At Round Top, LaNell Arndt, owner of Nellie's Boutique &AMP; Gallery
in Brenham, said washable linens have lured women away from other
styles. Most of the Flax garments also fit loosely and ``breathe''
during the warm, humid months, especially this season's new
seersucker linens.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Sante Fe-look garments worn today fall straight or
in A-line shapes from the shoulders, with skirts slit up the sides
for comfort and ease. Styles include sleeveless dresses and jumpers
or easy two- or three-piece coordinates with straight or broomstick
skirts. Accessories are turquoise, coral and silver jewelry, silver
concho belts and wide-brimmed straw hats.
</P>
<P>
   While hand-painting on garments _ blue geese, bluebonnets, etc.
_ isn't being done much anymore on country clothing, Sante Fe
styles seem to have only recently discovered it. Now designers of
Santa Fe styles are appliqueing painted patches and pockets on
dresses, skirts and tops.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Another trend, perhaps the closest to past country dress, is
``English garden chic.'' This style includes florals, ginghams and
patchwork, often all in the same garment, and again in fabrics of
cotton, linen or blends that include rayon.
</P>
<P>
   Jackets, smocks and jumpers made of thick floral or other
printed cotton drapery fabrics are popular, as are aprons made to
wear over dresses and separates.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Ballard, whose business, Forever, Rebecca, is in Flint,
Texas, sells a chintz floral cover-up apron with red gingham trim
($40) in a pattern she calls her ``grandma's apron.''
</P>
<P>
   Overalls and overall jumpers are as popular for women as for
children, with the women's wear in fabrics such as pink linen. But
again, these are items for city and country wear.
</P>
<P>
   Novelty items include drapery-fabric backpacks, lace-trimmed
socks and umbrellas with handles made from silver cutlery, so a
woman can choose her umbrella to match her wedding silver.
</P>
<P>
   Country clothing made from embroidered vintage dresser scarves
and napkins, so popular only a few years ago, is seldom seen today.
While embroidery is gaining popularity in city wear, it is falling
out of favor beyond the beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Pony- and cow-printed hide bags are catching on, while leopard
and zebra have moved beyond the zoo-zone no-nos. Raffia and
straw-pouch or basket-type bags are cool again.
</P>
<P>
   Other city trends creeping into country duds include pockets
that negate the need for purses. One sees these even on
garden-print long dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Authentic American Indian jewelry is enjoying a revival, not
only on the fashion runways of the world but in the country _ and
for both men and women. For women, at least, this stems from the
affinity of today's washable linen separates for Indian jewelry of
silver and natural semiprecious, often chunky stones.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of country dress is that it must lend itself to
outdoor wear, not air-conditioned confines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a poll yesterday, and three out of four people around
here aren't wearing underwear,'' said dealer Cynthia Anderson of
Kerrville.
</P>
<P>
   Brassieres are usually the first to go when the thermometer
climbs toward the 90-degree mark; other unmentionables are just
that.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, layering makes country dress easier with the addition
of thick American Indian-inspired sweaters or leather, suede or fur
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
