r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-GUNS-     04-23 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-GUN LEGISLATOR HAUNTED BY COLORADO SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ His family in Colorado Springs is living
under police protection because of death threats. He broke into
tears during an interview with a newspaper reporter.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Doug Dean, fairly or not, has become the focus of
anger in the aftermath of Tuesday's slaughter of 12 students and a
teacher by two schoolmates, who then took their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   As the state House majority leader in Colorado, Dean, a
Republican, was the sponsor of two bills that prompted the most
heated gun-control debate in the state's history. One would have
enabled most people to carry concealed weapons, while the other
would have eradicated rigid anti-gun rules in Denver that city
officials credit with reducing violent crimes by 40 percent in the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   And on the day of the massacre at Columbine High School, the
state House of Representatives was poised to pass both of them.
</P>
<P>
   While Dean's bills, since withdrawn, enjoyed the support of most
state politicians _ with strong Republican majorities in the House
and Senate _ it had appalled Denver's political leadership and
placed Dean in what now appears to be a remarkably vulnerable
position.
</P>
<P>
   To understand Dean's problem, it is necessary to travel back to
1993, when Denver, a city of 580,000 in a metropolitan area of
slightly more than 2 million, experienced what is remembered as its
``Summer of Violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Drive-by shootings ruled the headlines. A small child was killed
by a random bullet. The city responded by passing some of the most
restrictive anti-gun legislation in the nation. The City Council
banned ownership of all assault weapons, required safe storage of
guns at home, made it illegal to carry guns on hips and prohibited
firearms in city parks. Guns within reach of an automobile driver
were also forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Denver has tried pretty hard to control guns and
there (in Littleton), but for the grace of God go we,'' said
Jennifer Mouton, head of the city planning department.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver ordinances, though not by design, raised the
possibility that hunters passing through the city might be subject
to arrest if their guns were within reach. The National Rifle
Association, according to some politicians here, jumped on that
apparent unfairness and took it to the Legislature for redress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are large areas of rural Colorado where people have
grown up with guns and hunted. Guns are part of the culture.
They're not associated with crime,'' said House Minority Leader Ken
Gordon, a former public defender from Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The other view was hardened, he said, by ``the well-publicized
incident a couple of years ago where a mother bought her
15-year-old son a pistol for his birthday and he went out and
killed somebody. It was a completely unprovoked shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed, he said, was essentially a battle between
Colorado's two populations _ the rural people and the urbanites,
most of them living around Denver.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle escalated, gun control liberalization bills began
to appear on the floor of the House. One, ironically, would have
permitted guns in schools (though not carried by students).
</P>
<P>
   That was not forgotten this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have actually said that if the teachers
in Littleton had been armed, this could have been stopped,'' said
Happy Haines, president of the Denver City Council.
</P>
<P>
   The idea died when Gov. Bill Owens, a Republican and supporter
of concealed weapons laws, declared that he would not support guns
on campus. That followed large demonstrations against the idea on
the steps of the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The gun control liberalization bills were presented or endorsed
by Dean. He finally came up with two that were on the verge of
being passed and signed by Owens.
</P>
<P>
   One, said Denver District Attorney Bill Ritter, ``would have
preempted cities from passing any (gun control) laws more
restrictive than the state statute.''
</P>
<P>
   The other would have made it mandatory to issue concealed
weapons permits to anyone who was not a convicted felon, legally
mentally ill or obviously unsuitable to carry a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, it was the first bill that created the greatest
concern, because it meant that most of the legislation adopted by
the city would have been usurped.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've heard from Denver police is that they don't find
firearms in cars anymore because of those ordinances,'' said Ted
Pascoe of the Coalition Against Gun Violence, an offshoot of the
Denver-based chapter of the Physicians for Social Responsibility.
``The Denver ordinances were about to be preempted.''
</P>
<P>
   After the killing spree at the suburban high school, Dean
withdrew both bills from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That has not prevented him from being a target of hatred for
outraged citizens shocked by the mass murder in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten death threats because of his advocacy,'' said
Gordon, the minority leader who had fervently campaigned against
both of Dean's bills. ``I'm feeling bad for him because, even
though I disagreed with him, I think he's advocated in good
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Reimer, an aide to Dean, said: ``Doug is just destroyed by
this. There have been threats against his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst of it came Wednesday, the day after the shooting.
``The phone calls that came in _ `You have blood on your hands' _
just devastated him, absolutely devastated him,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
