<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REFRESHER COURSE ON COMPUTER BASICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing a computing column that's aimed at novice to
intermediate users is not an easy task. The trick is to keep things
clear and understandable for newcomers, but not put the more
techno-savvy folks to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, I usually make certain assumptions about readers'
knowledge. I figure most users of Windows 95/98 know what the
desktop is; how to launch programs using the Start menu; how to
find things on a hard drive using either My Computer or the Find
command; and how to copy files from one drive to another.
</P>
<P>
   I also presume users know the difference between hard drive
space and memory; where a file that's been downloaded from the
Internet gets stored; and what a Web browser is.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, often those assumptions are false. Judging from
my mail, there are a lot of people out there who don't know these
computing basics. They're not necessarily dumb _ these just aren't
the kinds of things they feel they need cluttering up their
everyday lives. That is, until they run into a jam and get
frustrated with trying to fix a problem themselves, or feel
overwhelmed by the jargon-laden patter of a technical support
person.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is essentially Computing 101 for beginning Windows
users _ some of the very basic things you need to know. This isn't
everything, mind you, but it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terms and concepts. &LR;  First, you'll need to know what's what.
</P>
<P>
   The big open area on your monitor where you see icons and where
programs appear is called the desktop. The bar at the bottom of the
screen that includes the Start button, as well as buttons that
correspond to each program, is called the taskbar. The boxed-off
area on the right side of the taskbar where the clock and possibly
some small icons are located is the system tray. My Computer,
usually located in the upper-left-hand corner of the desktop, is
another name for the Explorer _ a program that lets you see the
files stored on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The icons on your desktop, in the Explorer and in the system
tray mean different things. Most, but not all, of the desktop icons
are shortcuts _ they are pointers to files that start specific
programs. If you delete a shortcut, you do not delete the file
itself _ just the pointer to it. Most shortcuts have a small arrow
in the lower left corner of the icon.
</P>
<P>
   The icons in the system tray are programs that are running in a
kind of ``suspended animation'' state in the background. They
usually are waiting for some type of action _ the press of a
button, behavior that looks like a virus or a timed event _ before
they wake up and do something. You can usually find out more about
what they do by holding your mouse cursor over them, or by clicking
on them with the left or right mouse buttons.
</P>
<P>
   The icons you see when you open My Computer are the files and
folders stored on your hard drive. Delete these, and you have
actually removed the files _ and lost their functions.
</P>
<P>
   Your hard drive, by the way, is not the same thing as your
computer's memory. The hard drive is where your programs and the
documents they create are permanently stored. The computer's memory
is where programs are loaded when they are launched. You can think
of your hard drive as a book, and memory as your brain. When you
open a book and read the words there, they ``move'' from the page
into your brain, where you think about them and store them in your
own form of memory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Work those files. &LR;  Now that you know what they are, what can
you do with them?
</P>
<P>
   Moving files from one place to another is as easy as picking
them up and moving them by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you want to copy some files from a folder on your hard
drive called Documents onto a floppy disk. You'd open My Computer
and see several icons _ they'll represent your hard drive (usually
C:), your CD-ROM drive, your floppy drive, a folder called Printers
and another called Dialup Networking. Double-click on the C: drive,
and you'll see the first level of folders available to you. I say
``first level'' because you can have folders within folders. But in
this case, let's presume the Documents folder is on this first
level.
</P>
<P>
   Find the folder, double-click on it, then find the file you
want. Next, if you have Windows set up to open each folder in the
same window, go back to My Computer and double-click on it again to
open a second window. Put your floppy disk in the A: drive and
double-click on the floppy-disk icon in the second window.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the windows showing the Documents folder and the A:
drive contents side by side; click on the file you want, hold down
the mouse button, and drag the file from the Documents window into
the A: drive window, and release.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to move the file instead of just copying it _ so it
no longer resides in the Documents folder _ click with your right
mouse button and hold that down as you drag. When you release,
you'll get a menu that lets you choose to move rather than copy.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use just one window, you can drag the file
directly to the A: drive icon in the left pane of the Explorer
window.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a tip. Most Windows 95/98 systems are configured to
allow you to copy a file to the A: drive just by using the right
mouse button. Right-click on the desired file, choose Send to ...
and then click on the A: drive icon in the menu that appears.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Download blues. Where did that file go? &LR;  When you download a
file from the Internet using either of the major Web browsers
(Internet Explorer or Netscape Communicator/Navigator), a window
opens that lets you designate where on your hard drive it can be
saved. Note the name of this folder, which appears in a field at
the top of the window called ``Save in ...'' If you want to see
where this folder is in relation to the rest of your hard drive,
click on the down arrow to the right of your name. You'll see a
kind of map that gives more information about its location.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use this map to save the folder in a different
place. When the map appears, click on your C: drive, and in the
window beneath you'll see all the folders on your C: drive. Choose
a folder to save the file in. You can even create a new folder in
this window _ named, say, ``download'' _ by right-clicking in an
open area of the window, choosing New, then Folder.
</P>
<P>
   Open the folder by double-clicking on it, then click the Save
button. Now you'll know where your file is.
</P>
<P>
   If you still can't find it, there's still hope. Click the Start
button, choose Find, then Files or Folders. From the box that
appears you can search for the file by name, or even by just a part
of its name.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(a)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
