<HEADER>
A0769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PORTER-MEDICINE-2TAKE     04-23 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTER-MEDICINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROY PORTER, A GLUTTON FOR HISTORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British medical historian Roy Porter was embarking
on his first sabbatical in nearly three decades of frenetic
teaching and writing when he fell spectacularly ill last fall. ``I
got a gigantically enlarged testicle,'' he said cheerfully. What
was particularly notable about his condition, which turned out to
be a cluster of easily removable benign cysts, was that it was the
first time he had been sick in decades.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Porter's unexpected descent into the world of the
unwell was a fine illustration of one of his favorite observations,
that illness of the body often has its roots in the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been teaching nonstop for 27 years, and I've been healthy
for 27 years,'' he said recently in his vast, cluttered cavern of
an office at the Wellcome Institute for the History of Medicine,
where he is a professor of the social history of medicine. ``And
within a fortnight of taking sabbatical leave, when I finally had
nothing urgent to do, I got sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter has not had much time to be sick. He has written more
than three dozen books on topics ranging from the Industrial
Revolution to madness through the ages to the history of London.
(His latest book, written with G.S. Rousseau, is on the history of
gout.)
</P>
<P>
   Through them all he has earned a reputation as an expert who can
bring potentially dry subjects to life, making his work appreciated
as much by the general public as by specialists. He is the model of
a popular historian _ appearing on talk shows, writing book
reviews, being consulted by governments _ but is still admired by
academics for the rigor of his research and the sweep of his
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The books crammed onto his shelves reflect his eclectic
interests and his twin obsessions, the history of the 18th century
and the history of medicine. This year he is off in yet another
direction. ``I'm deep into the roots of feminism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he produced ``The Greatest Benefit to Mankind: A
Medical History of Humanity'' (W.W. Norton), a breathtakingly
thorough survey of medicine, its place in society and its
implications for civilization from the time of the ancient Greeks,
when Hippocrates devised his famous oath, to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The book might have lived a worthy but generally unacknowledged
existence if it had not been authoritative and enthusiastic enough
to appeal to a lay audience. The same could be said of Porter. With
his longish gray hair and shaggy, unshaven face, his black leather
jacket and his heavy use of gold necklaces, rings and bracelets
(his father repaired jewelry for a living, instilling a lifelong
taste for adornment in his son), he looks like a 52-year-old
undergraduate or the extremely cool college professor you never
had. What he does not look like is the kind of person whom The
Economist would call ``a formidably learned man,'' as it did in a
typically glowing review of his medical history.
</P>
<P>
   The book's title comes from Samuel Johnson, who had endless
faith in medicine's capacity to improve the world, but Porter
doesn't exactly agree. ``I kind of wanted the publishers to put a
question mark at the end of it,'' he said. (They didn't.) ``I'm a
great fan of Samuel Johnson, but I didn't want people to take the
title as an assertion. I wanted them to take it as a possibility. I
hope that I raise it as a question rather than a certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he does. While some reviewers said that Porter's book
reflected a Whig view of history, meaning that it assumed linear,
cumulative progress in which today was always better than
yesterday, the author doesn't see it that way. Medicine, he said,
has by no means been one long march toward something better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some areas in which medicine has really advanced and
made general progress,'' he said. ``But there are other areas where
it's made virtually no advance at all. And there are others in
which it's been pretty counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the great paradoxes of today, Porter believes, is that as
medicine becomes more sophisticated and develops better strategies
for diagnosing and treating illness, so the world at large becomes
increasingly anxious about health and mortality.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly to do with loss of faith. Now that fewer people,
especially in the Western world, believe that life is a
transitional phase leading to immortality, they are left with
nothing to believe in after death. So they put their faith in
technology and in doctors, who, Porter says, are less and less
equipped to deal with patients as humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are generally reassured these days that when they're
going to have surgery, there's an enormous amount of expertise and
they're not going to get hurt,'' Porter said. ``At the same time,
there's also a sense that the machinery is out of control. You're
making advances, and the consequence of that is that things become
too technical, too mysterious, too expensive, too complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   What really bothers Porter is the tendency to regard each new
breakthrough as the ultimate panacea. ``Nowadays, with the genome
project, people might say that all diseases have a genetic basis,''
he explained. ``In 20 years, they'll realize it was a gigantic
mistake, in the way that throughout history almost all obsessional
monocausal theories about how there's one model for disease _
they're all due to the humors or all due to the devil or all due to
bacteria or genetics _ turn out to be wrong because the human body
is so complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter came to his area of interest in a roundabout way. A
clever, bookish boy from a nonacademic family in South London
(``They look at me with total pity,'' he said), he advanced by
brains and ambition to Christ College, Cambridge, where Charles
Darwin once studied. He was taught history by Jack Plum, who he
said ``had a vision of history as being accessible to everybody''
and who infused him with a love of the 18th century. Being in
Darwin's old college sent him off on other paths, through geology
and then medicine and then the role of health and healing in
society.
</P>
<P>
   Porter has a historian's eye for detail. ``If I've made a
contribution to the social history of medicine, it's that I got
interested in terms of trying to see it from the point of view of
sick people,'' he said. This means his book is sprinkled with
engaging anecdotes and amusing, telling tangents taken from the
primary sources into which he loves to sink his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   History, he believes, should be as rooted in detail, and as
messy, as life itself. ``Specificities _ people, facts, statements,
quotations _ these are the sort of nuggets which are real and which
stick in the mind and excite me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a snobbery about theory,'' he went on. ``For example,
the post-modernists believe that somehow it is the academic's duty
to come up with high-level generalizations which have a kind of
intellectual loftiness to them. That's all very well _ I've got no
beef against other people doing that kind of thing _ but it's
always seemed to me that reality, society and my life are complex
and contradictory and full of opposites and that therefore my view
of history will be like that as well. Don't think there's anything
conclusive about history. It is a culmination of lots of different
pulls and drives and tendencies and trends. There's no master
narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   If Porter is fascinated by health, he is equally interested in
death. After all, the better medicine gets, the longer people live,
which raises profound questions about whether it is better to live
a diminished life than not to live at all. After a period in which
death was almost a taboo subject, he said people in the late 20th
century are again obsessed with it. Porter calls it an ``age of
anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure whether it's the fear of oblivion that's causing
the anxiety or the fear of having a bad death,'' Porter said. ``In
the past, there was a theater about dying and you stage-managed
your illness and your death. You prepared to die and had your
speech ready.'' (One of Porter's favorites: the deathbed words of
Oscar Wilde, who reportedly said, ``My wallpaper and I are fighting
a duel to the death. One or the other of us has to go.'')
</P>
<P>
   But people are becoming moved once more, he said, by the thought
of a ``good death.'' Porter certainly intends to have one. Ideally
he would like to die while gardening, and he would like it to be
quick, although not so quick as to deny him the opportunity of
uttering his final bon mot. ``I quite like the idea of being
conscious of dying, but actually in the middle of doing something
at the time, rather than going through a long process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After that he plans to donate his body to science. ``They can do
anything they like with me,'' he said. ``They can even eat me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
