<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0424-     04-23 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0424-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COERCION USED TO MOVE KOSOVO REFUGEES TO BETTER SITES
 &HT;    575&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Relief officials decried Albanian authorities'
coerced removal of Kosovar refugees from this overburdened city
Friday, but forced relocation may be the only effective tactic to
get them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said please do not use violence,'' said Jacques
Franquin, spokesman here for the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR), acknowledging Friday that Albanian police had
compelled some refugees to leave. The agency, he said, protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been expelled from Kosovo. Once is enough,''
Franquin said.
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up program urging voluntary departures has convinced
some refugees to leave, but not nearly the tens of thousands that
relief agencies say will be necessary to make places for a
potential influx of more escapees from Serbian ethnic cleansing in
the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday an estimated 4,500 refugees departed, according to the
aid agency, which was fewer than were leaving before the campaign
began. Earlier, officials had expressed hopes of relocating perhaps
10,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 200 refugees crossed over the border from Kosovo
Friday, but a torrent of wounded and exhausted people could be
released any time. In a bizarre twist, one group of 60 men arrived
without their wives and children, whom they said had been held back
by Serbian Yugoslav forces. Routinely, men -- especially young men
-- have been kept.
</P>
<P>
   Other pressures to vacate this place include fears that summer
conditions could be catastrophic, or that the Serbs' increasing
cross-border assaults into Albanian territory could target these
camps any day.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bad news is the city's estimate that by high summer
the water supply will stand at only one-third its present level.
</P>
<P>
   And the current spring flush of mountain melt, coupled with
unusually heavy rains, has barely been sufficient to meet the needs
of the additional 120,000 or more refugees piled on top of this
city whose normal population is only 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Local thugs and mafia groups also are a growing problem,
organizing thefts of everything from food stocks to refugees'
property.
</P>
<P>
   But these disadvantages are dwarfed by the refugees' wish to
stay as close as they can to home.
</P>
<P>
   The family of 12-year-old Bujar Mecini lost its single most
valuable possession when its tractor was stolen in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his family is willing to accept the risk and to tolerate
the mud swamp surrounding cold tents that are leaking water, in
order to stay close to relatives still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to leave,'' the boy said. ``All the men have
stayed there. My father is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   His camp on the outskirts of town was the site of a snafu that
only aggravated the problem.
</P>
<P>
   When the information campaign started Thursday to induce
refugees to leave for less crowded and safer areas, hundreds of
people here packed up and got ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the morning, we thought all these people will go, so we
will go too. We didn't want to stay here alone,'' said Sherife
Xhemajli, a 28-year-old mother here with eight relatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, the promised buses never came. So the families
unpacked, and many said Friday after considering the options that
they would not bother to try it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about how they didn't tell us we would go to better
houses,'' she said. ``We cannot accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials said the city government somehow failed to get
buses out to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Those who were sitting on buses in the center of town at noon
Friday were predominantly people who had some money or had family
or friends awaiting them elsewhere in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   On one bus, a family was heading to the port of Durres where a
relative from abroad had found them a house. Another family heading
to Rreshen had sent an envoy ahead to rent a house there, where
prices are cheaper. Families on a bus going to Berat had relatives
there.
</P>
<P>
   Few refugee families are so lucky. Most who agree to leave will
be heading to unknown accommodations, perhaps a gymnasium or
crowding into a private home, and that is another reason they are
reluctant to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian police here overcame that reluctance Thursday by
simply demanding that scores of tractors be moved from a parking
area in the center of the city, according to eyewitnesses and aid
officials. The people who have been living in open wagons attached
to the tractors were rounded up and put on buses.
</P>
<P>
   Families were separated because the tractor driver usually
stayed to look after the machine, while his family headed out on a
bus.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the tactics employed with the few tractors still
remaining at the site were more gentle. Police were demanding the
tractors and wagons be moved, but were permitting refugees to park
in another part of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where it is better and where it is worse,'' said
a confused Haxhi Haxhaj, 32, who was preparing to drive his family
of 16 people somewhere the police had yet to specify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they told us to stay in Kukes. Maybe there they will
tell us to leave too and go some place else,'' he said. ``I'm
afraid of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
