<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-CONTRACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams faces cap problems in getting top rookie contract
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although his client slipped to the sixth spot in the first round
of the NFL draft, agent Leland Hardy insisted that Heisman tailback
Ricky Williams should be awarded a contract ``commensurate with the
greatest player ever in the college game.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the New Orleans Saints agree with Hardy, they can't
give Williams the best deal in this year's draft. Because they had
the first one-player draft in NFL history, the Saints were awarded
one of the smallest pools of money for signing rookies. The maximum
aggregate salary-cap room that New Orleans is permitted to use on
its 1999 rookies is $1,749,185, the second-lowest total of any team
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some published reports Thursday erroneously placed the New
Orleans rookie pool at $1.479 million. But not even the additional
$270,000 can help Williams and Hardy in their pursuit of this
year's highest rookie contract. Even if the former Texas star
accepts the lowest possible base salary, in order to maximize his
signing bonus, the most up-front money he can earn is $9.15
million-$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch, the first overall pick, received
a signing bonus of $12.25 million from the Cleveland Browns. Couch
signed a seven-year contract worth $48 million and the deal voids
after three seasons if the quarterbacks achieves predetermined
performance levels.
</P>
<P>
   Saints general manager Bill Kuharich said Thursday that the team
is ``not married'' to the concept of voidable years. But to satisfy
the demands Hardy is certain to make, the Saints probably will
follow the same contract structure the Browns used with Couch.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, who had 11 selections during the weekend, have the
league's highest rookie-pool figure, $5.165 million.
</P>
<P>
   1999 ROOKIE POOL TOTALS
</P>
<P>
   The maximum salary-cap totals each NFL team can spend on its
rookies in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   1. Cleveland, $5,165,897; 2. Arizona, $4,605,838 3.
Philadelphia, $4,472,295 4. Chicago, $4,367,098 5. Cincinnati,
$4,161,202. 6. Minnesota, $3,888,436; 7. Denver, $3,695,756; 8.
Indianapolis, $3,635,638; 9. Pittsburgh, $3,617,785; 10. Green Bay,
$3,593,004. 11. New England, $3,401,861; 12. St. Louis, $3,370,031;
13. Detroit, $3,362,357; 14. Tampa Bay, $3,070,423; 15. Washington,
$3,027,415. 16. New York Giants, $2,959,528; 17. Buffalo,
$2,946,778; 18. Tennessee, $2,898,770; 19. Atlanta, $2,895,577; 20.
Dallas, $2,753,188. 21. Jacksonville, $2,588,648; 22. Kansas City,
$2,591,718; 23. Oakland, $2,546,575; 24. San Francisco, $2,482,789;
25. Miami, $2,420,065. 26. Seattle, $2,394,492; 27. New York Jets,
$1,963,025; 28. Baltimore, $1,962,372; 29. Carolina, $1,864,563;
30. New Orleans, $1,749,185; 31. San Diego, $1,616,642.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
