<P>
   BIZ-MIDSTREAM (Undated) _ Webster's Third New International
Dictionary defines the phrase ``miss the boat'' as ``to blunder
badly by failing to grasp an opportunity in time.'' A 1999 edition
of that dictionary might add, ``e.g., to have missed buying certain
Internet stocks.'' Real or possible losses in those stocks are no
longer what keep many middle-aged investors on edge. Rather, it is
the huge gains we could have had. By James Schembari. (Moved).
</P>
