A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIALSECURITY-0424-C     04-23 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIALSECURITY-0424-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS SAY THEY HAVEN'T ABANDONED SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stung by criticism from President Clinton, House
leaders Friday denied reports they have abandoned efforts to reform
Social Security until after the next election.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Friday's (ITALICS) New York Times (END ITALIC)
</P>
<P>
   that said Republican leaders had decided it would be too risky
to adopt fundamental changes in the nation's popular retirement
program was widely repeated by other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chided Republicans early Friday for being ``either
unable or unwilling to face up to the challenge of strengthening
Social Security. That is not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, Republican leaders declared their intent to
seek a ``bipartisan solution,'' to Social Security's long-term
problems.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert issued a statement calling the
(ITALICS) Times (END ITALICS) story ``not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of our four agenda items to secure America's future,
Republicans have strengthening retirement security topping the list
that also includes improving education, fortifying national
security and providing middle-class tax relief,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   The (ITALICS) Times (END ITALICS) said the GOP leadership had
decided not to pursue Social Security reform even though key
Republican lawmakers were on the verge of unveiling a proposal
based on using the projected federal surplus to finance a tax cut.
Individuals could then use the money that otherwise would have been
paid in taxes to invest in individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Republican from Fort Lauderdale who
chairs the Ways and Means Social Security subcommittee and has been
drafting the GOP proposal, was quoted as saying he would not push
the bill without support from the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement issued Friday afternoon, Shaw said he and
Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, planned to
introduce their legislation soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that now is the time to seize the
opportunity to
</P>
<P>
   strengthen this vital program,'' Shaw said. ``We have a strong
economy and a budget surplus. If we do nothing, we will end up
face-to-face with a disastrous situation. It is my hope that my
colleagues and our president will join us so that we can work
together for the good of our children and
</P>
<P>
   grandchildren. To succeed, and I believe we will, we must go
forward in a
</P>
<P>
   bipartisan way.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer also issued a statement saying he was ``fully committed
to strengthening and modernizing Social Security for the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless changes are made, the Social Security trust fund reserve
is expected to be depleted in 2034. At that time, Social Security
would be able to pay only 75 percent of monthly benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
