<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WOMEN-SERIES-NYT     04-23 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WOMEN-SERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN DRIVERS GET A SERIES OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ore., Wash.)  (See also CARS-WOMEN-SMITH) 
(mk) 
 By LESLEY HAZLETON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For three days in January, men were shut out of the Road Atlanta
race track in Georgia. All the drivers were women, there to vie for
a place in an automotive league of their own: the new Women's
Global GT Series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lilian Bryner, a former commercial pilot from Switzerland,
arrived with jet lag, having flown in that morning from her home in
Lugano. She had never driven on the 12-turn, 2.54-mile track, but
qualified easily with five fast laps. Then she flew out that
afternoon to Florida, where she finished fourth, in a field of 78,
in the 24 Hours of Daytona. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Bashford, who won the Jamieson Award as Britain's fastest
woman driver last year, was hoping the series could help women
crash through the glass ceiling at the highest levels of auto
racing. ``Right now, you have to be three times better than Michael
Schumacher,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racers like Bryner and Bashford came from three continents, 11
countries, nearly every state and just about every form of auto
racing, from Formula One to tiny karts. But not every top woman
racer turned up. The series' executive director, Lyn St. James, got
faxes and e-mail messages from some of them accusing her of
organizing a powder-puff derby, of running nothing more than a
showcase, even of bringing racing down to the level of mud
wrestling by making a display of women racing women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were quite volatile,'' she said, then grinned and added,
``but I guess I was pretty volatile at first, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Don Panoz, the promoter who owns Road Atlanta, first
approached her with the idea of a women's series, she turned him
down. ``I said: `This is one of the few sports where women can
compete equally with men. The car doesn't know the gender of the
person behind the wheel. So why would we want to separate
ourselves? We're already there.''' She paused, then added, ``We may
be invisible, but we are there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That invisibility is precisely what prompted her to reconsider
Panoz's offer. ``This series is a way of putting women on the
map,'' she said. ``A showcase? Certainly. A showcase can launch
careers, and that's what this is all about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked why some women would turn down the opportunity, St. James
picked her words carefully. ``Their credibility is established
because of their singularity. The tendency is to think it's somehow
OK to lose if you're the only woman. But it's never OK. `You did
well for a woman' is not acceptable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At age 54, Divina Galica, a four-time Olympic skier who now
teaches competitive driving at the Skip Barber Racing School, was
one of the oldest women to qualify. ``When I started 25 years ago,
there were only three or four women who could drive as fast as I
could,'' she said. ``Now half of them here have the potential to
beat me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of those who might beat her in the future is Jenny Hohfelt,
a 17-year-old kart champion who had never shifted a gear until four
weeks before qualifying. Jockey-sized and soft-spoken, she seemed
unfazed by the prospect of competing against the world's best women
drivers. ``There's a lot of really tough drivers here,'' she said
calmly. ``In fact, some of them have been racing longer than I've
been living.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not a single woman at Road Atlanta even mentioned the photogenic
potential of a winner's taking off her helmet and shaking loose a
cascade of hair. They left that to the men, who were where the
women usually are _ behind the fences, stopwatches and press
releases in hand, nervously watching as wives, girlfriends,
daughters _ and in one case, mother _ competed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bashford's husband accepted his role as the cheering section
with delight. ``I love seeing the men's faces when she gets out of
the car after a race and they realize they've just lost to a
woman,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But potential sponsors seem less enthused. Although auto racing
is America's biggest spectator sport, and though the Women's Global
GT Series would seem as good a match for chain stores, soft-drink
companies and gasoline brands as any other series, no major sponsor
had emerged by the time the first race was run.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz had invested $3 million in building the 400-horsepower GT
cars for the series, but competitors still had to find their own
sponsors or cover their costs, including insurance and a $3,000
entrance fee for each of the seven races in the women's series. And
no prize money had been lined up.
</P>
<P>
   So although many of the world's fastest women drivers had
qualified for the series, finances kept most of them away on the
inaugural day. Most of those on the starting grid were relative
unknowns. Yet the race provided a spectacularly close-fought battle
among two unexpected contenders and one seasoned racer: Audrey
Zavodsky, a registered nurse and teacher from Michigan; Kiki
Wolfkill, a Microsoft art designer from Seattle who specializes in
computer racing games, and Cindi Lux of Oregon, who started as the
favorite after posting the fastest qualifying times. Lux finished
third behind Zavodsky, in first, and Wolfkill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will the series propel Zavodsky's and Wolfkill's careers and
make them stars, as St. James intends? Or will the lack of
financing persist? Lux is sure which way it will go. ``You'll
see,'' she said. ``Now that we have this series, a lot of men are
going to want to come out and play on the track with us as much as
we want to play with them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, that group of men will include some
sponsors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
