<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-REVISITED-ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF AN OVERAGE `STAR WARS' CONSCRIPT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Force wasn't with me, and my little niece and nephew didn't
like it. I am, after all, their epic-making uncle, the one who
orchestrates sea battles in the bathtub, death scenes in the
elevator and costume dramas on demand.
</P>
<P>
   But when ``Star Wars'' became part of their world view (their
parents bought the trilogy on video last year) they started
spinning into a Luke- and Leia-centric universe without me.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen only the very first episode 20 years ago, when I was
a college freshman, remembered little about it and didn't even know
what it meant to be a Jedi. I lived in darkness. And with ``Star
Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' coming at us with meteoric
force, I decided that as a good uncle (italics)and(end italics) a
good American, I'd better get up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday last month, with Madeleine, almost 7, and Ian, 4, as
my pilots, I began my voyage into the well-known unknown by
slipping the first episode (confoundingly called Episode IV) into
the VCR. Immediately, I was in trouble. Did I actually have to
understand what all those words scrolling into the cosmos about
rebel forces and evil empires meant?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want the children to know I was confused, but
eventually, I had to pause the tape and ask Madeleine what was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to find Princess Leia to get the plans for the
Death Star,'' she said. She also let me know with some impatience
that the bad guys were wearing black (italics)and(end italics)
white and that R2-D2 and C-3PO were in the escape pod heading off
into space.
</P>
<P>
   Was it embarrassing to have to ask a first grader to explain all
this to me? Sure it was. But it was also necessary. Like getting to
know yourself through therapy, ``Star Wars'' is a commitment, with
much to learn before it all comes clear.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if I had been a child when ``Star Wars'' hit, I
wouldn't have to scramble to catch up. Now, as I watch the tidal
wave of hoopla rising before the ``The Phantom Menace'' opens on
May 21, with adults lining up just to see a preview in theaters, I
realize that I missed the original ground swell by about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Generation X may have missed Woodstock and Watergate. It may
have inherited civil rights and feminism without participating in
any revolutions. But as adolescents, its members were poised to be
yanked into the orbit of ``Star Wars'' and the relentless
merchandising it inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as I open myself up to all of it today, I can't help
wondering why George Lucas is deemed the most moral of pop
mythologists when he's marketing so much stuff.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Monday morning at FAO Schwarz in New York City, and a
robotic voice on the elevator was announcing: ``I am Go-2-Floor-2!
I am happy that your journey has brought you to our galaxy of
toys!'' I was happy, too, at first, just to see the happy look on
little Ian's face. Then I started being overwhelmed by what I
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Yoda, Uncle Bobby,'' Ian said of an E.T.-like
character I did not recognize. ``There's Chewie and the Millennium
Falcon.'' In this confusing landfill of expensive merchandise, I
was relieved to see a light saber for $6 and suggested we buy two.
That was fine with Ian until he noticed one for $24.99. ``I want
this one,'' he said. ``Please.''
</P>
<P>
   I started to sweat. I didn't have that much money to drop on a
light saber. Before the jaws of mercantilism could close around us,
I bought the cheaper ones and whisked Ian out of the store. It was
only a taste of the outsize world of ``Star Wars'' merchandising,
but it was enough.
</P>
<P>
   The weeks that followed were one big ``Phantom Menace''
preparation, and far more intensive than my scrambling to catch up
before any Oscars night. I screened ``The Return of the Jedi'' and
``The Empire Strikes Back.''
</P>
<P>
   I bought fan magazines. I studied a behind-the-scenes CD-ROM and
scanned spinoff novels, Joseph Campbell's musings on heroes and
``The Uses of Enchantment'' by Bruno Bettleheim, which analyzes how
myths affect young people.
</P>
<P>
   As I waged light-saber battles with the children, my commands
grew more and more ``Star Wars''-specific. Finally, I was ready to
take their imaginations forward. One evening, after getting them
dressed up Luke and Leia-style (oversize white T-shirts, belt for
him and earmuffs for her), I sat them down in front of the
television.
</P>
<P>
   I dimmed the lights, put a tape of the ``Phantom Menace''
preview into the VCR (by now the Force was with me, and the
publicity office of Lucas Films sent it), and to approximate THX
sound, I turned the volume up way too high. Then, feeling a tiny
bit of the thrill that Lucas himself must feel, I hit the play
button.
</P>
<P>
   Ian jumped around, waving his light saber. Madeleine, although
riveted by the possibility of a whole new cosmos of unknown
characters, digitized creatures and wacky hairdos, held her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's this loud in the theater, I'll have to wait for it to
come out on video,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as she said that, I remembered holding my own ears in
the movie theater in 1977, when ``Star Wars'' seemed to me like
nothing more than an overblown pop phenomenon with shag haircuts.
Back then, I could still dismiss it on principle just for being so
big.
</P>
<P>
   Now, like so many other adults who have dumbed down their taste
to go along with whatever the most popular phenomenon of the moment
happens to be, I'm a lot more willing to love what I'm supposed to
love.
</P>
<P>
   Even when I end up loving too much.
</P>
<P>
   At my most recent baby-sitting stint, for insance, the
encyclopedic trivia collection on CD-ROM that I bought, ``Star
Wars: Behind the Magic,'' didn't interest Madeleine and Ian at all.
``What kind of children would like this?'' she asked. ``Very old
children,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did they care much about the superslick fan magazine for
kids I tried reading to them instead of bedtime stories. Quite
simply, it was too much information. Unlike so many obsessed
adults, who can't take their myths or actors at face value, they
just wanted the story, not the making of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in these final days before the new movie arrives in
theaters and gives us something more important to discuss than the
war in Kosovo, I've been feeling a little pushy in my anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, when I was reading yet another ``Star Wars''
fan magazine to the children before bed, they didn't even want to
hear an exclusive profile of Jake Lloyd, the adorable 9-year-old
star of the new episode, who plays Darth Vader as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants people to think of him as a regular kid, not an
actor,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, Uncle Bobby, no problem,'' Madeleine said as I tucked
her in. ``Now, good night already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
