<HEADLINE>
DUPLICATED FILE NAMES COULD BE AT ROOT OF PROBLEMS WITH WORD 97 
 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have repeated problems with Microsoft Word 97 crashing on
me (illegal operation, page fault, etc.) when I try to print or
change some of the formatting on a page. I've uninstalled it,
reinstalled it, patched it, you name it. What can be causing this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Helping out a friend who was having similar problems, I
discovered something about how Windows stores its font files that
may be at the root of your woes.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's possible to store two files with the same name
in the windows/font folder if one of the files is named using all
lower-case letters and the other is in all upper case.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you have a file called courier.ttf, you also may
have a file called COURIER.ttf. In most cases, this duplication
apparently causes no problems.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until Word goes to use one of these fonts, either for
formatting or printing. Essentially, it gets confused and crashes.
</P>
<P>
   In my friend's case, the duplicated font was a crucial one:
Times Roman, the default typeface for Word. Once one of the
times.ttf files was deleted, his problems disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Before you go deleting any fonts, though, choose the Details
view and make sure the two files have the same file sizes and
dates. Rather than deleting one, move it into a temporary folder.
If you experience no new problems as a result, go ahead and delete
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After reading your column on the upgrading to Internet
Explorer 5.0, I decided to do it. Although it took all night, it
was successful. However, I have this problem. I have a Compaq
Presario with the easy access buttons on the keyboard to open
e-mail or access the Internet. Now, when I use these buttons, a
window comes up for ``dial up connection'' and I have to use the
mouse pointer to connect. This is an extra step that defeats my
easy access feature. Is there a way I can eliminate this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although this may be a problem specific to Compaq's setup _
and thus you might want to talk to the company's technical support
_ there is a generic fix you can try.
</P>
<P>
   You need to tell Internet Explorer 5's new connection-management
feature that you want to make an instant dialup connection when
your Internet software launches. The connection manager is handy
because it lets you set up multiple dialup accounts, each with its
own settings. But because the settings can be customized, it turns
off auto-dialup by default.
</P>
<P>
   Right-click on the Internet Explorer icon on the desktop, choose
Internet Options, then Connections. Make sure ``Always dial my
default connection'' is checked.
</P>
<P>
   When the dialup box next appears, make sure your password is in
place and both Save Password and Connect Automatically are checked.
From now on, your connection should be made without help.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a question on any alternates for the touch pad on my
laptop. I have tried to get used to the thing for hours, but
perhaps my fingers are too big or insensitive ... In any case, I
just can't seem to manage it and usually take a mouse along with me
on business trips and use my right leg for a pad! There must be a
better way. Other than the mini-ball option in the keyboard, do you
know of a small mouse or other device that would be a bit more
practical on the road than the conventional mouse?
</P>
<P>
   A: Logitech makes a mouse specifically designed for notebook
usage. It's slightly smaller than a regular mouse, so it will take
up less space _ very important on airplane meal trays _ and it has
a very short cord. That's a particularly thoughtful feature,
because the worst part of using a full-sized mouse in a cramped
area is always having to push the cord out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Wheel Mouse for Notebooks, as it's called, sells for about
$40.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question? Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(a)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
