<HEADLINE>
TV CYCLE SHOULDN'T INVOLVE EXERCISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, April 26)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest assault on the great national pastime of TV-watching
comes from one David Wells, an obesity researcher from New York who
has invented a torture device called the TV Cycle.
</P>
<P>
   When I think of the TV Cycle, I think of something that begins
at 8 a.m. with ``Dr. Katz,'' followed by the ``Daily Show.'' Then
it's time for a short nap in order to build up strength for reruns
of the ``Andy Griffith Show,'' which begins at 11 a.m. An hour of
Aunt Bea can put you in the mood for a little violence, which is
why I usually tune in ``Masters of War'' at noon on the History
Channel, or else live U.S. Senate coverage on CSPAN2.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 2 p.m., I have to choose between a ``Saturday Night
Live'' rerun, ``Casper the Friendly Ghost,'' ``Traditional
Medicines of Asia'' or the ``Jerry Springer'' show. (Is this a
great country, or what?)
</P>
<P>
   All that decision-making can be exhausting, which is why I
usually take another nap until ``Bill Nye the Science Guy'' comes
on at 4 p.m. (Did you know inertia is a property of matter? I
thought it was just a property of newspaper columnists.) In the 5-6
p.m. time slot, it's a choice between the news and the ``Match
Game.'' (I'll take Vicki Lawrence over Bob Hite any day.) Then it's
``Simpsons,'' ``Frazier,'' maybe a ``Seinfeld'' rerun, a ball game,
a little ``Sports Center'' and then wearily, happily, to bed to
dream of the morning and the start of another TV Cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But David Wells' TV Cycle is something entirely, perversely
different. He has invented a television that is connected to a
stationary bicycle. The television only works if you are pedaling
the bike. He found (big surprise) that people watch less television
this way, something that he and a lot of other members of the
Health Police view as a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking behind the TV Cycle is that television is evil
because it cuts into the time that we would otherwise spend
exercising, or, to put it another way, if it weren't for ``Funniest
Home Videos,'' we'd all be outside at this moment chopping wood or
limbering up for the next marathon.
</P>
<P>
   While it is probably true that most people who watch 18 hours of
television a day are not in peak physical condition, it is quite
possible that they would still find a way to avoid exercising even
if their television was taken away or, worse, hooked up to a
stationary bike. Staring at a blank wall or weeping softly to
oneself while rocking gently back and forth in the corner of a dark
room are (un)activities that spring immediately to mind.
</P>
<P>
   For people who do not like to exercise, TV-watching is a
wonderful alternative because it does not require a great deal of
strength or agility unless, of course, you drop the remote control
behind the couch. Very few people have accidentally sliced off a
finger or hand while watching ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' which is
more than you can say about people who spend their leisure time
chopping wood.
</P>
<P>
   While there is some validity to the argument that senior
citizens should be made to prove that they can see before their
driver's license is renewed, there is no reason why a person should
be required to have the cardio-vascular fitness of Wayne Gretzky in
order to watch reruns of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   One might even argue that excessive physical fitness would be
detrimental to prolonged TV-viewing. Hard, angular bodies don't fit
well with the soft contours of an overstuffed chair, plus the
clear-headedness that exercise promotes often runs counter to the
themes of such shows as ``Baywatch'' or ``Beverly Hills, 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking for new ways to punish gentle, unassuming,
avocado-shaped TV-viewers, it would be nice, for a change, if
scientists picked on fitness nuts, a group of people who are far,
far more annoying than folks who sit alone in a dark,
air-conditioned room watching ``Xena: Warrior Princess'' or reruns
of ``Love Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps invent some sort of contraption where they can't
exercise unless they're watching ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' or ``The
Newlywed Game.''
</P>
<P>
   See how they like that.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
