<P>
   ATT _ AT&AMP;T Corp. dragged U.S. stocks lower after its $62.5
billion bid for MediaOne Corp. sparked concern its acquisitions
will hurt earnings. ``It looks like it's a lot to digest in one go
for AT&AMP;T,'' said Neil Smeaton, who helps manage $1.4 billion in
U.S. stocks at Scottish Equitable Asset Management. MediaOne's
stock, however, was up sharply, as investors bet on a bidding war
for the cable TV operator. (Kanell/Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BIAS _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co., which has plenty of
experience dealing with glass bottles, must now contend with
allegations of ``glass ceilings'' and ``glass walls.'' The
Atlanta-based beverage company has been hit with a federal
discrimination lawsuit that accuses it of fosterting inequality
against black employees in pay, promotions, performance evaluations
and terminations. The lead plaintiffs' attorney, Cyrus Mehri of
Washington, handled the discrimination case against Texaco, which
resulted in the largest race discrimination settlement in history.
(Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BIAS-PROFILES _ ATLANTA _ Profiles of the plaintiffs in the
discrimination lawsuit against Coca-Cola: Motisola Abdallah, an
administrative assistant; Gregory Allen Clark, a security guard;
Linda Ingram, a senior information analyst; and Kimberly Gray
Orton, a former director? (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COX-COMMUNICATIONS _ Cox Communications Inc., the fifth-largest
U.S. cable-TV company, said it will sell its remaining 40.8 percent
stake in Cox Communications PCS LP to Sprint Corp. for 24.3 million
shares of Sprint PCS Series 2 stock. The transaction, valued at
$1.2 billion and expected to close in the second quarter, is the
final step in transferring ownership of Cox Communications PCS to
Sprint, the nation's third-largest long-distance telephone company.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-ETICKET _ Delta is extending e-ticketing to its regional
affiliates. Checking to see how much of its total booking is now by
e-ticket, which saves on processing costs. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-TRANSAM _ A review of the1999 Pontiac Firebird Trans
Am. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
