<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF GIVES BACK CONFISCATED MARIJUANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE GENIELLA   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UKIAH, Calif. _ Grasping a grocery bag of home-grown marijuana
worth about $2,000 that was given back to him by local authorities,
Christopher Brown on Thursday triumphantly walked out of the
Mendocino County sheriff's office to make medical marijuana
history.
</P>
<P>
   Brown became the first person in the United States to legally
retrieve a personal stash of pot seized by law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Local drug agents confiscated the half-pound of marijuana during
a 1997 raid on Brown's former residence in Willits and refused to
return it even after charges were dropped against him. Brown took
his case to the California Supreme Court, which in November upheld
a Mendocino County Superior Court judge's order that the marijuana
be returned to Brown. The high court agreed that Brown's marijuana
use met provisions of voter-approved Proposition 215, which
legalized pot use for medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good. I feel I've stood up for a lot of people who
need marijuana for medical reasons,'' said Brown, 37.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he smokes up to two marijuana cigarettes a day to
alleviate chronic pain from injuries suffered in a motorcycle
accident about 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview Thursday afternoon outside the sheriff's
office, Brown said he was eager to roll a joint and smoke it to see
if the three-year-old pot still could provide the relief he seeks.
</P>
<P>
   But, gesturing toward the sheriff's office, Brown said, ``I
don't think I'll do it right here. I still get real nervous around
cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's case is being touted as a milestone in the continuing
debate over implementing Proposition 215.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time a person has walked out of a police
station with marijuana legally in their hands,'' said Hannah
Nelson, a Redway attorney who represented Brown.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Nelson waged a legal battle on Brown's behalf. At
first local authorities, and later state officials, refused to give
Brown his pot back after felony marijuana cultivation and
possession charges were dismissed against him and his late wife.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers unsuccessfully argued that if law enforcement
officers returned Brown's home-grown marijuana they would be acting
as ``drug pushers.''
</P>
<P>
   The original order issued in August 1997 by Mendocino County
Superior Court Judge Joseph Orr ``commands law enforcement to
commit a federal crime,'' state attorneys argued to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court unanimously rejected the law-enforcement
appeal and ordered that the pot be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said law enforcement authorities scoffed when she first
made her request on Brown's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't imagine having to return the marijuana, even
though charges against my client had been dropped. But the fact is
that the marijuana was being used legally and he has a right to
it,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his late wife, Dorlissa Perrine, were arrested in 1997
at their Willits home and accused of cultivating marijuana for sale
after sheriff's deputies responded to a domestic dispute call and
saw some pot seedlings, along with buds and leaves, in their home.
Deputies notified the county Narcotics Task Force, which obtained a
search warrant and seized the pot after arresting Brown and his
wife at their home.
</P>
<P>
   But felony criminal cultivation and possession charges were
dismissed by Orr when the couple produced doctors' statements
contending that they each needed pot to ease chronic pain. Perrine
suffered from a degenerative tissue disease. Brown said his chronic
pain is eased by smoking marijuana regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rely on pot to help me get through the day,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown described himself Thursday as an honor student at Cabrillo
College in Santa Cruz, where he's studying physics. He plans to
transfer to the University of California, Santa Cruz, to get his
degree, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite critics' claims that persistent marijuana use dulls
minds and emotions, Brown said, he is succeeding academically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not function without marijuana. It's as simple as
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
