<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gift-Giving Retirees Angry at J.P. Morgan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., the banking giant, were
concerned enough about its plans to stop matching its retirees'
charitable contributions to raise the issue at the bank's annual
meeting earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's chief executive, Douglas A. Warner III, speaking the
same day that the bank said first-quarter profits had surged 64
percent, told questioners that the decision was part of
cost-cutting. Morgan had been a weak financial performer and was
criticized by Wall Street analysts as having bloated expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said it gave $18 million to charities last year and would
continue to match its employees' gifts. Most of its competitors do
not match retiree gifts, it added.
</P>
<P>
   But some Morgan retirees are still perturbed. ``I wonder what
the real expense benefit of this is when there's a tax benefit to
charitable contributions,'' said C. Helen Lovell, a retiree who
once was a vice president in the private banking unit.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote in a letter to The New York Times that she was
``shocked, angry and embarrassed to think that a firm of Morgan's
reputation would solve its problem of mismanagement by terminating
aid to the poor, handicapped and neglected members of our society,
our educational institutions, hospitals and other health care
providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy L. O'Brien
</P>
<P>
   Au Pair, the Luxury Model
</P>
<P>
   Au Pair in America, which operates in more than 35 states, is
hoping to satisfy parents' needs and attract better-qualified young
women from overseas to work in American households with a program
called Au Pair Extraordinaire. Participants are at least 20 years
old, compared with the usual minimum of 18, and have studied child
care or worked full-time in the field for two years.
</P>
<P>
   For a family hiring an Extraordinaire au pair, the annual cost
before travel expenses would be about $20,800, instead of $17,750
for a regular au pair. The totals include weekly stipends of $300
and $240, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gertz, the executive vice president of the American
Institute for Foreign Study, which runs Au Pair in America,
attributes a short supply of au pairs in part to the publicity
about Louise Woodward, the British au pair who was convicted of
manslaughter in 1997 in the death of her charge, Matthew Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gertz said, ``parents have become much more interested in
screening and training.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Freierman &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
