<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WOMEN-SMITH-NYT &LR;      04-23 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WOMEN-SMITH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 LOUISE SMITH: NEVER ONE OF THE GOOD OL' BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CARS-WOMEN-SERIES) 
(mk) 
 By LESLEY HAZLETON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best-known women in car racing are probably Lyn St. James,
Janet Guthrie and Shirley Muldowney, but on Thursday it was Louise
Smith who became the first woman inducted into the International
Motorsports Hall of Fame at Talladega Superspeedway in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 82, was once known as the queen of the Darlington
Speedway. From 1945 through the mid-'50s she was a big attraction
at races up and down the East Coast. The only woman on the circuit,
she chalked up 38 victories _ and almost as many crashes _ in the
rough-and-tumble world of stock-car racing, long before the
corporate sponsorships and television deals of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks she drove on were dirt or sand. The cars were
souped-up castoffs rescued from her husband's junkyard. And a tire
iron came in handy to deal with the fights that often broke out at
the end of races.
</P>
<P>
   How does she feel about the honor? ``It's about time,'' she said
in a telephone interview from her home in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty rough,'' she recalled. ``But it's still rough
for women. The men don't want women out there. They just will not
give you credit.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR drivers can now earn more than $1 million a race; the
most Smith ever won was $750. ``I thought I was in heaven,'' she
said. ``Usually they'd give me $100 or $150 to turn up. And if I
wrecked the car, I'd be lucky if I could borrow enough money to get
home, 'cause I couldn't get one dime's worth of insurance.'' &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-CITY-0424-COX     04-23 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-CITY-0424-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE THE NATO BUBBLE, A WORLD WITHIN A CITY
 &HT;    With NATO-SUMMIT.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After shopping for souvenirs at Planet Hollywood,
three teen-aged girls peered over the barricades along a deserted
Pennsylvania Avenue on Friday and wondered how they would rejoin
their classmates on the sophomore field trip from Tulpehockon High
School in Bethel, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get anywhere,'' moaned Lora Seiverling. ``Everything
is blocked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was as if a giant bubble had been dropped over
several blocks in the heart of the nation's capital for the
three-day 50th Anniversary NATO Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the bubble, city life went on at a lazy, weekend-like
pace. Amid fears of traffic gridlock resulting from closed streets,
thousands of federal employees were given the day off from work,
and others just stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot quieter than I would have expected on a Friday,''
marveled Greg Baker, shepherding Wisconsin safety patrol members
along an empty sidewalk beside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the NATO bubble, though, a bustling, surreal community
had sprung up. The citizens all wore plastic photo ID cards around
their necks testifying to their role: Host Committee. Secret
Service. Vendor. Print Journalist.
</P>
<P>
   The bubble is secure. Armed guards scanned the ID cards at
checkpoints along the perimeter as visitors passed through metal
detectors. Sharpshooters with rifles stood on the roofs of
buildings and scanned everything through binoculars. Dogs sniffed
purses and briefcases for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Two of America's most famous thoroughfares _ Pennsylvania and
Constitution Avenues _ run through the NATO bubble. These wide,
usually crowded avenues were strangely vacant on Friday, save for
the occasional motorcade carrying a leader of one of the 19 NATO
nations to a session at the Andrew Mellon Auditorium. Most other
traffic consisted of organizers in green golf carts or District
police officers wearing yellow shirts and black shorts and riding
bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   The limousines cruised down spiffy streets, both inside the
bubble and leading to it. The District of Columbia government
borrowed street-sweeping machines from Baltimore and Philadelphia
and drafted jail inmates to pick up litter. Tunnels were
steam-cleaned and graffiti scrubbed off. Homeless people were moved
from benches. Stylish tripods made from U.S., D.C. and NATO flags
stand at 260 spots along the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the official meetings of the NATO leaders are taking
place in the Mellon Auditorium, where the original treaty creating
the alliance was signed half a century ago. But the adjacent Ronald
Reagan Building is headquarters for the 1,700 dignitaries visiting
from 42 countries and the 3,400 representatives of the world's news
media.
</P>
<P>
   In the Reagan Building, conversations overlaps in countless
languages, but English blares forth from the NATO-TV feeds shown
nonstop on countless monitors. Hundreds of correspondents who have
traveled the globe to reach this historic event find themselves
hunched over laptop computers in a filing center, chronicling what
they see on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the media action takes place on a plush blue ``NATO 50
Summit'' carpet that muffles the sounds of thousands of footsteps.
TV crews film from the corners of the carpet, and young women rush
across it to powder the faces of perspiring correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   The bubble has its own bazaar. At a souvenir stand, a tan NATO
Summit jacket sells for $95, a blue denim NATO Summit shirt costs
$45 and a NATO Summit key chain goes for $8. At the nearby jewelry
booth, your choice of a gold-plated NATO cuff links or a
gold-plated NATO pin is $50 _ with part of the proceeds going to
the children of Kosovo, the vendor promises. The U.S. Postal
Service is selling T-shirts, neckties and stamps behind a sign that
says, ``Get your special envelope commemorating the 50th
anniversary of the NATO summit here!''
</P>
<P>
   The bubble has its own ``Science of NATO'' exhibit. Nearby,
private firms display cellular telephones _ nearly as prevalent as
the necklace ID's _ and futuristic high-tech gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the bubble, though, were scenes reminiscent of the '60s.
Sarah Stone was lounging on the grass listening to some aging baby
boomers _ older then her parents _ sing protest songs and speak
against NATO's war on Yugoslavia. An eighth-grader from Saint Mark
Lutheran School in Houston, she noted not only history repeating,
but also fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell bottoms, long hair, hippie style,'' she said, noting the
clothes of young people at the ``Citizens' Summit to De-Nuke NATO''
two blocks away from the official ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah shared the sentiment as well as the garb.
</P>
<P>
   Peace would prevail and the national debt would be reduced ``if
we would just leave other countries alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There were only about 100 protesters, and many didn't recall the
original words to the anti-Vietnam War anthem by Country Joe
McDonald and the Fish, the ``Feel Like I'm Fixin' to Die Rag.'' But
they sang gamely to the new verses: ``And it's one, two, three,
what are we fighting for? Don't ask me, I don't really know. Next
stop is Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So sell your mutual fund and pick up a gun, you're gonna have
a whole lot of fun,'' they sang.
</P>
<P>
   But they were outside the bubble, too far away for anyone inside
to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
