<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURES-NY     04-23 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN EXPOSURES: POLITICAL NEWS FROM A SOUTHERN PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   School Shootings Alter Political Debate on Guns
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With several state legislatures abandoning pro-gun
bills, the horrific shooting spree at a Colorado high school has
already altered the political debate on guns in America.
</P>
<P>
   But there's little evidence yet that the Republican-controlled
Congress will take up any new gun control measures this year. While
the Clinton administration wants to expand background checks,
require trigger locks on guns and increase penalties for adults who
transfer guns to juveniles, Republicans are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., who counts fighting juvenile
violence as a priority, said there are enough laws on the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``But very few of them have ever been used,'' Sessions said on
CNN's Crossfire. ``We've had less than 10 prosecutions, for
example, nationally of guns on school grounds. That really,
apparently, is not the real solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point to cultural reasons for the shootings, saying
that violence in the media and a breakdown in society's morals have
fostered an atmosphere that breeds killers. On Capitol Hill,
reaction to the shootings has generally been muted with most
lawmakers simply expressing their shock and grief over the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, however, wasted no time offering
its analysis of the shootings at a Colorado high school, suggesting
the slayings had little to do with a proliferation of guns.
</P>
<P>
   A letter from the NRA president, Charlton Heston, hinted the
group would give no ground in its fight against gun-control
legislation. ``We must stand in somber but unshakable unity, even
in this time of anguish,'' Heston wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential contenders were even blunter. ``I hope
we don't try to use this as an excuse to go and take away guns,''
former Vice President Dan Quayle said in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide has apparently turned against a raft of pro-gun
bills introduced in several state legislatures. Alabama, Florida
and Colorado all shelved bills aimed at either easing concealed
weapons laws or protecting gun makers from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   And the NRA did offer one public relations concession in the
wake of the school shooting. It scaled back plans for its annual
convention, which coincidentally is to begin in Denver later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold Shoulder
</P>
<P>
   With their eyes on textile jobs back home, two Southern senators
are leading the fight against China joining the World Trade
Organization, a move that would enhance the country's trading
status.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Fritz Hollings of South Carolina and Republican Jesse
Helms of North Carolina have long been leery of trade deals they
believe threaten domestic jobs. Textile production is a major
industry in both states, but China wants to further break open the
market here with its goods.
</P>
<P>
   The two men also cite China's poor history on human rights and
recent allegations of espionage as additional reasons why the
United States should be cool to any new trade deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any trade agreement with China would be premature before these
issues are resolved,'' the senators said in a letter to colleagues.
The debate is expected to heat up this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Beach Reading
</P>
<P>
   Southern coastal states have regularly come under criticism from
environmental groups for their failure to test water cleanliness at
public beaches and notify the public of any health risks.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, Georgia and Louisiana have no monitoring plan at all,
according to the Natural Resources Defense Council. Mississippi has
no closure policy and Florida and South Carolina have piecemeal
monitoring. Only North Carolina has what the group considers a
comprehensive policy.
</P>
<P>
   But that may now change. A bill moving through Congress would
authorize $30 million for states to develop and put into effect new
testing programs that meet federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation advocates said the bill had been kicking around the
last few sessions of Congress with Democratic backing but never got
moving. This year, Republicans seized on it as a way to give
lawmakers a solid environmental vote and demonstrate that the
Congress is getting some legislative work done.
</P>
<P>
   Party Politics
</P>
<P>
   Who says Congress can't be bipartisan?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., is busy promoting a favorite candidate
in the state's upcoming special congressional election to replace
Bob Livingston, saying David Treen would be in line for a spot on
the appropriations panel due to previous service in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's sudden departure left the state, which loves its
government pork, without a member on the committee. Should Treen
lose, Tauzin has another prospect for the panel _ Rep. Chris John.
Though John is a Democrat, Tauzin evidently feels having someone on
appropriations from the opposite party is better than having no one
at all.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
