<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRILLINGS-NYT &LR;      04-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRILLINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A PSYCHOBIOGRAPHY, JAMES TRILLING FOCUSES ON HIS FATHER'S LACK
OF FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next week The American Scholar will publish an article by James
Trilling, the son of Lionel and Diana Trilling, titled ``My Father
and the Weak-Eyed Devils,'' in which he writes that his father was
so blinded by his love of Freud and psychoanalysis that he missed
his real disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's worst problem was not neurosis, it was a
neurological condition, attention deficit disorder,'' he writes.
Then he lays out the diagnoses of the rest of his family. His
mother's affliction was ``panic disorder with agoraphobia, which
made her an emotional cripple for many years.'' His aunt had
Tourette's syndrome. His grandfather suffered from attention
deficit disorder. And so does he. Attention deficit disorder, he
emphasizes, is ``the most insidious culprit in my family.'' Its
main feature is ``the inability to maintain a productive level of
concentration (`focus') through the normal range of daily
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at this description, the reader might first think,
``Gee, I wish I could have Lionel Trilling's disorder, the kind
that is so crippling that you are forced to write important books,
become a judicious critic, teach at a major university and have a
family too.'' The reader then might wonder, ``Why does an article
about attention deficit disorder sound so Oedipal?'' Maybe it is
because confronting the Oedipus complex is something that the
rebellious son of a Freudian cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   This is an odd moment in psychobiography. For much of this
century Freud has been the lens for biography, Peter D. Kramer, the
author of ``Listening to Prozac'' noted in an interview. Now the
lens is biological psychiatry. ``Lionel Trilling in `Sincerity and
Authenticity' shows how in the modern world the moral man is
expected to take responsibility for not only his conscious but also
his unconscious motivations,'' Kramer said. ``His son claims that
in the post-modern world authenticity requires acknowledging one's
diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   James Trilling, an independent art historian who specializes in
the history of ornament, acknowledges the diagnosis not only for
himself (in a way that is quite convincing) but also for his father
and grandfather. Here is the son of a confirmed Freudian attacking
his father with biological psychology. His goal seems to be not
only to describe all his father's faults but to insure that no one
will look at them the way his father did, which is to say
psychoanalytically.
</P>
<P>
   Thus James Trilling takes his place on the growing shelf of what
Joyce Carol Oates calls ``pathography,'' biography whose main focus
is diagnosis. Like any other literary form, pathography can be good
or bad, Kramer said. When it is good, ``it destigmatizes an
illness. It's refreshing. It can show that depression or attention
deficit disorder doesn't disqualify anyone from the full range of
social behavior.'' When it is bad it attempts to show that the
subject is ``damaged goods.''
</P>
<P>
   How are we to understand the case of James Trilling and his
father?
</P>
<P>
   The most outstanding feature is the son's unwillingness to
concede that there is anything about his father that cannot be
explained by attention deficit disorder. He writes, ``All my
father's personality flaws, which continued to haunt my mother
almost 20 years after his death, were symptoms of attention deficit
disorder.'' He blames his father's absent-mindedness,
secretiveness, anger, impatience, indecisiveness, bad driving, bad
swimming and bad tennis on the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Here is his description of his father having attention problems
on the tennis court: ``He would wear himself to a frazzle on the
tennis court, always reacting too late and pursuing the ball with
all his energy when it was hopelessly out of reach.'' Here is the
son's description of his absent-minded father on the street: ``He
is said to have praised the appearance of a woman he passed on the
street, not realizing it was his own mother.'' (Did somebody say
Oedipus?)
</P>
<P>
   But the most reductive charge the son levels against his father
is the idea that Lionel Trilling's very thinking _ not only his
love of Freud, but his whole moral universe _ was determined by
attention deficit disorder: ``He saw the world as a practical and
moral obstacle course, but it was the obstacles that fascinated
him, not the ways around them. He loved to follow the path of most
resistance, and where obstacles were lacking he turned all his
ingenuity to inventing them.''
</P>
<P>
   James Trilling then challenges his father's literary judgment:
``During his entire career as an interpreter of literature, I doubt
my father ever solved a problem, in the sense of marshaling
evidence to prove or disprove a theory. On the contrary, he built
his career on the mistrust of certainties and was rarely content
with a simple answer when a complex one could be found. . . . Of
all `simple' solutions he mistrusted happiness the most. The idea
of living happily ever after must have seemed almost crass to him.
Certainly it left him all dressed up with no place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There it is then: Lionel Trilling, temperamental husband,
skeptical critic, abysmal tennis player, erratic driver,
absent-minded professor, impatient father, was the sum of his
neurological symptoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
