<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SALT-LAKE _ A little-known salt lake that has been at the
crossroads of South Texas history for centuries will open to the
public for the first time in years April 24. No one knows how La
Sal Del Rey formed, but experts estimate it holds 4 million tons of
salt. Local Indians, then Spanish settlers, Union and Confederate
soldiers, and private companies have mined salt from the lake,
which supplied South Texas and northern Mexico with salt. Now the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, which bought the lake and
surrounding land in the early 90's from the family that owned it,
is opening Sal Del Rey and 15,000 acres of its growing wildlife
corridor to the public. This is the first time the agency has
opened any of its wild tracts in 20 years. (Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
