<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Snowfall accumulations exceeded 30 inches in portions of the
Front Range of the Rockies Thursday and Friday as a late-season
storm stalled across the region, producing a prolonged period of
heavy snow. On Saturday, this same storm will weaken slightly as it
remains over the central Rockies. Nevertheless, areas of snow and
rain will once again pepper portions of the intermountain West and
Rockies. Up to 12 inches of fresh snow may occur in the Watsach
Mountains of Utah and higher reaches of the San Juan Mountains in
southwest Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, scattered showers and isolated strong
thunderstorms will erupt over western Texas and the Red River
Valley as a stream of humid air flowing north from the Gulf of
Mexico intercepts an approaching jet stream disturbance. A few of
these storms will produce hail and damaging wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and spotty thundershowers will surround a stationary
front draped across the interior Southeast Saturday. It should
remain dry and very warm along the Gulf Coast and across Florida,
however, where the threat of spreading brush fires remains quite
high.
</P>
<P>
   A bracing day is expected across the Northeast Saturday as brisk
winds from the northwest direct unseasonably chilly air southward
from Canada. Skies will be generally sunny across the region,
though clouds and isolated showers will affect portions of northern
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny and mild conditions will cover the Northwest coast
Saturday. Farther south, California will be mainly dry, though
isolated showers will occur in the Sierra Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Waiting for Humidity
</P>
<P>
   The rainy season cannot come fast enough for the
wildfire-charred landscape of southern Florida. The average date
for the start of the rainy season is May 21, but there is hope that
the season could begin as early as next week. The start and
duration of the summer rainy season is determined by the arrival
and persistence of sultry, tropical air. Specifically, the
dew-point temperature, which is an absolute measure of the amount
of moisture in the air, must reach and stay above 70 degrees. In
response to such high humidity, tropical afternoon thunderstorms
frequently develop.
</P>
</TEXT>
