<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUNDWAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EXPERTS SAY GROUND TROOPS WILL BE NEEDED TO WIN WAR IN
YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With airstrikes moving into a second month and
Yugoslavia showing no signs of knuckling under, military experts
and key lawmakers say the use of ground troops may be the only way
to end the fighting in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting this weekend in Washington to mark the 50th anniversary
of NATO, alliance leaders were expected to discuss the possibility
of deploying ground forces in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a
move not supported by all 19 NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has said repeatedly that the war can be
won without a ground assault, acknowledged on Thursday that the
updating of NATO's contingency plans to include a land attack is
``a wise and prudent course.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is under pressure from some members of Congress to use
ground troops to end the conflict. Lawmakers say the Serb military
has taken a tremendous pounding in past weeks but has survived.
They argue that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will not bend
to NATO demands unless he faces an all-out ground assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``In history, an air campaign alone has never decisively
affected a campaign,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a
presidential candidate who recently turned up the heat on Clinton.
``It's apparent that the administration wants to win a war without
waging it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain knows something about air warfare. A Navy fighter pilot
during the Vietnam War, he was shot down in 1967 but survived with
fractures of both arms and a knee, spending nearly six years as a
prisoner of war in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Senate hearing, McCain asked Gen. Henry Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, about Clinton's strategy to
avoid the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does it make sense ... to tell your enemy before you go
into a conflict that you will not exercise whatever options are
necessary?'' McCain asked.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton looked back at McCain and replied sternly: ``There's no
argument.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has military history on his side.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, a 43-day operation to drive Iraq's
army from neighboring Kuwait, allied pilots flew about 1,000
sorties a day and pounded Iraqi air defenses and command centers.
But it still took a 100-hour ground war to defeat Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO began airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24 to
thwart Milosevic's policy of ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo, allied
pilots have flown some 9,000 sorties, hitting bridges, oil
refineries, communications facilities and even Milosevic's Belgrade
home. But Army Gen. Wesley Clark, supreme NATO commander in Europe,
said recently that there is ``no evidence of any pullback of Serb
military or police forces,'' who have been driving ethnic Albanians
out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Military experts say that won't change unless NATO begins
amassing troops on the Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. William Nash, who led U.S. peacekeeping
troops into Bosnia during a previous Balkan conflict in 1995, said
in an interview that America ``relearned'' in the 1991 gulf war the
old adage that a war cannot be won from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the laser-guided bombs, cruise missiles and stealth
fighters that the Air Force and Navy bring to the air campaign in
Kosovo, the war will be won on the ground, like previous major
conflicts, Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, this strategy would be greatly enhanced by the
threat of a land campaign,'' Nash said. ``Barring that, diplomacy
will win this. Not bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash, like McCain, is critical of Clinton for pledging not to
use ground forces in Kosovo. He said that the president's pledge,
while politically appealing at home, gave Milosevic a strategic
advantage against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, coalition forces massed troops on the border between
Iraq and Saudi Arabia. The threat of a ground war forced Saddam to
keep his troops nearby and ready for combat, making them easy prey
for allied pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia, Clinton's strategy has allowed the Serbs to
disperse equipment and personnel, making them less vulnerable to
NATO fighters and bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elimination of the ground threat to Milosevic allowed him
to see the limits of our determination and may have given him false
hope that he could outlast us,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   But any move toward a commitment of ground troops is likely to
trigger a backlash from the American public, which, according to
opinion polls, would probably not support a war that brings heavy
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton must also consider the ramifications of such a decision
on political stability in Europe; the reaction of Russia, which is
sympathetic to the Serbs; and historical precedent, which indicates
that a ground war in the Balkans _ as the Nazis learned in World
War II _ could end in a blood bath for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most diplomatic observers say that Clinton must not allow
Milosevic to claim any semblance of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have put everything on this roll of the dice,'' said Joseph
Montville, a 23-year veteran of the State Department, who is with
the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot walk away from Milosevic and allow him to accomplish
his brutality in Kosovo. It looks now like only ground troops will
be able to secure the region.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some recent signs that NATO is considering the
prospect of a ground war. There are now about 13,500 NATO troops in
Macedonia. And NATO is building a force of 8,000 troops in Albania,
where the alliance is establishing a staging area.
</P>
<P>
   Also, U.S. Apache tank-killing helicopters arrived Wednesday in
Albania. The attack helicopters are expected to be used initially
against Serb targets in southwestern Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
fighting for independence have gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said it would probably take a NATO force of 200,000 to
accomplish the alliance's mission in Kosovo. The Serb army in the
region has about 40,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective has to be to drive the Serb military out of
Kosovo and create a situation where the Albanian refugees could
return,'' said Goodwin Cooke, a former State Department diplomat
who visited Yugoslavia regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke, a professor of international relations at Syracuse
University, said any military operation would be difficult in
Kosovo because many roads and bridges have been destroyed and Serb
forces are entrenched. But he said the size of NATO forces and
their technological superiority would give them a decided
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A NATO force fighting the Serb army would be very effective,''
he said. ``We are better trained and better equipped. The Serbs are
very undisciplined. They may be brutal and tough, but they are not
a particularly well-organized military unit. I cannot see them as
effective against American and British units.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO leaders, after a three-hour meeting Friday morning,
said nothing publicly about the prospect of using ground troops in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said only that the alliance will
pursue its month-old bombing campaign for as long as necessary and
would strike at ``the central nervous system'' of the Belgrade
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Shea said, is to attack ``those assets which are used
to plan and direct and create the political environment of
tolerance in Yugoslavia in which these brutalities can not only be
accepted but even condoned.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
