<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KLA-SURPLUS OF RECRUITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROWNWOOD, Texas _ Azem S. and his younger brother, Beqir, are
prepared to die. Like thousands of men in New York, Chicago,
Germany, Switzerland, even small towns in Central Texas, the ethnic
Albanian brothers would like to leave the homes and families they
have worked so hard for to join the Kosovo Liberation Army. But the
KLA, once a radical nationalist group that enjoyed few members in
its ranks, is apparently so overrun with recruits from around the
world that it is turning healthy and willing men like Azem and
Beqir away. By CHRIS VAUGHN. Story will move in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It was Adolf Hitler's birthday. And the evil unfolded
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. What does it all mean?
The answer is not simple. But religionists agree that America needs
a wake-up call in taking care of its children. By JIM JONES. Story
has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A reader asks: ``I am about to get my first PC, and it
will have Windows. I've read so much about Linux and how good it
is. Would it be possible to use it without removing Windows? Also,
would you recommend that a newcomer use Linux? 700 By DR. EMILIO
BOMBAY. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUNE CARTER CASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ June Carter Cash is two months shy of 70, bewildered
and a little saddened at finding herself in the matriarchal role.
She has, after all, spent a lifetime as the daughter of country
music's sainted mother, Maybelle Carter, and 31 years as the wife
of legendary Johnny Cash. Now it's her turn to, as Madonna might
say, express herself. And what a statement: June Carter Cash just
released an autobiographical album that is as much a personal
statement as Johnny Cash's ``American Recordings'' five years ago.
By SHIRLEY JINKINS. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Romance abounds in ``Love Songs,'' a modest Showtime
film that links three stories. TV critic Ken Parish Perkins takes a
look, and gives a rundown on what's coming up for the week. By KEN
PARISH PERKINS. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TANDY-INTERNET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Leonard Roberts has long believed that Tandy
Corp. would be part of the Internet revolution. So far this year,
it is. Tandy's stock price, a laggard for much of the decade, has
surged 75 percent since Jan. 1, ranking it No. 5 among the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index companies. That puts Tandy in the same
neighborhood as the index's No. 4, America Online, a bellwether for
today's digital times. By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN. Story has moved in
``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In trying to understand the reasons for the Littleton,
Colo., school massacre, we must not overlook the torment they
endured at the hands of their peers. Kids who aren't ``cool'' and
aren't part of the ``in'' crowd are all too often treated with
disdain by those who are. The ``nerds'' and outsiders who don't
wear the right clothes, join the right clubs or frequent the right
hangouts are all too often subjected to a level of public and
private humiliation that can destroy a young person's already shaky
confidence and sense of self-worth. By BILL THOMPSON. Story has
moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LABBE-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Perhaps sometime between now and the Republican
National Convention in 2000, Elizabeth Dole will give America some
idea where she actually stands on issues instead of just leaving
the media with a giddy glow because a ``credible'' woman might be
going after politics' brass ring next year. Then Republican women _
and men _ can decide about her qualifications as a viable
candidate. By J.R. LABBE. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
