<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, April 24. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ The leaders of the Western Alliance
hold a war council on Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ As NATO's leaders gathered behind
closed doors, the alliance's military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
offered a strikingly optimistic view of the war against Yugoslavia.
``We are winning,'' he declared. ``He is losing. And he knows it.''
The scorecard, however, is anything but that clear. By Steven Lee
Myers and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Lipkovo, Macedonia) _ Thousands of refugees are
straggling over the ice-packed mountains, carrying mud-caked
clothes on their backs, whimpering children in their arms, horror
in their heads. U.N. aid workers say that extraordinary numbers of
Albanians seem to be trekking their way through the rugged peaks
that span the border between Kosovo and Macedonia. There are at
least 10,000 on the move, and possibly 10 times that. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ The governor of
Colorado tours Columbine High School and says investigators are all
but certain that the two gunmen had help from others; the police
say security cameras may provide crucial evidence of a conspiracy.
The 911 tapes are released. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-KOSOVO (Washington) _ After outdoing each other for
months in their pledges not to fritter away the federal budget
surplus, both parties in Congress have quickly agreed that the
costs of the Balkans conflict should be an exception. But having
opened the door to spending some of this year's anticipated surplus
to pay for the direct costs of the air war and some relief aid
Republicans and Democrats alike now find themselves sorely tempted
to dip deeper for other military needs. A news analysis. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Undated) _ The status of efforts in the
recording and electronics industry to hammer out a universal,
pirate-proof technology for distributing commercial music on the
Internet. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
</TEXT>
