   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA (Washington) _ NATO leaders pledge to intensify
bombing of Yugoslavia and institute an oil blockade. By John Yemma
and Ann Scales. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-MEDIA (London) _ Bombing of Serbian TV headquarters, and
its resultant deaths, ires media. Journalists say now all reporters
are in harm's way. By Kevin Cullen. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT (Washington) _ NATO summit opens its 50th
anniversary celebration amid war, protocol and city gridlock. By
John Yemma and Mary Leonard. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   NATO-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ NATO has been part military
alliance, part symbol since its founding. Now, 50 years later, its
leaders are faced with a dramatically changed world. By David M.
Shribman. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SHOOTING (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Investigators hope surveillance
tapes made inside Columbine High School will show whether the two
gunmen had accompices. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-HOPE (Littleton, Colo.) _ Cassie Bernall committed
herself to Christ last Sunday. Tuesday one of the Columbine school
killers asked her if she believed in God _ and then shot her when
she said yes. By Eileen McNamara. 1100 words. (Includes poem by
murdered student.)
</P>
