<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-MOOD-HNS &LR;      04-23 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO MARKS 50 YEARS WITHOUT POMP OR CIRCUMSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a nearly deserted downtown Washington Friday,
the ceremony that was meant to be a self-congratulatory celebration
of NATO's 50 years and the end of communism instead turned into a
cheerless discussion of the harsh reality of war and ethnic
cleansing in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With NATO bombs falling on Yugoslavia, the alliance's leaders
decided to scrap most of day's more dramatic celebrations,
including a booming flyover of jet fighters and a colorful military
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the main ceremony took place in the newly-refurbished
Mellon Auditorium in the Old Customs Building _ near the Washington
Monument _ where the original North Atlantic Treaty was signed on
April 4, 1949.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization was designed
to counter Soviet expansion and the military might of the
Moscow-backed Warsaw Pact. Now NATO is struggling with a new role:
responding to an ethnic crisis in one of Europe's smaller states.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the ceremony was to be the centerpiece of a weekend
celebrating NATO's triumph over the Soviet bloc and the extension
of membership in the alliance to three former communist states _
the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland. In addition, the White
House had planned for several gala parties to celebrate the
alliance and other nations that aspire to join it.
</P>
<P>
   But during the ceremony, NATO leaders took a sober tone,
focusing as much on the organization's present struggles as on its
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an occasion to honor NATO's past, its mission in
Kosovo and to plan its future,'' President Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the alliance that
``helped bring Eastern Europe out of the darkness of communism ...
must (now) show the world that it is willing to fight for its
beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the auditorium, three 50-foot blue banners hung down in
front of the entrance to the building with a red carpet leading out
to the sidewalk. Across the street, a large grandstand, initially
built to be used by the NATO leaders to watch the military parade,
was being used by television crews to film the leaders leaving the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But as the leaders emerged from the building, there was no
feeling of celebration. Under a foreboding sky, they quietly walked
out onto streets lined with hundreds of security personnel rather
than cheering crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Even after leaving the security perimeter surrounding the event,
the leaders encountered a virtual ghost town. With nearly 100,000
federal workers given the day off and motorists warned for weeks to
avoid the center of the nation's capital, the streets were largely
empty, except for police vehicles and a few roller-bladers.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary ceremonies end on Sunday. Guests at several
White House dinners have been asked to wear business suits rather
than formal attire and music at every event has been changed to be
more restrained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
