<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-23 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME'S `LOVE SONGS' DARES TO BE DIFFERENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television rarely, if ever, does justice to romantic scenarios
involving black characters. If sex, for instance, isn't played for
laughs, its presentation is either too serious or too awkward.
Endearing and enduring relationships are practically nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Gossett Jr., who has found himself writing in his own love
interests now that he's spending more time behind the camera,
thinks Hollywood's skittishness toward black romance falls
somewhere between fear and ignorance. Fear that romance, like
drama, is simply unmarketable and unbankable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional wisdom is that no one wants to see it _ which is
the same reason why there are no regular TV family-type dramas
featuring black people as the lead,'' Gossett says. ``For whatever
reason, Hollywood has gotten in its mind that black people
shouldn't be seen as merely people, but super doctors or cops.
People who love and lust and get their hearts broken. Not being
comical makes us too human, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday night's ``Love Songs,'' a modest Showtime film that
links three stories, you'll find all of the above, and then some.
Gossett plays a bar owner and family man who kisses his wife
passionately, works hard and cares deeply for the welfare of his
son and abused sister-in-law. Like the other main characters who
turn up in this intriguing trilogy, he stars in one story and
weaves in and out of the others as a supporting player.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice little device that works, particularly once you get
the drift of what the creators are trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Love Songs,'' which airs at 7 p.m. CDT on the
cable channel, includes Gossett, Andre Braugher and Robert
Townsend, who all take turns starring, co-starring and directing
the short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Whitfield also stars, along with Rachel Crawford, Carl
Gordon, Dule Hill and Sandra Caldwell. All of the interlocking
stories were written by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright and
screenwriter Charles Fuller, and are set in the same working-class
black community. It's a place that has the usual variety of
problems, but judging from its closeness, is actually presented as
being quite idyllic.
</P>
<P>
   As is always the case with anthologies, the mix is uneven. In
``A Love Song for a Champ,'' directed by Gossett, Townsend plays a
boxer (Champ) who is either up-and-coming or over-the-hill. He
doesn't look much like a prize fighter, but perhaps that's the
point. His real job is being a car mechanic, but it doesn't pay the
bills. Nor does it satisfy the soul. The story centers around
Champ's frustration in the often corrupt boxing game, using a
specific event that tests his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend is charming as Champ, which isn't surprising, and
Crawford's turn as his very pregnant and very worried wife lends a
sense of seriousness to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The bar that Gossett's Reuben owns is Champ's hang-out place,
and in one scene, Braugher (Ellis) is shown yelling from his fruit
truck while Whitfield (Jean) rips into him for being ``a disgusting
loudmouth.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that once ``A Love Song for a Champ''
ends, ``A Love Song for Jean and Ellis,'' directed by Townsend,
begins with Ellis courting Jean, with no chance whatsoever. But a
brutal rape attempt on Jean changes both of their lives. The treat
is seeing Braugher's chronic ear-to-ear smile and upbeat nature. (A
shot of him waiting for his love, a picnic spread at the ready, a
huge smile on his face, will simply tickle ``Homicide: Life on the
Street'' fans.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Love Song for Dad,'' with Braugher taking his first shot
at directing, Reuben teaches his son (Hill) that violence is the
last resort when it comes to protecting his sister-in-law from her
abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Songs'' won't knock you over. In fact, even the stories
featuring abusive elements come with a twinge of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe that's the point. ``Sweetness'' isn't a word readily
attached to film projects where the cast is exclusively
African-American. How sad.
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE THIS WEEK:
</P>
<P>
   Now there's fashion, the series. American Movie Classics kicks
off a weekly series examining why we remember what Cher wore when
accepting her Oscar rather than the role in which she played to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hollywood Fashion Machine'' (6:30 p.m. CDT Monday) is a
sly attempt by AMC to gain a foothold into the enormously popular
fashion/celebrity hype. Daryl Hannah hosts the 30-minute opener, on
Edith Head, whose honors included eight Academy Awards. She had an
unparalleled career in costume design from the late 1930s until her
death in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Star Makers'' is the second installment of this series,
slated for May 3. It looks at Hollywood's star-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Note: AMC will soon premiere another weekly series (hosted by
Lauren Bacall) which showcases a film featuring trendsetting or, as
they put it in a press release, ``breakthrough costumes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic: Answers From the Abyss'' (7 p.m. CDT Sunday,
Discovery) _ Enough, already. Discovery revisits the luxury liner's
resting place and, with what it claims as new technology,
challenges some theories surrounding the disaster. Wait. Following
is ``Inside the Titanic,'' which looks at the living spaces of the
ship as they are today, submerged, in case some bored billionaire
wants to try and book them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimate Portrait: Lindsay Wagner'' (9 p.m. CDT Sunday,
Lifetime) _ Lifetime again digs deep for a subject. Wagner's
``Bionic Woman'' is her claim to fame, unless you count a string of
women-in-distress, made-for-TV movies. Lifetime lists her as
``Emmy-level,'' which is a polite way to say that she never won
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Durango'' (8 p.m. CDT Sunday, CBS) _ Based on the
autobiographical novel by Irish writer John B. Keane, this is the
story of a young Irishman who in 1939 plans a daring 40-mile-long
cattle drive to outfox a ruthless local merchant. Oscar winner
Brenda Fricker plays an irrepressible woman who helps the lad carry
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dean Koontz's Mr. Murder'' (8 p.m. CDT Monday, ABC) _ There's
a reason why this miniseries is close to, but not in the pivotal
sweeps month of May, and why it begins on a Monday. Hmmm. It's
about a successful mystery writer and his family who are terrorized
by a stranger. It stars Stephen Baldwin and Julie Warner (now
moving in on ``Party of Five'' as the latest Salenger girl toy)..
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights'' (8
p.m. CDT Tuesday, CBS) _ Does anyone care if Patty's still rockin'
in Brooklyn Heights? Duke reprises her roles from ``The Patty Duke
Show'' as look-alike cousins Patty and Cathy Lane. The girls are
not nearly as perky _ OK, OK, it's been 33 years. This might appeal
to the core fans or it might be used just for laughs. For even more
nostalgia, Cindy Williams (''Laverne &AMP; Shirley'') stars as the
cousins' high school nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nickelodeon's 12th Annual Kids' Choice Awards'' (7 p.m. CDT
May 1, Nickelodeon) _ Rosie O'Donnell is back as host of this
annual awards show, which ranks right up there with the MTV Movie
Awards as one that gives viewers a fun ride. Besides, it's
interesting to see what young voters have chosen in the fields of
music, film, television and sports.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
