<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-6     04-23 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES TELL OF HARSH TREK THROUGH THE MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(mb) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIPKOVO, Macedonia _ And still they come, thousands of refugees
straggling over the ice-packed mountains, freezing, exhausted and
bereft, carrying mud-caked clothes on their backs, whimpering
children in their arms, horror in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. aid workers say that extraordinary numbers of ethnic
Albanians seem to be trekking their way through the rugged peaks
that span the border between Kosovo and Macedonia. There are at
least 10,000 on the move, and possibly 10 times that.
</P>
<P>
   They emerge from their harsh, up-and-down journey in villages
like this one, where on Friday hundreds finally found shelter in a
mosque. They ate loaves of bread, dozed on the carpeted floor and
smoked up mounds of tobacco in hand-rolled cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Delivered into safety and warmth, the refugees nevertheless made
no secret of being belly-shot by life. Nazlie Hysku, 67, ached in
her shoulders, her legs and especially her heart. ``Is there a God
anymore for Albanians?'' she asked, closing her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Zyrije Hasani, 33, was relieved that her 4-year-old had
surrendered to sleep. The boy had been coughing up blood. He had
conked out an hour before, and now she watched him gratefully until
he began to twitch. Then she wondered what fears jolted through his
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has seen people being shot,'' the mother said. ``He has
seen people lying dead.''
</P>
<P>
   People were frantic to leave Kosovo, but the Serbians did not
permit the ease of automobiles. To get to Macedonia, the cold
mountains would have to be crossed on foot _ a forced march into a
treacherous and unfamiliar landscape. Often, they walked without
the benefit of even a slim path. People would have to sleep on the
snow, slip in the mud, collapse on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the pitch of one recent night, Zyrije Hasani of the village
of Begunce heard her little daughter stumble and then roll down a
gully. She was found with the help of a searchlight, and men formed
a human chain to pass the girl back to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Another toddler was not so fortunate. According to several who
were there, one night an 18-month-old boy similarly tumbled down a
mud-sloped ravine. The child was not found until the next morning.
He was given a burial not far from where he fell.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, these refugees _ and thousands like them _ had
found sanctuary in a 60-house flyspeck called Malina, just across
the border into Macedonia. The village seemed to be a vortex of
intersecting mountain paths, and its residents had taken it upon
themselves to patrol the area on horseback, welcoming the tired and
the sick to a very humble oasis.
</P>
<P>
   Malina is a poor place. Visitors slept 20 and 30 to a room. Tray
after tray of biscuits baked in the ovens, but flour was running
low. The U.N. High Commission for Refugees knew of the problems,
but the Macedonian government had refused to allow the agency's
trucks to bring in food and medicine. The narrow mountain roads ran
close to Serbian strongholds, and the government asserted that the
rescue operation was too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Macedonians relented, but when the aid workers
arrived in Malina, they found that most of the refugees had
journeyed on, returning to the mountain passes and looking for
other towns and other samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have teams searching for these people in the nearby
villages,'' said Paula Ghedini, a U.N. spokeswoman in Macedonia's
capital, Skopje. ``We have to hunt the refugees before we can help
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. teams have questioned people about their days _ and
sometimes weeks _ roaming through the steep terrain. From reports
compiled so far, at least 10 children and ``a few of the elderly''
have died during the long ordeal, Ms. Ghedini said.
</P>
<P>
   International aid workers may be doing their best, but in large
part it has fallen to the ethnic Albanians of Macedonia to take
care of the ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. Far more refugees are now
being housed in private homes than in official transit camps.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The people who left Malina walked five hours to the village of
Presnic, where they again received food and shelter. Then they
endured another five-hour struggle toward Lipkovo, which is about
25 miles northeast of Skopje. Lipkovo's farmers drove out to meet
them in tractors and carried them the final few miles in flat-bed
trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the mosque, fed and rested, the refugees told
frightening tales of two sorts _ calamities in their home villages
and calamities during their arduous escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbian paramilitary went house to house, demanding
money,'' said Azemine Hysku, 38, from the village of Libiste. ``You
could hear them knocking and the shouting. So much knocking, so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Serbian soldiers, ethnic purging carries the benefit of
personal profiteering. The Albanians were told to produce thousands
of dollars or pay with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the refugees who on Friday arrived in Lipkovo came from
Libiste. They told of the same triple murder. The Serbians had made
an example of three young men, beating them in the open road and
then mutilating the bodies with some odd and sordid symbolism. One
corpse was scalped. Another had its eyes plucked out. The third was
deprived of fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see such things, you grow sick with fear,'' Azemine
Hysku said.
</P>
<P>
   However difficult the effort to reach Macedonia, there was no
celebration _ or even psychic comfort _ upon reaching the border.
Serbian guards were there to extort a crossing fee.
</P>
<P>
   Adem Aziri, a 52-year-old man from Begunce, was in a large group
that pooled together almost $10,000 to bribe the guards. ``They
were very pleased with us,'' Aziri said. ``They told us where to
step in order to avoid the mine fields. And they gave us advice on
how to avoid the Macedonian police.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians already make up a share of Macedonia that is
variously estimated at 17 percent to 35 percent. The Macedonian
majority does not get along well with the Albanian minority _ and
it fears a disadvantageous change in the population's percentages.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian police are often as feared as the Serbians.
``When they saw us, they fired their guns,'' said Hazir Aziri, 22,
Adem's nephew. ``I froze up with fear, but it turned out we were
very lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called us dogs,'' he said. ``And then they let us go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
