<SLUG> BC-FIRE-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.2 MILLION AWARD IN CHILDREN'S FIRE DEATHS THROWN OUT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A jury's $1.2 million damage award against
the city of Houston is invalid because family members who sued over
the fire deaths of two children made their claim too late, a
federal judge said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The jury decided in a March trial that the Houston Fire
Department's failure to repair a ladder truck water pump
contributed to the deaths of Crystal Durden, 3, and her cousin,
Alex Freeman, 4.
</P>
<P>
   However, the jury also said that Ruth Hill, the children's
grandmother, and Schanell Durden, Crystal's mother, notified the
city of damage claims six months past the statutory deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Because that notification missed the deadline, U.S. Magistrate
Judge John Froeschner ruled the family cannot collect the damage
award.
</P>
<P>
   Froeschner's ruling puts the two-week March trial and verdict on
track for review by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court's ruling will be critical to whether the
children's family can press federal civil rights claims against the
city in connection with their deaths. In a portion of their
original lawsuit that has yet to be tried, the family maintains the
Fire Department discriminatorily placed old, run-down firefighting
equipment in minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Family attorneys want the appellate court to affirm the jury's
ruling that the Fire Department's failure to follow its own repair
guidelines contributed to the children's deaths in a January 1996
fire at Hill's home.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
