<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-TRANSAM24-C     04-23 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-TRANSAM24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refined Trans Am at its best
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox Service Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although only 30 years old, the Pontiac Firebird Trans
Am is absolutely antediluvian, having been launched before the
flood of emission restrictions, energy crises and pseudo muscle
cars that don't throb and go vroom-vroom.
</P>
<P>
   It's wonderfully primitive, in other words, and is intended to
appeal to enthusiasts in their 30s and 40s who have the means to
make their old memories come alive. A thirtysomething woman, one of
many admirers of the test Firebird Trans Am convertible, looked it
over inside and out, shook her head and said, ``If I'd had that car
when I was 17, I'd still be in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed, and time is what the Trans Am is running
out of, with AutoWeek and other publications reporting that General
Motors will eliminate the various Firebirds and Camaros in the next
couple of years. (GM's response is to say the cars are scheduled to
be built through 2002.)
</P>
<P>
   If so, the current models represent a good stopping point, and
the Trans Am convertible represents the beast at its best. Add the
ram air option package ($3,150) to a list of standard features that
includes air conditioning, leather seats, a 500-watt stereo with
eight speakers and keyless entry, and the Trans Am ragtop can be a
fairly comfortable, usually tractable daily driver.
</P>
<P>
   For $34,535, buyers also get a 320-horsepower V-8, their choice
of a four-speed automatic transmission or six-speed manual (the
drivetrain is a variant of the Corvette's) and EPA figures in the
same range as those massive sport-utilities being bought by many
peers of Trans Am owners. Suffice it to say that one of the best
changes Pontiac made for '99 was upping the fuel tank capacity to
16.8 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the Trans Am with the big V-8 (5.7 liters, or 346
cubic inches, in old-times terms) isn't a pure holdover from the
one-trick pony car days. It's got that same old straight-line speed
and still launches like those Trans Ams that had the screaming
chickens painted on their hoods, but is much more refined. The
suspension and ride are taut, the handling is decent (save when wet
pavement strips away traction) and the driving is, face it, fun.
</P>
<P>
   The negatives are around, though, if you care to complain. The
test car's power top operated only when the car was parked
perfectly level. Entry and exit are an athletic exercise, and the
token, scooped-out rear seats won't take even a small-bottomed
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long for those characteristics, along with the
pleasing ones, to reinforce the first impression: The Trans Am is
an either/or car, one that can be as easy to hate as to love. But
for those who love rumbly muscle cars, it doesn't get much better
than this today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
