<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASH-GORGE-DISPUTE-97     04-23 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-GORGE-DISPUTE-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT OVER HOUSE EXPOSES TENSIONS IN COLUMBIA RIVER GORGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ore., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINDLE, Wash. _ Perched on a gusty bluff high above the
Columbia River, the dream house that Brian and Jody Bea are trying
to build here looks out on a spectacular vista. Evergreens and
basalt hills are all around. And, across the way in Oregon,
620-foot Multnomah Falls, one of that state's most popular tourist
sites, cascades down into the broad river.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a big problem with this house with a view: It can
be viewed all too well.
</P>
<P>
   In an escalating dispute that pits environmental groups against
property-rights advocates and has become a major test of a
13-year-old federal law intended to protect the beauty of the
gorge, the bi-state Columbia River Gorge Commission has ordered the
Beas to move their house at least 200 feet so that it will be far
less visible from the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, any new structure must be ``visually subordinate
to its landscape setting.'' The commission says the
4,000-square-foot house, which sits in a clearing cut out of the
woods by the Beas and has a soaring cedar facade, bright green roof
and large windows, clearly violates that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   But Bea, a 28-year-old physician's assistant who grew up in a
smaller, less visible home owned by his parents, just below the new
house, and whose great-grandfather homesteaded the land on which
the house is being built, says it fits beautifully into the gorge
scenery. Backed by a conservative property-rights group, he is
suing the commission and vows to fight all the way to the U.S.
Supreme Court, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offends me that people would come here and say this is an
eyesore,'' asserted Bea, who said it cost $300,000 to build the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the environmentalists who say the house violates
the law, Bea, a first lieutenant in the Oregon National Guard,
invokes military terminology. ``This is their Armageddon,'' he
said. ``This is their Waterloo. They're drawing their line in the
sand. Well, we're ready to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Columbia Gorge, a nonprofit organization based in
Portland, Ore., that has taken the lead in opposing the Beas, said
that about 600 homes had been built in the gorge without major
controversy since President Reagan signed the gorge protection bill
into law. But Kevin Gorman, executive director of the group,
maintains that the Beas' house is such a clear violation of the law
that allowing it to stand as is would ``send a terrible message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let this go through,'' he added, ``you really have
pulled the rug out from under the act.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which has successfully challenged plans to build
other houses in the gorge but, until now, never one that is nearly
complete, has offered to give the Beas at least $20,000 worth of
help to move the house, but the Beas have said no. The house could
be damaged in transit, they fear, and they don't want to move
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit against the commission, the Beas call the act's
requirements unconstitutionally vague _ ``so vague that men and
women of common intelligence must necessarily guess at its meaning
and differ as to its application,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, they are obeying a stop-work order on the house, but
they said they could move in within weeks if they were allowed to
finish the drywall and other interior features.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's depressing coming up here,'' said Jody Bea, who is
pregnant and living in a rental home in nearby Washougal with the
couple's first child, 15-month old Brandon. ``Brian took me here
when we were first dating and said this is the spot. It doesn't
feel that way now. All we can do is look around.''
</P>
<P>
   How the construction of a single house mushroomed into a major
legal fight over the gorge protection act itself is a tale that
seems to spring from a series of misunderstandings, beginning with
Skamania County's initial approval of the Beas' plans for the house
and including what might charitably be called creative
interpretations on their part of those plans. (An upstairs
``loft,'' for instance, consists of four bedrooms and two
bathrooms.)
</P>
<P>
   The commission says Bea did not maintain adequate vegetation and
other natural screening, as promised in the plans.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight has also exposed tensions in communities along the
85-mile gorge over the law, which some here see as a clear abuse of
government power _ the Skamania County commissioners ordered the
courthouse flag flown at half-staff for a week when Reagan signed
the legislation into law. Others, however, view the law as an
important tool to keep the gorge pristine for tourism, which in
recent years has become the dominant industry here. (While a lumber
mill used to be the biggest employer in the county, that
distinction now belongs to the Skamania Lodge, a resort and
conference center.)
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners who have worked painstakingly to comply with the
law are clearly angry at the Beas, saying that it is very feasible
to build houses that blend in so well with the gorge that they are
nearly invisible, thus preserving the magnificent vistas that make
the area, which is essentially a large wooded canyon with one of
the greatest concentrations of waterfalls anywhere in the world, so
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house they have put up is an obscene gesture,'' said
Daniel Dancer, a writer and photographer who eight years ago built
his own house farther east in the gorge in Underwood, Wash. ``They
totally overdid it. We might have liked to make our home a little
taller or a little closer to the bluff, but I'm a firm believer in
the importance of following these rules, which are there to protect
the gorge.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are clearly on the Beas' side, and regard the house
as a way to fight back against the gorge protection act. Earlier
this year The Skamania County Pioneer News complained in an
editorial that bureaucrats and environmentalists ``want us all
living in camouflage yurts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And, invoking the region's most famous explorers, a recent
letter to the editor of The Columbian, a daily newspaper published
in nearby Vancouver, Wash., said: ``The right of an American family
to venture west and establish a home secure from capricious
government interference is threatened along the very stretch of
river where Lewis and Clark's discoveries culminated.''
</P>
<P>
   The order to move the house was described by one member of the
gorge commission as the ``least-worst of a lot of terrible
solutions.'' But the Beas, aided by the Pacific Legal Foundation, a
property-rights group whose offices are in Sacramento, Calif., are
fighting the order in court, and the battle could stretch on for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Bea says the real fight is between the gorge commission and the
county, which approved his plans in the first place. ``I simply
think we're a bone between two dogs here,'' he said, adding:
``We're not moving the house. It's ridiculous. Would you move your
house?''
</P>
<P>
   But Gorman of the Friends of the Columbia Gorge says that the
house is clearly in the wrong place and that the Beas should accept
the offers of help to move it. ``If they relocate the house now,''
Gorman added, ``the Beas could be in their home this spring and
still live in one of the most beautiful places on earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
