<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado Web site urges students to decry violence and gun use
 &HT;    Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet surfers curious about Colorado are greeted now with
information about the tragedy at Columbine High School in
Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you help? How can you get help?'' is a top link on the
Colorado state homepage, along with a link to Gov. Bill Owens'
pledge against gun violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state page directs potential donors to send money to the
Mile High United Way's Community Healing Fund, offers directions to
potential blood donors to locations on the Front Range and provides
a list of 14 hot line numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It also directs families and relatives of victims to the
Jefferson County Sheriff's Office victim's service center, where
people could arrange for transportation and lodging assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The center's voice mailbox was full Thursday night. Youngsters
also can print out a copy of the governor's pledge that they can
sign and give to their teacher or school principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never bring a gun to school; I will never use a gun to
settle a dispute; I will use influence with my friends to keep them
from using guns to settle disputes,'' says the pledge. ``My
individual choices and actions, when multiplied by those of young
people throughout the country, will make a difference. Together, by
honoring this pledge, we can reverse the violence and grow up in
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado state homepage is www.state.co.us and access to the
pledge is available at www.state.co.us/pledge/
</P>
<P>
   Harmon writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
