A0914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-COMMUNICATIONS24-     04-23 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COMMUNICATIONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox exits PSC business with Sprint sale
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two Cox companies completed their exit from the
day-to-day business of operating a digital wireless telephone
network Friday, selling off the last piece of this business to
long-distance carrier Sprint for $1.2 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The sale marks the end of a strategy announced last spring. At
that time, Cox Communications and privately held Cox Enterprises
Inc., which owns a majority of the cable TV concern, said they
wanted to leave the PCS business.
</P>
<P>
   The companies began that process by transferring a 20 percent
stake in a joint venture called Sprint Spectrum to a new company
controlled by Sprint. The Sprint venture sells wireless service
based on a digital technology called personal communications
services, or PCS. It is different from standard cellular telephone
technology because it is digital and enables several functions to
work in one device, such as telephone, pager, e-mail and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was among the pioneers of PCS, winning a special federal
license to develop a wireless network based on the technology in
Southern California in the early 1990s. Sprint has since expanded
that network across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Cox still believes in the technology. That's why, the company
said, it opted to receive Sprint stock rather than cash in exchange
for its PCS operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this transaction marks our departure from the PCS
business as an operator, we remain bullish on the business and are
delighted to remain an investor,'' said David Woodrow, Cox
Communications' senior vice president for new business development.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as a passive investor in new technologies has been Cox
Communications' traditional role. It holds many stakes in
new-technology companies, such as Internet access provider At Home.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal announced Friday, Cox exercised an
option to require Sprint to buy out its remaining 40.8 percent
stake in the PCS business. Sprint bought out Cox's stake with 24.3
million shares of its Series 2 common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Enterprises held an 8.8 percent of that stake and Cox
Communications the remainder. The transaction is expected to close
in the second quarter. Cox Communications is one of the country's
largest cable TV concerns, with 3.8 million subscribers. Cox
Enterprises is a diversified media conglomerate. Its holdings
include The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
