<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR TO SUIT UP DESPITE NEW INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ He battled the pain and aggravation of a
severely sprained ankle that forced him to miss 32 games, and dealt
with a groin strain that sidelined him for the final regular-season
contest against the Flyers. And during the Bruins' Game 1 victory
against the Carolina Hurricanes Thursday, center Tim Taylor added a
broken nose to his list of physical woes.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor finished the game, playing his usual steady style on the
club's top checking line, and Friday practiced as normal despite a
bad bruise across the bridge of his nose that had affected his
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (restricted) it for a time, but we put some cotton in there
and it was fine,'' said Taylor, who will suit up for Game 2 of the
best-of-seven series Saturday night at the Coliseum. ``Through the
night it was leaking out a little bit but now it's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who was elbowed in the face by center Jeff O'Neill after
a faceoff, said such injuries are the price you pay in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens to everyone,'' said Taylor. ``(Linemate Rob
DiMaio) goes through that five times a year. It's just something
that comes with the game. I had it broken a couple of times before.
This one seems to shove it over a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill wasn't assessed a penalty on the play, despite Taylor's
best efforts at getting the attention of the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came through on the draw and I was holding up (Ron) Francis
and he elbowed me as I was getting the puck,'' said Taylor. ``It
hurt and I tried to make the referee (notice it) and I thought he
was going to call a penalty but he didn't. I tried to let him know
that he did catch me with his elbow, but those referees did a good
job, especially in the first 10 minutes. It was a hard-hitting game
and they let a lot of things go. It kind of dictated the rest of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio scored the club's first goal early in the third period,
and fourth-line left wing Ken Belanger accounted for Boston's other
goal. The playoffs are often greatly affected by the contributions
made from the third- and fourth-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need everyone playing well,'' said Taylor. ``We know that
goals are going to be hard to come by. A big goal lifts our hockey
club and a big defensive play lifts us as well, so as long as we
can shut the other team down, if we get a goal it's going to help
our team win. The power play wasn't going too well so it was a
situation where Robbie stepped up and got a big goal for us. Then
Kenny Belanger scored and it was 2-0. I don't think it was two guys
the other team expected to score so it was a big boost for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was given the task of smothering Carolina captain Keith
Primeau. Primeau, who levied some huge hits during the contest, was
held off the board and Taylor said he's hoping he made a dent in
his pysche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game I can shut him down and get in his face a little
bit it's going to help us in the long run,'' he said. ``These
series aren't usually won in the first or second game, it's (the
later games) where you're pounding and pounding and in his face.
Hopefully, he'll take some retaliation penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor in that combination has been the contribution
of left wing P.J. Axelsson, who most likely won't get the
consideration he deserves for the Selke Trophy as the league's top
defensive forward. Axelsson is normally with Taylor and DiMaio but
Friday at practice was on a line with Joe Thornton and Anson Carter
because Steve Heinze was bothered by sore groin muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of times, little defensive things go unnoticed, but guys
who play defense notice it a lot,'' said Taylor. ``I know the
coaches really appreciate the way P.J. plays day in and day out.
His skill level is great defensively. He knows exactly where to be
at all times. For a guy his size to have that physical nature, a
lot of Europeans don't go like that, especially a guy his size. He
brings that attribute to the table every game. When he plays like
that, he's a big factor for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
