<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS ATTACK MERGER OF EUROPEAN TELEPHONE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Only two days after formally reaching an
agreement on the biggest merger in European history, Deutsche
Telekom and Telecom Italia came under attack Friday from Italian
government leaders, shareholders and competitors, raising doubts
about the deal's future.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrecting an issue that had seemed to be settled, Italian
officials threatened to block the $82 billion stock transaction
between the two telephone giants if the German government refused
to offer more explicit assurances about its plans to reduce its
stake in Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   There were also signs that some of Italy's top business leaders,
who are shareholders in Telecom Italia, were throwing their support
to a rival $65 billion bid by Olivetti SpA, Telecom Italia's main
domestic competitor.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Olivetti, which is pressing ahead with its
unsolicited offer, said Friday that investors had oversubscribed
Olivetti's new bond and stock offerings that would be used to
finance its takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Italian newspaper La Repubblica reported Friday
that a number of Telecom Italia's big shareholders had sided with
Olivetti. The list includes the Agnelli group, the insurance
company Assicurazioni Generali and Comit, an Italian bank.
</P>
<P>
   In an outward indication of shifting sentiment, investors bid up
the shares of Tecnost SpA, an obscure subsidiary of Olivetti that
it is using as the legal vehicle for the attempted purchase of
Telecom Italia. Tecnost shares, traded in Milan, jumped 10 percent
to 9.6 euros after Italian officials raised new complaints about
the deal with Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders were also grumbling in Germany Friday. The German
Shareholder Protection Group, a Duesseldorf association that
represents small investors, warned that the merger with Telecom
Italia still had ``skeletons in the closet'' and might be a bad
deal for Deutsche Telekom shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The group also complained that the merged company would remain
vulnerable to political interference, implicitly from the Italian
government, and warned that the two companies' awkward plan to
alternate chairmen every year would do little to solve that
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of configuration is not practical and hides a big
potential for risk,'' the association said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness of Deutsche Telekom's share price also could pose a
serious problem for the merger partners because it hurts the value
of the deal for Telecom Italia shareholders, who will be paid the
equivalent of one Deutsche Telekom share for every three Telecom
Italia shares.
</P>
<P>
   Although Deutsche Telekom shares ended unchanged Friday at 35.50
euros, they have fallen 1.6 percent since the deal was formally
announced Wednesday, when it was worth 12.03 euros a share or $82
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That means at Friday's price, the value of the deal is 11.8
euros a share or about $80.5 billion and could decline further.
Much of the speculation Friday grew out of muddled statements from
the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's finance minister, Vicenzo Visco, insisted Friday that
the German government had to provide greater assurances about its
plan to reduce its 72 percent stake in Deutsche Telekom. The issue
is the same one that bogged down Telecom Italia's board earlier
this week, but it appeared to have been resolved when the German
government issued a comforting but noncommittal letter saying that
it would reduce its stake over time and had no interest in running
Telekom on a day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Visco and other Italian officials demanded that the
German government offer more concrete assurances for ``parity''
between the Italian and German companies and more specific detail
about its own plan to reduce its stake in Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not reasonably acceptable or conceivable that Telecom
Italia is bought by a German state company,'' Visco told reporters
in Rome. ``The Germans must give clear, precise and rapid signals
on parity and on the timetable of privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   German officials offered nothing new in response. Torsten Albig,
spokesman for the German Ministry of Finance, said the Italian
objections had already been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom has already announced plans to float a big new
stock offering in the next several months, which would dilute the
German government's share. The government has repeatedly said it
wants to sell off its holdings in an orderly fashion over the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   But the German government has refused to limit its voting rights
and refused to spell out a particular timetable for selling its
stake.
</P>
<P>
   That has galvanized Italian critics. Silvio Berlusconi, the
former prime minister and financier, complained on Thursday that
Germans already own big stakes in Italy's second-biggest cellular
telephone company and in Wind, a competitor to Telecom Italia in
fixed-line service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Telecom also becomes German, we will have to send our
children to German school,'' Berlusconi told the Business Club
d'Italia. ``I don't like this project.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Anger over the deal also is rising at France Telecom, which
regards it as a double-cross by Deutsche Telekom. The two companies
are partners along with the Sprint Corp. in Global One, a
joint-venture that serves multinational corporations but which is
losing hundreds of millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining that Deutsche Telekom violated agreements to consult
with it before making a big strategic change, France Telecom said
it ``deplores this behavior and will undertake whatever action is
appropriate to protect its rights and the interests of its
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Though both Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom insist they
support the Global One venture, the merger would create new
conflicts. Telecom Italia, for example, is a shareholder in Telecom
9, a new competitor in France to France Telecom. It also owns a
stake in Retavision of Spain, a new competitor to Telefonica de
Espana. France Telecom owns a stake in a third Spanish telephone
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at France Telecom refused to say anything Friday
about their plans for Global One or about any legal action against
Deutsche Telekom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
