<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0919 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-B     04-23 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON SAYS PAIN IS GONE, HE'LL PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The ache, twinge, and soreness, whatever the
bubble and squeak has been around Joe Thornton's sternum,
disappeared Friday in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 100 percent,'' said the Bruins' ever-smiling sophomore
center. ``I'm in. I feel good. It will be good to be in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   So is this the South's version of Lourdes? Is there something in
the Greensboro Reservoir that makes the wounded want to shed their
bandages and kick up their heels?
</P>
<P>
   Thornton came here hurting, after getting banged up last week as
the regular season came to a close, and coach Pat Burns figured his
No. 2 center would have to sit out at least one or two games. When
the Bruins won their playoff series opener against the 'Canes
Thursday night, 2-0, the conventional wisdom was that Jumbo Joe
would sit out Game 2, adding another 48 hours to his recovery
process. Everyone knows that a 1-0 series lead can be as good as a
pocketful of anti-inflammatories when it comes to the
rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
   But when the puck is dropped Saturday night, Thornton will be
wearing his familiar No. 6 and playing his role as No. 2 center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took some hits along the boards to get a feel,'' said
Thornton, shortly after Friday's brief workout. ``I wasn't asking
guys to hit me or anything, but I was testing it _ and it feels
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's return now, when the postseason math says he doesn't
have to be here, is a reflection of the kind of struggle the Bruins
had in Game 1. The 'Canes came at them harder, banged them more
often and intensely, than any club has since they met the Islanders
in the 1983 Stanley Cup semifinals. Who could forget the
heavyweight bout between Clark Gillies and Terry O'Reilly? The
Islanders went on to win their fourth consecutive Stanley Cup _ a
4-0 sweep of Wayne Gretzky's Oilers in the finals _ and it was all
the more impressive after the pounding, brawling series they had
with the Bruins lasted six games.
</P>
<P>
   There were no fights between the 'Canes and the Bruins. The
former Forever .500s came out with a ferocious forecheck that left
the Bruins flatfooted for nearly the opening half of the first
period. If not for Burns recognizing the sparkle on Ken Belanger's
chiseled teeth, and Belanger being able to help neutralize the
runaway freight train that was Keith Primeau, the assault would
have lasted longer and the night's outcome could have been vastly
different.
</P>
<P>
   To open the game, Burns had Randy Robitaille filling Thornton's
pivot spot between Dmitri Khristich and Sergei Samsonov. Tossed
into the torrent, the line was a nonfactor. Either Robitaille
doesn't have the speed and quickness to compete, or he lacked the
confidence to play at full throttle in such a setting. His two
wingers looked equally lost. Robitaille was told to return to
Providence after the game and, hours later, Thornton's sternum was
feeling mighty fine. Funny how that works.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see a little more, I'd say, stability in our lines with
Joe back,'' said No. 1 center Jason Allison, who saw a variety of
wingers in Game 1, Burns rolling the numbers, looking for any
spark. ``You'll still see some mixing, but Joe's our second center,
and at times he's played great for us. He's an important part of
the team right now, and it will be nice to have him back _ as you
saw, we didn't have a first, second, third line out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if not for Belanger, they might have had a 60-minute
911 drill out there. But slowly, the momentum changed, the 'Canes
obviously losing their enthusiasm when faced with Belanger's
pound-for-pound return to their hits and Byron Dafoe's continuing
airtight work in goal. No team can play foot to the floor for 60
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Canes will spring the same attack on the Bruins again in
Game 2, hoping to cash in on a couple of early chances, and it very
well could be their last chance to win the series. They don't have
the kind of scoring depth to overcome a 2-0 series deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, meanwhile, can't count on winning again with goals
by Rob DiMaio and Belanger. Burns has to figure out which four
wingers to package around Allison and Thornton and keep his
dependable trio, DiMaio, P.J. Axelsson, and Tim Taylor, in their
valuable checking role. He kept borrowing from that line in Game 1,
sprinkling the three into different combinations, in hopes
something would click.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton came here wishing that he could play in Game 1. He left
Wilmington Wednesday with the dream of convincing Burns that he was
OK to play. Burns wouldn't listen. When the game began, Thornton
was in the stands, hearing the heavy Hurricane bodychecks resonate
through the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I say, `Thank God?' '' said Thornton, asked if, when he
saw the hitting, he was thankful not to bring his battered body
into battle. ``No, it wasn't like that. But I suppose it was smart
(to sit out), just in case I ran into someone like that, I might
have ended up worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight hours later, cured and eager, Thornton gets his
turn. Look out, Lourdes. There could be another player in the
miracle game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
