A0921 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLA-SURPLUSOFRECRUITS     04-23 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLA-SURPLUSOFRECRUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY APPARENTLY HAS A SURPLUS OF RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNWOOD, Texas _ Azem S. and his younger brother, Beqir, are
prepared to die.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of men in New York, Chicago, Germany,
Switzerland, even small towns in Central Texas, the ethnic Albanian
brothers would like to leave the homes and families they have
worked so hard for to join the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But the KLA, once a radical nationalist group that enjoyed few
members in its ranks, is apparently so overrun with recruits from
around the world that it is turning away healthy and willing men
like Azem and Beqir.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many men joining the KLA and they have no weapons
for them,'' Azem said. ``Also, I'm not too young. They're looking
for younger men, more strong men. They told me to wait a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago that the KLA was merely a rag-tag
guerrilla group that sought independence from Serbia, sometimes
using violent methods. But some estimates now put the KLA at around
30,000, some 2,000 of them from the United States who have joined
since hostilities increased a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the KLA staged its only public induction of
recruits from the United States. Almost 400 Albanians gathered
outside a hotel in Yonkers, N.Y., before flying to Tirana. A group
of about 10 Albanians from North Texas, including Ramiz Halili of
Granbury, left with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, the KLA recruited anyone, but now, they're
more selective,'' said Shirley Cloyes, an adviser to the New
York-based Albanian-American Civic League, a lobby organization.
``They've become more professionalized as an army.''
</P>
<P>
   That increased selectiveness has left Azem, 38, and Beqir, 34,
out of the fighting, at least for now. The two brothers _ and three
others _ continue to work long hours in the kitchens of their pizza
and pasta joints in Burleson and Brownwood.
</P>
<P>
   Their story is one of conflicted emotions, torn between the
security of their homes in the United States and their allegiance
to Kosova, the Albanian spelling for their home.
</P>
<P>
   It is also testimony to the fear this war has brought, even to
Brownwood, that the brothers asked that their last name not be
published, because they don't want their family in Kosovo targeted
for what they said here.
</P>
<P>
   The six brothers and four sisters of the family were raised on a
large farm in the southern part of the province, an area where most
of the family still lives.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, Azem had settled in New Jersey, the cradle of Albanian
immigration in the United States. Fully half of the 500,000
Albanians in the country live in the New Jersey/New York area. A
majority are Muslim, but a significant minority are either Eastern
Orthodox or Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the brothers settled in North Texas, where about
1,000 Albanians make their homes, following friends who moved here
to set up one of the many small Italian restaurants that have
popped up in shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   America is unquestionably their home now. Azem's children, a
7-year-old boy and 5-year-old girl, know no other. But their
parents, uncles, aunts and cousins are somewhere in Kosovo, out of
touch since the bombing began and presumably in great danger. They
believe two cousins have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to leave. Who wants to fight a war?'' Azem said.
``But we have to go. We have relatives. How would you feel if your
parents are not safe, if they are waiting to be killed or raped?
Who would want to leave good life here?''
</P>
<P>
   Azem and Beqir, who are in contact with commanders in the KLA,
said the group is mostly having to conduct a guerrilla war against
the Serbian army, which has far more and heavier weapons. The KLA
is also trying to protect refugees who have poured out of the
country, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could buy an F-16,'' Azem cracked, only
half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   While enjoying a resurgence among the Albanian diaspora, the KLA
has been compared to a terrorist organization and Congress has thus
far shied away from helping to arm its members. The KLA's financial
support now comes almost entirely from Albanians living abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Cloyes, the wife of a former New York congressman, strongly
denied the terrorist assertions, saying the KLA is a ``defense
force, a people's movement'' that has not taken any weapons or
money from fundamentalist Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
   Azem and Beqir aren't buying the accusations either.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you call someone a terrorist who is defending his
home?'' he said. ``KLA isn't fighting in Serbia. They're fighting
in their back yard to protect their homes. Since the war started,
do you see any Serb civilians get killed by KLA? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Azem and Beqir ever wear the uniform of the KLA or
whether NATO sends in ground troops to take back Kosovo, they
believe God will ensure them victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't send in ground troops, it will take longer. But
the KLA will win,'' Beqir said. ``You can never occupy someone
forever. You can occupy someone for one year, two year, 30 years,
500 years like Turks. But not forever.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
