<HEADER>
A0928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERUSALEM-RADIO-NYT &LR;      04-23 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERUSALEM-RADIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNING IN TO SALVATION ON ISRAEL'S ULTRA-ORTHODOX PIRATE RADIO
STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Wasted by drugs, his voice broken, the addict on the
line begged for help from Herzl Ben-Aharon, the late-night host on
an ultra-Orthodox pirate radio station, the Voice of Kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see only darkness and I want to see light,'' said the
addict, who identified himself only as Yitzhak. ``Physically I'm
alive, but my soul has been dead for a long time,'' he said,
crying.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Aharon appealed to his listeners for contributions so that
Yitzhak could join a drug rehabilitation program. The money was
raised in minutes, and Yitzhak was beside himself with gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``With God's help, I take upon myself to repent and return to
the faith,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yitzhak, we love you,'' Ben-Aharon said. ``Commit to repent
tonight, and you will be granted the goodness of the Creator. Say a
prayer now for the love of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak responded, ``Hear O Israel, the Lord is our God, the
Lord is One!'' To applause in the studio, Ben-Aharon chimed in,
``Well done, Rebbe Yitzhak.''
</P>
<P>
   Part revival meeting, part yeshiva of the airwaves,
ultra-Orthodox radio in Israel offers spiritual solace, community
assistance and religious guidance to untold thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The programming, geared mostly to Sephardic Jews of traditional
bent, is a window into a culture that is a world apart from
Israel's mainstream secular society, catering to entirely different
listener preferences.
</P>
<P>
   On about a dozen ultra-Orthodox pirate stations that have sprung
up in recent years, several of them in Jerusalem, rabbis and other
broadcasters serve up a mix of biblical lessons and Jewish music,
inspirational sermons, family counseling, stories for children and
charity collections for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting sole allegiance to rabbinic authority and rejecting
government regulation, the stations operate without licenses.
Although they are occasionally been shut down by the police, they
usually go back on the air unimpeded, offering what they call a
``positive Jewish'' alternative to what the broadcasters see as
hopelessly permissive radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   On ``the holy channels,'' as the stations call themselves,
announcers dispense dream interpretations to callers, warnings
against the evil eye, and morality tales about divine reward and
punishment. They exhort nonreligious listeners to become observant.
</P>
<P>
   Talk shows field questions from listeners that range from
marital and child-rearing problems to the occult. On a recent
broadcast, a listener complained that she had been suffering
headaches since she accidentally laundered an amulet, erasing some
of its sacred words. Other callers poured out personal troubles,
asking for a blessing from the rabbi in the studio.
</P>
<P>
   There are no news reports. Instead, programs have featured live
events like a newly religious listener smashing his television set
on the air and another ripping up a secular newspaper, ridding
themselves of the temptations of the material world.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to frequent appeals, listeners donate food, household
goods and appliances to needy families. In keeping with a strict
interpretation of religious law, women's voices are not heard. The
announcers are all male, the music is by male singers only, and
calls from women listeners are relayed by the broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news on Israel radio is hype and idle talk,'' said Shmuel
Ben-Attar, director of The Whole Truth, a pirate station linked to
the ultra-Orthodox Sephardic party Shas. ``The music there has
lyrics we can't listen to. The programs are full of malicious
gossip. We talk about eternal matters, not passing fancies. People
have begun discovering the Torah _ why they're living in this
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lend an ear,'' Ben-Attar continued, adding that the station
is supported by donations. ``We've flown sick people for operations
abroad, reformed criminals through our broadcasts and counseled
couples on the verge of divorce. Prisoners have called us from
jail; they want to discover God. This is community radio that the
state should take on as a project instead of harassing us. It's a
disgrace that we have to operate underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Attar spoke in his station's makeshift studio in a shabby,
smoke-filled hotel suite with a false number on the door to hide
its location. The station has been shut down more than once, and a
sign warned employees to check carefully before opening the door.
</P>
<P>
   The Whole Truth and other such stations seemed to get a new
lease on life recently when the Israeli Parliament passed a bill
legalizing pirate stations that have been broadcasting for at least
five years.
</P>
<P>
   But enforcement of the law, originally drafted to legalize a
station run by Jewish settlers on the West Bank, has been held up
by a challenge in the Israeli Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the pirate stations argue that because they are
unregulated, they can carry inflammatory messages. One rigorously
Orthodox pirate broadcaster was arrested and his station was
dismantled last month after he made a death threat on the air
against a leftist member of Parliament, Yossi Sarid.
</P>
<P>
   Despite, or perhaps because of, their run-ins with the law, the
``holy channels'' enjoy enormous popularity among their listeners,
whose numbers have never been authoritatively determined.
</P>
<P>
   David Ohana, a newly religious grocer who grew up as a secular
Jew, said he did not miss the news on mainstream Israeli radio and
television. ``I'm not interested in hearing who robbed, murdered or
committed suicide,'' he said. ``There are many lies on the news.
Thank God we listen to the words of the Torah.''
</P>
<P>
   To both broadcasters and listeners, these pirate stations are a
bulwark against what they see as the permissiveness of Israeli
society and culture.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent program on the Voice of Kindness, Rabbi Menashe Yona
cautioned listeners against pitfalls they might encounter on a mere
walk down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person goes outside, the atmosphere is inflamed, women are
wearing all kinds of immodest clothes and leading the holy sons of
Israel into sin,'' Rabbi Yona said. ``We must not feast our eyes.
When a young man overcomes his desire and lowers his eyes, his soul
is granted the grace of God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
