<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-WEB-BOS &LR;      04-23 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTITUDE OF ERIC HARRIS PAGES SPROUT ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're full of rough sketches of knife-wielding warriors,
apocalyptic song lyrics, and youthful bravado. At first glance,
they could be the on-line ramblings of any teenager obsessed with
pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   These eerie postings are allegedly the Web pages of Eric D.
Harris, a 17-year-old presumed gunman in the Littleton, Colo.
massacre. The pages were removed from the Internet on Tuesday night
by the service provider America Online and were later subpoenaed by
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Replicas of the pages have emerged in mirror sites all over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting on Tuesday, on-line sleuths have scoured the
Internet to find the pages. Web addresses with any reference to the
words ``trench coat mafia,'' the assailants' teen group, were
bombarded with hits.
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, on-line discussion groups overflowed with
queries about where to find the material on-line. In the first few
days after the tragedy, most of the answers led to dead ends, since
the pages had been removed from their original addresses.
</P>
<P>
   But as of Friday, the bulletin boards teemed with addresses of
Internet users who had captured the original material and reposted
it, with or without commentary. Some of the mirror sites have
already been removed by Internet service providers, but the sites
are going up as fast as they are being taken down.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mirror sites is set up as a sort of resource center
on Harris's Web activity, with photos from the high school
yearbook, copies of the various profiles Harris allegedly posted on
AOL, and news items. This site, which goes by the name ``Soupfreaks
Page of Madness,'' is run by David Hillenbrand, 31, a salesman in
Montclair, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when something like this affects so many people in the
way it did, people want to know what's going on in the mind of
these kids,'' Hillenbrand said in a telephone interview Friday. ``I
know I wanted to see it, and it shows a lot about these kids. They
were living in a fantasy world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillenbrand received the material by posting messages in on-line
bulletin boards. Several of his computer-savvy contacts captured
the pages after the shootings began, and they have been sharing the
information with others all over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One file, labeled simply ``The Book,'' is a primer on how to
build explosives. The description of the bombs contains a chilling
foreshadowing of the suicidal massacre: ``Since they won't be used
until NBK , it'll be kind of hard to report the results,'' the file
said, the ``NBK'' probably referring to the film ``Natural Born
Killers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You might try asking the survivors if they got a good look at
the bomb before it went off and then the remains!'' the file added.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mirror sites, including the one posted by
Hillenbrand, include clear warnings against using the bomb manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that some people might use the information for
the wrong reasons, but they're in the minority,'' Hillenbrand said.
``That's sort of something you have to live with when you want to
have freedom of speech. The majority of people are just interested
in finding out what triggered these kids, and that kind of
information should be preserved so people can see it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
