<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-ALBANIA-0424-     04-23 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ALBANIA-0424-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM ALBANIA: UNFILING TONIGHT -- HERE'S WHY
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Albright.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ ProForndesk ExAlbright: Sorry, Unfiling
Tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Friday's been one of those bad hair days.
</P>
<P>
   It started at 6:15 a.m. when I tried to check my e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   It's taken the last two weeks in Albania to get a reliable way
to send stories. We think there is no need to give further
sustenance to the quick-study capitalists who run the Rogner Hotel
business center and charge $7 a minute for overseas calls.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I went to bed about midnight Thursday, I had signed
up with two local internet service providers for the next three
months. Supposedly I could file stories by e-mail any time of the
day and it would cost us only pennies.
</P>
<P>
   My first internet provider, Abissnet, had to go. They'd only
been in business for a week.
</P>
<P>
   I signed up a rival called Adanet. Cox is Adanet's customer
number 300. The company has been in business all of a month.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, our communications finally seemed to be purring.
</P>
<P>
   But then on Friday morning, I picked up the phone in the
apartment we've just rented and there was no dial tone. It was the
next-worst thing that could have happened besides a lightning surge
that zapped my hard-drive.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment phones were down, and I had no time to ask anyone
about it_ even if I could speak Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   I had to rush for breakfast at the Rogner Hotel here, where most
of the journalists are staying. Then my driver had to hustle out to
Rinas Air Field and try to catch a helicopter for the largest
concentration of refugees near the northeastern border in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two weeks, Marcia Kunstel, my journalistic colleague
(who happens to be my wife), has been covering the flight of the
refugees to Kukes. And now I've gotten word that she needs things
-- a bunch of cash, a pair of Travelsmith quick-drying pants and
some undershirts.
</P>
<P>
   Getting up north to Kukes seemed do-able Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For the last week, I've been chatting up a certain Col. Salem
from the United Arab Emirates, or UAE, who has his own tent inside
the Rinas Air Field.
</P>
<P>
   Out of Muslim solidarity with the Kosovo refugees, the emirs of
UAE have dispatched Col. Salem and others, along with eight
French-made Puma helicopters, to support a slice of the refugees in
Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   To my delight, Col. Salem remembered my face when I turned up in
his operations tent inside the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Saalem Aleichem,'' which roughly means, ``Hello, God
Be With You.'' The colonel said, ``Aleichem Salem,'' (''And God be
With You.'')
</P>
<P>
   By now it is 9 a.m. Friday in Tirana, and pouring big-time.
</P>
<P>
   Someone appeared with a delicious cup of Arabic coffee that the
UAE helicopter pilots had brewed up over a field stove. That cup
was one of the best things that had happened to me in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, my friend Col. Salem said he'd cancelled journalists'
right to fly on all friendly helicopter flights to Kukes. Bad
weather, he said.
</P>
<P>
   I had five hours to kill before the only U.S. military ``media
availability'' of the day -- billed by the U.S. Army briefers as a
chance to meet a female Blackhawk pilot who wouldn't be flying in
the strikes into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   I decide that there will be time to drive up north to an old
Albanian fighter base called Gjader Air Base. Colleagues say the
U.S. military used the Gjader base a few years ago to launch drone
helicopters over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The betting in the press corps is that the Americans will pretty
soon move back into Gjader, perhaps for the U.S. Marines or perhaps
for the Army's MLRS rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Mike Hedges of Scripps-Howard, a pal from the Gulf
War press pools, I decided to drive north and check out what's
happening at Gjader.
</P>
<P>
   It should be only a two hours' drive. But when our driver Ilir
and his 1982 Mercedes taxi gets to the outskirts of the town of
Lac, we hit a traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Mike and I, and his photographer, get out of the Mercedes and
make our way through a crowd of about 500 Albanians to the center
of Lac.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder traffic is tied up. We see a half-dozen guys with
black masks over their heads. They are carrying Kalashnikovs.
</P>
<P>
   We hear some of them shooting a burst or two into what looks
like a restaurant with a big Coca-Cola sign over the entrance.
Someone inside is shooting back. It seems that the Coca-Cola guy
had been whacked.
</P>
<P>
   We lose about an hour, and our trip to the Gjader Air Base was
almost a total waste. The Albanian soldiers on duty at the sentry
posts said they hadn't seen any Americans in a long time. A look
around showed that they weren't fibbing.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike and I decided there was still time to make the Army
briefing back at Rinas Air Field at 4 p.m. -- despite the alarming
potholes on the road to Gjader.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't count on hitting a world-class traffic jam on
Albania's main north-south highway. It made think about how tough
it is going to be for the U.S. Army to move forward in the next
week toward the Kosovo border. Most of the state highways in
Albania look like abandoned logging roads in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Though we'd missed the military briefing by nearly two hours,
all was not lost.
</P>
<P>
   When we got back to our Tirana apartment, we found that the
telephone had regained its dialtone. We were on-line again.
</P>
<P>
   I used the momentary access to dial the internet to check my
e-mails. Then I headed off for the Rogner Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Three things caught my attention in the Rogner's Gift Shop.
</P>
<P>
   To change my luck, I decide to buy all of them: a copy of the
``Blue Guide'' for Albania, an oversized Swiss Army knife and a
bottle of Finlandia vodka.
</P>
<P>
   When I got back to the Cox apartment, I used my thumbnail to
open one of the little blades of the Swiss Army knife. This is what
I used to try and slash open the plastic top of the Finlandia
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Army knife and Finlandia bottle -- it was a bad
combination.
</P>
<P>
   The knife slipped. Instead of cutting off the clear plastic
collar around the bottle cap, the blade punctured my right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The blood started flowing. It keeps flowing, as though I
deserved a Purple Heart. After a while, I put my thumb into the
freezer compartment of the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The bleeding finally stops.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I'll try to explain to my Albanian landlord about why
there is frozen blood in her refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
