<HEADLINE>
D.C. UNITED-REVOLUTION GAME SHOULD BE A JAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rowdiness of the RFK Stadium crowd should be reduced for the
D.C. United-Revolution game Saturday night, and not because of the
50th anniversary celebrations of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. If anything, the presence of the world peacekeepers'
congregation will make traveling to the stadium potentially as
hectic as last week, when the largest regular-season home crowd
(35,167) in D.C. United history caused traffic jams and led to
disorderly conduct in the parking lots and long lines at the ticket
windows.
</P>
<P>
   This should be more like a typical United-Revolution game, with
D.C. setting the pace, the Revolution disrupting, and the fireworks
more likely to occur somewhere near the Revolution bench.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has lost in regulation time this season. But
because of the Major League Soccer rule of deciding tied games,
this will not be a matchup of the top two teams in the Eastern
Conference. If the MLS abided by FIFA regulations, D.C. United
would be in first place with 8 points and the Revolution in second
with 6. Instead, United has 7 points and the Revolution have 3,
since the teams have a 1-4 record in post-match shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   Further illustrating the contradictions and complications of
what is known as ``the simplest game,'' Revolution player-coach
Walter Zenga was dismayed to discover that he is ranked third among
goalkeepers in goals-against and shutouts but among the worst in
winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics are superfluous in soccer, fortunately, and
measurements of the status of a team must be otherwise determined.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have made remarkable defensive improvements, but
in two of their four games, a player has had a major dispute with
either Zenga or assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi. Following the
season-opener in Fort Lauderdale, Carlos Rocha was waived after
demonstrably rejecting Zenga's criticism. Early in the second half
of last week's game against Columbus, midfielder Edwin Gorter was
substituted and hostily encountered Galderisi on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes before, Gorter had complained in a live television
interview that he spent the first half watching the ball fly
overhead like airplanes taking off. Indeed, Gorter was hardly a
factor in a game that almost completely bypassed midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorter did provide a moment of magic, sending a defender
sprawling with some sleight-of-foot, and setting up Johnny Torres
for what could have been the deciding goal. Torres, who had
converted off a Gorter feed for the tying goal against D.C. United
the week before, missed this time and the match ended 0-0 in
regulation time.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Gorter and Zenga had a lengthy discussion in the
Stadium Club. The issue did not seem completely resolved, however,
and there was speculation that Gorter could join the Miami Fusion,
which was attempting to jettison Carlos Valderrama. For now, Gorter
has regained his status as the Revolution's midfield reference
point, at least nominally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edwin has been working hard and has put everything in the
past,'' Galderisi said Friday. ``The team had a meeting on Tuesday
and he knows what is expected of him and of everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my playing career, I used to fight, too. But during the
game, I would run for you. When it came time to play, I would be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorter's complaint about the Revolution's lack of offensive
style is not likely to be easily resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectively, we have to have a positive mentality,''
Galderisi said. ``We will do our best with the qualities we have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former D.C. midfielder John Harkes (right knee sprain) will be
among the Revolution reserves for the first time this season, but
his first extensive action is expected to be against Colorado at
Foxboro Stadium May 1 . . . United goalkeeper Tom Presthus is out
with the combination of a right groin strain and a fever as high as
104 degrees caused by an undetermined virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
