<SLUG> BC-DUDELESS-RANCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY GALS RIDE HERD ON COWS AT WYOMING RANCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBOIS, Wyo. _ A grin coiled like a rattlesnake at the side of
the wrangler's mouth as he explained the particulars of a cattle
roundup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only thing dumber 'n' a cow,'' he drawled from atop his horse,
``is a cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a real cowboy and being real polite, he didn't carry the
conversation a step further. But as he hawked a wet wad of snoose
to the ground and studied our group of city slickers from beneath
the shadows of his broad-brimmed hat, I couldn't help wondering if
there was more to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only thing dumber 'n' a cowboy,'' I could picture him saying,
as he sidled up to the town tavern to order a double whiskey, ``is
a bunch of latte-sucking urbanites who pay $1,200 apiece to chase
around a bunch of cows for a week in the quote-unquote Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   It's dumb, maybe, but fun.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of git-down, yeee-haw, sweaty, dirty fun a rambunctious
cowgal just can't find in the big city of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For six days, our all-girl group of Ibuprofen-poppin'
wranglerettes put the giddy in giddy-up as we swore at cattle,
nursed saddle sores and laughed at ourselves during the fall
roundup at the Bitterroot Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch, a 640-acre spread renowned for the quality and care
of its 170-odd horses, is 18 miles up a dirt road from the frontier
town of Dubois (Doo-boys) in a sparsely populated country where
bumper stickers affixed to beater trucks read: ``Have you hugged
your hoss today?'' and ``To hell with the whale. Save the cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   We were among 19 guests: 17 women, two men. A ``dudeless
ranch,'' one woman called it. As dudeless ranches go, it was of the
horsiest variety.
</P>
<P>
   Guests averaged four to six hours daily in the saddle. Most were
experienced riders; some owned horses. Nevertheless, after the
first day, knees ached, bums were numbed and walking bow-legged
felt unnaturally natural.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention hat hair? It was squished unmercifully under the
safety helmets that are de rigueur at this ranch, thanks to
cautionary tales of bucked-off riders doing head-first landings.
One of our riders, thrown when his horse hit a badger hole at full
gallop, came back with a cracked helmet and fully functional brain.
</P>
<P>
   It turned up the spotlight on this hot fashion trend.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in a picturesque valley in the Absaroka Mountain range
near Yellowstone National Park, the 7,500-foot-high Bitterroot
Ranch is surrounded by Indian reservation and public lands,
including acreage held by the U.S. Bureau of Land Management and
the Shoshone National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves a wide playing field for guests, who may head down
any of more than 100 trails. Some trails pass through beaver
marshes frequented by elk and bear, into hills where antelope leap
across the horizon like cottontails on steroids. Other trails lead
to 60 million-year-old fossil beds or climb from aspen-lined
riverbeds to hilly vistas looking out on the jagged white teeth of
the freshly frosted Absarokas.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery is starkly stunning, outlined in light and shadow
like an Ansel Adams study. It is so dry, the wind makes the grass
whisper and dirt crumbles to dust between the fingers. And it's
still wild enough that hikers venturing a quarter-mile from their
cabins may find animal bones with fresh meat still attached,
testament to after-hours feasting by coyotes or mountain lions.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a land that tolerates pretension, and the Bitterroot
Ranch doesn't attempt it. This is a dude ranch only in the
strictest sense. There are no gift shops, no golf courses, no
hayrides, no tennis courts, no paid storytellers and no organized
games.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the Bitterroot arise to a down-home cacophony of
neighing horses, honking geese, bleating cows and timing-impaired
roosters, who cock-a-doodle-doo at all hours of the day. Guinea
fowl, peacocks, ducks and chickens run free across the yards, and a
ranch dog may slump across your cabin porch, begging a pet.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 rustic cabins, which can accommodate up to 32 guests, are
simple and comfy, clumped close to the East Fork of the Wind River
that snakes through the property. Buffet meals are fresh and
abundant, and wine flows freely at dinner. Evening entertainment
may be a hootenanny 'round the piano, a game of pool or Scrabble, a
video from the film library, a hot-tub soak under the Milky Way, or
a long after-dinner chat with ranch owners Mel and Bayard Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The chat's bound to intrigue. Mel, a lean, handsome, no-nonsense
woman who is a former Olympic-class runner, grew up on a farm in
Tanzania and spent many years working with wildlife in East Africa.
She takes great pride in the Arabian horses she breeds and trains
at the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Bayard, a mustachioed, 6-foot-4 raconteur approaching his 70th
birthday, graduated from Yale University and worked overseas for
the CIA before buying the Bitterroot in 1971. His eyes wrinkle up
like a drawstring purse as he tells exotic tales of being chased by
lions or working undercover as a diamond hunter.
</P>
<P>
   The Foxes have turned their passion for horses and traveling
into an international business called Equitour. It offers rides in
such off-beat locales as Turkey, Zimbabwe, Iceland, Wales and
France.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyoming ranch is one of six domestic operations. At the
Bitterroot, a typical ride climbs 3,000 feet and covers 15 miles.
Rides are split into small groups, according to riding ability.
During the cattle roundup, the more experienced riders head for
high country to roust out cattle _ leaping logs, ducking branches
and scrambling up shale cliffs _ while the least experienced
content themselves with low-country riding.
</P>
<P>
   I belonged to the low-country club. Our job was to help push the
cows back to the ranch, where they were loaded onto rigs and
shipped to lower pastures to winter.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know what to do with a cow, but my horse, a once-wild
mustang, did. All I had to do was aim this alpha male _ a half-ton
of pure guy _ and he headed after the strays, nipping them in their
thick black rumps and setting the whole herd in mooing motion.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing quite compares with sitting atop a fine, feisty horse,
micromanaging a bunch of clueless cows and breathing deep the
green, manure-stained air that attends a cattle drive. It's a raw
and raucous scene.
</P>
<P>
   Cows bawl plaintively, their eyes big black puddles of woe.
Occasionally, two belligerent bulls stop for a duel. And
inevitably, moving boy cows attempt to mount moving girl cows, with
city slickers yelling ``git'' and ``haw'' and ``Get off her, you
moron.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, I counted 12 Bitterroot guests bossing around
eight bewildered cows. The cows didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that thought was playing beneath the broad-brimmed hat of
the snoose-chewing cowboy. Or maybe he was thinking something
altogether different as he cantered over to the scrub-brush site
where our group of cowgals dismounted after a hard day's herding.
</P>
<P>
   But being a real cowboy and being real polite, he adjusted the
hat, looked off at the craggy horizon and made a quiet
pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ya girls done good,'' he said, letting the words set a spell
in the high dry mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   We drank each word in, one by one.
</P>
<P>
   The Bitterroot Ranch offers horse lovers a choice of adventures,
from cattle roundups to pack trips. The 1999 riding season is May
23-Sept. 30, and trips begin at $1,200. For information, call
Equitour at 800-545-0019.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
