<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US OFFERS $70 MILLION TO BOOST SCHOOL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, grasping for ways to
prevent another school massacre, Friday rushed $70 million to local
communities for school-security programs and launched a new round
of gun-control initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The $70 million is expected to pay for 600 additional police
officers for school security in 336 cities and towns across the
country. In New England, 46 communities will share $6.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The funds were released three days after 12 students and a
teacher were slain at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., by
two gun-wielding students who also killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking actions to prevent future acts of violence in our
schools, we can best honor the memories of those who lost their
lives,'' President Clinton said in a statement before he opened
NATO's 50th anniversary summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Justice Department will make available $1.5
million to families of the shooting victims to pay for funerals,
medical bills, lost wages, counseling and other expenses. He said
the aid, provided through the Crime Victims Trust Fund, will ``help
the communities assist the victims in their long journey toward
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, will represent the
administration Sunday at a memorial service in Littleton for the
shooting victims. Clinton will be attending the NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up the push for stricter gun laws aimed at curbing
school shootings, the White House plans to pursue legislation that
would hold parents criminally liable if their children gain access
to household guns. The administration also will propose a lifetime
ban on gun ownership by juveniles who are convicted of violent
crimes. And Clinton will press for a law that requires
manufacturers to put child safety locks on guns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the White House wants to make it illegal for
individuals under the age of 21 to buy assault-style weapons that
were manufactured before 1994, when a ban on making such weapons
took effect. Current law permits anyone over 18 to buy
assault-style weapons.
</P>
<P>
   However, each of the gun-control initiatives is expected to face
stiff opposition in the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $70 million for tighter school security, Clinton said
the additional officers ``will work closely with the citizens they
serve _ with students, teachers and parents _ to improve campus
security, counsel troubled youth and medicate conflicts before they
escalate into violence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin optional trim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts will receive $2.2 million in the current funding,
enough for 18 cities and towns to hire at least one full-time
police officer to work in the schools. Communities in the Boston
area that will receive funds include Bridgewater, Foxborough,
Framingham, Haverhill, Methuen, Newburyport, Revere, Swampscott,
and Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Many other communities will receive aid this year as the
administration tries to meet its goal of funding 1,400 school
officers in addition to the 600 who will be hired with the money
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end optional trim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reminded school districts they have until the end
of April to apply for $17 million in Justice Department funds to
develop programs aimed at strengthening their partnerships with
local law enforcement agencies. The programs focus on school crime,
drug use, and student discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   Local communities also have until June 1 to apply for $180
million in federal grants from the Safe Schools-Healthy Students
program, which is aimed at reducing violence and drug abuse in the
schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
