<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      04-23 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO: A REALITY CHECK AT 50 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This week's NATO commemorative was planned as a
celebration of a half-century of peace and triumph over tyranny and
ethnic strife. The proceedings instead will be a mixture of
solemnity and ceremony for an organization at war _ and at a loss
to halt a new threat of ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of its history, the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, founded in a downtown Washington building constructed
largely of crushed oysters, has been part military alliance, part
symbol. And though the session began Friday morning with a
three-hour meeting on the organization's military operations in the
Balkans, the real utility of the anniversary summit may be as a
symbol of how swiftly, and how dramatically, world challenges _ and
NATO's focus _ have changed in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   This is an organization whose original worry was the security of
central Europe. Now it is engaged in a war on the periphery of
Europe. This is an organization whose strategic orientation was a
major war involving rival big powers. Now it is engaged in a civil
war involving tiny ethnic enclaves and small political
principalities. This is an organization whose focus was
ideological. Now it is fighting a war that is tribal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, NATO was formed to create European solidarity. Its
greatest challenge comes now in a fight over European divisions.
</P>
<P>
   This week's meeting of more than 40 leaders is a gathering of an
organization that won the Cold War _ but is in danger of losing the
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Since the original dozen nations created NATO in April 1949, the
West has prevailed in a tense confrontation with Soviet communism,
moving to the brink of war several times in tense face-offs with a
rival superpower in Europe, holding its breath over insurrections
in Hungary and Czechoslovakia, watching nervously as proxy wars
between the two blocs were fought far from Europe in Korea,
Vietnam, the cqCongo, and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, however, the great beginning being celebrated here
this weekend is far different from the reality being contemplated
here this week.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance began amid the Berlin airlift, when thousands of
Allied sorties supplied food, fuel, and mail to a city cut off by
Soviet troops, and its commemoration is being held the same week
Germans celebrated reunification by opening the Reichstag again. At
the start, NATO was an institution designed to protect and project
the United States' interests in Europe. Now it increasingly appears
to be an institution to assure that European interests are
addressed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech earlier this month, Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright said that NATO's ``core purpose'' was to act ``as a
defender of democracy, stability, and basic human decency on
European soil.''
</P>
<P>
   But American strategic interests in Europe today, on the eve of
the 21st century, are much like Britain's in the 19th century: to
assure that no single power dominates Europe. Beyond that,
administration critics argue, the United States has fashioned no
clear vision of its role in the world and no clear task for NATO to
perform. ``NATO's supporters say NATO must survive and must find
something to do,'' says Ted Galen Carpenter, a Cato Institute
diplomatic theorist. ``This is a dangerous confusion of means and
ends.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start, the American obsession was to blunt the westward
movement of Soviet-style communism and the strength of the Warsaw
Pact. It was packaged nicely, as a bulwark of democracy and free
markets, and though its godfather was British foreign secretary
Ernest Bevin, in reality its orientation was military and its
character was American. On the surface it was, as Boston University
historian David Fromkin wrote, ``the sort of alliance Theodore
Roosevelt had espoused: like-minded nations pursuing a common
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's mission was summarized briskly and accurately by
Britain's Lord Ismay, the first NATO secretary general, as ``to
keep the Americans in, the Russians out, and the Germans down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Americans are confused, the Russians are gone, and the
Germans are back, which helps explain the situation NATO is in at
its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo crisis has minor significance geopolitically but
major significance morally. It threatens the stability of the
Balkans but not of Western Europe. It represents the triumph of
European interests over American interests in NATO's calculus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of Europe, this is very significant,'' says Elizabeth
Pond, author of ``The Rebirth of Europe,'' just published by the
Brookings Institution Press. ``Kosovo ceased to be a tactical
question and became a moral question. For the Germans, especially,
it meant `no more Holocaust.' There is a feeling of outrage, that
this sort of thing can start again. It's important for the
self-respect of Europeans that this not be allowed to happen again.
And because it is important to Europe, it is therefore important to
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo crisis also represents a dramatic shift in the sort
of problem NATO was designed to address. The Cold War kept a lid on
the ethnic tensions that had boiled in the Balkans for generations.
Soviet intimidation kept the established states of the region in
line even as Tito kept the ethnic groups apart in a nation whose
citizens wrote in both the Latin and Cyrillic alphabets, practiced
Roman Catholicism, Greek Orthodoxy, and Islam, and spoke Serb,
Croat, Slovenian, and Macedonian.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Soviet presence is gone, the strategic calculation
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For nearly 50 years, NATO was oriented and organized to defend
and respond to an attack from the east,'' Senator Richard G. Lugar,
Republican of Indiana, said on the Senate floor this week. ``An
invasion by Soviet and Warsaw Pact forces was the primary threat
facing the alliance. Since the collapse of the Soviet Union, new
threats have replaced the nightmare of Soviet armed divisions
crashing through the Fulda Gap. The proliferation of weapons of
mass destruction, rogue states, terrorism, ethnic strife, and other
potentially destabilizing elements now threaten the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO leaders celebrate the alliance's golden anniversary,
they still have not answered the questions of where NATO interests
begin and end, whether and how NATO should work with the United
Nations, and how big NATO should become. The alliance has welcomed
the Czech Republic, Hungary, and Poland as newcomers, but pointedly
did not invite Slovenia, a stable and democratic part of the former
Yugoslavia that would have given it an anchor in southeastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the inevitable toasts and statements of resolve, the world
leaders meeting here face a sobering thought: The tensions that
opened the century in the Balkans still have not been resolved at
century's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you have a more stable situation in the Balkans,'' says
Stanley Slovan, a former Library of Congress researcher who
specializes in European-alliance issues, ``you do not have a stable
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is chief of the Globe Washington Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
