<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISTS OUTRAGED AT BOMBING OF TV STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ NATO's bombing of Serbia's state TV station was widely
denounced by international journalists, who say the attack puts
them in the line of fire in the increasingly bitter war between
NATO and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   While few journalists disputed NATO's claim that Radio
Television Serbia, or RTS, is controlled by Milosevic and
broadcasts propaganda for the regime, many argued that NATO had
endangered the lives of impartial journalists with an attack that
was as ineffective as it was ruthless.
</P>
<P>
   Serb authorities say about 150 people were in the building in
downtown Belgrade when it was struck by missiles. They said at
least 10 were killed. Friday night they were still digging for
about 20 others believed buried in the rubble. Six hours after the
attack, RTS was back on the air from another location.
</P>
<P>
   The International Federation of Journalists accused NATO of
breaking a promise it had given the organization earlier this week
that journalists would not be targeted in its attacks against the
Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing ``could lead to reprisals against independent
journalists and media staff who have been campaigning against media
distortion and control of information by the Milosevic regime,''
said Aidan White, general secretary of the federation, which like
NATO is based in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   White said the attack could have wider repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments who attack the media, whether in the Balkans, in
central Africa or central Asia, will now feel justified in making
journalists and all who work with them legitimate targets,'' said
White.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris-based Reporters Without Borders said the bombing
``creates a very dangerous precedent.'' The European Broadcasting
Union, which represents TV and radio stations in 49 countries,
called the bombing pointless.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Russian Journalists, openly sympathetic to the
fellow Orthodox Slavs in Serbia, called the attack an attempt to
crush the freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who have a long tradition of denouncing the
Milosevic regime's systematic silencing of an independent press in
Serbia were critical of the NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   Ann K. Cooper, executive director of the New York-based
Committee to Protect Journalists, said her organization was
``deeply disturbed'' by the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's decision to target civilian broadcast facilities not
only increases the danger for reporters now working in Yugoslavia
but permanently jeopardizes all journalists as noncombatants in
international conflicts as provided for in the Geneva Convention,''
Cooper said in a letter to NATO secretary general Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that while her group appreciates NATO's concern
``about the role of RTS in Milosevic's propaganda campaign, we
believe hate speech and propaganda is best countered with increased
objective reporting, not with violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrystyna Lapychak, the Eastern Europe program coordinator for
the Committee to Protect Journalists, said NATO's position on RTS
was hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough Yugoslavia was deciding what people can and
cannot watch on television, but now NATO's done the same thing by
bombing the station,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where NATO's 50th anniversary summit is being
held this weekend, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea defended the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb TV station, he said, ``has nothing to do with
journalism.'' It was ``directly responsible for inciting
conditions'' that led to ethnic cleansing in Croatia, Bosnia and
today in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its function is to incite hatred and distort reality. It is
the same thing as a military propaganda machine,'' said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Ursula Owen, editor in chief of the London-based Index on
Censorship, said she thought NATO's strike against RTS was
premature, saying such an attack should be a last resort and only
if there is no alternative for news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably surprise some people familiar with the
Index on Censorship, but I think there are instances when I would
do this. There is a case for stopping (the media) creating a
culture of hate, as happened in Rwanda,'' she said. ``But the fact
is people in Yugoslavia can get Voice of America and CNN. Besides,
to aim for a building which doesn't have any transmitters isn't
incredibly effective. They were back on the air pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   While NATO was unrepentent, and suggested further attacks could
follow, White said its tactics were futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killing journalists and media staff never wins wars or builds
democracy,'' said White. ``It only reinforces ignorance, censorship
and fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
