<HEADLINE>
LOCALS IN D.C. YIELD GROUND TO NATO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As legions of NATO officials invaded the nation's
capital Friday, the locals promptly retreated.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown area around the NATO summit was eerily quiet as
workers stayed home, scared off by the prospect of closed streets
and streams of motorcades.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic gridlock predicted for days by the local media
failed to materialize as motorists heeded the warnings to take the
subway or avoid the summit area altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also gave 90,000 workers around the
affected area the day off and many other employees opted for a long
weekend, contributing to a deserted feeling in the swath of
buildings between the White House and the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly the only people wandering around were tourists, many of
them trying to figure out how to circumvent the Federal Triangle
area where the event was held and which was off limits to all but
summit participants and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a ghost town here,'' said Mark Hammond, visiting
from Boston. Hammond, who flew in Thursday night with friends, had
no idea that the NATO event was going on until he arrived at the
airport and noticed signs warning of closed streets.
</P>
<P>
   His friend John Andersen approved of the tight security that
often forced pedestrians to walk blocks out of their way to cross
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering they are bombing, it's probably a good idea,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and other security forces appeared to be everywhere,
peering down from the rooftops of massive federal buildings,
guarding the street blockades and patrolling the underground Metro
stations.
</P>
<P>
   A number of major thoroughfares, including a stretch of
Pennsylvania Avenue, were closed, as was the Metro station under
Federal Triangle. However, most of the major tourist attractions,
except the Capitol, remained open.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Marie and Bob Montgomery of Albany, N.Y. , who were visiting
with their son Christopher, also said they had no idea about the
NATO meeting before they arrived Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they found the event exciting, particularly the
parade of limousines that chauffeured the leaders from the 19 NATO
nations to and from their hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're guessing who's in the cars,'' said Ann Marie Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   She said they were disappointed they could not visit FBI
headquarters because it was closed. Instead, they went to Ford's
Theatre, where Abraham Lincoln was shot.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sprayberry High School Orchestra from Marietta, Ga., the
NATO meeting was a blessing and a curse. As a result of the lack of
traffic, the musicians had no trouble getting to the outdoor square
near Pennsylvania Avenue where they were scheduled to give a
lunchtime performance.
</P>
<P>
   But they also found themselves playing for only a handful of
passers-by in the normally bustling locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy to get here, but unfortunately there is nobody
here to enjoy it,'' said Tom Bennett, the parent of two orchestra
members.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A big bonus for those who defied the warnings and traveled
downtown was the ready availability of prime restaurant seats.
</P>
<P>
   The lines that normally wrap around the trendy Planet Hollywood
at lunchtime didn't materialize. Assistant General Manager Sean
Honan blamed the media for exaggerating the inconvenience that the
summit would cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press kind of made it sound like a nightmare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Simon Landless, an office worker who declined to take the day
off Friday, said the whole affair had been ``overblown.''
</P>
<P>
   He said for many of his co-workers, the NATO meeting was ``just
an excuse to take the day off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people working in our office are the foreigners who
have seen this all before,'' said Landless who is from the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   One couple visiting from England, Bill and Una Thompson, said
they did not understand why the NATO summit was being held in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the NATO nations are in Europe, and yet they have to
come all the way over here,'' said Bill Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, the couple was not terribly
inconvenienced by the three-day event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a good wander about despite this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
