<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-800(2     04-23 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NEITHER NATO NOR YUGOSLAVIA ARE CLOSE TO WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With NATO's leaders gathered behind closed doors on
Friday to consider their next moves against Yugoslavia, the
alliance's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, offered a strikingly
optimistic view of the progress so far. ``We are winning,'' he
declared. ``He is losing. And he knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO is, in fact, far from winning.
</P>
<P>
   A month into the air campaign in the Balkans, Yugoslavia has
withstood nearly 3,000 combat raids and has shown no signs yet of
breaking. President Slobodan Milosevic has succeeded in expelling
hundreds of thousands of Albanians from Kosovo, routing the rebel
force fighting for Kosovo's independence and steeling the will of
the Serbs in support of his repressive regime.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, NATO's campaign has stumbled over a series of
foreseeable and unforeseeable problems _ from political limitations
on its initial strikes to the uncooperative weather to the
surprisingly effective tactics used by the Yugoslav air defenses to
keep allied pilots guessing.
</P>
<P>
   The latter has forced NATO to alter its raids and put off the
kind of low-flying patrols that could make a real difference
against the tanks and artillery battering Kosovo's villages. The 24
Apache attack helicopters that arrived in Albania this week with
much fanfare are now not expected to begin flying combat strikes
into Kosovo for many more days or weeks, officials said, in large
part because NATO's raids have still not hit the air defenses hard
enough to make it safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's been done right here,'' said Michael
Dugan, a retired general who served as Air Force Chief of Staff.
``The air war has been carried out without much political will or
military decisiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   It is very difficult, of course, to assess winners and losers
after only one month of conflict. Thirty days after Iraqi forces
seized Kuwait in August 1990, for instance, it was unclear how
Washington and its allies would evict President Saddam Hussein's
troops.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been much talk _ particularly from the British
and French in recent days _ of sending NATO ground forces into
Kosovo, none of the allies is eager to rush into a land war and
some are downright wary. There is a general understanding, however,
that if the alliance decides to send in ground troops this summer,
it needs to start preparing now.
</P>
<P>
   To commanders at NATO and the Pentagon, Milosevic's achievements
thus far are fleeting, tactical gains that have brought him little
strategic advantage. The expulsion of Albanians, which has
distracted NATO with a parallel relief operation, has only served
to harden the resolve of NATO's 19 members, who are now willing to
approve attacks on more sensitive targets, like Milosevic's homes
and Yugoslavia's state-run television.
</P>
<P>
   Officials vow to continue to grind away at Yugoslavia's military
and political leadership, insisting that time and firepower are on
NATO's side, though time may be what is needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic will run out of bullets and gas long before we do,''
a Pentagon official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the United States and it allies laid out
political objectives that military commanders warned would be
difficult to achieve by bombing alone.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the air campaign had three objectives: to
underscore NATO's unity in opposing aggression; to deter Milosevic
from expelling ethnic Albanians; and, if necessary, hurt Belgrade's
ability to wage war by ``seriously diminishing its military
capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The only objective met so far is a firm display of unity.
Yugoslavia's ability to endure the strikes has left NATO no option
but to step up the size and scope of its campaign far more than
envisioned when the attacks began 31 days ago. Clark has asked the
Pentagon to provide 300 more U.S. warplanes and dozens more from
other allies, raising the total to more than 1,000, more than
doubling the number NATO had on hand when the war started.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's campaign has become a case study in gradual escalation,
reflecting Vietnam more than the Persian Gulf War in 1991, when
allied pilots flew as many as 3,000 missions a day, compared with
300 to 600 against Yugoslavia, and targeted the heart of the
political and economic machine in Baghdad from day one.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO launched its strikes, commanders warned that it could
take weeks to break Milosevic's will, although privately, some top
Clinton administration officials were convinced that Milosevic
would fold after a few days of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he became more defiant, and his forces in Kosovo
splintered into smaller groups that were harder to hit. Now many of
those forces are hunkered down in defensive positions out of NATO's
gun sights _ in forests or next to residential buildings and
churches that NATO will not bomb.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unable to eradicate Yugoslav forces in the field, NATO has taken
its attack much closer to Milosevic himself. In addition to his
house and national television, NATO also struck two electricity
transformers, cutting off no only the power to command bunkers in
Belgrade but the residential and commercial areas around them as
well. This signaled a shift to hitting strategic targets aimed at
undercutting Milosevic's popular base _ a strategy that still
relies on an uprising that has no sign of forming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have your rock concerts, but pretty soon it's going to
be Belgrade unplugged,'' the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart,
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question the attacks have hurt Yugoslavia,
destroying its indigenous oil production and shattering its
transportation network as NATO cruise missiles and aircraft pick
off highway and railroad bridges from one end of the country to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pentagon's latest damage assessment, the director of
intelligence for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Rear Adm. Thomas
Wilson, described Yugoslavia's military and police forces has badly
strained, running low on fuel and ammunition and harassed by a
down-but-not-out Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslavia's forces have been resilient. A defense
intelligence official said the forces in the field learned from
President Saddam Hussein's mistakes in the Persian Gulf War, and
rather than confronting NATO's air power head on they have
effectively tried to slip out of its reach. ``They went to
school,'' the official said. ``They've learned how to offset our
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's leadership has been resilient, too. Milosevic's
special police have been shifting their headquarters to the
basements of various hotels in Belgrade, still functioning despite
the destruction of its headquarters three weeks ago, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was only a matter of hours after American F-117 fighters
leveled the headquarters of Serbian television in Belgrade that
state-controlled programming was again being broadcast, leaving
NATO little option but to go after the backup complexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said on
Friday, openly vowing to hit keep Milosevic's propaganda off the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The question in the end is which side can outlast the other.
NATO's leaders vowed to stay the course, with some Pentagon
commanders warning the attacks could go for months, even though
they have no clear idea when or if Milosevic will relent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to gauge the level of pain that somebody is
willing to endure,'' Wilson said. ``And I don't know what President
Milosevic's level of pain is. But other parts of the society have a
level of pain which may differ. And it's getting higher all the
time. That's all I can say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
