<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMOR VIOLENCE ESCALATES AS DIPLOMATS SEEK ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Violence overshadowed diplomacy in troubled East
Timor Friday, with fighting continuing between warring factions
despite a cease-fire and a UN-mediated attempt to bring a form of
self-rule to the Indonesian-occupied land.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian government officials say they are promoting a
compromise to satisfy both sides in the bloody conflict that has
raged since Indonesia invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975
and annexed it a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's rule in East Timor is not recognized by the United
Nations or most countries. Indonesian troops are blamed for 200,000
deaths during a 1976 crackdown and famine that followed, and for
human rights abuses ever since. Guerrillas have waged a 23-year
struggle for independence.
</P>
<P>
   This week's bloodshed between pro-independence and pro-Indonesia
forces does not bode well for a peaceful vote on an autonomy
package agreed to by Indonesian and Portuguese foreign ministers at
UN headquarters in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, a leaked Australian military intelligence document
accused the Indonesian army of arming, protecting and fighting
alongside pro-Jakarta militias, lending credence to those who say
the military is fanning the violence. The Indonesian army denies
any connection to the militias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The occupying armed forces are escalating the violence...to
derail the negotiations in New York and prevent a UN presence in
East Timor,'' complained Roque Rodrigues, a representative of CNRT,
the East Timor Resistance National Council. ``Without a UN
presence, they can continue to carry out mass-scale killings of
East Timor people, and they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Any solution will require a democratic and peaceful vote that
asks what people want, he said. ``A UN presence is needed to
supervise, organize and monitor'' the vote. ``In an atmosphere of
violence, it's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN-brokered talks led Friday to a proposal that government
sources in Jakarta say would offer East Timor's 830,000 residents
self-rule on all matters except defense, foreign affairs and fiscal
and monetary policy. The two nations expect to sign the agreement
May 5, paving the way for a vote this summer. But the deal may fail
to settle anything.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone interviews from East Timor, representatives of both
sides said they would reject autonomy at the ballot box _ either
because they want full independence or because they want rule from
Jakarta. The ballot is expected to be a yes-or-no vote on autonomy,
without any specified alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President B.J. Habibie reversed Jakarta's
long-standing hard line on East Timor in January, when he proposed
limited self-rule for East Timor, and said he would consider
independence if autonomy was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   That offer has led many to mistakenly conclude that the July
ballot is a choice between autonomy and independence. But in truth,
if autonomy is rejected by both independence supporters and those
who want to remain part of Indonesia, neither side could prove
victory for their position. Just as critical, if autonomy fails,
alternatives for East Timor's future would have to be approved by
the new parliament and the next president _ and there is no
guarantee they would approve independence.
</P>
<P>
   F.X. Lopes da Cruz, an East Timor native and adviser to Habibie,
called autonomy a ``a win-win situation'' to appease both sides and
restore peace.
</P>
<P>
   But others do not agree. After Habibie's offer seemed to tilt
the scales in favor of self-rule, Jakarta loyalists stepped up an
armed campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A human rights group in Dili, East Timor's capital, claimed
Friday that Indonesian troops and paramilitaries killed at least 40
people between January 1 and April 8, in a campaign to terrorize
independence supporters. Yayasan Hak said almost 80 people were
tortured and more than 18,000 fled their homes to escape attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen more are believed to have been killed in the last
two weeks, including 30 massacred when pro-Indonesia militas went
on a rampage last Saturday after their leaders advocated violence
at a rally attended by the Jakarta-appointed governor and local
military and police chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a jungle now,'' said Pedro Carrascalao, whose
father, former East Timor governor Mario Carrascalao, fled
Indonesia on Thursday after pro-Jakarta militias placed him on a
hit list. Mario Carrasalao's brother's home in Dili, where refugees
were sheltering, was a target in last Saturday's rampage, and his
17-year-old nephew was among 30 massacred.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador Soares, former member of parliament for East Timor from
the pro-Jakarta ruling party, said the continuing violence proves a
summer vote is premature. ``People are not ready to manage
themselves if they win autonomy....and they are not ready to accept
if their side loses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Correspondent Colum Lynch contributed to this report from the
United Nations.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
