<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRIAL OF REGGIE LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Through 70 depositions and countless hours of sworn testimony,
Donna Harris-Lewis has maintained a steely vigil in search, she
says, of the truth about the death of her husband, Celtics star
Reggie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Many widows would consider this process nothing short of
hideous. Yet Harris-Lewis described it Friday as cathartic, a
necessary step in her quest to prove that inadequate medical care
led to her husband's death from heart failure in 1993, at the
tender age of 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read transcripts, but I wanted to be there to hear and
to see,'' said Harris-Lewis. ``It's been helpful to me to
understand the difference between fact and fiction. From their lips
to my ears _ that was important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis is suing Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. and three other
doctors for medical malpractice in a trial that begins Monday in
Suffolk (Mass.) Superior Court. Her motivation, she says, is
simple: She wants the truth about her husband's death. She wants to
prove that her husband should still be alive, that the
highly-touted doctors who were expected to save his life instead
allowed him to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to Reggie's family and friends, fans and
community, to continue to see the person they had watched before
their eyes,'' she said. ``We're talking about people continuing to
understand the person he really was, not what's been portrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors will allege that past cocaine use by Lewis _ and his
refusal to disclose it until shortly before he died _ made
diagnosis and treatment impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis died on July 27, 1993, while shooting a basketball at
Brandeis University, just three months after he collapsed during a
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Things between Harris-Lewis and Mudge began to get ugly in 1995,
when the Wall Street Journal reported that Mudge and other members
of Lewis's medical team strongly suspected that Lewis had used
cocaine, contributing to the heart condition that killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge is expected to testify that Lewis had told him 15 days
before he died that he had used cocaine previously, as the two
talked in a Range Rover in a Brandeis University parking lot. There
were no witnesses to the conversation. Asked whether she believes
the conversation took place, Harris-Lewis _ who is under a court
order barring her from discussing the details of the case _ shakes
her head no, and says she cannot elaborate before the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's lawsuit has drawn critics. They point to the $10
million or more Harris-Lewis has received since Lewis's death, and
wonder what more money could possibly heal. They say Lewis's
once-exemplary reputation has already suffered and fear that a
trial will only give Mudge's allegation more air time. And some
worry, privately and publicly, that the allegation might be true,
that Lewis really did use drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis has heard it all. She said she mounted her own
investigation after Mudge's claim surfaced, asking friends and
acquaintances if they knew anything about her husband that she
didn't. The answer she came away with was no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people very close to him who I've asked, `Don't tell
me what you think I want to hear. Tell me what you know.' Because I
need to know, not just for myself but for my children. I wasn't
around him all the time. But the people who were around him, I've
asked questions. I'm more inclined to believe people who really
knew him than people who didn't really know him.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis scoffs at charges that she is motivated by greed.
No amount of money, she says, could compensate her for the loss of
her husband and the father of her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a defeated purpose from the beginning
because there's not a dollar amount that could justify what Reggie
meant to me, to our children and our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Lewis's son, Reggie Jr., is nearly 7. The daughter his
wife was carrying when he died, Reggiena, is 5. They barely know
their father was a basketball player _ though after a Bulls-Celtics
game at the FleetCenter last year, Michael Jordan told a scarcely
believing Reggie Jr. that he'd played against his dad, and that he
was a great competitor.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no such warm, sentimental moments in the trial. An
eminent cardiologist and a prideful widow are locked in a
winner-take-all battle over reputation. But in the court of public
opinion, Lewis's legacy has already suffered. Donna Harris-Lewis
may be seeking a vindication no court can bestow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe columnist Adrian Walker can be reached by e-mail at
walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
