<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-CHURCH-2TAKES-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN BY FAITH, PRIEST OFFERS REFUGE FROM GLOBAL MISERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 25)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ On this Sunday morning, the few die-hard faithful
of the tiny Christ and St. Barnabas Episcopal Church are joined by
about 18 visitors whose presence, in the Gothic oaken arches and
mellow light of the tiny church, provide the Rev. James Kenyon with
a golden moment during his sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Most are Burmese refugees. A few are Amerasian or Vietnamese.
Noticeably, a couple of men bear the scars of the long-standing
guerrilla warfare against Burma's military regime: Nyunt Win lost
part of an arm, and suffered permanent damage to his right hand,
eye and ankle during a grenade attack in 1991, he said; another
Burmese man is missing an arm and is blind.
</P>
<P>
   An Amerasian congregant, disabled since childhood by polio, had
almost been overlooked in the effort to bring the children of
American servicemen here. During a trip to Vietnam in 1994 Kenyon,
seeing him in the distance as a ``dark lump in the road,'' brought
him.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon's sermon is based on the gospel of John, in which the
Pharisees pointedly question a simple blind man whose sight was
restored by Jesus. The blind man's explanation for this miracle
``that though I was blind, now I see'' is a lesson in faith, Kenyon
preached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith is nothing less than trust that God has better plans in
mind for you and I,'' Kenyon said, ``than we do ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It is on faith that the latest refugees under the Episcopal
priest's wing are now living in the United States, beginning their
tentative steps by learning English, working the night shift as
stitchers at a mattress manufacturer and attending college.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon and his wife, Pat, approach the resettlement of refugees
with missionary zeal, but not to win converts to the church.
``We're in business to bring them to freedom,'' Kenyon said simply.
</P>
<P>
   As refugee coordinator for the Episcopal Diocese of Albany,
Kenyon since 1989 has brought more than 200 refugees to the region,
taking on the task with both compassion and realism. For nearly a
decade, the Kenyons called a turn-of-the-century mansion in
Rensselaer ``Welcome House,'' where the latest arrivals lived with
them until they could stand on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up the hotel-style life of Welcome House, the couple last
year moved to a rented condominium in the suburbs of Rensselaer,
its neutral contemporary space furnished with genteel camelback and
Empire-style sofas that seem more in keeping with an old-time
vicarage. Here, in the quiet of suburbia, it is difficult to
envision the Kenyons at the Burma-Thailand border, interviewing
potential refugees near a safe area designated for Burmese
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   But the lives of Jim and Pat Kenyon, 73 and 71, represent a
barometer of world events, usually catastrophes that have
threatened the people whose persecution allowed them here as
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes facing American ambivalence about new immigrants,
undertaking a constant cycle of doctors' appointments,
apartment-hunting and social-service appointments, Kenyon has been
at this since 1956, when Hungary collapsed under the communist
crackdown. Then came Cuba and Fidel Castro, and, later, Cambodia,
Vietnam, the Ukraine, Burma and Bosnia. Before moving to Albany in
1989, Kenyon resettled refugees in Brooklyn, and before that, in
Wisconsin and Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Through an agreement with the U.S. State Department, the
Episcopal church agrees to resettle the refugees and have them
gainfully employed as soon as possible, although refugees are
entitled to food stamps, Medicaid and, in some cases, public
assistance. As defined by the Refugee Act of 1980, a refugee is
anyone with a well-founded fear of persecution or physical harm, a
status ultimately granted by the U.S. Immigration &AMP; Naturalization
Service, Kenyon said.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer agencies resettle refugees whose cases are dispersed
by the New York-based Refugee Data Center, Kenyon said. Episcopal
Migration Ministries, which oversees that church's resettlement
programs, realizes Kenyon's special interest in Burma, so it makes
those cases available. But Kenyon also is waiting for the arrival
of a Bosnian and Vietnamese as well.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon's ministry is supported in part by the Episcopal diocese,
by donations, as well as by churches of any denomination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kenyons' drive to minister makes their resolve to help these
newcomers pretty uncomplicated. Kenyon puzzles a moment when he
thinks about why he does what he does, then reflects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that I have two spiritual gifts: one is missionary
and the other is hospitality. Those have allowed me and my wife to
bridge national lines and racial lines. Most of my work was in
black congregations. Three of our (four) adopted sons are black.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kenyon said resettling refugees has been a way to involve
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenyons' work has crossed often into the personal. Once,
because of a mix-up, a young Vietnamese man was due to arrive for
resettlement at Kenyon's Brooklyn church well before the parish had
actually approved the sponsorship. Once he secured approval, Kenyon
told the parish, ``I sure am glad, because he's arriving next
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Kenyons adopted the young man.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon has a blunt, robust delivery while Pat is softly
understated. To the refugees, they are mom and dad, and that is how
they address them.
</P>
<P>
   Myint Maung Maung, 30, who is Burmese, arrived at Albany
International Airport on March 17 with his young family. The
Kenyons were among his first sights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in my heart, he's not really my father, but when I see
his face, he really is my father,'' Myint Maung Maung said.
</P>
<P>
   On a chilly early April afternoon, Kenyon has come to the
Rensselaer apartment of Myint Maung Maung, his wife, Dint Tin Tin
Khing and their daughter, Pwint Phyu Hnin, almost 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Their customs still cling to the emigres like an exotic cloak.
Myint Maung Maung wears a longy, a tube-shaped sarong, and Dint has
mustard-colored makeup, worn by both Burmese men and women, applied
in circles on each cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you still chewing beetlenut?'' Kenyon asks Maung,
referring to a Burmese habit, similar to chewing tobacco. But Maung
makes a face of disgust, already believing that the habit will be
viewed here as a vice.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon is chipping away at a medical report, in anticipation of
a doctor's visit for Maung.
</P>
<P>
   In rudimentary English, and with the help of his friend Nyunt
Win, also Burmese, who lives in the same Rensselaer neighborhood
around the corner, Maung pieced together a story of resistance that
is all too familiar to Kenyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1988, I demanded democracy. Many students demanded
democracy,'' he said. The massive demonstration was harshly quelled
by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Myint Maung Maung fled Rangoon, the Burmese capital. Debilitated
by wounds and poor vision, he hid in the jungles for years. He and
Nyunt Win, gravely wounded in 1991, actually had fought the
military in one significant battle. Win, here since 1995, has a
strong command of English and is studying computer information
systems at a local community college.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the typical remarks of newcomers Maung huddles, for
instance, to show his reaction to the brace of Northeast cold he
makes another comment, still typical of immigrants, and heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very glad to live in the United States of America,
because the United States has a democracy and I want the
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The priest sometimes has been greeted with apathy, even among
churchgoers, when he explains the need to help refugees. Just one
of five churches responded to his appeal last spring to help his
ministry, run just by him and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It discourages me; I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He is mindful about the latest global misery: the outpouring of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. There is talk of a sketchy plan to
temporarily resettle 20,000 Kosovars, so his future involvement in
helping the Kosovar refugees is hypothetical. But, ``if there were
some Kosovars eligible, I'd just as soon help resettle them as
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon likes to rely on scripture to explain his job. He
recounts the gospel of Matthew, in which Jesus, Mary and Joseph
flee to Egypt to escape Herod's murderous rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever stop to think of what it must have been like for Jesus,
Mary and Joseph when they first arrived in Egypt? Well, this is
what we do. Jesus, Mary and Joseph were the first refugees of the
Christian era.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
