<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS COOL TO NHL, GREAT ONE'S EXIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever there was a time for the American hockey fan to step
forward, plop down and tune in, last Sunday afternoon was it.
</P>
<P>
   The Great One, Wayne Gretzky, was on final display, glowing like
a Roman candle for most of the country to see, right there on
fabulous Fox.
</P>
<P>
   And who among us watched, Bob and Doug McKenzie?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that's right. They're Canadian, eh? Can't blame them for not
watching, or hockey fans in Fort Worth-Dallas, for that matter. Fox
sent us the Stars game instead. As for the 82 percent of the
country that got Gretzky's going away party, well, not many of them
watched, either.
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing is that by hockey's standards, quite a few
people viewed Gretzky's NHL sendoff. The game featuring his New
York Rangers and the Pittsburgh Penguins pulled a 2.2 national TV
rating. Translated, that means that 2.2 percent of U.S. homes with
a television watched.
</P>
<P>
   That was the highest-rated NHL regular-season telecast on Fox
since March 31, 1996, and still it drew fewer viewers than the golf
tournament, the NBA game and the figure skating event that aired
that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which has been broadcasting NHL games since the 1994-95
season, has seen its ratings slide from an average of 2.0 in 1995
and 2.1 in 1996 to 1.9 in 1997, and to 1.4 in 1998 and 1999. Even
at the bargain-basement rights fee price of $155 million, that's
not much of a return on the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has been losing up to $12 million a year on hockey, so it
came as no surprise that the network said good bye and good
riddance when Disney (ABC/ESPN) agreed to pay $600 million for NHL
broadcast rights for the next five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has its reasons for stepping into the quicksand that
sucked Fox downward for half a decade. The company believes that
the cross-promotional benefits between its networks will help boost
ratings, particularly as the NHL improves its fan base in the South
and West. Hockey also provides hundreds of hours of programming
each year for Disney's all-sports cable networks, and you can never
have too much live programming when you broadcast 24/7. Finally,
the NHL is still cheap when compared with the cost of rights fees
to the NFL, NBA and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Still, selling hockey on TV hasn't been an easy job, and there
is no sign it will be easier in the near future. Fox tried
high-technology tools such as a glowing puck, innovative camera
angles that brought viewers closer to the action and a group of
announcers versed enough to appeal to veteran hockey fans but
willing to educate novices.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked. Not even the final adieu from Gretzky, a poet on
skates, the Jordan of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any hope for Americans' interest in televised
hockey, it could come from a market like Fort Worth-Dallas, a place
that has just started to take to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for Stars' regular-season contests on Fox Sports
Southwest this year were up 114 percent from last year. The ratings
numbers weren't huge (a 1.5 average vs. a 0.7) but that's partly
because the cable sports channel only reaches a little more than
one-half of area households.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff hockey ratings are traditionally much better than those
of the regular season and, because first-round opponent Edmonton
has been a traditionally strong ratings draw here, this series'
numbers bear watching. Game 1 on Wednesday, which was broadcast on
KDFI/Channel 27, drew healthy enough viewer numbers, and those
ought to improve in future rounds, assuming the Stars keep on
keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics might argue that the growing interest in the Stars is
merely another sign of this area's passion for any team that wins.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're talking about hockey, a sport that attracts
fewer viewers than a routine golf tournament even when it's
showcasing its greatest player, you have to find positives where
you can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 1932EDT &QL; 
