<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCKFULL-SARALEE-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFEE DIRECTORS BOUGHT COMPANY STOCK BETWEEN TAKEOVER BIDS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three directors of the Chock Full o'Nuts Corp.,
including the chairman of the board, bought company stock in the
months after they rejected an unsolicited takeover offer but before
that offer was disclosed to the public. The suitor remains
interested, however, and this week disclosed that it had approached
the company recently, sending the stock up almost 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Chock Full o'Nuts said the purchases did not
violate securities laws that forbid corporate officials from
trading on the basis of nonpublic information.
</P>
<P>
   But they were made just months after company lawyers forced one
of the three men to sell some shares because of an indisputable
conflict. Those shares had been purchased while Chock Full o'Nuts
was actively reviewing a buyout offer from the Sara Lee Corp.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sara Lee disclosed that it had approached Chock
Full o'Nuts on at least four occasions over the last two years with
acquisition offers. It most recently bid $10.50 a share in Sara Lee
common stock, or about $119 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chock Full o'Nuts, which roasts and markets coffee but which has
largely missed out on the coffee bar trend that has lifted rivals
like Starbucks, issued a statement late Thursday saying that it had
rejected the offer as inadequate. The company, whose shares rose
$3.125, to $9.50, Friday, earned $5.5 million, or 53 cents a share,
on sales of $396 million in the fiscal year ended in July.
</P>
<P>
   Both profits and sales were down from the previous year because
of declining coffee prices. In the first six months of the current
fiscal year, business slumped again from its year-earlier levels,
although the company sold 10 percent more coffee, as measured in
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Chock Full o'Nuts said the takeover offer was an unfair attempt
to take advantage of the depressed coffee market to buy the company
cheaply. But Sara Lee's persistent overtures raise concerns about
whether the directors took advantage of that information to try to
profit themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Securities lawyers say the stock purchases by directors may not
violate regulations against insider trading because they came well
after an offer was made and rejected. Companies generally are not
required to disclose unsolicited takeover offers if negotiations do
not progress, lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   Federal securities laws forbid someone in a position of
fiduciary responsibility with knowledge of material, nonpublic
information from trading on the basis of the information. But
interpretations of what is material information can vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed by Sara Lee with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the company contacted Chock Full o'Nuts in
August 1997 offering to negotiate a purchase. The same month, Chock
Full o'Nuts rejected the overture.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, in July 1998, Sara Lee offered to buy Chock
Full o'Nuts for $9.50 a share in cash. The company began reviewing
the offer, and representatives of the two companies met to discuss
the proposal over the next three months. Sara Lee, which is best
known for its baked goods but also sells several popular coffee
brands in Europe, raised its offer to $10.50 a share. On Oct. 23,
Chock Full o'Nuts rejected the revised offer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the offer nor the discussions were disclosed to
investors. Fredric Spar, a spokesman for Chock Full o'Nuts, said
Friday that the company kept the talks confidential because ``they
had not ripened to the point where they would require disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting Sara Lee's offer in October, Chock Full o'Nuts
did not hear from its suitor again until last month, Spar said. On
March 10, Sara Lee repeated its interest but lowered its offer back
to $9.50 a share, citing the company's recent poor financial
performance and its adoption of new severance agreements for some
senior executives.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee's renewed offer came two days after a group including
Norman Alexander, the nonexecutive chairman of the Chock Full
o'Nuts board, disclosed it had raised its stake in the company's
shares, to 5.3 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, the 84-year-old chief executive of the Sequa Corp., a
diversified manufacturer, bought 533,100 shares at $5 each, on Feb.
24. Half of the shares were purchased through an insurance holding
company called the Galleon Syndication Corp., which Alexander
controls. The next day, another director, Henry Salzhauer, bought
6,000 shares at $5.28 apiece. Salzhauer and a third company
director, Jerry Columbus, also bought shares in January with
Salzhauer picking up 2,500 and Columbus 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Spar, the company spokesman, said that the purchases were not a
problem because sufficient time had elapsed between this year's
purchases by directors and the October 1998 offer by Sara Lee,
which the directors had rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sara Lee abruptly broke off discussions at the end of
October,'' Spar said. ``There was nothing left on the table.''
After months of no contact whatsoever, a block of stock was offered
on the market, and the directors decided to buy some shares, he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Sara Lee spokesman declined to comment on whether the
companies had any contact from October to February, but the
company's filing with the SEC describes none. The filing also
states that Sara Lee this month bought the equivalent of 5.29
percent of Chock Full o'Nuts shares.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee did not disclose its overtures to the company before
this week. Nor did it propose any directors for the company's board
or make other attempts to rally support for its offer at Chock Full
o'Nuts annual meeting in December.
</P>
<P>
   One former SEC official who now practices securities law in
Washington said that companies generally did not have a duty to
disclose unsolicited takeover offers. If an offer is pending or
being negotiated when the company is required to make a quarterly
or annual report to the SEC, it may be required to disclose the
talks. But there are exemptions based on how serious the
discussions are.
</P>
<P>
   Chock Full o'Nuts apparently had been closely watching its
directors and their stock purchases. On Aug. 21, while the
company's board was in the middle of reviewing Sara Lee's
$9.50-a-share takeover offer, Salzhauer, the director, bought 4,200
shares of the company's stock at $5.25 a share, raising his
holdings to 125,300 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, Salzhauer sold the shares for $5.08 each.
According to Spar, the sale came after Salzhauer was advised that
he was not allowed to trade during the takeover negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee disclosed in its filing this week that it had recently
raised its offer back to $10.50 a share in cash. It also said that
Chock Full o'Nuts made a counterproposal, asking for $12.50 a share
in Sara Lee stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, Chock Full o'Nuts said it would ``continue
to consider all bona fide acquisition proposals.'' But it said that
it viewed Sara Lee's offers and its disclosure of the talks ``as
simply an attempt to take advantage of commodity price fluctuations
and depressed values for microcap stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
