<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANNIVERSARY-HNS &LR;      04-23 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 50, NATO TAKES TIME TO CELEBRATE AND TO DO SOUL-SEARCHING 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At an unexpectedly harrowing moment in its history,
NATO on Friday marked the 50th anniversary of what has been the
world's most successful military alliance &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But in the same gilded auditorium where the founding treaty was
signed, presidents and prime ministers of the 19 member nations
acknowledged that the fight in the Balkans with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic challenges NATO's reputation and future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebration is very hard,'' given the horrors in Kosovo,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said as each leader delivered
commemorative remarks. Almost all of them referred to the
importance of NATO solidarity in the face of attacks by Milosevic's
forces on ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet to honor NATO's past, to chart its future, to reaffirm
our mission in Kosovo, where NATO is defending our values and our
vision of a Europe free, undivided and at peace,'' President
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Unity, a classic rallying cry throughout NATO's history, was a
common theme as the three-day summit opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We send a clear message of unity and determination to sustain
our air campaign for as long as it takes,'' Clinton said, welcoming
fellow leaders at a working breakfast session.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the alliance won peacefully,'' French President Jacques
Chirac said at a subsequent session, ``it is because it is able to
combine freedom and solidarity. ... This alliance, which was forged
in adversity, today is confronted with a new trial, in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was marked by scattered shadows of doubt, including the
view of Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini that the NATO air
attack on Serb TV headquarters in Belgrade was ``terrible'' and
``not in the plans.'' Solana said there had been no widening of the
target list without agreement of the policymaking North Atlantic
Council.
</P>
<P>
   More prevalent were ringing declarations of ultimate victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last European dictatorship of the 20th century will not
destroy Europe's long-awaited chance to live at last together in
peace and freedom,'' Clinton said at the formal commemorative
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO cannot fail. NATO will not fail,'' said Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien. ``The world has changed in 50 years, but
our values do not change. And the need for NATO is as great as
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the enemy has changed, said Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres, who was born three weeks after the founding of
NATO and will be 50 himself next week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a country or a system or an ideology, he said, ``our
enemy is the rejection by so many in the world of the values of the
Enlightenment.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders gathered in the Andrew Mellon Auditorium, a
64-year-old neoclassical structure amid the Federal Triangle, the
capital's densest concentration of U.S. government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   On the same stage, April 4, 1949, the original 12 NATO members
signed the Treaty of Washington _ creating the United States' first
peacetime international alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The basic promise of NATO has been that an attack on any member
nation is considered an attack on all member nations. The alliance
became the principal international instrument of U.S. determination
to contain Soviet communism.
</P>
<P>
   As a symbol of the startling geopolitical changes over the last
decade, the meeting marked the first NATO summit since three former
Warsaw Pact nations _ the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland _ were
made full members of the Western alliance last month.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Europe's ``descent into darkness helped to spark NATO's
creation,'' Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Former adversaries have become friends,'' NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   The admission of the former Soviet satellites, said Czech
President Vaclav Havel, ``signifies the real and definitive end of
the imposed division of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Polish President Alexander Kwasniewski said, however, that the
celebration was overshadowed by ``tragic events in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balkan events,'' he said, ``have made us all realize that
NATO membership does not only bring a feeling of comfort, it is
also about shared responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leaders spoke of the sheer power of the alliance's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A visionary project,'' Solana said. ``What a journey this has
been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is unique,'' said David Oddsson, prime minister of
Iceland. ``There is no example in history of any other military or
defense alliance of free countries which has operated for so long
and in such close harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
