<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WEB-1000&AMP;     04-23 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WEB-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLINGS PROMPT YOUNG PEOPLE TO DISCUSS OSTRACISM ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Md., N.Y., Ga., Ala., Calif.)  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING and related stories.) 
(mb) 
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The electronic message was titled ``A post from an `outcast,'''
and its author, ``Swimmer K,'' sounded a theme that echoed through
cyberspace as young people reflected this week on the killings in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how they feel,'' she confessed, writing to an invisible
audience. ``Parents need to realize that a kid is not overreacting
all the time they say that no one accepts them. Also, all of the
popular conformists need to learn to accept everyone else. Why do
they shun everyone who is different?''
</P>
<P>
   A reply from 14-year-old ``Mandyjac'' came the next day. ``I
can't even begin to say all the problems with cliques,'' she wrote.
``I am seen as an `outcast' and `dork' by all of the popular people
just because of how I act.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandyjac, a high school student in Gaithersburg, Md., added:
``It hurts so much to be seen as `different' but I have learned to
get over it and move on. I think that if we had no cliques, or at
least others weren't looked down on as much, there would not be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In classrooms and around the dinner table, teen-agers' reactions
to the latest school killings may have been dominated by fear for
their own safety and horror at the violence that ended the lives of
young people much like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet, which serves as a sounding board for
teen-agers' inner thoughts, offers a glimpse at a more painful
chord struck by the Colorado killings. In online discussions, on
World Wide Web sites and in e-mail, young people are engaging in
what amounts to a fragmented national dialogue over social
ostracism and the unforgiving hierarchies of adolescent life, all
too familiar but rarely discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the electronic empathizers were quick to repudiate
the killings. But many wrote of identifying with the harassment
that the two killers, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, appear to have
been subjected to before they acted. At a time when it might be
easiest to simply dismiss the two as freaks, several young people
seemed to see pieces of their own experience reflected in that of
the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started out mostly saying, `This is so horrible,''' said
Laura Smith Kay, the online editor of Teen People, whose message
boards on America Online carried 300 responses the first day after
the shootings. ``But now they're talking more about cliques and the
treatment of outcasts and jocks, and how that interaction can
create a really unhappy and potentially dangerous atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of alienation online may be partly a result of
who uses the Internet. The medium is a refuge for many who consider
themselves ``outsiders,'' a place where subcultures of all kinds
connect. Gay teen-agers, for instance, have often reached out to
others online. And Goths, who listen to industrial music and dress
in black, take part in online discussions at Internet Relay Chat
and Web sites like www.slaughter.net. Harris also apparently spent
time online, maintaining a Web site and playing the computer game
Quake, in which the player stalks and kills opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter who is typing into the ether, the nature of the
online dialogue, which provides a sense of anonymity and safety,
also provokes the airing of feelings not so easily expressed face
to face. In the process, some teen-agers say they find the sense of
acceptance online that they cannot find elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the experts on television have been talking about the
problem in Colorado being a breakdown in community,'' said Robin
Jilton, an adolescent psychologist at New York Presbyterian
Hospital who has been monitoring Teen People's message boards on
America Online. ``I see kids coming to these bulletin boards and
forming community. It's especially helpful for kids who perhaps
have less access to a means of expressing themselves because they
have fewer friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Online observations of what it means to be an outcast are
cropping up throughout the Internet, from the current events forum
on theglobe.com, a popular Web discussion venue aimed at teen-agers
and college students, to alt.music.pearl-jam, where an anonymous
contributor wrote on Wednesday: ``HAD TO SAY _ I go to school every
day and am violated of my rights because I choose to be
`different,' and even though I would never take someone else's
life, maybe it will make people think before they opened their
mouths next time _ just a thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Belflower, 18, of Powder Springs, Ga., retooled his Web
site the day after the shootings to read, ``Neatoelito proudly
supports: THE TRENCHCOAT MAFIA,'' a reference to the group with
which Harris and Klebold were associated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were made fun of, they stood up for themselves,'' said
Belflower in a telephone interview. ``It's like in my school, the
preppier kids think they're just everything. People are constantly
harassing each other because they're different. I would never
personally do anything like that, but it did take guts.''
</P>
<P>
   On gurl.com, a popular Web site for teen-age girls, ``T.K.''
wrote, ``Hey, the kids say that they did this because they were
teased and I can understand where they are coming from and I think
that what they did to all of those kids was wrong but a person can
only take so much torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Such messages of identification online are not limited to
teen-age discussion groups. In the k12.chat.teacher forum, teachers
lamented the sense that teen-age cruelty is accepted as a fact of
life and worried over students who describe themselves as
``outcasts and weirdos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a kid with everything going for her thinks she's on the
outside, what is the kid with a troubled home environment supposed
to think?'' one contributor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Others with painful memories of adolescence also poured out
their memories online this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember purple nurples? How about wedgies?'' wrote a
29-year-old in Lawrence, Ala., of physical humiliations he
recalled. ``Until this culture actually learns to stop the out of
control behavior that is accepted by jock culture you will see a
lot more outcasts with guns.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gillian Fischer, 26, a database manager in Los Angeles and a
contributor to the alt.goth newsgroup, said fellow-students used to
spread rumors that she was a drug addict. ``I was one of those
people who would sit in a corner and read,'' Ms. Fischer said. ``It
was even worse to be a freak and be smart. There was everything
from name calling to horrible humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Adolescent alienation and Darwinist high school cliques are, of
course, nothing new. And such comments invariably came in the
context of more wide-ranging opinions. Many teen-agers used e-mail
and electronic postings to relay their support for the survivors at
Columbine High School in Littleton. Others found comfort in simply
voicing their fears, and hearing those of others.
</P>
<P>
   Messages critiquing cliquish cruelty often elicited quick
reminders from others that Harris and Klebold were not simply
victims of senseless teasing. ``They were not `cool different,'
they were racists,'' said one Georgia Tech student on
alt.pro-wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the event seemed to open a vein of troubling
introspection that is perhaps remarkable only because instead of
taking place between small circles of friends, it is on display for
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been in high school,'' said Steven Paternot,
co-chief executive of theglobe.com. ``But the Internet is the first
time you can create such a visible outlet. It's a bigger window
into someone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether such an outlet can serve as a form of catharsis, or even
a catalyst for change, is impossible to say. But Amanda Shank, a k
a ``Mandyjac,'' said in a telephone interview that she felt it was
important to voice her views on the Teen People board to make a
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my school personally, certain groups exist that are the
popular people and the jocks, then there's one group that aren't a
member of any clique, maybe 200 out of 2,000, and that's me,'' Ms.
Shank said in the interview. ``But I don't think it's right to
blame the whole clique system for what these people did. The clique
system is harsh. But it's not an excuse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
