<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEARY-LITTLETONCOLUM     04-23 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEARY-LITTLETONCOLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Colorado tragedy rattles veteran reporter
 &HT;    C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Snow falling on flowers couldn't dampen the
crispness of emotion on display in Clement Park.
</P>
<P>
   I pulled out my pen and notebook every time that emotion crept
into my gut. I kept it at bay, easily, it seemed, just like many of
the other 300 journalists scanning like vultures for that one great
quote to make the front page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that one girl had her journal half open in the
school library,'' one journalist said to another before one of
those elbow-to-elbow press conferences. There, apparently, on that
page, she had written something that her goal for the day was to
finish her college application.
</P>
<P>
   She never will.
</P>
<P>
   Another student said he was eating dinner in a mall restaurant
after the tragedy while wearing the school colors denoting he was
an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a trenchcoat guy in the mall last night,'' 16-year-old
Ben Oakley said to the circle of reporters inching closer as each
trembling word rolled off his parched and chapped lips. ``He looked
at me and laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of young boys kept a protective circle around two fellow
students clutched to each other in front of Rachel Scott's red
sedan. The car had become one of many monuments in the park's
parking lot. Laden with so many flowers and mementoes, the only
part visible was an accident-creased driver's door. The girl's wail
cut through the soggy night. The boy was telling her Rachel will
always be with them. The circle of friends sang a tapestry of
notes, lyrics about having a friend to lean on.
</P>
<P>
   I moved away, back toward the 11 p.m. EST newscasters ready to
tell the world that more than the two shooters might have been
involved in the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't understand the emptiness in my heart. I wrote
furiously about another dead friend, relative, nephew, dad, role
model. We all were.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emptiness is a kind of a form of deeply rooted spiritual
shock,'' my world-traveling friend, Steve Williams, told me, the
one now looking for an explanation. ``My spirit for humanity is
dampened,'' Williams continued. `` As a 'quote-unquote' world
citizen, after so many encounters with people in 68-odd countries,
I'm kind of in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control a few years ago published a
report that said the overall firearms-related death rate for
American children under 15 years of age is 12 times higher than
that in 25 other wealthy nations combined, Williams said he read.
</P>
<P>
   Movies, television, music.
</P>
<P>
   Church youth groups, softball leagues and family vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Dungeons and dragons.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son.
</P>
<P>
   High school graduation. Tragically dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This car, that is as close to that person these students can
get,'' Lutheran Minister Michael Skoor said as another group of
students huddled next to the red sedan. ``They can't reach that
person, but through that car they can turn around and reach each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Where do the journalists turn after they leave?
</P>
<P>
   I called my family because it has only begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, when are you coming home?'' my 7-year-old daughter
Kieran asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't, Kieran. A lot of young people have died so I can't
come home yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many died, Daddy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they get to hug their parents before they died?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Kieran. they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kieran, it is.
</P>
<P>
   I hope I make it home OK.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
