<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS &LR;      04-23 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES SIGNAL FLEXIBILITY IN DEADLOCK WITH YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and the other 18 NATO leaders,
sending a signal of flexibility Friday in the grueling standoff
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, offered to suspend
allied airstrikes if Belgrade begins withdrawing troops from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The allied leaders, addressing some of Milosevic's chief
concerns, also offered for the first time to involve the U.N.
Security Council in the quest for peace and the supervision of a
postwar international security force that would enter Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture offers Milosevic the prospect of having his
long-time ally, Russia, in a position to exercise a veto over plans
for Kosovo within the 15-member U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The international peace force would enter the troubled province
either after Milosevic agrees to allow it in or after the allied
air campaign eliminates Yugoslav forces as a threat, according to a
statement issued after a four-hour NATO session devoted solely to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also said NATO stands ready ``to form the core of
such an international military force'' potentially under United
Nations control.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton and his colleagues, gathered here for the 50th
anniversary of the Cold War-era North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), matched the carrots with a tough stick. They vowed to
intensify air strikes against Yugoslav forces and sites frequented
by Milosevic until he bows to allied demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace and humanity will prevail in Kosovo,'' Clinton told his
colleagues gathered the elegant, columned hall, called the Mellon
Auditorium, where alliance leaders signed the founding documents in
April 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last European dictatorship of the 20th century will not
destroy Europe's long-awaited chance to live at last together in
peace and freedom,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   In their three-page statement, the NATO leaders stipulated that
``there can be no compromise'' on allied demands that Yugoslavia
``ensure a verifiable stop to all military action,'' agree to ``an
international military presence'' in Kosovo, agree to the return of
1.4 million uprooted ethnic Albanian Kosovars and provide
``credible assurance'' that it is willing to work out a political
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   American Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme commander for
Europe, flew in from Brussels, Belgium, to brief allied leaders on
the bombing campaign that started March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning,'' Clark said. ``He's losing. And he knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Pentagon announced that 2,000 more Army troops
will be deployed to Albania to support 24 Apache helicopters being
sent to launch new attacks against Yugoslav tanks and troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the 19 leaders of the newly-expanded alliance that now
includes Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic laid out the most
pliable road map to date for ending the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is prepared to suspend its air strikes once Belgrade has
unequivocally accepted the above mentioned conditions and
demonstrably begun to withdraw its forces from Kosovo according to
a precise and rapid timetable,'' the allied leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies offered to go to the U.N. Security Council, where
Russia has a veto, to seek a resolution that would cover
``deployment of an international military force'' into Kosovo to
protect returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   NATO would merely have to be a key element of the force, with
other nations, including Russia participating, the leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, NATO has shunned involving the U.N. Security
Council in its effort to force Milosevic to end the killing and
deportation of Kosovar Albanians and agree to allow an
international security force in Kosovo. NATO officials have
insisted that the military operation remain under NATO command and
that any peace enforcement units entering Kosovo be led by NATO
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The allied wariness of bringing the Kosovo operation under U.N.
Security Council jurisdiction stems from the fact that Russia is
one of five nations with the power to veto any council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leaders did not detail the makeup or command structure
of the peace force that would protect returning ethnic Albanians
who have fled their homes in Yugoslavia's scorched-earth evictions.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders declared that Russia has ``an important role to
play in the search for a solution to the conflict in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies offered to seek a U.N. resolution that also would
require ``the demilitarization of Kosovo'' _ language designed to
allay Yugoslav concerns and force the ethnic Albanian Kosovar
Liberation Army to relinquish the weapons it has used to battle
Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO statement did not target Milosevic for prosecution as a
war criminal, vowing merely ``to support investigation'' of all
those suspected of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The allies stipulated too that while Kosovo would gain
``substantial autonomy'' within Yugoslavia under ``an international
provisional administration,'' the province would remain part of
Yugoslavia after hostilities end.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders put it: ``We reaffirm our support for the
territorial integrity and sovereignty of all countries in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies also did not mention any invasion of Kosovo by allied
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea again discounted the necessity for
ground troops, saying that ``the winning strategy is the air
campaign.'' He added: ``Ground forces are not some kind of
alternative panacea that you can introduce at a moment's notice.''
A number of NATO allies, including the United States, remain
opposed to a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   The allied flexibility followed former Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin's day-long meeting on Thursday with Milosevic.
Chernomyrdin emerged from the session saying that the Yugoslav
leader had accepted the concept of a U.N.-controlled
``international presence'' in Kosovo in return for NATO halting the
bombing campaign and the alliance withdrawing troops from
Yugoslavia's borders.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Milosevic's commitment
was ``an encouraging sign.'' But on Thursday night a spokesman said
Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair agreed that Milosevic's offer
``fell well short of what was required to meet NATO's conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
