<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-POLITICS-ART-     04-23 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS PULLS AT THE TIES THAT BIND THE YORUBA TO NIGERIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBADAN, Nigeria _ Resting his feet on a table before him,
youngest of his 22 children sitting beside him, a succession of
supporters prostrating themselves beneath him, Lamidi Adedibu
looked very much the part he ascribes to himself: a Yoruba
kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The strongman of Ibadan, to use the Nigerian media's name for
him, Adedibu huddled with advisers on this recent morning to
solidify support among his ethnic kinsmen for the man Nigerian
voters had recently chosen to end 16 years of military rule:
Olusegun Obasanjo, himself a Yoruba, as well as a retired general
and former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Yoruba,'' said Adedibu, 72, as his daughter, Tola, 5,
demanded attention. ``We are one family. We understand ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A family perhaps, but definitely a quarrelsome one. Two months
after the election of Obasanjo, a month before he is scheduled to
assume power, the Yoruba are engaged in intense debates over their
position in Africa's most populous nation and their complicated
relationship with the president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will shape this nation of 110 million people one way
or another. But it will also be watched closely in other African
nations that have struggled to foster democratic governments and,
like Nigeria, were drawn haphazardly by colonial powers and include
different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoruba, of southwest Nigeria, are one of the country's three
main ethnic groups, along with the Hausa-Fulani, of the north, and
the Ibo, of the southeast. After a Yoruba leader, Moshood K.O.
Abiola, was denied an apparent victory in the 1993 presidential
elections by Nigeria's northern military rulers, many Yoruba called
for secession. Not since the Biafran civil war three decades ago,
when the Ibo tried to break away, had Nigeria's survival been so
strongly put into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before February's elections, the country's northern
politicians agreed on a so-called power shift. To keep Nigeria
together, they would yield the presidency to the south. So the race
pitted two Yoruba candidates against each other, Obasanjo and Olu
Falae, a former finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   That the race was won by the Yoruba candidate distrusted by many
of his own people raises the question of whether ethnic ties will
prove stronger than memory as Yoruba leaders decide on their role
in an Obasanjo government. Can Obasanjo, serving as president in a
civilian government, win over the Yoruba without alienating the
country's 250 other ethnic groups?
</P>
<P>
   ``The nationality question is the most important one facing not
only Nigeria, but many other places in the world,'' said Bola Ige,
a leading Yoruba politician and former governor of the southern Oyo
state. ``That's why you have Kosovo, Indonesia, and, nearer home,
Zaire, Rwanda and Burundi.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If General Obasanjo succeeds in settling this question, his
name will be written in gold,'' Ige, 68, said. ``His place in
Nigerian history will be assured. So the ball is in his court.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also in the court of Yoruba leaders, without whom the
president-elect will not be able to begin creating unity.
</P>
<P>
   What role the Yoruba should play in a Nigeria led by one of
their own is being debated passionately here in the
quintessentially Yoruba city of Ibadan. It is home to the nation's
first university, built in 1948 by the British, the country's
former colonial rulers, a lasting testament to the Yoruba's
position as Nigeria's best-educated ethnic group. In keeping with
the city's nickname as the ``wild, wild west,'' political
discontent has often started in Ibadan before spreading throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 27, Obasanjo won decisively nationwide, but he lost here
in Oyo state, as well as in his home state, Ogun _ in fact, he lost
in all six Yoruba states. His loss was rooted in his first
presidency. In 1976, Obasanjo found himself Nigeria's military
ruler after his superior, a northern general, was killed during an
attempted coup.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Obasanjo cemented his reputation abroad by becoming the
first military ruler to step down voluntarily from power in favor
of an elected government. But at home, the reaction was mixed. In a
close presidential race between a northerner and a revered Yoruba
politician, Obasanjo was seen by the Yoruba as having favored the
northerner. The discovery that he had cast his own ballot for the
northerner fueled the Yoruba's anger and feelings of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's close ties to a military dominated by northerners
added to the Yoruba's lasting mistrust, which deepened in recent
years when he was quoted as saying that ``Abiola is not the
messiah.'' Abiola, a billionaire businessman, was imprisoned after
his 1993 presidential victory was annulled. Once held in suspicion
by the Yoruba for his own close ties to northerners, Abiola became
in prison the living embodiment of the Yoruba's political
disenfranchisement. He died last summer, still a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Obasanjo joined the People's Democratic Party, which
was backed by the retired military elite, and ran a presidential
campaign based partly on his self-description as a de-tribalized
politician who would look after the interests of all Nigerians.
Most Yoruba, meanwhile, voted for the Alliance for Democracy, a
party that swept all the Yoruba states but made no inroads beyond
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They campaigned against Obasanjo on the fear of
marginalization and extermination of the Yoruba race,'' said Layi
Balogun, 59, a prominent Yoruba architect and businessman here.
``Under those circumstances, Obasanjo had no chance in
Yorubaland.''
</P>
<P>
   As men waite hours outside his house for an audience, Lam
Adesina, the governor-elect of Oyo state, explained how Yoruba
leaders' attitudes toward Obasanjo had softened since his victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in Yorubaland that you do not send a bad child to
be eaten by a lion,'' Adesina, 61, said. ``The Yoruba leaders have
put our heads together with our obas, our kings, to see how we
could help him. We should not be seen as a race fighting against
each other. Whether Obasanjo is good or bad, he is part of the
Yoruba race. He is part of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ola Oni, a former economics professor at the University of
Ibadan who now runs a bookstore from his house, disagrees. A
onetime believer in pan-Africanism and nonethnic politics, Oni, 68,
gave up on the idea of a united Nigeria after the annulment of
Abiola's apparent presidential victory in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obasanjo still hangs on to the old idea of one Nigeria,'' Oni
said. ``I no longer believe in one Nigeria. We are calling on the
Yoruba people not to accept his government and to regard it as no
more than a transitional government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been chosen by the north to assist in realizing the
northern agenda of domination,'' Oni added, repeating the most
frequent attack against General Obasanjo during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Adedibu, the strongman of Ibadan, said it was time to move
beyond such talk. Yoruba leaders, so used to serving in the
opposition, must now learn to work in the mainstream. ``The federal
government,'' he said, ``belongs to us, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
