<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER GIVES VOTE OF CONFIDENCE TO BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Betting that Brazil's car market will
recover from a steep decline in sales, DaimlerChrysler AG
inaugurated a factory Friday to produce Mercedes-Benz automobiles
in Latin America's largest country.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, which already assembles Dodge pickup trucks at
a plant in southern Brazil, hopes to produce at least 25,000
A-Class compact cars in the first year at its new $820 million
factory. If the Brazilian economy climbs out of a recession and
manages to grow next year, as many economists are now predicting,
company officials said they could almost triple annual output to
70,000 by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country is passing through a difficult phase,'' said Ben
van Schaik, the president of the Mercedes-Benz Brazilian
subsidiary, in a speech at Juiz de Fora, the city in central Brazil
where the new plant was built. ``But with the help of an economic
recovery and a reduction in interest rates, we remain optimistic.`
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, along with a half-dozen other car manufacturers
including the General Motors Corp., the Honda Motor Co. and Renault
SA, has pressed forward with expansion plans in Brazil even as the
country's automobile industry struggled with its most sluggish year
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of 1.1 million vehicles are expected this year, down
substantially from the record 1.9 million units sold in 1997,
according to Anfavea, an automobile industry association. The
decline came amid an overall contraction in Brazil's economy,
though there is widespread belief that a rebound is under way.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler hopes to sell as much as 85 percent of the
output from the Juiz de Fora factory in Brazil, with the rest
destined for neighboring countries in South America. The factory is
modeled on a similar Mercedes-Benz plant in Rastatt, Germany, which
also produces the A-Class. The starting price for the compact car
is expected to be about $19,500 in Brazil, compared with $22,000 in
Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
