<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      04-23 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONIA GANDHI PARTY'S BID TO LEAD INDIA DISSOLVES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The dream of the Congress Party to once again
govern this nation of 980 million people by itself, with a member
of the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty to lead them, turned out to be a mirage
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party president, Sonia Gandhi, boldly _ and it
turns out prematurely _ declared on Wednesday that her party had
the votes to replace the nationalist coalition that collapsed last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Congress Party's 140 votes in Parliament are far
short of the 272 required for a majority, Mrs. Gandhi said more
than a dozen smaller parties would vote with a Congress government,
even without having Cabinet posts. Their votes would ensure that
Congress would win a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But two tiny Communist parties and a bigger party based in Uttar
Pradesh dashed the chances of any such arrangement Friday when they
announced that they were dead set against any government led by
Congress. Admitting that the numbers are running against Congress,
a senior party leader, Arjun Singh, said the party is willing to
consider supporting a coalition that would include many parties.
</P>
<P>
   Six days after Congress and the other opposition parties brought
down the coalition government by a single vote, they are still
struggling to come up with an alternative. If they fail, the
president is likely to call for a general election, which would be
India's third since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal blow to Congress' plans was delivered by Mulayam Singh
Yadav, the leader of the Socialist Samajwadi Party. He said his
party's 20 Parliament members would not support any government
unless they were eligible for ministerial and policy-making
positions _ and Congress was not allowed to lead it. ``If anyone
thinks of forming the government without giving due respect to a
party having 20 members, then he is living in a fool's paradise,''
said Amar Singh, a party spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Samajwadi and Congress are potential competitors for the votes
of Muslims in Uttar Pradesh, India's most populous and politically
powerful state. If Congress revives its winning ways by gaining
control of a national government, the Muslim voters who deserted
Congress over the past decade might drift back, political analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulayam Singh Yadav is being asked to commit suicide and he
says, `No, I'm not too keen,''' said Yogendra Yadav, a political
scientist at the Center for the Study of Developing Societies.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress gambit was in many ways an attempt by the grand old
party that governed India for most of the past half century to have
its cake and eat it, too. Congress, which has been in sharp decline
in recent years, wanted to have the power without the majority to
back it up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the principal reasons Congress lost power in the first
place was its failure to accommodate the rising aspirations of
regional and caste-based forces. So it is not surprising that
Samajwadi, whose most loyal voters come from Mulayam Singh Yadav's
own cow-herders' caste, would refuse to go along with restoring
Congress to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-FIREWALL-0424-CO     04-23 2129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-FIREWALL-0424-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (COX NEWS SERVICE EXCLUSIVE)
 &HT;    POTENTIAL NATO LEAKS HAS U.S. GOING ITS OWN WAY ON STEALTH
MISSIONS
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim at 1300 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon has kept from its NATO allies the
details of hundreds of U.S. combat missions to Yugoslavia under a
policy designed to ensure strict American control over all strikes
by cruise missiles and radar-evading stealth bombers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a security firewall aimed at preventing leaks from
NATO partners that might compromise those raids, give away tactical
or technological secrets or endanger American pilots, according to
senior Air Force officials.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is a sensitive one _ military officials would
discuss it only on background _ because it reflects tensions within
the NATO alliance over the sharing of top secret information.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman confirmed, however, that the bombing
sorties flown by the stealth F-117 Nighthawks and the B-2 Spirits _
the workhorses in the precision strikes on scores of refineries,
barracks, ammunition dumps and other fixed targets deep inside
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia _ are purely American operations.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, some say, is trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't keep secrets very long in the NATO command
structure,'' said an Air Force officer with extensive experience
with alliance operations in the Balkans, referring to the prospect
of leaks. ``That's just an accepted fact.''
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton hosts the heads of state and diplomats from
the 18 other NATO countries and two dozen formal NATO partners here
this weekend, the public focus is on five decades of alliance
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away from the diplomatic gala, American pilots and
planners are waging a war within a war, screening off from their
NATO partners the stealth missions military analysts believe have
hit well over 50 percent of the major targets destroyed so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary from a security standpoint,'' said a separate
senior Air Force official with command experience in NATO
operations in the Balkans. ``It is the downside of allied
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials are less explicit. They concede, however,
that the stealth bombing missions _ as well as the cruise missile
launches from B-52 aircraft and U.S. warships off the Yugoslav
coast _ are cordoned off from overall NATO operations and are
instead confined to U.S. control.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are U.S.-specific systems and technologies,'' explained
a Defense Department spokesman who was authorized to address the
issue only on the condition of anonymity. ``We don't transfer
operational control of these aircraft to NATO command.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. pilots began suspecting from the start of Operation Allied
Force that Yugoslav military and government officials were being
tipped off shortly before targets were attacked. In some cases,
barracks or other facilities appeared to be vacated just minutes
before a scheduled attack. U.S. officials have declined to discuss
these incidents publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly NATO remains very vigilant in terms of protecting the
security of its operations,'' the NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen.
Wesley Clark, told reporters in Brussels on April 13, when asked
about alleged security breaches. ``We're taking what I believe are
all necessary and appropriate measures in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is careful not to accuse individual
countries of giving away alliance military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Chinks in the armor of NATO security, however, have long been a
major concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody's nightmare,'' said former CIA anti-espionage
analyst Glen Buchan(CQ), now an expert on air power with Rand
Corp., a policy think tank based in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, there are specific foundations for caution.
</P>
<P>
   Several NATO members _ including Greece, France and Italy _
retain close historical and cultural ties to Serbia, the main state
in Yugoslavia. Greece is so cozy with Russia, another close partner
to Belgrade, that some new NATO members with histories of conflict
with Moscow have openly lamented having to share security
information with the government in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, NATO's only predominantly Islamic country, has been
working to cultivate ties with its giant neighbor, Iraq. U.S.
pilots have been flying combat air patrols over Iraq since the
1990-91 Gulf War, and have been regularly bombing Iraqi targets
since last December.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels last October, U.S. intelligence
agents caught a French military officer named Pierre-Henri Bunel
passing top secret details of NATO air strike plans against
Yugoslavia to Jovan Milanovic, head of the Yugoslav diplomatic
mission at the European Union. Bunel, facing espionage charges in
France, has admitted to handing off the information.
</P>
<P>
   Clark prepared those plans as NATO was threatening air strikes
against Serbs for ongoing aggression last fall against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo. In the face of those threats, Serb leader
Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, agreed to end the
repression. He later broke that promise, claiming the need to crack
down on what he said were Albanian terrorists. As his troops massed
to begin a sweep across Kosovo, NATO launched air strikes March 24.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. suspicions about NATO security were heightened four nights
later with the downing of an F-117 Nighthawk stealth bomber outside
of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first combat loss in the 18-year history of the F-117
Nighthawks, which survived thousands of Gulf War sorties unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has not released its findings over the downed F-117
_ the pilot was rescued and his name not released _ and hasn't said
publicly whether the plane was shot down or crashed because of
mechanical failure or pilot error. Six other F-117s have crashed
during training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Asked this week whether investigators had ruled out the
possibility that the F-117's flight details might have been passed
along in advance to Yugoslav forces, Air Force Maj. Gen. Bruce
Carlson declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should comment on any of that,'' replied
Carlson, who briefed reporters at the Pentagon on stealth
operations and the F-117 investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department spokesman who commented on background
said that at no time during the air campaign have the details of
stealth flight operations been shared NATO-wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still doing business the way we started out doing
business,'' the spokesman said. ``It's been this way since day
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The non-U.S. NATO participants are by no means flying blind.
</P>
<P>
   They are privy to the advance details of scores of sorties flown
each day by U.S. pilots of conventional fighters and bombers, as
well as refueling tankers, reconnaissance aircraft and other
support planes. Such conventional craft as F-16s, F-15s and A-10s
have been hitting targets as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots from Britain, Canada, France, the Netherlands and other
NATO countries have flown hundreds of sorties of their own,
moreover, that are woven into the American operations to form the
alliance-wide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. planners coordinate the American-only portion of their
operations with the NATO-wide campaign to prevent accidental
shootdowns or other mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stealth operations are kept secret from the U.S.
allies, however, and because of the large role those missions are
playing in the campaign, only the U.S. commanders and the national
command structure _ the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Secretary of Defense
William Cohen and President Clinton _ have access to a complete
picture of the ongoing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem we anticipated coming up sometime, we just
didn't anticipate it coming up quite so soon,'' said Buchan. ``One
of the things this means as a practical matter is that the other
NATO planners don't get to contribute intellectually as much as we
had hoped. It puts a big burden on the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Waging an air campaign is a monstrous planning and coordination
challenge. NATO pilots are flying between 300 and 600 sorties every
24 hours _ as much as a major airline, but in a decidedly more
hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   Each flight must be intricately planned and carefully folded
into the overall operation to ensure that bombers get the
protection, targeting and intelligence information and refueling
support they need. It also helps prevent accidents or mistakes
among allied warplanes flying missions in crowded skies.
</P>
<P>
   The master plan for each day's operation is contained in the air
tasking order, or ATO. It is contained in a thick book put together
each day at NATO's combined air operations center at Vicenza,
Italy, and also dispatched electronically to NATO members
participating in the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive guide to each day's campaign, the ATO is a sort
of air power playbook. Instead of x's and o's, it lists:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the F-16s, A-10s, Harriers, Tomcats, Prowlers, Hornets and
other conventional warplanes that will fly into combat on a given
day;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the bombs each will carry;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the targets they will pursue;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the times of their attacks;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the sequencing of support flights;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and the call signs and radio frequencies pilots will use to
communicate and an ocean of related details.
</P>
<P>
   The ATO is so secretive that the mere mention of its existence
seals lips instantly across the spectrum of military command.
</P>
<P>
   Even more secretive are the stealth operations, which are kept
off of the ATO that goes out NATO-wide each day. Those missions are
ordered separately, by U.S.-only command, as are the cruise missile
attacks, such as those that destroyed Milosevic's Communist-era
villa on Thursday and have repeatedly struck at government
buildings in the heart of downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, NATO pilots had flown roughly 9,500 sorties as
part of Operation Allied Force, roughly one-third of which were
actual bombing runs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials won't say how many of those have been stealth
flights. It's clear, though, that those aircraft have pulled the
lion's share of the weight in the precision targeting of barracks,
ammunition depots, refineries, and headquarters buildings,
particularly in the heavily-guarded skies above cities like
Belgrade and Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   There are two dozen F-117 Nighthawks in the NATO armada. Their
all-weather capability has made them indispensable to an operation
hampered by heavy clouds and fog on two days out of every three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have capabilities that the allies lack, particularly an
all-weather capability,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon told
reporters this week. ``And, to the extent that the weather's been
bad, the emphasis has been more on American systems than on foreign
systems, or allied systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history, moreover, suggests that the Nighthawks -- which
can hit two targets on a single flight -- have been freight haulers
in a campaign that has relied heavily on dropping the kind of
precision-guided munitions the F-117 deploys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 85 percent of the strategic targets were hit by the F-117
in the Gulf War,'' Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald told reporters
at the Pentagon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force planners distinguish between strategic targets major
fixed facilities such as barracks, command and control bunkers,
ammunition storehouses, airfields or refineries _ and tactical
targets, such as tanks, vehicles and troops deployed in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Even less has been said publicly about the operations of the B-2
Spirit, the most advanced _ and, at more than $2 billion a copy,
most expensive _ warplane in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we have flown a significant number of sorties,''
with the B-2, said the Air Force's Carlson. ``It's doing superbly
over there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying solo and in pairs, the B-2s have been regular
participants in the strikes, having flown dozens of 30-hour sorties
from the plane's home base at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri
into Yugoslav airspace and back.
</P>
<P>
   Individual sorties, though, are a poor measure of the B-2s'
contributions. The planes can carry 16 precision-guided 2,000-pound
bombs on a single flight and drop them accurately through clouds
and fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the B-2 _ one sortie, 16 different targets, all
weather,'' said Wald, summing up the utility value of the plane, as
he showed aerial imagery of eight buildings destroyed at an ammo
storage facility in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one B-2 aircraft that did that,'' said Wald.
``There's probably nothing left there.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0306 </DOCNO>
