</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we have flown a significant number of sorties,''
with the B-2, said the Air Force's Carlson. ``It's doing superbly
over there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying solo and in pairs, the B-2s have been regular
participants in the strikes, having flown dozens of 30-hour sorties
from the plane's home base at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri
into Yugoslav airspace and back.
</P>
<P>
   Individual sorties, though, are a poor measure of the B-2s'
contributions. The planes can carry 16 precision-guided 2,000-pound
bombs on a single flight and drop them accurately through clouds
and fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the B-2 _ one sortie, 16 different targets, all
weather,'' said Wald, summing up the utility value of the plane, as
he showed aerial imagery of eight buildings destroyed at an ammo
storage facility in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one B-2 aircraft that did that,'' said Wald.
``There's probably nothing left there.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
