<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKANS CONFLICT TESTS CONGRESSIONAL SPENDING DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After outdoing each other for months in their
pledges not to fritter away the federal budget surplus, both
parties in Congress have quickly agreed that the costs of the
Balkans conflict should be an exception.
</P>
<P>
   But having opened the door to spending some of this year's
anticipated surplus of $111 billion to pay for airstrikes and
relief aid, Republicans and Democrats alike now find themselves
sorely tempted to dip deeper for other military needs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Congress is facing an early test of its willingness
to hold the line on spending the huge and growing pot of excess tax
revenues being taken in by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   All of the current fiscal year's surplus comes from excess
Social Security revenues, money that both parties have argued
should be preserved at all costs to help deal with the retirement
system's looming financial problems. (There is not expected to be a
large non-Social Security surplus for two more years). So the
choice to spend any significant amount of the surplus beyond what
is needed immediately to wage the conflict in the Balkans will be a
particularly tricky one.
</P>
<P>
   The debate so far is over whether Congress should give the
Pentagon money beyond the $6 billion requested by Clinton to
finance military and humanitarian operations in the Balkans for the
next five months. Clinton's request by anyone's definition fits
into the category of emergency spending established a decade ago to
deal with expenses including wars and natural disasters, and is
therefore not subject to normal budget rules.
</P>
<P>
   But recent history suggests that both parties could also stretch
the definition of emergency this year to justify using the surplus
both for other military needs and pressing domestic issues like aid
to hard-hit farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most amazing thing is that having been so righteously
insistent about not spending a dime of the Social Security surplus,
to suddenly add other things to the emergency money for Kosovo
shows that they are abandoning the pledge at the first
opportunity,'' said Stanley Collender, a budget analyst for
Fleischman-Hillard, a consulting firm. ``The question is whether it
will extend to things beyond defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate cost of the war at this point is unknowable, but it
seems unlikely to make much more than a dent in a surplus that is
projected to reach $133 billion next year and to grow considerably
larger in subsequent years. The bigger issue may be whether it
alters budget politics.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for example, may conclude that they should
emphasize rebuilding military strength over tax cuts as their
signature issue for the next few years, particularly since the
groundswell of public support for tax cuts they had anticipated has
not materialized. Republicans including Dick Armey of Texas, the
House majority leader, have already said they would be willing to
scale back or postpone their proposed $800 billion, 10-year tax cut
to make way for new military spending.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will have to decide how to balance calls for
additional military spending against pent-up demand within the
party for new spending on social programs and their efforts to
build a reputation for fiscal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of the war, and the related push for more military
spending, is also likely to affect how Congress and the
administration deal with the challenge of remaining within tight
spending caps for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The caps were set by the 1997 balanced budget deal as a way of
imposing fiscal discipline, and if not changed will require deep
cuts in some programs next year. The conflict in the Balkans could
provide cover for both parties if they choose to raise or eliminate
the caps next year because of a need for higher-than-anticipated
Pentagon spending.
</P>
<P>
   Or, by adding more Pentagon spending in the current fiscal year
on an emergency basis _ money that is not subject to the spending
limits _ the two parties could pare back their Pentagon budget
proposals for next year, easing the pressure on the caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current definition of an emergency is anything we can't
pay for under the caps,'' said Susan Tanaka, vice president of the
Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, a fiscal watchdog
group.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Senate debated a Republican measure this week that
would lock away most of the surplus starting next year for debt
reduction or shoring up the Social Security system, Republicans in
the House were considering proposals for as much as $29 billion in
new military spending, to be paid for out of the surplus, during
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are unlikely to endorse a figure as high as
$29 billion, but have signaled a willingness to pass an emergency
supplemental spending bill providing the military with considerably
more than the $6 billion Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats and the White House see an opportunity
developing to brand Republicans as fiscally irresponsible, but are
wary of politicizing the debate over the money needed for the
Balkans conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful the supplemental will move forward without
delay in a way that funds the urgent and immediate needs, both
military and humanitarian, that arise from the Kosovo conflict,''
said Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman for the White House's Office of
Management and Budget. ``This is not the place to debate other
issues that should be addressed in the context and constraints of
the normal budget process.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House itself has a history of being flexible when
it comes to adhering to strict definitions of fiscal austerity.
Last October Congress patched together _ and Clinton signed into
law _ a spending package for the current fiscal year that stayed
within the caps only by designating $20 billion of spending on
programs like farm aid as emergencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
