<SLUG> BC-ATT-HOSTETTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTETTER THE POWER BEHIND AT&AMP;T'S MEDIONE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If investors believe AT&AMP;T has offered too rich a price for
MediaOne, they can largely thank a publicity-shy Boston
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Amos Barr Hostetter Jr., who spurred AT&AMP;T to make its bid,
pushed company executives to place a high value on MediaOne's
assets, AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael Armstrong said in an interview
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter is MediaOne's largest shareholder and a former top
executive, but he had a falling out with MediaOne management
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was careful to say that AT&AMP;T was already eyeing
MediaOne when Hostetter approached several weeks ago to propose a
merger. ``But he was able to give us a confirmation of the insights
we had about the value we could extract from the investment,''
Armstrong said in a telephone inteview. ``He was able to give us a
better understanding of the situation and of the value.''
</P>
<P>
   If its bid is accepted, AT&AMP;T will pay $4,700 for each MediaOne
subscriber, a huge increase over the $2,700 per subscriber that
AT&AMP;T paid last month when buying Tele-Communications Inc., the
nation's second-largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said Friday that AT&AMP;T's bid was high, and they
wondered if the company could manage the acquisition while still
absorbing TCI. Amid the doubts, AT&AMP;T shares fell almost 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said that MediaOne is worth the price because its networks
are in some of the top markets, such as Boston and Los Angeles.
MediaOne is also considered to have upgraded its network more than
other companies so that it can carry phone and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter, 62, is a cable industry visionary. A New York City
native and graduate of Amherst College and Harvard Business School,
he co-founded Continental Cablevision in 1963, long before most
people thought the industry had a future. He built his company into
one of the nation's largest cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He truly does walk on water in this industry,'' said Leo J.
Hindery Jr., head of AT&AMP;T's cable business, during a conference
call Friday with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Cablevision was sold in 1996 and became the main
portion of MediaOne. Hostetter retained a role with the company but
quit in a falling out when MediaOne moved its headquarters to
Colorado from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   According to Armstrong, Hostetter and his sister own 13 percent
of MediaOne shares. Forbes last year listed Hostetter as among the
nation's 400 wealthiest Americans with a net worth of $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   About four weeks ago, after Comcast Corp. made an offer for
MediaOne, Hostetter asked MediaOne to free him to pursue other
offers. He quickly approached AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already done a lot of our own thinking and work before
Amos and we sat down together,'' Armstrong said Friday. ``But he
was an early participant in understanding the potential of the
MediaOne plant,'' or cable network.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is struck, Hostetter will once again have a high
post in the industry in return for helping play matchmaker. He will
be ``non-executive chairman'' of AT&AMP;T's cable and Internet services
unit, while Hindery becomes chief executive of that unit. Hostetter
will also have a seat on the AT&AMP;T board.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does a non-executive chairman do for a living? His first
responsibility will be to support the CEO, Leo Hindery,'' Armstong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery said he and Hostetter could successfully lead the cable
and Internet unit together. ``Nobody should infer that I didn't
want this, didn't seek it out, that I didn't encourage it,''
Hindery said. ``Having him around is a delight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
