<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-CABLE-BOS &LR;      04-23 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-CABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS EXPECTED TO BE TOUGH ON ANY AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Convergence, competition, shopping on demand. For
years, high-tech executives have used buzzwords like these in
promising that consumers would soon have a wide choice of fantastic
new cable, phone and Internet services _ all at low, competitive
prices.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, the promises have been as empty as the missing
stations on the proverbial 500-channel TV dial.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, analysts said a range of new telecommunications
services might truly be on their way with the news that AT&AMP;T Corp.
wants to buy MediaOne Group. The deal would doube AT&AMP;T's cable
holdings and make it the nation's largest cable company as well as
the long-distance and cellular telephone leader.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne, which until recently was based in Boston and was
called Continental Cablevision, is the nation's No. 4 cable firm
and largest in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T made its unsolicited offer late Thursday. Its bid of $85 a
share, or $62.5 billion at Friday's stock prices, topped an offer
of less than $75 a share, or $56.5 billion that the nation's
third-largest cable operator, Comcast Corp., made several weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, several analysts said AT&AMP;T's offer would likely spark a
bidding war for MediaOne, though others said AT&AMP;T had offered a
high price _ equal to or better than $4,700 for each MediaOne cable
subscriber _ that no other company would top. Comcast Friday made
no comment on whether it would boost its bid.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne also declined to comment. AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael
Armstrong said he expects a response by May 6, the deadline for the
company to evaluate competing offers to Comcast's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also said that the AT&AMP;T deal, if consummated, might
draw tougher scrutiny from regulators than have other recent
telecommunications mergers.
</P>
<P>
   With cable rates already rising, it makes little sense to allow
a giant cable company to become even larger by buying one of its
potential competitors, said Gene Kimmelman, codirector of the
Washington office of Consumers Union, a consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormous amalgamation of power in one cable
company, which also owns dozens of the most popular cable
channels,'' Kimmelman said. ``We think AT&AMP;T will be in a position
to thwart the advancement of competition in the cable industry.''
He said Consumers Union would ask federal antitrust regulators and
the Federal Communications Commission to block the deal. A
prominent senator, Republican John McCain of Arizona, chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee, also said the deal would be bad for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors also questioned whether AT&AMP;T was offering too
high a price for MediaOne, and whether AT&AMP;T could swallow the
company while still digesting other big deals, including its $59
billion buyout of cable powerhouse Tele-Communications Inc. last
month. AT&AMP;T shares fell nearly 6 percent Friday, or 3 3/8, to 53
3/8. It was the day's most actively traded US stock. MediaOne
shares rose 7 7/8 to close at 77 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the deal, AT&AMP;T's Armstrong said Friday that the
acquisition would help AT&AMP;T accelerate its revenue growth. He also
said ``we don't think there's a regulatory risk'' in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And some analysts said that regulators might favor the deal
because of its potential effect on other parts of the
telecommunications industry: local telephone and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   It is in those arenas that the merger could bring consumers new
services at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   When the government broke up the Bell System monopoly in 1984,
it left AT&AMP;T with no direct line into homes and businesses. AT&AMP;T
became a long-distance company, but local phone lines and local
service were controlled by the new regional Bells, such as Nynex,
now Bell Atlantic, in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Now, AT&AMP;T is buying lines into homes once again _ not phone
lines this time, but cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to relatively new technology, the company plans to offer
telephone service over those cable lines, putting it in direct
competition with Bell Atlantic and other local phone providers. The
company also will sell high-speed Internet links over its cable
lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will ``go on the offense after that $110 billion local
exchange opportunity that's out there, and protect the $23 billion
long-distance business,'' Armstrong told reporters. Several Baby
Bells said they took Armstrong's words seriously. Denver-based US
West, for example, slammed AT&AMP;T's claim that it would reenter the
local market that it was forced to exit in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing less than a blatant attempt by AT&AMP;T to rebuild
its monopoly _ and do it on the backs of American consumers,'' said
Mark Roellig, vice president for public policy at US West. He said
the company was also trying to ``lock in a monopoly over the
Internet'' by controlling the links to homes and businesses when it
already owns a large share of the ``backbone,'' or main pipelines,
that carry Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Offering phone, Internet, and cable services over the cable
lines falls well short of the vision of ``interactive television''
that cable executives have promised for years. They had said
consumers would be able to buy clothing, groceries and other
products through sophisticated cable TV systems, and would be able
to pick from thousands of movies at will.
</P>
<P>
   Those services never materialized, thanks to high development
costs and low customer interest in the earliest versions. But if
AT&AMP;T can offer local phone service, Internet links, and cable TV
over its cable lines, it will have taken a large step toward
creating the sophisticated network that can carry ``movies on
demand'' and other services, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal isn't about telephone and isn't about cable. It's
about the convergence of the two _ of voice, data, and video all
coming together,'' said Mike Paxton, an industry analyst with
Cahners In-Stat Group in Scottsdale, Ariz. ``These things are
already happening right now, but at such a small scale that it's
not on most peoples' radar screens.'' The AT&AMP;T deal could bring the
trend to millions of new customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, an estimated 100,000 people receive telephone service
over their cable lines, including 24,000 who buy the service from
MediaOne. That is a tiny share of the 102 million US households.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 1 million people link to the Internet over high-speed
cable lines, a small share of the 40 million or so Internet
customers, Paxton said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Adamik, a telecommunications analyst with the Yankee Group
in Boston, cautioned that technological hurdles may hinder AT&AMP;T as
it tries to bring these services to more customers. ``AT&AMP;T will
command huge market share, and the question is whether its networks
can withstand that,'' he said. ``That's a question that's only been
answered in the labs.'' No company has tried yet to carry large
numbers of phone conversations over cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, however, is forced to search for revenues in these
businesses, said Boyd Peterson, also of the Yankee Group. Revenues
in the long-distance industry are flat, prices are falling and
competition is fierce. AT&AMP;T's market share is under constant
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Residential long-distance revenues now account for 42 percent of
AT&AMP;T revenues. The company wants them to account for about 15
percent by 2004, Peterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2009EDT &QL; 
