<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT24-COX     04-23 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO ALLIES AGREE AT SUMMIT TO PRESS AIR WAR
 &HT;    With NATO-CITY and NATO-FIREWALL.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his NATO counterparts brushed
aside Yugoslavia's latest peace offer Friday and agreed to press
forward with their air war, shunting aside the idea of using ground
forces.
</P>
<P>
   But in a shift, the 19 leaders meeting to mark the 50th
anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization expressed
guarded optimism that Russia might be persuaded to join an
international peacekeeping force in the embattled province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With that hope in mind, the leaders said they would seek United
Nations approval of a plan to place Kosovo under international
protection, a move that would leave the door open to the use of
ground troops at some point in the future.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said the alliance would
seek a U.N. Security Council resolution calling for the withdrawal
of Serb forces from Kosovo under Chapter VII of the U.N. charter.
</P>
<P>
   That chapter, among other things, addresses the provisions for
the authorization of ``action by air, sea, or land forces as may be
necessary to maintain or restore international peace and
security.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without such a resolution, however, the NATO leaders
vowed to continue the air campaign for as long as it takes to bring
peace to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not allow this campaign of terror to succeed,'' the
alliance members declared in a 17-point joint declaration. ``NATO
is determined to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   In a solemn ceremony in a flag-bedecked, columned auditorium,
the 19 heads of state and government walked to a podium to sign a
``vision statement'' of the challenges awaiting NATO in the next
century. It said the alliance will have to confront terrorism and
the spread of weapons of mass destruction even as it fulfills its
original mandate for collective defense.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as host of the anniversary gathering, Clinton cast the
mission to restore security to Kosovo as a vital goal for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance will not have meaning in the 21st century if it
permits the slaughter of innocents on its doorstep,'' Clinton said
at the Andrew Mellon Auditorium, where the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization was signed into being at the dawn of the Cold War, on
April 4, 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a question of territorial conquest or political
domination, but standing for the values that made NATO possible in
the first place,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last European dictatorship of the 20th century will not
destroy Europe's long-awaited chance to live at last together in
peace and freedom,'' he said, in a reference to the regime of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   White House national security adviser Samuel Berger dismissed a
Russian-brokered peace overture from Milosevic, which essentially
amounted to a plea for a halt in the bombing in exchange for
promises to end the repression in Kosovo and negotiate further
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously not acceptable to us,'' said Berger. He called
the Russian effort ``constructive,'' but said, ``on the question of
our stopping bombing, it could not be on the basis simply of a
promise.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO reiterated five conditions for halting the air strikes. It
said Milosevic must:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ensure a verifiable halt to all military action and the
immediate end of violence and repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Withdraw from Kosovo his military, police and paramilitary
forces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agree to the stationing in Kosovo of an international military
presence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agree to the unconditional and safe return of all refugees and
displaced persons, and unhindered access to them by humanitarian
aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide credible assurance of his willingness to work for the
establishment of a political framework agreement based on the
Rambouillet accords, which call for autonomy for the majority
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Behind the lofty rhetoric _ and behind closed doors _ Clinton
met with his NATO counterparts for more than three hours in a
meeting resembling a council of war.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging consensus was clear: Serb forces that have
terrorized Kosovo for more than 15 months will face escalating air
strikes of indefinite duration, and an oil embargo of uncertain
dimensions, but will not be confronted by NATO troops on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, as I said before, the strategy is not going to
change,'' said Solana. ``We're going to continue, with
determination,
</P>
<P>
   with intensification, with the air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, delivered a
detailed briefing on the air campaign to the delegates, essentially
offering them his assurance that 30 days of air strikes had taken a
withering toll on the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, we're winning, he's losing, and he knows it,'' said
Clark. He portrayed Serb field forces as the tattered remains of a
fighting force, cut off from supplies, orphaned from their
commanders, ''lurking in villages, running back in forests, and
otherwise trying to get away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clark, ``They are vulnerable to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said he thought there was ``a reasonably good chance''
that Moscow could be persuaded to support a U.N. resolution on
Kosovo and participate in a NATO-led peace-keeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some indication that the Russians have said that they
are prepared to participate,'' said Berger. ``That would be a step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that NATO would not back down from its campaign
in the absence of such a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would seek the U.N.'s approval, and I think we would have a
reasonably good chance of getting it,'' said Berger. ``That
</P>
<P>
   doesn't mean that if we don't get it, we won't go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is one of five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council with veto power, so its support would be essential to a
Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The planned ``celebration'' aspect of the anniversary was toned
down because of the ongoing war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the leaders repaired Friday night to the White House East
Room, where they feasted on soft-shell crab and lobster cakes,
lemon-flavored spring lamb, strawberry nougat glace and champagne
while enjoying the singing of opera star Jessye Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
