</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE PASSES $98 BILLION BUDGET THAT INCLUDES RAISES FOR
TEACHERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Blessed with a vigorous economy and a surplus,
the Texas Senate approved a $98.3 billion balanced state budget on
Friday, devoting almost two-thirds of that to education.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, a Senate committee authorized $1.7 billion to
increase teacher pay and benefits. But negotiations with the House
could shrink the Senate's proposed $4,000 pay raise for
minimum-paid educators in order to increase tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Containing no new taxes, and allowing for a cornucopia of
generally small tax cuts that would affect many Texas families, the
Senate's proposed spending plan for 2000-2001 should have
widespread appeal, lawmakers said. It would save roughly $20 in
sales taxes for most families outfitting their kids with
back-to-school items and take pressure off local districts to raise
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   While the budget represents a 5 percent overall increase over
current spending, House Bill 1 was described as a no-frills
document by Senate finance Chairman Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conservative,'' Ratliff insisted, noting that lawmakers
resisted the urge to dip into future tobacco settlement proceeds
and earmarked 63 percent of its non-federal income to schools and
universities. The budget does include $1.8 billion in tobacco money
set aside for the two-year period that starts Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And even though it provides about half of the $2 billion in
property tax relief sought by Gov. George W. Bush, Ratliff said it
goes a long way in helping taxpayers. He said Bush's goal was based
on an early, rosy revenue estimate that was later scaled back by
$700 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake to couch that as some sort of a failure
just because the ambitions earlier were higher,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Senate's budget plan differs substantially from the
House's version, a 10-member negotiating committee of House and
Senate members will begin meeting on Monday to iron out
differences. Although their bottom lines are $1.3 billion apart _
with the Senate's total the larger of the two _ the differences are
partly a matter of bookkeeping. The House listed some likely
expenditures on an unfunded ``wish list'' rather than adding them
to the total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there are any dramatic differences,''
Ratliff said. ``We put more money in higher education, but they've
got a wish list that has a lot of higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said the budget ``clearly articulates our
priorities _ education first, basic government, services and
significant tax cuts &UR; .'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The sum includes $3 billion for increases in teacher pay and
benefits and for property tax cuts, though specific amounts are
still being negotiated. The budget also includes $945 million in
new spending at universities and $100 million for new college
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate budget provides for a 3 percent pay raise for state
law enforcement officers, but since the House put the raise merely
on a ``wish list,'' it will be renegotiated next week.
</P>
<P>
   Because deficit spending is barred by the state constitution,
the House left about $700 million unspent but also agreed to allow
almost that much in tax relief. Measures allowing sales-tax breaks
for school-related spending and some children's medicine are
pending in both chambers, as are business tax reductions and
credits.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its budget strategy, the Senate Education Committee
on Friday approved an education spending plan to allow about $1
billion in property tax relief as well as $1.7 billion for teacher
compensation. Although the plan allows for raises of up to $4,000 a
year for minimum teacher salaries, Ratliff said it's possible that
the sum will be renegotiated to about $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   It would take $6,000 to bring the average Texas teacher salary
up to national pay levels, however. And 45 percent of the state's
teachers won't get the raise because they are already paid above
minimum levels cited in the bill. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
