<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BIAS-PROFILES24-     04-23 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS-PROFILES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The suit against Coca-Cola, case by case
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here are the allegations of each plaintiff in the
discrimination lawsuit against Coca-Cola Co. Several, according to
the suit, sought the company's help in dealing with problems at its
downtown Atlanta headquarters before seeking the assistance of the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and filing their lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   MOTISOLA MALIKHA ABDALLAH
</P>
<P>
   Status: Still employed
</P>
<P>
   Abdallah has worked for Coca-Cola for more than three years as
an administrative assistant. She currently works in strategic
channel marketing, a division that has only one other
African-American employee, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says for the past two years, Abdallah has asked to be
promoted to a higher-paying grade level. In 1998, when she applied
for her current administrative assistant position, she again asked
if it could be upgraded to a higher grade. Her request was refused,
the suit says. Abdallah said her predecessor, however, was given a
higher pay grade.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also says that five white managers whom Abdallah
supports have made ``inappropriate demands,'' such as asking her
and other African-American administrative assistants to ``run
personal errands and do personal chores.'' The suit says the
managers made Abdallah feel like their ``black maid.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she repeatedly sought assistance from the company's
Human Resources Division over the past year but says nothing has
changed. Abdallah also said she was retaliated against in her 1998
performance evaluation, receiving a ``meets minimum'' rating,
although earlier evaluations were more positive.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY ALLEN CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Status: Still employed
</P>
<P>
   Clark has been a security officer at Coca-Cola since 1996. The
suit says that despite his extensive education and experience, he
has been ``consistently denied promotional opportunities given to
his Caucasian counterparts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark joined Coca-Cola after working in security at Grady Health
Systems' Emergency Care Center. He also has experience as a
correctional officer at the Lorton Correctional Facility in
Virginia and as an operations manager for Crowd Control Security
Co. in Stone Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says he applied for an upgrade in his position at
Coca-Cola in June 1996, to a position in the Internal Security
Group. The position, which would have significantly increased his
responsibilities, was given to an employee with more seniority but
without a bachelor's degree, which was one of the requirements
posted.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Clark then applied for another position, in
February 1997, as a security team leader, but did not get that
position. In April 1997, he applied for a lead officer position. In
that case, he was not invited to interview for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Also during 1997, the suit says, Clark applied for ``multiple
jobs outside of security at Coca-Cola and did not get interviews
for any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had exhausted his administrative remedies before
going to the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   LINDA INGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Status: Still employed
</P>
<P>
   Ingram began working at Coca-Cola in 1990 as a customer service
representative in Dunwoody. The suit said she was ``quickly
promoted'' to technical dispatch adviser. During that time, she
noticed ``African-Americans worked disproportionately in lower job
grades and less desirable positions, and had difficulty moving up
in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingram, however, was promoted in 1993 to project coordinator in
the national accounts department, where she performed data
analysis. In 1995, she was promoted to senior information analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But as a senior information analyst, the suit says, Ingram has
``never been paid what her position merits'' and is underpaid when
compared with her white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the suit says, the pay range for her position was
$37,000 to $67,000, but her pay was below $37,000, and new postings
for positions with her title had higher pay ranges. The suit also
says other workers at her grade were being paid salaries of at
least $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also says Coca-Cola ``refused'' to give Ingram adequate
work space when she became a senior information analyst, providing
her with ``a cubicle and no phone.'' White counterparts, however,
had offices. The suit says Ingram also said a supervisor yelled at
her during a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   KIMBERLY GRAY ORTON
</P>
<P>
   Status: No longer an employee
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the company in October 1998, Orton was a 13-year
veteran of Coca-Cola. She began in 1985 in a field sales position
after holding sales positions at Proctor &AMP; Gamble and Whitehall
Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, she held account manager positions in
Seattle, St. Louis and New York, during which, the suit says, she
received good evaluations on her work.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Atlanta around 1992 as manager of Promotional
Packaging Graphics for Coca-Cola USA, supervising about 15 workers.
In 1994, she moved to Coca-Cola's corporate headquarters on North
Avenue in Atlanta as a company director.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Orton was ``grossly underpaid'' for her work at
the company, earning ``tens of thousands'' less than her white
counterparts. It says she failed to reach even the midpoint of the
pay scale for her director's position.
</P>
<P>
   Orton said employees she supervised had salaries higher than
hers. For example, her salary of $78,000 in 1995 was overshadowed
by an employee who made $85,000, even though the employee's grade
level was lower than Orton's. In 1998, the suit says, her $99,000
salary was ``one of the lowest paid directors in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
