<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-BUMP24-COX     04-23 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BUMP24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta CFO relinquishes flight freebies
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A senior Delta Air Lines executive whose children were
involved in a controversial bumping episode has given up free
flight privileges for himself and his family for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Warren Jenson announced the move in a
memo to employees Friday. He said it came after a private meeting
this week with Chief Executive Leo Mullin, who hired Jenson last
year from NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past week has been very difficult for me and my family,''
Jenson said, adding he offered ``sincere apologies'' to both
workers and customers. ``I take complete responsibility for what
happened. The blame goes no further,'' Jenson said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred March 4. Three of Jenson's children and
one of their friends were flying from Atlanta to Denver and arrived
late at the gate, accompanied by Jenson's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary had agents move seated first-class passengers to
coach so the youths could sit up front, a process that delayed
departure 24 minutes. The friend, who was traveling on a discounted
coach ticket, got a free first-class upgrade in apparent violation
of a ticketing rule crackdown championed by Jenson. The incident
later was described in a pilot union newsletter and reported last
week in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman said then that ``several mistakes'' were made,
adding Jenson had reimbursed the airline more than $1,000 for
vouchers given to the bumped passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But internal grumbling continued, prompting Jenson's memo and
the flight privilege action. A Delta spokesman said such a
suspension is within the range of penalties for employees who abuse
flight privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
