<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-BOSTON-BOS &LR;      04-23 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL SAYS BAY STATE READY TO WELCOME REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The first wave of refugees from war-torn Kosovo will
be heading to Boston within the next few weeks, and Cardinal
Bernard Law said Friday Catholic Charities will be working to
reunite refugees with relatives living in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration on Wednesday said it will bring
20,000 Kosovar refugees to American cities instead of sending them
to the US military base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba as originally
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first responsibility of the church _ and all of us _ is to
respond with humantarian aid to the immediate needs of the
refugees,'' Law said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Catholic Charities has set up a 24-hour hotline local
Albanian-Americans can use to notify officials about their
relatives and where they are being held in camps along the Kosovo
border. Law said Catholic Charities will then notify international
relief officials in the Balkans that those refugees have a place to
stay in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Under the administration's plan, refugees with relatives in the
United States will be given top priority for relocation as NATO and
its allies seek to ease the dangerous conditions confronting by the
hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians who have been driven out
of Kosovo by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has a substantial Albanian population _ estimated
at about 6,000 _ centered in Worcester and South Boston. The Bay
State has been identified as a priority location for refugee
relocation as a result, Catholic Charities officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The effort by the Catholic Church to help Kosovars was endorsed
Friday by Reverend Arthur F. Liolin, chancellor of the Albanian
Orthodox Archdiocese. Liolin said the archdiocese has been focusing
its efforts on raising money to ease suffering within Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church, he said, has greater resources and far
greater expertise dealing with immigration issues and the federal
government and is better able to handle the expected inflow of
refugees than the Albanian archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Law said Friday the administration's sudden strategic shift
means charitable organizations in Boston and around the country
must quickly gear up to offer housing, counseling and other forms
of assistance to the refugees once they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Law said the still-evolving plan launched by Catholic Charities
includes the use of two church-owned houses _ in Medford and
Brighton _ for refugees who cannot find housing with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   He also said charitable groups are in need of Albanian
translators who can help the refugees _ and those seeking to help
them _ navigate the cultural gaps and language barriers that will
inevitably divide them.
</P>
<P>
   Law said reports he has received from Claire Carroll, a Catholic
Charities offical now working at a refugee camp in Macedonia, is
that those driven out of Kosovo by the Serbs dream of someday
returning to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want simply to go home and live in peace and security
with their families and loved ones,'' Law told reporters in
Brighton Friday. ``The humanitarian commitment we share cannot rest
until we help them return to their homes and regain the sanctuary
of thier hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Catholic Charities has 70 years of experience in
resettling refugees, the cardinal said the church lacks Albanian
speakers amongst its staff and appealed for help from
Albanian-Americans who speak both languages to help as translators
for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Law also said the church has very limited resources to provide
temporary housing for the refugees and asked the public to consider
opening their homes _ or homes they own _ to serve as housing for
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Although a substantial portion of the Kosovars are Muslim,
Joseph Doolin, president of the Greater Boston Catholic Charities,
said Friday the emphasis will be on family reunification _
regardless of religious affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not specifying Catholic refugees,'' he said. ``We are
talking about refugees who want to come to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Law and other Catholic Charities officials Friday were uncertain
when the refugees will start arriving in the Boston area. Lisa
David, interim refugee and immigration services director, said she
has been told the airlift could start as soon as next week or three
weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The hotline to aid Albanian refugees is 617-629-5754, ext. 318.
Donations can be sent to Catholic Charities Kosovo Refugee Fund, 49
Franklin Street, Boston, MA 02110.)
</P>
</TEXT>
