<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGING IN THE EARLY TWOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 25, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you plan to spend New Year's Eve? Put yourself in the
driver's seat, says Cathy Minehan, president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of Boston. Look at it through the eyes of a Y2K pro.
</P>
<P>
   It's Friday night, December 31. Many of the world's markets
already have been closed for a day (although not the markets in the
United States.) They'll be closed Monday as well. There is time to
work through any unforeseen demand.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have sat through endless meetings discussing the way that
dates are handled in the the computers of your organization;
performed massive tests with customers and suppliers; conferred
with the phone, electricity, and airline companies; bought
insurance; and, if you are a bank, filed all the necessary forms
for an emergency loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet you are holding your breath, realizing that Y2K problems
anywhere in the complex and increasingly integrated world of global
finance could quickly become yours,'' says Minehan.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen? Not very much at all, says Minehan, one of the
Federal Reserve System's point persons on the Y2K problem and a
co-chair of the Fed's Century Date Change Council _ especially if
public fears about the possibilities can be allayed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Banks plan to increase their supply of ready
money to around $200 billion from their normal level of $150
billion, in expectation that many people will generally prefer to
keep a little more cash on hand through the holidays. Most ATMs are
Y2K compliant now, and the probability of banking problems is very
low.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the public mood at century's end is one of the few
variables that can't be confidently tested, measured, and modeled
in advance. Therefore, Minehan has begun speaking out on the
preparantion that have been made for history's most fraught turning
of a calendar page.
</P>
<P>
   The problem now familiarly known as Y2K had its roots in the
early punch-card days of computers in the 1940s and 1950s. Only a
little information could be put around the edge of a card; the
solution was to use just two digits for a four-digit date: 54
instead of 1954.
</P>
<P>
   The practice was carried over when computer memories went
magnetic: cost was still a problem. Core memory for IBM computers
cost about $1 per byte in 1960. But then the silicon chip was
invented; 40 years later $1 buys a million bytes of storage. The
problem could have been fixed early, but it wasn't. Only in the
last few years has it come into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Its significance for the Federal Reserve System is great. The 12
regional Federal Reserve banks process something like $2 trillion
every day _ the settlement of everything from the US government
securities market, the Eurodollar market, the dollar leg of all
other foreign exchange transactions, and many other security and
bond markets, plus handling about 66 million checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's record-keeping has been rendered completely Y2K
compliant, and tested end-to-end. ``Recognizing that nothing in
life can be fully guaranteed,'' says Minehan, ``I am as confident
that Reserve Bank systems will function without fail in the new
century as I am that they will function this afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   About the rest of the system, there are several grounds for
optimism, too, Minehan says. There's the financial industry's track
record of coping with operational challenges, for example. From
blizzards to power outages to major software failures, companies
and their regulators have ``learned from (their) errors, built
sophisticated and extensive backup capabilities, and gone on to
create a record of virtually error-free operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there was the relatively glitch-free implementation
of the Euro last January 1 _ an auspicious sign.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly there has been the massive corporate planning effort that
will have cost something like $600 billion world-wide by the time
that it is done. Extensive testing has taken place; problems that
led to failures in 1998 _ airline reservation systems, automatic
inventory programs, and the like _ have been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   And surveys by the Board's 12,0000 depository institutions, J.P.
Morgan, a special Senate committee and a presidential commission,
and any number of blue-ribbon studies have reached the same
conclusion. Most of the problems have been anticipated and will be
fixed by New year's Day. There will be no planet-wide brownout at
the millenium.
</P>
<P>
   As the study by the J.P. Morgan Bank puts it, ``The real Y2K
affect on society and the economy has been spread across a much
wider spectrum of time and is of a much more subtle form than the
overnight chaos predicted by Y2K doomsday experts. Y2K problems
have been occurring, will occur on January 1, 2000, and will
continue to occur throughout 2000 and into 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which means that Y2K is no longer the most pressing
problem. The spotlight is now shifting to the matter of what to
call the coming decade. All kinds of suggestions have been made,
none of them very good: the Oughts, the Noughts, the Zeroes, the
Zilches, the Ohs and the Oh-Ohs.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore consider the suggestion of my colleague Peter Hotten.
Call them, the Early Twos. That has a pretty good ring to it,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
