</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO LITTETON'S CLERICS, WORDS OF EXPERIENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ky. Ark.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One dreadful week last May, the Rev. Zane O. Wilson, pastor of
Springfield Lutheran Church in Springfield, Ore., got telephone
calls from fellow Lutheran clerics in far-off places like
Jonesboro, Ark., and Paducah, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   They were calling because they had heard on the news that a
gun-wielding adolescent had fired on classmates at a Springfield
high school, killing two and wounding others. Similar shootings had
occurred in their own communities, and they wanted to offer Wilson
support and advice.
</P>
<P>
   One caller, Wilson recalled in an interview, told him, ``You've
become a member of a club that no one wants membership in.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what they said _ that the people of his congregation
would want to find some way to be of service to their town _ was
something Wilson passed along this week when he called members of
the clergy in Littleton, Colo., scene of the school shooting on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the violence in Springfield, Wilson's congregation
threw open its doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right across the street from the doors to the emergency
room,'' he said. ``Everybody who wanted to find a place to get out
of the sun, or get a drink of water, or find a place to pray, came
in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters, parked outside the hospital, came over. The
congregation was host to a prayer service that night, drawing about
500 people to a sanctuary designed for fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that these folks do well,'' Wilson said of
his congregation, ``is they welcome the stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   One man who called him then, and who also phoned clerics in
Littleton this week, was the Rev. Laird H. Duran, pastor of Our
Saviour Lutheran Church in Jonesboro, the town where four girls and
a teacher were shot to death at Westside Middle School in March
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter he faxed this week to four Lutheran churches in
Littleton, Duran quoted Psalm 51, verse 14, which begins, ``Deliver
me from bloodshed, O God.'' Talking with one pastor, he advised
going to the school, the hospitals and meetings of parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Littleton clerics also need to take time for their own
spiritual needs, Duran said, lest they be overwhelmed. After the
shooting in Jonesboro, he said, it helped him to keep a prayer
journal on his computer, maintaining a communication with God that
ran from Job-like questions (``Why us?'') to reflections on the
Gospels' account of Jesus' suffering and Resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wilson and Duran said Littleton's clergy would have to
think about the long-term impact of the violence on the community.
In Jonesboro, Duran said, when he preaches against evil, once a
very broad concept, people now think he is talking about what
happened at Westside Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Littleton's high school students ought to be kept
together and active.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to community, and schools provide that in this
culture,'' he said. ``And these kids have lost their school, at
least temporarily. If you're a 16-year-old at Columbine High and
your school is shut, what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Littleton clerics who have been receiving the phone
calls is the Rev. Robert C. Barger, senior pastor at Abiding Hope
Lutheran Church. Barger got to the scene of the shooting shortly
after the police. He spent the day there, trying to comfort
students and staff members who had fled the school. ``I'm still
quite numb,'' he said in a phone interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Some who have called him from places where school shootings
occurred earlier have ended up crying on the phone. ``The common
thread,'' Barger said, is that each had thought the shooting in his
or her community ``would so shock the culture that things would
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiding Hope Church held a community service on Wednesday and
has begun providing space for counseling services by an agency
affiliated with the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America,
Barger's denomination.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, Barger tried to take a break, driving to a
video store to look for what he called ``a redemptive movie.'' He
had in mind ``Holland's Opus,'' about a high school music teacher.
But at the store, he felt surrounded by movies with highly violent
content. He had a feeling, he said, ``of wanting to scream out,
`Don't we get it?'''
</P>
<P>
   A question he said he wanted to put before his congregation was,
``Are we willing to be peacemakers, nonviolent, and say no to the
culture?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
