</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis said she was not aware of cocaine allegations until
reading the Journal story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had questions about what had happened, about how this
could have happened with a young person who had relatively good
health all his life,'' said Harris-Lewis, who had a year-old son
and was pregnant with her daughter when her husband died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, about two weeks before the retirement of Reggie's jersey
at the Boston Garden, when that article came out in the Wall Street
Journal, I read it in disbelief,'' she said. ``I had never heard
that, and it came to me as a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   After the story was published, Harris-Lewis said, she spoke with
several people who had been quoted in the story, including Mudge,
who confirmed that he had been quoted accurately.
</P>
<P>
   During that conversation, she said, Mudge ``said to me for the
very first time that there was a conversation that took place where
there was an admission of drug use by Reggie.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis said she viewed a lawsuit as her only means of
restoring her husband's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's always been a search for the truth, and the only
way I could do that is through the judicial system,'' she said.
``Upon filing this suit, my questions were, `What do I say to my
children?' I think that his mother and his brothers and his family
and his community need answers. . . . This is the system we have in
America, and that is the only way we can search for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she had requested that evidence of alleged illicit
drug use be barred from the trial, Harris-Lewis said she believed
that drug allegations ``sensationalize and hide the true issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge ruled last week that he will decide whether to consider
any evidence of drug use when individual witnesses claiming to have
such information are called to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   As she has since the Journal story was published, Harris-Lewis
vigorously denied that her husband used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the lifestyle we led. That's not what he was
interested in,'' she said. ``He was a very productive person and
cared about his health, his profession, and his family, so he would
not do anything irresponsible to jeopardize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis noted that several factors other than drugs could
have caused the damage to Lewis's heart, including a virus, as was
recorded on his death certificate. ``But this is sexier,'' she said
of cocaine allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had considered settling the suit out of court,
Harris-Lewis declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
