<SLUG> BC-WEB-TRENCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE IS ON TO GRAB `TRENCHCOAT' DOMAIN NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As TV screens flashed with live news reports of the school
shootings at Columbine High School on Tuesday, Jose Troche of
Taunton, Mass. rushed to his computer to register the Internet
domain names trenchcoatmafia.net, trenchcoatmafia.org., and
trenchcoatmafia.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want someone to use those names to come up with a
neo-Nazi Web page, saying `Let's blow up the world,' '' said
Troche, 29, who owns Kronix Beepers in Norton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In the 24 hours that it took to complete the transaction,
someone had beaten Troche by minutes for trenchcoatmafia.com, but
it was someone who also wanted to keep others from making money off
the name, Troche said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Colorado teens who presumably shot to death 12
classmates and a teacher before turning their guns on themselves,
belonged to group that called themselves the Trenchcoat Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   As the news stunned the nation, many looked to the Internet for
answers on what the group stood for. Others, Troche said, were
looking on ways to cash in on the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A name _ that's all it takes to make a million dollars off the
Net,'' Troche said. ``They'd have over 40,000 people a day going to
the Web page, being curious.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, two people have offered him big money for the Web
addresses. One man offered $30,000, he said. The other offered
$35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them said he wanted to do an antiviolence Web page, but
he wanted to keep his name anonymous and pay me cash,'' Troche
said. ``The other one said he wants to keep the page out of harm's
way. I said I'm already doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Web publisher e-mailed Troche, asking him whether he could
design a Web page that serves as a memorial to the victims,
complete with poems and photographs. Troche said sure, but he would
have to approve the page before it goes live.
</P>
<P>
   Troche said he thought about registering the domain names
immediately when he saw the TV news because it was fresh in his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Troche has been something of a player in the nascent world of
registering Internet names, in which users scramble to claim new
names and buzzwords _ either to protect them, sell them, or just
frustrate others who might want them.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Troche registered a domain name for his
company. He has also registered several other domain names, most of
them relating to hip-hop music producer Sean ``Puffy'' Combs _ whom
he says he wants to annoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate Sean Combs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't like Comb's style of music and says the
entertainer does not give back enough of his money to poor
communities. Combs and his company could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   As people find out that Troche owns the Trenchcoat Mafia-related
domain names, he has been getting a flurry of calls and e-mails.
Some call him nasty names, thinking he is trying to profit off it.
Others, he said, are supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Some have even called him noble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
