<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT24-COX     04-23 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax break welcomed by caregivers
 &HT;    EDS: EMBARGOED for Sunday, April 25
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Earnest Prather dabs rouge along the smooth, pale
ridge of his wife's cheekbone, careful to work the brush all the
way up to the corner of her eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get it high enough, she lets me know,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Prather applies his wife Beverly's make-up every morning, then
fixes her hair, the most recent of a long list of daily activities
he has had to assume for his 65-year-old wife as Alzheimer's
disease steadily robs her memory and her mental abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Prather, who is 68, must now help bathe her, feed her, dress her
and make sure she doesn't wander from their ranch home in Harrison
Twp. and into harm's way. His caregiving is a ceaseless, full-time
job, 24 hours a day every day, with much-needed breaks three times
a week, for six hours at a time, when he can take his wife to an
adult day care program and catch up on his housework.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the program is $564 a month _ a financial burden
Prather hopes he can continue to carry at least a couple more
years. ``I want to keep her home as long as I can,'' he said of his
one-time high school sweetheart. ``We've been together for 48
years. . . She waited on me hand and foot for a long time, and what
goes around comes around.''
</P>
<P>
   Prather is one of millions of Americans laboring quietly at home
for their disabled or elderly loved ones, often with little or no
outside support. Their burden in time and money is the great hidden
cost of America's health care system, a cost that could double or
triple over the next 30 to 40 years as baby boomers age and the
ranks of those needing long-term care swell.
</P>
<P>
   For every elderly person in a nursing home in America, there are
two of equal disability being tended to at home, experts say. More
than 65 percent of disabled elderly living in the community rely
exclusively on unpaid sources, usually family or friends _ a $196
billion annual price tag if government were to pay the bill,
according to a 1997 study published recently in the journal Health
Affairs .
</P>
<P>
   Many of these caregivers are themselves poor and one in three is
in relatively poor health, according to a U.S. House Ways and Means
committee report.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clinton administration is proposing a $1,000 tax credit
for people needing long-term care, or for the relatives taking care
of them at home _ a fraction of the $50,000 a year it would cost
the government for someone in a nursing home. The package also
calls for $125 million in funding for adult day care and respite
programs to help give family caregivers a break.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was in Dayton last week touting the tax
relief, which an estimated 2 million Americans will qualify for at
a cost of $5.5 billion over five years. Some version of the
proposal is expected to come before Congress this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the tax credit plan represents a small but long
overdue recognition of the important role families and friends play
in long-term care. But critics, including financial writer Jane
Bryant Quinn, point out that the credit won't help the poor who pay
little or no taxes, that it opens the door to fraud and that it
will only speed up the day of financial reckoning for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Both critics and supporters agree the tax credit is only a
downpayment toward providing more comprehensive support for the
nation's elderly infirm and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction, but clearly there's a long
way to go,'' said Judy Turner, executive director of the Miami
Valley chapter of the Alzheimer's Association.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas McGarry, executive director of the Area Agency on Aging,
a local advocacy group for the elderly, said the proposal won't
have much of an economic impact on struggling caregivers. ``But
from an emotional standpoint, it's at least some recognition of the
valuable role that they play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Clinton plan ``puts the discussion of
long-term care back on the table again. It gives us an opening to
talk about larger issues,'' said Judy Riggs, director of public
policy for the Alzheimer's Association in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include the so-called ``spend-down'' requirement
for Medicaid, which forces patients to exhaust their life savings
before they can qualify for assistance, as well as Medicaid's
built-in bias for institutionalizing the infirm rather than helping
keep them at home.
</P>
<P>
   The caregivers themselves say the $1,000 annual tax credit is
welcome relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Renate Lilly, who quit her job two years
ago so she could stay home and care for both her elderly parents.
Her parents' uninsured prescription costs alone come to nearly $800
a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you require outside help, and we do, the financial burden
just becomes overwhelming,'' Lilly said. She and her husband Tom
spend $1,200 to $1,400 a month to bring in a paid caregiver three
times a week, five hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Prather said he pays to put his wife into a day care program.
``I need the time to get the housework done, and she needs the
structured activity,'' he said. ``She doesn't have anything to do
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bennett of Kettering, a single mother who stays home to
care for a 6-year-old son suffering from a rare muscle disorder,
said the Clinton tax credit should extend to caregivers of disabled
children, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of disabled kids in this country are being raised
by single mothers and mothers who are working, and none of us are
millionaires,'' she said. ``Any break the government can give us
would be appreciated, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one piece of the Clinton plan _ $125 million in funding
for adult day care and respite programs to help family caregivers _
will be considered this summer in the Senate's Subcommittee on
Aging as part of the reauthorization of the Older Americans Act.
That subcommittee is headed by U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine (R-Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   Charles Boesel, a spokesman for DeWine, said DeWine favors
updating the Older Americans Act ``to make it easier for families
to care for the elderly and disabled, although it may not be
identical to what the administration wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
