<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-72     04-23 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFERS TO MORE HAWKISH LEADERS ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is President Clinton leading or following on
Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   The question came into sharp focus in the Rose Garden this week
as Clinton and Javier Solana of Spain, NATO's secretary-general,
met reporters at the opening of the alliance's elaborate 50th
birthday celebration in Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked about the possible use of American ground
troops in the Balkans, a decision that could prove the most
momentous of his presidency. Was he willing to take a look at
options for land combat in Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   His reply was jarring to an audience accustomed to American
leadership in NATO, an alliance to which the United States has
devoted hundreds of billions of dollars and hundreds of thousands
of troops since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to your first question is: I support the
secretary-general's decision to update the assessment,'' Clinton
said. ``I think it is a wise and prudent course.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not say that he had pushed NATO military authorities to
begin the preparations for a ground war, should it be needed. He
did not say that Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, should
be under no illusion about NATO's willingness to employ all
available means to drive his troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the president said that Solana, not he, had made a
decision to study the possible use of ground forces, and that he
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has perfected the art of exquisite followership in many
of his domestic initiatives, accurately reading public opinion and
then offering policy solutions _ like school uniforms or a balanced
budget _ that precisely mirror the public mood.
</P>
<P>
   But it is surprising to hear this approach applied to matters of
war and peace. Clinton has bucked public opinion in foreign policy
issues earlier in his presidency _ on Haiti and on Bosnia, for
example. But on Kosovo, Clinton seems content to lag behind the
more hawkish sentiments of Solana, Prime Minister Tony Blair of
England, even his own secretary of state, Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides deny that he has suddenly reverted to the
dovishness of his anti-war youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't read more into this than meets the eye,'' said Joe
Lockhart, the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart and others do not object to portrayals of Clinton
as a reluctant hawk, parsimonious with American blood and eager for
a quick and peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis on NATO's terms.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate that the public is growing uneasy about
how the war is being conducted in the Balkans. The conflict has
brought Clinton's job-approval ratings down to their lowest point
since June 1997, long before the Monica Lewinsky revelations that
led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of Americans polled approve of airstrikes
against the Yugoslav regime, but a growing number believe that the
conflict will be concluded only after ground troops are employed, a
more aggressive stance than that so far adopted by the president.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were reported in a new poll from the Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo has the potential of bringing the president's poll
ratings down,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew center.
``There's no reason for panic at the White House yet, but Kosovo
could change the public's evaluation of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approval rating fell from 62 percent in March to 56
percent in April, dragged down by falling confidence in his
handling of foreign policy. Only 51 percent of respondents approved
of his conduct of foreign affairs, against 39 percent who
disapproved. That represented a marked turnabout from last
September, when the public, 61 percent to 30 percent, approved of
his stewardship of foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials denied that Clinton's handling of the
Kosovo crisis was affected by public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anyone sitting around worrying about the
president's personal ratings,'' Lockhart said. ``We are focused on
a difficult campaign that with persistence and determination will
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If there are people worrying about it, I'm not in
the right meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   But a presidential adviser who did not want his name revealed
said that Clinton was concerned about how the public perceived his
handling of the war and was taking pains not to appear too eager to
commit American youth to battle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The president clearly shifted his position this week on the need
to consider the use of ground troops to end the conflict in
Yugoslavia. For a month, Clinton insisted that it was not even
necessary to update planning for land combat, but he has now
conceded that the time has come to dust off last year's war plans.
To disguise his shift and to signal his unease about a ground war,
Clinton allowed NATO officials and the more openly belligerent
British to announce the new policy, the presidential adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   A president seldom walks into the Rose Garden and announces he
has reversed himself, this adviser said. The allies gave Clinton
cover to change his mind on ground troops this week, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton may not appear fully engaged in
Kosovo and the NATO summit this week because he is deeply concerned
about the mass killings at the high school in Littleton, Colo., and
is trying to maintain some momentum on his domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's juggling a little bit,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revealed a bit of his state of mind at T.C. Williams
High School in Alexandria, Va., where he went late this week to
talk to students about guns, violence and rage. He said that even
mature people have trouble managing their anger because they have
not found a vocabulary for handling it.
</P>
<P>
   And he complained that he had tried since his first year in
office to pass strong gun control legislation, but had been stymied
by conservative opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to keep people alive,'' he lamented.
</P>
</TEXT>
