<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA2-BOS &LR;      04-23 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO LEADERS REMAIN STAUNCH ON DEMANDS TO MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under extraordinarily heavy security, leaders of
the 19 NATO nations Friday convened their 50th-anniversary summit
with a get-tough message for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic:
Agree to all NATO demands or face ever more intense bombing of
``central nervous system'' targets such as Serb TV.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic can expect more attacks like the ones that devastated
Serb TV on Thursday night and earlier smashed the ruling party
headquarters in Belgrade and one of Milosevic's residences. The
raid on Serb TV, which killed 10 people according to officials in
Belgrade, drew criticism from western media groups as well as from
Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said NATO's current strategy is to
``strike directly at the central nervous system of Milosevic's
regime.'' He justified Serb TV as a legitimate target _ part of
Milosevic's ``propaganda machine,'' which ``bears as much
responsibility, if not more, than the Serb forces themselves for
the chaos and mayhem that we have witnessed in Yugoslavia since
1991.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments on the 31st day of the conflict Friday:
</P>
<P>
   _ The European Union imposed an oil embargo on Yugoslavia to
prevent Milosevic from importing gasoline and other fuel now that
his refineries have been heavily damaged.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO leaders discussed the issue of deploying ground troops
during a closed-door session, and according to a senior US official
the point was made that ``the public had a right to know that we're
looking at every option.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon said it will send 2,000 more troops to the
Balkans. Defense Secretary William Cohen approved the new
deployments in conjunction with the arrival of 24 U.S. Apache
attack helicopters. The ground-based forces will help protect the
Apaches while they are on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Geneva, the UN Commission on Human Rights denounced ``war
crimes'' by Serb forces in Kosovo. Harold Hongju Koh, a US
assistant secretary of state, accused Milosevic of having
``meticulously planned'' atrocities in Kosovo. Only Russia voted
against the resolution. NATO leaders Friday said they would seek a
UN Security Council resolution requiring the pullout of hostile
forces from Yugoslavia and the return of refugees under
international military supervision.
</P>
<P>
   _ While NATO leaders dismissed a peace overture from Milosevic
that was carried out of Yugoslavia by Russian envoy Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, officials acknowledged that it did show small
movement on Milosevic's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that over the next few days we'll have more contact
and we'll get more detail,'' said Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger, the
White House national security adviser. ``I'm not sure that the
Russians are asserting that this is a sufficient basis on which
this can end. It certainly doesn't look like that from our
perspective. But we encourage them to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, said NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO
will continue to operate from the air, where it enjoys
``mid-to-high altitude air superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic has shown a willingness to accept a high
level of damage,'' Clark said. But his forces are increasingly
``vulnerable to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark and a series of American, British, and allied officials
hammered home the same message throughout the day as NATO tried to
carry out two very different types of events _ managing a war and
conducting a celebratory weekend to mark its 50th anniversary. It
was essential, they said, that Milosevic meet all of NATO's
demands, which would mean he would pull all his forces out of
Kosovo and allow an international military force to police the
return of Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary general, Javier Solana, said once NATO
accomplished those aims it would implement a ``long-term strategy''
to stabilize southeastern Europe in cooperation with the European
Union and other governments.
</P>
<P>
   Solana pledged economic and security aid to Albania and
Macedonia, in particular. Sunday leaders of the seven countries
that are on the front-line of the Balkan conflict _ Bosnia,
Croatia, Albania, Macedonia, Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria _ will
meet with NATO leaders. Solana said the seven ``will be at this
point closer partners to the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Friday looked more like a ghost town than the
glittering site of the most powerful gathering of world leaders
since the funeral of President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents heeded the dire warnings of traffic gridlock and
stayed away from downtown. Some 90,000 federal workers and all
District of Columbia employees had been given a paid day off, and
public schools in Washington were closed as well.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear from the nearly deserted streets and empty
restaurants and shops on what normally would have been a
dress-down, eat-out Friday, that it wasn't only government
bureaucrats who had taken leave of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had de-emphasized the social aspects of the summit in
light of NATO's serious Kosovo business, and if not for the
extraordinarily large and visible security force and the sirens of
speeding motorcades, the big meeting might have been missed
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations in Lafayette Park and on the Mall near the
Washington Monument were low key, too. During a noontime rally
across from the White House, about 100 Albanian-Americans, many
waving or wrapped in the red, double-eagle Albanian flag, chanted
``Bomb, NATO, bomb!'' and ``Send in the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Zherka, executive director of the National
Albanian-American Council, said his group supports the NATO air
campaign but fears Kosovo will be lost if the alliance doesn't also
launch a ground war and arm the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army soon.
</P>
<P>
   On the Mall, war protester Daniel Ellsberg, a prominent activist
against the Vietnam War in the the 1970s, told a small gathering
that NATO's bombing has made ``a human disaster into a
catastrophe.'' Instead of celebrating a success on its 50th
anniversary, NATO had created ``its own worst nightmare,'' Ellsberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday Serbian-American leaders hope to rally between 5,000
and 10,000 anti-NATO demonstrators to protest the bombing of
Yugoslavia, which is killing civilians and destroying the
republic's infrastructure, said Zoran Hodjera, president of the St.
Luke Serbian Church congregation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hodjera denied demonstrators would attempt to disrupt the NATO
meetings, an assertion made Wednesday by a NATO spokesman in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of security personnel were on hand Friday to ensure there
would be no disruptions. Law enforcement officers from every
jurisdiction _ the Park and Metropolitan Police, the Secret
Service, agents of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms,
and the Army _ kept a watchful eye on Friday's rallies and streets
around the summit meetings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mary Leonard of the Globe staff contributed to this report. Wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
