<SLUG> BC-TEN-OJAI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABRAMS STUNS TOP PAC-10 SEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Geoff Abrams finally got the coveted invitation.
The question now is, when will he leave the party?
</P>
<P>
   By the looks of things, not anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, a Stanford junior by way of Newport Harbor High, stunned
top-seeded Robert Kendrick of Washington on Friday 6-1, 6-4 to move
into the semifinals of the Pacific-10 men's singles championship at
the 99th annual Ojai Valley Tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was delayed twice Friday afternoon because of
rain. The first interruption came just before noon _ poor timing
for USC's Ditta Huber, who was up three match points in a
quarterfinal against Stanford's Gabriela Lastra. It took Huber
three minutes after the delay to close out the match 6-4, 6-2,
about 15 minutes before rain halted play again at 3:10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've experienced rain delays before but never at such a key
moment,'' said Huber, who is playing in her first Pac-10 singles
championship. Huber faces Teryn Ashley from Stanford in a semifinal
today at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has two men (Abrams and Ryan Wolters) and two women
(Ashley, along with Marissa Irvin of Harvard-Westlake) in the
semifinals, setting up a potential all-Cardinal final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, who is making his first appearance in the Pac-10 singles
tournament, will face Gustavo Marcaccio of Arizona State today at
11 a.m. Marcaccio defeated USC's Patrick Gottesleben 6-3, 6-3
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal, Wolters faces Arizona State's Jeff
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams has played at the Ojai since he was a junior and has
competed in the Pac-10 invitational the past two years. But this
year he finally earned his way into the Pac-10 men's tournament,
the most coveted draw of the Ojai.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to make the most of an opportunity like this,''
Abrams said. ``I've always wondered about playing in (the Pac-10
tournament) at Libbey Park in front of the big crowds. Over the
years I've always been at South Libbey, so this is really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams' fast start, a consistent serve-and-volley game and
cutting down on mistakes were crucial to defeating Kendrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big. I didn't give him any free points and that
helped,'' said Abrams. ``I didn't really do anything special. I
just played my game and played consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pac-10 women's singles, Stanford's Irvin advanced to the
semifinals with a 6-3, 6-4 win over Arizona State's Allison
Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was the ITA Player of the Month in February while winning
the Rolex National Indoor title, but had lost five of her past
seven matches in dual match play, slipping to third in the ITA
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back to Ojai, where she won the 14-under junior
championship in 1994 and the 16-under title in 1995, seems to have
straightened out her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season and it's tough to maintain (a high level)
of play sometimes,'' Irvin said. ``Even the pros go through a
mini-slump from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team won the Pac-10 team championship and that was great,
but this is an individual tournament so it's really easy to get up
for. Plus I love coming to Ojai, I've been playing it since I was a
little kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
