<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-VIETNAM-BOS &LR;      04-23 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING ALONE WON'T BREAK SERBS, MCNAMARA TELLS STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. Robert McNamara, the earnest technocrat whose
management of the Vietnam War incensed half a generation of
Americans in the '60s, and whose mea culpas alienated the other
half in the '90s, was again trying to make that war mean something
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This century will go down as the bloodiest in history. What
should we do today to prevent the carnage?'' the former Secretary
of Defense asked a group of Brown University students born years
after the last American soldier left Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the gathering, held with international relations
students studying the war, was to launch a new book by McNamara and
several other authors called ``Argument Without End: In Search of
Answers to the Vietnam Tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on discussions between civilian and military officials
from both sides of the war between 1995 and 1998, after months of
tense negotiations with Vietnamese authorities, the book argues
that the conflict was marked by missed opportunities on both sides,
that each side failed utterly to understand the other, and that it
could have been ended, or scaled down a decade before its official
end.
</P>
<P>
   That came as no surprise to McNamara's critics _ including the
son of one of the most important figures of the Vietnam era, former
Pentagon official Daniel Ellsberg, whose leaking of the so-called
``Pentagon Papers'' unleashed a torrent of criticism of McNamara
and the war.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the official topic of Friday's discussion was the
conflict that defined a previous generation, two other themes hung
over the proceedings like low clouds: the current crisis in the
Balkans, which to some observers is eerily similar to the beginning
of the Vietnam war, with the potential to lead America into a
similar quagmire. Also in the air was a sense of McNamara's own
failings as both war strategist and apologist.
</P>
<P>
   McNamara said the new book, begun long before Slobodan Milosevic
set his sights on ethnic Albanians, has plenty to teach Americans
about Kosovo. Vietnam proved that bombing campaigns alone have
rarely been successful at breaking the will of the enemy, McNamara
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a Congressman called him Friday to ask his advice about
voting on military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For God's sake,'' he said he told the Congressman, ``Don't
vote on any alternative till you've examined (others), don't vote
till you have it all in writing. That's what we didn't do. That's
why we made mistakes in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times op-ed piece last week, he called for ``a
Pentagon Papers-like project ...so that historians will have the
adequate raw material to identify the missed opportunities on the
road to the Balkans War.''
</P>
<P>
   But while McNamara urged an open discussion on the Kosovo
conflict, he declined to become part of it. When pressed, he
refused to be more specific about what those missed opportunities
had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong for an ex-Secretary of Defense to focus on
the mistakes,'' he said. ``I don't want to advise the US president
on how to win a war publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   The McNamara who appeared at Brown Friday seemed very much like
the former Ford motor company chief who advised Presidents John F.
Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson on Vietnam between 1961 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He was dressed neatly, as ever, in gray suit and starched white
shirt, his hair combed back, his shoulders slightly hunched, his
large hands slicing arcs through the air to explain strategy, or
slamming the table to underline a message when that gravelly voice
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   But this McNamara was different from the '60s incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1995 memoir, ``In Retrospect'' he finally conceded that
he and other war officials had made decisions that were ``wrong,
terribly wrong,'' during the war.
</P>
<P>
   That brought a visceral reaction barely seen at any time since
the war's turbulent years.
</P>
<P>
   For those who had opposed the war, McNamara's apologies had come
too late. For those who had fought in Veitnam and believed the
rhetoric with which he and the presidents he served had justified
their actions, the memoir was considered a betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   But McNamara, 82 now, is still a forceful man. He dominated
discussion at a breakfast to break the ice with the students, and
at a class on the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why have another damn book on Vietnam?'' he asked at the
breakfast, one arm slung over the back of his chair. So that we can
learn from our mistakes there, was his own answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who found this book interesting?'' he asked the students, as a
way of opening the class, which was being televised by C-Span. All
of the students, taught by one of McNamara's co-authors, raised
their hands. ``Now who thinks Americans will find it interesting?''
he shot at them. To which all hands were raised again.
</P>
<P>
   The students were all respectful of McNamara, barely speaking
during the breakfast, wrapping their questions in praises for the
book during the class discussion, eagerly posing for a group shot
with him afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Such reverence has been rare for McNamara since he stepped down
as Secretary of State in 1968 (``To this day, I don't know if I
quit or I was fired,'' he said Friday). The consensus, one student
said, was that McNamara had come out and admitted his mistakes, and
that in any case, her generation was sufficiently removed from the
period to see it more objectively than their parents.
</P>
<P>
   That was not true for one participant however.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ellsberg, son of Daniel Ellsberg, wanted McNamara to
answer a question many have asked before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given your interest in missed opportunities,'' said
Ellsberg,``I'm curious why you didn't explore one opportunity.
Right before you left the defense department. . .had you told
Congress what you revealed 27 years later, and spoken frankly. . .
it seems like the next seven years of the war could have been
avoided. That's a missed opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   To which McNamara gave a reply he has given several times: he
had previously testified that bombing the Vietnamese had not been
effective, and Senator Strom Thrumond had called him ``a Communist
appeaser.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The record was clear as to my views, but it's important to
recognize that I was in a minority,'' McNamara said. Still, few of
his critics forgive McNamara for remaining loyal to Johnson, and
going quietly to head the World Bank in 1968 instead of speaking
out publicly against the war.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ellsberg, 21, was chagrined by that response.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously didn't tell the public what he knew, otherwise
`In Retrospect' wouldn't have been news,'' he said later. ``Why
didn't he decide to do what my dad did? My dad is very frustrated
that he didn't do it earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ellsberg, who is writing his own memoir, praises
McNamara for coming clean now, but is disturbed that McNamara has
rebuffed his many attempts to meet with him after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because he has to tell himself it was unthinkable
to do what I did, disloyal to him and to his president to go
against the will of the executive branch to tell the truth,'' said
Daniel Ellsberg in an interview Friday. ``If he thought otherwise,
he would have to face the fact that he didn't consider doing that
and he'd have to take responsibility for the deaths of Americans
and Vietnamese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
