<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-ART-900&AMP;A     04-23 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NATO, A GOLDEN JUBILEE AND A COUNCIL OF WAR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO marked its 50th anniversary Friday with
minimal retrospective self-congratulation, focusing soberly instead
on the critical challenge it faces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the flags of all 19 members of the alliance, in
the same gilded hall where the NATO treaty was signed on April 4,
1949, President Clinton said the alliance was engaged in the
Balkans because it ``will not have meaning in the 21st century if
it permits the slaughter of innocents on its doorstep.'' He pledged
that ``when we fight, we fight to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier Solana, the NATO secretary general, described the
creation of the organization as ``a visionary project'' that had
not only espoused the values of freedom and democracy but also
acted upon them. Fifty years later, he said, ``the founding fathers
of this alliance would be proud of what we have done and what we
are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of state or government from each member nation made a
brief speech before walking to a podium to sign the Washington
Declaration, a statement of NATO's vision for the next century. It
said more about aims than means, asserting that the alliance would
have to confront terrorism and weapons of mass destruction while
continuing to provide for collective defense.
</P>
<P>
   A band played martial airs, but the mood was subdued, almost
flat, a little like a family reunion marred by the illness of a
much-loved relative. Despite assurances from allied military
leaders that ``we are winning'' in Kosovo, none of the presidents
or prime ministers could be sure when or how the conflict would end
and whether the Kosovo Albanians could reclaim their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the funeral of John F. Kennedy in 1963 have so many
leaders from so many countries assembled in Washington. In addition
to senior officials of NATO itself and its member nations, leaders
of more than 20 nations that have established partnerships with
NATO came to the capital. Only Russia and Belarus stayed away, to
protest the bombing of Serbia, their Slavic cousin.
</P>
<P>
   The city's streets were swept almost clear of traffic as
workers, fearful of security-induced snarls, stayed home or took
the subway. Helicopters and snipers augmented the usual security
forces around the Mellon Auditorium on Constitution Avenue _ a
magnificent space, six stories high, with enormous stone columns
along both sides. Known as the Departmental Auditorium in 1949, it
was renamed in 1995 to honor Andrew Mellon, the industrialist and
art collector who served as secretary of the treasury from 1921 to
1932.
</P>
<P>
   A swirl of activities filled the leaders' day. They began with a
three-hour meeting on Kosovo, a council of war at the outset of a
summit meeting celebrating NATO's keeping of the peace. They moved
on to the commemoration, then to Capitol Hill for a congressional
ceremony and finally to the White House for a dinner in the
glittering East Room. The male guests wore business suits, not
dinner jackets, lest anyone should use the word ``gala,'' which was
deemed inappropriate while allied pilots were at risk over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, things were going badly for the allies. Britain was
just ending rationing of clothing. Mao was winning in China. The
Communists were on the march in Europe, too, seizing power in
Czechoslovakia, threatening Italy and blockading Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   But at the NATO signing ceremony, President Harry Truman
remained resolute. He said this: ``For us, war is not inevitable.
We do not believe that there are blind tides of history which sweep
men one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   That same year, as Clinton recalled, William Faulkner, the great
American novelist, acknowledged the fear of nuclear annihilation
that then gripped much of the world. But he declared in his Nobel
Prize acceptance speech that ``humanity will not merely endure, it
will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Having broken ``the grip of the Cold War,'' Clinton said, NATO
is now confronted with ``the awful specter of ethnic cleansing in
southeast Europe.'' But he sounded as determined as his Democratic
predecessor half a century ago, promising that ``the last European
dictatorship of the 20th century'' _ that of President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia _ ``will not destroy Europe's long-awaited
chance to live at last together in peace and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the leaders of the three newest NATO members _ Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic _ who sounded fiercest in their
commitment to NATO. Once part of the Soviet bloc that NATO came
into being to resist, they were formally admitted to membership at
a ceremony in Independence, Mo., last month.
</P>
<P>
   President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic, a distinguished
playwright, said he spoke as a Czech, a European and ``an
inhabitant of this planet'' when he declared that ``peace among the
peoples'' could ``hardly be attained without the readiness to
defend it against the forces of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO membership marked the end of 300 years of war, partition
and misfortune for Poland, its President, Aleksander Kwasniewski,
remarked in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In the name of liberty, the very best of our people
went under fire, onto scaffolds, or were forced into exile,
generation after generation. Today this tragic tradition is but a
memento for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   President Jose Maria Aznar of Spain remarked that ``rarely does
an alliance celebrate its 50th anniversary.'' NATO had lasted
because it stayed unified, he said, and he and others emphasized
that it remained unified on Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Offstage, however, there were signs of tension between the
hawkish northern Europeans, especially Britain and France, and the
Mediterranean nations.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, who noted that his father
had fought in World War II, sounded a note of inflexibility,
telling his colleagues: ``We cannot, and we will not, stand by and
let this hideous policy of ethnic cleansing succeed. Defeating it
and reversing it is the best anniversary memorial NATO could
have.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greek Prime Minister Costas Smitis warned in an informal
comment Friday morning that prolonged bombing of Yugoslavia could
turn his country against NATO and the United States. The longer the
war, he added, ``the more difficult the problems will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini called NATO's bombing of
Serbian state television ``a terrible act.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, one of NATO's longtime champions, Sen. Richard
Lugar, R-Ind., advocated keeping the door open for further
expansion, an idea not all the members accept, and called for
``rough parity'' between U.S. and European forces in future NATO
enterprises _ another controversial proposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
