<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-INTEREST-2TA     04-23 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-INTEREST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAND STRATEGY: ROUND AND ROUND ON AMERICAN INTERESTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ill., Mass.)   (rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American involvement in Kosovo has started the most furious
debate since the end of the Cold War over what constitutes U.S.
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Persian Gulf War in 1991 have foreign policy
analysts filled the nation's airwaves, newspapers and policy
journals with such passion. ``The Kosovo crisis has sharpened and
intensified what was a largely theoretical debate within think
tanks and seminar rooms,'' said John J. Mearsheimer, a professor of
political science at the University of Chicago. ``The $64,000
question is what areas of the world and causes are worth Americans
fighting and dying for?''
</P>
<P>
   Experts call it ``grand strategy.'' During the Cold War,
containment was the grand strategy; American policy was based on
fighting any expansion of Communism. Yet almost a decade after the
collapse of the Soviet Union, there is still no consensus over how
this new world should be structured and what role the United States
should play in it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kosovo crisis does nothing else, Mearsheimer and others
agree, its resolution will affect whose ideas about U.S. national
interests will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Kupchan, an associate professor at Georgetown
University, says the United States has essentially been ``running
on the fumes of Cold War thinking for nearly a decade, tinkering
and making adjustments in policies left over from that era.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet before strategists could figure out what should take the
place of containment, they first had to agree on what the post-Cold
War world was shaping up to look like.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Fukuyama first gained attention by declaring we had
reached the ``end of history.'' The American victory over Communism
would usher in an era of peaceful competition among existing and
aspiring democracies, he triumphally predicted. Events quickly
overtook his theory, however, prompting Fukuyama to backtrack on
his unbridled optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Samuel Huntington of Harvard University argued that
conflict was inevitable. The next century's fault lines would be
along ``civilizational'' or ethnic and cultural divides, pitting,
say, Christian Europe against the Muslim Middle East or the
Confucian East. Although Huntington says the Balkans illustrates
his thesis, others disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Kosovo shows,'' Mearsheimer says, ``the world is not
divided into civilizations. In Kosovo the Christian West is
battling Orthodox Christian Serbs on behalf of Muslim Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the ``globalizationists'' or ``mercantilists'' came along,
people like Jeffrey E. Garten, dean of the Yale School of
Management, who argued that national sovereignty is inevitably _
and happily _ eroded by global economic forces. Ideology is dead.
Long live free markets.
</P>
<P>
   Such grand visions of the world are a starting point, but as
Kupchan explains, ``they do not give much direction to American
grand strategy or foreign policy.'' It took the crisis in Kosovo to
smoke out the new competing foreign policy camps, which can roughly
be divided into three groups.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the spectrum are the ``Fortress America''
advocates. Think of Pat Buchanan, the television pundit and repeat
presidential candidate, who basically says the United States should
not get caught up in other countries' messes, whether they're
military, economic or political.
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution, who worked in President George Bush's
National Security Council, says the Fortress America contingent has
the advantage of being straightforward, relatively consistent and
minimalist. ``Neo-isolationists believe that the purpose of foreign
policy is to have as little of it as possible,'' he explained.
While tragic, this camp argues, the brutal effort to drive Albanian
Muslims from Kosovo is not an American problem.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end are the ``interventionists'' or
``hegemonists.'' Philip D. Zelikow, director of the Miller Center
of Public Affairs in Charlottesville, Va., and another Bush
administration veteran, however, prefers to call this camp
``expansive idealists.'' They can be either liberal or
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The interventionists have found common intellectual ground in
the idea that the United States is the only superpower left
standing and simply cannot avoid getting involved. The United
States has an obligation to do whatever it takes to create a world
where it dominates, the thinking goes. In this view, the United
States has a ``window of opportunity to shape the world in its
image,'' Fareed Zakaria, the managing editor of Foreign Affairs
magazine and a skeptic of this approach, explains.
</P>
<P>
   Interventionists on the right include Robert Kagan and William
Kristol, whose prescription for victory in the Balkan war in a
recent issue of The Weekly Standard is to ``liberate Kosovo and
drive Milosevic from power,'' using ground forces and whatever else
to ``win it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Defeat or even the perception of defeat must be avoided at all
costs. ``At stake is the single overriding question of our time,''
they write. ``Will the United States and its allies have the will
to shape the world in conformance with our interests and our
principles? Or will we allow much of the world to slip into chaos
and brutality, to be shaped by men like Milosevic and Saddam
Hussein ... and the dictators in Beijing?''
</P>
<P>
   A similar definition of national interest in the Kosovo conflict
comes from liberal or ``humanitarian interventionists,'' who argue
that preventing and stopping genocide, ``ethnic cleansing'' and
other gross violations of human rights are in the strategic
interests of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humanitarian intervention is a more important challenge than
our interventions in Korea or Iraq,'' argues Leslie Gelb, president
of the Council on Foreign Relations, ``in that it goes to the very
heart of who we are and what we think our role in the world is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's foreign policy is liberal interventionist,
many analysts on the right and left agree. He has also been intent
on obtaining cooperation and consent for American policy from the
allies. ``This administration is very Bolshevik in its use of
force,'' said Mearsheimer, in an unusual choice of words. ``Air
power is their favorite tool and they haven't been reluctant to use
it. They've bombed four separate countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Kupchan, a more liberal analyst, concurs: ``The administration
has been incredibly lucky in its interventionism until now. There
have been American troops everywhere, but except for Somalia, no
Americans have died. Clearly that can't last.'' He and other
experts say that Kosovo, particularly the decision on whether to
send in NATO ground forces, will test liberal interventionism.
``Until now,'' says Kupchan, ``we've had liberal interventionism on
the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, like Charles Krauthammer, a conservative
columnist, say liberal interventionism will fail the test. In a
recent essay in The New Republic, he denounced President Clinton's
foreign policy as ``hopelessly utopian.''
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping or mending civil wars is not the job for a
superpower, he writes. ``It is a job for Canada.'' Forget about
multilateral agreements and consensus. A superpower should concern
itself with ``real'' threats, like the aggressive conduct of North
Korea, and not worry about what other nations think. In an
interview he called liberal interventionism ``dangerously ill
conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   Krauthammer calls himself a realist; it is a label that the
majority of foreign policy experts in this third camp are probably
most fond of using (although Mearsheimer prefers to say that his
group favors ``offshore balancing,'' intervening to prevent the
emergence of potential competitors). ``Most realists are offshore
balancers,'' Mearsheimer says. ``And most of us do not see any such
threat emerging as a result of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Haass, whose book, ``Reluctant Sheriff,'' reflects and promotes
``realist'' foreign policy thinking, argues that the American role
is the ``regulation of great power relations,'' that is, to work
out ``rules of the road with other major power centers.'' Building
alliances that promote free trade, discourage the use of force and
limit the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction all advance
American strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kosovo, Haass and other realists tend to be cautious. And
they often disagree over whether strategic national interests are
at stake. Do American interests justify ``such a commitment in
blood and treasure''? he recently wrote. The United States must
``balance humane impulses with strategic imperatives.'' Liberating
all of Kosovo with military force ``is not worth the costs it would
entail.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet as Kosovo illustrates, defining an American grand strategy
or the country's national interest is not necessarily
straightforward even if one has a clear notion of how the world
should be organized. Regardless of whether Kosovo is worth fighting
for, by getting involved, the United States has created a strategic
interest there even if one didn't exist before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once America stakes its credibility on an issue, it
automatically becomes strategic,'' Zakaria says. Even those
``realists'' who disapproved of American involvement in the war
against Yugoslavia concede that having made the commitment, the
United States must pursue victory with all possible means,
including ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not all self-described realists agree. Henry
Kissinger, who presided over the Vietnam War, which cost 50,000
American lives, argues against ``the proliferation of open-ended
American commitments involving the deployment of U.S. forces.'' He
draws the line on sending American ground troops to Kosovo; the
Europeans should provide the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Until there is more of a consensus over how the United States
should respond in this changing world, it may be that the U.S.
grand strategy can best be described as muddling through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
