<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW CONSUMER PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Paradox Of Corporate Spydom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a conundrum worthy of an Ian Fleming novel: Corporate
spies are becoming more and less numerous (italics)at the same
time.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A survey of about 50 large corporations by Fuld &AMP; Co., a
consulting firm based in Cambridge, Mass., found that 20 percent of
responding companies had shut down their corporate intelligence
departments, at a time when membership in a trade group, the
Society of Competitive Intelligence Professionals, is reported to
be growing by 25 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Fuld found that corporate intelligence departments are often a
casualty of a management shake-up, wiped out after the lone top
executive who championed it leaves the company. Others fail
``because they do not establish plans or practical approaches to
delivering value to the company,'' Leonard M. Fuld, the firm's
founder, said in announcing the results.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, to square the findings of fewer spy shops but more
spies? No clear answer emerged in the survey results, but
suspense-novel fans will have no trouble dreaming up scenarios.
Maybe those companies only want us to (italics)think(end italics)
that they shut down their intelligence departments. ... &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
