<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSWEEPS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV sweeps `Noah' in, `Nanny' out of lineup
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998-'99 television season is one month away from the
history books, but before it ends, the networks will indulge in a
little history themselves. Big, lavish movies about legends are on
tap for the May sweeps period Thursday through May 26:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  First up is ``Noah's Ark'' (May 2-3 on NBC) with Jon Voight as
Noah and Mary Steenburgen as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ABC is touting its four-hour ``Cleopatra'' May 23-24. Leonor
Varela (``The Man in the Iron Mask'') plays the Egyptian queen,
with Timothy Dalton as Julius Caesar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rising teen star Leelee Sobieski (``Deep Impact'') stars as
``Joan of Arc'' for CBS May 16-18. The supporting cast includes
Peter O'Toole, Maximilian Schell and Jacqueline Bisset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra'' and ``Noah's Ark'' are from Robert Halmi Sr., the
producer who recently won a Peabody Award for his spectacles such
as ``Gulliver's Travels'' and ``Merlin.''
</P>
<P>
   History of another sort will be recognized as four series have
big finale episodes, some with clips reprising their pasts. There's
no ``Seinfeld'' bidding adieu to generate national hysteria, but
those achieving closure (as opposed to just getting canceled like
most shows) are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Home Improvement'' (8 p.m. May 25). Tim Allen's family
stalwart gets a 90-minute sendoff on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Melrose Place'' (8 p.m. May 24). Once one of the hottest
shows on TV, now room temperature. Fox is keeping details under
wraps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mad About You'' (8 p.m. May 24, NBC). It, too, has faded
from its peak, but still gets an hour, with Janeane Garofalo
somehow playing Paul and Jamie's baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Nanny'' (8 p.m. May 19, CBS) wraps its six-year run with
Fran (Fran Drescher) preparing to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   During sweeps periods in February, May, July and November,
Nielsen measures the demographics (age, gender, etc.) of local TV
stations to set ad rates. The networks say they're sick of the
scheduling headaches but keep piling up the specials to please
their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   ABC takes a cheaper route, though, in an unusual move,
double-airing three theatrical films: ``The Rock,'' with Nicolas
Cage; ``Phenomenon,'' with John Travolta; and ``Father of the Bride
II'' each get two prime time slots.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Robbie Knievel: Grand Canyon Jump Live!'' (8 p.m. Thursday
on Fox). Note the exclamation point, to make it more exciting!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Double Platinum'' (9 p.m. May 16 on ABC) pairs Brandy and
Diana Ross in a drama about a singing mother and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman: The Movie'' (9 p.m. May 22 on
CBS). After canceling the series and infuriating fans, CBS makes
nice with a one-shot reprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeps is not all mind candy, though. CNN kicks off its 10-part
``Celebrate the Century'' retrospective May 2, and PBS'
``Masterpiece Theatre'' does ``Great Expectations'' May 9-10.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy it while it lasts. Come May 27, the networks head off for
a rerun-loaded summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
