<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIENELSON1STTAKE25     04-23 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 NELSON1STTAKE25-COX &HT;    Willie Nelson, a natural, a performer who connects with
heartland
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 25.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La. _ Everybody doesn't like something, but nobody
doesn't like Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Not here. Not tonight. Not even with tornadoes ripping up the
northwest Louisiana countryside all day long. It's a Saturday night
in Shreveport, for God's sake, and for the first time in nearly 40
years, the Louisiana Hayride has reconvened at the newly renovated
Municipal Auditorium, with none other than Willie Nelson himself
headlining the all-star roster.
</P>
<P>
   Before the night is done, Willie will be leading the whole gang
in a gospel sing-along. Kenny Wayne Shepherd, the hometown blues
guitarist made good, ragin' Cajun Doug Kershaw, Hank Williams'
long-lost daughter, Jett, four stately gentlemen known as the
Everready Gospel Quartet, a whole slew of silver-haired fiddlers
and guitarists in their fresh-pressed suits, bolo ties and
suspenders, all singing ``I Saw the Light.''
</P>
<P>
   There'll be time later for the garish neon temptations of the
riverboat casinos that have sparked this depressed, historic border
town back to economic life. This is a reminder of what gave the
city life to start with, back before Nashville came to music
industry prominence, back when regional radio and independent
record labels and endless tours of little nowhere towns were the
key to a country music career. Back when the Hayride was its own
kind of Opry, back when Elvis and Williams got their start, right
up on that very stage. Back when singers like Nelson, 65, were
barely out of the box, too young, in those dark and early years,
even to be legends in their own minds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, Nelson's legend is such that he doesn't even
have to be in the building to cast a spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like Jesus,'' says Karen Jordan, a youthful ``just
say I'm over 40'' fan. ``I mean, it's funky.''
</P>
<P>
   She's standing in the lobby near a display of T-shirts bearing
Nelson's suspiciously Messianic likeness. Though she prefers
Shepherd, the evening's other big name, to anything remotely like
'90s country music, she digs Willie. Big time. ``Who doesn't like
him? He's just like America. How could you not like him?''
</P>
<P>
   Something for everyone
</P>
<P>
   Just like America. That's a juicy thought. Nelson, who performs
Friday (his 66th birthday) in a headlining slot at Music Midtown,
Atlanta's annual three-day music event, is sure enough emblem-atic.
The ponytailed
songwriter-turned-singer-turned-star-turned-actor-turned-icon is,
in so many ways, a little of something for everyone: a one-man
democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Want your counterculture hero? There's Willie, an unrepentant
marijuana smoker, rolling up a fat one during a visit to the Carter
White House. Want your heartland populist? There's Willie,
organizing FarmAid and headlining those annual benefit concerts to
help the imperiled family farmer. Want your old-fashioned good
time? There's Willie, bandanna around his head, dressed in his
everlasting bluejeans, T-shirt and sneakers, leading his band
through a set of hits _ from the opening ``Whiskey River'' to the
send-off anthem, ``On the Road Again'' _ he's been playing 200
nights a year for as long as his tour bus has been rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Want your avant-garde Daddy-O? There's Willie, cutting
brilliantly austere records like ``Spirit'' and last year's
stunning ``Teatro'' that pare his art to an essence rare for a
performer who has nothing left to prove.
</P>
<P>
   But in that way, the native Texan is like some other pure
American geniuses, like the Louis Armstrongs and Frank Sinatras,
who, in doing it their way, embody and reflect all the good things
the republic can be. They can be popular and progressive, showman
and aesthete, wild card and poet, cowboy and Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Modernized country
</P>
<P>
   ``For so many reasons, he's a key transitional figure in country
music,'' says Paul Kingsbury, editor of the Country Music Hall of
Fame's ``Encyclopedia of Country Music,'' offering a semi-official
spin on Nelson's place in the cosmos. ``He's a songwriter who
excelled in the `Nashville Sound' era. He modernized country music
working with people like Waylon Jennings in the `outlaw' years. And
in the late '70s and early '80s he reached beyond the confines of
country music to find a broader audience with albums like
`Stardust.' And he's still creating great cutting-edge country
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all the respect Nelson gets from Nashville, he could
never make it there as a solo artist. This, the man who wrote
``Crazy'' for Patsy Cline, ``Hello Walls'' for Faron Young and
``Night Life'' for Ray Price. It wasn't until he left Music City,
not coincidentally after his house burned down, that he came into
his own in the mid-1970s. As Kingsbury notes, Nelson was too
original for his time. ``Willie had a unique way of phrasing,'' he
says. ``The rhythm he set up with his singing was offbeat for
country music and kind of jazzy. Also, he was not a matinee idol.
Country caught up with his style in the '70s, and Willie came into
his own as a handsome icon when he became scruffier in the '70s.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing with the master
</P>
<P>
   After the show in Shreveport, Willie's fans cling to the
auditorium's backstage gate, shouting his name in hopes of
receiving a handshake or an autograph. He complies, then disappears
inside his tour bus, a countryfied Biosphere and a Mecca-on-wheels
for the singer's hard-core fan base.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie talks, he's relaxed, with an easy, generous laugh,
the laugh of a Zen master who can't remember his golf handicap, or,
at least, prefers to keep it one of life's profound mysteries. ``I
lie too much,'' he says. ``Whatever I told you would be wrong.'' So
he answers questions about some other aspects of his life and
career.
</P>
<P>
   Q:When did you begin writing songs?
</P>
<P>
   A:I started writing poems before I could play the guitar, and
after I learned a few chords, well, then I started putting melodies
to the poems. So that was when I was 5 years old. It was just kind
of all there. It always was. I always knew I could make a rhyme and
write songs. And I thought everybody could. It really took awhile
to get started as a songwriter because there's a whole lot of good
songwriters out there.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I'm really impressed with your latest albums, that you're
taking chances and experimenting with things at this point in your
career. ``Spirit,'' for instance, was so minimal . . .
</P>
<P>
   A:Barren, I believe . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q:Yeah, that's right. What motivates you?
</P>
<P>
   A:I just wanted to do it. I guess I don't really have any smart
reasons. Whenever I have enough songs to go into the studio to
record then I have to decide how I want to do it. I never have any
really preconceived ideas. I knew I wanted to do the ``Spirit''
album the way it was done, with very few instruments. With
``Teatro,'' I turned it over to (producer) Daniel Lanois, and let
him do whatever he wanted to do. I had a lot of songs that I gave
to him, like 100 songs of mine, new and old. He picked 20 and then
we went in and did 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
