<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-LIGHT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grandstand '99 celebrates food and fitness
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Terri Evans of Atlanta isn't shy about cooking in
front of folks. ``But usually it's in my kitchen and I have a glass
of wine,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Evans will prepare her Banana Split Pie in front of many
more than can fit in her kitchen. She'll be on a stage at Turner
Field as part of Cooking Light magazine's Grandstand '99: A
Festival for the New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It's a two-day expo of the latest culinary and fitness trends,
complete with cooking classes taught by chefs from Atlanta and
across the country; seminars on kitchen remodeling; and fitness
activities such as a dribbling clinic and swing dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is one of 10 national finalists in a recipe contest
sponsored by Healthy Choice. They'll compete throughout the event
in a cook-off to determine who will win $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to create recipes, but this is a lark. I've never
entered a contest before,'' said Evans, 45. ``I just thought,
`Wouldn't it be nice to win $10,000 doing something I love?'''
</P>
<P>
   The festival is a first of its kind for the magazine, though the
idea took root two years ago, when Cooking Light celebrated its
10th anniversary with a street festival in its hometown of
Birmingham. The event drew more than 15,000, including readers from
across the country, South America and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking Light has gone from a style of cooking to a style of
living,'' said editor Doug Crichton. ``Our readers tell us they
have more energy and fun when they eat right and exercise. We make
that enjoyable and accessible. And that seems to be the big
spark.''
</P>
<P>
   That big spark has made Cooking Light the No. 1 magazine for
food and fitness in the nation, with an estimated 6 million
readers.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine has branched out to offer special cruises for
readers, and Crichton said the Atlanta festival could be a model
for future festivals in other cities. The event will be from 9:30
a.m to 6 p.m. today and noon to 6 p.m. Sunday. Admission is $5.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
