<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLEN22-COX     04-23 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLEN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: A calculating threesome spends time assessing
the pesky airborne grains that cause so much misery
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every morning by 5:10, Atlanta's pollen patrol peers through a
microscope at hundreds of pink circular blobs. Then they sort and
count: one pine, two pine, three pine; one oak, two oak; one ash;
one sweet gum.
</P>
<P>
   How those numbers add up will make or break the day for hundreds
of thousands of allergy sufferers in the Atlanta area. The numbers
represent how thick with tree, grass and weed pollen our local air
is.
</P>
<P>
   LaWanda Day, Marie McFalls and Pam Griggs are the pollen
counters for the Atlanta Asthma &AMP; Allergy Clinic, which posts the
information daily on its pollen hotline. While this is the only
official pollen collection site in metro Atlanta, the readings
represent pollen concentrations from Cartersville to Covington.
</P>
<P>
   The more blobs on the slender glass rod under the microscope,
the higher the pollen count. Each pink spot represents a particular
pollen from a tree, grass or weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one that resembles Mickey Mouse ears is pine,'' Day
explained, peering into the 40-power microscope. ``We have to come
up with descriptions we can easily remember. Cedar is like a circle
with a star in the middle of it. Elm we think of as having a circle
within a circle.''
</P>
<P>
   When the pollen numbers soar to record levels, as they did this
month, the job becomes even more tedious for Day, McFalls and
Griggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems I spent five hours last Monday counting it, and I
started at 4:30 that morning,'' said McFalls. On that day, April
12, Atlanta set a new record: 6,013 grains of pollen per cubic
meter of air. It was the second-highest sneeze reading in the
country that day, behind Tulsa, Okla., with a count of 6,299.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, Atlanta's pollen level had fallen to 1,286, still
10 times the amount considered ``extremely high'': 120 or above.
And that spells misery for many of the estimated 700,000 metro
Atlantans with pollen allergies of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I was shocked at how high it was,'' said McFalls of the
record-breaking day. ``But I had been doing yardwork the previous
day, and you could feel the pollen on your skin. And the air was
hazy from the pollen.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta doctors say they've never seen so many patients cram
their waiting rooms hoping for relief from the tidal wave of
allergy symptoms. And residents swear there's never before been
such a thick yellow coat of pine trees' fertilizing dust on their
cars, patio furniture, windowsills and driveways. The yellow stuff
was even blamed for causing an 18-vehicle pileup on I-285 when it
mixed with rain and oil to form goo earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   When pollen counts climb into the thousands, people who usually
suffer mild symptoms experience the irritation of severe sufferers.
And for those who become miserable when the count hovers at 50 to
100, breathing becomes a chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been unbelievable. I can't even breathe when I sleep,''
said Kay Bargamian of Snellville. ``I have to get up and walk
around and sit a while to clear my clogged nose. Sometimes I sleep
propped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bargamian keeps her windows closed, goes outside only for short
periods and seeks relief from prescription nasal spray. ``I stay
inside,'' she declared. ``That's the price we pay for living in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Many assume that because the city is in the midst of a
bulldozing frenzy, the pollen count should decline as trees are
chopped down. According to NASA satellite data analyzed by
University of Georgia researchers, metro Atlanta is losing 50 acres
of tree cover every day to make way for new roads, residential
subdivisions, shopping malls and office parks.
</P>
<P>
   But the area's burgeoning growth doesn't really affect the
pollen count all that much, said Dr. Bob Berkowitz, research
director for the Atlanta Asthma &AMP; Allergy Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know pollen travels hundreds of miles, from sailors being
affected while out on ships,'' he said. ``Even if we blacktopped
all of Georgia, we would still get Alabama pollen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Marietta clinic, pollen is collected in a wooden box on a
second-story roof. Inside the box is a slender, inch-long glass
spindle nestled inside a narrow metal holder.
</P>
<P>
   One side of the tube is covered with silicone grease, to which
pollen particles stick. After the sample is collected every
morning, another tube is inserted and the box is put back into
place on the roof. To get an accurate reading, the collector must
spin for 30 seconds every 10 minutes, or 72 minutes out of every 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spinning time can be critical during peak season,''
McFalls said. ``It must be carefully timed for accurate sampling.''
</P>
<P>
   After a day and night of exposure to the air, the spindle is
covered with a dusty fuzz. To identify the pollen under a micro-
</P>
<P>
   scope, the glassware is streaked with a pink stain that picks up
the proteins of each distinct pollen grain. The count begins from
one end of the dle and ends at the other. After one-third of the
surface is counted, a mathematical formula tabulates the total
count.
</P>
<P>
   Then, promptly at 6 a.m. the magic number is called into 35
radio, television and newspapers. ``If we're even a few minutes
late, they call us, '' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Allergy &AMP; Asthma Clinic has provided pollen counts
since 1987. It began as a way to satisfy the curiosity of allergy
doctors, then turned into a public service. On many spring and fall
days, area residents ruminate over it with as much angst as daily
lottery numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The counts are only taken in spring and fall when pollinating
trees, plants and weeds make life miserable for many area
residents. Many depend on allergy shots to lessen their symptoms.
The shot serum is prepared by extract technicians such as Day,
McFalls, and Griggs, who mix allergy potions when not tabulating
populating pollen. This year's count began early on March 1, and
will end in June. Weed counts start Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Come rain or shine, the pollen patrol must report before sunup.
The only time they missed a day in recent memory was last April 9
when a tornado set down in Cobb County. That day's reading was
chalked up to ``mechanical failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind-blown pollen is how trees spread their male seed but the
pollen counters say they don't think about their livelihood in
terms of nature, science or propagation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't joke about it or anything like that,'' Day said.
``We pretty much take it serious. Atlanta takes the pollen very,
very seriously. This is something that to many people is vital that
they know.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sneezing and sniffling this spring, Atlantans
seem to have only two concerns: Why's it so bad? And when will the
numbers go down and stay down? ``All of this relates to the large
amount of rainfall throughout 1998,'' said Berkowitz. ``The yearly
rainfall gave the trees the high energy of a teenager when
pollinating. With that energy, and with the unusually high
temperatures of this winter, everything pollinated at the same
time. That's why we had such a high pollen count.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the warm, dry weather pattern of this winter
tricked many trees into pollinating earlier than usual. The result?
Twenty tree types budding at once.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful. And miserable. The good news, the allergy experts
say, is that trees are nearing their end of their high season and
giving way to grasses that cause fewer allergic reactions. ``The
peak is over,'' declared McFalls who has 13 years' experience on
pollen patrol. ``The trees are leafing and turning green.''
</P>
<P>
   But for at least another couple weeks, the pink blotches will be
focus of the dawn ritual for McFalls, Day or Grimes: Squint through
the scope, recite and write down: One pine, two pine, three pine,
four. One oak, two oak, three oak, four. None of Atlanta's pollen
counters, by the way, have allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Said Day: ``I was blessed, I guess. ''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Allergy &AMP; Asthma Clinic pollen hotline: 770-662-6100.
</P>
<P>
   website: www.atlallergy.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Tree Pollen Counts on April 12, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: 6,013
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh: 35
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C.: 96
</P>
<P>
   Miami: 10
</P>
<P>
   Fort Smith, AR. : 1,867
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, Okla.: 6,299
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi, Texas: 1
</P>
<P>
   Denver: 210
</P>
<P>
   Los Angles: 24
</P>
<P>
   Tucson: 30
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa holds highest pollen count ever recorded in nation: 14,000
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Highest pollen count ever recorded in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rain washes pollen out of air. Reading below 1 is rounded up.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Academy of Allergy, Asthma &AMP; Immunology
</P>
<P>
   WEED POLLEN
</P>
<P>
   (x 4000): Weeds, such as ragweed (Ambrosia), cause lots of
allergy misery. Just one ragweed plant can produce 1 billion pollen
grains. Rag-
</P>
<P>
   weed is prevalent from mid-July through the first deep frost.
</P>
<P>
   TREE POLLEN
</P>
<P>
   (x 3600): Many tree pollens, such as oak (Quercus), tend to
pollinate from February through May, causing allergy problems for
people in the Northeast, Southeast, South-
</P>
<P>
   west and along the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   GRASS POLLEN (Poaceae, x 1600): Grasses make up about 20 percent
of the earth's vegeta-
</P>
<P>
   tional cover. There are more than 1,200 species native to North
America; they are the primary cause of allergies from May through
October.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
