<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIENELSON2NDTAKE25     04-23 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIE </SLUG>
 NELSON2NDTAKE25-COX
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La.: in and did 15.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Were you surprised by his choices?
</P>
<P>
   A:Some of them. I was surprised that he picked out ``I Can't Let
You Say Goodbye.'' You got to watch that guy.
</P>
<P>
   Q:There are a few pretty cold songs on there, but that one _
about a man who strangles his girlfriend _ is the coldest.
</P>
<P>
   A:(Laughs.) I tried to talk him out of it. Maybe there was some
personal reason he wanted it in there. He might have been sending a
message. (Laughs again.)
</P>
<P>
   Q:I think a lot of people, when they think of your music, would
say it was romantically inspiring, with a sweetness, a soulfulness.
And yet, there are songs like ``I Never Cared for You,'' ``I Just
Destroyed the World,'' that have a piercing, bitter or despairing
imagery. What sort of things motivate you to write those?
</P>
<P>
   A:Again, each one has its own origin. Maybe some of them have no
origin at all.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The ones that verge on catastrophe and tragedy?
</P>
<P>
   A:Darkness on the face of the world . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q:Those have such a wallop to them, yet you never overplay it.
You let the words hang in the air. What do you think of your voice?
Do you like it?
</P>
<P>
   A:Sometimes I do. Sometimes I can actually endure it. But I hear
me a whole lot. I know when I'm not doing it right and when I think
I am.
</P>
<P>
   Q:In your life, you've become a counterculture icon on the one
hand and then kind of, with FarmAid, very much someone that people
see as a populist figure. And then you're at the Kennedy Center
getting a medal pinned on you . . .
</P>
<P>
   A:I've got somebody fooled, don't I?'' (He laughs.)
</P>
<P>
   Q:That's pretty clever. But how do you really feel about it?
</P>
<P>
   A:Naturally, I eat it up. I love it. Don't quite understand it
all, but I don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I notice how, looking over your biography, that when your
house burned down, it was time to leave Nashville, and you had your
first great success as a solo artist. Then the Internel Revenue
Service comes in (seeking $16 million-plus in back taxes), and your
career takes another interesting turn. It seems like you weather
all the ups and downs pretty well. What guides you?
</P>
<P>
   A:(Laughs.) Fortunately, we're not in control. That's the only
thing we go by out here. We know that we're not running the show,
so it doesn't matter. The why, or nothing. Don't ask no questions,
that's where I think we're all coming from. Everything's working
too good to start asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   Follow him anywhere
</P>
<P>
   After Shreveport, Willie heads for New York and the taping of a
TNT television tribute to his pal Johnny Cash. He'll join Sheryl
Crow for a version of ``Jackson'' as the cameras roll. Life is
good.
</P>
<P>
   Or as one of Willie's fans, crammed backstage before his
entrance in Shreveport, puts it: ``He's the guy who'd been around
for so long and all of that time he'd been there, nobody paid any
attention to him, and all of a sudden this song hits and you follow
him forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The song that Claudia Mayence, a 40ish civil employee in
Shreveport, refers to is ``Blue Eyes Cryin' in the Rain.'' But she
could mean almost any Willie song, at almost any time, because his
songs are like that. Because he's like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is,'' she exclaims, proud in a cardigan whose red, white
and blue beads are sewn in the image of Texas, her native state,
``a natural man.''
</P>
<P>
   WILD ABOUT WILLIE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: April 30, 1933 in Abbott, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Raised by his grandparents. Married to Ann-Marie
D'Angleo since 1991. They have two children; five other children
from three previous marriages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Odd jobs: Worked in cotton fields until he was 10, then played
guitar in local German and Czech polka bands. Also sold Bibles and
encyclopedias door-to-door, worked as disc jockey and musician and
taught Sunday School.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: A stint in the Air Force; attended but did not
graduate from Baylor University.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  As a songwriter: Wrote ``Crazy'' for Patsy Cline, ``Hello
Walls'' for Faron Young, ``Night Life'' for Ray Price, ``Wake Me
When It's Over'' for Andy Williams and ``Pretty Paper'' for Roy
Orbison, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A few notable movie roles: ``The Electric Horseman'' (1979),
``Honeysuckle Rose'' (1980), ``Barbarosa'' (1982), ``Songwriter''
(1984) and ``Wag the Dog'' (1997). ``I need a horse or a guitar ...
or both is better,'' Nelson says. ``Everything else doesn't matter.
Whether's there's a plot or not. I never had to act. I wouldn't
take a role that I thought I had to act in. Slim Pickens, we did
'The Electric Horseman' together, and we got to be good buddies,
somebody asked him about my acting and he said: 'Well, he plays
Willie Nelson better than anyone I know.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Honors: Inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1993.
Earned Kennedy Center Honor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Selected discography: Nelson's career is summed up by the
title of his 1974 album ``Phases and Stages.'' He's been through
enough of them for several average humans, from his earliest days
as a songwriter in the 1950s and '60s _ anthologized on ``Nite
Life: Greatest Hits and Rare Tracks'' (1990) _ to such latter-day
excursions as ``Spirit'' (1996) and ``Teatro'' (1998), in which
artful arrangements strip classic material down to the pure
gestural power of the singer's autumnal baritone. And, of course,
there's the ``outlaw'' years, which include collaborations with
Waylon Jennings and the mainstream success of ``Wanted: The
Outlaws'' (1976; with Jennings, Jessi Colter and Tompall Glaser).
</P>
<P>
   Nelson rather brilliantly followed the hangdog charisma of that
project with 1978's ``Stardust.'' The glowing standards collection,
produced by Booker T. Jones, was what really made the singer a pop
star _ and ``Georgia on My Mind'' a new signature tune. The output
gets a little sketchier after this, until a sustained resurgence
that began, ironically, when he recorded a 1991 album (''Who Will
Buy My Memories'') which was sold on TV to pay millions in back
taxes. If you can find them, though, a series of duet albums (with
such greats as Ray Price, Webb Pierce, Faron Young and Hank Snow)
light up Nelson's early '80s catalog. Other titles to look for
include: ``To Lefty From Willie'' (1977), ``Me and Paul'' (1985)
and ``Across the Borderline'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Favorite songwriter: Hank Williams. ``He's my favorite singer,
too. I just thought there was none better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guitar influences:
</P>
<P>
   Legendary ``gypsy'' guitarist Django Reinhart and Mexican border
music. ``I grew up listening to a lot of the Mexican radio
stations.. I lived across the street from a couple of families of
Mexicans and they kept the radio going all the time, 24 hours a
day. I loved all of it. And then I heard Django Reinhart, and
thought there's a guy I want to hear more of. I was about 20 when I
first heard him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If he's not playing music he's probably: Golfing on Maui.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coming up: A new album of standards, and an instrumental blues
set.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Nelson and the Family
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Friday. Music Midtown (96rock stage). Festival site is
north of Centennial Olympic Park in downtown Atlanta. Tickets:
404-249-6400. Festival hotline: 404-643-8696.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Day-by-day and stage-by-stage lineups plus other
details about the three-day event.
</P>
<P>
   www.musicmidtown.com
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
