<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CARE24-COX     04-23 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CARE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faced with massive suffering, relief workers often wonder where
God is _ or if God is
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abby Maxman peered inside the sanctuary of a rural Catholic
church in East Africa near Lake Victoria and froze.
</P>
<P>
   Piles of rotting corpses, mostly women and children, were
scattered under the church's wooden pews. Some of the babies, still
clinging to their mothers, had machete wounds in their skulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was numb. My head was spinning,'' Maxman said. ``I wanted to
throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   The women had fled to the church for refuge, Maxman was told,
but the killers didn't care. They tossed grenades inside. Then, too
tired to continue, they slit the Achilles' tendons of the survivors
so they couldn't escape. They returned the next morning to finish
their butchering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, madame, this is Rwanda,'' said Maxman's guide, a
relative of one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Maxman, 33, was in Rwanda on that March morning in 1995 as a
part of CARE, the international relief agency based in Atlanta. She
was helping the country resettle returning refugees a year after
rampaging Hutus murdered at least 500,000 Tutsis in a genocidal
fury.
</P>
<P>
   She was taken to the church by relatives of the victims, to bear
witness to their suffering. Maxman called the morning one of the
most powerful moments in her life.
</P>
<P>
   It was the day she decided that God did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I desperately want to feel sure about,'' she
said. ``Sometimes I can become fatalistic and say things happen for
a reason. But I cannot think that in these kinds of settings
because they're too big, too painful, too monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is full of grim images. The latest come from the
Balkans, where photos of thousands of hungry and ill refugees
fleeing brutality in Kosovo have now become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Such images are hardly new, only the latest in a series of dark
snapshots in recent years that have included waxen corpses in
Rwanda, skeletal figures of famine victims in Sudan, dazed
survivors of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers see the worst that humans _ and Mother Nature _
offer. Some, like Maxman, say the experience has extinguished their
faith in God. Others say it has rekindled their faith. All,
however, say they have learned profound lessons about the human
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Robert MacPherson, an ex-Marine wounded in Vietnam and a member
of CARE's Emergency Group operations, has seen his share of
unforgettable images.
</P>
<P>
   He was part of an airlift operation in 1992 that ferried food to
starving refugees in Somalia. As his helicopter approached the
Somalian city of Baidoa, MacPherson, 53, said the sunbaked horizon
was filled with thousands of skeletal people.
</P>
<P>
   As the Somalians surged toward the descending helicopters,
MacPherson saw many of them collapse. Only gradually did he realize
what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the presence of the helicopters landing . . . people were
so malnourished that they died from the excitement,'' MacPherson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He's also learned that there are decent people everywhere _ even
in Kosovo, among groups labeled as evil.
</P>
<P>
   MacPherson spent last winter in the war-torn area, teaching
people about land mine safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I think the Serbs are completely bad and the others
are good people, I will come across some Serb family living in the
middle of Kosovo, scared to death,'' he said. ``They are farmers,
just like anybody else, who don't want their kids to die, just like
everybody else, and who are out of food, just like everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE workers cope with the demands of their jobs in various
ways. Many share common traits _ idealism, a sense of humor and
bravado.
</P>
<P>
   But organized religion doesn't seem to play a big part for most.
Many, like MacPherson, are not regular churchgoers. They find their
inspiration in people, not piety.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Giannone, who has been with CARE for three years, said he
discovered a surprising truth while working with impoverished
people in war-ravaged countries such as Vietnam, Sudan and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad people get all the publicity,'' he said, ``but there's
a lot more good people out there and that keeps me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding joy despite pain
</P>
<P>
   Giannone, 50, who directs CARE's emergency operations, said
people living in brutal surroundings know how to find joy, even in
the harshest of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen the children of war refugees playing with toys made
out of discarded war materials. He's driven through a desert with a
group of tough Iranian men who stopped just to marvel at a patch of
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   And the passionate faith he's encountered in his work has made
the Western practice of religion seem puny in comparison, Giannone
said.
</P>
<P>
   To explain this point, Giannone details an encounter he had in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   While visiting a rural village, he met a 28-year-old farmer who
had been abducted by rebels. They beat the man and threw acid into
his eyes, welding them shut.
</P>
<P>
   After talking to the farmer, Giannone drove away, turning to
look at the man one last time. The farmer was standing in a
courtyard, clutching a Bible he couldn't read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their faith becomes my faith,'' Giannone said. ``If they've
got the guts to go on, I've got the guts to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The harsh conditions CARE workers encounter often cause cultural
whiplash when they return home.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone gets excited when he shops for groceries. ``To go into
this huge place and buy any kind of meat or vegetable you want is
amazing to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Constant and prolonged travel also creates special problems.
Giannone said he's abroad about three to four months a year. Once,
when he put on his coat to go to the drugstore, his 5-year-old
daughter asked, ``Daddy, are you coming back?''
</P>
<P>
   And at times, the enormity of the job can be overwhelming. To
combat compassion fatigue, many say they focus on helping one life
_ not 30,000 _ at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mentor was a Vietnamese doctor,'' Giannone said. ``He said,
`If you can save one human being's life, you have done everything
that God expects of you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lessons in courage
</P>
<P>
   Maxman, who is Jewish, finds her inspiration in the human spirit
as well. She finds it in the most unlikely places _ even Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning she saw the corpses in the church, Maxman spotted
a woman, ashen-faced and silent. The woman's husband and her entire
extended family, save for three children, had been killed on her
wedding day. Two years later, when Maxman was leaving Rwanda, she
attended a going-away party where she saw the same woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost didn't recognize her,'' said Maxman, who is now
deputy director of CARE's East Africa and Middle East region. ``We
looked at each other and she was glowing.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman told Maxman that she had started a new life and had
fallen in love with a man. Maxman met other survivors in Rwanda who
were also forging ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was witnessing this in little pieces all over the country,
slowly by slowly every day,'' Maxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Such encounters restored her faith in human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned a lot about strength and courage,'' Maxman
said. But she is still searching for belief in God. The memories
from the Rwandan church linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I wish I knew,'' she said. ``Sometimes I want
that strength and power. But my beliefs are so challenged all the
time that I've not yet been able to say, `I can believe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
