<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBTEXTS AND SUBTLETIES SHADOW THE NATO SUMMIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's bifurcated commemoration day allowed for no
diplomatic slack at the regular Yugoslav bombing briefing,
transferred from the European war theater for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a dictator,'' the briefer, Jamie Shea, said with
palpable disrespect in one corner of NATO's elaborate 50th
anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But over in the company of statesmen, President Clinton took
care to say ``Mr.'' Slobodan Milosevic, the Serb autocrat who has
viciously routed Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, confounded NATO Friday
as its member nations opened their anniversary ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoising of ``Mr.'' and dictator, of war resolve and
diplomatic hope, was the subtext of a day that provided a study in
fury and frustration at NATO's predicament. But the day that
unfolded in the eerily crowd-free heart of this security-steeped
capital was also a reflection of considerable pride at the
alliance's past _ its rising from the ashes of World War II as a
successful redoubt against the Cold War threat of Soviet expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the dozens of darting motorcades and looms of sound bites
and diplomatic briefings, the NATO gathering offered moments of
simple, honest emotion when members _ particularly the three
newcomers from the defunct Warsaw Pact of the departed Soviet Union
_ looked back across the century of turmoil and oppression that
sparked NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my country, this is one of the most important moments in
its long and dramatic history,'' President Vaclav Havel gently
observed in hailing the guarantee of peace represented by NATO's
inducting the Czech Republic. ``Such peace can hardly be attained
without the readiness to defend it against the forces of evil,'' he
added in one of the day's sobering references to NATO's
confrontation of the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   President Aleksander Kwasniewski of Poland stirred the gathering
in Mellon Auditorium, where NATO was signed into being in 1949,
when he looked back across postwar history and underlined the sheer
hope that NATO represented in the suffering Polish people's
yearning for freedom and, he emphasized, for the values now at
stake in Kosovo. ``In defense of these values, Poland will not
fail,'' he declared with obvious emotion as the audience of
dignitaries and generals broke into applause.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep and passion of the events being pondered by the
commemorative gathering, from Hitler's rise to Communism's fall to
the Kosovar agony, was touched on by Viktor Orban, prime minister
of the republic of Hungary. He beamed in open joy at joining NATO,
but he dwelled on this fading century and its harsh lessons. ``Time
is too slow for those who wait, too swift for those who fear, and
too long for those who grieve,'' he said. ``And too short for those
who rejoice.''
</P>
<P>
   A private meeting on Kosovo consumed the summit's first three
hours and the national leaders then headed for the ceremony,
preceded by a grave request to the waiting audience. ``Ladies and
gentlemen,'' boomed a voice, ``We ask you to please turn off all
cell phones and pagers.'' In a blur of obedience, one of the
best-wired throngs in diplomatic and military history saw to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Mikulski darted 10 rows up from the Congressional
VIP section to snap a quick photo of Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. She hurried back to her seat before a column of soldiers
in regal dress uniforms strode forth to deliver an earsplitting
trumpet fanfare in advance of the parade of NATO flags, then the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton found a parallel in NATO's founding and
William Faulkner's Nobel prize for literature both occurring in
1949. ``Humanity will not merely endure, it will prevail,'' he
quoted Faulkner's prediction.
</P>
<P>
   President Jose Maria Aznar of Spain went further back in
literature, noting today was the anniversary of the death of Miguel
de Cervantes. He quoted Cervantes on liberty: ``No treasures the
Earth contains or the sea conceals can be compared to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In quoting the next line, Aznar once more stirred the shadowy
implications of Kosovo falling across the NATO summit: ``For
liberty, one can rightfully risk one's life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the summit appeared nowhere near settling the question of
risking NATO lives by the commitment of ground troops. The hope
that air bombardment alone might drive the Yugoslav leader to the
negotiating table seemed to cling to each use of ``Mr.'' by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic's forces burn and loot homes and murder innocent
people,'' he declared in defending NATO's continuing bombing.
``When Mr. Milosevic's vision of the future is defeated, a better
one can rise in its place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
