<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV25-NYT     04-23 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Cabinet Member's Middle-Class Values &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton wealth redistribution program begins with his
Treasury Secretary, Robert E. Rubin. The editor of The New Yorker,
David Remnick, interviewed Rubin, a former co-chairman of Goldman,
Sachs, last week before a well-off audience that included Laurence
A. Tisch, the co-chairman of Loews; Bruce Wasserstein, the
investment banker; John Gutfreund, the former Salomon Brothers
chief, and Mike Wallace of CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't Rubin kicking himself for missing out on Goldman's public
offering, Remnick asked, especially in view of the bills Rubin had
run up by making the Jefferson Hotel his Washington residence?
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had a joke,'' Rubin answered. ``I came to the
administration to help the middle class, and I'm going to leave as
a member of the middle class.'' Pause. ``He also finds it very
amusing. I don't.'' Another pause, before Rubin, whose
self-discipline is almost scary, lobbed one back at a president
notorious for schedule-busting behavior. ``What I say in response
is, I came to the administration knowing what punctuality meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen R. Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Office &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Harry J. Pearce, 56, the vice chairman of General Motors,
went in for his annual physical a year ago, he had every reason to
believe that his fitness program had kept him healthy. But his
white blood cell count was low. Just in case, he had a bone marrow
test. On May 26, during a meeting of GM's top executives, he was
told by phone that he had to hear the results in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelming fear was absolutely the first reaction,'' even
before his doctor confirmed that he had leukemia, Pearce said in an
interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   After chemotherapy and a bone marrow transplant in September,
Pearce has managed a remarkable comeback, subject to confirmation
by follow-up tests. Except during a five-week hospital stay in the
autumn, he continued working from home until he began coming into
the office early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, who says he can now work as hard as before, has also
regained his status as a leading contender to succeed John F. Smith
Jr. as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that we not discriminate against people
who have had such a disease when they do have a full recovery,'' he
said. Two unexpected benefits: He has lost 10 pounds and kept them
off, and his temporarily impaired immune system has given him an
excuse for skipping some social events. ``I'm not wild about
cocktail parties anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Bradsher &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Vintage Takeover &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bernard Arnault likes a wine, he buys more than a case.
Last week, he and his company, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton,
gained control of Bordeaux's Chateau d'Yquem after years of
battling in court against Count Alexandre de Lur-Saluces, whose
family has owned d'Yquem since 1785.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet sophistication of d'Yquem, made from grapes shriveled
with noble rot, has drawn devotees from Thomas Jefferson to those
who today pay about $245 for the 1990 vintage. Arnault, who
privately bought another prime Bordeaux chateau, Cheval Blanc, with
a partner a few months ago, has eagerly posed for photographs with
a golden glass of d'Yquem in his hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allen R. Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shattering the Glass &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy for women to make it to the top of any law firm.
But it's especially daunting in New York. The percentage of female
partners at many leading New York firms still sits in the single
digits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a sign of change. The partners at New York's Hughes
Hubbard &AMP; Reed have just elected Candace Krugman Beinecke to be
chairwoman of their 300-lawyer firm. Hughes Hubbard joins just
three other firms among the nation's 100 largest that are managed
by women.
</P>
<P>
   The others are Mayer, Brown &AMP; Platt of Chicago; Pillsbury,
Madison &AMP; Sutro of San Francisco, and Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoar of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Beinecke, 52, says women should be tenacious, always do a
bit more than clients expect and not try to be one of the boys if
that isn't their style. She said law firms had made great strides
since she graduated from Rutgers University's School of Law in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   After applying to a New York firm she would not name, Mrs.
Beinecke said, she received a letter regretting to inform her that
``we already have our woman lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Melody Petersen &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
