<SLUG> BC-TIDY-ORGANIZED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWN CLUTTER LED WOMAN TO ORGANIZE HER OWN COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Julie Morgenstern didn't know a to-do list from a file
folder when her daughter, Jessi, was born 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She was, in fact, a disorganized mess who fantasized that
someone would appear and magically organize her life. She called
this fantasy ``Rent-A-Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   When it took her a couple of hours to pack a diaper bag for a
walk in the park, she realized she had to change her ways.
</P>
<P>
   She started small, putting the diaper bag in order. Then she
tackled closets and rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Three years and a divorce later, Morgenstern realized that her
nighttime theater work (she has a Master of Fine Arts in directing
from Chicago's Goodman School of Drama) wasn't compatible with
single parenting. She needed a day job.
</P>
<P>
   The result is Task Masters, a more authoritative and powerful
name than Rent-A-Mom, she decided. Her firm helps people and
companies get organized.
</P>
<P>
   She was on the West Coast recently to meet with clients, sign
copies of her book, ``Organizing From the Inside Out'' (Henry Holt
Owl Books, 262 pages, $12.95), and share tips on spring cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Spring cleaning is more about getting organized and decluttering
than washing walls, Morgenstern says. This New York expert gets
$150 per hour for organizing homes, offices and lives.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern and her eight employees are not to be confused with
housecleaners. They don't do dust bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   They expect a clean, if cluttered, work site. Morgenstern says
she's even specified that a home be professionally cleaned before
they begin working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clutter is OK. Piles are fine. But if they're a barrier
between you and what you need, it's not good,'' she says. A drivers
license renewal form and an outdated party invitation lost in a
stack of unopened mail, for example, are bad. So is a ``misplaced''
check that leads to overdraft charges from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge mistake to approach organizing with an
I've-got-to-get-rid-of-it mentality. It's more about identifying
what's important, then giving yourself quick and easy access to
it,'' Morgenstern says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step back. Analyze yourself. Assess what's important to you.
What do you need to use on a daily basis?,'' she advises. She says
research has shown we use only about 20 percent of our possessions
_ 20 percent of the clothes in our closets, and 20 percent of
papers we so carefully file.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern recommends arranging rooms like a kindergarten
classroom, with areas for various activities. Most people store
things where they'll fit, not necessarily where they're needed. A
favorite reading chair and lamp should be near the books and
magazines, for example.
</P>
<P>
   If family paperwork is done at the kitchen table, bills,
stationery, pens and calculator should be nearby, not in a box in
the den.
</P>
<P>
   See where the piles accumulate, she says. Then get containers to
keep them attractively stacked. But make certain you buy the
container after you figure out what's staying in the pile, she
advises.
</P>
<P>
   The most common problem is paper piles that get out of hand
because there is no filing system, or maybe there's one that isn't
understood or trusted, Morgenstern says.
</P>
<P>
   She advocates filing everything in a user-friendly system. That
means one with only about five categories, each with a colored file
folder. Then alphabetize within each category.
</P>
<P>
   Financial files could be red, with personnel files in green, for
example. Then use a straight tab filing system (all tabs on the
left, or right _ not staggered). Morgenstern calls this system
``peaceful'' to look at, and a person can add or subtract files
without messing up a tab pattern.
</P>
<P>
   She says organizing skills are similar to directing: ``Theater
is about preparation, about being ready, about having everything at
your fingertips.'' And the phrase ``what's your motivation'' works
with both actors and disorganized people.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern doesn't work with unmotivated people. She wants only
clients who are feeling the pain of being disorganized. Then she
knows they'll be motivated to change.
</P>
<P>
   But even the highly motivated can have an experience that's a
mixed blessing. Morgenstern mentions a shopaholic New York client _
a woman with bags of new clothing stashed on closet floors
throughout her apartment. She hired Task Masters to help her get
organized.
</P>
<P>
   A second bedroom was converted into a large, walk-in closet.
Clothes were removed from their shopping bags and hung according to
function. The client was delighted to be able to see instantly what
she had to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, however, was stunned at the display.
</P>
<P>
   Waaaaay too many clothes was all he could see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
