<SLUG> BC-CLEAN-LIST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON HOW TO GET ORGANIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Need a nudge to move into a spring-cleaning mode? Here
are tips from professional organizer Julie Morgenstern and other
experts:
</P>
<P>
   -Organize surface clutter first. Visible results will keep you
going.
</P>
<P>
   -Closets and garages are great places to clean/re-organize in
spring.
</P>
<P>
   -Organizing is not a game of catch-up. Sort, identify and place,
but don't use this time to catch up on unfinished chores.
</P>
<P>
   -Do only one area at a time.
</P>
<P>
   -Start with one corner of a room.
</P>
<P>
   -Never zigzag (work on several areas at once).
</P>
<P>
   -Work with a box or bag labeled ``goes elsewhere'' for things
that don't belong where they're found. When you're finished
organizing an area, put these misplaced pieces away.
</P>
<P>
   -Consolidate all ``To Do's'' onto one list and file away all
related paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   -Use containers _ baskets for magazines, boxes for storage, for
example. But don't shop for containers until you know the sizes and
styles needed.
</P>
<P>
   -Surround yourself with useful, inspiring things that make you
feel good.
</P>
<P>
   -Donate unneeded items, especially clothing and household goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
