<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO HAS PLENTY OF TIME TO CHALLENGE THE DOLLAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Mass., Calif.)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western Europe's new currency, the euro, ought to be a
powerhouse, already diminishing America's place in the global
economy. Such was the advance billing. But nearly four months into
its existence, the euro is hardly noticeable on this side of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   That is not too surprising. Even thoroughbred currencies inch
their way up rather than leaping. Children now in diapers may be
finishing college before lives are changed by the existence of the
euro. And even then, a solid American economy _ one that has
avoided the deterioration of severe recessions _ would dilute the
impact. The robust economy today keeps the focus on dollars, not
euros.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the euro's potential challenge to the dollar's dominance
is considerable. ``Establishing a European currency that will rival
the dollar is indeed one of the points of the whole exercise,''
said Peter Kenen, an international economist at Princeton
University.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the dollar finally eclipsed the British pound after
World War II has a currency had the potential to eclipse the
dollar. In the process, the euro could lift its 11 sponsoring
nations toward the top of the heap in political and economic power.
Neither the German mark nor the Japanese yen, the closest rivals
until now, represents a population or an economy as large as those
of the United States. But the euro does.
</P>
<P>
   American hegemony could give way to a 21st century in which
America and Europe vie with each other, says Martin Feldstein, the
Harvard economist. A more solidified Europe, thanks to the euro,
``creates the potential for political clash,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   France might even succeed in putting one of its generals in
charge of NATO in place of an American. Feldstein argues for
diluting European power by dealing with governments there
separately, not as a union.
</P>
<P>
   The other great concern is the American trade deficit. Rather
than lend so much to Americans to help pay for imports and for
spending abroad, the world's investors could funnel some of their
money into the new haven. Euro investments in a powerful Western
European economy would become an alternative to Treasuries and
other holdings in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And Americans would find themselves scratching for overseas
loans to finance their way of life _ pushing up interest rates to
attract enough money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be surprised to see a significant shift to euro
investments when and if the marketplace focuses on the widening
American current account deficit,'' said William Cline, chief
economist at the Institute for International Finance, referring to
all of the nation's international transactions.
</P>
<P>
   According to the advance forecasts, the shift to euros was
supposed to have begun as soon as the euro was born, on Jan. 1. But
the money did not flow. The euro rose by only a penny from its
initial value of $1.17 and then fell steadily to just over $1.06.
</P>
<P>
   The means were there. Checking accounts, traveler's checks and
credit card purchases are all now available in euros, as well as in
the national currencies of Germany, France, Italy and the eight
other countries in the European Union. Hundreds of billions of
dollars in stocks, bonds and government securities are denominated
in euros. And in 2002, after the new European Central Bank begins
to issue euro coins and paper bills, the old currencies will
vanish.
</P>
<P>
   But confidence in the euro, for all its powerful backing, comes
slowly at all levels. American Express says European merchants have
sent in only 5,000 credit card charges in euros since Jan. 1, a
tiny number. Tourists report that traveler's checks in dollars are
far easier to cash in Europe than checks in euros. And central
banks continue to keep most of their foreign reserves in dollars,
hardly changing the mix since the euro's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance runs deeper. Even though they are all denominated
in euros, European government securities are still issued by the 11
different member countries, with each nation's paper bearing its
own separate risk and credit rating, just as municipal bonds issued
by different American cities do.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, euro securities may represent as huge a market as
American Treasuries and corporate bonds, but they do not constitute
as unified a market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As European financial markets grow and develop, and
demonstrate their stability and unity, the euro will gradually
rival the dollar, but over a period of decades,'' said Barry
Eichengreen, an economist at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The euro arrived just as the American economy completed three
years of robust economic growth and Western Europe found itself in
a slowdown _ bad timing. ``People have been saying for the longest
time, `Shouldn't we worry about the euro?''' Eichengreen said.
``And we should, if the European economy becomes the engine for the
world and we stop being the engine.'' Or if the United States
plunges into confidence-robbing troubles like those that
characterized the 1980s: inflation, rising deficits, a real estate
bubble that burst, a savings and loan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Then the alternatives were the mark and the yen, neither with
the euro's potential for luring worried investors in the event of
another dismal spell for the American economy. The 21st century
would not then be an American century, but rather a century shared
by the United States and Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
