<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARCLAYS-GLOBAL-ART-3     04-23 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-GLOBAL-ART-3TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INDEXING GIANT NOBODY KNOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Pa., Conn., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an era when being biggest in any endeavor
brings hubris and hype, Barclays Global Investors stands out by
being nearly invisible to the untutored eye.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Barclays Global, not the much vaunted Vanguard Group,
that is king of the stock-market indexers _ managing $407 billion
in investors' money by mimicking the performance of major market
indexes. And it is Barclays Global, not a white-shoe bank or
insurance company, that is the world's biggest manager of funds for
institutions, like corporate pension funds and nonprofit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It even has designs on displacing the giant Fidelity
Investments, with $765 billion in its care, as the world's biggest
manager of money.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global, a unit of the British bank Barclays PLC,
started out as part of Wells Fargo, the San Francisco bank. The
unit already has a remarkable perch, considering that it lacks a
well-known American brand name to advertise, sits far from the
biggest financial centers, was long hobbled by legal restrictions
not affecting some competitors and is led by a chairman who joined
the company as a temporary secretary because she couldn't land a
job in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even more than Vanguard, which has concentrated on
individual investors and met their demands for an array of
products, Barclays Global has ridden the indexing rage to dizzying
heights, managing a total of $619 billion at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason can be found at the nation's pension plans.
Just like small investors across the country, leaders of those
plans are often choosing the indexing route, having grown tired of
watching most mutual funds and other money managers fail to match
the performance of the overall market. After all, what can be more
unpleasant, not to mention costly, than having to face disgruntled
employees to explain their pension fund's underperformance?
</P>
<P>
   Size, too, works to Barclays Global's advantage. Bigness can be
an impediment for so-called active managers of money _ those who
use a variety of strategies and criteria to pick and choose stocks
_ but it helps an indexer. Barclays Global has so much money under
its roof that it obtains staggering economies of scale, allowing it
to charge annual fees that are in many cases less than one-tenth of
1 percent of the money being managed, half the level that wins
Vanguard so much praise for its fund indexed to the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500. And every day, Barclays Global does $1 billion in
trades among clients in house.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Barclays Global pioneered indexing and remains at its
forefront, with a couple of dozen PhDs prowling the investment
frontiers behind doors marked ``This is a secured floor.'' While it
manages some $400 billion through plain-vanilla indexing _ in
itself not always as easy as it sounds _ it also has huge sums
assigned to its computer jockeys, quantitative investors who try to
tease a bit more than market returns from more complex investment
products.
</P>
<P>
   Indexing, of course, is a rejection of what much of Wall Street
holds dear _ especially its faith in stock-picking prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what happens in this business is more justified by
hope _ and perhaps a little greed _ than by experience,'' contended
Patricia C. Dunn, 46, the chairman of Barclays Global, coolly
sipping from an ever-handy bottle of spring water. ``We get a lot
of our energy from being outsiders and challengers of investing
wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   As indexing's biggest practitioner, Barclays Global hears all
the criticisms leveled at a practice that is both popular and
threatening to many plush livelihoods. One contention is that
indexing is a fad that has looked attractive because the market has
been enamored, at least until this month, of the big stocks that
dominate the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the benchmark for 70 percent of
indexed equity mutual funds and a good deal of institutional money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sentiment shifts away from the big-cap stocks in the S&AMP;P,
indexing will take a powerful hit,'' said Jeremy Siegel, a
professor of finance at the Wharton School of the University of
Pennsylvania. ``You leave yourself very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Index-fund management is also inherently a commodity business;
it produced a relatively modest $83.2 million of profit last year
for Barclays Global's parent, 2 percent more than in 1997. Slender
margins put a premium on volume.
</P>
<P>
   As it aspires to become the world's No. 1 money manager,
Barclays Global faces a big challenge: protecting its institutional
turf against traditional rivals like State Street Global Advisors,
Mellon Capital and Bankers Trust while it pushes into the retail
market, especially 401(k) and other retirement savings vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Coy about its plans, Barclays Global says it will not buy a
public mutual fund group. But it rules out little else. Tom
Taggart, the company's recently hired spokesman, used the term
``instividual'' to refer to what is widely seen as a convergence of
the institutional and individual investment businesses. ``Look for
BGI leveraging its expertise in this area,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Others speculate that the company might act as a subadviser to
someone else's funds, a business into which it has already dipped a
toe, or provide indexing skills in an alliance, say, with a major
brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes Barclays Global from most other money
managers is its commitment to indexing, a theory of investing built
on the idea that the stock market is a highly efficient
information-processing machine, one in which a giant web of
participants quickly incorporates every scrap of information into
prices. By the time word circulates of a predicted drop in the
quarterly profits of Gillette, to cite a recent example, the price
has already fallen.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the stock market is far different from the place
portrayed in personal finance magazines, mutual fund advertisements
and popular mythology, one in which smart or well-connected people
profit by outwitting the less smart.
</P>
<P>
   About $407 billion of the money entrusted to Barclays Global is
invested in straightforward replicas of various market averages.
But while this kind of investing is often derided as something that
could be done by a monkey, Steven Schoenfeld, a senior Barclays
Global official whose job title is index strategist _ not an
oxymoron _ knows otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Among the numerous practical problems he faces are dealing with
sudden inflows or outflows of clients' money and keeping from
running prices up on himself when buying a small-capitalization
stock.
</P>
<P>
   And when should someone in his position buy a company like
Safeway, which Standard &AMP; Poor's announced a few months ago as a
new addition to its 500 index? Should he buy as soon as the
announcement is made, or the morning of the day the company is
initially counted? Or five minutes before the market closes? Or a
day or two later? Or should he buy options instead?
</P>
<P>
   It's a constant, high-stakes game of cat and mouse in which
Barclays Global, as the world's biggest indexer, is everybody's
Sylvester. ``We have to make sure our strategy is not predictable _
or we're the suckers,'' Schoenfeld said. ``There's plenty of hedge
funds, mutual funds and brokers who would be all too happy to pick
us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Indexing gets treacherous overseas when rivals know that
Barclays Global is a near-certain buyer in a thin market with
rudimentary benchmarks. ``Once you go outside the United States,
just tracking the index is a major investment challenge,''
Schoenfeld said. ``Not just anyone could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, not surprisingly, is difficult, but so is a market like
Switzerland, which is dominated by a handful of huge companies,
mostly in finance and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global follows more than 50 foreign markets, so ``when
you get into all the splicing and dicing, we're probably tracking
close to 1,000 different indexes,'' Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its success as a replicator of benchmarks, Barclays
Global also recognizes the human urge to try to do better than
average. The company puts about one-third of its invested money in
``tilts,'' funds that are basically index-matched but also
``enhanced'' with variations engineered to match a client's
tolerance of risk.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the product Barclays Global calls NeuAlpha _ in
investing, alpha refers to the amount by which you beat a benchmark
_ is a long-short tilt, one that, as its name implies, includes a
mix of short and long positions that reflect negative as well as
positive information the firm has uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   The detective work behind it relies heavily on immense computing
power, enough gigabytes to audit every American income-tax return
in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at making big bets on 20 or 30 or 50
companies,'' said Blake R. Grossman, the company's chief global
investment officer. ``We're making small bets across hundreds,''
scooping up what he calls the ``nickels and dimes'' invisible to
others.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors, for example, track Wall Street's estimates of
company earnings, especially trends in analysts' revisions.
Barclays Global keeps tabs on individual analysts, combining their
forecasting records with other data to find patterns in how stocks
react to shifts by certain analysts on certain companies.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, Barclays Global also tracks the buying and
selling by executives of their companies' stocks, but it evaluates
this information in the context of other facts, like how a
company's executives are managing its financial structure. For
instance, is expansion being financed with borrowing or new shares?
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global, however, does not borrow money to invest and is
sparing in its use of futures and derivatives. ``We don't have many
funds that are leveraged,'' said Andrea Zulberti, the head of the
firm's risk-management operation.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Barclays Global's results have been sparkling, people
in the industry say. But performance for some clients has been
hampered in the last few years by the huge gulf between a relative
handful of big-capitalization stocks driving the main indexes and
the rest of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As that top group has done better and better,'' said John F.
Casey, chairman of Barra RogersCasey, a consulting firm in Darien,
Conn., the Barclays Global approach ``is forcing them to
underweight these and to put money into the stocks that are so much
cheaper.''
nn
</P>
<P>
   But Casey said the clients he has steered toward Barclays Global
are a highly satisfied group. ``What they like,'' he said, ``is
that the research function is so rigorous that it's like bringing
out a new pharmaceutical product in testing these things.'' And he
said Barclays Global makes investment results dependably
transparent, giving clients enough information so that they can see
the source of the returns.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals acknowledge Barclays Global's trailblazing in indexing
and its aggressiveness in building its institutional business, with
clients like the pension funds of Exxon. But they don't hold
Barclays Global in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using very similar techniques,'' said Gus Sauter, who
oversees Vanguard's index and active quantitative group.
``Everyone, if they're not on the same page, then at least they're
reading from the same book.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sauter complained that so-called enhanced indexing
products, like the tilts, are not actually index funds; instead, he
said, they reflect active strategies, however closely controlled.
``There's no such thing as half pregnant or half wet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas A. Lopardo, chairman of State Street Global Advisors,
which manages $485 billion and is the No. 2 indexer, contended that
his old-line firm interacts with clients more than Barclays Global
does and noted that it had grown without acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   (In 1995, however, State Street did seek to buy Wells Fargo
Nikko Investment Advisers, as Barclays Global Investors was then
known. Negotiations failed over who would end up in charge.)
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global's money under management has roughly tripled
over the last four years _ a result of a combination of mergers,
growing interest in outside management of investments for
companies, increased popularity of indexing and, of course, one of
the greatest bull markets on record.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the growth was at the expense of traditional active
managers; other new money came from public entities that had
previously been obliged by law to manage their funds themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The chief architect of the firm's development was Fred Grauer, a
Wells Fargo strategist who had left the bank after a short stint in
1979 and 1980 and was lured back in 1983, when the business was
floundering. He masterminded the 1990 deal in which half of Wells
Fargo's investment unit was sold to Nikko Securities, then managed
the late-1995 sale of the resulting business to Barclays, the
latter bringing $85 billion in managed money.
</P>
<P>
   If the firm is under pressure from London to contribute more to
its parent's so-so bottom line these days, nobody here will
acknowledge it.
</P>
<P>
   Grauer, citing an interest in ``brand new challenges,'' resigned
suddenly in July, leaving Ms. Dunn in charge; as co-chairman since
early 1997, she was the natural successor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the size of Barclays Global and its reputation do not
prevent it from worrying about its competitive position as it
serves a highly demanding clientele in a low-margin business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest challenges they face in this country is
competition from the big trust banks that frequently bundle indexed
products in with their custody services,'' said Paul Holt,
president of Cambridge International Partners, an investment
management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Custody business includes record-keeping, accounting and serving
as a transfer agent, and it opens the door to the lucrative
practice of lending securities. Such lending, mainly to investors
who wish to sell the securities now and repay them later after
repurchasing them at a hoped-for lower price, accounts for some 15
percent of Barclays Global's revenues, which totaled about $460
million in 1998, and an even larger share of its profits.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks the Barclays Global retail strategy will be to
jump into the mutual fund business or to market directly to
individual investors. That, among other things, would violate its
stated core belief that it should focus strictly on what it does
best _ managing money.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, suggested Avi Nachmany, head of research at
Strategic Insight, a New York firm that researches funds, the cost
would probably be prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global expects to unveil an expansion plan in coming
months _ an expansion that it hopes will make it burst into public
consciousness. ``It's not soup yet,'' Ms. Dunn said of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   But when it's ready, she added in an interview in her 33d-floor
office overlooking San Francisco Bay, ``we'll be shouting from the
rooftops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
