A1142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BIAS24-COX     04-23 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawsuit claims Coke practiced bias in pay, promotions
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First, Motisola Malikha Abdallah got frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   After working at Coca-Cola Co. headquarters as an administrative
assistant for more than three years, she said she was repeatedly
passed over for promotions because she was African-American.
</P>
<P>
   When she complained, Abdallah said, the situation only got
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt disrespected and dehumanized,'' the 44-year-old
Atlantan recalled Friday. ``I wanted to try to make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Abdallah joined two other employees and a former
executive in filing a federal lawsuit, accusing Coca-Cola of
discriminating against African-Americans in pay, promotions,
performance evaluations and terminations.
</P>
<P>
   The workers also are attempting to get a judge to give their
complaint ``class-action'' status so they can represent 1,500 other
salaried, African-American employees. The class action would
include those who have worked at the company in the United States
at any time since April 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discrimination represents a company-wide pattern and
practice, rather than a series of isolated incidents,'' the suit
says. ``Although Coca-Cola has carefully cultivated
African-Americans as consumers of its product by public
pronouncements, strategic alliances and specific marketing
strategies, it has failed to place the same importance on its
African-American employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coca-Cola Co. was built over time by people of all races,
colors and creeds,'' M. Douglas Ivester, the company's chairman and
chief executive, said Friday in a statement. ``Discrimination at
the Coca-Cola Co. is not tolerated. If discrimination is alleged,
we investigate it. If we find it, we act to stop it. Our goal is
the fair, equitable and honest treatment of all of our associates.
While we believe this lawsuit is without merit, we take these
allegations seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester also sent out an e-mail Friday to all U.S. employees
communicating the same idea and adding, ``As you have heard me say
many times, we will do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta, makes many
serious claims against the company:
</P>
<P>
   _It says African-American employees face a ``glass ceiling'' or
barrier to equal opportunity when they try to step up the corporate
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few African-Americans advance to senior levels in the
company,'' the suit says. ``Indeed, although African-Americans make
up about 15.7 percent of the employees in the corporate
headquarters, they are under-represented at higher pay grades.''
</P>
<P>
   _Not only are there glass ceilings, the suit says, but there are
``glass walls'' that ``virtually segregate the company into
divisions where African-American leadership is acceptable, and
divisions where it is not.'' It says blacks in senior positions are
concentrated in less powerful and nonrevenue generating
departments, such as human resources and external affairs.
</P>
<P>
   _A salary review shows ``dramatic differences in pay'' between
whites and blacks at Coca-Cola's headquarters. In 1995, the suit
says, the average African-American was paid more than $19,000 less
than the average white employee. By 1998, the gap had risen to
$27,000.
</P>
<P>
   _The performance evaluation system, which affects raises,
bonuses and advancement, is biased, the suit says. ``Because of the
undue discretion of managers, African-Americans receive more low
evaluation scores than Caucasians and fewer higher scores,'' the
suit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1998, about 56 percent of white employees scored
in the three highest evaluation categories, compared with 46
percent of the black employees.
</P>
<P>
   _Black employees are involuntarily terminated at corporate
headquarters at a much higher rate than white workers, the suit
says. In 1997, blacks accounted for 37 percent of the firings at
corporate headquarters, which was more than double the rate of
their representation in the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he obtained the company statistics, plaintiffs'
attorney Cyrus Mehri replied Friday, ``We have conducted a thorough
investigation over more than six months and have obtained and
analyzed the data underlying the complaint.'' He would not be more
specific.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin said the company has not had
enough time to study the suit's statistical allegations, and,
therefore, could not comment on them.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the company did investigate three of the employees'
complaints and found them to be without merit. The fourth employee,
he said, was terminated for allegedly violating the company's
business code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Mehri, who is based in Washington, was one of the principal
lawyers who handled the Texaco workers discrimination case in 1996.
In the largest such settlement in history, Texaco agreed to pay
plaintiffs $176 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the Coca-Cola suit, Mehri is seeking unspecified monetary
damages and court orders prohibiting Coca-Cola from engaging in
discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
