<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-DUNN-PROFILE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAREER DETOUR THAT LED TO THE CHAIRMAN'S OFFICE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1976, when she joined Barclays Global Investors, Patricia
C. Dunn has taken a turn at nearly every job there _ the clearing
and settling of trades, portfolio management and positions in
sales, accounting, trading and administration _ none of which she
was initially qualified to do.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the fall she told a women's leadership conference at
the University of California's Haas School of Business that she
couldn't even have gotten into business school. ``My expectations
were so low,'' she said in explaining her start at Barclays Global
as a temporary secretary, ``that I can honestly say I did not have
a career ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Ms. Dunn graduated from the University of California at
Berkeley, she was unable to find a job in journalism, her first
choice. She also thought people who worked for long in corporate
America ``didn't have a life'' and recalls thinking, ``It's just
not in my future to work for a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet nobody was surprised last summer when the sudden resignation
of Fred Grauer left her the undisputed boss. The two had shared the
top job for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   She has clearly mastered the theory of Barclays Global's heavily
quantitative work _ she calls herself a ``huge believer'' that
investing should be considered science, not art. But it is
management skill and an adaptive mind that have lifted her to her
powerful job. Senior industry officials guess that she earns at
least $1.5 million a year and perhaps as much as $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to bring together the technical with the
real,'' Ms. Dunn said. ``Probably the thing that I did at the point
of my career where I advanced the most involved helping clients
figure out how to use our highly sophisticated investment services
to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   About the most foolish thing some investors do today, she
contends, is chase after the hottest fund managers. ``Past
performance explains nothing about the future,'' she said. ``That
search for predictive power _ you can't find it.''
</P>
<P>
   And how does it feel to be responsible for $619 billion? ``I
dream about it,'' Ms. Dunn responded. ``Sleep deprivation is an
occupational hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   But she allowed that she would probably worry just as much about
one-thousandth of that sum, which would be a mere $619 million.
``After a point,'' she said, fretting that she might sound flip,
``it gets to be zeros, doesn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
