<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRA-BIKES-TEX     04-23 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-BIKES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Angelle Seeling proving doubters wrong 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ENNIS, Texas _ Angelle Seeling has heard it before. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can this petite woman handle one of those powerful
drag-racing motorcycles? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was racing back home they would see me and say, `That
is a nice bike,' and ask, ``Whose is it?'' I would say that is my
bike,'' the 5-foot-2, 107-pound racer said. ``Then they thought I
owned it. But when I walked up in my leathers, they were like,
`Wow, she really does drive that bike.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeling, a 28-year-old New Orleans resident, enters this
weekend's Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex leading the
NHRA's Pro Stock Motorcycle point standings after one race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeling, who drives for George Bryce's Star Racing, scored a
National Hot Rod Association maximum of 138 points at the
Gatornationals last month in Gainesville, Fla. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeling won the final and was the fastest qualifier with a Pro
Stock Motorcycle national elapsed-time record of 7.21 seconds on
her 1,500cc Suzuki. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like the first \RNHRA\S race I ever won,'' Seeling
said. ``We were No. 1 qualifier, set a new record and won the race.
I was wondering if it was ever going to happen again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, drag racing was a hobby for Seeling as she
pursued a career as an intensive-care nurse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after racing a drag bike in Louisiana for four years,
she used some of her nursing money to attend Frank Hawley's Drag
Racing School in Gainesville. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bryce, one of the NHRA's most successful Pro Stock Motorcycle
owners and crew chiefs, taught at the school. By July 1996, Seeling
was driving for Bryce on the NHRA circuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeling won her first race Sept. 15, 1996, in Reading, Pa.,
becoming the sixth woman to win an NHRA national event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She won three of 14 races in 1998 and finished second to Matt
Hines in the series standings. &QL; 
``She has the combination of having the unmatched fire, desire,
goals and dreams to be a champion and be the best,'' Bryce said. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
