A1153 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-LIGHTS-TEX     04-23 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-LIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLOBE-GIRDLING E-MAIL SUGGESTS AND OUTLET FOR GRIEF FROM SCHOOL
SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIMBERLY DURNAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The sorrow that followed the Littleton,
Colo., school massacre may have found an outlet in a simple gesture
suggested by an Arlington man in an e-mail that traveled around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Retired educator Klaus Driessen sent a note to about 250 e-mail
addresses asking people to turn on their headlights and porch
lights Friday, Saturday and Sunday in remembrance of those who died
and in support of those who survived the Columbine High School
shooting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also asked those receiving the e-mail to pass the message on.
It quickly snowballed into a mass-mailing that brought responses
from as far away as Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal that one person can write an e-mail and the
lights come on around the world,'' Driessen said.
</P>
<P>
   The former teacher, principal and superintendent said he was
driving past a school Thursday when he noticed the flag was flying
at half-staff. He then asked himself what he could do to show
others that he, too, felt the pain of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to turn on my lights for the families in Littleton
to show them that I care about them, that I feel the pain and hurt
and heartache,'' he wrote in his e-mail. ``I'm going to turn on my
lights for what is right about this country. I'm going to turn on
my lights against darkness, the anger and the prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, Driessen said he had received about 40
phone calls and 2,000 responses to the e-mail he had sent early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Responses came from Littleton, Japan, Germany and a variety of
places throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Marine colonel called to say he was going to forward the
e-mail to all his subordinates; secretaries for Minolta and Xerox
called to say they would forward it to all employees at their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The speed and amount in which someone's e-mail can be forwarded
is, of course, immeasurable. It depends on how soon people read
their e-mail, whether they forward it and when they forward it,
said Sajal Das, who teaches computer science at the University of
North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But just imagine if Driessen sent out 200 e-mails, and those
people sent out 200, you would have 40,000. Multiply that by
another 200 and you have 80 million, Das said, adding that even he
got a copy of Driessen's note.
</P>
<P>
   One response came from Stanci Hagans, in Littleton, Colo.,
thanking Driessen for his gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``... the continued efforts of the nation to reach out and
console and support us is incredibly touching,'' Hagans said. ``I
hope that we can all learn something from this terrible tragedy and
walk away better, more tolerant people. Our community has really
pulled together, strangers are hugging, families are realizing the
value of each other. I pray that we can carry this sense of
camaraderie with us long after the funeral services have passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Driessen said he had no idea his gesture would attract so much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken on a life of its own,'' he said. ``It's a shame
that a tragedy like this had to wake us up.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
