<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SALT-LAKE24-COX     04-23 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SALT-LAKE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preserving history with return of salt lake to public domain
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINN, Texas _ The shores of the lake sparkle, the sun glinting
off a thick layer of crystallized salt that has drawn people to
this small South Texas lake for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden in the brush country off Texas 186, La Sal Del Rey, as
the legendary salt lake is known, has melted into near-obscurity
since the last horse- and ox-drawn carts pulled loads of salt from
its banks in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in decades, what was once the most
important lake in Texas will return to the public domain today when
the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service opens roughly 40,000 acres of
its Rio Grande Valley wildlife corridor to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The lake and the land surrounding it were purchased from
longtime owners in 1992 as part of the wildlife service's 20-year
effort to create an unbroken stretch of protected land from Falcon
Dam to the Gulf of Mexico. Along with its long history _ Indians,
Spaniards, Civil War troops and early Texas settlers all mined
precious salt from its shores _ Sal Del Rey is a natural novelty, a
500-acre lake surrounded by a thick apron of 90 percent pure salt
crystals that quickly encrusts fence posts, branches, and anything
else the water touches.
</P>
<P>
   La Sal Del Rey is one of seven tracts that will open to the
public today. Another significant tract is 12,000 acres at Boca
Chica, a wide coastal plain of wetlands, tidal flats and brush near
the mouth of the Rio Grande. The site includes the Palmito Ranch
battlefield _ the last battle of the Civil War _ and was the
subject of years of legal wrangling between developers and
environmentalists before the Fish and Wildlife Service bought it a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, the agency has spent about $80 million to acquire
90,000 acres across the Rio Grande Valley. The decline of
agriculture in the area has helped agency officials approach their
eventual goal of controlling 132,500 acres to serve as habitat for
hundreds of species _ including the ocelot and jaguarundi, the two
endangered cats whose range includes South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Ditto, project leader for the agency's Lower Rio Grande
Valley National Wildlife Refuge, has seen more and more land come
up for sale near the Rio Grande as the farmers who once dominated
the local economy leave the business. Ditto has heard a list of
last straws: the extended drought in South Texas, low profits,
competition from Mexico, younger generations that just aren't
interested in carrying on the farming tradition.
</P>
<P>
   After closing a sale, the Fish and Wildlife Service pays the
farmers and ranchers to re-plant the land with native flora like
ebony, huisache, prickly pear, and retama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about anything you can name _ we put about 40 species out
here,'' Ditto said as he drove past what used to be sorghum fields
near Sal Del Rey. ``The farmers spent their life clearing this
brush so they could farm out here, and now they're helping put it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto said the restored tracts have become magnets for wildlife,
which he hopes will attract nature lovers and birders, who pour
about $90 million into the local economy each year.
</P>
<P>
   Birds such as green jays and pygmy owls that are rarely seen in
the United States have been sighted around Sal Del Rey, he said,
and the lake's shallows and the surrounding brushland are now
teeming with shorebirds, coyotes, javelina, deer, and other
wildlife. In the lake itself, only brine shrimp and a hardy breed
of water beetle can live in the super-salty water.
</P>
<P>
   The lake is one of three salt lakes in Hidalgo and Willacy
counties that the Fish and Wildlife Service purchased along with
15,000 acres of surrounding land. All three have played a central
role in the history of South Texas and northern Mexico since the
first treasure-seeking Spanish explorers stumbled upon them in the
early 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eloise Campbell, who owned La Sal Del Rey and
surrounding land for 40 years and became its most fervent
historian, Cabeza de Vaca and his men immediately claimed the lakes
for the Spanish crown _ hence its name, which in Spanish means
``the king's salt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most precious commodities at that time in
the world,'' said Campbell, who now lives in Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   The explorers had discovered a natural treasure that to this day
baffles experts. No one knows how Sal Del Rey formed or exactly how
much salt it contains, although engineers have estimated as much as
4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries before the Spaniards arrived, bands of
Coahuiltecan Indians obtained salt from Sal Del Rey and the nearby
Sal Vieja and East Lake, which are separated by a narrow isthmus.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1750s, the lakes were fixtures on Spanish maps of the
area. A salt road stretched from Sal Del Rey to Reynosa, a Spanish
outpost on the south bank of the Rio Grande that today is a teeming
border city. Salt became the first export from the Rio Grande
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, after Texas won its independence from Mexico
and then became a state, Sal Del Rey became a prized resource for
the confederacy, which began one of Texas' more unusual experiments
in commercial transport.
</P>
<P>
   Confederate leaders decided that camels would be ideally suited
as pack animals in South Texas, and began using the animals to haul
salt from Sal Del Rey to supply their troops. Campbell said the
camels could indeed carry bigger loads than other pack animals and
required less water, but they so terrified horses that riders were
sent ahead of the trains to warn people ``the camels are coming!''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the slow-moving camels made inviting targets for
salt thieves, who absconded with many loads. The experiment was
abandoned, and the camels were left to wander the brushland,
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, whose father had wagonloads of salt from Sal Del Rey
delivered to his Harlingen ranch in the 1920s, bought the lake and
5,400 acres around it with her husband in the 1950s, and for 40
years, they raised cattle and farmed cotton, sorghum, and peas on
the land.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of giving her own tours to hundreds of visitors
over the years, she said she's glad to see the lake finally opening
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame to have something that historic and not have
people enjoy it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
