<HEADER>
A1159 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     04-23 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW MAY BE THE TIME TO CLOSE THE CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rotation, rotation, rotation. That, seers say, is what the stock
market needs to sustain its run. Unless stocks that have missed
most of the run-up the last year or so start to do better _ and
that is most stocks _ the market's gains rest on shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's one argument. And for a time the last two weeks,
it seemed that investors were listening. Signs of improving world
economic growth, as well as rising oil prices, sent money rushing
into the basic blocking and tackling companies that for generations
have been the backbone of the Industrial Age. Money poured out of
technology shares, the broken-field runners of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   But technology's tailspin didn't last long. By the end of last
week, investors seemed as enamored as ever with making very
expensive stocks even more so.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas V. Reilly, chief investment officer of global value
equities at Putnam Investments, doesn't hate technology. He just
likes cyclical stocks better. And he took some time last week to
say why. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)How big is the universe of cyclical stocks?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Cyclical industries make up about 40 percent of the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index. They include consumer stocks like autos and
household appliances, commodity companies, machinery companies, oil
companies of all stripes and transportation stocks. And we think
the cyclical stocks we own will have earnings growth significantly
more rapid than the average company.
</P>
<P>
   One of the really interesting things at this time is that you
can be pretty well invested and be a value investor. That's because
the market is so broadly cheap. At the moment, the S&AMP;P 500 is
trading at about 35 times earnings. But if all the stocks in the
index were unweighted, the ratio would be 16 times. That is a cheap
market. But you have to look beyond the top 20 or 30 names. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)With dividend yields as low as they are these days,
aren't most stock investors looking to buy stocks that will
grow?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No matter what company you are looking at, it's always a
matter of earnings growth. It's just a question of what price you
are willing to pay for growth and what your time horizon is.
</P>
<P>
   If a stock is expensive and doesn't meet earnings expectations,
it is going to go down a lot. Gillette and Coca-Cola went way down
last summer but then bounced back up a lot. That happened because
there was a lack of clear alternatives. At this point, that may not
be the case. A company like International Paper may not have as
many problems as it did, and its earnings might grow faster than
Coke's. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)In the final analysis, what will it take to move
money out of technology stocks?(end italics)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sustained earnings growth from a broader array of stocks will
change the rotation. So will any question of faltering growth from
the market leaders. But at the moment, there is no sign that
investors are buying into this argument.
</P>
<P>
   The time horizon for many investors got very short last year,
and it remains that way. They are thinking they can't look out two
or three years, but need to focus on stocks that are performing
right now. So they have looked at stocks that have had great
earnings momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like International Paper or Weyerhaeuser or Dow
Chemical can't come up with earnings growth of the sort we have
been seeing from these technology companies on a sustained basis,
but they can do it for a couple of years because their earnings are
so depressed. And how much will the market pay for that spurt? A
lot more than currently, I think. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)So where are you putting your money?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, we have taken a lot of money out of technology. Last
summer, companies like Intel and Texas Instruments qualified as
value stocks. They don't any more. We still own some IBM, but we
have pared back our position some.
</P>
<P>
   We have spread that money into commodity cyclical stocks,
machinery stocks, transportation stocks and auto stocks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Could you be more specific?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We are overweighted versus the market in stocks like Dow
Chemical and Weyerhaeuser. Those are big bets, as are General
Motors and Ford. We are overweighted in all areas of the energy
sector, including oil-service stocks like Halliburton and
Schlumberger. We love B.P.-Amoco, and like Mobil as a play into its
merger with Exxon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What about bank stocks?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Bank stocks have been through a period of underperformance.
We still like them, and are still way overweight in the
financial-service sector. But we have spread our exposure there
around to insurance companies like Chubb and brokerage stocks like
Lehman Brothers, which is trading at an outrageously low
price-earnings multiple.
</P>
<P>
   Of the banks, we like Chase Manhattan, Bank One and PNC Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
