<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADS OR TAILS, GOLD COINS MIGHT LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: La.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Blanchard &AMP; Co., a gold-coin dealer in New Orleans, the
phones begin to ring in earnest when the price of gold drops to
around $280 an ounce. Investors, said Christopher W. Holton, the
vice president of marketing, ``are bargain hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, it is a switch for American investors, who
have too often been attracted to the glitter of gold when the price
was rising, only to be disappointed when a rally was followed by
another slump, a regular occurrence in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But bargain hunting is not the only reason for the spurt in
buying of the American Eagle gold bullion coins this year, Holton
said. Fear of a Year 2000 computer meltdown has given sales a big
boost, especially of the one-tenth ounce Eagle coin, which has been
singled out by many gurus of the Year 2000 survivalists.
</P>
<P>
   According to the United States Mint, 127,500 ounces of these
coins have been sold so far this year, compared with 15,000 ounces
in the corresponding period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Holton says other investors are buying because they want some
``insurance'' against a stock market reversal. And he gives credit
to the marketing program of the Mint, which announced last week
that total sales of American Eagles, first struck in 1986, have now
exceeded 10 million ounces.
</P>
<P>
   But buyers should remember that all of this has not done much
for gold prices. In 1998, the average price of an ounce of gold
fell 11 percent, to $294.09, the lowest average annual level since
1978. As of Friday, the spot price in London was down to $283.30.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, gold coin sales in the United States jumped 120
percent, to 1.84 million ounces, according to Gold Fields Mineral
Services, a London-based commodities research and consulting firm.
But those sales accounted for just 1.4 percent of the total demand
for gold in 1998. Worldwide gold coin sales were just 3 percent of
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe and other regions, which appear less prepared than the
United States for the computer shift into the new millennium, coin
sales fell 9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   One argument for a price spike has been that the world's central
banks will shut off their gold lending around year-end because they
are worried about Year 2000 computer problems. Because the central
banks, through their loans, supply much of the gold that is needed
in hedging by gold producers and speculating by investors, a
shutdown would send the price of gold soaring.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Klapwijk, managing director of Gold Fields, does not
see a major Year 2000 effect on prices. Klapwijk, who talks
regularly to central bank officials, said, ``I see no evidence that
central banks won't lend over year-end.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold Fields is predicting that gold will trade in a range of
$265 to $305 an ounce for the rest of the year. So far this year,
the average spot gold price in London is down to $285.95 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this forecast is the sharp decline in the cash
cost of producing gold, which fell in 1998 to $206 an ounce, from
$250. Klapwijk argues that this much lower cost will encourage gold
producers to sell more of their gold forward, which allows them to
lock in a price now and deliver the gold in future years.
</P>
<P>
   By selling like that at gold-price peaks and earning interest on
the proceeds from the sale, gold producers can increase their
return.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrick Gold Corp. of Toronto, which owns mines in North and
South America, reported record first-quarter earnings that were
based on such strategic forward selling. While the average spot
price of gold in the first quarter was $287 an ounce, Barrick was
getting $385 an ounce from its previous forward sales.
</P>
<P>
   So if there is no Year 2000 disaster, coin investors have two
routes to losses: a lower gold price and the premium, higher than
usual this year, that many buyers have had to pay for coins.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, the Mint sold 694 million ounces of coins.
It and its authorized wholesalers charged premiums ranging from
3.25 percent, which is normal, to 5 percent on the one-ounce coins
and 9 percent to 25 percent on the one-tenth ounce coins, according
to Paul Deckert, director of trading at Blanchard.
</P>
<P>
   That is a price per ounce _ before the charges of retail dealers
like Blanchard _ of $297.04 to $358.75. That will be hard to get
back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
