A1165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-G7-DEBT-NYT &LR;      04-23 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G7-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD'S RICHEST CONSIDER THE DEBTS OF THE WORLD'S POOREST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the number of people living in absolute
poverty on under $1 a day likely to reach 1.5 billion next year,
five major industrialized powers _ the United States, Canada,
France, Germany and Britain _ have acknowledged that a plan devised
three years ago to forgive debts of the poorest countries is not
working well.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions these countries have made for improving that plan,
the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Debt Initiative, will be
discussed at the meeting on Monday of finance ministers from the
so-called Group of Seven richest countries, which also includes
Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision on ways to change the initiative, first
disclosed in October 1996 by the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank, is expected at the Cologne meeting of heads of
government of the Group of Seven in June.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine countries have been classified eligible for relief
under the plan because their debts are more than two-and-a-half
times export earnings, average incomes are less than $925 a year
and they have carried out at least three years of economic changes
approved by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   But the debts of only two _ Uganda and Bolivia _ have been
reduced. Another five _ Burkina Faso, Guyana, Ivory Coast,
Mozambique and Mali _ are likely to receive relief this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a confidential report to member governments earlier this
month, the monetary fund acknowledged what it called the
shortcomings of the debt-relief initiative, saying it did not
adequately lower payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a consensus on the need for further steps to relieve
debt,'' Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, told a news
conference here Wednesday at the spring meeting of the monetary
fund and the World Bank. James D. Wolfensohn, president of the
World Bank, told a news conference Thursday that ``we need to do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But a clear difference of emphasis emerged between the IMF and
World Bank approaches to easing the debt burden of impoverished
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Camdessus said he favored making more countries eligible for
relief since this would bring more developing economies under the
fund's supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn, by contrast, presented debt forgiveness as a way to
release additional money for fighting poverty, saying the number of
people living on less than $1 a day had risen from 1 billion a few
years ago to about 1.3 billion today and would probably reach 1.5
billion by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn also warned of the rising cost of granting debt
relief. The cost of the current system is estimated at $12.5
billion, and is up almost 30 percent from last summer. This is
partly because falling commodity prices have reduced the export
earnings of many poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions on increasing debt relief to be discussed at the
Group of Seven meeting Monday involve relaxing the conditions
heavily indebted countries must meet before they can receive help.
Canada and Britain are the most generous, France the least. Germany
has shifted from opposing debt relief to welcoming it following its
recent change in government.
</P>
<P>
   But many private humanitarian organizations pressing for debt
relief have criticized these suggestions. ``They are all
inadequate, though Canada's and Britain's are relatively good,''
said Veena Saddarth, a representative of the Oxfam International
aid organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debt sustainability is still linked to exports, not to
development and poverty reduction needs,'' said the Jubilee 2000
Coalition, an alliance of private aid and church organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
