<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A&AMP;P refuses to comment on report it will sell stores
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A&AMP;P is making moves to leave the metro Atlanta market,
according to a local news report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P is selling nearly half of its 35 stores to Publix Super
Markets Inc., according to a story in the Atlanta Business
Chronicle that cited anonymous sources in the ``Atlanta real estate
community.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P officials refused to comment, and Publix rebuffed the
report. ``We haven't bought any A&AMP;P stores,'' said Publix
spokeswoman Rita Owens. ``And we don't comment until the deal is
done.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been much speculation that A&AMP;P would give up on metro
Atlanta because it faces stiff competition from Kroger and Publix.
Last year, Great Atlantic &AMP; Pacific Tea Co., which operates stores
in metro Atlanta as A&AMP;P, said it was closing more than 120
underperforming stores. The company also said it had a goal of
being the No. 1 or No. 2 chain in its chosen markets. A&AMP;P's
presence is nowhere near that in metro Atlanta. Kroger just opened
its 100th store, and Publix operates nearly 70 stores here.
</P>
<P>
   Publix is a likely buyer for some of the A&AMP;P stores because it
has significant cash flow, and it's also trying to close in on
Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
