<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DEFENSE MINISTERS AGREE ON OIL EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the opening session of the NATO summit meeting
here on Friday, the 19 allied defense ministers agreed on a plan to
impose an oil embargo on Serbia by searching ships in the Adriatic
Sea suspected of carrying fuel for forces fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The defense ministers, acting after a three-hour session where
NATO leaders discussed the Kosovo war, also decided to order NATO
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, to carry out heavier airstrikes
against overland pipelines and railroads that carry fuel from the
ports of Montenegro to Serbia, a senior Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for carrying out the oil embargo were the most
definitive action taken at the summit which was designed to
celebrate 50 years of the alliance but which has been overshadowed
by the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the defense ministers said they would provide ships to
conduct the searches and inspections on the Adriatic, the Pentagon
official said. The effort would be intended to stop oil flowing
into the ports of Bar and Kotor Bay, on the coast of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   An oil embargo had been proposed by the United States, officials
said, after it became clear that as NATO was bombing Serbia's oil
storage and refining facilities, new oil was coming in.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing for an oil embargo against Serbia, Washington argued
that NATO needed to do more than strike the oil facilities of
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Thursday that
``basically it didn't make a lot of sense for us to be bombing
refineries and at the same time not doing enough to prevent the
access of oil by sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are particularly focusing on oil because that is the way
that forces move around,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   But preventing oil getting to Serbia without hurting Montenegro,
the second republic in Yugoslavia which has been supportive of
NATO's war, makes the embargo difficult to impose, Pentagon
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how to stop the flow of oil into Montenegro
and to stop the flow out of Montenegro without hurting the
Montenegrins,'' a Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO will be careful not to hit oil storage facilities inside
Montenegro, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, NATO has been concerned as tankers
from Russia, Greece and Ukraine have docked at Montenegro ports and
unloaded oil.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's session, the leaders of the Western alliance spelled
out for the first time the conditions that Yugoslavia must accept
before the air strikes end, including a return of refugees to
Kosovo under the protection of an international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique, the 19 leaders said that if President Slobodan
Milosevic began to withdraw his forces from Kosovo according to a
set timetable, the alliance would deploy the international military
force and establish an ``international provisional administration''
in the province that would give Kosovo autonomy, but not
independence, from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO again laid out the five basic demands that it said
Milosevic must agree to before the air campaign is brought to a
halt: a ceasefire that is verifiable; withdrawal not just of the
military but also his police and para-military forces from Kosovo;
the stationing of an international military presence that would
have NATO at its core; the safe return of the ethnic Albanian
refugees and a willingness to work toward a political agreement
based on accords from the failed talks held in Rambouillet, France.
in February.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to an endorsement of an international force, the
alliance pledged to seek a U.N. Security Council resolution
requiring the withdrawal of Serb forces. Both elements of the
proposal appeared aimed at drawing Russia into a diplomatic
solution.
</P>
<P>
   But also put in writing on Friday was a rejection of the recent
offers for settlement made by Milosevic. Without specifically
mentioning the latest proposal made on Thursday through Russia's
new Balkan envoy, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
communique said the Yugoslav leader's ``offers to date do not meet
this test.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leaders' agreement on Kosovo set the stage for a
three-day summit whose celebrations of the alliance's 50th
anniversary have been considerably scaled back under the shadow of
the Balkan conflict. The ceremonial elements took a back seat to
day-long briefings on the military and economic strategies under
way as NATO keeps building pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-point communique was made public against a backdrop of
tough language. Phrases like ``resolve to see this challenge
through'' and declarations that ``NATO will prevail'' reverberated
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman, set a tone that combined
perseverance and defensiveness.``NATO has an obligation to
succeed,'' Shea said. ``We cannot afford to lose this one.''
</P>
<P>
   At a closed session of the 19 leaders, Clark, gave an upbeat
10-minute briefing on the status of the air campaign. He told them
that NATO had ``achieved air superiority at mid to high altitudes
throughout Yugoslavia,'' according to his spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   He then left to return to Brussels, Belgium, without meeting
with President Clinton. His spokeswoman said it was necessary for
him to return to his command.
</P>
<P>
   In public briefings by various NATO leaders, their ministers and
spokesmen invoked the idea of ground troops as they tried to send a
unified message _ the the notion of when and how they would enter
Kosovo was not addressed in the communique. Much of that talk
seemed aimed at Milosevic personally, since the leaders of the
alliance insist that the air campaign, in its 31st day, is
effective.
</P>
<P>
   But there was some discussion about ground troops at the closed
session, the Canadian defense minister, Art Eggleton, later said.
The talk focused on asking the military planners at NATO
headquarters to review all options, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their discussion followed a decision by NATO's Secretary
General, Javier Solana, two days ago _ at the request of the allies
_ to review all plans for sending ground troops to the region.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
