<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-DNA-CLASSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES EXPLORE THE TANGLED WEB OF DNA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ There were the most unmagisterial comments
coming from a great many distinguished justices of the
Massachusetts Superior Court on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is incredible!'' ruled Judge John Cratsley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this, scientists of America!'' ordered Judge Thomas
Connolly in eureka-moment of delight as he spooled some viscous
strands of human DNA around a pipette as if twirling tiny spaghetti
around a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, even a ``Wow!'' could be heard among the two
dozen Superior Court judges clustered about the laboratory as they
learned to purify human DNA and perform on it a recombinant trick
or two.
</P>
<P>
   The delight was optional, however. The intent was serious.
Increasingly, in the wake of federal and state rulings, judges are
required to rule on the merits of scientific testimony, and, also
increasingly, the testimony on which they must rule involves the
fast-advancing frontiers of genetics.
</P>
<P>
   So some members of the Massachusetts bench are spending much of
Friday and Saturday at the laboratory bench. That is, at their own
behest, about one-third of all the Massachusetts Superior Court
judges came to the prestigious Whitehead Institute for Biomedical
Research here to trade their gavels for pipettes and learn
first-hand what DNA is all about.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory lessons, held for the first time this year, are
just about unique, said Philip Reilly, a lawyer and clinical
geneticist who helped educate the justices. He knows of only one
other similar program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, it is part of a broad trend of great hunger among
judges to understand the DNA science that comes up in their
courtrooms _ and in their society at large.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Reilly said, he lectured on genetics for two hours to
280 federal bankruptcy judges, and ``they couldn't get enough of
it,'' he said. ``They realize the profound implications of genetics
for society.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Massachusetts, he said, ``The judges really came
to us about this and said, `We want to know more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the Whitehead Institute was willing to oblige, said its
director, Gerald Fink, as part of a civic mission to spread genetic
knowledge among opinion leaders. While the institute's scientists
are wrapped up in frenetic work in areas like the Human Genome
Project, on the other hand, ``they are citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the O.J. Simpson trial, Fink noted, the lawyers dealing
with DNA evidence managed ``to befuddle everyone.'' But after a
program like this one, he said, ``I don't think a judge will be
intimidated by the science.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a scientist,'' he added. ``You just have
to know what the limits are, what the issues are. They'll
understand what is black-and-white _ some things are, some aren't _
and what to allow in the courtroom, what not to allow.''
</P>
<P>
   That is just the kind of aid that several judges said they were
seeking to help them fulfill their new gatekeeper roles. Formerly,
judges were supposed to gauge expert witness testimony on the basis
of whether it conformed to current scientific consensus, but recent
rulings have loosened that standard and require judges to apply
more of their own judgment on whether something seems to be good
science. Such cases come up rarely, judges said, but often enough
to add extra urgency to their curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to almost be mini-scientists,'' said Judge Elizabeth
Donovan. ``We have to understand all of this, so any opportunity we
get to come to a seminar, we jump at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen Neel added, ``Obviously, this doesn't turn us into
scientists, but we get a sense of what the culture and methods
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they didn't become scientists, but significant signs of
progress among the judges could be observed as the day wore on. In
an initial lecture, after David Page, a Whitehead geneticist,
welcomed them to ``human genetics boot camp,'' there were awkward
silences when Page asked the class simple questions like how many
cells they thought there were in a human body. (The answer is 10
trillion).
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough, he had introduced his jurist-students to the
great cookbook metaphor: that the chromosome is like a cookbook,
the genome is like a whole shelf of cookbooks, the gene is like a
recipe, and the DNA base pairs are like the letters in the recipe.
And now, he told the participants, they were going to learn ``how
to shake and bake.''
</P>
<P>
   The hands-on lessons began with a paper-based exercise in
aligning cut-outs of chromosomes, work reminiscent of fitting
pieces in a puzzle, which gave the judges a visual sense of
chromosomes and the trickiness of deciphering them. But it was the
afternoon session in the laboratory that offered the judges the
direct experience with DNA they had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by Whitehead graduate and postdoctoral students, they
took a test tube full of cells whose nuclei had already been broken
open to release the genetic material within; they spun the mixture
in the centrifuge to help remove the proteins; they poured off the
DNA-containing liquid into another test-tube and added ethanol to
it, and there it was. Stirring a glass rod in the test tube allowed
them to ``spool'' the gooey DNA strands onto the rod.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the course, they were to go on to learning about
amplifying the DNA using the technique called polymerase chain
reaction, and about how enzymes could be used to cut DNA strands at
specified points. But that first spooling of DNA can be emotional
milestone for young life-scientists, Page said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd like to have an existential moment, that would be a
good time,'' he told the judges.
</P>
<P>
   And while no one waxed philosophical about the nature of
humankind as the DNA was spooled, many of the judges sounded more
exultant than any bailiff has probably ever heard them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is human DNA!'' Judges Paul Chernoff exclaimed as he
contemplated the stirring rod. ``Pure DNA!''
</P>
</TEXT>
