<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1178 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLBY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-23 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLBY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 The Net's New Music Man
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
As a recording artist in the 1980s, Thomas Dolby hit the top of the
music charts with ``She Blinded Me With Science,'' a tech-pop song
that explored creative ways to use synthesizers in music.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dolby has reinvented himself as a Silicon Valley
entrepreneur with hopes of making a hit in the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Dolby, now known as Thomas Dolby Robertson, is co-founder of
Beatnik Inc., a San Mateo company that produces Web design software
to help businesses add music to Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Beatnik also sells technology that helps music industry artists
and publishers keep track of song licenses and royalties. Robertson
believes this particular feature will generate huge profits as the
$40 billion worldwide recording industry seeks to turn Internet
music, which is now largely available for free, into a money-making
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're laying the groundwork for a shift in the way the music
business operates,'' said Robertson, the son of a British
archaeologist. ``Music and technology have a unique partnership and
have for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, most of the attention about music on the Internet has
centered on the popular MP3. That format allows songs to be
compressed for storage on a desktop computer before they are
transmitted to the Internet where they can be downloaded and played
back.
</P>
<P>
   The market for online music is potentially huge. Forrester
Research Inc., a market research firm, estimates the sales of music
off the Internet could add about $1.1 billion more in revenues to
the worldwide recording industry by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   That potential has driven the world's five biggest record
labels, along with major technology companies such as Microsoft,
IBM and Sony, to move quickly into the emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson believes the dramatic growth of Internet music over
the next four years will give his company an opportunity to carve a
niche as a business-to-business company selling products and
services to Web designers as well as firms in the recording music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-employee company has already taken some steps in this
direction. Earlier this month, it changed its name from Headspace
Inc. to Beatnik to take advantage of the brand recognition of its
flagship product, the Beatnik Player, an audio player that can be
downloaded for free into a Web browser. A more advanced Beatnik
Player costs $19. More than 3 million free copies of the Beatnik
player have been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the company hired Lorraine Hariton, a former
executive with Network Computing Devices, as its new CEO, with
Robertson remaining as owner and chief technologist.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson declined to disclose revenue figures for the privately
held company, which is still trying to turn its first profit. The
firm generates revenue from licensing its special design software
that puts music in standard HTML code on a Web site. The Beatnik
Player can interpret the code and play the music back on the user's
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robertson, the Beatnik system allows Web sites to
play music more quickly than rival RealNetwork Inc.'s RealPlayer,
which moves sound in segments through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's firm recently caught the attention of David Bowie, a
big-name artist for whom Robertson played keyboards in the 1980s. A
page on Bowie's own Web site,  &LR; www.davidbowie.com &LR; , is configured
in such a way that his fans can use the Beatnik Player to create
their own MP3 encoded version of his hit song ``Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This new stuff he's doing with Beatnik technology is
amazing,'' Bowie said in a recent statement.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also cut licensing deals to include Beatnik with
Netscape Communication Corp.'s latest Communicator 4.5 browser,
Intel Corp.'s new Pentium III, Sun Microsystem Inc.'s Java 1.2
Virtual Machine and Macromedia Corp.'s Web design software.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company has helped design music into Web sites
for Sony's Columbia Tri-Star unit, MTV Online, Virgin Radio,
Imagine Media, Universal Pictures and 7Up.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also sees opportunities in making big money from
licensing Beatnik technology to download production music off the
Internet. These are original tunes composed not for consumers, but
for use in productions like commercials, broadcast productions or
corporate training videos.
</P>
<P>
   Zomba Enterprises Inc., one of the world's three largest
production music publishers, agreed last month to invest an
undisclosed amount in Beatnik. As part of the deal, Zomba will use
Beatnik technology to push Internet sales of music from its large
library of production music.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Roberts, Zomba's senior vice president of finance and
commercial operations, said the production music market generates
about $800 million in worldwide revenues annually.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said Beatnik's technology represents the first use of
the Internet to streamline the now complicated licensing process.
``We had the content, they had the technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mooradian, an analyst with Internet market research firm
Jupiter Communications Inc., said it's hard to judge just how
successful Beatnik will be since it is heading into uncharted
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Mooradian does not expect the use of songs and soundtracks on
the Web will be ``something that is going to be terribly
widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he is impressed that Beatnik has developed a
solid software tool for the music industry and that Robertson has
credibility among both artists and record labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has been involved in this space much longer than the
vast majority of musicians out there,'' Mooradian said. ``He
understands the technical underpinnings. So him being in that
business makes a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Egypt, Robertson taught himself how to play music. As a
teen, friends started calling him Dolby, after the famed San
Francisco noise reduction studio, because of his fascination with
gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   He used Dolby as his stage name after he dropped out of school
at 16 to pursue a musical career. He has since agreed to revert to
his original family name as part of a settlement of a lawsuit filed
by Dolby Laboratories Chairman Ray Dolby against him. The suit was
aimed at avoiding confusion between Dolby Laboratories and
Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``She Blinded Me With Science,'' from the album ``The Golden Age
of Wireless,'' hit the top five on the pop charts in 1982. Although
subsequent albums like ``Aliens Ate My Buick'' were never as
successful as his first, Dolby as a composer gained critical praise
for work in the production of albums from singers like Joni
Mitchell and George Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Music historians credit Dolby with helping usher in a new era in
pop music by exploring new technology like synthesizers. He also
got good reviews for the soundtracks of films like George Lucas's
``Howard the Duck,'' although the movie itself was a box office
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Using his own money, Robertson and his manager co-founded
Headspace in 1993, originally to compose music for video games and
virtual reality programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always been very passionate about how music works in
different environments,'' said Robertson, his British accent
punctuating each syllable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by music in film, TV and commercials. When
interactive environments started to emerge in the 1990s, I was very
intrigued about how music would fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the technology world at the time was focused on
graphics and computing power, not on audio.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Robertson decided to turn his company into an
audio software producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appealed to the entrepreneurial side of my nature,''
Robertson said. ``If there was really this absence of tools and
technology to do this, then some company was going to make a
fortune by figuring it out. I was determined that it would be mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very strong need for both the music industry to
migrate to the Net to do business and for nonmusical companies to
make use of sound and music to get their message across,'' he said.
``Music is such a powerful medium. Everyone you talk to has a
strong personal sense of connection to music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
