<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS OF NATO ATTACK ON SERB TV HEADQUARTERS: LUCK, PLUCK AND
RESOLVE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ After surviving a NATO missile attack
that hit Serb state television headquarters early Friday morning,
an anchor, Zeljko Pantelic, said that he felt reborn, but not
converted.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:10 a.m., he was at the station when the missiles struck in
an attempt to silence the voice of the Yugoslav government.
Pantelic and 10 other journalists heard two explosions, one after
the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything crashed,'' he said. ``There was no way out. There
was smoke everywhere. It was terrible. People were screaming. It
was like a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 people died in the explosion, a Cabinet minister,
Goran Matic, said, and perhaps an additional 20 were missing Friday
evening, presumably buried in the rubble. Eighteen people were
badly injured and remain hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m., six hours after the missiles knocked Radio Television
Serbia off the air, the service returned, transmitting from an
alternative site prepared long ago. But emergency workers continued
their search for survivors and the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very lucky,'' Pantelic said. ``Yesterday I was born
again.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was unconvinced by the rationale for such
destruction. ``This bombing must stop now,'' he said. ``All our
people, Serbs and ethnic Albanians, now think, `Stop bombing right
now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Djuricic, 25, a sound man, was editing the news when he
heard a ``huge detonation, and everything went completely dark.''
Eight people were with him, he said Friday in the hospital where he
is being treated for wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky,'' Djuricic said. ``We tried to find an exit
with a cigarette lighter, and we finally managed to crawl outside
and get down over the rubble.''
</P>
<P>
   Svetlana Radosevic, a sports journalist for the station, was not
in the building, but she said five friends were believed to have
died there. ``If you think I lie,'' Ms. Radosevic said, ``you don't
have to kill me to prove I'm lying. I'm in shock. My workplace
doesn't exist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene was an increasingly familiar one of smashed glass,
broken walls, twisted timbers, scorched paint and emotional
devastation.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers shifted rubble in the rain, which cut gashes
through the layer of fine gray dust that seems to cover everything
after an explosion, as if spray painted.
</P>
<P>
   Passersby milled around in the park near St. Mark's Church,
overlooking the rear of the station.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish style entrance of the television station was ripped
away by the blasts, which seemed to hit the roof just under the
large girder tower that holds numerous satellite dishes. Although
the tower and blackened dishes remained, the control rooms and
studios underneath had simply disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and American officials defended the attack as an effort to
undermine the regime of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia,
which they described in unusually harsh terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb TV is as much a part of Milosevic's murder machine as his
military is,'' a spokesman for the Pentagon, Kenneth Bacon, said at
a a briefing in Washington. ``The media is one of the pillars of
Milosevic's power machine. It is right up there with security
forces and the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said NATO was simply trying to destroy the
free marketplace of ideas and ensure that just one side's
``propaganda'' could be propagated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This attempt to dig out our eyes and cut off our ears so that
you will be exposed only to one side, to the factory of lies, will
not be successful,'' a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry , Nebojsa
Vujovic, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new step to silence the truth, to monopolize the
situation and to sideline not only Yugoslav journalists, your
colleagues, but also yourselves,'' Vujovic said, noting that
foreign television journalists needed state television equipment to
file their reports.
</P>
<P>
   That is only partly true, however. The Serb authorities have
generally banned television companies from sending material through
their own equipment without censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini of Italy criticized the attack on
state television, saying, ``It is terrible, and I disapprove of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Serb journalist who is working for a Western agency
said he thought that NATO had crossed an ambiguous moral line.
``NATO began in a very precise, slow way, but now seems to have
lost the distinction between military and civilian targets and
aims,'' the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one thinks of the content of Serb television, he added
tartly, the people who died were not responsible for creating, but
rather only for transmitting the work of others. ``The people who
were there were just doing their jobs, to eat and live,'' he said.
``They have no influence on the content or on Milosevic. I hate
Serb television.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first two years after the Tito regime fell apart, the
television operation tried to be a non-partisan outlet. But
Milosevic turned it back into an instrument of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are not Iraqis,'' he said. ``We can differentiate
between big lies and little ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Andjelko, 35, a factory worker from Rakovice, south of here,
echoed the argument and said, ``I want to change television here by
myself, not have it changed by American bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another journalist who works for state television, and insisted
on anonymity, said that the editor in chief, Dragoljub Milanovic,
left on Thursday at 2 p.m. Despite NATO's warnings that the
television building was a target, Milanovic had made it very clear
to the night shift, the journalist said, that they would be
discharged if they did not report for work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a twist on the mood of general defiance, the main state
television news Friday night did not lead with the destruction of
its building. That report was in the 20th minute of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the first piece described the Serb government's
condemnation of the NATO attack 24 hours earlier, on an official
house of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire nation,'' the government said, ``is with our
president, Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   How the government knows that with such precision was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs in random interviews have said they regard Milosevic
now, however much they may dislike or detest him, as the commander
in chief of a nation that is trying to protect its sovereignty in a
war against the most powerful nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on transmitters throughout Serbia have cut off
television reception in Kosovo and the northern province of
Vojvodina. NATO planes attacked at least three other transmitters
Friday, as well as additional bridges and electrical plants.
</P>
<P>
   Those targets, too, were described by NATO officials as an
integral part of the war effort, even though the electrical power
largely goes to civilians, who are also the main users of the
country's bridges.
</P>
<P>
   NATO appears to be trying to convince Milosevic of the need to
negotiate a peace settlement for Kosovo that will meet Western
demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Bacon said of the Serb population, ``the broad
message is that they should put pressure on their leadership to end
this.''
</P>
<P>
   He made no suggestion, however, on how they should go about
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
