<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY STILL ON GOP AGENDA, SPEAKER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (jw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Dennis Hastert insisted Friday that
Republicans still saw an opportunity to reach a bipartisan
agreement on shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Denying a report in The New York Times on Friday that Republican
leaders in the House had abandoned efforts to deal with Social
Security before the next election, Hastert said he wanted to
encourage both Republicans and Democrats to come forward with ideas
and to find common ground that might lead to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that over time even more ideas emerge and make
their way into the public dialogue so that eventually a bipartisan
solution to strengthening Social Security can be found,'' Hastert,
R-Ill., said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article reported that Republicans in the House had
said that their leaders had decided not to push for passage of the
main piece of legislation drawn up within the party to deal with
Social Security. That bill is being completed by Rep. Bill Archer
of Texas, chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, and Rep. Clay
Shaw Jr. of Florida, chairman of the Social Security subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who had spoken with the party's leadership said they
had been told that in recent polls, many more of those who felt
strongly about Social Security viewed the Republican approach
skeptically than favorably. The Republican approach is built around
private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said they had also been told there was little
point in taking the political risk of voting for changes in a plan
that Democrats have long used to their political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if Hastert was supporting the Archer-Shaw bill,
Pete Jeffries, a spokesman for the speaker, said, ``We are not
going to get locked into any one specific proposal at this time,''
and that Hastert wanted to encourage both Democrats and Republicans
to come forward with ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican leadership and President Clinton now appear
to agree that it is counterproductive to put forward competing,
detailed partisan plans, and that only through some sort of
bipartisan negotiation, perhaps out of public sight, is there any
chance of reaching a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and members of both parties on Capitol
Hill said the prospects for such a deal were dim, especially with
the 2000 elections drawing nearer, the war in the Balkans
distracting both parties and Social Security still expected to show
a surplus for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article also reported that Sen. William Roth, R-Del.,
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, had told colleagues that
he did not intend to move Social Security legislation this year.
Assistants to two Republican senators on Roth's committee said they
had been told by their bosses that Roth had no intention of
bringing up Social Security legislation this year. But a
spokeswoman for Roth, Virginia Flynn, said Friday that Roth had not
made such statements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seized on the suggestion that Republicans might be
backing away from dealing with Social Security to call for further
efforts to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have proposed concrete steps to bolster Social Security and
offered time and again to work with Congress in a bipartisan way to
make the tough choices needed to secure the trust fund over the
long term,'' Clinton said. ``Republican leaders have yet to
consider my proposals or advance any of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while Republicans have endorsed only the general notion
of private accounts as the centerpiece of a redesigned Social
Security system, they have spent considerable time considering
Clinton's proposals, and have rejected them.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Clinton's plan to bolster the retirement
system's finances through an accounting mechanism linked to
reducing the national debt was nothing more than a gimmick that
would still leave future generations of taxpayers on the hook for
benefit payments. And they said Clinton's proposal to allow the
Social Security trust fund to invest a portion of its reserves in
the stock market would amount to government meddling in private
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the White House economic adviser, said, ``If
elements of the Republican leadership now want to put aside the
sniping and truly be constructive on finding bipartisan common
ground, the president said from the start that that's what he'd
like to engage in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
