<HEADLINE>
DEPARTMENT OF JUSTICE SETTLES WITH LAWYER IN BANK FRAUD CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The U.S. Department of Justice has reached a $500,000
settlement _ and could be liable for millions more _ in a case in
which a federal prosecutor and an FBI agent allegedly lied to grand
jurors to win indictments in a mammoth bank fraud case.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Paul Licata received the payment April 16,
three years after U.S. District Judge Kenneth Hoyt acquitted him
and nine others of fraud and conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt found that prosecutors had lied and suppressed evidence
favorable to the defense during grand jury proceedings and after
the indictments were issued.
</P>
<P>
   Although documents state the settlement is not an admission of
guilt, the Justice Department could be vulnerable to malicious
prosecution claims by Licata's co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for at least one has sent a demand letter to the
Justice Department _ the required precursor to a civil lawsuit.
However, another attorney in the case said the statute of
limitations could thwart further action.
</P>
<P>
   Licata's 1997 civil lawsuit said Assistant U.S. Attorney Julia
Hyman lied and withheld exculpatory evidence from the grand jury,
then made at least 66 false statements in the resulting indictment.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Special Agent Thomas Conlon allegedly made at least 10
misleading statements during his testimony. He even created the
impression he had extensive experience as a white-collar crime
investigator, when it was actually his first case, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been one of the most frightening experiences of my
life, seeing what goes on inside the grand jury proceedings,'' said
Leonard Simon, Licata's attorney. ``What she (Hyman) did in that
grand jury room, the hatchet job, was an abuse. She basically lied
to the grand jury and there is no protection against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon refused further comment, saying Licata fears that
statements to the media would result in government retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyman said she has been vilified for doing her job.
</P>
<P>
   An internal investigation by the Justice Department's Office of
Professional Responsibility not only found no wrongdoing, but
confirmed that she acted appropriately. Although internal
investigation findings are normally secret, Hyman said the Justice
Department may issue public findings because of the high-profile
nature of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents said Licata's legal expenses exceeded $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors and agents have been almost impervious to
claims of misconduct, because of the secrecy surrounding
investigations and grand jury proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But public outcry about the tactics of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr and claims by former FBI chemist Frederic Whitehurst
that FBI lab reports were altered to win convictions have raised
concerns that prosecutors and agents breach the boundaries of law
and ethics to justify long and costly investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department attorneys agreed to settle Licata's suit
after a three-day bench trial in December _ before U.S. District
Judge Lynn Hughes rendered a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy and malicious prosecution arose from the criminal
investigation of two failed banks: Memorial and Village Green
National.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had contended the banks were in danger of being
closed during the late 1980s and that 10 men schemed to conceal the
institutions' financial problems from regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Licata maintained that Hyman and Conlon assumed that criminal
activity was involved in the banks' demise, then tailored the
evidence and their remarks to the grand jury to fit that
perception.
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorneys united in asserting that the men had
merely devised an innovative _ and legitimate _ plan to keep the
banks viable.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
