u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIATONE-440&AMP;AD     04-23 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIATONE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMCAST NOT PLANNING ON BIDDING WAR OVER MEDIAONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (rk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors who had hoped that the Comcast Corp. would touch off a
bidding war with a counter offer for Mediaone after Thursday
night's surprise bid from the AT&AMP;T Corp. may be be disappointed.
Comcast executives Friday privately told several Wall Street
executives that it was unlikely the company would sweeten its
initial offer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who had talked with the company did not completely rule
out the possibility that Comcast might yet team up with a
deep-pocket partner to raise the bidding. Friday the company and
its bankers, Salomon Smith Barney, were still exploring options.
</P>
<P>
   But any potential partner would need cash. AT&AMP;T's offer of
roughly $58 billion for Mediaone included about $20 billion in
cash, with the balance in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the offer 17 percent higher than Comcast's all-stock
bid, based on Thursday's closing prices, but it has a ``collar,'' a
guarantee that if the value of its stock drops, AT&AMP;T will cover up
to a 10 percent decline with additional cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect Comcast to counter-offer for the Mediaone
properties,'' said Fred Moran, who follows cable for ING Barings
Furman Selz. ``The AT&AMP;T offer not only represents almost a 20
percent premium to Comcast's offer but also comes with a
substantial cash portion and a collar to protect against downside
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast would have trouble raising cash anywhere near AT&AMP;T's
level. It has roughly $4 billion in debt, against $987 million in
annual cash flow, according to estimates by Jessica Reif, who
follows the company for Merrill Lynch Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's fifth largest cable company, Comcast could raise
some cash by selling assets: it owns a total of about $6.3 billion
in shares of AT&AMP;T, NTLI, SprintPCS and At-Home. But those sales
would trigger heavy capital gains taxes, and would come nowhere
near the the $20 billion in cash AT&AMP;T is offering.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, top Comcast executives, hunkered down on conference
calls between its headquarters in Philadelphia and Salomon Smith
Barney in New York, did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has invested $1 billion in Comcast and could easily
put up more, perhaps by buying newly issued stock. But several
industry experts saw that scenario as unlikely. Besides, they
pointed out, Comcast would walk away from a failed offer, with a
$1.5 billion fee.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast's stock closed down 37.5 cents a share Friday, at
$65.8125. Mediaone's shares jumped $7.875, to $77.375, while AT&AMP;T
fell $3.375 to close at $53.375.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts warned Friday that Comcast stock would surely
be hurt if it raised its offer for Mediaone, since investors had
viewed its initial bid as a full price.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alan Gould, who follows cable for Gerard Klauer Mattison, said
Microsoft's goal when it put $1 billion into Comcast was to
accelerate the cable industry's deployment of high-speed data
services and to improve the chances that Windows CE, a
stripped-down version of its industry-standard operating system,
would be used in the next generation of cable set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft joins Comcast in a losing enhanced bid for
Mediaone, it could jeopardize its chances in the set-top box
market, which will be increasingly dominated by AT&AMP;T. Through its
ownership of Tele-Communications Inc., AT&AMP;T already has 10.7
million subscribers and passes some 18 million homes, and through
TCI's joint ventures with other cable companies, it reaches several
million more. A Microsoft spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has stipulated that no
single cable company may serve more than one third of the 95
million U.S. homes that can receive cable.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T completes the deal for Mediaone, it might pass that
level. Indeed, when AT&AMP;T announced the purchase of TCI last year,
AT&AMP;T's chairman, C. Michael Armstrong, boasted that his company was
gaining access to one third of all cable households, recalled Bruce
Leichtman, who follows AT&AMP;T for The Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is now saying that its purchase of Mediaone would reach 26
percent or 27 percent of homes able to receive cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have simply eliminated the joint ventures,'' Leichtman
said of deals with smaller cable providers like Falcon, Lenfest and
Cablevision . ``They are using the TCI numbers and the Mediaone
number _ about 8.5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T spokeswoman said the affiliates did not count for cable
regulatory measures since TCI did not own and operate them.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Comcast and its bankers and lawyers are tracking the
regulatory issues. But whether they could block the deal is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will certainly raise the eyebrows at the FCC,''
said Leichtman. ``It depends on how much the FCC wants to focus on
cable as opposed to the competition it creates in the phone market
and potentially in the data market.''
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T, the appeal of the deal is the opportunity to offer
local telephone service over a large portion of the United States,
competing with the Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   For Comcast, the AT&AMP;T bid appears to have destroyed a strategy
of becoming one of the three large cable companies along with
AT&AMP;T/TCI, and Time Warner. Comcast, which is controlled by the
Roberts family, has been competing with the Baby Bells to offer
high-speed access to the internet. In an ironic twist, it is doing
that by large-scale implementation of the At-Home cable modem
service, whose largest owner is now AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast could attempt to team up with another cable company, but
several industry experts said Friday that in the end, most cable
operators would probably prefer to strike deals with AT&AMP;T to
deliver local telephone services under the AT&AMP;T brand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
