<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-MAIN24-COX     04-23 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    911 tapes reveal more of horrifying Littleton scene
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ With gunshots booming in the background, a
frightened teacher shouted for her students to take cover under the
library tables. ``He's right outside in the hall,'' the frantic
woman told a 911 police dispatcher in tapes of the Columbine High
School shooting rampage released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the tables, kids, heads under the table,'' she shouted,
her voice edged with terror. ``Oh, God. Oh, God ... I've got the
kids under the table here ... On the floor, everybody, stay on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The panic in her voice helped draw a stark new portrait of
Tuesday's horror, in which students Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, gunned down 12 of their classmates and a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Police released the short excerpts from the four-hour ordeal as
their painstaking investigation continued. After completing 500
interviews with witnesses, about 150 investigators met Friday to
begin the laborious process of sorting through the information,
matching accounts and weighing the credibility of the sources.
</P>
<P>
   Police still wonder whether others might have helped the two
boys, either in preparing for the melee or by helping carry more
than a dozen home-made bombs into the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one, we've been hearing from the students there may
have been a third party,'' Jefferson County Sheriff's Sgt. Jim Parr
said.
</P>
<P>
   But police either don't have any individuals under suspicion, or
if they do, they haven't released that information, Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have not yet reviewed images from the school's video
security cameras, which may shed light on the student accounts of
an additional accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to earlier reports, there were no cameras in the school
library, where much of the killing took place, sheriff's spokesman
Steve Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the first of many memorial services for the slain
students was held, with family and friends of 16-year-old John
Tomlin gathering at Foothills Baptist Church in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he'd do anything for me, but we were going to my prom
and he said dancing was going to be so hard,'' said Tomlin's
girlfriend, Michelle Oetter. ``I miss him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin, who loved his pickup truck and did missionary work in
Mexico for his church, will be buried in his native Wisconsin. More
services are scheduled for the coming days, with a large public
memorial in Denver on Sunday. Vice President Al Gore plans to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy's impact continued to ripple across the country,
with schools in several states reporting bomb threats, hate calls
and other incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The national debate over what parents and educators can do to
stop future school violence intensified.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced an initiative that will bring more
police officers to schools. He also made $1.5 million available to
help Littleton schools and law enforcement agencies in the
aftermath of the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Mayor Wellington Webb called on the National Rifle
Association, the nation's largest gun lobby, to cancel its upcoming
meeting scheduled in the Colorado capital. The group had offered to
scale the meeting back from three days to one, but Webb said that
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   He angrily dismissed NRA President Charlton Heston's comment
that the Columbine tragedy could have been avoided if armed guards
had been stationed outside the school. The mayor said the Hollywood
actor's statements didn't deserve the dignity of a response.
</P>
<P>
   A few more details emerged in reports about the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Former friends describe Eric Harris as a shy preteen when he
lived in Plattsburgh, N.Y., in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to reports that Harris targeted athletes and
minorities in his shooting frenzy, ``That's not the kid I
remember,'' Mike Condo, who played Little League baseball with
Harris, told the Denver Post. ``His best friends back then were ...
an Asian kid ... and a black kid. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Littleton girl who dated Harris four years ago said he and his
friends in the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' were hassled at school in the
past year by athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere they went, they were taunted and teased about how
they dressed, about being gay,'' Tiffany Typher said. ``You could
tell he'd get upset by it.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no reports that Harris was gay, but apparently
that reference was used as an insult by some students.
</P>
<P>
   Typher recalled that Harris behaved in a weird fashion when she
broke up with him. A mutual friend called her to his house, she
said, where he lay in the back yard with fake blood spattered
around him, as if he had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shook me up,'' she admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend told television reporters that Harris' life ``in
a shambles'' because he hadn't been accepted by any college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric wasn't very happy with everything that was going on in
his life,'' Pat McDuffee, 17, said on the ``Leeza'' talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a girlfriend. I don't think he was getting
along with his parents. I think he just got fired from his job. His
life was pretty much in a shambles, and I think he conned Dylan
into going in with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The two boys worked together as cooks at the Blackjack Pizza
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Harris also reportedly wrote an essay for a psychology class
detailing a dream in which he and Klebold went on a shooting
rampage in their school.
</P>
<P>
   The essay was an eerie parallel to a video the two made for
another class, in which they used play guns to shoot other students
in the school hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had an older brother who was apparently a successful
athlete at Columbine and went on to college, friends said.
Psychologists say that growing up in the shadow of a successful
older sibling can be difficult on teen-agers. In fact, in at least
two of the other recent school tragedies, the shooters were less
successful younger brothers of popular siblings.
</P>
<P>
   School officials announced Friday that Columbine students would
finish their academic year at nearby Chatfield High School,
attending afternoon sessions after the Chatfield students have
departed.
</P>
<P>
   Classes will begin next Thursday, in what is certain to be an
emotional reunion for the shaken students and staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it is very important that they are together,
that they are there to support each other,'' Jefferson County
Schools Superintendent Jane Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
