<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     04-23 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ CONTINUES TO CLIMB ON STRONG EARNINGS REPORTS
</P>
<P>
   After setting a high Thursday, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index slid 1.97 points, to 1,356.85. The Dow Jones industrial
average dropped 37.51 points, to 10,689.67. The Nasdaq composite
index, which includes many computer companies, climbed 29.08
points, or 1.14 percent, to 2,590.69, capping its second-best
four-day gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Computer shares rallied for a fourth day on optimism about
profits, while AT&AMP;T pulled the Dow Jones industrial average lower
on concern that the phone company's $58 billion bid for Mediaone
would hurt earnings. IBM soared over 200 before settling at 199},
up 5\. The computer maker gained $28 billion in market value this
week after reporting higher-than-expected profit and sales.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCK FULL O'NUTS SHARES ACQUIRED
</P>
<P>
   Three directors of Chock Full o'Nuts, including the 84-year-old
chairman, bought company stock in the months after they rejected an
unsolicited takeover offer from Sara Lee, but before that offer was
disclosed to the public. The suitor remains interested, however,
and this week disclosed that it had approached the company
recently, sending the stock up almost 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MERCK PROFITS INCREASE 12 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter earnings at Merck &AMP; Co. jumped 12 percent, to $1.3
billion, on gains in the sale of key prescription products and
growth of its drug benefits business. Sales rose 24 percent, to
$7.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES OPENS A PLANT IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler opened a factory to produce Mercedes-Benz cars
in Brazil. DaimlerChrysler, which already assembles Dodge pickup
trucks at a plant in southern Brazil, hopes to produce at least
25,000 A-Class compact cars in the first year at its $820 million
factory. If the Brazilian economy manages to grow next year,
company officials said they could almost triple annual output to
70,000 by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   DEBT-RELIEF PLAN IS NOT WORKING
</P>
<P>
   With the number of people living on under $1 a day likely to
reach 1.5 billion next year, five major industrialized powers _ the
United States, Canada, France, Germany and Britain _ have
acknowledged that a plan devised three years ago to forgive debts
of the poorest countries is not working well.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOROS DECLARES FINANCIAL CRISIS OVER
</P>
<P>
   Financier George Soros declared the global financial crisis over
and said that Brazil's $2-billion bond sale showed that the world's
financial markets had recovered after their recent turmoil.
Brazil's sale of five-year bonds marked the first time the country
tapped international capital markets since last April. The bonds
were priced on Thursday to yield 11.88 percent, 6.75 percentage
points more than United States Treasury securities of comparable
maturity.
</P>
<P>
   LOSSES AT JAPAN'S BROKERAGE FIRMS
</P>
<P>
   Japan's biggest brokerage firms reported huge losses for the
year. Nomura Securities cited a $3.3-billion loss on its overseas
bond trading and aid to an affiliate. Daiwa Securities, Japan's
second-biggest brokerage firm, and Nikko Securities also reported
losses for a third year, as they too wrote off bad loans at
financing affiliates and closed most of their overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY EAST TO BUY GAS COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Energy East plans to acquire Connecticut Energy, which is based
in Bridgeport, Conn., for about $617 million in stock and in cash.
Energy East, based in Ithaca, N.Y., said Connecticut Energy
shareholders would receive $42 a share and can specify the
percentage they wish to receive in stock and in cash.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI GROUP PLANNING TO REVAMP
</P>
<P>
   The Hyundai Group plans to reduce the number of its subsidiaries
to 26 from 79 by 2003 through sales and mergers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
