<HEADLINE>
$41 MILLION AWARDED IN 1997 TRAFFIC PILE-UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A jury awarded $41.2 million in damages Friday over a
deadly highway pileup and primarily blamed a construction company,
saying it failed to post adequate warnings that could have
prevented the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The British company, Balfour Beatty Construction, was found 75
percent liable for the Jan. 27, 1997, accident on Interstate 10 in
Chambers County that killed two Colorado men and caused brain
injury to their friend.
</P>
<P>
   The trio _ computer engineers and entrepreneurs _ were driving
to Houston to catch a flight home after watching the Super Bowl in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated for about 11/2 days before returning their
10-2 verdict in state district court.
</P>
<P>
   About $34 million was awarded to the brain-injured man, Stephen
Eugene Parkhouse, 32, of Highlands Ranch, Colo., co-founder of a
computer consulting company. The remainder of the award went to the
three men's families.
</P>
<P>
   The four-vehicle pileup killed Michael Scott Ragsdale, 32, of
Littleton and Michael George Devoy, 38, of Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might now ease their plight,'' said lead plaintiffs'
attorney Kevin Krist, who called the verdict one of the largest in
state history for only actual damages.
</P>
<P>
   Krist's father, Ronald, who helped represent the plaintiffs,
said the verdict sends a message that ``when taxpayers pay millions
of dollars for highway construction and the construction company
does not provide the safety measures it is required to provide, the
injured parties will be compensated.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury assessed the remaining 25 percent of the award against
Peter Reagan, driver of a tractor-trailer that plowed into the
men's rental minivan, and his employer, Luciano Refrigerated
Transport of Houma, La.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, of Eades, Tenn., was driving his 18-wheeler too fast for
the congested conditions, the jury said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
