<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
911 TAPES RELEASED AS POLICE CONTINUE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct slug; no other changes)  (lh) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ ``The school's in a panic, and I'm in the
library,'' the teacher is desperately trying to explain to the
police dispatcher as she begs for help. ``I've got students down
...
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the table, kids!'' she says now, directing her attention
back to the students who, moments before, had been quietly studying
in the library at Columbine High School. ``Kids, under the table.
Kids, stay on the floor ... Oh, God. Oh, God _ kids, just stay
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher's frantic voice, heard as gunfire reverberates in
the background, was part of a tape recording made public by the
police on Friday of some of the emergency calls placed Tuesday as
two students began their lethal rampage through the school, in
which they killed 12 fellow students _ 10 of them in the library
from which the teacher placed her desperate phone call _ and one
teacher before turning the guns on themselves. The teacher on the
phone, whom police identified on Friday only by her first name,
Peggy, survived the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes were made public as the police continued with dozens
of interviews aimed at finding out whether, as many investigators
here strongly believe, the two young men had help in preparing for
their attack or in bringing more than 30 home-made explosive
devices into the school. But while many of the killers' friends and
acquaintances have been questioned, no arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also said on Friday that they believed the two,
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, may have wandered through the school
after their initial attack in the library for up to an hour before
returning to that room to kill themselves. Some students had made
their escape while many others remained barricaded inside other
classrooms during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Owens, who toured the school Thursday night, said on
Friday that ``the devastation is difficult to exaggerate,'' and
said that many of the most haunting sights were the most ordinary
ones, from books left open on their desks to computers still
switched on.
</P>
<P>
   ``One young woman had been filling out an application to the
University of Denver,'' the governor said in an interview. ``Next
to it she had a to-do list. Monday was all checked off. She was
halfway through Tuesday. One of the items on the list was to write
her life story.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, the Jefferson County district
attorney, David Thomas, interrupted his briefings on the status of
the investigation to offer an emotional plea to reporters and the
nation at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to most of the families in this case, and they
said there has to be some meaning to this, this has to result in
something,'' Thomas said. ``These deaths cannot be in vain. We
can't walk away from here here and wait for the next incident to
occur and then go cover that incident and not learn from this.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 50, suggested that part of the problem was the easy
availability of guns in this country. ``The kinds of things that
were involved in this case were simply _ it was so simple to get
them,'' he said. ``Guns are everywhere. You can buy them on the
street. You can get them anywhere you want. You can steal them.
They're readily available. You can go to gun shows. You can have
your friends go to gun shows if you're underage. They're very easy
to acquire.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
