<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LOWER GREAT EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis is the first one to admit it: The Lakers are
no longer talking about, least of all expecting, a championship
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, the goal is still there. But the Lakers' sights are
set on a decidedly more realistic objective _ improving. It's been
Rambis' mantra for the last week, and he's standing by it. As for
the once-talked-about championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we started off the season with a team that had a
good chance to go to that level,'' he said. ``With all of the
changes that happened, I think the expectations of the team had to
change, because you have to go through an adjustment period of
getting all these new guys on the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the disruptions that we went through, it's just not
fair to stick the same expectations on the team that started the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony here, of course, is that those very ``disruptions'' _
the signing of Dennis Rodman, the firing of coach Del Harris, the
trade that brought Glen Rice _ were supposed to be moves that would
improve the Lakers' championship prospects. Now those same moves
are acknowledged as hindrances to reaching that goal.
</P>
<P>
   So with six games left in the regular season, the Lakers in
fifth place in the Western Conference and about to face the two
teams just ahead of them (San Antonio and Houston), Rambis
continues to preach that victories are of secondary importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a state of growth and improvement. I don't know
why that's a hard thing to understand,'' he said. ``I'm not gonna
panic _ `Oh, we have to win a championship, therefore we have to be
playing perfect basketball by tomorrow.' I mean, you can't put that
type of pressure on a team to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the basketball games to me are not near as important
as improvement. The best example I can give is, if (the opponent's)
whole starting five goes out and we win the basketball game but we
play (poorly), that doesn't do us any good. So that's the way I
look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have bought into the new mindset, painful as it may
be to lower their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard,'' Shaquille O'Neal admitted.
</P>
<P>
   And he hesitated when asked if the Lakers could still win a
championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just have to get better. It's still too early,'' he
said. ``We just have to get better and play smart. We play like we
played the last couple games, no. But if we play smart, then
yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Rick Fox, out the last three games because of a
sore right knee, did not travel with the team to San Antonio on
Friday. He was sent to the Kerlan-Jobe Orthopaedic Clinic for an
MRI. Results were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't certain if Fox would rejoin the team on this trip,
which ends Monday night in Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
