<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-23 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
911 TAPE   TELLS CHLLING TALE OF MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The horror inside Columbine High School came
chillingly to life Friday as authorities released a ``911'' tape in
which a faculty member pleads for help and tries desperately to
protect students in the library just before it became a killing
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, authorities said surveillance videos from a camera
near the school's cafeteria might help investigators determine
whether presumed killers Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold had help in
their killing spree.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have said they doubted Harris and
Klebold alone could have hauled into the school four guns and more
than 30 bombs, ranging from homemade hand grenades to specially
rigged 20-pound propane tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Several students said Friday in interviews they saw a third
gunman, and at least two media outlets reported that officials had
identified a third suspect. Authorities, however, continued to
maintain they have no evidence of co-conspirators and were still
reviewing the surveillance tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal authorities said one of the guns used in the
massacre was a semi-automatic pistol whose manufacture has been
banned by federal law. The gun is the TEC DC-9, a foot-long weapon
with magazines that can carry up to 32 cartridges. Though illegal
to manufacture, sales of existing weapons are legal.
</P>
<P>
   The other weapons used were two illegal sawed-off shotguns and a
9mm semiautomatic carbine, officials said. The same type of gun was
used in last year's Jonesboro, Ark., schoolyard massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sheriff Steve Davis said federal authorities have traced
the pistol and the carbine to their original owners, but have not
tracked subsequent sales. No links have been found to the presumed
killers or their families. Tracking the shotguns will be more
difficult, he said, because they might have been manufactured as
long ago as the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``911'' tape, a faculty member identified only as Peggy
tells a dispatcher that an armed intruder is approaching the
library, and she and her students are hiding under tables. ``Oh
God, oh God, he's right outside!...I am on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you've the kids there?'' the dispatcher asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got every student in this library on the floor,'' she
says, her breaths growing short and her voice frantic as she calls
to the students: ``And you better stay on the floor!''
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher asks: ``Is there any way you can lock the
doors?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, smoke is coming from out there, and I'm a little ...,''
Peggy says. Just then, seven gunshots ring out. ``My God, the gun
is right outside the library door! ... I don't think I'm going to
go out there, OK. I've got three children, OK...''
</P>
<P>
   Dispatcher: ``We have paramedics and we have fire and we have
police en route.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape ends, but there was little question what happened
shortly thereafter. Ten of the 13 victims died in the library,
where witnesses say the gunmen first told athletes to stand up and
then targeted a black student, Isaiah Shoels, for execution. Harris
and Klebold also died in the library, apparently from
self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy, the faculty member, apparently suffered a shoulder
injury, either from flying glass or debris before the shooters
entered the library.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also released the tape of a 911 call from an
unidentified female student outside the school in which she asks
for help and describes a chaotic scene. ``Some girl is on the
ground. I think she's paralyzed,'' the girl says. ``People are
running out of the school like mad right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're out of the way of danger, aren't you?'' the dispatcher
asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe so, I don't know,'' she answers. Davis said the
young caller was uninjured.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators spent much of Friday meeting to review their
findings, sharing notes from the crime scene and more than 500
interviews with witnesses, victims' families, and others. More than
150 officers from local, state, and federal agencies remained on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Among the investigators in Littleton Friday were two Los Angeles
sheriff's deputies who were invited by local authorities to help
evaluate the response of Colorado SWAT teams. Those teams have
faced criticism over their decision Tuesday to wait until the
shooting inside the school stopped _ roughly an hour after it began
_ before entering in force. Officials here have defended their
tactics, noting that it was not a hostage situation and suggesting
that an ill-timed assault might have caused even more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a second day of heavy wet snow, a steady stream of
mourners continued making their way to the school grounds,
traipsing through slushy, muddy patches of grass to place flowers,
leave a teddy bear, or pause to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Several visitors Friday cried when discussing reports that one
of the victims, 17-year-old Cassie Bernall, engaged in a brief,
tragic colloquy with her killer. He reportedly asked, ``Do you
believe in God,'' punctuating his question by pointing a gun at
her. She answered, ``Yes, I believe in God.'' He responded,
``Why?'' then shot her dead before she could respond.
</P>
<P>
   The Foothills Bible Church was packed with more than 900
mourners Friday as the first memorial service was held for one of
the victims, 16-year-old sophomore John Tomlin, whose beloved Chevy
pickup truck has become a shrine in the school parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   His deeply religious parents, a sister, and a brother sat in the
front pew, dressed in black and looking exhausted. A funeral for
Tomlin will be held in his native Wisconsin. ``In September, I
don't know why, I guess God just put it on my mind. I asked John,
if you died, where would you want to be buried? And he told me,
Wisconsin, of course, Mom,'' his mother told the mourners.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Friday that Columbine would not reopen
before the end of the school year. Students will finish the
semester at Chatfield High School, where students have embraced
their crosstown rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, authorities released reports written on Harris and
Klebold upon their completion of an 11-month juvenile diversion
program. The two were required to undergo the program after being
charged with first-degree criminal trespass, theft, and criminal
mischief, for allegedly breaking into a car March 25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, written just two months ago, were glowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is a very bright young man who is likely to succeed in
life,'' an unidentified officer wrote of Harris. ``He is
intelligent enough to achieve lofty goals as long as he stays on
task and remains motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   The report on Klebold called him ``solid'' and ``motivated,''
adding: ``Dylan is a bright young man with a great deal of
potential. If he is able to tap his potential and become
self-motivated, he should do well in life.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the diversion program, both also were required to
perform 45 hours of community service, the details of which were
not disclosed. They also underwent regular testing for alcohol and
drugs. District Attorney Dave Thomas said he did not know the
results of those tests, but believed that their success in
completing the program indicated they tested clean.
</P>
<P>
   Harris also was required to undergo individual counseling; the
records were not clear on what mental health evaluations were
required for Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the officer who wrote the report is ``anguishing
over what happened here.'' Thomas declined to name him.
</P>
<P>
   Information from numerous media sources also shed new light on
their families and backgrounds. Klebold, who other students said
professed admiration for Adolph Hitler, was the great-grandson of a
Jewish philanthropist from Ohio, the late Leo Yassenoff. Klebold's
father, Thomas, 52, is a former geophysicist who runs a mortgage
management business. His wife, Susan, works for the Colorado
community-college system, helping disabled students.
</P>
<P>
   Harris moved to Littleton in 1996 from Plattsburgh, N.Y. His
father, Wayne, was an Air Force pilot who now works in a
flight-safety business. His mother, Katherine, worked for a
catering company, according to court documents and media reports.
</P>
<P>
   In televised interviews Friday, members of the ``Trench Coat
Mafia,'' the outcast group to which Harris and Klebold belonged,
sought to distance themselves from the shootings and explain the
killers' actions. ``We were just a group of friends who hung out
like anyone else,'' said group member Joseph Stair. ``We received a
lot of persecution from the athletes in the school. I guess they
just got pushed too far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
