<HEADLINE>
911 CALLS TELL OF TERROR IN HIGH SCHOOL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ A frantic, breathless teacher tried to keep
students safe in a school library while calling 911 for help as two
other students door blasted classmates with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God (deep breath). Oh, God. Kids, just stay down!'' the
teacher, identified only as Peggy, said while talking to emergency
dispatchers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson County Sheriff's Department released Friday a
recording of the teacher's desperate call for help, along with
another 911 call and recordings of police radio transmissions
during the siege at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher was in the library at 11:20 a.m. Tuesday when Eric
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, stormed the school spraying
gunfire and igniting homemade bombs. They killed 12 students and a
faculty member, then fatally shot themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims were found in the cafeteria and library
along with the bodies of Harris and Klebold, members of a clique
known as the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   As the emergency dispatch operator tried to calm the panicked
teacher, at least six gunshots were recorded in the background of
the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anyone been injured?'' the dispatcher asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes and the school is in a panic, and I'm in the library,
and I've got... (yelling at the students) Get down under the table,
kids! Heads under the tables!'' the teacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Recomposing herself, the teacher continued: ``Kids are screaming
and the teachers are, you know, trying to take control of things.
We need police here.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher assured her help was on the way and tried to get
a better description of who was shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who the student is,'' the teacher said. ``I was
on hall duty. I saw a gun. I said, `What's going on out there?' And
a kid that was probably from video production told me it's a joke.
And I said, `Well, I don't think that's a good idea,' and I went
walking outside to see what was going on. He turned the gun
straight at us and shot, and my God, the window went out. And the
kid standing there, I think he got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher told the dispatcher the shooter was right outside
the library door and alarms were going off in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's smoke,'' she said. ``My God, smoke is, like, coming
into this room. I've got the kids under the table here. I don't
know what's going on in the rest of the building. I'm sure someone
must be calling 911 besides me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County officials said at 11:21 a.m. they received five
calls reporting an explosion in the area of the school located in
this suburban community southwest of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:25 a.m. a Columbine High School custodian told
Jefferson County officer Neil Gardner, who was on duty at the
school, that an explosion had occurred in the southwest parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 10 minutes, a number of callers, including the
teacher, clogged the county's emergency center lines.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher was able to give authorities a chilling account of
what was happening as the dispatcher tried to calm her fears while
asking for detailed descriptions to pass along to officers arriving
at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatcher: ``We need to know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``OK. I am on the floor and I've got every student in
this library on the floor _ (shouts at students) You guys stay on
the floor!''
</P>
<P>
   Dispatcher: ``Is there any way you can lock the door?''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``Smoke is coming in from out there, and I'm a (shot
goes off) little afraid (two more shots) the gun (three more shots)
is right outside the library door. I don't think I'm going to go
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds of the tape were inaudible, but the teacher
decided to try to get to the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to go to the door, just to the door,'' she said.
``OK, I've got the kids on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not release the rest of the teacher's call but
said she was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first calls emergency workers received was from a
Columbine student who reported a girl was hurt in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who was not identified, calmly gave information
about where students were fleeing from the building. She told
dispatchers she did not see what happened, but saw students running
and went to the phone to call for help for the injured girl.
</P>
<P>
   The other recording released by the sheriff's department
contained a series of police radio transmissions, mostly officers
arriving at the location and seeing one of the gunmen in a trench
coat on the second floor of the school.
</P>
<P>
   It also contained Gardner's account of exchanging gunfire with
one of the suspects in a parking lot as the assault began, and the
dispatcher telling other officers that Gardner was under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was not wounded and apparently did not hit either of the
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a couple of shots off at the shooter,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   He later told the dispatcher, ``It's a big gun.`` &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
