<HEADLINE>
REED TO LEAVE UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After two seasons of scattered play and sporadic
playing time, sophomore power forward Travis Reed will transfer
from UCLA, the Bruins announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, a 6-foot-6 Fontana native, averaged 15.9 minutes and 5.4
points as a reserve last season. He is considering Long Beach State
and UC Santa Barbara, UCLA sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's departure leaves the Bruins with four frontcourt players
next season: center Dan Gadzuric and forwards Jerome Moiso, Matt
Barnes and Sean Farnham. In addition, small forward JaRon Rush can
play power forward if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Reed could not be reached for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-FAMILY24-COX     04-23 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-FAMILY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pain of loss won't go away easily for slain teen's family,
friends
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The first picture in the photo montage was of
John and his little brother, Patrick, wearing blanket sleepers and
grinning at the camera. John was maybe 6 and Patrick, 4.
</P>
<P>
   They looked rosy-cheeked and ready for bed, the grins letting
whichever parent was holding the camera know they wouldn't make
going to bed easy that night.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years, John Robert Tomlin's grin hadn't changed much _ it
still was wide and generous and let people know that he was a nice
guy but he wouldn't make going to bed easy.
</P>
<P>
   The photo montage of John's life that flashed across screens in
the chapel of Foothills Bible Church on Friday morning was part of
his memorial service, the first of 12 that will be held over the
next week. He will be buried next week in Kenosha, Wis., where he
was born and lived until age 12.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin was one of 12 students murdered Tuesday morning at
Columbine High School. He was 16. The two boys who shot the 12
students _ Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris _ also died, apparently
from self-inflicted gunshot wounds. A teacher, Dave Sanders, was
killed in the attack as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was a 16-year-old killed simply because he went to school
Tuesday morning,'' said Rev. Bill Oudemolen, senior pastor at
Foothills Bible Church. ``Even though we know the facts, we may
never be able to make sense of this senseless slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday John's family and friends seemed weighed down by that
idea, that this may never make sense. They bent against the
persistent snow that fell all morning as they entered the church,
wiping their eyes and trying not to slip in the slush. Several men
attacked the snow on the sidewalks with a fervor that comes from
desperately needing to have something _ anything _ to do.
</P>
<P>
   The chapel filled quickly with friends from John's church youth
group, extended family members, people who knew him from school.
They sat close and touched each other often, needing the comfort of
human contact. A woman patrolled the aisles, handing out full boxes
of tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Before the family entered the chapel, Garth Brooks' song ``The
Dance'' played over the chapel's audio system, and people knew what
Brooks meant when he sang, ``For a moment, all the world was right,
how could I ever have known you'd say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   John left so quickly they didn't hear him go, just heard the
echo of his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, John and Doreen, clung to each other as they
entered the chapel. Patrick trailed behind them, his young face
crumpled in grief, looking older than 14 in a black suit. John's
sister, Ashley, 11, carried a light brown teddy bear and sobbed.
Other people followed, including John's best friend, Brandon Sokol,
18, and girlfriend, Michelle Oetter, 18, who carried John's Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible symbolized what people said was John's absolute
devotion to God. Last summer he went on a mission trip to Juarez,
Mexico, to help build houses for the people there ``and after that
trip, and the Lord's working on him, John recommitted his life to
Jesus Christ,'' Oudemolen said. ``He told his friends he wanted to
dedicate his life to serving God.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Youngblood, one of John's good friends, said John was a
hard worker ``who set an example for me to get a job done right,''
he said. ``He was very courteous and thoughtful and always extended
a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll never forget the first time I met him at (Arapahoe
Acres). The first thing he said to me was, 'Ford or Chevy?' I said
Ford, and I think he was ashamed of me,'' Youngblood added,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   John loved Chevys, particularly his _ a yellow-orange colored
truck, tough like an old junkyard dog. In honor of his friend and
the times they spent driving around to dealerships looking at
Chevys, Brandon wore a black baseball cap with a red Chevy insignia
on it to the memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``John had a grin that you couldn't help smiling when you saw
him smiling,'' Michelle said. ``I thank God for allowing me to be
part of his life, and I'm grateful for how John's life and death
brought so many people together and to Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the service was over, the more than 600 people in
attendance filed past his family, hugging them, crying with them
and offering to do anything, anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't leave the church with answers _ nobody knows why
what happened did, why a 16-year-old with an I-won't-go-to-bed-easy
grin lost his life when the whole thing still stretched unwritten
before him, why the emptiness and hurt and heartsickness weren't
going away.
</P>
<P>
   But they knew their lives were better for having known John
Robert Tomlin, the boy who loved Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
