<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-23 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LITTLETON, Colo.: to acquire.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia B. Holloway, who as chairwoman of the Jefferson County
Board of Commissioners is expected to help set up a gubernatorial
task force on school violence, said in an interview on Friday: ``We
have got to make parents responsible. Parents have got to start
communicating. They've got to take control. Some of these children
are so belligerent. They've been given free rein. Everyone's afraid
to stand up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Littleton, the first of more than a dozen memorial and
funeral services that this community will have to cope with took
place Friday morning, when John Robert Tomlin Jr., a 16-year-old
sophomore who was murdered in the library, was mourned by a crowd
of 500 people at Foothills Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend, Michelle Oetter, tried to speak at the service.
``He had a grin. You just couldn't help smiling when he smiled,''
she said. ``He treated me like I was the queen of the world. He
spent so much money driving back and forth to my house, but he told
me I was worth it.'' But then she broke down into deep, shaking
sobs and was helped away from the front of the church by two of
Tomlin's best friends.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Bill Oudemolen addressed the family and friends of
Tomlin, telling them: ``A 16-year-old was killed simply because he
went to school in the morning. Kids are not supposed to kill kids.
Schools are supposed to be safe zones, not killing fields.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tomlin Sr., the dead boy's father, spoke briefly to
reporters afterward and conveyed this message: ``For the families
of the children who did this, we are praying for them. We feel no
hatred for them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the mourning continued, there was some news of recovery.
Mikai Hall, a junior wounded in the leg by a shotgun blasts,
appeared with his parents on Friday and spoke briefly at St.
Anthony Central Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know that I am going to get better,'' said
Hall. Expressing bewilderment at the incident, he said of Klebold,
one of the perpetrators who killed himself: ``Dylan was in French
class of mine. Dylan, I thought he was an all-right guy. I worked
with him sometimes. He is not the kind of person he is being
portrayed as. He was a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering an account that paralleled that of the audiotapes made
public, Hall said: ``I remember a teacher running into the library
screaming that some kids had guns, so everyone got under their
desks pretty quick. A few minutes after that, two people came in
and started shooting. They fired a number of shots, and one hit me
and I laid on the ground. They moved towards me. That's all I can
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   County officials released the tapes in part to address questions
raised by students, parents and reporters about whether the
building could have been secured any earlier, possibly leading to
earlier rescues of students who lay grievously wounded inside.
Police officials have resolutely defended their response to the
incident, saying they surrounded the building but held off entering
for fear that they might have set off a new gunfight that could
have led to even more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes came with a timeline indicating that first sheriff's
deputies on the scene were there within three minutes of the first
emergency call.
</P>
<P>
   They were responding to a call from an unidentified student who
said she believed there was someone with a gun loose in the school.
``I just saw everyone running out,'' she said on the tape. ``People
are running out of the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the call from the teacher, who said there were two
gunmen. ``I do not know them,'' she said, her voice rising in fear.
``He turned the gun straight at him ... and I think he got hit in
the right shoulder. Oh, God! Oh, God.!''
</P>
</TEXT>
