<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SENIORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HORRIFIC CIRCUMSTANCE, SENSE OF LOST POMP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo. Ark., Ariz., Okla., Britain)   (jw) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Autumn Hettinger, 18, and her mother, Cheryl,
baked a cake Friday to celebrate Shakespeare's birthday, just as
Autumn had planned to do all along for her advanced-placement
English class. She wore her special English class famous writers
T-shirt that says Homer on the front and lists everyone from
Chaucer to Wordsworth on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Autumn is fighting to reclaim her senior year at Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night she joined a crowd of Columbine teachers and
students in shouting the school cheer and singing the school fight
song (``Fight on for CHS, for we will win over all the rest'') at a
rally at the West Bowles Community Church here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole feeling was that two gunmen took our school, and
we're going to take it back,'' Autumn said. The two gunmen, who
ended their bloody rampage by committing suicide, were two of her
classmates, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. Autumn had had Dylan in
her second-period calculus class this semester, and Eric in
third-period philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Autumn and her fellow seniors would have been the first class to
graduate from a renovated and modernized Columbine, but now their
school, bullet-riddled and blood-stained, has been closed
indefinitely. The seniors learned Friday that they, along with
everyone else, will finish out the year at a neighboring high
school. But Autumn, who was on the pom squad her junior year,
declared: ``Columbine is more than just the name of our school.
It's our community. I'm still graduating from Columbine. I'm still
a senior.''
</P>
<P>
   Like seniors everywhere, the Columbine Class of '99 had waited a
long time for this year, when finally they would be on top at their
school, when they got some of the best teachers, when they could
get a space in the parking lot, when after all the hard work and
pushing to get into college they could finally kick back and cruise
toward graduation.
</P>
<P>
   They had already gotten their blue and silver class sweat
shirts, with the names of all 443 seniors, including Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold, on the back. They had danced the night away at
the prom on Saturday night, and played carnival games at the
traditional after-prom party in the gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   They had selected their class flower (tiger lily), the class
colors (yellow and purple) and the class song (``Time of Your
Life'' by Green Day). They had chosen the class mom, Cheryl Lucas,
an English teacher, and the class dad, Troy Manuello, who teaches
physics. They were looking forward to Class Day, May 21, when the
class mom and dad give inspirational speeches, and awards are
handed out for best smile, best hair, cutest couple, worst driver.
(Autumn had a hunch her friends had put her in for the Mario
Andretti award, though she says she does not speed in her 1989
Honda Civic.) They were counting down the days till May 22,
Graduation Day.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in the aftermath of the massacre that left 15 among
them dead, including the two gunmen and a teacher, the anticipation
of the final rituals of the waning senior year, the parties, the
yearbook signing, the graduation ceremony itself, the
postgraduation senior trip to Mexico, has given way to prayer
services and funerals, to a media encampment and daily updates on a
huge police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Haney, a senior who sings in the concert choir and was in
the choir room when the shooting began, was crying on Thursday as
she stood in the wet snow beside the memorial piles of flowers and
cards outside the high school with her mother, Teri Haney, and her
grandmother, Pat Brewster. She was mourning not only the dead but
the irrevocably altered collective history of her class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so sad,'' she said. ``Everything was going so great, but
now all anyone is going to remember is this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Haney said she and her daughter had had their own ritual
for marking the days left in the school year. ``She would call me
at work every Monday and say only five more Mondays till
graduation, only four more Mondays, only three more Mondays,'' said
Mrs. Haney, who handles tax reports in a mutual funds office.
</P>
<P>
   For Mindy, who will attend Harding University in Arkansas in the
fall, it had been a carefree time. ``I knew where I was going to
college,'' she said. ``I didn't have to worry about all that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her best friend, Janelle Behan, also a senior, and a
member of the concert choir, were planning a post-graduation road
trip to Arizona, Mindy's first to that state, to visit Janelle's
cousins. With the days flying past, Mindy still could hardly
believe she was a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always looked forward to being a senior,'' she said. ``It
always seemed like they were so cool. They just all stuck together,
and they were all friends, and they seemed so old. It seems so
weird that now we're seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   As they listened to her talk, Mindy's mother and grandmother
said they remembered their own senior years, Mrs. Haney's at
Arapahoe High School in Littleton 23 years ago, Mrs. Brewster's at
Will Rogers High School in Tulsa, Okla., 42 years ago. All these
years later, both women said, they remembered it as a perfect time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just make sure hers is still special,'' Mrs. Brewster
said, wrapping her arm around her granddaughter. A graduation
barbecue is in the works, with relatives coming from all over
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another senior, Dan Holsey, brought a bouquet of flowers to lay
on the sprawling memorial, soaked with rain and snow. ``I really
didn't get to finish my senior year,'' he said. ``Even if school
did start up again, I don't think I could go back in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan, a shy, polite 18-year-old who was shivering in the cold in
his short-sleeved shirt, said he had waited a long time to be a
senior. ``I feel like everyone's looking up to me,'' he said. He
said sometimes underclassmen left soda cans in the cafeteria. ``I
told them to clean up, you don't want our school looking trashy.''
</P>
<P>
   And after working hard all year, he was able to relax this
semester. His classes included video productions, psychology,
physics, international foods and bowling. Bowling? ``Yeah, it's a
class,'' Dan said with a sheepish smile.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead he was honoring was Lauren Townsend, a senior who
had been the captain of the volleyball team and a National Merit
Scholar and who, rumor had it, was bound to be class valedictorian.
Lauren was in Autumn Hettinger's advanced-placement English class,
and they had both been in the group that had gone to England in
March on the English class trip. Autumn's mother had gone along as
a chaperone. ``Lauren came to Windsor Castle with my mom and me,''
said Autumn, who will attend the University of Colorado at Boulder
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to remember Windsor Castle, she said, and all the
other highlights from her senior year: the boys' and girls' soccer
teams going to the state finals, the school play, ``Oklahoma,'' the
prom. ``I wore a black dress with spaghetti straps and a train,''
Autumn said. ``We had a limo. I felt like a princess.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as anyone knows, graduation is still scheduled for May 22
in the usual place, the Fiddlers Green amphitheater. ``We don't
want Columbine to be remembered for the massacre,'' Autumn said.
``We want to be remembered for how we stuck together. We want to be
remembered for the love we have for each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
