<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-THREATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPYCAT THREATS LEAD TO SWIFT RESPONSES ACROSS U.S .
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Md., Pa., Wash., Calif., Texas, N.Y., Conn.)  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A wave of copycat threats of violence prompted by the Tuesday
massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., led school
and law-enforcement officials across the country to respond quickly
to any new sign of trouble, even if the threats were pranks brought
on by a dose of youthful spring fever.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of students were suspended, some for wearing black trench
coats like those worn by the two Columbine seniors who killed a
dozen classmates and a teacher before turning their guns on
themselves. Others were arrested for more serious offenses, such as
calling in bomb threats to force the closing of schools, carrying
guns and threatening students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The trench coat issue became so sensitive in Colorado that
officials banned students from wearing them in schools in Denver
and most other districts amid fears that the coats could help
conceal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In Cherry Hill, N.J., three teen-agers who wore black trench
coats to school, then stood in the hallway pantomiming gunfire,
were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take tough discipline against anyone showing bad
judgment, serious or not,'' said Morton Sherman, the superintendent
of schools in Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   At numerous other high schools, gestures and threats related to
the Colorado massacre have been far more serious.
</P>
<P>
   A high school in Laurel, Md., a Washington-area suburb, sent
home 2,000 students Friday morning after a note was found in the
boys' restroom saying there was a bomb in the building, Reuters
reported. No bomb was found.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the Pennsylvania Emergency Management Agency
reported 19 bomb threats at schools in 17 counties, The Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating these copycat threats can be difficult, said David
Walsh, director of the National Institute on Media and the Family
in Minneapolis. ``It's a challenge to walk the middle line and not
go to the extreme so that every kid who wears a black jacket
becomes a suspect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some threats, however, are clearly serious and have been quickly
prosecuted by law-enforcement officials. In south-central
Washington state, a 14-year-old high school student in Prosser was
arrested for threatening to blow up the high school there.
Investigators said the boy told another student that he ``would
like to position anti-personnel mines in every class, set them off
simultaneously and kill everyone in the school,'' according to
documents filed Thursday in Benton County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   In Spotswood, N.J., an 18-year-old senior, Russell Saul, was
being held on $10,000 bail at the Middlesex County Adult Correction
Center Friday after threatening to blow up the Spotswood High
School. He was arrested Tuesday after he told a teacher in a rage
that he wanted to kill her and another teacher and blow up the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials in Palmdale, Calif., reported the
arrest of two students who said they were members of a trench coat
mafia, threatened a fellow student and talked about making a bomb.
The Palmdale police said that one of the suspects was said to have
told a girl that he thought the Littleton attack was funny. ``He
told her that if he ever began to act crazy like the two killers in
Colorado, she would be the first he would kill,'' said Palmdale
Deputy Sheriff Steve Owen.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesquite, Texas, outside Dallas, a seventh-grade girl was
suspended after she is said to have shown classmates a list of
names of 35 students she wished were dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, what happened in Colorado has caused every district
to re-examine the way they handle possible threats and security
issues,'' said Ian Halper, spokesman for the Mesquite Independent
School District. ``Things that previously were taken lightly or
ignored will now be re-examined.''
</P>
<P>
   In Yonkers, N.Y., a 16-year-old boy was arrested for bringing a
gun to Gorton High School, and two of his classmates were accused
of helping him hide the gun.
</P>
<P>
   In Waterbury, Conn., four boys were arrested for making two fake
bomb threats in the North End Middle School, using a classmate's
cellular phone. State police said a 911 operator heard what sounded
like children laughing in the background. The school was closed for
half a day while police conducted a search.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
