<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-CHURCHGROUP24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youth minister hopes to offer grievers ``something solid,
tangible''
 &HT;    C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The sign on the office door simply said
Reach.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the calls were flooding in from as far away as Sydney,
Australia, London, England, Atwater, Calif., and Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The janitors Friday were in the adjacent gym, mopping the floor
in cadence with the religious rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   It's healing time in Littleton as a community turns full-tilt to
its churches to help bury its dead.
</P>
<P>
   The vigils and prayer services are becoming funerals and
memorial services.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's sermons will be about life ever after, forgiveness and
moving to a more spiritual level.
</P>
<P>
   The students and their families are flocking to the pews and
crisis rooms for at least some sort of temporary protection.
</P>
<P>
   At least one youth minister hopes it's happening across the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are running to the churches looking for hope and an
answer,'' said Jim Beckman, youth minister at St. Francis of
Cabrini Catholic Parish in Littleton. ``That is what motivates
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Four students in Beckman's Life Teen program died Tuesday. They
were Dan Mauser, 15; Matt Kechter, 16; Kelly Fleming, 16; and
Lauren Townsend, 18. A funeral for Mauser, Kechter and Fleming will
will be held at 5:15 p.m. Sunday evening, the mass offered by
Denver Archbishop Charles Chaput.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want love and are looking for answers, I want to give
them something solid, something tangible,'' Beckman said.
``Otherwise, we miss an incredible opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckman, a youth minister for 15 years, said he hopes those who
lead youth nationwide will capture the opportunity presented by
circumstances such as the tragedy at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   With 700 members, Life Teen is one of the largest youth groups
among the Catholic community in the Denver diocese.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Francis parish has 7,000 members, with 40 new families
added to the parish roll each month. The youth group is connected
to 550 other youth groups in the Western United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many had been calling since Tuesday asking what they could do to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman said members of his youth group started coming up to him
as soon as they could Tuesday, looking for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid said you have been telling us about this for a long
time,'' Beckman said. ``You have been telling us to get ready for a
mass conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Families must make their own choices about how they deal with
tragedy and where they find solace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman's message for those who come his way is one of a God who
meets a person exactly where that person is at and makes them
comfortable in that place.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the Columbine High School students who need
comfort right now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman has already organized efforts to print 2,500 T-shirts
for distribution, to students, faculty and staff to wear, if they
choose, on the first day back in class.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts say: ``We survived. We will prevail. We have hope to
carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
