<HEADLINE>
SLAIN TEEN'S LOVE OF CHEVY TRUCKS FONDLY RECALLED AT FUNERAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ His voice shaky, his eyes red and puffy,
Jacob Youngblood stood before hundreds of mourners Friday and
recalled the first time he met his friend John Tomlin, a victim of
the Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing he ever asked me was `Ford or Chevy?'''
Youngblood said. ``I said 'Ford,' and got myself on his bad side
for the rest of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a brief moment of poignant levity in an otherwise
profoundly sad tribute to the 16-year-old sophomore who was
remembered as a ``perfect son'' who loved Chevy trucks, country
music and God.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin will be buried in his native Wisconsin next week, but the
memorial service on Friday at the Foothills Bible Church where he
and his family worshipped was the first of many traumatic rituals
that will take place during the next few days as this community
begins burying its dead.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen people, including a popular teacher, were murdered
Tuesday when two students at the school assaulted the building with
semiautomatic weapons and homemade pipe bombs. After their rampage,
the two students, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, committed suicide
in the school's library.
</P>
<P>
   While the music of Garth Brooks filled the church Friday,
Tomlin's parents, two siblings and extended family were led to
their seats to begin a service marked by tearful remembrances, a
strong sermon on the power of good over evil and the quiet sobbing
of those who had braved cold, snowy weather to pay their final
respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in our country, today in our state, today in our
community, today in our church, families are grieving,'' said
Pastor Bill Oudemolen. ``They are grieving because a 16-year-old
was killed simply because he went to school Tuesday. Schools are
supposed to be safe zones _ not killing fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the lobby, on a table, lay the cherished artifacts of
a teen-age boy's life: His drawings of a hummingbird and a bass
taking a lure; 4 x 4 and Field &AMP; Stream magazines; a Green Bay
Packers jacket; a Chevy Racing Team cap; photographs of him with
his family and his girlfriend; and the familiar `cheesehead' hat of
a Packers fan.
</P>
<P>
   Inside between prayers and music, the life of John Robert
Tomlin, the son of John and Doreen Tomlin, the brother of Ashley
and Pat, was described through the words of those who loved him.
</P>
<P>
   They talked of his deep faith in God, of how he was ``the
perfect son.'' They described how last year he and his father had
traveled on a church mission to Juarez, Mexico, to build a house
for the poor. They showed pictures of him as a small child holding
his infant sister Ashley, now an 11-year-old at Bear Creek
Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend, Micelle Oetter, who attends nearby Ponderosa
High School, said through her tears there were no words to describe
what Tomlin meant to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would do anything in the world to make me smile and to make
me happy,'' she said. ``He treated me like I was the queen of the
world. He spent so much money driving back and forth to my house,
but he said I was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngblood said that after Tomlin forgave him for his choice of
vehicles, they became good friends. Tomlin, he said, was always
respectful and courteous, quick to extend his hand in greeting to
strangers, a boy whose goodness and faith in God assured him a
place in heaven, where he and all those he left behind would
ultimately be reunited.
</P>
<P>
   ``John, I'm on my way,'' Youngblood sobbed. ``You just beat me
there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the service, at which neither of them spoke, Tomlin's
deeply devout parents pointed to a decline in piety as a reason for
many of the problems in today's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are disintegrating, partly because prayer has been
removed from them,'' said Doreen Tomlin.
</P>
</TEXT>
