<HEADLINE>
NFL BACKS DEAL FOR $250M STADIUM AT FOXBOROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects basis for market rank to broadcast revenues sted viewers;
a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Going on offense in their drive to keep the New
England Patriots in Massachusetts, National Football League
officials met with Beacon Hill leaders Friday to negotiate a plan
for a new Foxborough stadium that they hope will make it past the
tough fiscal defense of House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for the state to provide about $75 million in
infrastructure improvements along Route 1 but no public money for
the facility itself, people close to the talks said. In return, New
England Patriots owner Robert Kraft would build a $250 million
open-air stadium, partially funded with a loan from the league that
would be backed by sales of luxury seats.
</P>
<P>
   NFL negotiators also discussed whether an easement could be
granted on land Kraft owns around the existing Foxboro Stadium,
allowing the state to make infrastructure improvements on private
property, those familiar with the preliminary plan said.
</P>
<P>
   The league, worried about the loss of broadcast revenues, wants
to keep the Patriots in the Boston television market, the nation's
sixth largest, by offering Kraft an alternative to his planned move
to Hartford, which ranks just 27th in broadcast revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Its plan for a new Patriots home in Foxborough is similar to a
bill approved last year by the Senate, with one key difference: It
does not call for the use of public money to buy land around
Foxboro. The Senate included that provision a year ago to get
around restrictions against using public money to make improvements
to a privately owned site.
</P>
<P>
   But that Senate bill was rejected by House Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran, prompting Kraft to enter talks with Connecticut. The
Nutmeg State, eager to lure an NFL franchise, agreed to build a
$374 million stadium in Hartford, the plushest deal to date for a
team owner.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, working with a group of Boston civic leaders, has
gained yardage in formulating a stadium pitch acceptable to
legislators. Kraft has refused to comment; he is restricted by his
Connecticut deal from negotiating with other states.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still not known whether Finneran would approve $75
million in taxpayer funds to improve roads, lighting, and other
infrastructure in Foxborough. His final offer last year was $57
million for such work. The Senate plan would have provided $52
million for infrastructure and $20 million for land, which Kraft
would have leased back and on which the state would have built
access ramps to the stadium for luxury box owners.
</P>
<P>
   At a State House press conference late Friday after meeting with
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue for nearly an hour, Finneran said
he would not discuss specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to conduct negotiations or discussions
(publicly) . . . on this new chapter,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue clearly went to Finneran's office in search of
finding a middle ground. Even Governor Paul Cellucci conceded that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a bill that would provide necessary
infrastructure. It would go a little bit beyond that, but we're
trying to respond to the speaker's principles,'' Cellucci said
after a 25-minute discussion in his office with Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner left the governor's office and met with Senate
Ways and Means chairman Mark Montigny for about half an hour.
Tagliabue later huddled with Finneran, devoting nearly an hour the
talks behind closed doors. The speaker and NFL executives have
tentatively agreed to confer again next week to solidify a
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue, who was a political science major in college, emerged
from his meeting with Finneran deferential and vague about any
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a series of very constructive meetings dealing with
a novel subject here. We indicated a strong willingness to be
respectful to the speaker's concerns,'' Tagliabue said. ``Our
differences are being narrowed.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's day began at an informal meeting with the
Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce's executive committee.
BankBoston Corp.'s chief executive, Charles Gifford _ a close
friend of Kraft and chairman of the chamber's board _ hosted the
event.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen of the city's business leaders listened to
Paul Kirk, former Democratic National Committee chairman, as he
explained why he was spearheading the effort to keep the team. They
also heard from Reverend J. Donald Monan, Boston College's
chancellor, who gave a mini-history lesson on Boston's civic
divisiveness. And they listened to Tagliabue, who said league
financing would depend on corporate sponsorship and luxury seating
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said he received unanimous support from the room, but
joked about not having draft cards with him to close on any luxury
suit sales. Tagliabue also said that the Hartford stadium deal is
still the team's ``first option'' but a facility in Greater Boston
would be ``optimal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to develop an alternative'' to Hartford, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The league wants to have a proposal together by May 2 when Kraft
must decide whether to continue pursuing a Hartford deal. The NFL
recently passed a new rule that would allow it to finance at least
one third of the privately funded portion of a major-market stadium
through a loan _ as long as the public sector contributes to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Kraft would abandon the lucrative Connecticut deal for a
stadium he would effectively pay to build in Foxborough -- or
Boston -- would largely be based on whether his heart is with
Massachusetts or the money.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Kraft is anxious about whether the goal of moving
the Patriots by 2002 is realistic because of the complexities of
clearing the contaminated site along the Connecticut River. The
date has already been pushed back from the initial target of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the league has until the week of May 24, when the
NFL owners could vote on the Patriots move. As expected, the team
Friday filed with the league its application to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The team called the filing ``an extremely significant step
towards our goal of playing football in a new state-of-the-art
facility in Hartford beginning with the 2002 football season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were required to make the filing within 30 days of
an owners meeting in order to put the matter on their agenda. The
owners could postpone a vote, however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
