<HEADLINE>
`VISIONARY' KRAFT MIGHT JETTISON CONN. DEAL, TAGLIABUE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Who would walk away from a deal that over time is
guaranteed to be worth more than $1 billion _ and instead pay $250
million out of his own pocket?
</P>
<P>
   National Football League commissioner Paul Tagliabue said Friday
he believed New England Patriots Robert Kraft would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine anyone even considering it, but I think
Bob Kraft is a visionary and so would be willing to,'' Tagliabue
said in an interview. ``He has a very deep loyalty to
Massachusetts, and a strong orientation to the league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if a sound alternative to Connecticut can be
developed, he would consider those loyalties, and in the long run
put Patriots fans and the league's interests over his own,''
Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue was in Boston to meet with political and business
leaders in a last-minute effort to develop a plan that could keep
the Patriots in Massachusetts rather than move to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics question whether the NFL and local business leaders
like national Democratic Party powerhouse Paul Kirk and advertising
executive John J. Connors can come up with an agreement that
satisfies House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran. But Tagliabue believes
it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's real momentum here. The league is not only researching
whether any realistic options for keeping the team in Massachusetts
exists, we are working to develop them,'' Tagliabue said.``And if
that happens, I think Massachusetts has a clear advantage over a
new venue in terms of its historic fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue added: ``It's not a dollar-for-dollar proposition.
Massachusetts does not have to match Connecticut's offer. No one is
even talking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nutmeg State has agreed to provide the Patriots with a $374
million stadium package. But the deal, signed by Kraft and Conn.
Governor John Rowland earlier this year, is worth more. A lot more.
</P>
<P>
   To woo the Patriots to move from Foxborough to Hartford, Conn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
