<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LEAD24-COX     04-23 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LEAD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police release tape of frantic 911 call
 &HT;    Chris Barker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The shootings that left 15 dead at Columbine
High School snapped into horrifying focus Friday, as an audio tape
of a 911 call released by authorities revealed a scene of
panic-filled seconds before two students cut a bloody slaughter
through the school's library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the tables, get your heads under the table!'' screams a
teacher identified only as Peggy.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, six gunshots ring out in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-minute tape contains a recording of the teacher and a
female student who called for help from inside the building. Also,
several minutes of radio chatter between officers and dispatchers
details the first minutes after authorities arrived at the high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve students and a teacher were killed in the shooting on
Tuesday. Authorities believe two students, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, carried out the rampage before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that others participated in the crime had not
been ruled out as of Friday. Authorities believe the two gunmen
might have had help carrying in several homemade bombs that were
used during the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one we've been hearing from the students that there
may have been a third party,'' said Sgt. Jim Parr, a Jefferson
County Sheriff's Office spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Rocky Mountain News reported Friday that one
Columbine student and the parent of another said they had been
questioned by police about a teen-ager suspected of lugging duffel
bags of bombs into the school and fleeing before the assault.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement source confirmed that police are seeking a
third suspect, the News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance tapes from the security cameras at the school may
show whether the two gunmen had accomplices, investigators said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the center of the slaughter _ the second-story library,
where nearly all of the dead were found _ had no cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally they would show the movement and also the actual
placement perhaps of some of the explosive devices, prior to the
incident,'' said Jefferson County sheriff's Lt. John Kiekbusch.
</P>
<P>
   They are time-lapse cameras, meaning they periodically take
pictures instead of running continuously. Each tape goes back about
a week. Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said the tapes have not yet
been viewed.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of students from all over the Denver area
continued to visit makeshift memorials to the dead in nearby
Clement Park, Jefferson County School District officials announced
that classes would begin in less than a week at neighboring
Chatfield High School.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 Columbine students will split schedules with
Chatfield students starting April 29, and school activities and
athletic events will be held as planned, said district
Superintendent Jane Hammond.
</P>
<P>
   All district schools will continue to have beefed-up security,
including additional supervision at all school entrances and events
like spring proms, Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking out for the first time, Columbine Principal Frank
DeAngelis recognized the sacrifice of Dave Sanders, the only
teacher who died.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders ran out of the teacher lounge to help students after he
heard gunshots, DeAngelis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his life, but saved the lives of hundreds of our
students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold had never been disciplined for any behavioral
problem at Columbine, DeAngelis said. He added that he had no
knowledge of a video the pair reportedly made in school that
depicted them shooting students.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 federal, state and local investigators exchanged
information on Friday, including material gathered over the course
of 500 interviews that have been conducted since the shooting,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb squads plan to begin the task of checking over 2000 student
lockers today.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings released Friday brought home the terror of
Tuesday's violence, which began shortly before the first 911 call
at about 11:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy, the teacher in the library, told the dispatcher that
students were screaming and said she saw a student with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went walking out to see what was going on,'' Peggy said.
``He turned the gun straight at us and shot and a guy at the window
went out. And the kid standing there, I think he got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dispatchers in constant radio contact with the first officers at
the school documented a chaotic scene at Columbine. Students poured
out of the building as a deputy exchanged fire with a gunman
wearing a black trenchcoat and firing a large caliber gun, officers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Thomas, district attorney for the area that includes
Columbine, said the shooting should spark serious reflection about
American society. Columbine should be a benchmark for change, not
just another school shooting, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it to be known as a place where we started a change in
this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
