<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INCREASES TROOP COMMITMENT TO ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (jw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon announced Friday night that it was
sending sizable armored combat units _ equipped with tanks and
howitzers _ to Albania to back up the Apache helicopter gunships
that began to arrive there with much fanfare this week.
</P>
<P>
   Once these soldiers join the fight, they will operate within
miles of Yugoslavia's mountainous border with Albania, well within
range of Yugoslav forces, raising the prospect of clashes on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The additional deployment further deepens the commitment of
American troops in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of 2,350 troops will nearly double the number of
American soldiers that were expected to be based in Albania when
NATO and the Pentagon approved the use of the Apaches three weeks
ago. More significant, the new forces are to include many more
heavy weapons: 15 Abrams M1-A1 tanks, 8 howitzers capable of
lobbing shells nearly eight miles and 14 Bradley fighting vehicles
in addition to the 14 that already have been sent.
</P>
<P>
   The American force in Albania now numbers about 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman, Col. Richard Bridges, said the force was
in no way a vanguard of ground troops to invade Yugoslavia. He said
the purpose of the heavy weapons was to protect the Apaches, which
are now arriving at Albania's capital, Tirana, after several
logistical delays.
</P>
<P>
   Although based in Tirana, the Apaches will operate from
positions close to the border. From those spots, they will dart
into Kosovo, using barrages of rockets fired from the rear as
cover.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks and Bradleys _ part of the 1st Armored Division based
in Bad Kreuznach, Germany _ will protect these forward positions
from any Yugoslav counterattack. In addition, the deployment
includes more rocket batteries and a company of vehicles equipped
with anti-tank missiles from Fort Bragg, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to want some force protection when these forces
get close to the border,'' Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   The buildup is expected to begin next week and take some time.
That could further delay the use of the Apaches against Yugoslav
forces. Officials at the Pentagon said the Apaches may not fly into
combat for many more days or weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      04-23 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO LEADERS SPURN MILOSEVIC'S LATEST OFFER 
 
JOHN C. HENRY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sitting as a war council, NATO leaders on Friday
rejected Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's latest peace offer
and vowed to step up bombing and economic pressure until he yields
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not allow this campaign of terror to succeed. NATO is
determined to prevail,'' the 19 allied leaders declared in a
communique following a three-hour meeting devoted to the Balkan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from alliance leaders, in Washington to celebrate
the 50th anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
promised to end the bombing campaign, now in its fifth week, only
after Milosevic ends atrocities against non-Serbian ethnic groups
and withdraws his forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With no equivocation, summit leaders pledged to expand the air
attacks unless Milosevic stops all violence, agrees to an
international military force, permits the safe return of all
refugees and accepts autonomy for Kosovo, a rebellious province in
southern Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no compromise on these conditions,'' the
three-page communique said.
</P>
<P>
   The document also pledged to beef up economic sanctions against
Yugoslavia and embraced an oil embargo pushed by the European
Union. NATO leaders stopped short of endorsing a U.S.-proposed
naval blockade. The communique also did not target Milosevic for
prosecution as a war criminal, but it vowed ``to support
investigation'' of all those suspected of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The allies dismissed a proposal from Milosevic, relayed to
Washington through Russia's Balkan envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, to
allow an international military force in the Yugoslav province if
NATO would stop the bombing. Officials in Belgrade later
backpedaled, saying Milosevic had mentioned only the possibility of
an unarmed contingent from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac called the offer ``totally
insufficient.``
</P>
<P>
   Friday's communique did not mention the possibility of sending
ground troops into battle, a topic dividing the alliance's member
nations in how to force Milosevic to surrender in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate on ground troops is no longer on the table'' during
the summit, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Pentagon confirmed plans to send 2,000 more
troops to the Balkans over the next several days to help protect
the 24 Apache attack helicopters while they are on the ground in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment increases the number of U.S. military personnel
in the region to 5,350. Also being shipped to Albania are 15 Abrams
tanks, a battery of eight 155mm howitzers, several truck-mounted
missile launchers and 14 Bradley fighting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, Defense Secretary William Cohen has been
working up a proposal that would involve calling up an additional
33,000 Reserve troops, a decision that must be cleared by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana has ordered a
review of the alliance's military assessments of the forces that
would be required for a ground offensive or for enforcing any
cease-fire in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO's Supreme Allied Commander Gen. Wesley Clark
said air attacks have paid off. Yugoslav air defenses have been
rendered ineffective, Serb forces are hiding from NATO aircraft and
a fuel crisis has forced Milosevic to suspend military operations
in Kosovo three times, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, we're winning, he's losing, and he knows it,`` Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO and U.S. military officials defended the attack
early Friday at the Belgrade headquarters of Serbia's state-run
television network, a precision missile strike that Serb officials
say killed at least 10, injured 19, and left 20 others buried in
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Radio and Television Serbia was broadcasting an interview with
Milosevic, which had been taped by Houston's KHOU-TV, when
sea-launched Tomahawk cruise missiles struck, knocking it off the
air early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When told that RTS had resumed broadcasting six hours after the
attack, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon indicated NATO forces
could soon draw another bead on the network. ``Stay tuned, is all I
can say,'' Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to bomb the network building and main transmitter
was made after a lengthy debate among Clinton aides and NATO
officials. Concerns over possible civilian casualties gave way to
the argument that the war is being prolonged by the one-sided diet
of pro-Milosevic propaganda aired by RTS and its refusal to carry
reports of systematic killings, rapes and burnings in ethnic
Albanian villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb TV is as much a part of Milosevic's murder machine as his
military is,'' Bacon said, calling RTS transmitters and nearby
electrical power sites ``a new class of targets'' in the Balkan
war.
</P>
<P>
