</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAW-TO-CLEVELAND24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaw dealt to Browns
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former LBJ High School star running back Sedrick
Shaw was traded Thursday from the New England Patriots to the
Cleveland Browns for a player to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   The trade will allow Shaw, the third-year player who had fallen
out of favor with the Patriots' coaching staff, a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good situation for Sedrick to go with a new team and
new coaches,'' said Ed Cunningham, Shaw's Austin-based agent.
``There wasn't a problem with New England. He's just more valuable
to Cleveland than he was to New England.''
</P>
<P>
   New England selected Shaw with the first pick of the third round
of the 1997 NFL draft. Coaches had hoped he would be able to step
in for Curtis Martin, the Patriots' star runner who became a free
agent in 1998 and signed with the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw never excelled with the Patriots. He did not have a
carry his rookie season. Once Martin left New England in 1998, Shaw
was beaten out by rookie Robert Edwards, the Patriots' first-round
pick. Shaw started one game and gained 237 yards last season.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards suffered a knee and leg injury in January that could end
his career, but the Patriots, rather than relying on Shaw to fill
the void, drafted Louisiana State tailback Kevin Faulk in the
second round of last Saturday's draft to fill Edwards' spot.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw flew from Austin to Cleveland after the trade was completed
Thursday and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Browns have six running backs on their roster. The
only one with any NFL experience is former San Francisco 49er Terry
Kirby.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's 99-yard touchdown gallop for LBJ in 1990 is the longest
run from scrimmage in Austin Independent School District history.
He left Iowa in 1996 as the Hawkeyes' career rushing leader with
4,156 yards. His 1,477 yards in 1995 set an Iowa single-season
record, and he became only the eighth back in Big Ten history to
rush for 1,000 yards in three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
