<SLUG> BC-NUKE-DRUG-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRC TRIES TO AVOID FINANCING FALLOUT DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., N.Y., Ohio)  (Exclusive) 
(rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has quietly
backed away from its offer to give states with nuclear power plants
stockpiles of a drug that cuts the risk of thyroid cancer in people
exposed to fallout in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   The commission decided in July 1997 to pay for the drug,
potassium iodide. But on Thursday it approved a document that calls
for trying to shift the cost to the Federal Emergency Management
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of stocking the drug say the commission's move will
only prolong a policy debate that dates from 1986, when health
authorities in Europe distributed potassium iodide after the
accident at Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in that debate: whether it would be worthwhile for the
nation to have regional stockpiles of the drug _ already available
in many states for distribution to emergency workers _ large enough
that it could be distributed to the general population in the event
of a nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to fund the purchase, and repurchase when the
shelf life ran out,'' William F. McNutt, a senior policy adviser at
the emergency management agency and chairman of a multi-agency
subcommittee on potassium iodide, said of the NRC ``Those
rascals.''
</P>
<P>
   McNutt said his agency had made no plans to finance the
purchase, variously estimated at a few hundred thousand dollars a
year to a little over $3 million, but could ask Congress to make it
part of the agency's Radiological Emergency Preparedness Program.
That program is fully financed by charges to utilities, the same
source that pays for the nuclear commission's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Crane, an NRC lawyer whose lobbying as a private
citizen led the commission to agree to pay for the drug, complained
Friday that ``the NRC has reneged on its promise.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael T. Jamgochian, a senior nuclear engineer at the
commission who is in charge of policy on the drug, said the promise
had only been modified: the commission will pay for the drug, he
said, if the emergency agency cannot. The document approved by the
commissioners on Thursday, without announcement, was a memorandum
from them to their staff. It said the commission's budget ``has
continued to decrease and offers little margin for the commission
to divert resources to new initiatives.'' So, it said, the
commission will try to get the emergency agency to pay for the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, a year after agreeing to pay for the potassium
iodide, the commissioners, approving a longstanding petition from
Crane, said they would require utilities to consider stockpiling
potassium iodide for public use. On Thursday, the commissioners
noted that Crane's petition, calling on them to impose such a
requirement, had not asked them to pay for the purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But Crane said today that ``my petition was premised on the fact
they'd already promised it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my fault,'' he said, ``for having trusted their
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Many states already stock potassium iodide, but only enough for
use by police officers, firefighters, other emergency workers and
``captive populations'' like nursing home residents or prisoners,
who could not be easily moved in case of accident. Several states
with such policies had begun considering larger stockpiles because
of the NRC's offer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one such state, New Jersey, the chief radiation safety
officer, Gerald P. Nicholls, said Friday that if they wanted to,
officials there could presumably afford to buy the drug on their
own. But, he said, the NRC's decision ``seems convoluted,'' since
utilities would ultimately be bearing the cost whether it was the
nuclear commission or the emergency agency that paid for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, which has held hearings on whether to expand its
stockpile, officials said they were surprised. ``Everything Ohio
has been doing was based on the premise that the NRC was going to
pay for the potassium iodide,'' said Randy Hertzer, a spokesman for
the state's Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   New York has also considered an expansion but is making no
change. Officials in Albany, as in some other states, said that
they were concerned about the effect of giving the drug to people
with unknown medical histories and that they feared that some
people who had taken the pill, feeling invulnerable, might then
refuse orders to flee their homes in the event of an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has also been considering a larger stockpile, but a
spokesman at the Health Department in Hartford was not able to say
what effect the NRC's decision would have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
