<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-CASTROL-PROBIKE-H     04-23 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CASTROL-PROBIKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brown giving relative ride in fast lane
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ Philadelphia Eagles cornerback Troy Vincent has a
passion for motorcycles. He owns six of them, and he would like to
race them, but his NFL contract prohibits that sort of hazardous
activity.
</P>
<P>
   So Vincent did the next best thing. He organized a Pro Stock
Bike team and hired his wife's cousin to be the rider.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Antron Brown, 23, a sophomore on the National Hot Rod
Association circuit, has not disappointed. He ranked seventh in the
series last year and has improved since.
</P>
<P>
   He was fourth in his first event this year _ the Gatornationals
at Gainesville, Fla. And he set an elapsed-time track record of
7.39 seconds Friday in time trials in his second event _ the
Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy started riding street bikes when he played for Miami
(Dolphins),'' Brown said. ``But he got away from street-bike racing
because he saw how people got hurt. So he decided to get involved
in drag racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he and Vincent ``are like brothers. A lot of people
think we are brothers because we look a lot alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is very much an athlete. While earning an associate degree
in business administration at Mercer County Junior College in New
Jersey, he ran track and ranked No. 1 nationally at 55 meters.
</P>
<P>
   But he prefers riding bikes to running. He rode a dirt bike when
he was 5, and by 13 he was competing nationally in amateur
motocross.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad raced drag bikes when he was growing up, and my uncle
raced two super stock cars,'' Brown said. ``My dream was to race
pro stock bikes when I retired from motocross, which is not a
longevity sport. I had several injuries, because in that sport
you're falling all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Vincent called to ask if he'd like to take early retirement
from motocross, Brown couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy wanted a new face; he didn't want to take a rider who
already was out there,'' said Brown, who is from Chesterfield, N.J.
``He knew motocross is good training for a lot of other motor
sports. It's easy to go from there to road racing and Pro Stock
Bike racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were a new team, and we had to feel everything
out. But we're a contender for the championship this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In Friday afternoon's session, he reached a speed of 180.5 mph
in setting the elapsed-time mark. Conditions were far from ideal,
with 80-degree temperatures, 70 percent humidity and a crosswind.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the first time pro bikes have raced here since
1991, so improved technology made up for problematic weather.
</P>
<P>
   Brown expects his record to be broken in today's time trials,
``as soon as the wind lets up a little. When the wind is coming
across the track, the bike is like a sail; it gets blown. The front
end of the bike is floating. You have to lean into it and pull hard
to keep the bike straight.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to success in his sport is reaction time. The driver
must achieve ideal positioning and operate the gears while
withstanding dramatic shifts of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you let the clutch out, you feel so much power in the
seat,'' Brown said. ``I've seen a lot of people flip off the back
of the bike when they let the clutch out. The bike goes forward so
fast and they don't react. It's like having a horse saddle on a
rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the sport is safer than playing in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fall ratio on these bikes is actually very low,'' Brown
said. ``And the leather suits we wear are so good that you can fall
on the track and you won't even get a skin rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had an accident in seven years on the national
circuit, since Dave (Schultz) fell off in Dallas. He broke his
pinkie, but that was all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave is 51 and a six-time world champion. So basically you can
race until you're ready to get off. I want to ride until I'm 50
years old and then retire and watch my kids grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of career would make Vincent happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells me all the time that he's living a dream through
me,'' Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
