</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
911 TAPES RELEASED AS POLICE CONTINUE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for final add-on; last six grafs are new.)  
(mb) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ ``The school's in a panic, and I'm in the
library,'' the teacher is desperately trying to explain to the
police dispatcher as she begs for help. ``I've got students down
...
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the table, kids!'' she says now, directing her attention
back to the students who, moments before, had been quietly studying
in the library at Columbine High School. ``Kids, under the table.
Kids, stay on the floor ... Oh, God. Oh, God _ kids, just stay
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher's frantic voice, heard as gunfire reverberates in
the background, was part of a tape recording made public by the
police on Friday of some of the emergency calls placed Tuesday as
two students began their lethal rampage through the school, in
which they killed 12 fellow students _ 10 of them in the library
from which the teacher placed her desperate phone call _ and one
teacher before turning the guns on themselves. The teacher on the
phone, whom police identified on Friday only by her first name,
Peggy, survived the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes were made public as the police continued with dozens
of interviews on Friday aimed at finding out _ as many
investigators here strongly believe _ whether the two young men had
some kind of help in preparing for their attack or in bringing more
than 30 home-made explosive devices into the school.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. John Kiekbusch, of the Jefferson County sheriff's office
said there were others involved who seemed to have had ``if not
direct participation, limited participation, knowledge'' related to
the two youths. Another Sheriff's Department official said Friday
night that investigators now had the names of a few ``possible
suspects,'' at least one of whom had not yet been located for
questioning. While many of the pair's friends and acquaintances
have been interviewed, so far no arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also said on Friday that they believed the two,
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, may have wandered through the school
after their initial attack in the library for up to an hour before
returning to that room to kill themselves. Some students had made
their escape while many others remained barricaded inside other
classrooms during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Owens, who toured the school Thursday night, said on
Friday that ``the devastation is difficult to exaggerate,'' and
said that many of the most haunting sights were the most ordinary
ones, from books left open on their desks to computers still
switched on.
</P>
<P>
   ``One young woman had been filling out an application to the
University of Denver,'' the governor said in an interview. ``Next
to it she had a to-do list. Monday was all checked off. She was
halfway through Tuesday. One of the items on the list was to write
her life story.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, the Jefferson County district
attorney, David Thomas, interrupted his briefings on the status of
the investigation to offer an emotional plea to reporters and the
nation at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to most of the families in this case, and they
said there has to be some meaning to this, this has to result in
something,'' Thomas said. ``These deaths cannot be in vain. We
can't walk away from here here and wait for the next incident to
occur and then go cover that incident and not learn from this.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 50, suggested that part of the problem was the easy
availability of guns in this country. ``The kinds of things that
were involved in this case were simply _ it was so simple to get
them,'' he said. ``Guns are everywhere. You can buy them on the
street. You can get them anywhere you want. You can steal them.
They're readily available. You can go to gun shows. You can have
your friends go to gun shows if you're underage. They're very easy
to acquire.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Patricia B. Holloway, who as chairwoman of the Jefferson County
Board of Commissioners is expected to help set up a gubernatorial
task force on school violence, said in an interview on Friday: ``We
have got to make parents responsible. Parents have got to start
communicating. They've got to take control. Some of these children
are so belligerent. They've been given free rein. Everyone's afraid
to stand up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Littleton, the first of more than a dozen memorial and
funeral services that this community will have to cope with took
place Friday morning, when John Robert Tomlin Jr., a 16-year-old
sophomore who was murdered in the library, was mourned by a crowd
of 500 people at Foothills Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend, Michelle Oetter, tried to speak at the service.
``He had a grin. You just couldn't help smiling when he smiled,''
she said. ``He treated me like I was the queen of the world. He
spent so much money driving back and forth to my house, but he told
me I was worth it.'' But then she broke down into deep, shaking
sobs and was helped away from the front of the church by two of
Tomlin's best friends.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Bill Oudemolen addressed the family and friends of
Tomlin, telling them: ``A 16-year-old was killed simply because he
went to school in the morning. Kids are not supposed to kill kids.
Schools are supposed to be safe zones, not killing fields.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tomlin Sr., the dead boy's father, spoke briefly to
reporters afterward and conveyed this message: ``For the families
of the children who did this, we are praying for them. We feel no
hatred for them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the mourning continued, there was some news of recovery.
Mikai Hall, a junior wounded in the leg by a shotgun blasts,
appeared with his parents on Friday and spoke briefly at St.
Anthony Central Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know that I am going to get better,'' said
Hall. Expressing bewilderment at the incident, he said of Klebold,
one of the perpetrators who killed himself: ``Dylan was in French
class of mine. Dylan, I thought he was an all-right guy. I worked
with him sometimes. He is not the kind of person he is being
portrayed as. He was a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering an account that paralleled that of the audiotapes made
public, Hall said: ``I remember a teacher running into the library
screaming that some kids had guns, so everyone got under their
desks pretty quick. A few minutes after that, two people came in
and started shooting. They fired a number of shots, and one hit me
and I laid on the ground. They moved towards me. That's all I can
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   County officials released the tapes in part to address questions
raised by students, parents and reporters about whether the
building could have been secured any earlier, possibly leading to
earlier rescues of students who lay grievously wounded inside.
Police officials have resolutely defended their response to the
incident, saying they surrounded the building but held off entering
for fear that they might have set off a new gunfight that could
have led to even more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes came with a timeline indicating that first sheriff's
deputies on the scene were there within three minutes of the first
emergency call.
</P>
<P>
   They were responding to a call from an unidentified student who
said she believed there was someone with a gun loose in the school.
``I just saw everyone running out,'' she said on the tape. ``People
are running out of the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the call from the teacher, who said there were two
gunmen. ``I do not know them,'' she said, her voice rising in fear.
``He turned the gun straight at him ... and I think he got hit in
the right shoulder. Oh, God! Oh, God.!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more agonizing scenes was that of a bleeding youth
who wriggled out of a second-story window and let himself fall in a
desperate attempt to escape. He was identified on Friday as Patrick
Ireland, a 17-year-old senior, who is in intensive care with
gunshots wounds to the head and foot.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at St. Anthony told reporters that Ireland was suffering
from weakness on the right side of his body and was having
difficulty speaking and comprehending, the effects of the bullet to
his head. He is expected to live, but doctors said they could not
predict his course of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The local superintendent of schools, Dr. Jane Hammond, announced
that students from Columbine High School would finish the term at
another high school in the district. But she vowed that Columbine
would reopen next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not considered leaving the school closed,'' Dr.
Hammond said Friday. ``We have not been asked by any group of
community members or anyone not to reopen the school. We absolutely
will be reopening.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students have said this week that they would feel fear or
revulsion returning to the building. But Frank DeAngelis, the
Columbine principal, said many more students had told him that they
wanted to return because abandoning the school would represent an
intolerable concession to the killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me,'' the principal said, ``do not let them take
Columbine from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAGEL-MCDONALD'S-NYT     04-23 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAGEL-MCDONALD'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
NERVY McDONALD'S INTRODUCES McBAGELS IN McYORK  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eli Zabar stands over the specimen, like a coroner on
his first autopsy of the day. He pokes and pinches and cuts, and
bends close to take a sniff, and then straightens to render his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a true bagel,'' says Zabar, 55, who, as one of New
York's foremost food merchants, would know. ``This is a roll in the
shape of a bagel.''
</P>
<P>
   After some three centuries of culinary history, it has come to
this for the ubiquitous bagel: McDonald's is selling them.
</P>
<P>
   To be more precise, Friday, after months of testing, McDonald's
officially unveiled _ in 6,000 stores across the Midwest and
Northeast, including New York and New Jersey _ three new ``bagel
breakfast sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   Ana Madan-Russo, president of McDonald's New York Tri-State
Owners and Operators association, says franchise owners are excited
about selling bagel sandwiches ``in the bagel capital of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Zabar, dissecting a McDonald's steak, egg and
cheese bagel in Eli's, his market on the Upper East Side. A true
bagel, he asserts, must be boiled, then baked to achieve
authenticity. ``This one,'' he says regretfully, ``has been
steamed, not boiled.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes the wimpy crust and the soft inside that pulls apart
without a fight. ``It's like Wonder Bread in a circle,'' he says.
``A New York bagel fights with you. It's tough on the outside, and
chewy on the inside, and you struggle with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elena Ramos, marketing director for McDonald's in New York,
dismisses as irrelevant whether McDonald's bagels are steamed or
boiled, or treated with any special preservatives. ``I'm not sure
if the customers buying them up get into all that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The company has no plans to sell bagel sandwiches in its other
7,000 restaurants outside the Midwest and Northeast, and Ms. Ramos
says it is too soon to tell whether the McDonald's bagels will
catch on with New York City's sizable population of bagel nuts.
But, she notes, they sold briskly in several test markets,
including Hartford, Conn. In addition to the steak bagel,
McDonald's is offering a Spanish omelet bagel and one with ham, egg
and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the customers love them as much as we do,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   For some New York food aficionados, who view the bagel as the
city's cultural equivalent to Paris' baguette, the notion of a ham,
egg and cheese bagel topped with McDonald's special ``breakfast
sauce'' may seem like pastrami with mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Levine, author of ``New York Eats (More),'' bemoans the
McDonald's bagel invasion as ``a scary proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be that this is the logical extension of the
commodification of bagels,'' he says. ``A bagel used to have
character. Now anything that's vaguely round, that's puffed up with
a hole in it, can be called a bagel. I knew this was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   He worries that in the age of fast food chains and relentless
mass marketing, McDonald's $2.49 bagel sandwiches will diminish a
durable New York icon. ``I'm nostalgic, but many people will taste
McDonald bagels and think they're fine,'' he says. ``They've made
the bagel into a neutral food. They used to be made with malt and
have a crust. Now even many New Yorkers don't want their bagels
with a crust.''
</P>
<P>
   New York didn't invent the bagel. According to one popular
legend, that honor dates to 1683, when some Viennese bakers cooked
up a few in tribute to Jan Sobieski, the king of Poland. Bagels
made their way to New York in the early part of this century, with
Eastern European Jewish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bagel is everywhere. In Canada, Toronto holds a weekly
Bagel Bash. Mattoon, Ill., sponsors Bagelfest! In Boston, there's a
New Year's Eve Bagel-Off. Some of New York's most established bagel
makers have done their share to spread bagels to the masses. Yet
Helmer Toro, owner of H &AMP; H Bagels, in Manhattan is crushing in his
response to McDonald's product: ``They're not a quality product.''
</P>
<P>
   The reviews are more generous in Zabar's, another New York bagel
landmark. The owner, Saul Zabar, 70, is the older brother of Eli
Zabar. Just as his brother dissected the steak bagel, Saul Zabar
dissects the Spanish omelet bagel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, these bagels aren't bad,'' he says, tasting first the
egg, then the sausage patty and then the bagel itself. ``My God, I
think it's remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rick Feinberg, eating a Zabar's bagel with Nova and cream
cheese at the counter, makes a sheepish concession: If he were on
the highway in some strange place, and if he were really hungry, he
might stop at a McDonald's and try one _ though he probably would
stick with an Egg McMuffin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
