<SLUG> BC-BBA-WELLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES ARE BETTER OFF DESPITE WELLS' MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About 75 fans stood behind metal barricades beside
the players' entrance at Yankee Stadium Friday, the rain slapping
their disappointed faces while Yankee after Yankee sprinted by.
This was too dreary a day for stopping to sign autographs, but the
fans waited because they are fans and because David Wells was
certain to appear.
</P>
<P>
   When a luxury bus finally arrived, the fans pressed closer to
the barricades. One, two, three Blue Jays exited the bus. Then
Wells stepped onto the sidewalk and walked that lefty swagger of
his. The fans howled as if Derek Jeter had just tossed them
autographed baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wells seemed touched by the boisterous adulation. He lifted
his right arm, looked down at his shoes and then looked back at the
fans again. He had a small smile on his chubby face and a glazed
look in his eyes. If Wells was curious about how the fans were
going to treat him as the enemy, he found out instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Is Wells even the enemy? The Toronto left-hander received a
one-minute standing ovation when he sauntered to the mound in the
first inning, and the raucous bleacher fans chanted, ``David Wells,
David Wells,'' making an opponent part of their roll call for the
first time. Wells motioned to his ``people'' in right before
tossing his second pitch.
</P>
<P>
   One poster along the left-field line had pictures of Joe
DiMaggio and Wells and read: ``Two Great Yankee Losses, We Miss You
Both.'' A 20-year-old fan in the bleachers wore a Wells T-shirt and
could have passed for Wells' brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my idol,'' said the fan, John Farley. ``People tell me I
look like him. This is my 20th birthday. When I found out he was
pitching, I had to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Farley continued to speak glowingly about Wells, Paul
O'Brien, one row ahead of him, interjected and said, ``He's on the
other team, so he's the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   As rainy a night as it was, it was definitely Wells' night.
Wells had longed for this night for two months, talking about it
like a 17-year-old who is playing against the high school of his
ex-girlfriend's new boyfriend. To Wells, it is all about showing
who is tougher and about the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wells loves the attention; Wells craves the attention. A Yankee
in 1997 and 1998, he loved talking with Howard Stern, loved
bouncing from bar to bar in Manhattan and loved embellishing the
supposedly rebellious image of the pierced and tattooed son of a
woman who dated members of Hell's Angels. When Wells arrived in New
York on Thursday, a day ahead of the rest of the Blue Jays, he had
dinner with Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Wells deserved last night. He won 22 games, including four in
the postseason, for a team that won an unprecedented total of 125
games, and the magic of last year would not have been as magical
without him. Still, embracing the attention and creating even more
attention is another one of the reasons the Yankees are better off
having traded Wells for Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be distractions in Yankeeland. See George
Steinbrenner, Hideki Irabu, Darryl Strawberry and maybe even
Clemens someday. But the Yankees, who know that duplicating 1998
will be almost impossible, must control as many of these annoyances
as they can. So when a five-time Cy Young Award winner like Clemens
became available, Wells became expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Wells is 8-1 in the postseason, but he is also the
pitcher who criticized manager Joe Torre before Game 1 of the 1998
American League Championship Series for not starting him until Game
3 a year earlier, and he is the pitcher who predicted a sweep over
San Diego in the World Series. The remarks did not hamper the
Yankees, but they were risky.
</P>
<P>
   Even Friday, Wells started his pre-game preparations about 30
seconds after reporters were permitted into the clubhouse. That
meant that Wells, wearing shorts and a sleeveless T-shirt and
looking thicker than 240 pounds, played a Metallica compact disk,
turned the volume up to 10 and began stretching.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Enter Sandman'' was over, Tony Fernandez lowered the
volume. Wells snapped, ``My day, my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said, ``Your day?''
</P>
<P>
   Wells repeated, ``My day,'' and hiked the volume back to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Because of who Wells is and who he can be and who Clemens is and
who he can be, no Yankees have lamented the departure of Wells.
Even David Cone, Wells' closest friend, essentially admitted that
the Yankees are superior with Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you not feel good about Roger Clemens being on your
team?'' Cone asked. ``We traded the best left-hander in the league
for the Cy Young Award winner and the best right-hander. Time will
tell, but I think everybody in here likes the fact that Roger is on
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone went on to claim that ``some of us probably wish we could
have Boomer and Roger.'' But that was merely his attempt to be
diplomatic. Sorry, it was too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
