<HEADLINE>
DID KILLERS ACT ALONE? SURVEILLANCE TAPE MAY HOLD ANSWER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Investigators looked to a cafeteria
surveillance camera to settle suspicions that two gun-toting
students did not act alone in their deadly attack at Columbine High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are analyzing videotape from the time-lapse camera,
which runs intermittently but holds a tape that goes back about a
week, in their painstaking search of the scorched and bloodstained
school.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, stormed in late Tuesday
morning with semiautomatic weapons, shotguns and handmade bombs.
They fired more than 100 rounds and detonated bombs wrapped with
nails, killing 12 students and one teacher before fatally shooting
themselves in a second floor library.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind were at least 30 homemade bombs, some on timers.
Investigators questioned whether the two teen-agers could have
carried them all inside without help from others.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Bill Owens toured the school Friday and called the
damage ``stunning'' and the evidence unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are backpacks with bombs in there everywhere,'' Owens
told The Associated Press. ``The officers in there are convinced
there had to be more people involved. There's just too much stuff
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Though authorities have found no motive for the massacre, the
two seniors were self-described outcasts who professed a hatred of
minorities and athletes. They belonged to a social group called the
``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' known for members' long black coats.
</P>
<P>
   Harris maintained a Web page on the Internet referring to plans
to kill enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine Principal Frank DeAngelis on Friday denied claims that
a parent of another student warned him about Harris and Klebold.
DeAngelis said he had known nothing about them before the shooting
other than that they were students. He said they had never done
anything at the school requiring disciplining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard of the Trenchcoat Mafia was when it was
brought out Tuesday,'' DeAngelis said.
</P>
<P>
   The two wounded 23 people including Patrick Ireland, 17, whose
dramatic escape through the library window after being shot in the
head was aired on television as the attack ensued. Ireland and 12
others remain in hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said Friday that Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents have traced a High Point
semiautomatic rifle and a Tek 9 semiautomatic handgun used in the
attack to their original buyers. He declined to give further
details but said there was no connection between the gunmen and the
original registered owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how many times those guns had changed hands
before getting into the hands of the suspects,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   He said ATF agents were having a tougher time finding the
original registered owners of the shotguns. Those guns may be
nearly 40 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, teams of investigators are scouring the school for
evidence in an ``inch-by-inch'' search of every room. While about
50 investigators searched the school, another 20 conducted
interviews with students, teachers and people who knew the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Among those already questioned were former members of the
Trenchcoat Mafia. Most of the group's members, believed to have
numbered as many as 15, graduated last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the planning required, including building the bombs,
the two either mapped out their plans over a long period of time or
had accomplices, police believe.
</P>
<P>
   Some students have told investigators they saw a third gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard it now more than once, that's why we're paying a
little more attention,'' said Davis. ``Some of the students did say
there were three people. We've been looking for three people, but
so far we've only been able to find two,'' said Sgt. Jim Parr,
sheriff's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that if a third gunman was involved, spent
shell casings from the gun he fired will be found.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
