<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VARYING PATHS FOR HORNETS AND KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks have been dissected beyond recognition;
the only way to understand the franchise is to examine its opposite
_ the Charlotte Hornets. The Hornets have done a lot with not very
much and apparently have found a way out of no way.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought a month ago that in mid-April the Knicks
and Hornets would be headed in opposite directions, and that
Charlotte would be the team going the right way?
</P>
<P>
   On April 6, the Hornets had lost their fifth straight game and
seemed to need a miracle to make the playoffs. Eddie Jones, who had
recently joined the Hornets in a trade from Los Angeles, said,
joking, ``I guess we're going to have to go on an 18-game winning
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets are halfway there. Entering Friday night's game at
Madison Square Garden, Charlotte had won nine consecutive games in
a streak that began on April 7 with a rout of the Knicks. The
Knicks' house of cards appears to be collapsing, but the Hornets
have gone from five and a half games out of a playoff spot to
contention for the final berth in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The focal points of the respective turnabouts are two old
buddies. Paul Silas, now the Hornets' head coach, and Knicks coach
Jeff Van Gundy shared space on the bench as assistants to Pat Riley
when Riley coached the Knicks earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Silas' career followed the meandering, often frustrating, path
of the permanent assistant. Van Gundy hung in there and hung in
there and received a well-earned inheritance in 1996 when he
replaced Don Nelson, who had replaced Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Odd how things work out. Now Silas, 55, is soaring and Van
Gundy, 37, appears to be headed for the gallows, just a few steps
behind Ernie Grunfeld, who was moved out on Wednesday. Silas was
asked Friday if, all things considered, he would want to be the
Knicks' head coach now.
</P>
<P>
   Silas recoiled. ``Oh, no,'' he said. ``No no no no no no no. Oh,
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Van Gundy, he said: ``I love him to death. We came
in together, remained close friends. He's in a tough situation.
He's done a good job here, and there will be other job openings for
him.'' Silas caught himself and added a disclaimer: ``If something
happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and the Hornets were faced with similar puzzles this
season: the Hornets solved theirs, the Knicks have not. The Hornets
had a hodgepodge of injured, mismatched players. They traded Glen
Rice and J.R. Reid to the Lakers for Jones and center Elden
Campbell in a deal that has turned out to be a steal.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was given Marcus Camby to replace Charles Oakley and
Latrell Sprewell to replace John Starks and Chris Mills. Not bad
players, but the Knicks have found neither rhyme nor reason. The
Hornets are firing on all cylinders. Why?
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets have a signature; the Knicks do not, and this gets
to the core of the Knicks' problems. Coaches develop a stamp over a
period of time. Silas developed his as a NBA player _ a tough,
no-nonsense approach featuring muscle and hard work. But in his
first head coaching job, in 1980 with a rotten San Diego Clippers
team, it was all he could do to put a team on the court. He was
dismissed in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets rallied around Silas, who they know is getting a
long overdue second chance. Last year Silas interviewed in Seattle,
Chicago and Sacramento. There were previous attempts at jobs in New
Jersey and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Silas got his shot, on an interim basis, when Dave Cowens
stepped down on March 8. Like Silas, many of the Charlotte players
_ David Wesley, Charlotte's starting point guard; Campbell, the
center, and Bobby Phills, a guard-forward _ have something to
prove. The Knicks have all been paid, and you get the sense that
for some that alone is the proof.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets merged into one personality, the Knicks have no
collective personality. Perhaps Van Gundy's greatest failure is
that he hasn't been an effective alchemist. For all the blame put
on Grunfeld _ and this is not an attempt to absolve him completely
_ the fact is that Van Gundy was given All-Star caliber players and
they didn't fit his mold or his philosophy. He hasn't been willing
or able to break the mold and cast a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Silas picked up the pieces of a shattered season and created a
playoff contender. But the scars of 10 years as an assistant erased
any illusions he had of longevity and reward. He said he was sorry
to see his friend Grunfeld go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him, but this is the NBA,'' Silas said. ``These
things happen and it's all a part of it. When you sign your
contract, you sign your resignation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
