<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine 0-3 after 9-1 loss
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tom Glavine's quest for his first win of 1999 _ the
first since winning 20 games last year along with a Cy Young Award
_ continues.
</P>
<P>
   It started at Turner Field with matchups against Curt Schilling
and Randy Johnson. It was delayed for a day in Philadelphia because
of rain and another day in Colorado because of snow. It nearly
ended, oddly enough, in Colorado before disappearing into thin air
when John Rocker blew a save in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The odyssey passed through Pro Player Stadium Friday night in a
9-1 loss to the Marlins, the one team that has given Glavine more
fits than any other team in its short existence.
</P>
<P>
   It may be fitting, then, that Florida is the team to give
Glavine his first 0-3 start since his rookie year in 1988. His ERA
climbed to 5.61 after he allowed four runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   He is 0-4 in his last five games against the Marlins. Florida
hasn't lost to Glavine in a regular-season game since July of 1996
and is the only team to have a winning record against Glavine in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd team to give him trouble, especially given that the
Marlins came into the game with a 4-11 record. Odd players on that
team to do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Redmond, who was hitting .118 entering the game,
got three of his career-high four hits off Glavine, drove in a run
and scored another. Pitcher Livan Hernandez took Glavine deep for
his first major-league home run and finished with four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Hudek provided no help as he gave up five runs on
four hits and a pair of walks _ all in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   The first three innings went smoothly enough for Glavine after
he gave up three hits and a walk but managed to strand all four
runners. But then the Marlins made him pay in the fourth and sixth
with two runs in each inning, including Hernandez's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dunwoody and Kevin Orie both singled to bring up Redmond
with one out. Redmond slapped a grounder just past Randall Simon
down the first-base line, driving in his first run of the season.
It was his second hit of the game and only the fourth of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It put Orie at third and in position to score on a sacrifice fly
by Hernandez. That gave the Marlins a 2-1 lead on Glavine. It
doubled two innings later when Redmond came up again. With two
outs, he singled softly to center and scored when Hernandez pulled
a pitch to left field for a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the 22-year-old right-hander who ruined the Braves
1997 NLCS with his 3-hit complete game gem in a 2-1 win, didn't do
too shabby on the mound either. He was little trouble for the
Braves last year as they beat him twice in three starts. But on
Friday he was mixing his pitches nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
