<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nixon 16th ever to steal 600
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Otis Nixon wasted no time picking up career stolen base
No. 600.
</P>
<P>
   He drew a walk from Livan Hernandez in the first inning Friday
night and then stole second base, sliding in head-first to beat the
throw from Marlins catcher Mike Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't pick up the base.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had joked earlier this week that when he reached this
milestone he would pick up the base and show it to the fans like
Rickey Henderson did when he broke Ty Cobb's record for career
stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 other players in major league history have reached the
600 mark, only seven since World War II. Nixon, 40, who's in his
17th major league season, ranks 16th all-time in stolen bases. He
has averaged 37 a year. He had his best year on the bases in 1991,
stealing 72 for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who leads the Braves with six steals, was thrown out in
the seventh inning Friday, the first time he's been caught this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Too much time off, Cox says
</P>
<P>
   The fourth and fifth members of the Braves rotation are in the
process of regrouping after rough outings the last trip through the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood said his focus now is on making some minor
mechanical adjustments. For Odalis Perez, his problems may be
solved by getting back into regular work since he was skipped the
previous time through the rotation because of off-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in Millwood and Perez's case they probably had to sit
too long for young kids,'' manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood had his first side session Friday since his 5-4 loss in
L.A. when he walked four and gave up a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a couple small mechanical things I can
change that will make me better,'' Millwood said. ``I don't think
it's going to be an overnight fix-it thing. It's a trial-and-error
kind of thing.... I can't get too caught up in how things have
gone. I've got to work on my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood has allowed four runs in each of his three starts, the
last of which didn't even last four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun to go out and pitch like that,'' Millwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Perez looked uncharacteristically wild in his start on Wednesday
night in L.A. when he had five walks in four innings. He left after
throwing 99 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pitch the way I'm supposed to pitch, maybe because I
was not in a routine,'' Perez said. ``Too many walks, too
</P>
<P>
   many pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez pays a visit to Galarraga
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez spent Thursday's off-day visiting with
cancer-stricken Andres Galarraga at his home in West Palm Beach.
Galarraga received his latest chemotherapy treatment a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said the only thing that looked different about Galarraga
was his shaved head. He lost a patch of his hair because of the
treatment and decided to shave the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not feeling so bad,'' Perez said. ``He doesn't look like
he's got something.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said Galarraga had some problems last week when a vein
used for treatment became irritated but otherwise is doing well. He
may drop by Pro Player Stadium for a visit while the Braves are in
town through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly...
</P>
<P>
   Running out a pinch-hit infield single in the 10th inning
Wednesday night may not have set Ryan Klesko back, but he's still
not ready to return to the lineup because of his sore hamstring.
Klesko has been taking batting practice but he's still not done any
work at first base. ... Tonight's game will start at 7:15 p.m.
instead of 7:05 because of a pregame ceremony and first pitch by
Hank Aaron, as part of his continuing year-long celebration of the
25th anniversary of career home run No. 715. ... Reliever Russ
Springer made his first appearance for Class AAA Richmond on
Wednesday in Indianapolis, pitching a perfect inning in his
rehabilitation assignment as he makes a comeback from back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
