<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andretti becomes honorary Alabaman
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ The Gang's here after all. It just took was a
state proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's DieHard 500 has been lamented as the first Winston Cup
race at Talladega Superspeedway without a home-grown driver. There
are no Alabama drivers entered in the 60th Cup event at the
30-year-old track.
</P>
<P>
   The state will be represented by John Andretti, driving the No.
43 Pontiac. Andretti is a native of Bethlehem, Pa. But the Alabama
House of Representatives fell for a publicity ploy and voted to
grant Andretti honorary citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Andretti's publicist Chip Williams tried to
get the City of Talladega to adopt Andretti. Track officials
discouraged the move, claiming it might embarrass a couple of
Alabama drivers still seeking a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti was happily surprised by the House proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I got in unanimously or like by one vote,
50-49, or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't trying to embarrass anyone from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole deal was just something to honor Alabama and to
honor the `Alabama Gang.' Bobby Allison, Donnie Allison, Davey
Allison, Neil Bonnett, Red Farmer and the rest, they just meant a
lot to me and meant a lot to how much I enjoyed stock car racing,''
Andretti said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the track honored the Gang by announcing it will build
the new 22,000-seat Allison Grandstand, named for Bobby and Donnie,
replacing current grandstands on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Bama's in the Busch
</P>
<P>
   The state won't be represented by a ringer in Saturday's
Touchstone Energy 300 Busch race. Birmingham native Jimmy Kitchens,
who drives the No. 22 Chevrolet, made the race by standing on his
Thursday lap of 189.010 mph. He'll start 33rd in the 43-car event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud to make a NASCAR race here at our home
track,'' he said. ``I really wish we could've been in the top 10. I
felt like we had a strong enough car to do that. We had a little
engine problem yesterday that hurt us in first-round qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens has made four earlier races, wrecked in two, and has a
best finish of 29th at Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Fast start, no stop
</P>
<P>
   Chad Little was the first out to qualify Friday and after
dashing around Talladega Superspeedway in 48.841 seconds (196.065
mph), he looked like he might just keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody pulls their brake pads back to qualify,'' Little
said. ``That's kind of a given, a little less resistance. Usually,
you pump them a half-dozen times and you get your pedal back. I
started pumping them going down the back straightaway like the
normal deal and about the time I got into turn 3 I was still
pumping them and there was no sign of anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got real serious about it between 3 and 4 when I still
didn't feel anything. And then coming out of turn 4 when I still
didn't have any pedals, I figured, `I'm in trouble here.' So I just
put it in gear and let the compressor slow the car down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
