<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE24-COX     04-23 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schrader answers challenge by winning pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Richard Petty's stable of Pontiacs aren't the
only race cars making a strong push lately on NASCAR'S Winston Cup
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet owner Andy Petree, who all but put his drivers on the
spot with some strong statements last week, watched his top driver,
16-year veteran Ken Schrader, win the pole for Sunday's DieHard 500
at Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, who earned his first Winston Cup victory here in July
1988, covered the 2.66-mile oval in 48.421 seconds, an average
speed of 197.765 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader's speed was faster than all but three of the top
qualifying attempts in the 24 races at Talladega since NASCAR
introduced restrictor plates in 1987. It also was the fastest here
in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, who is 16th in points and 373 behind leader Jeff
Burton, followed last week's ninth-place finish at Martinsville,
Va., with his first pole of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole lot of people pretty disappointed (with the
season so far), and I'm one of them,'' Schrader said. ``I heard
(Petree's quotes) were in one of the newspapers and I read it when
I got home. That wasn't anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy said he was disappointed in the way Kenny Wallace and Ken
Schrader were running. If he'd pulled me and Kenny and the two crew
chiefs into the truck, we would have said the same thing. Nobody's
neck is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader's No. 33 Chevrolet was one of only nine cars to eclipse
an average speed of 196 mph in one of two qualifying laps. Bobby
Labonte will start second, while Burton, Joe Nemechek and Rusty
Wallace round out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't turn anything around,'' Schrader said. ``We had a
good run last week at Martinsville and we happened to come to a
restrictor-plate race this week. We've always had a good
restrictor-plate program.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, the only driver who finished in the top 10 in each of
the last six races, will make his fourth top-5 start in eight
events this year. He was one of several Ford drivers who made great
strides from a year ago. In last year's DieHard 500, Fords needed
six of the seven provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's first-round qualifying, Ford took 11 of the top 25
spots, including five of the first 10. Chevy had three top-10 cars,
while Pontiac owner Joe Gibbs had two
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
