<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paulk an old-fashioned hitter
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hard to learn much from rookie minicamp, but
after the Falcons' nine draft choices and eight rookie free agents
worked out Friday for the first time, one thing was clear. The
nickname ``Jurassic Paulk'' fits Atlanta's rookie fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Paulk, a third-round pick from Arizona State, picked up
that moniker as a freshman at ASU, ostensibly for his heavy-handed
methods.
</P>
<P>
   Players wore just cleats, shorts, jerseys and helmets Friday,
but somebody forgot to tell the 6-foot, 245-pound Paulk to avoid
contact. While running routes, he repeatedly smashed into
linebackers in one-on-one drills. Though he was primarily a
blocking back and caught only two passes in college, Paulk said the
Falcons ``told me they are going to try to incorporate me into the
passing game. I don't think that's too big a leap.''
</P>
<P>
   Test results
</P>
<P>
   After physical exams, rookies were tested in a variety of
drills, including the 40-yard dash, broad jump and vertical jump.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Rondel Menendez, a seventh-round pick from Eastern
Kentucky, was the top tester. He had the best time in the 40, 4.48
seconds, and the best broad jump _ 10 feet, 4 inches. Safety
Johndale Carter, a fourth-round pick from Utah State, was second
with a jump of 10 feet, 3 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Patrick Kerney, the first-round pick from
Virginia, ran the 40 in 4.82 seconds. The best vertical jump was 38
1/2 inches, turned in by wide receiver Eugene Baker, a fifth-round
pick from Kent. Menendez and Carty had 38-inch verticals.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking redemption
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Lamont Green is out to prove people wrong. The linebacker
from Florida State was first team All-ACC last season, though he
missed four games with a dislocated elbow.
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-3, 230-pounder was not drafted, and signed a free
agent contract with Atlanta. It was a letdown for the former USA
Today national defensive player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult coming from a very highly regarded program to
not getting drafted,'' Green said. ``I got calls from a lot of
teams, but I signed with a team that went to the Super Bowl. I
think it's a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll work initially at weakside linebacker, behind Keith
Brooking. Early in his career at FSU, Green backed up Henri
Crockett, the Falcons' starter at strongside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett was at practice Friday, helping coach Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's instinctive,'' Crockett said. ``He's going to make it; I
won't let him slip up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
