</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 23, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SENIOR-2, 4-23 -- Mindy Haney, a senior at Columbine
High School, at her home on Friday. Haney and her fellow seniors
would have been the first class to have graduated from a newly
renovated and modernized Columbine. But now their school,
bullet-riddled and blood-stained, has been closed indefinitely.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 23, 1999 --
SUB-JUDGES-DNA-CLASSES, 4-23 -- Judge John Cratsley, right, moves
in to take a better look at a vial being held by fello Judge Peter
Lauriat at the Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research. Looking
on are David Page, of MIT, left, and Judge Thomas Connelly,
background center. In what is believed to be a unique program,
Superior Court judges are taking part in biology classes at MIT to
learn how to understand DNA evidence, which is determining more and
more cases in their courts. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) IBADAN, Nigeria -- April 23, 1999 -- NIGERIA-POLITICS,
4-23 -- Lamidi Adedibu with his youngest child, Tola, 5, earlier
this week. Adedibu is a Yoruba kingmaker, known locally as the
strongman of Ibadan. The Yoruba, of southwest Nigeria, are one of
the country's three main ethnic groups. What role the Yoruba should
play in Nigeria is being debated passionately here in the
quintessentially Yoruba city. (Norimitsu Onishi/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 23, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1, 4-23 -- Students read memorial messages
left near Columbine High School on Friday. Two students stormed
into the suburban Denver school on Tuesday firing shotguns and
tossing pipe bombs. Fifteen people were killed including the two
suspects who committed suicide hours after the rampage started.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 23, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1, 4-23 -- Memorial messages left near
Columbine High School on Friday. Two students stormed into the
suburban Denver school on Tuesday firing shotguns and tossing pipe
bombs. Fifteen people were killed including the two suspects who
committed suicide hours after the rampage started. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 23, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1, 4-23 -- Memorial messages left near
Columbine High School on Friday. Two students stormed into the
suburban Denver school on Tuesday firing shotguns and tossing pipe
bombs. Fifteen people were killed including the two suspects who
committed suicide hours after the rampage started. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) JERUSALEM -- April 23, 1999 -- JERUSALEM-RADIO, 4-23 --
Shmuel Ben-Attar, left, the director of an ultra-Orthodox pirate
radio station, The Whole Truth, with a host who gave his name only
as Dani. Part revival meeting, part yeshiva of the airwaves,
ultra-Orthodox radio in Israel offers spiritual solace, community
assistance and religious guidance to untold thousands. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) UNDATED -- April 23, 1999 -- PICKLE-BOTTLE, 4-21 -- This
pickle jar, circa 1850, had bidders hopping at the Ebay auction
site. The bottle actually cost only $3, and it sold for $44,100.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- BUDGET-KOSOVO, 4-23 --
From left, Prime Minister Vikton Orban of Hungary; Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.; NATO Secretary General Javier Solana;
and Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., listen to speaches during the
Congressional ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of NATO on
Friday at the Capitol. After outdoing each other for months in
their pledges not to fritter away the federal budget surplus, both
parties in Congress have quickly agreed that the costs of the
Balkans conflict should be an exception. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) LONDON -- April 23, 1999 -- PORTER-MEDICINE, 4-23 -- Roy
Porter, the British medical historian, says the mind and illness
are connected. ``I've been teaching nonstop for 27 years, and I've
been healthy for 27 years,'' he says from his cluttered cavern of
an office at the Wellcome Institute for the History of Medicine.
``And within a fortnight of taking sabbatical leave, when I finally
had nothing urgent to do, I got sick.'' (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- STEPHENS-THEATER, 4-23 --
Toby Stephens in the play ``Ring Round the Moon'' at the Belasco
Theater. ``I was brought up in a theater family, but that doesn't
mean it was a constant Noel Coward play,''' says Stephens, 30, in
his dressing room. ``I saw a lot of plays and understood that this
was what some people did: they dressed up in funny clothes and
pretended to be different people in different periods. And they
earned money from it.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) LAKEWOOD, Colo. -- April 23, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-SENIOR,
4-23 --Autumn Hettinger, a senior at Columbine High School, in her
room at her home on Friday. Autumn and her fellow seniors would
have been the first class to have graduated from a newly renovated
and modernized Columbine. But now their school, bullet-riddled and
blood-stained, has been closed indefinitely. Hettinger lost one
firend to the shooting on Tuesday and has several others still in
the hospital. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO, 4-23 --
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, right,
talks with Supreme NATO Commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, prior to a
ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of NATO in the Capitol
Rotunda on Friday. Western leaders taking part in the celebrations
pledged on Friday to intensify their military fight against
Yugoslavia and maintain it until their demands are met. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
SUB-AUDREY-HEPBURN-IMAGE, 4-23 -- Little black shift dresses in the
Audrey Hepburn theme windows at Bergdorf Goodman. Hepburn's status
as style goddess is spreading from the fashion world to the real
one with new urgency. On May 4 she would have turned 70, but as far
as her rejuvenated image is concerned, it's ingenue all over again.
(Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- April 23, 1999 -- TRILLINGS, 4-23 --
Next week The American Scholar will publish an article by James
Trilling, seen at his home during a recent interview, titled ``My
Father and the Weak-Eyed Devils.'' The work by Trilling, the son of
Lionel and Diana Trilling, recalls that his father was so blinded
by his love of Freud and psychoanalysis that he missed his real
disease. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
HAUTE-HIPPIE-FASHION-2, 4-23 -- For a haute hippie biker with
$6,800 (and good balance on Dolce &AMP; Gabbana heels), designs by
Chrome Hearts can furnish a look. Kelli Delaney, the senior fashion
editor at Glamour magazine, says the hippie trend ``is a backlash
to the almost masculine streamlined forms of spring.'' (Marilynn K.
Yee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
HAUTE-HIPPIE-FASHION-1, 4-23 -- Chanel's flower child needs a
$3,355 budget: if a mirror-studded silver belt is a bit much around
the forehead, it also drapes nicely on the hips. ``The '60s hippie
clothes are feminine, flowy, sexy,'' says Kelli Delaney, the senior
fashion editor at Glamour magazine. ``You feel groovy wearing
them.'' (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
NITEOUT-TITO-PUENTE, 4-23 -- Tito Puente greeting birthday
well-wishers at Jimmy's Bronx Cafe on Tuesday night. As dusk fell,
stars were heading uptown on the Major Deegan, and local Bronx
heavyweights like the rapper Fat Joe were suiting up in their
flashy best. All were coming out to pay homage to Puente, the
godfather of Latin music, who was celebrating his 76th. (Miles
Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
ABOUT-CARS-LESABRE-3, 4-23 -- Although the Buick 2000 LeSabre has a
smaller engine - a 3-liter V6 - its horsepower rivals that of its
bigger competitiors and it holds its own in interior roominess.
With a LeSabre Custom starting at just $23,505, this new,
much-improved Buick seems a compelling value. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
ABOUT-CARS-LESABRE-2, 4-23 -- The Buick 2000 LeSabre's body has
been considerably stiffened, the handling is as crisp as any large
car selling for less than $30,000. The car holds the road, takes
the turns, accelerates onto freeways and isolates its occupants
from noise and bumps. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
ABOUT-CARS-LESABRE-1, 4-23 -- Except for its powertrain, the 2000
LeSabre is new from the bottom up, though it still resembles other
members of the Buick family. The ride and handling have been
improved. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
EUROPE-BUYOUTS-2, 4-23 -- Joseph Rice, right, chairman of Clayton,
Dubilier &AMP; Rice, and Charles Ames, a Clayton partner, oversee a
German acquisition from New York, but plan a German office. ``Our
efforts are at getting the European community to know us and
understand that when we say we are going to do a deal, we'll do
it,'' says Rice. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LONDON -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
EUROPE-BUYOUTS-1, 4-23 -- John Muse, chief operating officer of the
Dallas-based buyout firm Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, has moved to
London outright to pursue deal-making in England and elsewhere in
Europe. In Piccadilly Circus, he rests against the ornate base of
the statue of Eros. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ST. LOUIS, Mo. -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
25 -- BIZ-ST.-LOUIS-3, 4-23 -- Jasna Mruckovski fled Banja Luka and
now sells real estate in here. ``St. Louis is seen as a cheap place
to live,'' says Ms. Mruckovski, 25. ``Bosnians don't care if they
start by buying the smallest, ugliest house. At least they feel
they have something.'' (Tim Parker/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ST. LOUIS, Mo. -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
25 -- BIZ-ST.-LOUIS-2, 4-23 -- Among the wave of Bosnian immigrants
arriving here is Alem Boric, who fled Sarajevo in 1995, worked as a
laborer for a couple of years and then used the money he made to
open a market. ``This is a great place to start a business,'' he
says. (Tim Parker/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ST. LOUIS, Mo. -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
25 -- BIZ-ST.-LOUIS-1, 4-23 -- Steve Hrdlicka, a loan officer in
St. Louis, says his bank branch was a sleepy backwater until a wave
of Bosnian newcomers arrived. ``Eight years ago when we opened this
branch, we sat on our hands most of the time,'' says Hrdlicka, 39.
``Then this place became a rally place for Bosnians.'' (Tim
Parker/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- NATO-CITY-COX, 4-23 --
Security agents on the balcony of Mellon Auditorium while NATO
leaders met inside during ceremonies marking the 50th anniversary
of the alliance. Security around the capital has been tightened as
NATO leaders take part in events marking the anniversary. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) RUSHKULL, Albania -- April 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
4-23 -- A carpenter walks past tents on Friday at a refugee camp
being prepared for ethnic Albanians fleeing the violence in Kosovo.
The camp is intented to hold some 50,000 refugees. (James Hill/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- NATO-SUMMIT-4, 4-23 --
President Clinton talks to NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
while flanked by leaders of nations belonging to NATO on Friday.
Western leaders, celebrating NATO's 50th anniversary, pledged to
intensify their military fight against Yugoslavia and maintain it
until their demands are met. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- NATO-SUMMIT-3, 4-23 --
The leaders of the NATO countries during the opening ceremony,
German, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder shakes hands with NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana, right, as President Clinton looks
on during a group photo session on Friday. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
4-23 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo are taken to a camp
after crossing the border on Friday. U. N. aid workers say that
extraordinary numbers of ethnic Albanians seem to be trekking their
way through the rugged peaks that span the border between Kosovo
and Macedonia. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LONDON -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25 --
BIZ-CREDIT-CARDS, 4-23 -- Vern and Jillian Perry of Laguna Hills,
Calif., paying by credit card at a cafe in the Covent Garden Piazza
of London. Exchange rates offered by credit cards have generally
been better than those at local currency exchange counters. But
some travelers are finding such shopping a little more expensive
than it used to be, as some card issuers are adding fees on
transactions in foreign currencies. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 25 --BIZ-PROFILE-MIYAMOTO, 4-23 -- Shigeru Miyamoto, who has
created various blockbuster video games in 22 years at Nintendo,
receiving the first lifetime achievement award at last month's Game
Developers Conference in San Jose. ``He's the god of gaming,'' says
Jennifer Pahlka, director of the industry trade show conference.
(Anne Dowie/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) RAHWAY, N.J. -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 25
-- INVEST-OGDEN, 4-23 -- Trash is moved at Ogden's operation at the
Union County Resource Facility in Rahway. Converting waste to
energy is a core business for Ogden, but entertainment and aviation
services are gaining. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
25 -- BARCLAYS-DUNN-PROFILE, 4-23 -- Patricia C. Dunn, who now runs
Barclays Global, started there as a secretary after she couldn't
find a job in journalism after college. ``My expectations were so
low that I can honestly say I did not have a career ambition,'' she
says. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BELMONT, Mass. -- April 23, 1999 -- PROFILE-MURPHY-BOS,
04-22 -- Dale Murphy, in the office of Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-Day Saints, popularly known as Mormons. Murphy, winner of
two consecutive National League Most Valuable Player awards and
clubbing 398 home runs during a 14-year career, is now the
volunteer president of the church's Boston Mission. ``I'm like the
supervisor,'' says Murphy, 43, about his current job. ``I help, I
train, I educate, I see how they're doing.'' (Joanne Rathe/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- April 23, 1999 -- BBO-DIMAGGIO, 4-23 --
Carmine Comito, a lifelong New York Yankees fan making his 82
birthday today, listens to speakers during a memorial service for
Joe Dimaggio at St. Patrick's Cathedral on Friday. DiMaggio, the
Yankees Hall of Fame centerfielder, died March 8 of complications
from lung cancer. Though he was buried in California following a
small funeral, family and friends wanted a service in New York, the
city where the shy son of a Bay Area immigrant catapulted to
national prominence. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LANGHORNE, Pa. -- April 23, 1999 -- POKEMON-CRAZE-2, 4-23
-- Marie Summa, 12, of Beverly, N.J., wears a homemade Pokemon hat
resembling one of the game's characters, Pikachu, at a Pokemon
trading card show. Pokemon, originally a video game that features
150 monsters, or Pokemons, is the new craze among schoolchildren
across the country. Introduced in Japan by Nintendo just three
years ago, Pokemon has already grown into a $5 billion
international industry that includes comic books, plastic
figurines, virtual pets, bean-bag toys, lunch boxes, T-shirts, a
television cartoon show, compact disks and trading cards. (Jeff
Zelevansky/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LANGHORNE, Pa. -- April 23, 1999 -- POKEMON-CRAZE-1, 4-23
-- Players at a Pokemon trading card game. Pokemon, originally a
video game that features 150 monsters, or Pokemons, is the new
craze among schoolchildren across the country. Introduced in Japan
by Nintendo just three years ago, Pokemon has already grown into a
$5 billion international industry that includes comic books,
plastic figurines, virtual pets, bean-bag toys, lunch boxes,
T-shirts, a television cartoon show, compact disks and trading
cards. (Jeff Zelevansky/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 23, 1999 -- YELLING-EXCERPTS-COX, 4-23
-- The ability of children to manage anger and handle conflict, the
topic of conversation in the wake of the school shootings in
Colorado, is a subject handled by the book ``Tired of Yelling,
Teaching Our Children to Resolve Conflict'' from Longstreet Press.
(Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- NATO-SUMMIT-2, 4-23 --
President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair before the
start of the NATO summit meeting on Friday. Western leaders,
celebrating NATO's 50th anniversary, pledged today to intensify
their military fight against Yugoslavia and maintain it until their
demands are met. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 23, 1999 -- NATO-SUMMIT-1, 4-23 --
French President Jacques Chirac greets Czech President Vaclav Havel
just before the start of the NATO summit on Friday. Western
leaders, celebrating NATO's 50th anniversary, pledged today to
intensify their military fight against Yugoslavia and maintain it
until their demands are met. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
