<SLUG> BC-GEN-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE NARROWS AD SEARCH TO FIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The five finalists for the athletic director post
at Cal State Northridge present a breadth of experience.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate _ Myles Corrigan, assistant athletic director at
the University of Washington _ has the best football background.
That may make him the favorite when the university announces the
new athletic director in mid-May. Interim AD Sam Jankovich is
signed to a contract that ends at the beginning of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an opportunity that is unique,'' said Corrigan, a 1977
CSUN graduate who went on to become an assistant football coach at
Washington from 1987-93. ``The job presents a variety of
challenges. It's an opportunity to make a real mark on a program
that is certainly in need of an identity.''
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists announced by the school on Friday are Robert
Arias, a Los Angeles civic leader; Richard Dull, a former athletic
director at the University of Maryland; William Lide, athletic
director at North Carolina Central University; and Brian Quinn,
Loyola Marymount's athletic director from 1985-98.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges facing the new athletic director _ inadequate
facilities, a shoestring budget and the looming threat of being
jilted by the Big Sky Conference in football if a new on-campus
stadium is not approved _ are daunting.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the issues the candidates could face in
scheduled, one-hour public forums. That's the mandate the school
has attached to the finalists' interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The five men will have very little downtime in their whirlwind
campus visits, which start with Lide on Tuesday and end with Arias
on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Finney, CSUN's sports information director, said public
meetings with athletic director candidates is nothing new to CSUN _
the university did the same thing when former AD Paul Bubb was
hired in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the community, even from the corporate world that
could possibly be current sponsors or future sponsors, would have
an opportunity to meet the candidates and ask them questions,''
Finney said. ``It's the same with the (football) stadium issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Finney said finalists will get a break of ``about 15 minutes''
between meetings on the days they interview.
</P>
<P>
   Dull, Corrigan and Quinn have the most experience at the
Division I level. Dull, athletic director at Moravian College, a
Division III school in Bethlehem, Pa., was the AD at Maryland from
1981-86.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn has the most experience as an athletic director _ he
headed the department at LMU for 13{ years before being promoted to
executive director of athletic development and promotion in June
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Arias, a 1973 graduate of CSUN, was AD at LMU in the year prior
to Quinn. He is now president of One to One/Los Angeles Communities
in Schools, a position he has held since January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lide has been director of intercollegiate athletics at North
Carolina Central, a Division II school in Durham. He was also AD at
Salisbury State (Md.) from 1987-93 and West Chester University
(Pa.) from 1993-95. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
