</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDONEZ COMES OFF BENCH TO HELP METS BEAT CUBS, 6-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Mets' game began Friday with the wind blowing in
at Wrigley Field, a bright sun in right field and the Gold Glove
shortstop Rey Ordonez on the bench for the second straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez said it was the first time he could remember missing two
consecutive starts while healthy. But no matter how much manager
Bobby Valentine might have been trying to teach his shortstop a
lesson, the game came down to an Ordonez at-bat. He lofted a ball
to right field, an area that belittled the Mets all day.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez's sacrifice fly came with the bases loaded in the ninth
and broke a 5-5 tie. And after John Franco set the Cubs down in
order to finish off his seventh save in seven attempts, the Mets
had a strange 6-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Never in his major league career had Bobby Jones opened a season
4-0. A 29-year-old right-hander, Jones had never even been 3-0
before this season. But then, Jones _ 8-1 against Chicago in his
career with a 3.53 earned run average _had also never lost to the
Cubs at Wrigley Field, where he was 5-0 with a 3.42 ERA coming in.
</P>
<P>
   So it figured something just might give Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, the wind, and that was fortunate for Jones.
But a bright sun ended up costing the pitcher dearly, and making
the afternoon one Jermaine Allensworth would probably just as soon
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Allensworth entered the game in the bottom of the sixth with the
Mets ahead by 1-0. Lance Johnson began the inning with a single,
and stole second. Mickey Morandini followed with a tricky liner to
right.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had inserted Allensworth for Bobby Bonilla after
Bonilla lost a ball in the sun, turning an apparent out into a
double by Benito Santiago. When Allensworth caught Morandini's
ball, there was one out _ and Valentine looked especially smart.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa was next and he grounded a ball between short and
third. Luis Lopez, making his second straight start at short in
place of Ordonez, attempted an Ordonez-like move by sliding for the
ball. But the ball looked as if it nicked the outfield grass,
kicking over Lopez's glove.
</P>
<P>
   So Lopez, who had driven in a run and who later would drive in
another run, had just now missed a ball. Three pitches later, Mark
Grace knocked a sacrifice fly to center to tie the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   When Henry Rodriguez hit a two-out single to right, Sosa
advanced to third. And then the sun came into play for Santiago
again. With Jones ahead in the count, 1-2, Santiago reached out for
a sharp curve and blooped the ball to right. Allensworth charged in
and attempted an awkward stop. At the last moment, the defensive
replacement thrust out his glove, but the ball nearly hit him in
the face.
</P>
<P>
   It dropped for a two-run triple and a 3-1 Cubs lead. An
aggravated Jones nearly threw away Manny Alexander's comebacker
before getting the final out of the inning on his final pitch of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley was not finished with Allensworth. After Lopez singled
home Brian McRae in the seventh to make the score 3-2, the Cubs
scored twice in the bottom of the inning for a three-run lead. The
key hit off the reliever Dennis Cook was a triple just inside the
right-field line by Johnson. It was a triple because Allensworth
slipped and fell as he was attempting to field the ball near the
brick wall along the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson scored on a safety squeeze by Morandini, the Mets
were down by three runs. But nothing is safe at Wrigley. And the
Mets rallied for three runs in the eighth, with Allensworth getting
a single, Robin Ventura a run-scoring double and Todd Pratt a
two-run single with the bases loaded that kicked off both the mound
and Morandini's glove.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets _ on another bizarre afternoon at Wrigley _ had
somehow tied the score at 5-5 to get Jones off the hook and set the
stage for Ordonez to become a hero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
