<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-VOWS-NYT &LR;      04-23 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-VOWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ROBBING PETER TO PAY PAUL AS CITY STALLS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ed Phelan took a vow of poverty when he joined the
Christian Brothers, a Roman Catholic religious order. He is in no
danger of breaking that sacred promise. He runs the Highbridge
Community Life Center in the Bronx, directing an 80-person staff
that provides welfare recipients and high school dropouts with
counseling, job training and an education. It's front-line social
service work that gives him more psychic income than the green kind
would.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he opened a line of credit to sustain successful
training programs financed last year through the federal
empowerment zone in the South Bronx. A $494,000 grant for the
second year of staff salaries and program costs has been held up,
because the empowerment zone board has not met to approve any
projects. Brother Ed, whose group trained almost 70 people for jobs
as nurse's aides or package deliverers last year, had entered the
new year borrowing money and shifting other grants, thinking the
money would be approved quickly. But the empowerment zone seems
like the Twilight Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on my staff who say, `Ed, you took a vow of
poverty, but I don't have to live it,' '' he said. ``This has
sapped all of my energy trying to find money, worrying about it and
trying to keep the message from our staff that it's panicville.''
</P>
<P>
   The board was to have met last February, but the meeting was
canceled when Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington, who represents the
city, asked for more information on zone projects in Harlem. While
another meeting is scheduled for next month, Brother Ed has tried
without luck to shake loose his group's share of the money a little
earlier. He said Washington has yet to respond to his entreaties.
</P>
<P>
   Payrolls can't wait, and Brother Ed had to take out $230,000 in
bank loans at 8 percent interest. Although only six staff members
are affected by the impasse in financing, his entire staff may have
to take pay cuts to keep the programs running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going from day to day,'' Brother Ed said. ``We need to
bring pressure on Rudy Washington to approve this contract. The
city talks about the importance of people getting off public
assistance and into jobs. Their delays are killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Washington did not respond to a request for
comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ithier, the president of the Bronx Overall Economic
Development Corp. and a member of the zone's board, said the
Highbridge group was not the only project affected by the delay in
convening the board. He said that several businesses that had
applied for grants and loans to open up in the zone have had plans
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could tell us they're going to Jersey where things move
fast,'' Ithier said. ``The empowerment zone is supposed to cut red
tape. What we're doing is adding to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving anywhere is not an option for Brother Ed. He has stayed
in this hilly corner of the Bronx for years, even when some of his
friends joked that it seemed the landscape got bleaker the longer
he was there. Things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are working together,'' Brother Ed said.
``It's not about having a lot of awards or nice-looking buildings.
It's about the struggle of people. It's about helping.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not want people to get lost in the quagmire over budgets
and grants. Every day he sees his neighbors from Highbridge sitting
at computers or filing into classrooms ready to learn new skills.
Dorenda Gibbons was there last Monday, studying for her high school
equivalency diploma. She used to be stuck at home, surviving on
welfare and feeling sorry for herself because of chronic bursitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get off public assistance,'' she said. ``I can't
take it anymore. If I can get my diploma, I'm good to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Betty Mitchell was taking a break from her first day of
nurse's aide training. She already earned her high school diploma
at Highbridge, now she wanted to find a job in a nursing home to
help care for the elderly. She got the idea for that recently, when
her parents died from cancer months apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people show emotion when they care for old people,''
she said. ``It's just a job to them. I want to make a difference in
somebody's life. We're all going to get old. We all need somebody
to help us eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Brother Ed nodded. He understood her perfectly well. Especially
on payday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
