<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENARIOS FOR RESOLUTION OF STRAWBERRY'S STATUS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Darryl Strawberry's baseball career in jeopardy,
his standing with Major League Baseball could be resolved within
the next two days, according to a baseball official.
</P>
<P>
   Results from drug tests Strawberry took subsequent to his arrest
for cocaine possession and solicitation of prostitution on April 14
were expected late this week, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the charges, the test results could have an impact on
Strawberry's future.
</P>
<P>
   There likely are three possible resolutions to Strawberry's
case:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strawberry could be subject to some sort of penalty. As a
second-time offender in 1995, Strawberry was suspended for 60 days.
If he is found to have violated the rules of baseball's after-care
program a third time, he could receive an even greater penalty.
However, if baseball officials discern mitigating circumstances _
Strawberry is being treated for colon cancer and, like most
recovering cancer patients, has suffered from depression _ the
suspension could be less than 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Major League Baseball would not comment on
Strawberry's case. However, if the case is resolved within the next
two days _ before his charges in Tampa, Fla., are settled _ then
logic would suggest he faces some sort of penalty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strawberry could agree to take counseling with either no
penalty or a minimal penalty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Major League Baseball could take the unusual step of
announcing that Strawberry passed all of his drug tests. Baseball
typically does not announce the results of drug tests that are
passed, but Strawberry's case has drawn such attention that
officials may feel the need to clarify Strawberry's status.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the resolution, Strawberry's career could already
be finished. If he is penalized in any way, the Yankees could
attempt to void his contract based on very strict behavioral
clauses. If Strawberry is cleared, he would still have to overcome
his legal case, which could drag on for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said Friday that he
had no idea when Strawberry would resume working out. ``We're
taking it day by day, while he's dealing with his personal
issues,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   Four things must happen before Strawberry returns to the field
for the Yankees: he must be cleared by Major League Baseball; he
must hurdle his legal issues; he must be forgiven by George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, and he must prove he is
in good enough condition to play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
