<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOARD-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S ACCORD WITH CITY COUNCIL SPEAKER WOULD END NEW YORK CITY
SCHOOL BOARD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich.)   (rk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of criticizing the Board of Education
from separate corners in City Hall, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone have agreed to pursue legislation
that would abolish the board and replace it with a system more
beholden to the mayor and the City Council, representatives from
both sides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They have not yet ironed out the details of a specific proposal,
but are looking at various options, including systems already in
place in Chicago and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Anthony P. Coles, a senior adviser to the
mayor, Giuliani and Vallone agree that any new system would
probably include a commissioner of education, appointed by the
mayor with the advice and the consent of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Coles said that Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew would be the
mayor's first choice for commissioner. A spokeswoman for Crew said
Friday that the chancellor's office was unaware of the plan by
Giuliani and Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the proposal are still under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus in City Hall hardly ensures, however, that the plan
will receive the necessary approval of the state Legislature.
Although both sides said that they had the general support of Gov.
George Pataki, they acknowledged that they would have a difficult
time convincing the Democrat-controlled Assembly of the merit of
their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lynch, a spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver _
who is not an ally of either the mayor or the speaker _ confirmed
Friday that they had reason for concern, saying that the Assembly
was predisposed against any plan to give the mayor control of the
school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who is sitting in City Hall,'' she said.
``It is just a philosophical approach to education. It should be an
independent school board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education is a semi-autonomous body that oversees
the education of 1.1 million children in more than 1,100 schools
throughout the city. Its seven members include two mayoral
appointees and a representative from each of the city's five
boroughs. Its chancellor is appointed by the board, but mayors,
including Giuliani, have traditionally had significant input in the
selection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-23-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990423.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-MEMORIAL     04-23 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 LAVISH MEMORIAL FOR DiMAGGIO DRAWS THE FAMOUS AND THE FANS  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most private of men, Joe DiMaggio, was
memorialized Friday in the most public of places, St. Patrick's
Cathedral, where his teammates from the Yankee glory years joined
Manhattan's celebrity elite and baseball die-hards from the outer
boroughs to say goodbye to a bona fide hero.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was as diverse as the city that was DiMaggio's
baseball home through 10 pennants, 9 championships, 3 most valuable
player awards and a legendary hitting streak. As contradictory as
the peerless center fielder, who was the son of an immigrant
fisherman and the husband of a Hollywood star.
</P>
<P>
   Who else but DiMaggio could draw a crowd that included Henry A.
Kissinger, the former secretary of state, and Frank Petrizzo, a
court reporter from Staten Island? Or E.L. Doctorow, the author of
``Ragtime,'' and Jim McGonigle, a Queens cabbie? Or Mort Zuckerman,
the owner of The Daily News, and Tim Curley, a eighth grader from
Brooklyn's Xavarian High School?
</P>
<P>
   John Cardinal O'Connor, who presided at the prayer service with
a bandage on his nose after minor surgery, welcomed them all to the
splendid cathedral where Yankee greats Babe Ruth, Billy Martin and
Roger Maris also had been mourned. Quoting his father, the cardinal
offered the first of many tributes to DiMaggio's athletic prowess
and personal grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father liked Joe DiMaggio,'' O'Connor said simply. ``He had
tremendous respect for him. And he paid him the highest accolade
you can give anyone. He said DiMaggio seemed to be a very decent
fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   This very decent fellow guarded his privacy, begging that no
daily medical bulletins be issued during his long siege of lung
cancer and choosing a small, private funeral, which took place in
his hometown of San Francisco last month. But Friday, at the
insistence of friends who thought a hero deserved a hero's tribute,
the reclusive Yankee Clipper was celebrated in the grandest, and at
times the gaudiest, way.
</P>
<P>
   The formal eulogies were delivered by Dr. Bobby Brown,
DiMaggio's teammate and a former American League president, and
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, a lifelong Yankee fan.
</P>
<P>
   Brown spoke of DiMaggio's quiet leadership, through deeds not
words, and his physical gifts, in the batter's box, on the base
paths and in the yawning space of center field, much larger then
than now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't lead in the modern sense,'' Brown said, scoffing at
team meetings, pep talks and clubhouse chemistry. ``What Joe did
each and every day is set for himself the highest standards and
give you no choice but to try and emulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor spoke of DiMaggio's influence as a role model for
other Italian-Americans, especially during World War II, and the
luster he added to the place where he played from 1936 to 1951.
``He graced our city with style, dignity and class that made New
York even better than it actually is,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The informal eulogies came from the 2,000-odd people who nearly
filled the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a strong man with great character,'' said Kissinger,
who shared the first pew with the mayor; Yogi Berra and his wife,
Carmen, and George M. Steinbrenner III, the Yankee owner. ``He was
as close to perfection as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Romano, a 62-year-old retiree from Union, N.J., echoed that
sentiment. ``Joe DiMaggio was a gentleman,'' he said. ``With him,
there was no baloney. He never looked for glory, but it was there
for him. So I'm here to honor Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the current Yankees were spotted in the huge crowd, and
Steinbrenner said they had stayed away because they had a game last
night and would have a chance to honor DiMaggio in another ceremony
at the stadium on Sunday afternoon. But the difference between
today's ballplayers and those of DiMaggio's era was a motif of the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, for instance, noted in his eulogy that DiMaggio never
argued with umpires, never watched the flight of his own home-run
balls, never danced clownishly around the bases, never left the
dugout for a curtain call. With DiMaggio, he said, there were no
alibis when he played poorly, no theatrics when he played well and
no efforts to ``enhance his own status or reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He set the tone for everyone else's behavior,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL MATERIALS FOLLOWS
</P>
<P>
   Friday's memorial events stood in contrast to last month's
unimposing family funeral for DiMaggio, whose record-breaking
56-game hitting streak and marriage to Marilyn Monroe made him one
of the most famous men of this century. His contemporaries said
that he would have approved of the stately memorial service, even
though he insisted that he did not want one. But the festivities
afterward, an invitation-only brunch at Le Cirque 2000, skipped by
many of the baseball old-timers, would likely have left him coiled
up in shyness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have been against the wall in the corner,'' said Tim
McCarver, the baseball announcer who switched from the Mets to the
Yankees this season. ``In the most obscure part of the room, like
he always was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
