<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-BUZZER-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE OF JOLTING HORSES BECOMES KENTUCKY DERBY TOPIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Ark., Texas, La., Mass., Pa., Ariz., Ill.)   (jw) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It is sometimes referred to as ``plugging in''
a race horse _ the act of shocking the animal with a crude,
hand-held electrical device to prod it to go faster. Though it is
prohibited and reviled within the industry, the longtime practice
has become one of the seamier, and bizarre, story lines as American
thoroughbred racing's grandest moment approaches.
</P>
<P>
   A gelding named Valhol churns the Churchill Downs oval in the
morning along with other race horses preparing for next Saturday's
Kentucky Derby. The strapping 3-year-old earned his chance to
compete in the nation's premier race by winning the Arkansas Derby
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But how Valhol won is in question, as well as whether he will be
eligible for the Kentucky Derby. The Arkansas Racing Commission has
withheld the $300,000 winning purse and alleged that there was
evidence that Valhol's jockey, Billy Patin, was in possession of an
illegal electrical device when the horse romped to a 4{-length
victory as a 30-1 long shot at Oaklawn Park on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   The jockey, a 36-year-old Louisiana native, has denied the
allegation, as has the trainer, Dallas Keen. Valhol's owner, Jim
Jackson, said he believed his rider, although he acknowledged that
a video replay of the race showed something dropping from Patin's
hand shortly after Valhol crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson also believes that the Arkansas Racing Commission is
improperly withholding Valhol's winning purse in an effort to keep
the horse out of the Kentucky Derby. The race is limited to 20
horses, and the entry criteria include money earned in stakes
races. Without the $300,000 from the Arkansas Derby, Valhol
probably will not make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am frustrated by the uncertainty of it all and how long it
is taking,'' said Jackson, who owns Valhalla Farm in Texas. ``Why
am I being held accountable? I did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   What Jackson has done, however, is notify racing officials in
Arkansas and Kentucky that he will use the courts, if necessary, to
press his way into the 125th running of the Derby. Friday, his
lawyers submitted a demand to Arkansas officials for payment of the
$300,000 purse, arguing that the racing commission's own rules
require payment no later than 96 hours after the race. Arkansas
officials rejected the demand, however, arguing that in
circumstances such as this one, the commission was allowed to
overrule itself.
</P>
<P>
   But that was hardly the last word, since one of Jackson's
lawyers, Bill Rambicure, said he and his associates were ``prepared
to do whatever we need to o'' to get the $300,000 released,
including seeking a quick injunction in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Patin's lawyers successfully asked that an Arkansas
hearing on the buzzer allegations be delayed. It will now be held
on May 5, which is four days after the Derby, rather than on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the controversy has had an impact on the storied
backside of Churchill Downs, where Valhol munches hay and takes
sponge baths while his human connections pace the shed row and
answer questions about an investigation that has put them virtually
in quarantine.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the pre-race atmosphere is buoyant with the talk of
who will canter off with the Derby's blanket of roses. But instead,
trainers, testily, and jockeys, sometimes angrily, have had to
address a lightly publicized but very unappealing aspect of their
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer Nick Zito, a two-time winner of the Derby, jumped
from a chair in his small office and marched down to the stalls of
his two current contenders, Stephen Got Even and Adonis. He waved
his hands at his horses and said: ``Who would want to do something
like that to these beautiful animals? Would you stick something on
his neck? If somebody did this to one of my horses, there would be
no need for a security investigation. I'd go tear them apart
myself!''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is a well-documented history in racing of
the use of the devices, often referred to as buzzers or batteries
or machines. The device is about the size of a disposable lighter
with an exposed end that delivers a jolt to a horse's neck while
the rider has the reins in his hand. It is exceedingly hard to spot
such a tactic, because the rider is hunched over and often shielded
by other horses and jockeys. Decades ago, before track security was
improved, they were sometimes built into the jockey's whip.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974 there have been at least 242 instances in which
racing commissions have investigated and taken action against
jockeys, trainers, grooms or escort riders for infractions
involving the devices, according to documents obtained from the
Association of Racing Commissioners International, a racing-data
clearinghouse in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the 1990s alone, there have been 42 buzzer cases at race
tracks, most of them on minor tracks like Suffolk Downs in
Massachusetts, Turf Paradise in Phoenix, Philadelphia Park and all
four Louisiana tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997 the Illinois Racing Board issued a lifetime
ban against a jockey, Patrick Boxie, for ``possessing and
conspiring to use an electrical device'' at Fairmount Park. ``There
is no place for these devices in racing,'' said Gina DiCaro, a
spokesman for the board. ``We take it very, very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Arkansas Derby victory, Patin had never been accused
of using an electrical device, and there is a feeling shared by
Valhol's owner, trainer and jockey that they have been subjected to
extra scrutiny because of their modest backgrounds. It is the first
Kentucky Derby for all three, and their horse had never won a race
until the Arkansas triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, before the Arkansas Derby, Patin had never won a graded
stakes race over a 20-year career spent for the most part on the
minor tracks of Louisiana, which have a colorful, but not always
spotless, reputation. Last summer, for example, Louisiana racing
officials reinstated Sylvester Carmouche, the notorious ``fog
jockey'' who was suspended in 1990. In a race shrouded in fog at
tiny Delta Downs, Carmouche stopped his horse, hid while his
competitors continued racing, then when he heard them come back
around, restarted his horse and scored a short-lived victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Valhol does get into the Derby, it is likely Patin will
not be the rider because of the cloud hanging over him. Still,
Patin remains here to exercise Valhol. ``It's breaking my heart,''
he said of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   And Keen, a trainer for 13 years, has glumly gone about the work
of readying a horse that may never get to the starting gate. He,
too, has never been accused of using an electrical device.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been much fun,'' said Keen, who after days of delay
was finally given an official Derby saddlecloth for Valhol and a
courtesy car. ``Our horse wasn't buzzed. There's not a mark on
him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
