<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO opened its 50th-anniversary summit meeting by pledging
to intensify its air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   -- Yugoslav officials denied that President Slobodan Milosevic
had told a Russian envoy that he would accept an international
military presence in Yugoslavia, saying he only meant unarmed U.N.
observers.
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO and the European Union agreed to ban the sale and supply
of oil to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   -- As the NATO air strikes entered a second month, warplanes and
missiles hit a wide swath of Yugoslavia, including Nis and an area
southwest of Pristina, the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   -- Serbian state television returned to the air, hours after a
NATO missile wrecked its main building. Yugoslav officials said 10
people were killed and 19 injured; 20 are missing.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   -- The United Nations appealed for more money to tackle Europe's
worst refugee crisis since World War II. More than 610,000 Kosovo
Albanians have fled to other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONERS
</P>
<P>
   -- The International Committee of the Red Cross protested its
continued lack of access to three captured American soldiers,
despite President Milosevic's assertion to a Texas television
station this week that the Red Cross was free to visit them.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
