<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-PAY-RAISES24-     04-23 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-PAY-RAISES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate plan puts focus on teachers
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pressured by Democrats to give more to teachers,
the Senate Education Committee on Friday agreed to put $1.7 billion
in new money toward educators' compensation and about $1 billion to
cut local school property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would mean at least $840 million in guaranteed pay
raises for teachers. But individual raises could vary from as much
as $4,000 to nothing depending on teachers' current salaries and
how school districts handle the new money.
</P>
<P>
   While hailing the new focus on teachers, one teacher group
pronounced the raise insufficient and called on lawmakers to drop
the tax cut idea completely in favor of a $6,000 pay hike.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-raise and tax-cut plan, a compromise forced by
Democrats, is a near flip-flop from the $2 billion that GOP Gov.
George W. Bush proposed for property tax cuts and $1 billion he
wanted to give schools to distribute among teachers. Bush, a likely
candidate for the Republican presidential nomination, is likely to
face criticism for not getting his wishes from the
Republican-controlled Senate. The GOP holds 16 of the 31 Senate
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by Sens. David Cain of Dallas and Eliot Shapleigh
of El Paso, said they might be the minority party in the Senate,
``but we represent the majority of the thought of the State of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An overwhelming majority of Texans are most interested in the
education system,'' Cain said.
</P>
<P>
   Cain said Democrats also want property tax cuts but say they
think teacher pay raises should come first. ``It's just a shifting
of the priorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Shapleigh, ``People want to invest in kids. We tried to
use whatever influence we had in this body to direct the thinking
in the Senate to those priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The influence boiled down to votes. Senate rules require two out
of three members to agree to even debate a bill. Neither the
governor's plan nor a Republican-backed alternative had enough
support from Democrats to reach the 21 votes needed to get
consideration. The compromise bill is expected to come up for
debate as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' money includes $1.4 billion intended for pay
raises. At least 60 percent of that, $840 million, must go directly
to teachers. Committee Chairman Sen. Teel Bivins (R-Amarillo) said
he believes school districts will face enormous pressure to give
all of the money to teachers. But to require that would leave
schools without money to pay for other costs created by the raises,
including local input to teachers' retirement benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although $840 million would be guaranteed, raises for each
teacher would vary. That's because the $1.4 billion would be used
to increase the minimum teacher salary schedule by $4,000. That
means teachers paid at the minimum level will get $4,000 raises,
Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   But because more than half of the state's teachers are paid
above the minimum salary level, some might not get anything. In a
rough estimate, however, Cain said the plan _ and the requirement
that at least 60 percent goes directly to teachers _ means more
than half of the state's teachers would get at least an average
raise of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The committee-adopted version of Senate Bill 4 also could mean
good news for retiring teachers. The $1.7 billion includes $110
million for higher retirement benefits and $170 million to help
schools adjust to the new teachers' salaries. The bill also would
increase the percentage of a retiring teacher's service used to
calculate retirement benefits from 2 percent to 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Cole of the Texas Federation of Teachers applauded the
effort to raise teacher salaries but said more money still is
needed. TFT and other groups have argued that teachers should get
across-the-board raises of $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have to settle for $4,000 if you decide you need
another property tax relief bill like we had last session. Once you
get that idea out of your head, then the $6,000 is doable,'' Cole
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tax cuts and teacher raises, the bill
includes Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's Master Reader Teacher proposal. That
would give teachers extra pay if they get advanced training in
teaching reading courses. They would get even more if they used
those skills in low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would force cuts to local school property taxes by
having the state take over more of the cost of old and new school
buildings. Much of local school tax rates go to pay for buildings
and would have to be reduced if the state paid more toward that
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts also would be forced by more money flowing to
fast-growing schools and $100 million in continued tax exemptions
for residential property.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Paul Sadler (D-Henderson) has delayed
decision-making on the issue by his Public Education Committee in
hopes of seeing what the Senate can accomplish. He said he still
wants more for teachers but needs to look at the Senate bill and
other ideas before moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to give a teacher pay raise, we ought to assure
that every school district gets the money but that the money flow
directly to every teacher in the state,'' Sadler said. ``That's
different from moving the minimum salary schedule. I think we can
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   This article contains information from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
