<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-CASTROL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP FUEL POINTS LEADER CONTINUES RUN THROUGH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS _ Larry Dixon's ``True To Texas'' Tour continues to be a
qualified success.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon became the first NHRA Top Fuel driver to crack the
4.5-second barrier when he ran 4.486 seconds during qualifications
for the O'Reilly Nationals at Houston Raceway Park in Baytown on
April 9. The national elapsed-time record-holder based upon that
lap, Dixon lowered the event record for the third annual Castrol
Nationals with a 4.545-second pass at the Texas Motorplex last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, of San Diego, topped a list of four Top Fuel drivers who
cranked out 4.5-second laps during the second session as the sun
went down and track temperatures cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Five-time Top Fuel champion Joe Amato began the barrage with a
4.592-second pass that eventually positioned the Tenneco/Keystone
Dragster fourth. Gary Scelzi, the two-time series champion who
failed to qualify for the first time in his 48-race career at
Baytown, rebounded with a 4.581-second pass at 321.54 mph to place
third on the 16-car ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked like Scelzi had the pole, Tony Schumacher
reeled off a pass at 4.569 seconds and a track-record 323.62 mph in
the Exide Batteries Dragster. Moments later, Dixon one-upped them
all in search of his third consecutive No. 1 position.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we smoked the tires on the first run, we were just
looking to get a clean second run and get in the field,'' said
Dixon, driver of the Miller Lite Dragster owned by Don Prudhomme.
``I thought if we could run in the mid-4.50s it would be nice. We
weren't trying to do another 4.40.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, who ran 316.12 mph on his lap, said he felt his ET would
be in jeopardy today, especially with Scelzi and owner/tuner Alan
Johnson apparently back on line.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi, the Top Fuel champion in 1997 and 1998, served notice
that his first career DNQ might be his last in the Team Winston
Dragster. He clocked laps in 4.613 seconds and 321.77 mph _ the
latter tying Cory McClenathan's former track record _ and followed
with his stout 4.581/321.54.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been trying to do with this five-disc
clutch thing,'' Scelzi said. ``It looks like maybe we're headed in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit Bazemore of Indianapolis is the provisional leader in Funny
Car, with the Brothers Pedregon occupying spots two through four.
</P>
<P>
   Bazemore, third in the points chase to Team Castrol's John Force
and Tony Pedregon, ran 4.921 seconds at 304.15 mph on his second
pass in the Kendall Chevrolet Camaro Z/28. And he deleted some of
car owner Chuck Etchell's engine inventory to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hurting pistons, and finally blew it up at the
end,'' said Bazemore, who qualified No. 1 at Gainesville, Fla.,
last month. ``But when you're going for No. 1, you have to make a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz Pedregon, the 1992 NHRA Funny Car champion, is No. 2 at
4.936 seconds and 310.34 mph in the Interstate Batteries Firebird.
Frank Pedregon is third at 4.947 seconds and 309.27 mph in Jim
Dunn's Penthouse-sponsored Pontiac, followed by brother Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Pedregon's car suffered extensive fire damage on its second
pass, but is fourth overall based on his first-round lap of 4.967
seconds and 308.95 mph. Pedregon rolled his Castrol Syntec Ford
Mustang to a stop with flames engulfing the front wheel wells and
the top of the imitation engine compartment. Pedregon scrambled out
unhurt, although he said he did inhale ``a big gulp of smoke''
after he lifted the front of the car's fiberglass body to help
fight the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Force, the eight-time series champion and winner of three of
four events this year, is 15th after two rounds of tire-smoking
laps and a best ET of 5.718 seconds in the Castrol GTX Ford.
</P>
<P>
   In Pro Stock, Warren Johnson of Sugar Hill, Ga., is the
provisional leader in the GM Goodwrench Service Plus Pontiac after
a lap of 6.989 seconds and 198.28 mph. If Johnson retains the No. 1
spot at the end of today, he will have qualified No. 1 in all four
events this year and five in a row dating to last year's season
finale.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
