<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1433 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPERTS-SHOOTING-SPI &LR;      04-23 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERTS-SHOOTING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS QUICK TO OFFER THEIR HELP IN WAKE OF COLORADO TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995, sociology
Professor Bill Gibson was quoted in the media as an expert on the
motivations of paramilitary extremist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Current events have again prompted the California State
University-Long Beach professor to jump back into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tuesday's rampage in Littleton, Colo., Gibson, author of
``Warrior Dreams: Violence and Manhood in Post-Vietnam America,''
has actively sought opportunities to air his opinions on what drove
two students to enter Columbine High School with guns blazing.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings are a parent's nightmare. The media coverage is a
publicist's dream.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, newsrooms are being deluged with e-mail,
faxes and phone calls from professional experts, many of whom
employ polished public relations professionals to help get their
names in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe they have information that could help the public
understand events.
</P>
<P>
   Others have a book to sell, a training tape to market or a need
to make points with a university tenure committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing is public-relations people responding to a
situation in which they can enhance their message,''said Kurt
Wildermuth, who teaches public relations at the University of
Missouri School of Journalism. ``A good public relations person is
watching the world to see what's happening and if an opportunity
presents itself will jump on it.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is a press release titled ``Atlanta psychiatrist
reveals solution for decreasing violence in schools'' that offers
interviews with Lyndon Waugh, author of ``Tired of Yelling _
Teaching Children to Resolve Conflict,'' (Hardcover, $22.95, May
1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at this as, the news media needs expert
sources,'' said Amy Burton, publicity manager at Marietta,
Ga.-based Longstreet Press, which e-mailed about 300 major-market
newspapers and television stations Wednesday afternoon to promote
Waugh's book. ``This story probably has a strong window of three or
four days... This is one of our front-list books for the season,
and we just jumped on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said she received 20 ``positive replies'' to her e-mail
and five requests for interviews with Waugh.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the media needs to be chased. Reporters look
instinctively for expert sources in situations such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is twofold,'' said Fred Blevens, who teaches
journalism at Southwest Texas State University. ``The first reason
is perspective. The second would be knowledge. The problem is that
journalists have to be experts on different subjects on different
days, weeks, months or years. And the only way to become an expert
is by talking to experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Profnet, an Internet-based expert-finder for journalists, has
had about 20 queries for experts on violence in schools in the past
few days, says Ellen Levine, Profnet's search editor. Profnet's
searchable database is made up of experts from colleges, think
tanks, and the occasional random person fronted by a
public-relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a dozen queries about this already today,'' Levine
said Thursday afternoon. ``We've had just a tremendous volume on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   All manner of advocates have been trying to get their messages
across, from academics such as Gibson to Terri Lynn, who does
public relations for the Florida-based Ryce Foundation, a group
that helps parents whose children have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail was titled: ``Experts available _ My child was
murdered.'' The parents, the e-mail said, ``can share their
experiences about how they deal with grief, cope and endure on a
daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the publicist quickly got reporters in touch with the
parents, who hadn't yet contacted any parents in Littleton, Colo.,
but were willing to talk to the media about the mourning process.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Gibson contacted Profnet himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even a Seattle agency, more than 1,000 miles away from
Littleton, has gotten into the act of offering experts to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent tragedy in Littleton, Colo., I'm
writing to offer Family Services as a resource to you in the
completion of follow-up stories,'' wrote Karen Brandvick-Baker,
director of communications for Family Services, a Seattle-area
non-profit counseling agency. Brandvick-Baker faxed her offer to
the media Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have counselors on staff who work with troubled teens and
can offer ideas around prevention and listening to their kids, as
well as grief counselors who can speak to how such a tragedy can
affect surviving teens in the aftermath.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say Brandvick-Baker was just doing her job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do in public relations is be advocates,'' Missouri's
Wildermuth said. ``And maybe we advocate a good position or not.
Maybe we just want to help you write a story, but down the road,
remember, we're advocates, and we want the story told from our
position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
