<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YZERMAN HAS PLAYOFF TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Steve Yzerman won the Conn Smythe Trophy as MVP of the
1998 Stanley Cup playoffs, and the Detroit captain has picked up
right where he left off.
</P>
<P>
   He had a hat trick in Game 1 after being cut by Steve Rucchin's
stick early in the first period. Friday night he assisted on the
Red Wings' first goal and scored their fifth, on a deflection
midway through the second.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered a one-dimensional offensive player, Yzerman has
become one of the league's top two-way players. According to
Detroit winger Darren McCarty, Yzerman doesn't say much _ but when
he speaks, everyone in the dressing room listens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything stops,'' McCarty said. ``Because you know he's the
first guy to block a shot or take a hit to make a play. If he's
doing it, we should too. He's like a father figure to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman's hat trick Wednesday night was the fourth of his
playoff career. Only Wayne Gretzky (10), Maurice Richard (7), Jari
Kurri (7), Dino Ciccarelli (6) and Mike Bossy (5) have more.
</P>
<P>
   Short on experience:Compared to the Red Wings, the Ducks are
mere babes when it comes to playoff experience. Coming into the
series, eight Ducks had yet to play in a playoff game, two others
had played only one and four had played less than 10.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Sandstrom, the only Duck to own a Stanley Cup ring, has
played in 136 postseason games, but he would rank only fourth on
the Red Wings behind Larry Murphy (191), Chris Chelios (164) and
Jamie Macoun (158).
</P>
<P>
   Eight Red Wings have played in 100 or more playoff games and 17
have more postseason experience than the second-most experienced
Duck, Kevin Haller, who has played in 61 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Friday's game, Sandstrom had 32 playoff goals; the
rest of the Ducks had combined for 38.
</P>
<P>
   Tough guy:As he sat in front of his locker after Friday's
morning skate, Anaheim's Jason Marshall looked as though he had
already played 20 playoff games. He was pale and had a black eye,
stitches and an ice bag on his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   But the Anaheim defenseman couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison to the regular season,'' he said.
``There is more intensity, the crowd is into it... it's what you
dream about doing all season long.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Steve Rucchin's three assists in Game 1 doubled his career
playoff scoring total. The Anaheim center had only one goal and
three points in eight games during the 1997 playoffs, when he was
hampered by a back injury.... Friday night's crowd of 19,983 marked
the 132nd consecutive game that Detroit fans have filled Joe Louis
Arena to capacity. The Red Wings have sold out 180 of their last
186 home games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
