<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-23 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-CAMP24-C     04-23 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-CAMP24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cecil ``The Diesel'' cheered in Dolphins debut
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Most of the Miami Dolphins' players already had
gotten out of the heat and headed back into the training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Collins, however, was busy with some extra-credit work.
</P>
<P>
   When the first practice of the Dolphins' mini-camp ended Friday,
the community relations department had gone searching for
volunteers to sign autographs. Veteran running back Karim
Abdul-Jabbar patted Collins on the back, volunteering the rookie
running back.
</P>
<P>
   So Collins stood by the fence near the bleachers at the team's
training facility, signing scraps of paper, T-shirts, hats and
balls, until after about 15 minutes a member of the public
relations staff came over and said, ``Sorry folks, but Cecil has to
get to a team meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   As Collins trotted back to the training facility, the fans
shouted encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil, we want you out there, man!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil, you're the man!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil, I can't wait to see you starting next year!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very impressive, Cecil. Very impressive!''
</P>
<P>
   A couple hours earlier, Collins had wondered what kind of
greeting he would receive the first time he stepped on a field
wearing a Dolphins practice jersey with No. 34 on it.
</P>
<P>
   Would they voice their displeasure with the Dolphins for
drafting someone who was kicked off two college teams, failed three
drug tests and pleaded guilty to charges he fondled two women in
their apartments?
</P>
<P>
   Or would they cheer and hope Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson had
found a future star in the fifth round?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Collins said. ``Maybe some cheering, maybe
some booing. That's going to come with it. I know there's going to
be some negative reaction out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 fans showed up to watch the players work out in
shorts and helmets. And when Collins took a handoff from Dan Marino
and burst downfield untouched, they didn't seem to care about his
past _ or the fact that he was untouched because hitting isn't
allowed in mini-camp.
</P>
<P>
   He was greeted with cheers and shouts of his nickname, Cecil
``The Diesel.''
</P>
<P>
   For Collins, the cheers were merely a bonus added to something
he had been looking forward to for seven months _ being on a
football field again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road,'' he said before practice. ``I'm just
ready to get all this over with and go out there and play
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins hadn't played football, other than to perform for
scouts, since last September. He was at McNeese State, his first
stop after being kicked out of Louisiana State for the first of his
two arrests. But two games into his stint at McNeese, he failed a
drug test, a violation of a bond agreement, and ended up in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Those 27 days, he said Friday, were the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail will change a lot,'' he said with a slight laugh. ``When
I went in there, I tried to find the Lord a lot more. I had strayed
away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he wanted the fans to know about him, he said:
``Well, on the field I'm a great player, 110 percent. Off the
field, I made some mistakes in life, but I accept that. I don't
blame that on anyone else. I put that all behind me. I'm just ready
to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   As he tries to do that, he will have plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is one of 12 running backs in camp. This off-season, the
Dolphins traded for Tyrone Wheatley, signed Roosevelt Potts, then
drafted Mississippi State's James Johnson, Collins and Syracuse
fullback Rob Konrad.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of new competition brought a shrug from the
incumbent, Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   He has been through this before. Last year the Dolphins used
their No. 1 pick to draft John Avery. And when this off-season
began, Jimmy Johnson sat him down and said the team planned to
search for a big running back who could solve the short-yardage
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to always have people coming after you when
you're a champion, you're a starter or No. 1 in anything,''
Abdul-Jabbar said, managing to find a positive in the competition.
``You think you can reach your potential when you're alone, but
sometimes you need a push.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly will have that this year.
</P>
<P>
   After the first practice, Johnson gave the new backs rave
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Johnson is a big back who's extremely smooth,'' he said.
``And you can see where Cecil's going to break a lot of tackles.
But they're in shorts. So we don't want to get too excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
